<HEAD>A
HISTORY
OF THE
CZAR of MUSCOVY.</HEAD>
<P>_PETER ALEXOWITZ, his pre&s;ent
<HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty; Emperor, or Cae&s;ar,
or King, or Grand Duke of <HI>Mu&s;covy,</HI>
call it which we will, who&s;e glorious
Life and Actions are the particular
Subject of this Undertaking, was the younge&s;t
Son, tho' at pre&s;ent, the only &s;urviving Son of
the late <HI>Czar Alexis,</HI> or <HI>Alexyea Michaelowitz,</HI> his
Father left one elder Son, and one Daughter, by a
former Venture; which Daughter was living, till
about the Year 1715, and &s;omething of the Hi|&s;tory
of both Son, and Daughter, may be briefly
under&s;tood, in their Management of Affairs.</P>
<P>THE elde&s;t Son a weak Prince, and $ncapable
of any great Undertaking, was however at fir&s;t
po&s;&s;e&s;t of the Government, and reign'd about &s;ix
Years; dying, as &s;ome have &s;aid by Poi&s;on, by
<PB N="2" REF="3">
the in&s;tigation of &s;ome of the Trayterous <HI>Boyars,</HI>
and in Confederacy with the Prince&s;s <HI>Sophia</HI> his
Si&s;ter.</P>
<P>AFTER his Fathers Death, the pre&s;ent Czar <HI>Peter,</HI>
tho' <HI>Evan</HI> or <HI>John,</HI> his elder Brother was then living,
took Po&s;&s;e&s;&s;ion of the Government, being then on|ly
twelve Years of Age; but afterward there was a
terrible Con&s;piracy, carry'd on by the General of
the <HI>Strelitz$s</HI> or &s;tanding Forces, and underhand
by the &s;aid Prince&s;s <HI>Sophia,</HI> which threw the Go|vernment
into great Covul&s;ions, during which,
many of the Nobility, or <HI>Boyars</HI> who were in the
Intere&s;t of the Czar <HI>Peter,</HI> were Sacrificed in a
mo&s;t bloody manner to the fury of the Soldiers,
and the Per&s;on of the <HI>Czar</HI> pre&s;erv'd, but with in|finite
difficulty by Prince <HI>Gallitzen,</HI> or <HI>Golloffken,</HI>
as &s;ome write him, who &s;natching the young
Prince, as it were by Violence out of the Hands
of the enrag'd Soldiers, hurried him in the Night
out of the Palace, and happily &s;ecur'd him in the
Mona&s;try of <HI>Trotski,</HI> above fifty Miles from the
Court; and then drawing together &s;uch Forces as
were at Hand, and &s;uch of the <HI>Strelitzes</HI> as con|tinu'd
faithful, and making a kind of an Accom|modation;
the two Princes were Proclaim'd equal
in the Government, and the Admini&s;tration car|ried
jointly in both their Names.</P>
<P>THIS kind of Government had perhaps conti|nued
longer, had the Czar <HI>Peter</HI> been of as &s;oft
and ea&s;y a Di&s;po&s;ition, and as willing to be
manag'd by his Si&s;ter <HI>Sophia,</HI> as the Czar <HI>Evan</HI>
appe$r'd to be; but the <HI>Czar Peter</HI> appearing to
be of a manly Genius, an enterprizing gallant
Temper, and a Spirit fi$ted by Nature for Em|pire.
The Prince&s;s <HI>Sophia</HI> ea&s;ily fore&s;eeing the
Termina$ion of her Authority in the ripening
<PB N="3" REF="4">
Age of her younger Brother, fill'd the State with
continual Plots and Con&s;piracies, which at la&s;t
Ended, as &s;uch things generally do, in e&s;tabli&s;hing
the Authority of the pre&s;ent <HI>Czar,</HI> and in her
own Ruin, as &s;hall appear in its Place.</P>
<P>AS to the Czar, <HI>Evan</HI> or <HI>John,</HI> he dyed a|bout
the Year 1691, and left the pre&s;ent Czar <HI>Pe|ter</HI>
&s;ole Governour of the greate&s;t Dominion in
<HI>Europe,</HI> and in who&s;e Reign tho&s;e Dominions have
received &s;uch Additions of &s;trength from an altera|tion
of the Conduct of the Prince, as the like can|not
be &s;hewn in the Hi&s;tory, of any Country in the
World, e&s;pecially con&s;idering that it has been
generally brought to pa&s;s, without any con&s;ide|rable
Conque&s;t of other Princes Dominions, but
chiefly by altering the Oeconomy, the Cu&s;toms,
Manners and Commerce of his own People.</P>
<P><HI>BY this Means,</HI> he has brought a Nation, who
were before the mo&s;t blind and ignorant, and
the greate&s;t contemners of Knowledge, and of all
manner of Learning, to be Searchers after Wi&s;|dom,
&s;tudying Sciences and eagerly bringing Home
Books, In&s;truments, and Arti&s;ts, from the mo&s;t
learned parts of the World for their In&s;truction.</P>
<P><HI>BT this Means,</HI> he has brought his Soldiery,
who were before the mo&s;t Scoundrel undi&s;ci|plin'd
Crowds, Rabbles, rather than Soldiers,
and ju&s;t good for nothing to be regular Di&s;ci|plined
Troops, Cloath'd, Arm'd and Paid like
other Nations, and behaving on all Occa&s;ions in
a manner &s;ufficient to make them formidable to
tho&s;e who us'd to Di&s;pi&s;e them.</P>
<P><HI>BY this Means,</HI> he has reduc'd his People in ge|neral,
to a legal kind of Obedience to their Go|vernors;
not the &s;ame blind kind of Homage they
us'd to pay to their Princes, who they rather
<PB N="4" REF="5">
wor&s;hip'd than obey'd; but, a more polite Re|gulation,
&s;o that now the <HI>Czar</HI> endeavours to
convince their Rea&s;on, of the real Advantages
which his new Laws are to them, at the &s;ame time
that he exacts their Obedience.</P>
<P><HI>BY this Means,</HI> he has regulated their Com|merce,
&s;hew'd them the Profit of a va&s;t Expor|tation
of their own Product to other Countries,
and of the Importation of the Product of other
Countries to them; by which their Wealth daily
encrea&s;es, their People who before had little
Bu&s;ine&s;s, now begin to get Employment, and their
Lands encrea&s;e in Value.</P>
<P><HI>BY this Means,</HI> he has brought his People to be
acquainted with the Sea, and they who had be|fore
&s;carce a Ship of any Con&s;equence, either for
Trade or War in the World, are now able to ap|pear
in the <HI>Balti$k</HI> with a Royal Naval of near
30 Men of War of the Line, Six and Twenty Fre|gat$s,
and 300 Galleys, &s;uch they had in their
great Expedition again&s;t <HI>Sweden,</HI> in the Year 1719,
be&s;ides Tran&s;port Ships, and on board of all,
which as I have been inform'd were employ'd 18000
Seamen, be&s;ides Soldiers, which Fleet are &s;ince ve|ry
much encreas'd, as &s;hall be &s;hewn it its Place.</P>
<P>THE former part of this Princes Reign, was
taken up, either in the Quieting the inte&s;tine
Troubles of his Subjects, the Factions of his Cour|tiers,
and the Rebellions, and Con&s;piracies of the
Nobility and Soldiery, who were continually
rendred Unquiet, and Unea&s;ie to him, by the $word$
Con&s;pira$ies of his Si&s;ter, the Prince&s;s <HI>So|phia,</HI>
and her Creatu$$s, OR in reducing the en|croa$$ing
<HI>Tartars,</HI> on the &s;ide of <HI>A&s;tra$an,</HI> and
the Countr$ of <HI>Circ$a&s;&s;ia,</HI> who &s;everal times gave
him great Di&s;turbance, ravag'd the Country, and
<PB N="5" REF="6">
carried off great Numbers of his People into Sla|very;
but in all his Encounters with the&s;e Peo|ple,
he was follow'd with a Series of continual
Succe&s;s, his Rebels were every where not only
Conquer'd, but entirely Subdu'd, and almo&s;t uni|ver&s;ally
fell into his Hands, and &s;o were either cut
off by the Hand of the Executioner, in which
Ca&s;es, tho' the Severities us'd were terrible, yet
they were no other than the Cu&s;tom of the Coun|try
made lawful; or el&s;e, were bani&s;h'd to <HI>Siberia,</HI>
where they are at full Liberty, and yet rendred
entirely uncapable of ever returning to di&s;turb
the Government.</P>
<P>THE utter impo&s;&s;ibility of any Per&s;ons, ex|cept
&s;uch as are at the Head of every Action, gi|ving
any Account of things in <HI>Mu&s;covy,</HI> where no
Records are kept, or Hi&s;tory written of publick
things, makes it not to be expected that I &s;hould
be able to give Journals of the March of Armies,
and exact Accounts of the &s;everal Expeditions of his
Czari&s;h Maje&s;ty to the Southern part of his Do|minions,
either again&s;t his own Rebellious <HI>Circa&s;&s;i|ans,</HI>
the <HI>Calmuck Tartars,</HI> or any other, except
&s;uch as tho&s;e, the Accounts of which we have from
the Hi&s;tory of the other Countries he was engag'd
with, of which I &s;hall give as full an Account as
the be&s;t Intelligence of tho&s;e times will permit.</P>
<P>THE enterprizing Genius of the <HI>Czar,</HI> and
his early attempts to put his Empire in a po&s;ture
of Defence again&s;t the Potent Neighbours who
&s;urrounded it, was not at all agreeable to the com|mon
Notions of the <HI>Mu&s;covites;</HI> Building Ships of
War, Entertaining Foreign Arti&s;ts and Engineers,
and laving Schemes according to the Manner of
the other Nations of <HI>Europe,</HI> who&s;e way of making
War is &s;o eminently improv'd, were all things
<PB N="6" REF="7">
di&s;agreeable to them, who as they had no Know|ledge
of Arts and Sciences, no Mathematical un|der&s;tandings,
or Sen&s;e of Improvement, &s;o they Ha|ted
and Di&s;pi&s;ed all tho&s;e who knew more than
them&s;elves.</P>
<P>NAY, &s;o eminently were they carryed out in
the E&s;teem of their own Ignorance, that they
made it a Point of Religion, and thought it a
breach of the Laws of God to mingle their Cu|&s;toms
with tho&s;e of other Nations, or to bring
the U&s;age of Foreigners among them; as if Wi&s;|dom
and Knowledge were not to be &s;earch'd af|ter
to the Ends of the Earth, and it were no
lo&s;s to them to be the mo&s;t blind, and uninform'd
Nation in the World.</P>
<P>BUT the <HI>Czar</HI> &s;aw with other Eyes; it was
ea&s;y to him who had a Penetrating Judgement,
and a Mathematical Head, tho' uninform'd by
the Knowledge of Art, to be &s;en&s;ible of the want
of it; and when he &s;aw the readine&s;s of Foreign
Arti&s;ts, how they acted their Part by Scale and
Rule, and had a whole Sy&s;tem of things in their
Heads, there needed no more for a Prince thus a|ble
to &s;ee the Defect of his own People, and the
Advantage which Neighbouring Nations had o|ver
them on that account; I &s;ay there needed no
more than a Sen&s;e of this, to cau&s;e him to re&s;olve
upon a general Application to the great Work of
informing him&s;elf, and by degrees his People al&s;o in
the u&s;eful Knowledge which flouri&s;h'd among the
other Nations of <HI>Europe;</HI> and to bring them to
receive &s;uch Notions, and &s;uch Cu&s;toms as might in
time render them equal to their Neighbours: If any
Man were to have a true Account of the former
ob&s;tinate Ignorance of the <HI>Mu&s;covite</HI> Nation;
how they di&s;pis'd and refus'd all Information,
<PB N="7" REF="8">
how they made it Criminal to &s;uffer any of their
People to travel Abroad, much le&s;s to pretend to
bring Home any experimental Knowledge, or a|ny
Cu&s;toms, however good in them&s;elves, from
other Nations; one wou'd fir&s;t wonder how the
<HI>Czar</HI> came, as it were alone, among his whole Na|tion,
to re&s;olve upon being better inform'd; and
much more how he has been able to Conquer the
ob&s;tinate Ignorance of his People.</P>
<P>NOT that he has Effectually done it yet, or per|haps
ever will; and if his late Son, the Prince of
<HI>Mu&s;covy</HI> had liv'd, 'tis certain he had &s;o little
Ta&s;t of tho&s;e things, tho' he had been Abroad,
that he would have unravell'd all that his Father
had done, and brought the Nation back to their
Native &s;tupidity again.</P>
<P>BUT that ob&s;tacle is remov'd, and &s;o are many
other; the <HI>Czar</HI> lives &s;till, and proceeds to
bring all the <HI>European</HI> Cu&s;toms and U&s;ages into
Fa&s;hion with his People; and in a few Years
more it may happen, that there will be &s;o many
Men of Learning and Judgement found in <HI>Mu&s;|covy,</HI>
that they will never return again to the bru|tal
Life, which they formerly led; e&s;pecially, if
the Succe&s;&s;or to his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty &s;hould hap|pen
to be &s;ome <HI>German</HI> Prince, who may Marry
his Daughter, or that the pre&s;ent Heir apparent
&s;hould live to have a foreign and learn'd Education.</P>
<P>IT has been &s;aid, that this in&s;ight which the
<HI>Czar</HI> had &s;o early receiv'd, into the Deficiency of
his Countries Cu&s;toms, and the Impre&s;&s;ions
of his own Ignorance, in tho&s;e things, which
a Prince ought to know, were fir&s;t formed by
Conver&s;ing early with one Mon&s;ieur <HI>Le Fort</HI> a
<HI>French</HI> Gentleman, of excellent Parts and Learn|ing,
who he had Entertain'd in his Court, while
<PB N="8" REF="9">
he (the <HI>Czar</HI>) was very young, and who&s;e Con|ver&s;ation
he was extremely Fond of: That
this Gentleman first exited him to Great and He|roick
Actions, fill'd his Mind with generous and
gallant Principles, and at la&s;t recommended to
him to take that happy &s;tep of Travelling in|cognito
thro' all the polite Parts of <HI>Europe,</HI> that
there he might &s;ee whether what he <HI>Le Fort</HI> had
intimated to him of the exqui&s;ite Management
of things in other Countries were true or not; and
that he might from thence return furni&s;h'd with
Knowledge of all things relating to Peace, War and
Government, and make him&s;elf Ma&s;ter of what
ever was Nece&s;&s;ary to make him truly Great, and
&s;o be in time an equal Match for his (at pre&s;ent)
more powerful Neighbours.</P>
<P>IT is the harde&s;t thing in the Worlds for Man
to be Convinc'd of his own Defects, and till he is
&s;o Convinc'd, 'tis impo&s;&s;ible to make him apply to Improvement; for who &s;ubmits to be taught
what he believes him&s;elf to know enough of.</P>
<Q><L>If Fools could their own Ignorance di&s;cern,</L>
<L>They'd be no longer Fools, becau&s;e they'd Learn.</L></Q>
<P>BUT here was a Prince arriv'd to the Perfe|ction
of Knowledge, (<HI>viz.</HI>) to know that he knew
nothing; and from this original Sen&s;e of his own,
and of his Peoples Deficiency, he fir&s;t re&s;olv'd to
Travel, that he might Learn every thing, and
then return to be the general Teacher of his own People.</P>
<P>HAPPY Humillity! he Travel'd in que&s;t of
Knowledge, that he might be qualified to be the
Great School-Ma&s;ter of his Subjects; and we &s;hall
&s;oon &s;ee the Succe&s;s in a Manner, &s;uch as the
<PB N="9" REF="10">
whole World can &s;how not One Example of the
like.</P>
<P>BUT to return to his other Enterprizes, before the
great Undertaking of all, which takes up &s;o much
Room in all the Hi&s;tories of the Age. The fir&s;t
of his Undertakings was the reduction of the
<HI>Circa&s;&s;ian Tartars,</HI> who in the infancy of this
Reign had Revolted, or rather made War again&s;t
the <HI>Mu&s;covites,</HI> had pa&s;s'd the <HI>Wolga,</HI> and &s;eiz'd upon
<HI>A&s;tra$an,</HI> where they committed unheard of Cru|elties,
and Barbarities upon the Inhabitants.</P>
<P>THE <HI>Mu&s;covite</HI> Army was not in this War Com|manded
by the <HI>Czar</HI> in Per&s;on, but by his Fa|vourite
Prince <HI>Gollofkin,</HI> and under him by &s;ome
foreign Officers, who carried on the War at fir&s;t
with Succe&s;s, but made no great Progre&s;s till the
<HI>Czar</HI> coming in Per&s;on with &s;ome additional
Troops, pu&s;h'd the <HI>Tartars</HI> with &s;uch Vigour, and
u&s;ed his Victrory &s;o effectually, that he brought
the whole Country of <HI>Circa&s;&s;ia</HI> to his Obedience:
And &s;ome of his Troops Ravaged the <HI>Crimmee,</HI>
and &s;truck a Terror even into the &s;everal other
Nations of <HI>Tartars,</HI> up to the Borders of the
<HI>Bori&s;thenes.</HI></P>
<P>THIS War brought on another of more
Weight, and indeed of more Danger, and that
was a War with the <HI>Turks,</HI> which it mu&s;t be con|fe&s;s'd,
the <HI>Czar</HI> &s;hew'd his Pollicy in adven|turing
upon at that Time; becau&s;e the <HI>Turks</HI> were
ju&s;t then Embarra&s;s'd in a War with the Emperor
of <HI>Germany,</HI> the King of <HI>Poland,</HI> and the State,
or Common-wealth or <HI>Venice</HI> all together; &s;o that
they were in no Condition to &s;end any Number
of Men to make their Arms formidable to the <HI>Czar.</HI></P>
<P><PB N="10" REF="11">
UNDER the&s;e fair Pro&s;pects, the <HI>Czar</HI> of
<HI>Mu&s;covy</HI> broke with the <HI>Turks</HI> in the Year, 1694,
and then follow'd a Series of Succe&s;&s;es, which rais'd
the Fame of the <HI>Mu&s;covite</HI> Arms above what they
ever reach'd before; but e&s;pecially, gave the
World a ta&s;te of the per&s;onal Valour and Conduct
of his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty, of whom they had heard
very little till now.</P>
<P>THE <HI>Tartars</HI> who had &s;o long been the Terror
of <HI>Mu&s;covy,</HI> were mi&s;erably Defeated by the <HI>Mu&s;|covite</HI>
Army in Three very con&s;iderale Actions;
of which however, Intelligence coming very &s;low
and uncertain from Places &s;o Remote, and from
Nations who held &s;o little Corre&s;pondence with
the re&s;t of the World; we had no particular Ac|count
till &s;ome Years after, when we were be|holding
to the Relations given of them from the
Memory of &s;ome <HI>Scots</HI> Officers who &s;erv'd in the
<HI>Mu&s;covite</HI> Army.</P>
<P>THE fir&s;t thing done in this War, was to clear
the ea&s;tern Banks of the <HI>Wolga</HI> from the <HI>Tartars,</HI>
and drive them effectually into their own Bounds.</P>
<P>THIS had in part been done before, when
Prince <HI>Gollofkin</HI> the Elder, had recovered <HI>A&s;tra|can</HI>
from them. But they &s;till remain'd in great
Numbers on the Calmuck &s;ide, and frequently
made Incur&s;ions into the Countries po&s;&s;e&s;s'd by
the <HI>Mu&s;covites,</HI> and Ravag'd far and near, accord|ing
to their u&s;ual Method, making an inexpre&s;&s;i|ble
De&s;olation wherever they came.</P>
<P>THE fir&s;t Troops the <HI>Czar</HI> &s;ent this way upon
his new Scheme of this War, effectually drove the
<HI>Calmuck Tartars</HI> over the <HI>Wolga;</HI> at the &s;ame
time the <HI>Co&s;&s;acks,</HI> &s;uch of them as were Subject to
the <HI>Czar,</HI> had fallen upon a great Body of the
<HI>Crim-Tartars,</HI> who had made an Attempt to fall
<PB N="11" REF="12">
into the <HI>Czar</HI>'s Dominions on the &s;ide of <HI>Circa&s;&s;ia,</HI>
and gave them a great Defeat, killing 15000 of
them upon the Spot.</P>
<P>BESIDES this, the <HI>Czar</HI>'s General <HI>Gordon</HI> a
<HI>Scots</HI> Gentleman, and an Officer of great Experi|ence
entered into <HI>Circa&s;&s;ia</HI> it&s;elf, and after giving
the <HI>Tartars</HI> &s;everal Defeats, reduced that whole
Country under the Obedience of the <HI>Mu&s;covite</HI>
Government, as it remains to this Day.</P>
<P>IT &s;hould have been ob&s;erv'd here, that tho'
the <HI>Mu&s;covite</HI> Militia were not yet brought to the
happy Regulation and Di&s;cipline, they are $ince
by the <HI>Czar</HI>'s Application and Management
arriv'd to; yet they had been much Improv'd,
and were in a much better Condition than they
had formerly been in; and this by the Manage|ment
and Direction of the late Czar <HI>Alexis Mi|chaelowitz,</HI>
the pre&s;ent <HI>Czar</HI>'s Father, who indeed
began to alter &s;everal things in the former un|poli&s;h'd
Method of the <HI>Mu&s;covite</HI> Government;
and particularly that of the Army; and remark|ably
in this, that he re&s;olv'd to introduce the
<HI>German</HI> Military Discipline among his Troops;
and to have the Soldiers taught the Exerci&s;e for
the handling their Arms, Marching, Counter|Marching,
Wheeling, drawing up, Forming and
Embattleing, &amp;c. after the <HI>German</HI> Manner. And
to this purpo&s;e, he Entertain'd a great Number of
foreign Officers in his Army, who he Encourag'd
to come out of the Service of all the Princes near
him, by Promi&s;es of large Pay and good U&s;age,
with Preferments according to their Merit, and
which Terms they found very punctually Com|ply'd
with; and his Son the pre&s;ent <HI>Czar</HI> per&s;u|ed
the &s;ame Method.</P>
<P><PB N="12" REF="13">
BY this means he had at the time of his Un|dertaking
the War I am now &s;peaking of, two
Generals (viz.) <HI>Mon&s;ieur le Fort,</HI> and Mr. <HI>Gordon,</HI>
the fir&s;t a <HI>French</HI> Man, the &s;econd a <HI>Scots</HI> Man,
and above 3000 inferior Officers of &s;everal Na|tions
in his Pay, be&s;ides Engineers, Cannoniers,
Bombardiers, and Firemen in abundance.</P>
<P>AND this was the great Rea&s;on why his En|terprizes
in this War were carry'd on with great
Regularity; his Sieges managed, and Trenches
open'd according to Art; his Batteries, Mines,
Attacks &amp;c. well &s;erv'd; and every thing done
as it ought to be done. Things which in former
Times the <HI>Mu&s;covites</HI> knew little of.</P>
<P>I am oblig'd to pa&s;s over the fir&s;t Actions of
his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty's Generals in this War, in a
&s;ummary Method, not being able to come at the
particular Days of the Month, or the particular
Circum&s;tances of every Action, nor any Diary
of the March of the Armies, in a time when as
before, &s;carce any thing was done with that Re|gularity,
which has been u&s;ual in &s;uch Ca&s;es in
other Countries, and which has &s;ince been better
Manag'd there: Be&s;ides, this was a kind of a
Tumultuary War, the <HI>Tartars</HI> being a People
that made only a kind of <HI>Camp Volant</HI> in all their
Marchings; and in every thing they did, it might
be only &s;aid, that it was by way of Excur&s;ion, and
Incur&s;ion; Plundering and Burning, when they
Advanced, and Runing or rather Flying, when
they Return'd; &s;o that they were only to be Fought,
with by the way of Intercepting them, and by
Surprize; and when at any time they were brought
to Fight, it could never be call'd a pitch'd Battle,
but rather a runing Fight, their whole Army be|ing
<PB N="13" REF="14">
always on Hor&s;eback, for as to an Infantry,
they know nothing of them.</P>
<P>HOWEVER, as the <HI>Co&s;&s;acks</HI> were likewi&s;e
Hor&s;e, tho' not &s;o well Mounted, they, often met
with and routed the <HI>Tartars</HI> too; and that ra|ther,
becau&s;e the mo&s;t Soldiery part of the <HI>Tar|tars</HI>
were at that time Engag'd again&s;t the <HI>Po|landers,</HI>
or in <HI>Hungary,</HI> again&s;t the Imperial Ar|mies,
in Conjunction with the <HI>Turks.</HI></P>
<P>BUT to come back to the Per&s;on and Conduct
of the <HI>Czar,</HI> it was in per&s;uit of his Conque&s;ts on
this &s;ide, that his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty found how fair
a way lay open to him to make him&s;elf Power|ful
by Sea; a thing which had long lain upon his
Thoughts, but which till now he never had &s;o
much as room to find feazible, or indeed po&s;&s;i|ble;
having no Out-let into any Sea where his
Power might exert it&s;elf: As to the <HI>Wolga,</HI>
tho' it be a very great River, and of a prodigious
extended Cour&s;e, having run above 2500 Miles,
including the Windings and Reaches of its Cour&s;e,
yet there is no depth of Water in the Channel at
the Mouth or Influx of it into the Sea; but the
Sands and Flats of the Shore in the <HI>Ca&s;pian</HI> Sea on
the <HI>Ru&s;&s;ian</HI> &s;ide choking up the River, makes it un|capable
to carry Ships of any Force, except at
the time of the Winter Floods; and even then,
the <HI>Ca&s;pian</HI> Sea it&s;elf for &s;ome Leagues, has no
depth of Water an&s;werable for a Royal Navy of
Men of War, &s;uch as the <HI>Czar</HI> had Projected to
Build.</P>
<P>ON the other hand, had the <HI>Ca&s;pian</HI> Sea been
deep and every where Navigable as wou'd be &s;uf|ficient,
yet this re&s;pected only the Shores of <HI>Per|&s;ia,
Armenia, Georgia,</HI> and tho&s;e Countries, which
rendered the <HI>Czar</HI> no Pro&s;pect of Glory, or Con|que&s;t.
<PB N="14" REF="15">
But his De&s;igns lay another way, that is
to &s;ay, to open to him&s;elf a Navigation into the
<HI>Black</HI> Sea, where he might either extend his Con|que&s;t
or his Commerce, or perhaps both, into the
le&s;&s;er <HI>A&s;ia,</HI> and even to the Gates of <HI>Con&s;tanti|nople;</HI>
and either by Force or by Treaty, might
obtain a Pa&s;&s;age thro' the Straits of <HI>Hellespont,</HI>
and the <HI>Thracian Bo&s;phorns</HI> into the Mediterrane|an
Sea, and &s;o might e&s;tablish an open Trade be|tween
his Country and the Ports of <HI>Italy, France,</HI>
and <HI>Spain,</HI> and con&s;equently with all the known World.</P>
<P>THIS open'd a Scene of Glory fit for a Prince,
and &s;uited to the great Enterprizes which his
<HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty had formed in his Mind: In a
word, here was a Field of Action large enough
to gratifie the Ambition of a Sovereign, Born for
great Things, and who po&s;&s;e&s;&s;ing an Empire Su|perior
to any of his Neighbours, wanted nothing
but an Entrance upon the Stage of Greatne&s;s, that
he might Act like himelf.</P>
<P>HE &s;aw at once all the great Things which
might be the Con&s;equence of this Conque&s;t in many
Ages to come; and it was from this Judgment
that he had made of Things, that he had purpo&s;ed
to Build a large Fleet of Men of War, even while
the World &s;tood Amaz'd at the My&s;tery of it; &s;ee|ing
they were Built many Leagues up the Coun|try,
on the bank of a River, (<HI>viz.</HI>) The <HI>Don</HI> or <HI>Ta|$$is,</HI>
who&s;e Out-let into the Sea was not in his
Po&s;&s;e&s;&s;ion, but Bl$ck'd up by the <HI>Turks</HI> with in|numerable
Ob&s;tacles; &s;uch as &s;trong Fortrc&s;&s;es,
narrow Straits, great Batteries, Ships of War, and
the like, particularly, the City and Forts at
<HI>A&s;oph,</HI> the Lines at the Mouth of the River <HI>Don,</HI>
and Works at the Straits of <HI>Caffa,</HI> which la&s;t is,
<PB N="15" REF="16">
the only Entrance into the <HI>Black</HI> Sea, out of that
Sea call'd the <HI>Palus Meotis.</HI></P>
<P>BUT his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty's de&s;igns were not to
be Diverted with the Pro&s;pect of tho&s;e Difficul|ties;
and therefore even before he &s;eem'd to aim
at opening the Pa&s;&s;age of tho&s;e Places, or Enga|ging
in any War to bring it to pa&s;s, he employ'd
Agents into <HI>Holland,</HI> and into <HI>England,</HI> to furni&s;h
him with experienc'd Ship-Wrights, and Builders,
in order to build a Royal Navy of Men of War,
even when no Body could fore&s;ee in what Part of
the World they &s;hould be Employ'd; his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI>
Maje&s;ty having then not one Port in the <HI>Baltick</HI>
Sea, the <HI>Euxine</HI> Sea, or any where el&s;e, except
that of <HI>Arch-Angel</HI> opening to the North Seas, in
the Latitude 72 degrees, where he could have no
occa&s;ion to u&s;e them.</P>
<P>BUT the Event &s;oon di&s;cover'd the Sagacity
of the De&s;ign, for the &s;ame Year the <HI>Czar</HI> having
before been long Solicited by the Confederates,
came into the War with the <HI>Turks,</HI> which was
&s;olemnly proclaim'd the twentieth, of <HI>February,</HI>
1694.</P>
<P>IN pur&s;uance of this War, and of the Mea|&s;ures
concerted with the Allies, the <HI>Czar</HI> appear'd
with two Armies in the Field, the beginning of
the Year 1695, the one con&s;i&s;ting of 90000 Foot,
and 20000 Hor&s;e and Dragoons, Commanded by
his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty in Per&s;on, and with which he
march'd into the <HI>Ru&s;&s;ian Circa&s;&s;ia,</HI> and entering the
<HI>Turki&s;h</HI> Dominions, &s;at down before <HI>A&s;oph,</HI> an im|portant
Fortre&s;s upon the Banks of the <HI>Tanais,</HI>
near the Mouth of that great River, where it em|pties
it&s;elf into the great Lake, or Sea call'd the
<HI>Palus Meotis;</HI> and the other Army con&s;i&s;ting of
24000 Foot and 36000 Hor&s;e, the latter being
<PB N="16" REF="17">
all <HI>Coa&s;&s;acks,</HI> and was therefore call'd the <HI>Co&s;&s;ack
Army,</HI> Commanded by Lieutenant General Prince
<HI>Czeremetoff,</HI> of whom we &s;hall often have occa&s;i|on
to &s;peak hereafter in the Cour&s;e of this Hi|&s;tory.
This Army march'd by the Way of the
<HI>Ukraine,</HI> and keeping the Cour&s;e of the great Ri|ver
<HI>Bori&s;thenes,</HI> or the <HI>Neiper</HI> to the Mouth of the
&s;aid River, &s;at down before the &s;trong Town of
<HI>Ka&s;ilkermeen,</HI> a <HI>Tartarian</HI> City, Situated on the
South Bank of the &s;aid River <HI>Neiper,</HI> and within
two Leagues or thereabouts of the <HI>Black-Sea.</HI></P>
<P>THESE Towns were equally considerable, as
Situated at the two great Enterances into the <HI>Pontus
Euxinus,</HI> neare&s;t to his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty's&punc; Domi|nions;
and mo&s;t conveniently Seated, both to fa|cilitate
his De&s;igns for the Commerce of his Sub|jects
in tho&s;e Seas, and equally Advantageous to
him for carrying on his farther De&s;ign again&s;t the
<HI>Turks.</HI></P>
<P>IF the Chri&s;tian World were agreeable &s;ur|pris'd
at the <HI>Czar</HI>'s breaking with the <HI>Turks</HI> in a
Juncture &s;o very Momentous, and &s;o Sea&s;onable
to the Confederates, they were even amaz'd to
find a Prince, of who&s;e enterpri&s;ing Genius they
had yet form'd no Notions, begin a War with &s;uch
apparent Proofs, both of an exqui&s;ite Fore|knowledge,
and al&s;o of a perfect Under&s;tanding
of the Weight and Con&s;equence of what he had
Undertaken; on the other Hand, the manner of
his Entrance into this War, and the formidable
Power with which he began it, gave the <HI>Turks</HI> a
terrible Alarm, e&s;pecially con&s;idering how their
Affairs were at that time Embara&s;s'd in a heavy
War with the Emperor, the King of <HI>Poland,</HI>
and the State of <HI>Venice,</HI> all at the &s;ame time, and
in which they had receiv'd &s;everal terrible Over|throws,
<PB N="17" REF="18">
and had already lo&s;t almo&s;t all the King
of <HI>Hungaria,</HI> all the <HI>Morea,</HI> and &s;everal con&s;ide|rable
Fortre&s;&s;es in <HI>Dalmatia,</HI> and other Places, be|sides
having their Millitary Power, broken both
at Sea and Land, by innumerable Defeats of their
Armies and Fleets; but we &s;hall &s;ee them farther
Alarm'd in the proce&s;s of this War, by the Succe&s;s
of his Czari&s;h Maje&s;ty in the Pro&s;ecution of
it.</P>
<P>IT was now too late, that the <HI>Turks</HI> &s;aw their
Mi&s;take, in that having for many Years the City
of <HI>A&s;oph,</HI> in their Po&s;&s;e&s;&s;ion, if they had con&s;i|der'd
it as one of the mo&s;t important Frontiers
of their whole Empire, they would have made it
as impregnable, as the Con&s;equences of &s;uch a
Place requir'd, and as the Situation of it very
well allow'd; for it was mo&s;t advantageou&s;ly Si|tuated
on the North Bank of the River <HI>Don,</HI> with
a low Mar&s;hy Ground oppo&s;ite to it, which was
capable of being &s;o Fortify'd, as appear'd after|wards,
and to be &s;o &s;urrounded with Water, as
not to be any way attack'd, otherwi&s;e than by a
Bombardment, or to be taken, but by a &s;trict
Blockade.</P>
<P>ALL that the <HI>Turks</HI> could do, upon the &s;udden
approach of the <HI>Czar</HI>'s Army, was, to &s;upply the
Want, or Weakne&s;s of the Fortifications, with a
bold re&s;olute Garri&s;on of ten thou&s;and <HI>Jani&s;aries,</HI>
all old Soldiers; be&s;ides <HI>Tartars;</HI> and under cho&s;en
Officers, well furni&s;h'd with all things for a vigo|rous
Defence; and this they plac'd the more Confi|dence
in, by how much they had the <HI>Mu&s;covites</HI>
&s;till in the utmo&s;t Contempt, as to their Military
Capacity of attacking &s;uch a Place.</P>
<P>NOR did the Garri&s;on di&s;appoint their Ma&s;ters,
or fail in doing their Duty, and in &s;uch manner,
<PB N="18" REF="19">
that altho' the <HI>Czar</HI> attack'd the Place in Form,
and that his Engineers made their Approaches
with the utmo&s;t Skill, and Batter'd and Bombard|ed
the Place with a 100 Pieces of Cannon, and 40
Mortars; yet the Garri&s;on &s;o Harra&s;s'd them with
Continu'd bold and de&s;perate Sallies, and &s;o ply'd
them with a numerous Artillery from the Walls, &s;o
often levell'd the Trenches of the Be&s;iegers, Nail'd
their Cannon, and ruin'd their Works; that the
Winter coming on, and Provi&s;ions growing Scarce,
the <HI>Czar</HI> tho' he was in Per&s;on at the Siege, was
oblig'd to give it over, after having lo&s;t as &s;ome
have reported above 30000 Men before the Place,
and half ruin'd his Calvalry for want of Fo|rage.</P>
<P>BUT Prince <HI>Czeremetoff</HI> had better luck be|fore
<HI>Ka&s;ikermeen,</HI> which tho' it was better Forti|fy'd,
was not &s;o well Defended; and the <HI>Co&s;&s;acks</HI>
pu&s;hing on their Attacks with a de&s;perate Fury,
they carried the Place Sword in Hand, the Gar|ri&s;on
having but ju&s;t time to retreat into two large
Forts, which cover'd the City on the &s;ide of the
River, where beating a Parley, they had good
Conditions granted by the Be&s;iegers, and &s;o the
whole City was taken.</P>
<P>THERE was a complaint made again&s;t the
<HI>Mu&s;covite</HI> General Prince <HI>Czeremetoff,</HI> for &s;uffer|ing
the <HI>Co&s;&s;acks</HI> to Plunder the Garri&s;on after the
Capitulation was Sign'd; and that Princes Di&s;|grace
happening &s;oon after, was a&s;&s;ign'd to that
Cau&s;e; but I do not take upon me to &s;ay, this
was the Cau&s;e of it, and as that Prince has been
receiv'd into his Ma&s;ters Favour &s;ince, that, with
very great Reputation, 'tis generally &s;uppos'd,
that he acquitted him&s;elf of that Accu&s;ation.</P>
<P><PB N="19" REF="20">
IF the <HI>Turks</HI> committed an Over-&s;ight an their,
not fore-&s;eeing the Importance, <HI>and Fortifying in
time the City</HI> of <HI>A&s;oph,</HI> they were now guilty of
the greate&s;t and mo&s;t inexcu&s;able Neglect and O|mi&s;&s;ion,
in not taking the opportunity of the Win|ter,
when the <HI>Czar</HI>'s Troops were with-drawn, to
&s;end a powerful Succour to the Garri&s;on, that they
might have Defended the Place another Year, as
they had done the Year before.</P>
<P>ON the contrary, the <HI>Mu&s;covites</HI> left a Body
of Forces in the Country, who as it were, effect|ually
Block'd up the Place by Land; and the
<HI>Turks</HI> neither &s;upplyed the Magazines with Provi|&s;ions,
or reinforced the Garri&s;on with fre&s;h Troops;
both which it was very ea&s;ie to have done by Sea;
the <HI>Mu&s;covites</HI> having then no Naval Strength at
all: Of both the&s;e there was an ab&s;olute Nece&s;&s;i|ty,
for the Magazines were not only Empty, the
Ammunition being extremely le&s;&s;en'd in the fre|quent
Sallies and continued Fireings during &s;o
long a Defence, as that of the la&s;t Siege, but the
Garri&s;on was reduced from ten Thou&s;and, to two
Thou&s;and eight Hundred Men.</P>
<P>IN this di&s;tre&s;s'd Condition, they were oblig'd
to &s;u&s;tain the &s;econd Siege, having long &s;ollicited
for Succours but in vain, till it was too late to re|ceive
them, as will appear in the Sequel of the
Story.</P>
<P>DURING the Winter, the <HI>Czar</HI> was not Idle;
the prodigious Preparations made in all Parts of
his va&s;t Dominions, for Recruiting his Army,
Remounting his Cavalry, and &s;upplying the Ma|gazines
with all nece&s;&s;ary Stores of Ammunition,
&amp;c. Intimated plainly, that the Attempt upon
<HI>A&s;oph</HI> was not laid a&s;ide; but that which was
mo&s;t con&s;iderable of all, was the Expedition
<PB N="20" REF="21">
with which his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty furni&s;h'd him&s;elf
with a Fleet in one Winter; and that odd and
extravagant Manner in which &s;ome of the Ve&s;&s;els
were Built, &s;everal of them having been Built
in the River <HI>Occa,</HI> and carried over Land to the
<HI>Dona,</HI> and mo&s;t of the re&s;t at <HI>Voranowitz,</HI> a
Town on a River of that Name, which emplies
it&s;elf into the <HI>Dona</HI> above 300 Miles above <HI>A|&s;oph.</HI></P>
<P>THE Detachment of Troops which the <HI>Czar</HI>
had left to Block up the Place during the Winter,
had maintain$d their Po&s;ts upon the Neighbouring
Hills, and &s;o well &s;cour'd the Country, that the
Garri&s;on of <HI>A&s;oph</HI> had no opportunity of reccive|ing
any Relief or Supply by Land; and early in
the Spring the <HI>Mu&s;covite</HI> Troops began to arrive,
&s;o that they were actually Be&s;ieg'd again, before
they had received the lea&s;t Recruit.</P>
<P>THE Preparations for this &s;econd Attack, were
&s;o much greater than tho&s;e of the fir&s;t Siege, that
the Garri&s;on had much more need to have been
doubled than le&s;&s;en'd, the Violence they had to
&s;u&s;tain, being &s;o much the greater; for the Artil|lery
the <HI>Czar</HI> had prepar'd for this Attack, were
400 Pieces of Cannon, and 150 Mortars.</P>
<P>THE Expedition us'd in all the&s;e Preparations
was &s;uch, that the Body of the Army arriv'd be|fore
<HI>A&s;oph,</HI> in the End of <HI>April;</HI> but the Rivers
not being open for bringing the Ve&s;&s;els loaden
with Artillery, Bombs, <HI>&amp;c.</HI> and for the Ships
from <HI>Veranowitz,</HI> till the middle of <HI>May,</HI> it was
the beginning of <HI>June,</HI> before the Siege was actu|ally
form'd; all which time the <HI>Turks</HI> had fairly
before them to have relieved the Place; which
however, as if an Ill-fate attended them, they o|mitted
till about the middle of <HI>July,</HI> when their
<PB N="21" REF="22">
Squadron began to appear in the <HI>Black</HI> Sea, and
when they found to their Co&s;t that they were too
late, as we &s;hall &s;ee pre&s;ently.</P>
<P>THE <HI>Czar</HI> came in Per&s;on to his Army the be|ginning
of <HI>May,</HI> and the Siege begun with the
utmo&s;t Vigour; the Garri&s;on, tho' extreamly re|duced,
and in want of many things, yet defended
them&s;elves with a de&s;perate Valour, rejecting the
Summons &s;ent them in his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Majesty's Name,
by General <HI>Gordon,</HI> with offers of an honourable
Capitulation, and another Summons after that,
threatening them that they &s;hould have no Quar|ter,
if they were taken by Storm.</P>
<P>THE <HI>Mu&s;covite</HI> General <HI>Gordon</HI> found that the
Ground did not admit of Carrying on Trenches,
&s;o well as could be wi&s;h'd, and the Garri&s;on ha|ving
near 300 Pieces of Cannon upon their Works,
made &s;uch a continual Fire, as ruin'd the <HI>Mu&s;covite</HI>
Batteries; for the &s;aid Batteries being made of a
loo&s;e Sandy Earrh, which would not bear the Weight
of the Artillery. When the Shot of the Town had
but beaten them a little in the Front they fell down;
&s;o that the Guns were di&s;mounted by the Enemy,
with the greate&s;t ea&s;e immaginable: Upon this, the
&s;aid General <HI>Gordon</HI> undertook to carry on a rol|ling
Trench, or rather a rolling Parapet, which
by the help of a multitude of Hands, and near
&s;ix Weeks labour, he brought to &s;uch perfection,
that it terrify'd the Be&s;ieged more than all the
Bombs and Cannon in the Army.</P>
<P>THIS Work was begun at a good di&s;tance
from the Place, and as there were above 30000
Men continually employ'd in it, who reliev'd one
another every four Hours, the Work came gra|dually
rowling forward, the Men behind it &s;till
throwing the Sandy Earth from the bottom, up
<PB N="22" REF="23">
to one another upon Stages, till the uppermo&s;t
threw it quite over the Top, &s;o that at la&s;t they
brought it within half a Mu&s;quet Shot of the
Town, and the height &s;o great, that it overlook'd
the highe&s;t part of the Wall, and all the Ba&s;tions,
to the great a&s;toni&s;hment of the Be&s;ieg'd.</P>
<P>DURING all this time, the Batteries for Mor|tars,
which were &s;o effectually cover'd from the
&s;hot of the Ramparts, play'd &s;o ince&s;&s;antly upon
the Town, throwing Bombs Night and Day;
that the whole Town was reduc'd to A&s;hes, and
the Garri&s;on continually Harra&s;s'd with the fury
of the Bombs, no Place being &s;ecure for them; nor
could they appear upon their Works, but they
were immediately knock'd down with &s;mall &s;hot
from the Top of the rowling Trench, which over|look'd
them like a big Mountain, commanding
the Town!: While this was doing from the Land|&s;ide,
the <HI>Czar,</HI> who took upon him&s;elf, the Di|rection
of the naval Part in particular, brought
his Gallies down by a different Channel of the
River <HI>Don,</HI> which as it was out of the reach of the
Cannon of the Town; &s;o there was &s;o little depth
of Water in that part of the River, that no Ve&s;|&s;el
of bulk were ever known to pa&s;s that Way
before, except in Ca&s;es of great Fre&s;hes, or Land
Floods, which were all now over and gone.</P>
<P>THUS the <HI>Czar</HI> appear'd with a Fleet of Gal|lies
below the Town, to the a&s;toni&s;hment of the
Be&s;ieged, who believ'd it impo&s;&s;ible they &s;hould
pa&s;s any way, but in the Mouth of their Guns,
which would have been altogether impracticable,
there being above 150 Pieces of Cannon mounted
to defend the Pa&s;&s;age.</P>
<P><PB N="23" REF="24">
BESIDES this, his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty cau&s;ed &s;e|veral
Batteries of Cannon to be Planted on the
other &s;ide of the River <HI>Donn,</HI> on a &s;mall I&s;land,
which is very properly Situated to prevent Suc|cours
from coming to Relieve the Place; and
behind this I&s;land he placed all his Arm'd Sha|loups
and Brigantines, as in an Ambu&s;cade, to be
ready to &s;how them&s;elves as occa&s;ion &s;hou'd pre&s;ent.</P>
<P>IN this po&s;ture, both the Be&s;iegers and the Be|&s;ieged
expected the <HI>Turki&s;h</HI> Fleet, which at length
appear'd, bringing Succours for the Garri&s;on;
the Fleet con&s;i&s;ted of 12 large Gallies, 30 arm'd
Brigantines, and about 60 Tran&s;port Ve&s;&s;els, ha|ving
on Board 8000 Soldiers to Reinforce the
Garri&s;on, a va&s;t Quantity of Ammunition of all
&s;orts, Stores of Provi&s;ion, and Cloths for the
Garri&s;on, and 50000 Ducates in Money for the pay
and Encouragement of the brave Fellows, who had
&s;o well behav'd them&s;elves as above.</P>
<P>IT was about the 24th of <HI>July,</HI> that they ap|pear'd
in the <HI>Palus Meotis,</HI> &s;tanding in among the
I&s;lands in the Mouth of the <HI>Donn,</HI> &s;o to enter the
Place; the fir&s;t thing they had to Encounter, was
the <HI>Czar</HI>'s Gallies, who drawing le&s;s Water than
the Great Gallies of the <HI>Turks</HI> lay farther up the
River, where the other could not come.</P>
<P>IN the mean time the <HI>Turki&s;h</HI> Saicks and Bri|gantines
to &s;hun tho&s;e Gallies, kept among the
&s;aid I&s;lands in &s;hoal Water, which the <HI>Czar</HI> per|ceiving,
he took a &s;ufficient Number of Troops
into his Shalloups and Brigantines, and re&s;olv'd
to Attack them where they lay, which they did
with &s;uch Bravery and Succe&s;s, him&s;elf ap|pearing
in Per&s;on in the hotte&s;t of the Action,
that the <HI>Turks</HI> were entirely Defeated and Di|&s;pers'd,
and the whole Convoy of Provi&s;ions,
<PB N="24" REF="25">
Ammunition, <HI>&amp;c.</HI> taken even &s;ight of the Gar|ri&s;on,
not one Ve&s;&s;el being able to reach the
Town.</P>
<P>THIS Overthrow of the <HI>Turki&s;h</HI> Fleet, with the
Succours was follow'd with the Surrender of the
Town; the Garri&s;on Capitulating the 28th of <HI>Ju|ly,</HI>
the <HI>Czar</HI> granting them very honourable Con|ditions,
in Con&s;ideration of that Bravery they had
&s;hewn in Defence of the Place: It was &s;aid, that
when they Surrendred, there was not above 1300
whole Men left of them, who were upwards of
12000 at the beginning of the Siege.</P>
<P>THIS glorious Victory of the <HI>Czar's</HI> &s;urpris'd all
<HI>Europe,</HI> and fill'd every Bodies Mouth with the Per|&s;onal
Fame of his Cazri&s;h Maje&s;ty's Valour and Con|duct,
which was the more talk'd of, becau&s;e it had not
been often, that the World had heard of the <HI>Mu&s;co|vites</HI>
good Conduct, much le&s;s of a Warlike Emperor
at their Head: On this Account and that I may be &s;ure
to leave a full Account of this great Action, I &s;hall
give it in the very Words, in which it was publi&s;h'd
to the World in the &s;everal Countries, from whence
we had then an Account of it; <HI>For Example;</HI> one
Account, and back'd with good Authority, which
came by the way of <HI>France,</HI> is as follows.</P>
<P>HIS <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty having before-hand re|ceiv'd
Intelligence of the approach of this Suc|cour,
had caus'd &s;even of his large&s;t Gallies of a
hundred Foot in Length each, be&s;ides &s;everal le&s;&s;er,
and a great Number of Brigantines to pa&s;s into
that &s;mall Branch of the <HI>Don,</HI> which i&s;&s;ues forth
a little above the Town. As the Water is very
Shallow in this <HI>Channel,</HI> &s;o it was not without a
great deal of difficulty, that the large&s;t Gallies
could be brought along that Way, and would in
all likelihood not have &s;ucceeded, if the <HI>Czar</HI> by his
<PB N="25" REF="26">
Pre&s;ence and Encouragement, had not animated
the Workmen to &s;urpa&s;s all the Difficulties, which
at la&s;t they did, to the no &s;mall A&s;toni&s;hment of
the Be&s;ieged.</P>
<P>THIS Ob&s;tacle being happily &s;urmounted, his
<HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty judg'd it of very great Con&s;equence,
for his purpo&s;e to plant good Store of Cannon up|on
the little I&s;land we have mention'd before,
becau&s;e the Shoar being very Low, the Cannon-ball
would &s;trike even with the Surface of the Water;
be&s;ides that the greate&s;t part of the I&s;le being
cover'd with Wood, did prevent the Enemy from
di&s;covering the De&s;ign.</P>
<P>THE &s;ame favourable Di&s;po&s;ition of this I&s;land,
furni&s;h'd the <HI>Mu&s;covites,</HI> with an opportunity of
putting &s;ome of their lighte&s;t Gallies and Brigan|tines
for a Re&s;erve behind the I&s;le unperceiv'd by
the Enemy, whom they intended thus to attack
both in the Front and Flank as they pa&s;&s;ed by that
Way, which &s;ucceeded according to Expectation.</P>
<P>FOR all the&s;e Precautions having been made
before, when the Enemies Fleet came in &s;ight, the
bigge&s;t <HI>Mu&s;covite</HI> Gallies, with many Brigantines
were &s;ent out to meet them, making a &s;how as if
they intended to Engage the <HI>Turki&s;h</HI> Fleet; but
no &s;ooner were they come within Cannon-Shot of
one another, but the <HI>Mu&s;covites</HI> $eigning to dread
the <HI>Ottoman</HI> Fleet, as &s;uperiour to them in Num|ber,
made a running Fight, making the be&s;t of
their way towards the Shoar, and po&s;ting them|&s;elves
below the I&s;land: The <HI>Turks</HI> perceiving the
Enemy to fly before them, and not in the lea&s;t fore|warn'd
of that Plot laid behind the I&s;land, thought
them&s;elves, by the &s;mall Number of the <HI>Mu&s;co|vite</HI>
<PB N="26" REF="27">
Gallies that appear'd in Sight, a&s;&s;ur'd of the
Victory.</P>
<P>FLUSH'D with the&s;e Hopes, they made all
the Sail they could to fall in among the <HI>Mu&s;co|vites,</HI>
but no &s;ooner were they come within reach
of the Cannon from the I&s;le, but they receiv'd &s;uch
a warm &s;alute from thence, that they &s;aw their
Gallies torn to pieces on all &s;ides, by the Enemies
Cannon in an In&s;tant, with a great Slaughter of
many of their Men; but this was only the Fore|runner
of what was to en&s;ue.</P>
<P>FOR his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty, who had a watchful
Eye on all Sides, and who was &s;ometimes upon the
I&s;le, &s;ometimes on Board the Fleet of Re&s;erve
that lay behind; having &s;oon ob&s;erved the Con|&s;ternation
the <HI>Turks</HI> were put in by this unexpect|ed
Salute, and willing to improve their Confu&s;i|on
to his Advantage, got on Board in Per&s;on one
of the lighte&s;t Gallies, Mann'd only with forty
Men, giving the Signal for the re&s;t to follow him,
with all the Oars they could. Thus the Enemy
found them&s;elves &s;urrounded on all Sides by the
<HI>Mu&s;covites,</HI> who Attack'd them with great Brave|ry;
the <HI>Czar</HI> him&s;elf Boarding the <HI>Turki&s;h</HI> Admi|ral,
and being &s;ucce&s;sfully Seconded by the re&s;t,
the Victory was almo&s;t as &s;oon compleated, as be|gan.
The <HI>Turks</HI> being Routed &s;o entirely, that
not one Galley e&s;cap'd, but what was either Sunk
or taken; and it mu&s;t be confe&s;s'd, that the <HI>Czar</HI>
&s;hew'd &s;o much Conduct during the whole Action,
that no more could have been expected, from the
Prudence and Valour of the greate&s;t Captain of
our Time.</P>
<P>ANOTHER Account of this Affair expre&s;&s;es
it &s;elf in the&s;e Words.</P>
<P><PB N="27" REF="28">
AT length it is agreed on all Hands, that the
City of <HI>A&s;oph,</HI> which the <HI>Turks</HI> and <HI>Tartars</HI> had in
vain attempted to Relieve; both by Sea and Land
was Surrender'd to the <HI>Mu&s;covites,</HI> upon Articles
the 28th, of <HI>July;</HI> in pur&s;uance of which, the Gar|ri&s;on
con&s;i&s;ting of three Thou&s;and Men, be&s;ides
<HI>Tartars,</HI> March'd out with their Arms and Bag|gage;
300 pieces of Cannon were found in the
Town, together with a great quantity of Ammu|nition:
But want of Provi&s;ion ha&s;ten'd the Sur|render
of the Town; this Town was formerly
call'd <HI>Tanais,</HI> as being Seated upon the River <HI>Ta|nais,</HI>
now call'd <HI>Don,</HI> the ancient Bounds of <HI>A&s;ia</HI>
and <HI>Europe</HI> to the <HI>North-Ea&s;t:</HI> It is a Town of great
Trade, e&s;pecially in <HI>Furrs,</HI> lying not above 15
Miles from the Mouth of the River, upon the
con&s;ines of <HI>Mu&s;covy;</HI> but that which makes it
more Con&s;iderable is, that it affords the <HI>Mu&s;co|vites</HI>
and <HI>Co&s;&s;acks</HI> a fair Opportunity to become
Ma&s;ters of the <HI>Euxinus</HI> or <HI>Black-Sea,</HI> and gives an
Entrance to the Victor, to penetrate as far as
<HI>Con&s;tantinople</HI> it&s;elf, for which Rea&s;on, it has been
more than once Conte&s;ted for by the <HI>Turks,</HI> and
<HI>Mu&s;covites.</HI></P>
<P>THE News of this Lo&s;s was known at <HI>Con&s;tan|tinople,</HI>
upon the 7th, of <HI>Augu&s;t,</HI> which put the
City into a great Con&s;ternation, for fear of lo&s;ing
tho&s;e Supplies of Provi&s;ions that come to that City
by the <HI>Black-Sea.</HI> They tell us al&s;o, of a Victory
obtained over the <HI>Turks</HI> and <HI>Tartars,</HI> by the <HI>Mu&s;|covites</HI>
near <HI>Precoop;</HI> which Succe&s;&s;es as they re|vive
the Reputation of the <HI>Mu&s;covite</HI> Arms, and
render formidable an Enemy; that for &s;everal
Years has hardly been thought worth taking No|tice
of; &s;o the Confequences of their Pro&s;perity,
<PB N="28" REF="29">
may chance to prove more Fatal, then was at fir&s;t
expected to the <HI>Ottomen</HI> Empire.</P>
<P>THE <HI>Mu&s;covites</HI> have lain untalk'd of a great
Time, and the <HI>Turk</HI> has look'd upon them, as a de|&s;picable
Enemy for many Years: But 'tis &s;carce to
be imagin'd how &s;oon the change of the Monarch's
Genius, alters the Manners and Conditions of a
Nation; the Warmth and Vigour of Martial
Princes, infu&s;e the &s;ame warlike Motions into
the Brea&s;ts of the People, as the voluptuou&s;ne&s;s
of a di&s;pirited Sovereign effeminates them, and o|verwhelms
them in Sloath and Cowardice. The
<HI>Mu&s;covites</HI> are now another &s;ort of People; they
have a Valiant, and politick Leader, under who&s;e
Conduct they have wre&s;ted one of the chief Barri|ers
of the <HI>Ottoman</HI> Empire, from the <HI>Turks,</HI> who
were Vanqui&s;h'd fir&s;t by Sea, and then by Land:
Encouraged thus by Pro&s;perity, what may not the
<HI>Mu&s;covites</HI> do? they want neither Numbers or
Strength of Bodies; and there are few Princes
that can re&s;i&s;t the Temptations of Succe&s;s, &s;o
that it is high time for the <HI>Sultan</HI> to call to his re|membrance,
how often the&s;e <HI>Northern</HI> Deluges,
have proved Fatal to the Empires of the <HI>South.</HI></P>
<P>THESE accounts &s;hew the Sentiments of the
re&s;t of <HI>Europe,</HI> concerning the <HI>Czar</HI> of <HI>Mu&s;covy,</HI>
and his Affairs at that Time; and the Advantage
which the <HI>Czar</HI> was repre&s;ented with to the re&s;t of
the Princes of that Age. The <HI>Turks</HI> in particular,
were under a ju&s;t Con&s;ternation, and indeed, they
had Rea&s;on, when they came to under&s;tand that
the <HI>Czar</HI> had Built Men of War at <HI>Veranowitz,</HI>
which carried 700r 80 Guns each, and which would
in Time, be able to Cope with the be&s;t Ships the
Port was able to fit out. This gave them a ju&s;t
Allarm, even at <HI>Con&s;tantinople</HI> it&s;elf, which City
<PB N="29" REF="30">
would be but ill able to Sub&s;i&s;t, &s;hould the Free|dom
and Commerce of the <HI>Black-Sea</HI> be taken from
them, or even Di&s;puted with them; and there|fore
the <HI>Turks</HI> are not to be blam'd at all, for the
great Conditions which they Granted the <HI>Czar</HI> of
<HI>Mu&s;covy</HI> afterwards, when they had him as it were
in their Power, for the Recovery of this impor|tant
Place out of his Hands.</P>
<P>WHEN the <HI>Czar</HI> had made this Conque&s;t, he
was far from contenting him&s;elf with letting it
remain in the Condition he found it in; but know|ing
of what Con&s;equence it was to the <HI>Turks,</HI> as
well as now to him&s;elf, he immediately order'd it to
be Strengthned with new Fortifications, and that
of &s;uch a Kind, as render'd it the mo&s;t impreg|nable
Place in tho&s;e Parts of the World; he not
only repair'd the old Works, and added two new
Ba&s;tions to the Body of the Place, but he cau&s;ed a
new Counter&s;carp, with a cover'd Way to be
drawn round the whole, and the Ditch to be Se|cur'd
with half Moons, Lunettes, Tenailles, and
all &s;uch nece&s;&s;ary Out-works, as might render it
Inacce&s;&s;ible; bringing the River <HI>Donne</HI> &s;o into the
Ditches, as that it might be &s;aid, not that the Ri|ver
&s;upply'd the Ditches with Water, but rather,
that the River ran round the Town.</P>
<P>ON the other hand, in the low mar&s;hy Grounds
on the <HI>South-Side</HI> of the River, which the River u|&s;ually
over-flow'd, and which was a meer Bog, his
<HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty cau&s;ed fir&s;t, a firm &s;olid Founda|tion
to be made with Timber, Stones, Gravel, and
the like Materials; and having rais'd the whole
Surface to a con&s;iderable height, above the u&s;ual
Flux of the Water: He Built a Royal Fort upon
it, containing &s;ix Ba&s;tions, with their Cavaliers
Courtins, and Counterguards, with &s;ome Out-Works
<PB N="30" REF="31">
where it was needful; joyning the whole
afterwards to the main Land, with a prodigious
Stone-Bridge of thirty Arches, reaching over the
whole Mora&s;s.</P>
<P>THUS he made the Place truely Impregnable,
there being no Attacking the &s;aid Fort by any of
the u&s;ual Methods of Approach, the whole Ground
round it being to be laid under Water by Sluices
appointed for that purpo&s;e, when ever the Garri|son
found it convenient.</P>
<P>IN this po&s;ture the <HI>Czar</HI> left <HI>A&s;oph,</HI> at the lat|ter
end of the next Year (<HI>viz.</HI>) 1697, and the <HI>Turks</HI>
had as littles hopes of over Recovering it again,
as any Prince could de&s;ire; he al&s;o left it well
&s;tor'd with all manner of military Provi&s;ions,
having above 400 pieces of Cannon mounted up|on
the Works, and Ammunition in proportion;
and left in it be&s;ides, a Garri&s;on of 15000 Men.</P>
<P>AND now it was, that his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty
re|solv'd to furni&s;h him&s;elf with a Royal Navy, not
of Gallies and Brigantines, Saiks and Armed
Barks, &s;uch as was the u&s;ual Ve&s;&s;els for tho&s;e Seas:
But of capital Men of War, of 60 to 80 Guns
each, the Magazine and Center of which, and of
the Stores belonging to them, &s;hould be always
laid up at <HI>A&s;oph,</HI> and the Ships them&s;elves be pre|&s;erv'd
in the River <HI>Donn</HI> at proper Places, of
which I &s;hall give a farther Account; waiting till a
convenient Port might be po&s;&s;e&s;s'd in the <HI>Black-Sea,</HI>
where they might be laid up and Secur'd.</P>
<P>WITH the&s;e va&s;t Thoughts, the <HI>Czar</HI> left the
Place, and cea&s;ed not after he was gone, to go
immediately forward with the Execution of it;
and here may be &s;aid to be laid one of the fir&s;t
Foundations of that Re&s;olution this Prince took
to go Abroad; not only to furni&s;h him&s;elf with
<PB N="31" REF="32">
Skill in all the mechanick Parts of Know|ledge,
nece&s;&s;ary in carrying on &s;uch Undertakings;
but likewi&s;e to furni&s;h him&s;elf with able In&s;tru|ments,
Men of Knowledge and Capacity for &s;uch
Things, that might not only do the Work for him
as Occa&s;ion requir'd, but In&s;truct al&s;o his own
People to do it after them.</P>
<P>AT his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty's return from this Con|que&s;t,
he took a Re&s;olution to make a publick
triumphal Entry into his capital City of <HI>Mu&s;cow,</HI>
and that with all-the Pomp and Splendor that was
po&s;&s;ible to be Devi&s;ed; but it is worth ob&s;erving,
that this was not founded upon the Vanity of
Temper, which Princes have often been &s;ubject to
upon &s;uch Occa&s;ions; but from the true <HI>Roman</HI>
Principle of provoking Emulation in Vertuous
Actions among his Nobility, and for acquainting
his People with the Value and Importance of the
Victory he had obtained.</P>
<P>IN this triumphal Entry it was ob&s;erv'd, that
there was one of his Officers who&s;e Name was <HI>Ja|cob,</HI>
had in the fir&s;t Siege of <HI>A&s;oph,</HI> not only De|&s;erted
to the Enemy, but Nail'd up &s;ome of the
<HI>Czar</HI>'s Cannon, and thereby encourag'd the Garri&s;on
to make a de&s;perate Sally on that Side, in
which they ruin'd the Works, and &s;o Di&s;courag'd
the <HI>Mu&s;covite</HI> Soldiers, as was one great Rea&s;on of
rai&s;ing the Siege: This <HI>Jacob</HI> was at the &s;econd
Siege &s;urrender'd by the <HI>Turks,</HI> the <HI>Czar</HI> having
refu&s;ed to Grant any Terms to the Garri&s;on, un|le&s;s
he had this Traytor deliver'd up to him.</P>
<P>THIS Wretch made Part of the Triumph of
the <HI>Czar;</HI> he was carried Naked and Chain'd on
a Stage in an open Waggon, with a Gibbet over
his Head; on which, after he had been three times
Tortur'd, he was publickly Hang'd for the Terror
<PB N="32" REF="33">
of Traytors; &s;ome &s;aid he was broken fir&s;t alive,
which however, I do not affirm.</P>
<P>AT this Triumph of the <HI>Czar,</HI> there was an o|pen
Court, and all the Boyars or Noblemen of
<HI>Ru&s;&s;ia,</HI> were admitted to come and Ki&s;s the <HI>Czar</HI>'s
Hand, and pay their Complements on the Occa|sion,
which was a Favour they were not admitted
to formerly, but as the <HI>Czar</HI> re&s;olv'd to acquaint
his People with the Cu&s;toms and u&s;uage of other
Countries, &s;o he began already to make the open
free Conver&s;ation of the <HI>French,</HI> and <HI>British</HI> Na|tions
Familiar to them.</P>
<P>AFTER this, the <HI>Czar</HI> call'd them all to an
A&s;&s;embly, where he open'd and explain'd to 'em,
the Nature and Advantages of his Conque&s;ts on
the <HI>Black-Sea;</HI> and how he intended to improve
it to the welfare of his own Dominions, in &s;e|curing
the Navigation of the &s;aid <HI>Black Sea</HI> to
them, by a powerful Navy, and perhaps to obtain
a Commerce even thro' the narrow Chanels, at
<HI>Can&s;tantinople</HI> into the <HI>Levant.</HI></P>
<P>To this purpo&s;e, it was ea&s;ie to convince them
of the Nece&s;&s;ity of building a good Fleet of ca|pital
Men of War, &s;uch as &s;hould be always a
Match for the Grand <HI>Seignior</HI>'s Fleet, and &s;hould
maintain the Commerce if need were by &s;trong
Hand: And at the end of this Di&s;cour&s;e, he ac|quainted
&s;ome of them, that he re&s;olv'd to Tra|vel
in Per&s;on to &s;ome of the Maritime Courts of
<HI>Europe,</HI> to make him&s;elf compleat Ma&s;ter of the
Mea&s;ures of tho&s;e Nations, who were &s;o Superior
to the re&s;t of the World by their naval Strength;
and withal, to bring back with him the be&s;t Ar|ti&s;ts
that could be found; not only to undertake
the Building part for his fir&s;t Fleet, and for the
pre&s;ent Occa&s;ion, which admitted no delay; but
<PB N="33" REF="34">
also to in&s;truct his own People in all the nece&s;&s;a|ry
Arts, Handicrafts, and Workman&s;hip which
might be wanting; that &s;o in time none but his
own Subjects might be employ'd, and they might
be capable, in time to come, to make <HI>Mu&s;covy</HI> the
Terror of all its Enemies. That they had the
Materials for building and equipping the greate&s;t
Ships in the World, and in &s;uch Plenty, that all
the Marine Powers of <HI>Europe</HI> were oblig'd to &s;eek
to them for their Naval Stores; and it was an un|accountable
Indolence and Neglect, that they
alone &s;hould be ignorant of the building of Ships,
and of the Sea Service of every kind, who were
furni&s;hed by Nature and Providence with the
principal Funds of all Naval Provi&s;ions: That
they had Timber for the Hulls and Ma&s;ts of Ships
enough to &s;upply all the World; Hemp and Flax
for Cordage, Cables and Rigging; Iron for Anchors,
Bolts, Spikes, Nails and Tools; Pitch and Tar for
Caulking, Graving, Paying, and for working and
pre&s;erving the Cordage and Rigging; that all the
Nations of <HI>Europe</HI> were &s;upplyed with tho&s;e things
from <HI>Mu&s;covy,</HI> and it was very hard that <HI>Mu&s;covy</HI>
alone &s;hould not know how to u&s;e and apply all
the&s;e for them&s;elves, but that they &s;hould buy and
hire Ships of other Nations, and even of tho&s;e who
fir&s;t fetch'd the materials from <HI>Mu&s;covy</HI> by which
tho&s;e Ships were made.</P>
<P>THIS was a Di&s;cour&s;e too rational not to con|quer
the Judgment of any rea&s;onable Creature,
who was not before po&s;&s;eds'd with an invincible
Prejudice. But how far it fail'd to an&s;wer his
Expectation, as to the Impre&s;&s;ions it made on the
Minds of his People, we &s;hall have frequent occa|sion
to &s;ee.</P>
<P><PB N="34" REF="35">
BUT <HI>Mu&s;covy</HI> is not the only Nation in the
World that are to be made Great, Rich, and
Happy again&s;t their Wills; and in &s;pight of the
mo&s;t o$ &s;tinate endeavours to ruin them&s;elves;
there have been Nations infatuated before them,
tho' I think &s;carce ever in &s;o gro&s;s a manner.</P>
<P>FOR in&s;tead of receiving ju&s;t Notions of the
Wi&s;dom of &s;uch Councils, of the Opportunity
that pre&s;ented to rai&s;e the Glory and Reputation
of their Country, and to lay a Foundation of Wealth
and Opulence for their Po&s;terity, they made this
very Di&s;cour&s;e a Foundation of Faction, and even
of Rebellion and Trea&s;on; forming a Con&s;piracy
again&s;t not the Government only of the <HI>Czar,</HI> but
again&s;t his Life al&s;o, and giving tho&s;e very De|&s;igns
of his for the advantage of his Country, as
Rea&s;ons for their con&s;piring his De&s;truction.</P>
<P>AND that which was &s;tranger &s;til than all
this, was, that in forming the&s;e Factions, and $o|menting
the Trea&s;on I &s;peak of, they brought in
the Clergy to in&s;inuate to the People, that it was
contrary to the Principles of the <HI>Greek</HI> Church to
oblige the People to conver&s;e with Foreigners,
and much more to bring Foreigners in among
them on any pretence whatever; pretending that
they would poi&s;on the People with Erroneous
Doctrines, and Heretical Opinions, and that it was
Dangerous to their Religion; <HI>and the like.</HI></P>
<P>IT is to no purpo&s;e to exclaim here again&s;t the
Ab&s;urdity of the&s;e Things, it is &s;ufficient to my
Hi&s;tory to relate the Fact as it lies before us,
which I &s;hall do in its order as di&s;tinctly as po&s;&s;ible.</P>
<P>THE Triumph of the Day being over, and the
Traytor <HI>Jacob</HI> executed as above, the <HI>Czar</HI> ap|plyed
him&s;elf with his u&s;ual Re&s;olutions and Vi|gor,
<PB N="35" REF="36">
in per&s;uit of what he had propo&s;ed to him&s;elf
as above: <HI>Fir&s;t,</HI> he ordered the building &s;uch
Men of War as he had immediate occa&s;ion for,
and to this purpo&s;e tax'd his principal Noblemen
with &s;uch proportions towards the Expence, as he
thought fit, and as by the Cu&s;tom of that ab&s;o|lute
Government he might legally do; allowing
them however this alternative, that if any particu|lar
Nobleman did not think fit to advance &s;uch
&s;ums of Money, and &s;uch numbers of Workmen
as he was Tax'd at, he might take upon him&s;elf
the Work, and build &s;uch Ship or Ships, or &s;uch
part of a Ship, or furni&s;h &s;uch quantity of Mate|rials
as were equivalent to the proportion of Mo|he
was a&s;&s;e&s;&s;ed at.</P>
<P>BESIDES this, his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty obliged &s;uch
particular degrees of his Boyars and Gentlemen as
he thought proper, to &s;end abroad their Sons into
Foreign Countries, to &s;tudy and to improve them|&s;elves
in &s;uch arts, as were nece&s;&s;ary to qualify
them for publick Employments; particularly Ma|thematicks,
Navigation, Engineering, and the
like; who&s;e Expence however, the <HI>Czar</HI> ordered to
be &s;upplyed out of the publick Trea&s;ury.</P>
<P>WHILE the <HI>Czar</HI> was thus bu&s;ied in laying
a Foundation of Glory and Greatne&s;s for his Sub|jects,
<HI>Hard lot of Princes!</HI> his Subjects re&s;i&s;ting
their own Advantages, were Con&s;piring again&s;t
his Life, and in a word form'd the mo&s;t horrid
Trea&s;on again&s;t their Sovereign, and for the cut|ting
off all that were faithful to him, and to the
Intere&s;t of their Country, that has been heard of
in any Age.</P>
<P>It is true the Hi&s;tory, <HI>if the few and loo&s;e ac|counts
that are to be found of this affair de&s;erve the
Name of Hi&s;tory,</HI> of the&s;e things, lay the main
<PB N="36" REF="37">
part of this Trea&s;on upon the Prince&s;s <HI>Sophia</HI> his
<HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty's Si&s;ter: But as this turbulent La|dy
was a clo&s;e Pri&s;oner on account of former Con|&s;piracies,
and that it was not ea&s;ie for her to cor|re&s;pond
or to carry on any Con&s;piracy with Peo|ple
without Doors, without, giving ground of
&s;u&s;picion; So tho' &s;he might be made acquainted
with the Plot, yet none of the Con&s;pirators,
tho' put to the extrene&s;t Torture, ever charg'd
that Prince&s;s with being the Author of it.</P>
<P>THE fir&s;t of this Plot as I find it either in the
publick Accounts, or from private Intelligence,
was founded in the Di&s;contents of the Nobil$$y,
at being rated, or tax'd for the building of Ships
of War for the <HI>Black Sea,</HI> after the manner as
above: All the other Pretences were brought in
as an accumulated Charge upon the <HI>Czar,</HI> for im|po&s;ing
Novelties upon them, &s;uch as the &s;end|ing
their Sons abroad to Travel, a thing always
not only avoided, but even forbid in <HI>Mu&s;covy,</HI>
and reckon'd or e&s;teem'd to be unlawful; nay,
even the very building of Ships was counted Exo|tic
and Ab&s;urd, and was rendred as a wicked De|sign
to pu&s;h at foreign Conque&s;t, and bringing
War upon the Country.</P>
<P>THE better and more effectually to embark
the Soldiery in the Quarrel, the <HI>Strelitzes,</HI> that
is to &s;ay, the &s;tanding Forces of the Empire, &s;uch
as were the Mamalucks in <HI>Egypt,</HI> the Pretorian
Bands in the <HI>Roman</HI> Empire, and the Janiza|ries
in <HI>Turky,</HI> were put in mind how hardly they
had been treated; how their number was conti|nually
le&s;&s;en'd by the Executions among them in
the former Tumult at the <HI>Czar's</HI> coming to the Ad|mini&s;tration;
how their number was not made up,
or their Companys recruited, but as they were put
<PB N="37" REF="38">
upon the harde&s;t Services on all occa&s;ions, &s;o their
Companies being not fill'd up, it was apparent
the <HI>Czar</HI> had a mind to wear them out by De|grees;
that the pre&s;ent <HI>Czar</HI> had no Affection for
them, and had vowed their De&s;truction; and that
his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty had frequently declared he
would &s;uppre&s;s the very Name of them as a Body;
all which, in fact, might be true; for the <HI>Czar</HI>
not only had no occa&s;ion for them, but re&s;olved,
in time, to &s;ink the Name of them out of the
Army.</P>
<P>NOW, much of this might be true (<HI>viz.</HI>) that
the <HI>Czar</HI> having had terrible experience of the mu|tinous
Temper of the Strelitz, and how they often
took upon them to act in a bloody and furious
manner; in&s;ulting the Government, and even
their Prince, pretending to &s;et up or depo&s;e who|ever
they plea&s;ed, had &s;ecretly re&s;olv'd to let them
wear gradually out, and by warm Service and hard
Duty, to wear away as fa&s;t as they could, without
&s;uffering them to be fill'd up or recruited, and he
had abundant rea&s;on to re&s;olve to do &s;o.</P>
<P>THESE Men were therefore the more ea&s;ie to
be brought into any de&s;perate Mea&s;ures, to pre|vent
the annihilation of their Order, and to keep
up the figure they had always made in the Go|vernment;
and as their pretences of Di&s;gu&s;t were
very plau&s;ible and popular, &s;o they were the more
ea&s;y to be brought into the De&s;ign. But &s;till I
mu&s;t leave the dead weight of this Con&s;piracy up|on
tho&s;e People, who, as I &s;aid before, were
pinch'd by the new Order for &s;ending their Chil|dren
abroad, and upon the Boyars who were a|warded
to build Ships of War at their own charge,
they and their Va&s;&s;als as above</P>
<P><PB N="38" REF="39">
THESE Men provok'd at the Severity of the
<HI>Czar</HI>'s u&s;age of them, as they call'd it, were be|ginners
of the Trea&s;on, but they did not find it
&s;o hard as it might have been expected, to engage
others in it for the Rea&s;ons above-mentioned.</P>
<P>THE building of the&s;e Ships, which had not
been done in <HI>Russia</HI> before, and at the &s;ame time
obliging the Boyars and Gentlemen to &s;end their
Sons abroad to Travel, were both look'd upon as a
great Grievance, the one being not only to entail
a Charge upon them beyond the common Tax,
but of bringing in of Foreigners to build and &s;ail
their Ships; and the latter, (<HI>viz.</HI>) the &s;ending abroad
their Children, was &s;uch an innovation they could
not well bear; Be&s;ides this, it was in&s;inuated
by the Prie&s;ts, that it would be a means of cor|rupting
them in the Principles of their Religion,
and which they held to be a thing that was direct|ly
contrary to the Law of God; adhering to tho&s;e
Texts of Scripture which forbid the Children of
<HI>I&s;rael</HI> to have any Communion with the Nations
that were round about them, that they might not
partake of their Idolatry; for which Rea&s;on even
the Envoys which have been &s;ent heretofore to fo|reign
Courts, have been denied to take their Sons
with them; and upon pain of Death it was forbid
that any <HI>Mu&s;covite</HI> &s;hould go out of the Country
without e&s;pecial leave from the Patriarch; but
they now murmured that the <HI>Czar</HI> wholly adhered
to Strangers, went him&s;elf daily to their Hou&s;es,
and freely admitted them to his Conver&s;ation,
which &s;tirred up the di&s;contents of the Party that
were out of favour at Court, and who had been
made unea&s;y at their di&s;appointment &s;ince the
la&s;t Rebellion; who were &s;till in the Intere&s;t of
the Prince&s;s <HI>Sophia,</HI> and wanted to be them&s;elves
<PB N="39" REF="40">
at the head of the Government, they therefore
take this opportunity in hopes to give a turn to
Affairs, and that they might effectually bring
about their Purpo&s;e.</P>
<P>BUT to come to the matter of fact, the Con|spiracy
being laid deep as Hell, and cruel as Death,
is de&s;crib'd by one of the Writers of that time in
the following words:</P>
<P>&startq;NOTWITHSTANDING that the whole
Empire &s;eemed to take &s;hare in the glorious
Conque&s;ts of their Prince, and that nothing but
Fea&s;ting and Rejoicing were to be &s;een in all
parts during the whole Winter, there remained
neverthele&s;s a certain di&s;contented Party among
the Nobility, who being encouraged by the &s;e|cret
Cabals of the Prince&s;s <HI>Sophia,</HI> found means,
in &s;pight of her confinement, to keep an under|hand
Corre&s;pondence with her for the promo|ting
their de&s;igns again&s;t the <HI>Czar</HI>'s Per&s;on;
they were &s;o well prepared for the undertaking
of any Enterprize of this nature, that there
wanted but little Fuel to kindle the Flame,
they could not brook the lo&s;s of their beloved
Strelitzes, whom they had always looked upon
as the chief Supporters of their Authority,
which at la&s;t made them conceive &s;o implacable
a hatred again&s;t the <HI>Czar,</HI> that they entred in|to
a Con&s;piracy again&s;t his Life; to put their
Design in execution, they had brought over to
their Party four Captains of the fir&s;t Regiment
of Strelitzers; but the difficulty was, in what
manner the Attempt was to be made, for they
looked upon it as impracticable to declare open|ly
again&s;t a Prince, who, be&s;ides that he was
much beloved by the People, had at his Devo|tion
a good number of the be&s;t Troops, com|manded
<PB N="40" REF="41">
by foreign Officers, who were quarter|ed
in and about the City of <HI>Mu&s;cow,</HI> and ready
upon all Occa&s;ions to Sacrifice their Lives for
his Maje&s;ty; it was propo&s;ed among them, that
the <HI>Czar</HI> was u&s;ed to go &s;ometimes abroad with
very &s;lender Attendance, and to appear in the
Streets of <HI>Mu&s;cow</HI> without any con&s;iderable Re|tinue;
this was al&s;o look'd upon as too dange|rous,
con&s;idering the general Love the People
bore to the Per&s;on of the <HI>Czar.</HI>&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;AFTER many Debates it was at la&s;t re&s;olved,
that con&s;idering the <HI>Czar,</HI> who takes &s;hare in
every thing that concerns his Subjects Welfare,
was wont to appear in Per&s;on, in ca&s;e of any
accident of Fire, which frequently happens,
and makes mo&s;t terrible havock in the City of
<HI>Mu&s;cow,</HI> where most of the Hou&s;es are of Wood;
they looked upon this as the mo&s;t proper op|portunity
to encompa&s;s their De&s;ign; where|fore
it was concluded to &s;et Fire to &s;ome Hou&s;es
in the night time, when they did not que&s;tion
to draw the <HI>Czar</HI> thither, and during the con|fu&s;ion,
to find means to A&s;&s;a&s;&s;inate him. The
next thing to be done was, according to their
own Confe&s;&s;ion, to have joined the <HI>Donaick Co&s;|&s;acks</HI>
with their Party, to have relea&s;ed the
Prince&s;s <HI>Sophia</HI> from her Confinement, recalled
Prince <HI>$$a&s;&s;ily Galickzin</HI> out of <HI>Siberia,</HI> and &s;urren|dred
the Admini&s;tration of the Government in|to
their hands, who were also to re&s;tore the Stre|litzes
to their antient Station.&endq;</P>
<P>THIS was the Sub&s;tance of the Plot, and to car|ry
it on more effectually, four Captains of the Stre|li$zes,
or Troops of the Hou&s;hold were brought
into it, be&s;ides &s;everal great Men as well in the
Court as in the Army.</P>
<P><PB N="41" REF="42">
THE Attempt was now ripe for Execution,
and a great number of the Strelitzes were come pri|vately
into the Town to a&s;&s;i&s;t at the horrid work
of murthering their Sovereign, and perhaps at
that of de&s;troying the whole City; for any one
that knows the City of <HI>Mu&s;cow,</HI> how that not on|ly
the Hou&s;es, but even the Pavement, as we call
it of the Streets, are all of Wood; and what ha|vock
a Fire often makes among them, may ea&s;ily
&s;uppo&s;e, that the City being wilfully fired in three
places, and the People being put into &s;uch a Fright
and Confu&s;ion, as would have been the ca&s;e at the
murther of their Emperor, and of &s;uch bloody and
cruel Executions, or rather Butcheries, as would
nece&s;&s;arily have follow'd &s;uch a thing, the nece&s;&s;ary
care for extingui&s;hing the Fire would be omitted
in a great mea&s;ure, and perhaps the greater part
of the City had been de&s;troy'd, which is horrible
but to think of.</P>
<P>THE Day appointed for the Execution was the
20th of <HI>Feb.</HI> 1697, when the Evening before two
of the Captains of the Strelitzers, namely, Cap|tain
<HI>Largou Gili&s;aroski</HI> and Captain <HI>Greg Siteri,</HI>
went and di&s;covered the whole Plot to the <HI>Czar,</HI>
who was then at Supper at Mon&s;ieur <HI>le Fort</HI>'s, a
<HI>French</HI> Gentleman, of whom mention is often
made in this Relation. The account of the Di&s;|covery,
with the Name and Fate of the Con&s;pi|rators,
take in a few words from another Pen as
follows.</P>
<P>&startq;It was on the fir&s;t Day of <HI>February</HI> in the
Year 1697, when his Maje&s;ty was informed
concerning this Con&s;piracy formed again&s;t his
Life, at the Hou&s;e of General <HI>le Fort,</HI> were he
happened to dine that Day; he appeared very
little moved at &s;o &s;urpri&s;ing a piece of News;
<PB N="42" REF="43">
but without any change in his Countenance, aro&s;e
from the Table, and being followed only by a few
Persons in whom he confided mo&s;t, he went di|rectly
to the Hou&s;e of one of the Con&s;pirators,
who&s;e Name was <HI>John Sickler,</HI> and elevated by
the <HI>Czar</HI> to the chief Dignity of a Coun&s;ellor of
State. When his Maje&s;ty came to the Hou&s;e of
this wicked Wretch, he commanded the re&s;t to
remain without Doors, and he him&s;elf entred, only
with three Gentlemen more, and pretending he
had occa&s;ion to ask his advice in &s;ome matter
of moment, ordered he &s;hould follow him; but
no &s;ooner was he come into the Street but he
was &s;eized and immediately carried to Pri&s;on,
as were likewi&s;e five more, to wit, the Boyar
<HI>Alexis Sekonnin, Feodore Puskin,</HI> Son of the Boyar,
<HI>Matfefeoa Puskin,</HI> Ten Captains of the Strelitzes,
and a <HI>Donaick Co&s;&s;ack;</HI> they all confe&s;&s;ed their
Crimes, and being condemned by all the Boyars,
were executed on the fifth Day of <HI>March</HI> in the
Year 1697, in the great Market-place before
the Ca&s;tle. Fir&s;t their Arms and Legs were cut
off, then they had their Heads &s;evered from
their Bodies; their Heads were fixed on the top
of a Stone Column erected for that purpo&s;e,
and their Arms and Legs &s;tuck upon Iron Bars
round about it; the Trunks of their dead Car|ca&s;&s;es
were left in the Market-place for eight
Days after, till the &s;cent became &s;o nau&s;eous to
the Inhabitants, that they were forced to be re|moved
from thence.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;IT having by confe&s;&s;ion of &s;ome of the Con|&s;pirators
been made apparent, that the Boyar
<HI>Ivan Milo&s;laski</HI> was the chief Head of the Rebel|lion
which happened in the Year 1682, immediately
after his pre&s;ent <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty's Ac|ce&s;&s;ion
<PB N="43" REF="44">
to the Crown, his Body was di&s;interred,
which being found very near entire, without
any con&s;iderable decay, tho' it had lain under
ground near twelve Years; &s;everal Gibbets
were erected, on which were hung the Quarters
of the Carca&s;s, which were torn to pieces in an
in&s;tance by the enraged Multitude.&endq;</P>
<P>THE Severity of the Executions in this Ca&s;e
are excu&s;ed by their being at <HI>Mu&s;covy,</HI> where Ex|perience
has taught them, that &s;uch Executions
are needful; and where if &s;uch a &s;evere cour&s;e had
not been taken, it might have been hard to per|&s;wade
the People to believe that the Con&s;piracy
had been real, or the Government in earne&s;t.</P>
<P>WHEN his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty had ma&s;ter'd the&s;e
Commotions, and all things were calm again, the
<HI>Czar</HI> who was now &s;o re&s;olv'd upon his De&s;ign, as
that nothing could divert him, I mean as to his
Travelling Abroad, began to prepare publickly
for his going, and to let the &s;editious Boyars
know that he was not under the lea&s;t Apprehen&s;i|ons
from any thing they were able to do in his
ab&s;ence, he made it publick al&s;o, in who&s;e Hands
he re&s;olved to entru&s;t the Government in his ab|sence:
He appointed a good Army to Encamp
within a League of the City of <HI>Mu&s;cow,</HI> of whom
a &s;trong Detatchment were to do Duty daily at
the Palace; and among all the&s;e Troops which
amounted to 22000 Men, it was e&s;pecially pro|vided,
that none of the Strelitzers were allow'd,
intimating, that the <HI>Czar</HI> who had re&s;olv'd to &s;up|pre&s;s
effectually that body of Men, did not think
them worthy to be entru&s;ted with the protection of that Government which they had so often at|tempted
to di&s;turb.</P>
<P><PB N="44" REF="45">
WHILE this was doing, Expre&s;&s;es came fre|quently
in from <HI>A&s;oph,</HI> and from General <HI>Skeen</HI>
who commanded the Army there, with News of
Advantages gain'd every Day over the Tartars
and Rebel <HI>Co&s;acks,</HI> of whom great numbers were
often cut off; and that General, who is a vigilant
Officer, daily extended his Quarters in the <HI>Crim Tar|tary,</HI>
ravaging the Country and bringing in a great
Booty: So that all things went on that &s;ide
to his mind; and as the <HI>Turks</HI> had their Hands full
in <HI>Hungary</HI> with the Imperiali&s;ts, who had beaten
them in &s;everal great Battels, and continued their
Conque&s;ts till even <HI>Con&s;tantinople</HI> it &s;elf began to
tremble at them, they were in no condition to do
any thing towards the recovery of <HI>A&s;oph;</HI> &s;o that
the <HI>Czar</HI>'s Affairs were in a mo&s;t Formidable Po&s;ture
on that &s;ide.</P>
<P>THE Preparations for the intended Progre&s;s
of the <HI>Czar</HI> were now fini&s;hed; and tho' I cannot
&s;ay I have a full account of them, neither perhaps
was any full account ever publi&s;hed; yet, as I
believe, the following Particulars are rather &s;hort
of, than an over reckoning of the va&s;t Trea&s;ure and
Expence furni&s;hed on this Occa&s;ion, I &s;hall tran&s;mit
it as I find it, leaving the Reader to judge of
the Rea&s;onablene&s;s and Truth of the Relation by
the Particulars they will meet with in the account
of the Journey.</P>
<P>IT was for &s;ome time unre&s;olv'd in what Ca|pacity
his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty &s;hould Travel, and &s;e|veral
Propo&s;itions were con&s;idered of, as particu|larly
fir&s;t, that he &s;hould go as a private Gentle|man,
and with a &s;mall Retinue, which was the
fir&s;t Propo&s;al. (2.) As a Clergy-man of the <HI>Greek</HI>
Church, as had been practi&s;ed by &s;ome of his
boyars the Year before. (3.) As an <HI>Armenian</HI>
<PB N="45" REF="46">
Merchant, under which Di&s;gui&s;e &s;everal <HI>Per&s;ians</HI>
and <HI>Turks</HI> had travelled into <HI>Europe;</HI> for as to go|ing
publickly, and owning him&s;elf to be what he
really was, <HI>Czar</HI> or Emperor of <HI>Mu&s;covy,</HI> that the
<HI>Czar</HI> him&s;elf had re&s;olved again&s;t for many &s;ub|&s;tantial
Rea&s;ons; as, (1.) The Expence of it.
(2.) The lo&s;ing the opportunity of in&s;pecting per|sonally
into things, which he had with great Rea|&s;on
&s;een could not be done but in a private Capa|city.
And (3.) Becau&s;e the whole time would be
taken up in Shows and Ceremonies, things below
the important De&s;ign of the Journey, and utterly
incon&s;i&s;tent with it. At length Mon&s;ieur <HI>le Fort</HI>
propo&s;ed what the <HI>Czar</HI> immediately approved, a
method which as he &s;aid would con&s;i&s;t both with
the Honour and Safety of his Maje&s;ty's Per&s;on,
and yet give him all the opportunity of a Con|cealment
that he could de&s;ire, and this was, that
a &s;olemn Emba&s;&s;y &s;hould be &s;ent from his Maje&s;ty
to all the Courts to which he had intended to go,
with a Compliment of Honour, and Propo&s;als of
Amity and Commerce; and Amba&s;&s;adors to be
ve&s;ted with full Plenipotentiary Powers to enter
into Treaties of Alliance and Treaties of Com|merce
with the &s;aid Nations re&s;pectively; and
that his Maje&s;ty &s;hould Travel <HI>Incognito</HI> in the
Retinue of his &s;aid Amba&s;&s;adors, and under the
Protection of the Emba&s;&s;y it &s;elf, by which means
it would at the &s;ame time be known that he was
per&s;onally pre&s;ent, and thereby his Emba&s;&s;y
would be receiv'd with the greater Di&s;tinction;
and yet as he would be at liberty to receive all
po&s;&s;ible Ceremony and Honour where he thought
fit to accept it, &s;o he would be at liberty to de|cline
it al&s;o, as he found occa&s;ion.</P>
<P><PB N="46" REF="47">
THIS hit his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty's Thoughts imme|diately,
and was &s;o perfectly agreeable to his
whole De&s;ign, which was to make him&s;elf Ma&s;ter
of all the Methods of the Nations he intended to
pa&s;s thro,' in the management of their Military
and Naval Affairs; and particularly of all Ma|thematical
and Mechanical Knowledge, which he
pre&s;ently fore&s;aw he &s;hould by this Method be
fully able to do.</P>
<P>THIS being therefore re&s;olv'd on, &s;everal
things remain'd to be done, and were to be
fully concerted before-hand.</P>
<P>1. WHO &s;hould be the Amba&s;&s;adors appointed
for this Honourable Po&s;t.</P>
<P>2. WHO the Government &s;hould be committed
to in the <HI>Czar</HI>'s ab&s;ence. what Power &s;hould
be committed to them in the Admini&s;tration, and
what Forces &s;hould be left them.</P>
<P>5. WHAT Nations the Amba&s;&s;adors &s;hould go
to, and the Form of their Powers.</P>
<P>4. THE rai&s;ing a &s;ufficient Sum of Money for
the Expences of &s;uch an Emba&s;&s;y, and for the ex|traordinary
Service abroad, namely, of purcha&s;ing
things proper to be brought away, and what Sum
would be wanting.</P>
<P>5. PROVIDING &s;uch Jewels and Cloths, Li|veries
and Habits as the Amba&s;&s;adors and their
Servants &s;hould have occa&s;ion to appear in on the
occa&s;ion of Publick Entries, Audiences, <HI>&amp;c.</HI> or
for pre&s;ents to carry with them.</P>
<P>6. THE determining who &s;hould be appointed
to Travel with or after the Emba&s;&s;y.</P>
<P>THE re&s;olving the&s;e Particulars took up &s;ome
time, &s;everal of them being of very great Con&s;e|quence,
and we find they were adju&s;ted with a
great deal of Prudence and Caution.</P>
<P><PB N="47" REF="48">
THE Choice of the Per&s;ons of the Amba&s;&s;adors
fell upon the&s;e three; <HI>Fir&s;t,</HI> General <HI>le
Fort</HI> Captain of the Guards, and at that time Ad|miral
of the Fleet, who, as he was a <HI>Frenchman</HI>
born, had liv'd many Years at <HI>Am&s;terdam,</HI> and
&s;ome time in <HI>Italy,</HI> &s;o he in the fir&s;t place was
fully acquainted with all the Cu&s;toms and Man|ners
of tho&s;e Countries, and capable of advi&s;ing in
the particular Mea&s;ures to be ob&s;erv'd in each
Country; and of the Ceremonial; as well what
Re&s;pect was to be &s;hewn, as what was to be ex|pected
where-ever they came; and in the next
place, as he knew the Language, &s;o he &s;erv'd the
<HI>Czar</HI> as an Interpreter upon the mo&s;t important
Occa&s;ions. The next was <HI>Theodore Alexiamvitz
Golloffkin,</HI> a Grave Maje&s;tick Per&s;on, and fully ac|quainted
with the Intere&s;t and Trade, as well as
the Laws and Cu&s;toms of <HI>Mu&s;covy,</HI> and how to
carry on any Treaty of Commerce, or receive
Propo&s;als for the Advantage and Intere&s;t of Trade;
having been Chancellor of the whole Empire, and
the &s;ame who formerly made the Treaty of Peace
between his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty and the Emperor of
<HI>China,</HI> of which we &s;hall &s;peak in its place, and
who had been twice by Land at <HI>China</HI> in the Qua|lity
of Amba&s;&s;ador and Plenipotentiary to the
Emperor there. The third was call'd, <HI>Proco|$et
Bodgnanovitz Woluitzin,</HI> who had been employ'd
in &s;everal Emba&s;&s;ies to the Grand Seignior, and
was perfectly acquainted with his Ma&s;ter's Inter|e&s;ts,
with re&s;pect to the <HI>Turks,</HI> the &s;ettling Limits,
the Affair of <HI>A&s;oph,</HI> and in any thing el&s;e that
might happen on that &s;ide, e&s;pecially if at <HI>Vienna</HI>
any Propo&s;als of an Accommodation &s;hould be
made to the Emperor and his Allies.</P>
<P><PB N="48" REF="49">
THESE were the three Amba&s;&s;adors to whom
the whole Affair was committed; nor were there
three Men equally capable to &s;o great a Work in
his whole Dominion; and as his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty
was always with them, there was no occa&s;ion of
any delay, or &s;pinning out the Negotiations, as is
u&s;ual in other ca&s;es.</P>
<P>THE General <HI>le Fort</HI> was made fir&s;t Plenipo|tentiary,
and con&s;equently was at the Head of this
Emba&s;&s;y, being partly qualifyed by his Know|ledge
in the Languages and Cu&s;toms of <HI>Europe</HI> as
above, to appear at the head of all the Negotia|tions.</P>
<P>THE &s;econd Article (<HI>viz.</HI>) who the Admini|&s;tration
of the Government &s;hould be committed
to in the <HI>Czar</HI>'s ab&s;ence, was &s;oon re&s;olv'd by the
<HI>Czar</HI> him&s;elf, who pitch'd upon the Princes <HI>Na|riskin,
Procorofski,</HI> and <HI>Boris Galitzen,</HI> all faith|ful
Servants of the Crown, and &s;teady in the Per|sonal
Intere&s;t of the <HI>Czar;</HI> the fir&s;t being the <HI>Czar</HI>'s
Mother's own Brother and prime Mini&s;ter; the
&s;econd the Grand Receiver, or Lord Trea&s;urer,
an ancient faithful Prince, always &s;teady to the
<HI>Czar</HI> and to his whole Family; and the third a
particular Favourite, po&s;&s;e&s;&s;ing &s;everal high Tru&s;ts
in the Government, and va&s;tly rich al&s;o him&s;elf.</P>
<P>THE Military Tru&s;t was committed to Gene|ral
<HI>Skeen</HI> or <HI>Scherin,</HI> who was made Generali&s;&s;imo
for all that concern'd the War again&s;t the <HI>Turks</HI>
and <HI>Tartars</HI> on the Borders of the <HI>Black-Sea,</HI> and
on the &s;ide of <HI>Circa&s;&s;ia;</HI> and to General <HI>Gordon,</HI> a
<HI>Scots</HI> Man, for what concern'd the Guard of the
Palace and Capital City of <HI>Mu&s;cow,</HI> and all the
Northern Parts of the <HI>Czar</HI>'s Dominions: The
former had under his Command the whole Army
<PB N="49" REF="50">
at and in the Neighbourhood of <HI>A&s;oph,</HI> or from
<HI>A&s;tracan</HI> to <HI>Kai&s;erkameen</HI> on the <HI>Bori&s;thenes;</HI> and
the other had the Command of the re&s;t of the Troops,
as well at <HI>Mu&s;cow</HI> as afore&s;aid, as on the Frontiers
of <HI>Poland</HI> and of <HI>Sweden, Courland, &amp;c.</HI> and had
in particular the Charge given him of Protecting
the Admini&s;tration in the hands of the three
Princes above-mentioned.</P>
<P>3. THE third Article was to con&s;ider what Na|tions
or Courts this Emba&s;&s;y &s;hould be directed
to, and this was &s;oon determined; the Rout or
Cavalcade being ordered to pa&s;s forward thus;
Fir&s;t to <HI>Pru&s;&s;ia</HI> and the Court of <HI>Berlin.</HI> II. To
<HI>Holland.</HI> III. To <HI>England.</HI> IV. To <HI>Vienna</HI> to the
Emperor. And La&s;tly, to <HI>Venice:</HI> The&s;e being
the Capital places where Military and Naval
Knowledge were now to be found in the greate&s;t
Perfection; except in <HI>France,</HI> which for weighty
Rea&s;ons his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty re&s;olv'd not to go
to <HI>France,</HI> at that time, being engaged in a heavy
War again&s;t almo&s;t all the other Princes of <HI>Eu|rope.</HI></P>
<P>4. THE next Head was the Funds for the Ex|pence
of this Journey: This the <HI>Czar</HI> took up|on
him&s;elf to direct; and I am a&s;&s;ur'd that his
<HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty &s;et apart for this Work above two
Millions of Rubles, which in <HI>Engli&s;h</HI> Money is near
800000 Pounds Sterling; but I do not po&s;itively
affirm that &s;o great a Sum was taken: Mo&s;t of
this Money, be the Sum what it will, was ex|pended
in buying Ships, materials for forwarding
&s;everal Sciences for the publick u&s;e in <HI>Mu&s;covy,</HI> as
al&s;o for buying Arms, Artillery and Ammuniti|on
to be &s;ent to <HI>Mu&s;covy.</HI></P>
<P>5. THE Povi&s;ion for Pre&s;ents to be made to
&s;uch Princes, and States where they were to appear
<PB N="50" REF="51">
in Ceremony, and for Audiences, for which
purpo&s;e twenty large Bales of the riche&s;t Furs,
&s;uch as Sables, Ermins, <HI>&amp;c.</HI> were provided, and
&s;everal Bales of rich Cloth of Gold made in
<HI>Per&s;ia</HI> and <HI>Georgia;</HI> and &s;everal Parcels of very
valuable Jewels, as al&s;o &s;ome fine <HI>Turki&s;h</HI> and
<HI>Tartarian</HI> Hor&s;es.</P>
<P>6. THE determining who &s;hould be appointed
to Travel with the <HI>Czar;</HI> and this Article was ve|ry
Significant, as it intimated that the <HI>Czar</HI> took
with him about Forty Per&s;ons of the Prime Rank
in his Dominion, or their Sons; This was call'd
an Honour done them, but was wi&s;ely determined
to &s;ecure them from Plotting and Con&s;piring a|gain&s;t
him during his ab&s;ence: In the mean time
&s;uch other Noblemen as were Di&s;tru&s;ted, or out of
Favour, were commanded to retire to their own
Seats, and not to come to the City of <HI>Mu&s;cow,</HI> or
to Court on pain of Death.</P>
<P>HAVING thus with an inimitable Conduct
a&s;&s;ur'd things at home to his full Satisfaction,
and having taken of the Foreign Merchants in his
Dominions Bills of Exchange upon Merchants in
<HI>Holland</HI> and <HI>England</HI> for a great part of the Trea|&s;ure
he had appointed for his Journey; and all
things being ready to depart; the Baggage was &s;ent
before with a &s;trong Guard, and having obtained
proper Pa&s;&s;es for the whole Emba&s;&s;y for <HI>Koning&s;|burgh,</HI>
a City in the Ducal <HI>Pru&s;&s;ia</HI> belonging to the
King of <HI>Pru&s;&s;ia,</HI> then Elector of <HI>Brandenburgh,</HI> his
Maje&s;ty &s;et out the &s;econd of <HI>May,</HI> or thereabouts,
him&s;elf going <HI>Incognito</HI> at &s;ome di&s;tance from his
Amba&s;&s;adors and their Train, and the 10th of the
&s;ame Month be entred the Province of <HI>Livonia,</HI> at
that time belonging to the <HI>Swedes.</HI></P>
<P><PB N="51" REF="52">
IT was &s;aid his Maje&s;ty receiv'd &s;ome ill Treat|ment
at <HI>Riga,</HI> that is to &s;ay, they declin'd &s;ati&s;|fying
his Curio&s;ity in letting him view the Works
and Forts in the manner he de&s;ir'd; and as it was
the fir&s;t Town compleatly fortified after the <HI>French</HI>
manner, his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty was the more pre&s;&s;ing
to make his Ob&s;ervations, which they not admit|ting,
extremely di&s;gu&s;ted him; but he has had op|portunity
to remember it &s;ince, to the Co&s;t of
the <HI>Swedes,</HI> from whom he took not that City only,
but the whole Province in a few Years after, and
remains po&s;&s;e&s;s'd of them to this Day; and 'tis
ob&s;erved that the Re&s;entment of the U&s;age of his
Amba&s;&s;adors, for he does not take notice of his
being in Per&s;on with them, is mentioned in his
Declaration of War again&s;t <HI>Sweden,</HI> as one of the
Cau&s;es of his breaking the Peace with them.</P>
<P>BUT he found him&s;elf treated after a quite
different manner at the next Place of Note he
came to, which was at <HI>Koningsberg</HI> the Capital of
the Ducal <HI>Pru&s;&s;ia</HI> as above: Hither the Duke of
<HI>Brandenburgh,</HI> &s;ince King of <HI>Pru&s;&s;ia,</HI> came with his
whole Court to receive and entertain him; and
here the <HI>Czar</HI> re&s;olv'd to &s;how the World the fir&s;t
Specimen of his Glory and Greatne&s;s. His Em|ba&s;&s;y
had hitherto a Retinue of Three Hundred
per&s;ons, &s;everal little Troops of Guards arm'd,
&s;ome with Bows, &s;ome with Battle Axes, and o|thers
with Lances; and abundance of the young
Nobility, who afterwards were di&s;pers'd to other
parts, were at this fir&s;t Entry.</P>
<P>THE manner of this glorious Entry, as it was
publi&s;h'd and &s;pread in Print in all the Languages
of <HI>Europe,</HI> take as follows.</P>
<P>&startq;THE Letters are dated from <HI>Koningsberg</HI> in
<HI>Pru&s;&s;ia</HI> May 31. <HI>N. S.</HI> That the Amba&s;&s;adors
<PB N="52" REF="53">
from the <HI>Czar</HI> of <HI>Mu&s;covy,</HI> who are the Lords
<HI>Francis Jacow Lewits Le Fort, Mexiewits Holo|win,</HI>
and <HI>Precophei Bodanowitz Wornitzien,</HI> being
arriv'd upon the <HI>Thur&s;day</HI> Morning before
at <HI>Lauterburg,</HI> within a Mile of the City,
with a train of Three Hundred Per&s;ons;
the Elector of <HI>Brandenburgh</HI> immediately &s;ent
away M. <HI>Dankelmen</HI> to compliment the Am|ba&s;&s;adors
in his Name, and to keep them com|pany
After Dinner, Mr. <HI>Be&s;&s;er,</HI> the Ma&s;ter of
the Ceremonies, arriv'd at the &s;ame place al&s;o,
with a great company of Nobility to conduct
them to the City, at what time their Excellen|cies
taking Coach with M. <HI>Dunkelmen,</HI> and M.
<HI>Be&s;&s;er,</HI> in one of the Elector's Coaches, about
four a Clock that Afternoon made their Publick
Entry into <HI>Koningsberg</HI> in the following manner,
Fir&s;t came his Electoral Highne&s;&s;es Led Hor&s;es,
to the number of Forty. Secondly, an Officer
attended by the Kettle Drums of the Guards,
and Three Troops of the Guards of the Body
clad in Red; next the principal Nobility of
Ducal <HI>Pru&s;&s;ia</HI> in Twenty Six Coaches with Six
Hor&s;es, then two of the Elector's Coaches, and
One of the Margrave <HI>Albert</HI>'s; after them the
Court Pages Two and Two, with a Page of the
Amba&s;&s;adors between 'em in Red Liveries Lac'd
with Gold Lace. Sixthly, the chief Mini&s;ters
and Officers of the Elector's Hou&s;hold in Thirty
Six Coaches. Seventhly, the fir&s;t Kettle-Drum,
and the fir&s;t Trumpet belonging to his Electo|ral
Highne&s;s, follow'd by the Amba&s;&s;ador's Foot
Guards clad in Green, with each a Silver Bat|tle
Axe upon his Shoulder; then Thirty of the
Amba&s;&s;adors Hor&s;e-guards in the &s;ame Livery,
but without Battle Axes. Ninthly, the Coach
<PB N="53" REF="54">
wherein their Excellencies rode. La&s;tly, the
march was clos'd with twelve Coaches fill'd
with <HI>Mu&s;covite</HI> Gentlemen and <HI>Brandenburghers.</HI>
Their Excellencies being thus conducted over
the <HI>Karkerbrug</HI> to a magnificent Lodging pre|pared
for 'em in the long Street of <HI>Kneiphoff,</HI>
the Burghers being drawn up in a double File,
and lining the Streets all the way, and a trip|ple
di&s;charge of all the great Guns &s;aluting
them from their entrance into their Lodging,
where the Garri&s;on of the City &s;tood to re|ceive
them: So &s;oon as they alighted they were
conducted to their Apartment, which was guard|ed
by twenty Soldiers; and then the Lords of
the Court, together with M. <HI>Dankelman,</HI> and
the Ma&s;ter of the Ceremonies left 'em, and
were waited on by the Amba&s;&s;adors to the Stairs
of the Hou&s;e.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;UPON the Fourth of this In&s;tant, <HI>N. S.</HI> they
had their Publick Audience of the Elector, to
which they were conducted by M. <HI>Dankelman,</HI>
and the Ma&s;ter of the Ceremonies above-nam'd,
with a Train of Thirty Coaches; before the
Amba&s;&s;adors went Thirty Per&s;ons carrying the
<HI>Czar</HI>'s Pre&s;ent to the Elector; the Amba&s;&s;adors,
who were richly habited in Cloth of Gold
and Silver embroider'd with precious Stones,
being enter'd into the great Hall of the Ca&s;tle,
where the Elector was &s;eated upon a Throne
attended by the principal Lords of his Court,
made their Reverences; and after they had
every one in their order complimented the E|lector
in &s;hort but &s;ignificant Speeches, they
deliver'd him the Pre&s;ent, and a Letter pur|porting,
that the <HI>Czar</HI> had &s;ent the &s;aid Em|ba&s;&s;y
to his Electoral Highne&s;s to a&s;&s;ure him of
<PB N="54" REF="55">
his de&s;ire to improve the Affection and good
Corre&s;pondence which had always been, as well
between him, as his illu&s;trious Ance&s;tors. That
the &s;ame Emba&s;&s;y being from thence to pro|ceed
to the Court of <HI>Vienna,</HI> in order to farther
Con&s;ultations and Propo&s;itions for the continu|ance
of the War again&s;t the <HI>Turks</HI> and <HI>Tartars.</HI>
His <HI>Mu&s;covite</HI> Maje&s;ty therefore reque&s;ted the
Elector to a&s;&s;i&s;t 'em in their Journey, withal
returning his Electoral Highne&s;s thanks for the
Engineers and Bombardiers which he &s;ent him the
la&s;t Year, and which had been &s;o u&s;eful to him
in the Siege of <HI>A&s;oph:</HI> To all which the E|lector
an&s;wer'd, that he was much oblig'd to
the <HI>Czar</HI> for the a&s;&s;urance of his good intentions,
and the &s;plendid Emba&s;&s;y he had &s;ent him.
And then M. <HI>Dankelman</HI> return'd an An&s;wer
more at large, and very obligingly to the Com|pliments
of the &s;everal Amba&s;&s;adors, who were
after that reconducted to their Lodgings with
the &s;ame Ceremonies, and treated with a &s;plen|did
Dinner at the Elector's Charge. The &s;ame
Evening they were al&s;o entertained with a
Shew of Fireworks which la&s;ted till Midnight.
Their Pre&s;ent con&s;i&s;ted of Sables, Ermins, and
other rich Furrs, &s;everal f$owered Silks and Ti&s;|&s;ues
of Gold and Silver; and other precious
Rarities, valu'd in all at Seventy Five Thou|&s;and
Crowns&endq;</P>
<P>DURING his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty's &s;tay at this Court
he receiv'd the News by an Expre&s;s of the Electi|on
of the Elector of <HI>Saxony,</HI> now King <HI>Augu&s;tus,</HI>
to the Crown of <HI>Poland;</HI> and as his Maje&s;ty had
before di&s;covered him&s;elf to be in the Intere&s;t of
that Party, which oppos'd the Prince of <HI>Conty</HI>'s
Election; &s;o upon this News he immediately &s;ent
<PB N="55" REF="56">
a Mini&s;ter to the new King, to make his Com|pliment
of Congratulation, and to declare pub|lickly,
that he would &s;upport his Preten&s;ions,
and would maintain him on the Throne with his
whole Power; and particularly, that he would
cau&s;e an Army of 60000 Men to march immedi|ately
to the Frontiers of <HI>Lithuania</HI> to be under his
Maje&s;ty's Orders, for his A&s;&s;i&s;tance in ca&s;e of
need.</P>
<P>ALL the while of the &s;tay of the Emba&s;&s;y, the
Elector of <HI>Brandenbourgh</HI> did every thing that was
po&s;&s;ible, as well to &s;hew his own Magnificence,
as to Honour the Emba&s;&s;y of &s;o great a Monarch;
and e&s;pecially con&s;idering that this Emba&s;&s;y, how|ever
glorious in it &s;elf to the Court of <HI>Pru&s;&s;ia,</HI> was
yet the more &s;o by the addition of this Article,
that the <HI>Czar,</HI> the greate&s;t Monarch of the <HI>Ea&s;t,</HI>
was there in Per&s;on, under the &s;helter of the Am|ba&s;&s;adors
his Servants.</P>
<P>HIS <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty had here &s;everal Occa&s;ions
to Conver&s;e intimately with the Elector, and
that with the greate&s;t Freedom and Openne&s;s;
communicating to him the Rea&s;on of his coming
thus out of his own Dominions, and pa&s;&s;ing
<HI>Incognito:</HI> I have been told that the Elector,
a Wi&s;e and Polite Prince, exceedingly approv'd
and applauded his Intentions,' and &s;aid &s;ome very
fine things both of his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty in his Mi|ni&s;ter's
ordinary Di&s;cour&s;e, as well as per&s;onally
to him; and at the Conclu&s;ion, willingly entred
into a Defen&s;ive Treaty with his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty's
Amba&s;&s;adors. In a word, the Elector omitted
nothing that could either te&s;tify his Affection to
the <HI>Czar</HI> in the mo&s;t obliging manner, or add any
A&s;&s;i&s;tance to him or his Retinue, cau&s;ing them to
be defray'd at his own Expence, not at <HI>Koning&s;|berg</HI>
<PB N="56" REF="57">
only, but all the while he was pa&s;&s;ing thro'
his Dominions.</P>
<P>FROM hence his Maje&s;ty went by Water thro'
the <HI>Pillau</HI> and the <HI>Frei&s;ch Haft,</HI> as it is call'd, to
<HI>Dantzick;</HI> the Elector ordering &s;ome Yachts to at|tend
his Maje&s;ty in the Pa&s;&s;age. This Water
call'd the <HI>Frei&s;ch Haft,</HI> is an Inland Lake or Wa|ter
which reaches from the <HI>Pillau</HI> near <HI>Koningsberg,</HI>
to a Branch of the great River <HI>Vi&s;tula,</HI> which
pa&s;&s;es by <HI>Dantzick,</HI> and by which Ve&s;&s;els pa&s;s
from <HI>Koningsberg</HI> to <HI>Dantzick,</HI> and is &s;eparated
from the Sea by a narrow Tract of Land not above
three Leagues over, which however lies parallel
with the &s;aid <HI>Haft,</HI> and entirely parts it from the
main Sea.</P>
<P>HIS <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty took great Delight in &s;ail|ing
upon this Water, and in ob&s;erving the dex|trous
manner of the Seamens working the Yachts,
in turning to Windward, and the like; and he &s;pent
&s;ome Days on purpo&s;e to divert him&s;elf in that
Water with &s;ailing up and down, the Weather
al&s;o being very plea&s;ant and agreeable at that
time.</P>
<P>ABOUT the 20th he arriv'd at <HI>Dantzick,</HI> where
the Burghers and Magi&s;trates treated his Amba&s;&s;a|dors,
and that is to &s;ay his Maje&s;ty him&s;elf, with
all po&s;&s;ible Di&s;tinction, and cau&s;ed all the Forts,
Lines, Magazines, and Haven or Port, and every
part of the Fortifications of that great City to be
&s;hown him; which Fortifications far exceeded tho&s;e
of <HI>Riga,</HI> and which was very much to his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI>
Maje&s;ty's Satisfaction. His Emba&s;&s;y made no
Entry here, being not directed to &s;ay any thing
to the Citizens as a Body, and as to their Sove|reign
the King of <HI>Poland,</HI> that Kingdom was at this
time as it were in an <HI>Interregnum,</HI> the late King
<PB N="57" REF="58">
<HI>John Sobieski</HI> being dead, and the new King <HI>Au|gu&s;tus</HI>
being but newly cho&s;en, and not yet
Crown'd.</P>
<P>HOWEVER, the Magi&s;trates of <HI>Dantzick</HI> re|ceiv'd
&s;everal Te&s;timonies of his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty's
Favour, and to let them know how well he was
pleas'd with their Conduct, a&s;&s;ur'd them of his
Favour and Protection upon all Occa&s;ions; And
as his Emba&s;&s;y had been pre&s;ented with great
quantities of fre&s;h Provi&s;ions, Wines, and Refre&s;h|ments,
&s;o much as was almo&s;t &s;ufficient for their
whole Retinue; in return of this the <HI>Czar</HI> cau&s;ed
his Amba&s;&s;adors to make the Magi&s;trates a pre&s;ent
of Sables, and other rich Goods to a very con&s;ide|rable
Value.</P>
<P>FROM hence his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty went direct|ly
thro' the Ducal <HI>Pomerania</HI> to the City of <HI>Berlin,</HI>
the Court of the Elector of <HI>Brandenbourgh,</HI> where
he was Royally entertained and his whole Em|ba&s;&s;y
and Retinue: They made no Publick Entry
here, it being the Court of the &s;ame Prince who
had receiv'd them with &s;uch Splendor at <HI>Koning&s;|berg:</HI>
But the <HI>Czar</HI> had here the Occa&s;ion of &s;eeing
the mo&s;t &s;plendid Court in <HI>Europe,</HI> except that of
<HI>France,</HI> and to Conver&s;e in the mo&s;t Polite man|ner;
and was &s;o exceedingly pleas'd with the
Gallantry and Magnificence of all he &s;aw here,
that he re&s;olved to &s;end his Son the Hereditary
Royal Prince to re&s;ide there for &s;ome time to fi|ni&s;h
and poli&s;h his Manners for the great things
which they then &s;uppos'd him to be born to: But
time furni&s;hed the <HI>Czar</HI> with Rea&s;ons to take o|ther
Mea&s;ures, with re&s;pect to that Prince, of which
in its Order.</P>
<P>FROM <HI>Berlin</HI> the <HI>Czar</HI> bent his cour&s;e towards
the <HI>Low Countries,</HI> where his &s;olemn Emba&s;&s;y was
<PB N="58" REF="59">
principally de&s;ign'd to appear; and it is certain
the <HI>Dutch,</HI> that is to &s;ay the <HI>States,</HI> had made it
much of their bu&s;ine&s;s to obtain this Honour;
intimating to the <HI>Czar</HI> their de&s;ire to form &s;uch
Treaties of Commerce and A&s;&s;i&s;tance as might
be for the mutual Profit of the Subjects of both
Nations; and particularly their Re&s;olution to
furni&s;h his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty with Workmen, Build|ers,
Shipwrights, and Trade&s;men of every kind,
nece&s;&s;ary for the Building of his Men of War;
and as they had obtain'd an a&s;&s;urance that his
<HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty intended to Honour them with
his Pre&s;ence, and with his Emba&s;&s;y, &s;o they were
not wanting in all the nece&s;&s;ary Preparations, to
give him a Reception &s;uitable in &s;ome mea&s;ure to
the greatne&s;s of his Per&s;on and Character.</P>
<P>IT was not till the Month of <HI>Augu&s;t</HI> that the
Amba&s;&s;adors could &s;et their Foot in the Territo|ries
of the <HI>States General:</HI> For tho' my bu&s;ine&s;s is
to write of the <HI>Czar,</HI> and of him per&s;onally, yet
I mu&s;t be allowed to &s;peak here only in the
Name of the Emba&s;&s;y and of the Amba&s;&s;adors.
As &s;oon as the <HI>States General</HI> had notice of their
arrival upon their Frontiers, they &s;ent a &s;olemn
Deputation to attend them at <HI>Nimeguen,</HI> from their
whole Body; for them, and in their Names, to
bid them welcome into their Country, to de|fray
all the Charges of the &s;aid Amba&s;&s;adors
and their whole Retinue, to receive them at
the fir&s;t entrance into their Bounds, and to com|pliment
them accordingly.</P>
<P>THUS they were carried thro' all the Towns
with the noi&s;e of Cannon, and of &s;mall Arms on
the one hand, and with the Shouts and Acclama|tions
of the People on the other; the States being
willing to pre&s;erve the Memory of their being
<PB N="59" REF="60">
thus honoured by &s;o &s;olemn an Emba&s;&s;y, the mo&s;t
Glorious that had ever been &s;een in the&s;e Parts of
the World.</P>
<P>IT would be to omit the mo&s;t glorious Demon|&s;tration
of the <HI>Ru&s;&s;ian</HI> Greatne&s;s, if I &s;hould fail
to give a full Account here as well of the said
Publick Entry, as of the great Ceremony of Au|dience
given the&s;e Amba&s;&s;adors afterwards at the
<HI>Hague,</HI> and al&s;o of the noble Appearance and
Deportment of the Amba&s;&s;adors them&s;elves; ne|ver
any Men from the Polite&s;t Nation under Hea|ven
behav'd better, or made their Speeches with
a better Grace, or better became the Character
they bore.</P>
<P>IT is certain the <HI>States-General,</HI> who, as I &s;aid
before, had earne&s;tly de&s;ir'd this Occa&s;ion of
&s;howing their Re&s;pect to his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty,
intended to receive his Amba&s;&s;adors with great
Marks of Di&s;tinction, and e&s;pecially knowing that
the <HI>Czar</HI> was in Per&s;on with them: But they
found them&s;elves a little &s;urpriz'd when they
came to &s;ee the Amba&s;&s;adors them&s;elves; their
Per&s;ons, their Behaviour, and the perfect Know|ledge
they had of every thing that came before
them to Di&s;cour&s;e of; the Judgment they made
of the Intere&s;ts of Nations, and of the Advan|tages
of Commerce, the manner of extending it,
and of what was fit to propo&s;e or not to propo&s;e
in that part; and al&s;o the Judgment they were
able to make of their being well or ill treated;
&s;o that upon &s;eeing what &s;ort of Mini&s;ters they
had to do with, the States found it nece&s;&s;ary to
out-do, if po&s;&s;ible, what they had at fir&s;t intend|ed
in the Honours they de&s;ign'd them.</P>
<P>WE are to &s;uppo&s;e them now pa&s;s'd thro' the
<HI>Lower Saxony,</HI> and approaching the Frontiers of
<PB N="60" REF="61">
the States Country; the States Deputies gone to
meet and compliment them in the Name of the
Republick, and conducting them to <HI>Sourdam,</HI> near
the Capital City of <HI>Am&s;terdam,</HI> and to defray their
Charges upon the Way. The next thing is that
of their Publick Entry, which was the 26th of
<HI>Augu&s;t.</HI></P>
<P>THE Magnificence of their Reception here
con&s;i&s;ted of &s;everal parts, that is to &s;ay, not only
in their meer Entry into the City, which was in|deed
very fine, but in the Entertainment they
had there till the time they went to their Publick
Audience at the <HI>Hague;</HI> and al&s;o in the Recepti|on
they had at the &s;everal Cities which they pa&s;s'd
thro', as well before they came to <HI>Am&s;terdam,</HI> as
when they went from thence to the <HI>Hague;</HI> in all
which it is to be ob&s;erved, that tho' the <HI>Czar</HI> was
a con&s;tant Eye-witne&s;s to the Reception of his
Amba&s;&s;adors, and had a great deal of Rea&s;on to
be very well &s;atisfied with the Honours they re|ceiv'd,
which indeed was no more or le&s;s than
Honours done to him&s;elf in the Per&s;ons of his
Servants; yet his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty keeping firm to
his fir&s;t Re&s;olutions of being conceal'd, and of not
appearing in Publick, was never &s;een in any of
the publick Cavalcades; but either went in the
Retinue conceal'd in the ordinary Dre&s;s of a pri|vate
Per&s;on, or had him&s;elf placed in &s;ome pri|vate
Station to be a Spectator of what pa&s;s'd, as we
&s;hall find he did at their Audience at the <HI>Hague;</HI>
and if he was at any time di&s;covered, as was on
Two or Three Occa&s;ions his ca&s;e, while he was in
<HI>Holland,</HI> nothing gave him more unea&s;ine&s;s, nor
would he leave till he found him&s;elf &s;o di&s;guis'd
$word$ to be able to go publickly about and not be
known.</P>
<P><PB N="61" REF="62">
THIS, and his de&s;ire to view the Yards, the
Docks, the building of Ships, and all the parti|cular
Operations of the Carpenters, Caulkers,
Anchor-&s;miths, Black-&s;miths, Rope-makers, and
&s;o of all the re&s;t, I &s;ay this, made him for &s;ome
time Dre&s;s him&s;elf in the ordinary Habit of a
common Seaman with a <HI>Monmouth</HI> Cap, a &s;hort
Jacket and wide Breeches, &s;o that it was impo&s;&s;ible
to di&s;cover him; and in this Di&s;gui&s;e I have been
a&s;&s;ured, tho' I cannot affirm it of my own knowl|edge,
that he has &s;uffered him&s;elf to be hired in|to
their Carpenters Yards as a Workman, and has
both performed a Day's Work, and received his
Wages. But I &s;ay again, that I rather repeat this
from other hands, than &s;ay I believe it, or re|commend
it to others to believe.</P>
<P>BUT let that be as it will, certain it is, that
in this Di&s;gui&s;e he had a compleat liberty, with|out
the Interruption of the Crowding, and Curio|&s;ity
of the People to look at him; I &s;ay he had
the liberty of &s;eeing every thing that was done,
and al&s;o, <HI>which was the main thing to him,</HI> how it
was done.</P>
<P>BUT to return to the Amba&s;&s;adors, the Depu|ties
&s;ent to receive them on the Borders of the
Country, having brought them to <HI>Sourdam,</HI> a
Town about Miles from <HI>Am&s;terdam,</HI> they
were lodg'd there till the Preparations could be
made for their Reception in the City, which was
done at the Charge of the Magi&s;trates; the Pro|ce&s;&s;ion
was in the following manner.</P>
<P>IN the Morning early Five Deputies from the
States of <HI>Holland,</HI> and Three from the City of
<HI>Am&s;terdam,</HI> attended the Amba&s;&s;adors at <HI>Saurdam,</HI>
to Compliment them on their Arrival, and to In|vite
<PB N="62" REF="63">
them into the City; and the Yacht's of the
State were order'd to lye ready to attend them,
and take them on Board, with all their Retinue;
which was done accordingly, and they arriv'd at
the Place appointed for their Landing about ten
a$Clock.</P>
<P>A certain Number of the Magi&s;trates were
Deputed to attend them at their Landing, with
about fifty Coaches of the Burgoma&s;ters, and of
the Principal Citizens, and were to Complement
them on their Arrival. The Principal young Ci|tizens
form'd them&s;elves into a Troop, and being
well Mounted, and with extreamly rich Furni|ture
and Equipage, attended their Excellencies
Entry, being to the Number of near three Hun|dred
Hor&s;e.</P>
<P>BESIDES the&s;e the principal Citizens, and
all the Per&s;ons of Di&s;tinction went to meet them
in their Coaches to a very great Number.</P>
<P>AS &s;oon as the Amba&s;&s;adors landed, and were
&s;eated in their Coaches, the Cannon from the
Ramparts fir'd round the whole City, and under
the Thunder of the &s;aid Guns the Cavalcade be|gan.</P>
<P>IN the fir&s;t Place march'd a Body of the City
Officers to clear the Way, and prevent Di&s;orders
from the infinite Throng of People in the Streets;
then march'd 16 Companies of the Burghers un|der
Arms, who when they came to the Place
appointed for them, form'd two Lines to Lin$e
the Street, thro' which the Amba&s;&s;ador and their
whole Retinue were to pa&s;s, other Bodies of the
Burghers under Arms, lin'd the re&s;t of the Way
to the Place where the 16 Companies took their
Po&s;t.</P>
<P><PB N="63" REF="64">
NEXT to the&s;e came the Troop of young
Gentlemen on Hor&s;eback, very richly Dre&s;s'd,
and their Equipages <HI>as before</HI> very &s;plendid; and
before them went the States Trumpets, and City
Mu&s;ick; then came a &s;mall Troop of <HI>Circa&s;&s;ian
Tartars</HI> on Hor&s;eback, being of the Amba&s;&s;adors,
Retinue, arm'd with Bows and Arrows; then &s;ix
and thirty <HI>Mu&s;covite</HI> Gentlemen on Hor&s;eback;
then twenty Pages of the Amba&s;&s;adors, clothed
in Scarlet lac'd, or rather overlaid with Gold
Lace; then came the elde&s;t Burgoma&s;ter's Coach
of State, in which were the Amba&s;&s;ador <HI>Le
Fort,</HI> and the <HI>Mu&s;covite</HI> Prince <HI>Me$$zike$$;</HI> then
the Grand Pen&s;ionary of <HI>Holland's</HI> Coach, in
which were the two other Amba&s;&s;adors, and another
<HI>Mu&s;covite</HI> Prince: On either &s;ide the&s;e Coaches,
march'd the Amba&s;&s;ador's Guard, on Foot, carry|ing
&s;ilver Battle-Axes, and by their Sides large
Scymetars; they were Clothed after the <HI>Sclavo|nian</HI>
manner, with &s;hort Doublets, and large
Breeches, and over them Scarlet Cloaks, or Robes
trim'd with &s;ilver Buttons, and large Loops, and
Scarlet lac'd with Silver very rich: After the&s;e,
came the re&s;t of the Coaches mention'd above, in
which were the re&s;t of the Amba&s;&s;adors Retinue;
among them the <HI>Czar</HI> him&s;elf, but Dre&s;s'd in an
ordinary Habit, &s;o as not be di&s;tingui&s;h'd; nei|ther
was it po&s;&s;ible to Di&s;cover him, tho' the
People were mighty inqui&s;itive about it.</P>
<P>AFTER the&s;e Coaches came 120 Coaches of
Citizens, Merchants and Gentlemen, who came
to wait upon the Amba&s;&s;adors; and among the&s;e
were the Magi&s;trates of the City; the whole
Clo&s;ing with another Body of Burghers in
Arms. But the Magi&s;trates did not End here,
<PB N="64" REF="65">
for after having thus Conducted the Amba&s;&s;adors
to their Appartments, they treated them in the
mo&s;t Magnificent manner immaginable, for five
Days &s;ucce&s;&s;ively, and thus prepar'd a mo&s;t ex|traordinary
Firework, rai&s;ed upon Floats, built
on purpo&s;e in the Water of the <HI>Am&s;tel.</HI> It would
take up too much Room in this Work, to give
the De&s;cription of this Firework, which was
fram'd in the mo&s;t Exqui&s;ite manner, that the
be&s;t Engineers and Architects could Invent; nor
was any Co&s;t &s;par'd in either, the Device or the
Building. In a Word, it was the mo&s;t Magnifi|cent
that ever was &s;een in the&s;e Parts of the
World, and his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty was exceedingly
pleas'd with it, as he had a great deal of Rea&s;on
to be; for it was Executed with all immaginable
in Order and Succe&s;s.</P>
<P>IT is true, this Sight was attended with an un|happy
Accident among the People, for that the
Railes of the Bridge over the River, being Crow|ded
with People, gave way, and above 100 Peo|ple
fell into the River, where about thirteen or
fourteen were Drown'd; and indeed it was a great
Wonder the Night being dark and the Water
deep and the Crowd &s;o great, that there were not
more lo&s;t.</P>
<P>HIS <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty was now in the Center
of his Bu&s;ine&s;s, and had before him the main
Thing he came to &s;ee; and therefore &s;hunning
all publick Appearances, other than tho&s;e which
Nece&s;&s;ity oblig'd him to, he took a &s;mall Hou&s;e,
near the <HI>Ea&s;t India</HI> Companies Yards or Docks,
that is to &s;ay, among the Shipwrights and Buil|ders,
and where he could with ea&s;e get Admit|tance
in Digui&s;e, to &s;ee every thing which he
<PB N="65" REF="66">
thought fit to Enquire after, and to take his Ob|&s;ervations
at his own Lei&s;ure.</P>
<P>IT is true, he was oblig'd to go from thence
for &s;ometime to the <HI>Hague,</HI> to &s;ee his Amba&s;&s;adors
admitted to a publick Audience of their High
Mightine&s;&s;es the States General; but he &s;oon re|turn'd
again and remain'd perfectly retir'd for
&s;ome Months, where he &s;pent his Time in the
mo&s;t u&s;eful Studies of Life (<HI>viz.</HI>) the gaining true
Ideas of the mo&s;t noble Things, and &s;earching the
height and depth of Mathematical Knowledge.</P>
<P>I &s;hould have ob&s;erv'd here that the <HI>Czar</HI> him|&s;elf
having receiv'd the Deputies on the Fron|tiers
of <HI>Guelderland,</HI> and being de&s;irous to Tra|vel,
perfectly undi&s;cover'd, left his Amba&s;&s;adors
and their Train, which was very great, to come
lei&s;urely forward with the &s;aid Deputies&punc; and
him&s;elf with only four or five Gentlemen di&s;guis'd
as ordinary Travellers, came to <HI>Am&s;terdam,</HI> four
or five Days before them, where he Lodg'd at fir&s;t
in a common Inn, or Hou&s;e of Entertainment,
and walk'd freely about the City, view'd the Situa|tion,
the Buildings, the River, the Port, and that
infinite Number of Ships, which always are to
be &s;een there; particularly he pitch'd upon the
Place for his Retreat, or private Re&s;idence, which as
I have mention'd above was among the Ship-Yards,
Docks and Building-Places, that he might parti|cularly
make his Ob&s;ervations of tho&s;e things;
The enquiry after which was his Delight, and
the e&s;pecial Bu&s;ine&s;s of his whole Emba&s;&s;y.</P>
<P>THE Ceremony ended as above, his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI>
Maje&s;ty retir'd to the Hou&s;e which he had Hir'd,
and went on with his Equipage and Ob&s;ervations;
and as he &s;poke Dutch indifferently well before, &s;o
he took occa&s;ion to Di&s;cour&s;e with all the Work|men
<PB N="66" REF="67">
and Arti&s;ts that he could find, who he di&s;co|vered
to have any tollerable Judgement in things
of that Nature. Nor was his Maje&s;ty &s;o retir'd,
but that he admitted &s;ome of the Merchants of
<HI>Am&s;terdam</HI> to his Conver&s;ation, and e&s;pecially
&s;uch as had re&s;ided in <HI>Mu&s;covy;</HI> that is to &s;ay at
<HI>Arch-Angel</HI> and <HI>Mu&s;cow,</HI> of which &s;everal were
then living in <HI>Am&s;terdam,</HI> and with the&s;e he would
be very free and Courteous, and &s;ometimes <HI>even
Merry</HI> only not allowing them to Treat him with
too much Ceremony and Di&s;tinction.</P>
<P>BY the Conver&s;ation of the&s;e Men he had &s;everal
People brought to him, who were mo&s;t
Ma&s;ters of Science, and who entertain'd his Ma|je&s;ty
very much to his Satisfaction, with the &s;e|veral
Experiments in Nature, in Phylo&s;ophy, and
in the Mathematicks, which they had made in the
Con&s;equence of long Study; and it was to their
Aftoni&s;hment how &s;oon, and how readily his <HI>Cza|ri&s;h</HI>
Maje&s;ty took in the ju&s;t Ideas, which their Di&s;|coveries,
and Experiments pre&s;ented, and how
knowingly he would Di&s;cour&s;e, even of tho&s;e
things, which he had received no Notion of before.</P>
<P>THE Deputies of the Admiralty al&s;o &s;hew'd their
re&s;pect to his Maje&s;ty, in cau&s;ing every thing that
was curious, relating to Naval Affairs to be &s;hew|ed
him, and Arti&s;ts of all kinds to be pre&s;ented to
him.</P>
<P>IN the mean time the publick Audience of his
Amba&s;&s;adors call'd him away to the <HI>Hague,</HI> where
he had the &s;atisfaction of &s;eeing their High-Migh|tine&s;&s;es
the States General do him the utmo&s;t
Honour in the Per&s;ons of his Amba&s;&s;adors, and
even to out do them&s;elves, no Audience having e|ver
been known like it in that Country.</P>
<P>IT would be tire&s;ome to relate the Magnifi|cence
of their Reception all the way from <HI>Am|&s;terdam</HI>
<PB N="67" REF="68">
to the <HI>Hague,</HI> whether they and all their
Retinue went the latter End of <HI>October.</HI></P>
<P>HIS <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty al&s;o having Intimation of
the great Preparations the <HI>States-General</HI> made for
the Reception of his Emba&s;&s;y, and for Gracing
their Audience, re&s;olv'd to make a &s;uitable pre|paration
for it on his Side; and therefore cau&s;ed
his Amba&s;&s;ador to make three of the mo&s;t Mag|nificent
Coaches that could be made for Money,
and order'd them to buy Jewels likewi&s;e, and
Cloths the Riche&s;t that could be had, to en|crea&s;e
their Retinue with about Forty more Ser|vants,
and to Cloth them and all the re&s;t in new
Liveries quite different from tho&s;e they had be|fore;
in a Word, he directed that every thing
&s;hould appear in the greate&s;t &s;plendor po&s;&s;ible;
&s;o that 'tis &s;aid the Expence co&s;t above 200000
Dollars extraordinary.</P>
<P>ALL things being ready, and the Audience ap|pointed,
they &s;et out from <HI>Am&s;terdam</HI> the 24th of
<HI>September,</HI> and arriv'd at the <HI>Hague</HI> the &s;ame Day.</P>
<P>THEIR publick Entry was infinitely Superi|or
to that at <HI>Am&s;terdam,</HI> this being at the Ap|pointment
of the <HI>States-General,</HI> the other only a
Reception of them by the Citizens and Magi|&s;trates
of <HI>Am&s;terdam;</HI> and yet the particulars of
this part were not &s;o publickly &s;et down as the o|ther,
what I have met with amounts to this.</P>
<P>THAT the Amba&s;&s;adors were receiv'd at a di|&s;tance
from the <HI>Hague,</HI> where they had gone on
purpo&s;e for the Occa&s;sion, by five Deputies of the
<HI>States-General</HI> as Introductors of Amba&s;&s;adors:
They were attended by the Reigment of Hor&s;e-Guards,
and two Battalions of the Guards of
Foot, call'd the Blew Guards; with two Coaches
of State, drawn by eight Hor&s;es each, for the Am|ba&s;&s;adors,
<PB N="68" REF="69">
and forty other Coaches with &s;ix Hor&s;es
each, for their Retinue.</P>
<P>THE Amba&s;&s;adors were preceeded by forty
Gentlemen on Hor&s;eback, habited as <HI>Co&s;&s;acks,</HI>
arm'd with Bows and Arrows, and thirty others as
<HI>Tartars,</HI> arm'd with Lances and Bows; all exceed|ing
richly Cloth'd, but after the manner of their
own Countries: They had forty Pages in different
Livery, but all cover'd with Gold and Silver Lace
as rich as po&s;&s;ible. Their immediate Guard were
as at <HI>Am&s;terdam,</HI> Habited after the <HI>Mu&s;covite</HI>
manner, carrying &s;ilver Battle-Axes in their
Hands, and Symetars with &s;ilver Hilts by their
Sides.</P>
<P>THE Amba&s;&s;adors were in two Coaches of
State, and their own new magnificent Coaches
follow'd, having Thirty two Footmen in rich Li|veries
walking on the Sides.</P>
<P>THE whole was follow'd with a numerous
Train of Coaches belonging to the Nobility and
Gentry, and to the foreign Mini&s;ters, of which
there are always a great many at the <HI>Hague,</HI> but
more e&s;pecially at that Juncture, it being the time
of that <HI>Congre&s;s</HI> for the Peace with <HI>France,</HI> call'd
afterwards the Treaty at <HI>Ry&s;wick.</HI></P>
<P>HIS <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty was in the Train in Di&s;|gui&s;e,
wearing a plain blew Coat, a large white
Perriwig, and a white Feather; and being perfect|ly
well acquainted both with the Person and ex|traordinary
Merits of the Sieur <HI>Wit&s;en</HI> (who was
that Year Burgoma&s;ter of <HI>Am&s;terdam</HI>) he borrow|ed
his Coach, and de&s;ir'd him to Accompany him
thit$$r; which was perform'd with &s;o much Dex|terity
and Secre&s;y, by the &s;aid Sieur <HI>de Wit&s;en,</HI>
that his Maje&s;ty was not di&s;cover'd by any body
living.</P>
<P><PB N="69" REF="70">
IT was in the Month of <HI>September</HI> of the &s;aid
Year, when there was the greate&s;t &s;how of foreign
Amba&s;&s;adors that ever was &s;een at the <HI>Hague,</HI> oc|ca&s;ion'd
by the Negotiation, <HI>as above,</HI> at <HI>Ry&s;wick:</HI>
Thither mo&s;t Courts of <HI>Europe,</HI> had &s;ent their
Plenipotentiaries, who all &s;triving to out vie
one another in Magnificence. It was no ea&s;ie Mat|ter
to add any thing to the Splendor of their Equi|pages;
yet his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty being &s;en&s;ible that
the Eyes of the World in a mo&s;t peculiar manner
would be fix'd upon his Emba&s;&s;y; and being in|vited
by a mo&s;t commendabl$ emulation to main|tain,
as well on that as other Occa&s;ions the glory
and lu&s;tre of his eminent Station in the World,
as claiming the Title of an Emperor, and bearing
the Imperial Arms; he was fully re&s;olv'd that
this mo&s;t &s;olemn Emba&s;&s;y, honour'd by his Pre|&s;ence
&s;hould bear the Marks of, and be fully an|&s;werable
to his high Station and Grandeur.</P>
<P>In effect according to the Te&s;timony of all that
were Spectators of this &s;olemn Audience, every thing
was manag'd with &s;o much order, maje&s;ty and gra|vity,
and with &s;o much Magnificence, that nothing
could add to the Lu&s;tre of this Solemnity, which
in all Re&s;pects was &s;uitable to his Maje&s;ty's De|sign.</P>
<P>IT is confe&s;s'd by all Hands that never any
Amba&s;&s;ador appear'd in a more &s;plendid Attire
then the General <HI>le Fort</HI> the <HI>fir&s;t</HI> Amba&s;&s;ador did
that Day; he was clad after the <HI>Mu&s;covite</HI> Fa&s;hi|on,
in a long Robe of Cloth of Gold, lin'd with
the mo&s;t precious Sables that ever were &s;een. This
Robe as well as the Ve&s;t which he wore under it,
was cover'd before with Diamonds in the Shape
of a Hern's feather, with &s;uch Lu&s;ter as dazl'dthe
Eyes of the Beholders; he Harang'd their High and
<PB N="70" REF="71">
Mightine&s;&s;es in the <HI>Ru&s;&s;ian</HI> Tongue, with an Air
altogether Maje&s;tick, and &s;uitable to the Cha|racter
he bore upon &s;o &s;olemn an Occa&s;ion. The
two other Amba&s;&s;adors, who appeared likewi&s;e in
very rich Apparel, made al&s;o their Compliments
to their High and Mightine&s;&s;es with a Maje&s;tick
Gravity; but that which added the greate&s;t Lu&s;tre
to the Audience, was, that all the Amba&s;&s;adors of
mo&s;t Princes in <HI>Europe,</HI> honoured the&s;e Men with
their Pre&s;ence; and his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty had the
&s;atisfaction to be an Eye-witne&s;s of all that pa&s;|&s;ed
from a Clo&s;et Window opening into the Au|dience
Room, without being perceived by any
Body; and returned the next Day privately to
<HI>Am&s;terdam,</HI> extremely well plea&s;ed with his Jour|ney;
neither did their Excellencies make any long
&s;tay in the <HI>Hague,</HI> they having no other matters
to propo&s;e to the States, but the confirming of
former Treaties.</P>
<P>THE Ceremonies now ended, the <HI>Czar</HI> not on|ly
applyed him&s;elf to the Work he came about
as before, but all the Per&s;ons of Di&s;tinction which
he brought with him, di&s;pers'd them&s;elves according
to the different Commands he gave them; ap|plying
them&s;elves according as their different In|clinations
led them, to the Knowledge of &s;uch
things as were needful, according to the Pattern
of their great Ma&s;ter.</P>
<P>THIS le&s;&s;ened the Retinue which at fir&s;t ap|peared
in the Emba&s;&s;y exceedingly; and yet the
Amba&s;&s;adors retain'd an Equipage &s;uitable to the
Character they bore, and &s;uitable to the Glory of
their Ma&s;ter.</P>
<P>IN the mean time the <HI>Czar</HI> receiv'd an invita|tion
very agreeable to him, which was to have an
Interview with the King of <HI>Great Britain</HI> at that
<PB N="71" REF="72">
time, the Glory of that part of the World, and
who had ju&s;t fini&s;hed, with Honour to him&s;elf,
and Satisfaction to all his Allies, a long and bloody
War with the King of <HI>France</HI> by the Treaty at
<HI>Ry&s;wick.</HI></P>
<P>THE King came to <HI>Utrecht,</HI> where the <HI>Czar,</HI>
accompanied only with Prince <HI>Menzikoff</HI> and Ge|neral
<HI>Le Fort,</HI> but all <HI>Incognito,</HI> went to &s;ee him;
the&s;e two mighty Monarchs receiv'd a mutual Sa|tisfaction
in this interview, as both of them af|terwards
te&s;tified: They continued &s;ome Hours to|gether,
Mon&s;ieur <HI>Le Fort</HI> &s;erving as an Interpre|ter;
and here it was that his <HI>Briti&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty in|vited
the <HI>Czar</HI> to come and &s;ee his Court at <HI>Lon|don;</HI>
and that his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty accepted the
King's invitation, of which by it &s;elf.</P>
<P>HIS Maje&s;ty now having his full lei&s;ure for
the perfecting what he came about, he hir'd Ar|ti&s;ts
in <HI>Holland</HI> of &s;everal &s;orts, and giving them
very good Conditions, di&s;patch'd them for <HI>Mu&s;|cow,</HI>
&s;ome by Land, the Sea&s;on not admitting to
go about by the North Cape to <HI>Arch-Angel,</HI> and
&s;ome were maintain'd and employ'd in making
Models and Draughts for Building, 'till the Sea|&s;on
for going by Sea came on: In this manner they
were di&s;pers'd many ways, &s;ome went to Schools or
Ma&s;ters to learn Navigation and the Elements of
<HI>Euclid;</HI> others Bound them&s;elves for terms of Years
to Artificers; in a word, none were Idle, the
<HI>Czar</HI> re&s;olving to furni&s;h him&s;elf and all his At|tendants
with a Fund of Knowledge &s;ufficient to
an&s;wer his End; and indeed con&s;idering his Ma|je&s;ty's
View, it was a very great Fund of Human
Learning that ought to be laid up, to carry home
and in&s;truct a Nation.</P>
<P><PB N="72" REF="73">
IT was an immen&s;e Sum of Money that his
<HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty laid out here in buying Tools
and In&s;truments for the Works, and &s;everal Trades
and Arts which he and his People were to put in
Practi&s;e; there was not a Handicraft of any Note,
that his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty did not acquaint him&s;elf
more or le&s;s with, and with the manner of their
Working, no not from the making of a Watch to the
builder of a Ship; but it is to be noted, that the Ma|rine
Affairs were tho&s;e his chief Delight was in, and
which &s;uited be&s;t with his Genius; and while he
was at <HI>Am&s;terdam</HI> he bought him a Yacht, with
which he diverted him&s;elf continually upon the
River and the <HI>Zuyderzee,</HI> till by Cu&s;tom he learnt
to &s;teer and work her as dexterou&s;ly as the able&s;t
Seamen he could get.</P>
<P>HERE he al&s;o hir'd &s;everal Seamen and Offi|cers,
and made them Captains and Lieutenants
of his Men of War, &s;ome of whom are in his Ser|vice
to this Day.</P>
<P>ABOUT the of <HI>Septemb.</HI> 1698, he re|&s;olv'd
upon his Journey, or Voyage rather, to
<HI>England,</HI> and accordingly he arriv'd here in <HI>No|vember</HI>
1698, of which pre&s;ently.</P>
<P>BUT I &s;hould have noted here, that while his
Maje&s;ty remain'd at <HI>Am&s;terdam,</HI> after he had been
at the <HI>Hague,</HI> and was return'd as above, he re|ceiv'd
three Couriers from his Lords, to whom he
had left the Admini&s;tration of the Government at
<HI>Mu&s;cow</HI> in his ab&s;ence; bringing him the welcome
News of a great Victory obtain'd by his Army
under the Command of General <HI>Schein</HI> at <HI>A&s;oph</HI>
over the <HI>Turks</HI> and <HI>Tartars.</HI> The Particulars of
this Action, as they were then related, were as
follows, (<HI>viz.</HI>)</P>
<P><PB N="73" REF="74">
HIS Maje&s;ty fir&s;t receiv'd an Expre&s;s from
<HI>Mu&s;covy,</HI> with the agreeable News of this Bat|tel;
the other Accounts came &s;ome time after
by different ways: The <HI>Cham</HI> of the <HI>Crim Tar|tars</HI>
had, in the beginning of the Spring,
cau&s;ed great numbers of his Troops to pa&s;s in
many &s;mall Bodies, and at different times,
through <HI>Caffa,</HI> in order to join them with the
<HI>Tartars</HI> of <HI>Circa&s;&s;ia,</HI> and e&s;pecially tho&s;e inha|biting
near the River <HI>Cubanoc,</HI> knowing that the
<HI>Mu&s;covite</HI> Army was divided into &s;everal Bodies,
the better to cover the Workmen, who were em|ploy'd
in &s;everal places, in compleating the be|fore-mentioned
Fortifications, looking upon this
as a fit opportunity to &s;urprize them unawares:
For this purpo&s;e he order'd the <HI>Tartars</HI> com|manded
by <HI>Sultan Galga,</HI> to advance with great
and <HI>&s;peedy</HI> Marches towards the <HI>Mu&s;covites:</HI> But
the <HI>Mu&s;covite</HI> General <HI>Schein</HI> having received intel|ligence
of their approach, had ju&s;t &s;o much lei|&s;ure
given him as to draw down his Troops toge|ther
in an advantageous Place, where he re&s;olv'd
to engage the Enemy; the&s;e perceiving them|&s;elves
&s;uperior in number to the <HI>Mu&s;covites,</HI> and
being encourag'd by the fancy'd fear of the <HI>Mu&s;|covite</HI>
Army, which did not move from their
Po&s;t, fell with great Fury upon them, and were
received with great Bravery by the <HI>Ru&s;&s;ians,</HI> who
were contented to defend them&s;elves in their Po&s;t,
till their General perceiving the fir&s;t heat of the
<HI>Tarters</HI> &s;lacken, attacked them very briskly, put
them fir&s;t into Confu&s;ion, and &s;oon after to the
Rout, with a great Slaughter on the Enemy's
&s;ide, whom they pur&s;ued to the River <HI>Hagalinc,</HI>
were many of them were drown'd; this River
runs through <HI>Circa&s;&s;ia,</HI> about two Leagues di&s;tant
<PB N="74" REF="75">
from <HI>A&s;oph;</HI> tho' our Maps put this River to the
North on the other &s;ide of the River <HI>Don,</HI> above
thirty Leagues from <HI>A&s;oph.</HI></P>
<P>THEIR Excellencies the <HI>Mu&s;covite</HI> Amba&s;&s;a|dors
made Publick Rejoicings upon this Occa&s;ion,
and invited the Magi&s;trates of <HI>Am&s;terdam</HI> and o|ther
Per&s;ons of Quality to a magnificent Enter|tainment,
where they were diverted with Dancing
and Mu&s;ick, Fireworks, and all &s;orts of other Di|verti&s;ements:
His <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty was pleas'd to
appear there in Per&s;on, and in &s;o plea&s;ant a Hu|mour,
all the Gue&s;s were extreamly &s;atisfy'd
with his Goodne&s;s.</P>
<P>TOWARD the end of the Winter this Victory
was &s;econded by the News of another Advantage
obtain'd near the River <HI>Bori&s;thenes;</HI> for the <HI>Crim
Tartars,</HI> in Conjunction with tho&s;e of <HI>Budziack</HI>
and <HI>Oczakow,</HI> having be&s;ieged <HI>Ka&s;ikermeen,</HI> had
carried on their Trenches to the very Counter|&s;carp,
and at the &s;ame time made them&s;elves
Ma&s;ters of the adjacent &s;mall I&s;le of <HI>Tomam;</HI> but
a Body of <HI>Mu&s;covites</HI> having joined the <HI>Co&s;&s;acks</HI> in|habiting
tho&s;e Frontiers, came time enough to the
Relief of the place, forcing the <HI>Tartars</HI> to aban|don
the Siege, and that with a con&s;iderable Lo&s;s
on their &s;ide; upon which his Maje&s;ty gave or|ders,
that the &s;aid I&s;land &s;hould be &s;trengthened
by &s;ome regular Fortifications.</P>
<P>ALL the&s;e Succe&s;&s;es added to his Maje&s;ty's
Glory; and the more, in that they were obtain'd
in his Ab&s;ence, as it was a Te&s;timony that the
Government of his Affairs was left in good Hands,
and that he had made a right Choice of his Men,
with whom he had entru&s;ted the Command of his
Armies, as well as of tho&s;e to whom he had com|mitted
<PB N="75" REF="76">
the Admini&s;tration of his Civil Govern|ment.</P>
<P>THESE Advices were follow'd with other
Letters, giving him an Account of the progre&s;s
of his Engineers, and how well they had &s;ecur'd
and fortify'd the Places he had won; as well <HI>A|&s;oph</HI>
as <HI>Tuba, Kai&s;ikermeen,</HI> and other Places; and
that the fir&s;t of the&s;e <HI>e&s;pecially,</HI> was put into &s;uch
a Po&s;ture that it might ju&s;tly be e&s;teemed one of
the &s;tronge&s;t Fortre&s;&s;es of the World, particularly
that part which he had directed to be built in the
Mora&s;s mention'd above.</P>
<P>THIS was the more agreeable to the <HI>Czar,</HI> as
it was &s;uitable to his wi&s;h, for that in a Word,
<HI>A&s;oph</HI> was the Center of all his va&s;t De&s;igns, and
he had as we may &s;ay, laid no le&s;s than a Scheme
for the Ruin of the whole <HI>Ottoman</HI> Empire in the
Gradations he had Projected from that one Place,
as will be &s;een hereafter.</P>
<P>WE are now to &s;uppo&s;e his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty on
his Voyage to <HI>England,</HI> his <HI>Britanick</HI> Maje&s;ty &s;ent
over &s;everal Yatches to bring him over with a
Man of War, or two for his Convoy, and he arriv'd
in the River of <HI>Thames</HI> the of <HI>October.</HI> 1697.</P>
<P>WHEN he came to <HI>London,</HI> the King omitted
nothing to &s;how him that he had a very particular
e&s;teem for him; indeed the Intent and Meaning
of his thus hazarding his Per&s;on in foreign Parts
for enabling him&s;elf to Government, and People
was a thing &s;o inimitably great, and &s;o prai&s;e
worthy in a Prince of his Rank, that it merited
all the regard, and all the A&s;&s;i&s;tance that could
po&s;&s;ibly be given him.</P>
<P><PB N="76" REF="77">
HIS <HI>Britanick</HI> Maje&s;ty at fir&s;t offer'd the <HI>Czar</HI>
all the publick Honour due to his Character as a
Royal or Imperial Soveraign and Crown'd Head;
as particularly, his Maje&s;ty offer'd him <HI>Somer&s;et-Hou&s;e</HI>
for his Re&s;idence, being a Pallace Royal,
and that he &s;hould be attended by the Officers of
the Royal Hou&s;hold, and that all the Expence of
his Kitchin, and of his Retinue &s;hould be de|frayed;
that he &s;hould have a Detachment of the
<HI>Engli&s;h</HI> Hou&s;hold Troops for a Guard to his Per|&s;on,
and a certain Number of the King's Coaches
to attend him.</P>
<P>BUT the <HI>Czar</HI> after returning a very obliging
An&s;wer, declin'd all tho&s;e Honours; let his Ma|je&s;ty
of <HI>Great Britain</HI> know the Rea&s;ons of his
Re&s;olution to be every where Incognito, and
how nece&s;&s;ary it was to his De&s;ign in coming a|broad;
that he came for Improvement, and had
no time to &s;pend in Ceremony, receiving and
returning Vi&s;its, and the like.</P>
<P>HE therefore de&s;ir'd his <HI>Britanick Maje&s;ty</HI> that
he would &s;uffer him to be as much conceal'd
as po&s;&s;ible, and yet that he might have &s;o much
of his Royal favour, as &s;hould admit him to &s;ee
what was proper for his Improvement in Maritime
Affairs, which was the principle thing that he
de&s;ir'd to In&s;pect, and which he found here was
manag'd even in a greater Perfection than in any
other part of the World.</P>
<P>HIS <HI>Britanick</HI> Maje&s;ty was &s;o extreamly
pleas'd with this, and with all the other Te&s;ti|monies,
which the <HI>Czar</HI> gave of his Per&s;onal
Capacities, and his Genius to the things he came
to enquire after; and particularly, the truly no|ble
End and De&s;ign of his enquiring after them;
that he immediately order'd that all po&s;&s;ible En|couragement,
<PB N="77" REF="78">
and A&s;&s;i&s;tance &s;hould be given his
Maje&s;ty; that he &s;hould be &s;howed every thing that
he had a de&s;ire to &s;ee, and that all the Men of
Art &s;hould communicate every thing that his
<HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty &s;hould de&s;ire to know: In a
Word, his <HI>Britanick</HI> Maje&s;ty let him know that
nothing &s;hould be wanting in <HI>England</HI> to give all
po&s;&s;ible A&s;&s;i&s;tance to his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty in &s;o
glorious a Search after Knowledge, and Wi&s;dom,
and that he would do every thing that was in his
power to let him (the <HI>Czar</HI>) &s;ee what e&s;teem he
(the King) had for him on that particular Ac|count.</P>
<P>HIS <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty after his letting the King
know his Re&s;olution of remaining Private, took
a Hou&s;e, as proper, and as happily Situated for
&s;uch a purpo&s;e, as the whole City could hardly have
afforded &s;uch another, con&s;idering its being a well
built commodious Hou&s;e al&s;o; for as it had a good
front Gate to bring a Coach to, in the <HI>Great-Row,</HI>
of <HI>Norfolk-&s;treet,</HI> in the <HI>Strand;</HI> &s;o it had a pri|vate
pair of Stairs to the River, peculiar to the
Hou&s;e only; where Boats could come even at low
Water to &s;et him on &s;hore, or take him in, as he
thought fit, and &s;o that it was &s;carce po&s;&s;ible to
the People to &s;ee him go or come.</P>
<P>WHILE he re&s;ided here, he had frequent In|terviews
with the King, and made &s;ome Vi&s;its
to the Prince&s;s <HI>Ann,</HI> afterwards Queen; went to
&s;ee <HI>Wind&s;or</HI> Ca&s;tle, <HI>Hampton</HI> Court, and other
publick Places; was particularly &s;hew'd the <HI>Tower</HI>
of <HI>London,</HI> and all the Varieties there, where he
was particularly taken with the Great Armory,
and the admirable Order of the placeing
the &s;mall Arms, and Furniture for Hor&s;e and
Foot; and ep&s;ecially the keeping the Arms &s;o
<PB N="78" REF="79">
clean, well fix'd, and ready for Service; and, as
we hear, has appointed one to be Built after the
&s;ame manner at <HI>Petersburgh,</HI> and to be furni&s;h'd
with &s;mall Arms for an Hundred Thou&s;and
Men.</P>
<P>AT the &s;ame time he was accommodated at
<HI>Deptford</HI> with an Apartment which had a private
Door into the King's Yard and Wet Dock, and
a way al&s;o into the Merchant's Yards and Wet
Docks, on the way from <HI>Deptford</HI> to <HI>Redriff;</HI> by
which he had opportunity to &s;ee every part of the
Builders Art exemplifyed; and which was mo&s;t
delightful to his Maje&s;ty, the Ma&s;ter Builders
having expre&s;s, Orders to oblige his Maje&s;ty as
much as po&s;&s;ible, laid before him their Moulds
and Draughts, and the accurate Method by which
they fitted every piece of Timber, and directed
the building of the large&s;t Ships of War.</P>
<P>HIS <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty was &s;o extremely pleas'd
with that part, whether it was that their Method
was not &s;o good in <HI>Holland,</HI> or that they did not
let him &s;o far into the Secret of their Art, I know
not; but he was pleas'd to declare, that our
Building far exceeded all that he had &s;een before,
and that he was re&s;olv'd to make the <HI>Engli&s;h</HI> Men
of War be the Pattern by which all his own Ships
&s;hould be built, and to have his Builders in&s;truct|ed
to work their Models the &s;ame way; and I am
informed, he made him&s;elf &s;o much Ma&s;ter of
the Method, that he has &s;ince drawn the fir&s;t
Draught of his large&s;t Men of War with his own
Hand.</P>
<P>AFTER this his Maje&s;ty the King of <HI>Great
Britain</HI> ordered Admiral <HI>Mitchel</HI> to go down to
<HI>Port&s;mouth,</HI> where there then lay a Squadron of
Men of War, and caus'd them to be form'd into
<PB N="79" REF="80">
two Fleets, and to &s;how the <HI>Czar</HI> the manner of
an Engagement at Sea, making them draw out
and Engage, tho' without firing with Ball.</P>
<P>HERE his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty being on board the
Admiral's Ship, was &s;hewed the manner of two
Fleet's preparing to Fight, their Unmooring, their
Scouts giving Signal to the Fleet, the Admiral
giving Signal to draw up in a Line, and when to
engage; their &s;triving for the Weather-gage, bear|ing
down upon the Enemy, &s;tanding off and on to
keep out of the Fight, keeping the Line, putting
off of Fire&s;hips, and attacking with Fire&s;hips;
firing Broad&s;ides, clapping one another aboard,
lying thwart Haw&s;e, coming up under the Stern,
and pouring in Broad&s;ides upon a Ship's Quarter
or Bow, and in &s;hort, all the ways of taking Ad|vantage
of an Enemy in Fight.</P>
<P>THIS was perform'd with &s;o much Order, &s;o
Dexterou&s;ly, and &s;o without the lea&s;t Dammage,
that his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty profe&s;s'd him&s;elf exceed|ing
well pleas'd with it; and that much more than
he was with &s;omething of the &s;ame kind offered
him in <HI>Holland,</HI> which being performed al&s;o by
&s;maller Ve&s;&s;els, could not &s;o well explain the Par|ticulars
nece&s;&s;ary to be known for the ordering a
Sea-fight with Capital Ships.</P>
<P>THUS the <HI>Czar</HI> employ'd his time in <HI>England,</HI>
viewing every thing that was Curious, and enter|ing
into due Enquiries after tho&s;e things, which
he found mo&s;t nece&s;&s;ary for his Purpo&s;e, as parti|cularly,
be&s;ides what I have mentioned above, he
was very curious in his viewing the Mint, and
E&s;&s;aying the Metals, reducing them to the Stan|dard
Value, the Melting-hou&s;e, the Flatting Mill,
the Stamping, and the Dye, or Stamp which
makes the Impre&s;&s;ion. Likewi&s;e he went to the
<PB N="80" REF="81">
University of <HI>Oxford,</HI> where he &s;aw the publick
Libraries, the manner of di&s;po&s;ing the Books and
Manu&s;cripts; view'd the Rarities, and particular|ly
the Printing-hou&s;e, which he was &s;o pleas'd
with, that he cau&s;ed all the Materials, and all the
Uten&s;ils for &s;etting up the like, to be Bought,
with Fonts of Letters of every &s;ize, and of every
Character, re&s;olving to &s;et up a Printing-hou&s;e at
<HI>Mu&s;cow</HI> and at <HI>Petersbourgh,</HI> which I am a&s;&s;ur'd he
has &s;ince brought to pa&s;s.</P>
<P>HIS &s;tay in <HI>England</HI> was about three Months,
during which time he improved him&s;elf &s;o much
in all the Parts of tho&s;e Sciences, which he apply|ed
him&s;elf to look into, that a learned Per&s;on
who convers'd with him freely, &s;aid publickly,
that an ordinary Proficient would not obtain &s;o
much in three Year.</P>
<P>AT his going away his Maje&s;ty pre&s;ented the
<HI>Czar</HI> with a fine Yacht or Frigate built for his
own particular u&s;e, for his pa&s;&s;ing and re-pa&s;&s;ing
between <HI>England</HI> and <HI>Holland,</HI> being not only a
beautiful and finely fini&s;hed Ve&s;&s;el, but an ex|cellent
Sailer; carrying 24 Bra&s;&s; Guns, and mo&s;t
richly painted and guilded; in which Ve&s;&s;el his
<HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty, after taking leave of the King and
the Prince&s;s, and with great Profe&s;&s;ions of mutual
Kindne&s;s and Satisfaction in what had pa&s;s'd, &s;et
Sail for <HI>Holland,</HI> and arriv'd &s;afe at the <HI>Brill,</HI>
tho' not without &s;ome hazard, in the Voyage,
having had very bad Weather in his Pa&s;&s;age.</P>
<P>ALL the while his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty was in <HI>Eng|land,</HI>
he employ'd &s;ome <HI>Engli&s;h Ru&s;&s;ia</HI> Merchants
to Hire for him, and Contract with as many of
the be&s;t Ma&s;ter Builders, Caulkers, Carvers, and
the like of other Trades, which were generally
employ'd in fini&s;hing and fitting out Ships in or|der
<PB N="81" REF="82">
to &s;end them to <HI>Mu&s;covy,</HI> and his Maje&s;ty
left Commi&s;&s;ioners with the &s;ame Merchants to
Contract with others after he was gone, and to
&s;end them after him, which was done to his con|tent;
and 'tis by the help of the&s;e very Men
chiefly, that the <HI>Czar</HI> has at this time &s;o many
Ships, as well Capital Men of War, from 50 to 96
Guns, as light Fregates, Brigantines, Tran&s;port-Ships,
and the like; which they have built, and
are &s;till ever building at <HI>Croon&s;lot</HI> and <HI>Petersburgh,</HI>
where the <HI>Czar,</HI> who at that time had not a Ship,
or a Port in the <HI>Baltick,</HI> has now &s;uch a Fleet, and
&s;o well Mann'd, as no Prince ever had before him
in &s;o &s;hort a while; and we have News from thence
ju&s;t at the writing of the&s;e Sheets, that his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI>
Maje&s;ty has built at the Port of <HI>Petersburgh,</HI> and
other adjacent Place, no le&s;s then &s;ix Men of
War, from 76 to 98 Guns, which are &s;ome of
them Lanch'd, and the others almo&s;t ready to
Lanch, and will be ready for the approaching
Summers Expedition.</P>
<P>ALL this while his Amba&s;&s;adors remained at
the <HI>Hague,</HI> except that Mon&s;ieur <HI>La Fort</HI> had
been allow'd to go over to <HI>England</HI> with the
<HI>Czar,</HI> in a private Capacity, and return'd to <HI>Hol|land,</HI>
again a little before him.</P>
<P>AND now having fini&s;h'd his enquires, and
having viewed every thing that was curious, and
Improving as well in <HI>England,</HI> as in <HI>Holland;</HI> &s;et|tled
Amity and a good Under&s;tanding between
him&s;elf, and both tho&s;e Nations, and having far|ther
Progre&s;s to make, e&s;pecially, re&s;olving to
&s;ee the Imperial Court at <HI>Vienna,</HI> the Senate, and
City of <HI>Venice,</HI> and the Antiquities of <HI>Rome</HI> and
<HI>Italy</HI> he prepar'd to be gone.</P>
<P><PB N="82" REF="83">
I SHALL omit the particulars of his Pa&s;&s;age from
<HI>Holland,</HI> thro' <HI>Germany</HI> to <HI>Vienna</HI> fir&s;t, becau&s;e it
would &s;pin out this Work too far in the Affairs
of lea&s;t Con&s;equence, and perhaps &s;traiten us for
Room in tho&s;e of moreweight: And Secondly, be|cau&s;e
we have not a full Account of all the parts
of the Rout he took come to Hand: It may &s;uffice
to &s;ay that his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty arriv'd at <HI>Vienna,</HI>
about the 10th of <HI>June</HI> with his Amba&s;&s;adors, and
all their Train, as before; having been receiv'd, with
particular Marks of Re&s;pect and Di&s;tinction, in
all his Pa&s;&s;age thro' the Empire: As to <HI>France</HI> his
Maje&s;ty di&s;tingui&s;h'd him&s;elf &s;o much in Favour
of the Confederates, as not &s;o much as to &s;et
his Foot in any part of <HI>France,</HI> nor to have the
lea&s;t Intentions of &s;eeing that Court, which values
it&s;elf &s;o much upon its being the Center, and the
Scene of all Peoples curio&s;ity.</P>
<P>HIS Imperial Maje&s;ty came immediately into
the &s;ame Sentiments, as to the <HI>Czar</HI>'s de&s;ign of Tra|vel
as others had done, e&s;teeming it an Action tru|ly
glorious and worthy a Monarch of the highe&s;t
Rank in the World, and re&s;olv'd therefore to &s;how
to his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty all the Re&s;pect, and do him
all the Honours the Imperial Court was capable of.</P>
<P>THE <HI>Czar</HI> and his Amba&s;&s;adors continu'd in
a particular Lodging appointed for them till the
26th, having fir&s;t notify'd their arrival in form
as Amba&s;&s;adors; they had the Pallace of <HI>Gun|dersdoff,</HI>
belonging to the Count <HI>de Koning&s;ec,</HI>
where they remain'd till the 26th, when they
made their publick Entry with their u&s;ual Mag|nificence.</P>
<P>THE Amba&s;&s;adors went to a Place call'd Mount
<HI>Tabor,</HI> whence the &s;how was appointed to &s;et
out, and Commi&s;&s;ioners were &s;ent thither to re|ceive
<PB N="83" REF="84">
them attended by a Party of Dragoons of
the Guards.</P>
<P>THE March began with the Trumpets and
Kettle-Drums, belonging to the States of the
Province, follow'd by two Companies of Dra|goons,
and &s;ome Imperial Officers; after them
the Amba&s;&s;adors Trumpets in rich Liveries, as
al&s;o the Pages and Footmen in the &s;ame; thence
proceeded a great Number of Coaches and &s;ix
Hor&s;es, of the Lords of the Court, which were fol|low'd
by two of the Emperors Coaches. The fir&s;t
for Princes that came along with the Amba&s;&s;a|dors.
The &s;econd for the Amba&s;&s;adors them&s;elves,
and the Imperial Commi&s;&s;ioners; &s;urrounded with
Hey-dukes bearing their Maces, and followed by
Pages on Hor&s;eback, and other dome&s;tick Servants,
and three noble Coaches belonging to the Amba&s;|&s;adors.
Which with a va&s;t Train of Coaches be|longing
to the principal Per&s;ons in the Imperial
Court, followed by another Detatchment of Dra|goons,
clos'd the Cavalcade.</P>
<P>THE 29th of the &s;ame Month, the Amba&s;&s;a|dors
had a private Audience of the Emperor; and
here, tho' incognito, his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty appear'd
with his Amba&s;&s;adors, <HI>that is to &s;ay,</HI> went as one
of their Train, after the Audience of the Am|ba&s;&s;adors,
which was matter of Ceremony, the
<HI>Czar</HI> in particular was admitted to an Enterview
without them.</P>
<P>WHILE the Amba&s;&s;adors had their Audience,
the Emperor &s;tood for &s;ome time cover'd; but af|terward
&s;at down, and de&s;ir'd the Amba&s;&s;adors to
&s;it al&s;o, but they excu&s;ed them&s;elves which they did
more particularly, in regard to the Pre&s;ence of
their own Soveraign, who being near them, mu&s;t
have been &s;tanding, while they had &s;at down,
<PB N="84" REF="85">
which the Emperor pre&s;ently under&s;tanding to
be the Rea&s;on, ro&s;e up al&s;o him&s;elf and receiv'd
them &s;tanding; Mon&s;ieur <HI>Le Fort</HI> made his Ha|range
here in Latin, which the other two Amba&s;|&s;adors
&s;poke in the <HI>Ru&s;&s;ian</HI> Tongue, and the Empe|ror
an&s;wer'd in Latin, which by the way, his Impe|rial
Maje&s;ty &s;poke very fluently.</P>
<P>WHEN they were di&s;mi&s;s'd, the <HI>Czar</HI> and Ge|neral
<HI>Le Fort</HI> (no more being admitted) went to the
Interview with his Imperial Maje&s;ty. They went
in by a back Pair of Stairs from the Chamber of
Audience, when the <HI>Czar</HI> advancing, his Imperial
Maje&s;ty receiv'd him at the Door of his Anti-Chamber.</P>
<P>AFTER the fir&s;t Complements the Emperor
put on his Hat; but &s;eeing the <HI>Czar</HI> refus'd to be
cover'd, becau&s;e he was incognito, his Imperial
Maje&s;ty uncover'd al&s;o; no Body was pre&s;ent at
this Interview, but the Count <HI>Deichten&s;tein</HI> grand
Chamberlain to the Emperor, and the Count <HI>de
Dictrick&s;tein</HI> his Grand 'Squire, with general <HI>Le
Fort,</HI> who &s;erv'd as the <HI>Czars</HI> Interpreter; and
then it was that the <HI>Czar</HI> took his opportunity to
impart to the Emperor the Letters he had re|ceiv'd,
which gave him an Account, how that
eight Thou&s;and of his Garri&s;on of <HI>A&s;oph</HI> had ta|ken
thirty Thou&s;and Hor&s;es from the <HI>Tartars,</HI>
after they had defeated a Body of three Thou&s;and
Men that Guarded them.</P>
<P>THE 6th of <HI>July,</HI> the Count of <HI>Staremberg,</HI>
Camp-mar&s;hal General of the Emperor's Ar|mies,
and Pre&s;ident of the Council of War,
gave the <HI>Czar</HI> and his Amba&s;&s;adors a magnificient
Collation, accompani'd with a Con&s;ort of Mu&s;ick,
and after that a noble Ball; where were pre&s;ent
he principal Lords, and Ladies of the Court; the
<PB N="85" REF="86">
9th being the Fe&s;tival of St. <HI>Peter,</HI> the Name
which was given to the <HI>Czar</HI> in Bapti&s;m, the
&s;ame Prince gave a great Fea&s;t, and a Ball in
<HI>Guntersdorf</HI> Hou&s;e, the Emperor &s;ent him his Mu|&s;ick
and order'd lovely Fire-Works to be made
ready, which were play'd off in the Evening, to
augment the Diverti&s;ement of the Fea&s;t; the
&s;ame Day his Imperial Maje&s;ty &s;ent a Pre&s;ent of
all manner of Mathematical In&s;truments to the
<HI>Czar,</HI> who two Days after went to &s;ee the Armo|ry,
the Libraries, the Pictures, and all the other
Rarieties of the Imperial Palace.</P>
<P>UPON the 21&s;t was a great Fea&s;t in the Palace <HI>de
le Favorite,</HI> which began with a Ball, and a Con|&s;ort
of Mu&s;ick, afterwards a &s;plendid Col|lation;
then another Ball, which la&s;ted all
Night, till break of Day; every Masker was in
the Habit of a different Nation; &s;o that all the
mo&s;t noted Nations of the World were there re|pre&s;ented,
and every Prince or Lord had a Lady
by his Side in an&s;werable Habits of the &s;ame Nat|tion;
and the Habits made of rich Stuffs, &s;parkling
with precious Stones; &s;o that in the memory of
Man, a Sight &s;o Magnificient had not been &s;een
their.</P>
<P>THE Emperor, who repre&s;ented an Ho&s;t, with
two and thirty Pages, habited like Butlers, drank
in a mo&s;t lovely Gla&s;s, the Countryman of <HI>oe&s;t
Fri&s;e</HI>'s Health, who was repre&s;ented by the chief
of the <HI>Mu&s;covite</HI> Princes; &s;aying at the &s;ame time,
that he knew well his extraordinary Zeal for the
<HI>Czar</HI> of <HI>Mu&s;covy;</HI> and on the other Side, the Coun|tryman
of <HI>Oe&s;t Fri&s;e</HI> drank the Ho&s;t in Di&s;gui&s;e's
Health; &s;aying at the &s;ame time, that he was not
ignorant of his inviolable Affection for the Em|peror;
after which his imperial Maje&s;ty reply'd
that he gave the Gla&s;s to the Countryman of <HI>Oe&s;t
<PB N="86" REF="87">
Fre&s;e,</HI> de&s;iring him to pre&s;erve it carefully in
Memory of the Healths drank in &s;uch good
Company.</P>
<P>UPON the 29th the grand Emba&s;&s;y had their
publick Audience, to which they were conducted
in the following Manner. Fir&s;t march'd a Com|pany
of Foot, follow'd by &s;ix Trumpeters belong|ing
to the Emba&s;&s;y, clad in rich Liveries, after
the <HI>German</HI> mode, tho&s;e were follow'd by fifteen
of the Court Coaches, wherein rode the <HI>Mu&s;co|vite</HI>
Lords, in their own Country Habit, and
others after the <HI>French</HI> dre&s;s; after the&s;e came
fifty Burghers, clad in black Velvet, bearing the
Pre&s;ents de&s;ign'd for his Imperial Maje&s;ty, which
con&s;i&s;ted in a great Number of lovely Ermins
and Furs, Sables, Cloath of Gold and Silver,
and a Harne&s;s enrich'd with Pearl; after this rode
a <HI>Mu&s;covite</HI> a Hor&s;eback, carrying the Letters of
Credence, follow'd by one of the Emperor's
Coaches; wherein the Emba&s;&s;adors rode, together
with his Imperial Maje&s;ty's Commi&s;&s;ioners. This
Coach was &s;urrounded and attended by Pages and
other in Liveries belonging as well to the Amba&s;|&s;adors
as to the Grandees of the Court, who with the
Amba&s;&s;adors Coaches clos'd the March; the Am|ba&s;&s;adors
entering into the Court of the Palace
<HI>de le Favorite</HI> found the Guards in Arms, and were
conducted to the Hall of Audience, with the ac|cu&s;tom'd
Ceremonies, after which they were mag|nificently
Treated at the Emperors Charges, and &s;o
Conducted back to the Place where they lay.</P>
<P>THE <HI>Czar</HI> was ju&s;t upon his departure for <HI>Ve|nice,</HI>
in his way to <HI>Rome,</HI> and had already &s;ent
eight Per&s;ons of his Train before, but at the very
time he was preparing to depart; he was con|&s;train'd
to alter his Re&s;olution, and to take Po&s;t
for <HI>Mu&s;cow,</HI> with a Train of between thirty and
<PB N="87" REF="88">
forty Hor&s;e, upon Advice of a revolt of &s;everal
Malecontents within his Dominions, and that if
he did not &s;peedily return, by his Pre&s;ence to
put a &s;top to the Current of the Commotion, he
might unhappily find all the Pa&s;&s;ages &s;top'd.</P>
<P>WE are now come to the End of this unexam|pled
Journey, <HI>viz.</HI> the Travels of the <HI>Czar,</HI> and his
Amba&s;&s;adors, in a Circle of near 2000 Miles, not in|cluding
his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty's Trip to <HI>England:</HI> It
is now time to look back to <HI>Mu&s;covy:</HI> His <HI>Czari&s;h</HI>
Maje&s;ty had received &s;everal Expre&s;&s;es from his
Generals at <HI>A&s;oph,</HI> of their &s;ucce&s;sful Encounters
with the <HI>Tartars,</HI> and ju&s;t before he left the
<HI>Hague,</HI> where his Amba&s;&s;adors had their Audience
of leave, there arriv'd another Courier with an
Account, that General <HI>Gordon</HI> had very happily
&s;uppre&s;s'd a kind of an In&s;urrection of 10000 of
the <HI>Strelitzes,</HI> and had kill'd 3500 of them upon
the Spot, and taken almo&s;t all the re&s;t of them
Pri&s;oners; that he had Decimated the Pri&s;oners, and
hang'd every Tenth Man upon the Field of Bat|tle,
had retain'd in Pri&s;on the re&s;t, with &s;e|veral
of their Ringleaders, and &s;ome of the No|bility
who had Fomented their in&s;olence, and in a
Word, had effectually &s;uppre&s;s'd the Rebellion.</P>
<P>IN the Neck of this came another from <HI>A&s;oph,</HI>
with the News, that a Detachment of 8000 Men
from the Gari&s;on of that City had defeated 6000
<HI>Tartars,</HI> who had been Po&s;ted as a Guard to the
<HI>Tartar's</HI> Hor&s;es, who were put into the Mar&s;hes
on the Frontiers of <HI>Circa&s;&s;ia,</HI> and had taken no
le&s;s than 30000 Hor&s;es of which mention is made,
as above.</P>
<P>BUT all the&s;e good Tidings had their Allay,
and the la&s;t News his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty receivd,
was &s;uch as intimated the Danger to be very
<PB N="88" REF="89">
great, and that they fear'd a general In&s;urrection,
entreating him to ha&s;ten back, not only that by his
Pre&s;ence he might encourage his faithful Subjects,
but that he might arrive before the Con&s;pirators
&s;hould be able to get a Force together, and &s;eize
upon the Pa&s;&s;es, and Entrances into his Country,
and either make it impracticable for him to return,
or perhaps make him run the Danger of falling
into the Hands of his Enemies in the attempt.</P>
<P>It will ea&s;ily be granted that his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Ma|je&s;ty
had Rea&s;on to u&s;e the utmo&s;t Expedition
in his Return, and indeed upon that Expedition
depended his &s;ucce&s;s; for the celerity or &s;wiftne&s;s
of his Return was &s;uch, that the Con&s;pirators &s;aw
him in the Ca&s;tle or Pallace of <HI>Mu&s;cow,</HI> &s;ur|rounded
with his Army, and ready to fall upon
them before they thought it had been po&s;&s;ible
that he could &s;o much as have any Account of
their proceedings.</P>
<P>THIS was &s;uch a &s;urprize to them as broke all
their Mea&s;ures; for the <HI>Czar</HI> fell to work with
them, the very Moment he arrived, and particu|larly
with tho&s;e who General <HI>Gordon</HI> had in Cu|&s;tody;
for fir&s;t his Maje&s;ty order'd that the princi|pal
Contrivers and Encouragers of the &s;aid Rebel|lion
&s;hould be brought before him, and after he
had him&s;elf re-examin'd them, they having before
been condemn'd in a full Hearing before all the
Lords; they were all Sentenc'd to Death, among
whom were Prince <HI>Colorin,</HI> General <HI>Romanodo&s;|lowski,</HI>
with &s;everal Ladies of Quality, and Friars
and Prie&s;ts of the fir&s;t Rank, &s;ome of them were be|headed,
&s;ome broke upon the Wheel, others bu|ried
alive, and the afore&s;aid <HI>Strelitzes</HI> or Soldiers,
whe had actually march'd and fought again&s;t the
<HI>Czar's</HI> Arms, and who had ever &s;ince the <HI>Czar's</HI>
<PB N="89" REF="90">
fir&s;t coming to the Crown upon all occa&s;ions been
in the Plots and Intreagues of the Prince&s;s
<HI>Sophia,</HI> and the Party that adhered to her, and
had in &s;everal In&s;tances &s;hew'd their will and
readine&s;s to revolt upwards of 2000 of them
were executed, &s;ome their Heads taken of in the
publick Market-place, others hung up upon Gal|low&s;es
erected on purpo&s;e at the Gates of all the
three Walls round the City, with the Crimes
writ upon the Gallows: This Execution being per|form'd
in the depth of Winter, their Bodies were
immediately bury'd; tho&s;e that were beheaded, were
order'd to lie in the &s;ame po&s;ture, as their Heads
were cut off, in Ranks upon the ground, with
their Heads lying by them; and tho&s;e which were
hang'd round the Walls of the City were left
hanging, the whole Winter in the &s;ame po&s;ture to
the view of the People, till the warm Weather
began to come on in the Spring, and then they
were taken down and buried in a Pit together, to
prevent the infection of the Air.</P>
<P>THERE was likewi&s;e other Gibbets plac'd on all
the publick Roads leading to <HI>Mu&s;cow,</HI> at about two
Miles di&s;tance, where others of the&s;e Rebels
were hang'd, and a large Monument of Stone
erected upon the &s;everal Roads, with the De|&s;cription
of their Crimes deeply engraven, and
order'd to be repair'd and kept up for ever, and
the very Hou&s;es wherein they had liv'd were or|der'd
to be raz'd to the ground, and the Name of
<HI>Strelitzes</HI> to be no more made u&s;e of in the Army
of <HI>Ru&s;&s;ia</HI> forever, but being chang'd, from that
time they were call'd <HI>Soldatee</HI> or <HI>Soldiers;</HI> &s;uch of
the <HI>Strelitzes</HI> that were judg'd mo&s;t Innocent, or
not &s;o deeply involv'd in the guilt with the re&s;t,
having their Lives given them, were &s;ome &s;ent
<PB N="90" REF="91">
to <HI>Siberia,</HI> others bani&s;h'd to <HI>A&s;tracan, A&s;oph,</HI> and
all the out Parts of the Kingdom, with their
Wives and Families and others of their near Re|lations
to &s;uffer with them, as it is the way of
mo&s;t of the Ea&s;tern Countries.</P>
<P>THUS his Maje&s;ty upon his return from his Tra|vels
by the example of &s;o vigorous a Proceeding
having &s;urpre&s;s'd the Enemies to his Government,
it was the more ea&s;ie for him to go on with the&s;e
things, which he had re&s;olv'd upon for the reforming
his Country; he began fir&s;t, with e&s;tabli&s;hing his
Guards, which were tho&s;e Regiments that were fix'd
in the Place of the afore&s;aid <HI>Strelitzes;</HI> then put
his whole Army upon a new Foot, form'd a new Di&s;|cipline,
which he had collected from what he had
ob&s;erv'd Abroad, and he order'd all his Army to be
regularly Cloath'd, with &s;ome di&s;tinction in the
Colour and Trimming of the Cloaths like the cu|&s;tom
of other Nations of <HI>Europe;</HI> this had not till
now been done in <HI>Mu&s;covy,</HI> but every one wore his
Claths according to his own Fancy; he order'd
al&s;o an Account to be brought to him of &s;uch Per|sons
of the Nobility and Gentry of con&s;iderable
E&s;tates, who were not in any Service or Employ|ment;
out of which he commanded a great part
to go and &s;erve as Voluntiers in the Army, and
others he order'd to attend, and appointed them
Duty in &s;everal Stations, &s;ome in Equipping his
Navy, and others order'd to go and re&s;ide at the
frontier Garri&s;ons, that if they did no good, they
might be out of the way of doing any Mi&s;chef.</P>
<P>WHEN he had thus di&s;pos'd things in <HI>Mo&s;cow,</HI>
with Relation to his Army, he went down him&s;elf
to <HI>Veronize</HI> to view tho&s;e Ships and Gallies that
were built there by the <HI>Dutch</HI> in his Ab&s;ence, and
to ha&s;ten the Equipment of his Fleet that was prepa|ring
for the <HI>Black Sea,</HI> he made tho&s;e <HI>Engli&s;h</HI> that he
<PB N="91" REF="92">
had brought over with him chief Ma&s;ter-builders,
and di&s;charg'd all the <HI>Dutch</HI> Builders, except what
were to fini&s;h the Ships which they had begun, and
tho&s;e were left under the Command of the <HI>English,</HI>
Ordering that there &s;hould be none but <HI>English</HI> fa|&s;hion'd
Ships to be built for the future; one of which
being a Ship of 50 Guns, his Maje&s;ty him&s;elf im|mediately,
as &s;oon as he came there &s;et upon the
Stocks, by a Draught which he had drawn with his
own Hands; and &s;o contriv'd her by an Invention
of his own, that tho' the Keel &s;hould be knock'd off,
the Ship &s;hould be Tight as he propos'd; which
Ship when he had advanc'd a little way, he left
to be carried on by two young <HI>Ru&s;&s;ian</HI> Gentle|men,
that had been Abroad with him, and learn|ed
to build Ships along with his Maje&s;ty; only he
left Orders for them to ask &s;ometimes Advice of
the <HI>English</HI> Builders, when there was any occa&s;ion
for it; he left al&s;o Orders at <HI>Veronize</HI> with Vice
Admiral <HI>Cru&s;s,</HI> and Real Admiral <HI>Raes,</HI> together
with the Sea Captains, Officers and Seamen that
he had taken into his Service in <HI>Holland,</HI> before
he went over to <HI>England,</HI> and who were now
arriv'd in <HI>Veronize</HI> to get tho&s;e Ships and Gallies
that were built there, rigg'd and ready fitted, to
Sail down to <HI>A&s;oph,</HI> whither he intended to go
with them in the Spring of the Year, together with
his Favorite <HI>le Fort,</HI> who tho' he knew nothing
of the Sea, was declar'd Admiral.</P>
<P>WHEN his Maje&s;ty had thus &s;ettled the Affairs
of his Navy, as he had before done of his Army, he
return'd back again to <HI>Mu&s;cow,</HI> where be&s;ides what
he had done at his fir&s;t coming over, he made a
Choice of Lords to be of his Council, and begun
to regulate Affairs in Government, both in the
Church, and in the State.</P>
<P><PB N="92" REF="93">
AND now we are to Enter in the Cour&s;e of his
Maje&s;ty's Hi&s;tory on a new Scene of Action, and
of a differing kind from what he had ever known
before: Hitherto all his Enterpri&s;es had been at|tended
with an uninterrupted Cour&s;e of Succe&s;s;
his Wars with the <HI>Turks</HI> and <HI>Tartars,</HI> happening
at a time when the <HI>Turki&s;h</HI> Power &s;eem'd to be in
a <HI>Cri&s;is,</HI> went all to his Content, and Victory at|tended
his Arms upon all occa&s;ions.</P>
<P>BUT now his Maje&s;ty had another kind of E|nemy
to deal with, I mean the King of <HI>Sweden;</HI>
who&s;e Fume, tho' yet it had made no Noi&s;e in the
World, yet he was attended with a well di&s;ciplin'd
Army, a Nation fierce and daring, who&s;e Reputa|tion
in Arms, was equal, if not Superior to the
mo&s;t glorious Nations in the World.</P>
<P>WHEN his Maje&s;ty, as I have ob&s;erved, went
from <HI>Vienna</HI> in ha&s;te to <HI>Mu&s;cow,</HI> he was not how|ever
&s;o much alarm'd with the News of his Rebel|lious
Subjects, but that he found room in his
Thoughts as well as lei&s;ure in his &s;peed, for a &s;hort
Interview with the King of <HI>Poland,</HI> thro' who&s;e
Dominions he was nece&s;&s;arily oblig'd to pa&s;s.</P>
<P>A LITTLE time may contrive what a great
many Years may be employ'd to Execute; here in
a few Hours they concerted that dreadful War be|tween
them, and the King of <HI>Sweden,</HI> which pro|ved
at fir&s;t &s;o fatal to them both, and which in
its whole Cour&s;e was fatal to all the Northern
Part of <HI>Europe,</HI> de&s;tructive to the whole Coun|tries
and in which fir&s;t and la&s;t above 500000
People have lo&s;t their Lives; nay, I have heard
it affirm'd that <HI>Sweden</HI> alone has by this very
War been drein'd of 300000 Men to the irrepara|ble
De&s;olation of that Kingdom, and we &s;hall
find abundant of Rea&s;on to believe that <HI>Poland</HI> and
<PB N="93" REF="94">
<HI>Mu&s;covy,</HI> and the <HI>Provinces</HI> adjoyning, put them
all to gether have lo&s;t a much greater Number.</P>
<P>IT was not however till the Year 1700, that
the War between the <HI>Czar</HI> of <HI>Mu&s;covy,</HI> and the
King of <HI>Sweden</HI> was openly declar'd after there had
been a &s;eeming renewing of the Peace between
them the Year before.</P>
<P>THIS War they &s;ay was concerted between
the King of <HI>Poland,</HI> and his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty at
this Interview, and the Mea&s;ures agreed on; al&s;o
how the &s;ame &s;hould be pro&s;ecuted, and &s;ome Mea|&s;ures
too for the engaging the King of <HI>Denmark</HI>
in the League; which propo&s;al afterwards prov'd
Succe&s;sful, <HI>that is to &s;ay,</HI> Succe&s;sful to bring the
King of <HI>Denmark</HI> in, but Un&s;ucce&s;sful to all the
three in the beginning of it, as will appear in the
pro&s;ecution of the Story.</P>
<P>IT was now in the Year 1699, when the <HI>Czar</HI>
had &s;pent about eight Months at Home, and
News was brought him to <HI>Mu&s;cow,</HI> that his Ple|nipotenaries
had concluded a Truce with the <HI>Turks</HI>
at <HI>Carlowitz,</HI> where at the &s;ame time, the Peace
between the <HI>Turks</HI> and the other Allies, (<HI>viz.</HI>) the
Emperor, the King of <HI>Poland</HI> and the State of <HI>Ve|nice</HI>
had been concluded.</P>
<P>IT was &s;ugge&s;ted that the <HI>Czar</HI> de&s;ir'd that tho'
the other Allies made a Treaty for 25 Years with
the <HI>Turks,</HI> that yet his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty's part &s;hould
be no more than a kind of Truce for two Years; and
that he did this, that he might have time in tho&s;e
two Years to compleat the Fortifications of <HI>A&s;oph,
Kai&s;ikermeen,</HI> and other Places; and to build a power|with
ful Fleet of Men of War at <HI>Veroneze,</HI> with
which at the end of the two Years, he doubted not
to be able to di&s;pute the Lord&s;hip of the <HI>Black Sea</HI>
with the Grand <HI>Seignior,</HI> and to bring him to
<PB N="94" REF="95">
grant a Pa&s;&s;age for his Subjects through the <HI>Bo&s;&s;|phor$s</HI>
into the <HI>Levant</HI> Seas.</P>
<P>BUT this was a blu&s;ter which his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI>
Maje&s;ty had no Hand in, and 'tis apparent it was
the <HI>Turks,</HI> who declin'd a Truce with <HI>Mu&s;covy</HI> for
any longer than two Years, purpo&s;ing as it was
apparent afterward that when they had got the
<HI>Hungarian, Venetian</HI> and <HI>Poli&s;h</HI> War off of their Hands,
they would fall upon the <HI>Czar</HI> with all their
Forces for the Recovery of <HI>A&s;oph, &amp;c.</HI> But the
<HI>Czar,</HI> who was &s;en&s;ible how heavy &s;uch a War
would be upon him, at lea&s;t till he had brought
his Army into all the new Mea&s;ures he had de|&s;ign'd,
apply'd immediately to the <HI>King</HI> of <HI>Great-Britain,</HI>
who was Mediator of that Treaty to give
In&s;tructions to his Plenipotentiaries at the Treaty,
to in&s;i&s;t that the Peace with <HI>Mu&s;covy,</HI> might
have the &s;ame Duration of 25 Years, as the Peace
with the Emperor had, which his <HI>Britanick</HI> Ma|je&s;ty
did, and obtained it for him accordingly,
which we &s;hall &s;ee in a little time acknowledged
under his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty's own Hand.</P>
<P>ACCORDINLY the Treaty was, I <HI>&s;ay,</HI> conclud|ed
at <HI>Carlowitz,</HI> and immediately the <HI>Czar</HI> began
the War again&s;t the King of <HI>Sweden,</HI> for the &s;ame
Day that the Peace with the <HI>Turks</HI> was proclaim'd
at <HI>Mu&s;covy,</HI> the &s;ame Day the War was proclaim'd
again&s;t <HI>Sweden.</HI></P>
<P>I HAVE nothing to do to enter here into a Di&s;|qui&s;ition
of the Ju&s;tice of this War, or of the
particular Cau&s;es moving the <HI>Czar</HI> to engage in it:
That his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty was Agre&s;&s;or, that we
do not di&s;pute, one of the Cau&s;es a&s;&s;ign'd was the
Affront offer'd his Amba&s;&s;adors at <HI>Riga,</HI> which
con&s;idering that his Maje&s;ty him&s;elf was in Per|&s;on
<PB N="95" REF="96">
in the Train, was &s;peaking the Language of
Princes a very great Indignity to his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Ma|je&s;ty,
and &s;ufficient to demand Satisfaction upon.</P>
<P>IN Con&s;equence however of having declar'd
War, it behov'd his Maje&s;ty to make &s;uitable
Preparations, for that he knew that he had a vi|gilant
and gallant King to deal with, tho' but a
young Man, and that he was the Head of a brave
People, had a good Army of old, and di&s;ciplind
Soldiers on Foot, led by &s;ome of the able&s;t Gene|ral
in <HI>Europe.</HI></P>
<P>HOWEVER, as the King of <HI>Sweden</HI> was young,
and far off, and that the Alliance was &s;trong, even
three-fold, his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty had room to expect
he might have made a con&s;iderable Progre&s;s be|fore
any Number could be brought again&s;t him,
that would be to any purpo&s;e.</P>
<P>THIS was began with the beginning of the
Year 1700, and his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty drew toge|ther
&s;uch a Body of Men, that had they been well
manag'd, would have been &s;ufficient to havewith
&s;tood a much greater Force than tho&s;e they were to
deal with; but the de&s;perate Bravery of the <HI>Swedes,</HI>
and the exact Di&s;cipline of their Troops &s;truck
&s;uch a Terror in the <HI>Mu&s;covites,</HI> that in a Word,
there was no Oppo&s;ing them, nor any bringing
the Troops to keep their Array, when pu&s;h'd
with the violence of an Army of Men, that knew
how to die, and how to Conquer, but had not yet
been taught to fly.</P>
<P>THE <HI>Czar</HI>'s Troops were wonderfully improv'd,
and infinitely better than they us'd to be, but,
were not yet come to a perfection &s;uitable to the
Work they had now before them; or to be a
Match for the <HI>Swedes;</HI> but as they had been put
into a Method of improving, yet farther we &s;hall
<PB N="96" REF="97">
find them in time be taught by the <HI>Swedes</HI> the
way of fighting, till they came to be a Match for
any Body, and at la&s;t learn'd to beat their Ma|&s;ters.</P>
<P>THUS the <HI>Romans</HI> by often beating the barba|rous
Nations, &s;uch as the <HI>Gauls,</HI> the <HI>Goths,</HI> the
<HI>Vandals,</HI> and the <HI>Huns,</HI> taught them the <HI>Roman</HI> di&s;|cipline,
and manner of Fighting; till tho&s;e Na|tions
return'd In&s;tructed how to Fight, and beat
their Teachers, not out of their Empire only, but
even out of the World.</P>
<P>IN order to Introduce the Hi&s;tory of this ter|rible
War in &s;uch a manner, as the Reader may
be fully inform'd of every Action, and of the na|ture
and rea&s;on of things, as he goes along with
the Fact; it will be nece&s;&s;ary to look a little into
the State of Affairs in tho&s;e Northern Parts of the
World in General, at that time, and how it came
to pa&s;s that tho&s;e three Powers, the <HI>Danes,</HI> the
<HI>Poles,</HI> and the <HI>Mu&s;covites</HI> broke at once with <HI>Swe|den;</HI>
and how their Intere&s;t and Forces came &s;o to
be disjointed and &s;eparated, that the <HI>Swedes</HI> had
opportunity to attack them &s;ingly, and deprive
them of the Capacity of Succouring or A&s;&s;i&s;ting
one another, and this I &s;hall do as conci&s;ely as
I can.</P>
<P>AT fir&s;t his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty did not appear in
this Quarrel; but the King of <HI>Poland,</HI> and the
King of <HI>Denmark</HI> both at once, whether declaring
War, or not declaring War, is not the Que&s;tion,
having an Alliance for that Purpo&s;e, fell both of
them upon the King of <HI>Sweden:</HI> The King of <HI>Poland</HI>
march'd in Per&s;on at the Head of a powerful and
experienc'd Army of <HI>Saxons,</HI> out of <HI>Poland</HI> direct|ly
for <HI>Courland;</HI> from whence he continu'd his
March, and the 28th of July, 1700 pa&s;s'd the
<PB N="97" REF="98">
<HI>Dwina,</HI> enter'd into <HI>Livonia,</HI> the Dominions of
the King of <HI>Sweden,</HI> and having beaten Count
<HI>Welling</HI> the <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> General, and the few Forces
he had with him, advanc'd towards <HI>Riga,</HI> and in|ve&s;ted
the Town, took the <HI>Dunamunder Schans,</HI>
began to Bombard the Town, but was prevail'd,
with to &s;pare it, in re&s;pect to the Effects of the
Foreign Merchants, as was given out, who were his
Allies, and &s;o Cantoning his Forces held the Town,
as it were Blocked up, re&s;olving to attack it in
Form the beginning of the next Year.</P>
<P>AT the &s;ame time the King of <HI>Denmark</HI> ha|ving
attack'd the Duke of <HI>Hol&s;teins</HI> Fort at <HI>Hu&s;um;</HI>
and Bombarded <HI>Toningen,</HI> made no difficulty to
&s;peak openly of a Rupture with <HI>Sweden,</HI> and to ac|knowledge
that he was engag'd in Alliance with
the King of <HI>Poland:</HI> The <HI>Czar</HI> all this while lay
&s;till, and made a &s;eeming offer of continuing
Peace with <HI>Swede;</HI> but civily demanded the
Town and Port of <HI>Narva</HI> for the Convenience of
having a Trade for his Subjects into the <HI>Baltick,</HI>
which at that time was the great thing that the
<HI>Mu&s;covites</HI> de&s;ir'd.</P>
<P>WHEN the King of <HI>Denmark</HI> had openly de|clar'd
him&s;elf, and the King of <HI>Poland</HI> had actually
attack'd <HI>Riga,</HI> then the <HI>Czar</HI> as had been concert|ed
between them at the enterview I mention'd, re|&s;olv'd
to declare him&s;elf al&s;o, and accordingly
as I have ob&s;erv'd before; the War again&s;t <HI>Sweden,</HI>
was Proclaim'd at <HI>Mu&s;covy</HI> the &s;ame day that the
Peace with the <HI>Turks</HI> was al&s;o Proclaimed.</P>
<P>BEFORE I go on here, I mu&s;t pay a Debt
which is the reward of Vertue, and which &s;o much
Merit demands from every faithful Hi&s;tiorian, I
mean a Debt to the Memory of that truly great
and wi&s;e Man General <HI>Le Fort;</HI> a Man to whom
<PB N="98" REF="99">
the <HI>Czar</HI> owes much of the true Notions of Vertue,
and Honour, which he took in at his fir&s;t Entrance
upon his Government, who always gave him ju&s;t
and &s;olid Ideas of things, and who prompted him to
all the great Actions of his Life, and who died
a little before the&s;e new Mea&s;ures were taken.</P>
<P>THIS great Man was really treated by the
<HI>Czar</HI> according to his Merit, for he valu'd him a|bove
any of the greate&s;t Men in his whole Em|pire,
and depended entirely upon his Council in
the mo&s;t difficult Ca&s;es that came before him; he
was the principal Agent in all the Mea&s;ures the
<HI>Czar</HI> took in his Travels, was his fir&s;t Amba&s;&s;ador
<HI>as has been &s;aid</HI> in the great Emba&s;&s;y, was his Ple|nipotentiary
upon all Occa&s;ions of Treaty, and
in a Word, he was &s;o at the time of his Death, all
which &s;hewed that the <HI>Czar</HI> knew how to put a
ju&s;t value upon the Merit of tho&s;e who he
employ'd, and that he was a true Judge of Merit
in general: <HI>I &s;ay,</HI> he was at the time of his Death
chief General of his Armies, Admiral of all his
Fleets, and his chief Mini&s;ter: He had &s;erved the
<HI>Mu&s;covites</HI> along time, by which he had advanc'd
him&s;elf to that degree of Honour, wherein he gli|ter'd
at his Death; the <HI>Czar</HI> had a particular Love
and E&s;teem for him, and was pleas'd to give the
World a demon&s;tration of it by the Funeral
which he be&s;tow'd upon him; for <HI>Mu&s;covy</HI> had ne|ver
&s;een &s;o much Pomp before upon any occa|&s;ion
all the military Ceremonies of the inter|ment
were the &s;ame as in the&s;e more civiliz'd
Parts of <HI>Europe;</HI> the Drums and Colours were co|ver'd
with black, the Officers of three Regiments
that preceeded the Hear&s;e, had black Scar$s, and
the Pikes garni&s;h'd at the top with Knots of black
Ribband; the En&s;igns of Honour belonging to
the deceas'd, were laid upon black Cu&s;hions em|broider'd
<PB N="99" REF="100">
with Gold; five Mini&s;ters preceeded
the Corps, three of which were of the reform'd
Religion, and two of the <HI>Ausburg</HI> Con&s;e&s;&s;ion and
one <HI>Stomnies</HI> preach'd the funeral Sermon, taking
for his Text the Words of the 8th Chapter <HI>Eccle|&s;ia&s;tes,</HI>
ver. 8. The <HI>Czar</HI> him&s;elf led the Regiments
in deep Mourning.</P>
<P>THE place of this Gentleman was fill'd up, I
cannot &s;ay it was &s;upply'd by Major General <HI>Car|lowitz,</HI>
and afterwards that of General of the Army
was made up, with the Duke <HI>de Croy,</HI> an Officer of
great Experience, and who had &s;erved the Emperor
many Campaigns again&s;t the <HI>Turks,</HI> but he could
never come to be &s;o well e&s;teem'd or belov'd by
the <HI>Mu&s;covites</HI> them&s;elves, and con&s;equently not
be &s;o well followed.</P>
<P>THE War being thus re&s;olv'd on, the <HI>Czar</HI>
caus'd his Cavalry to draw together about <HI>Novo|gorod,</HI>
and particularly the Hor&s;e who had done
&s;uch great Service at <HI>A&s;poh</HI> were order'd by ea&s;y
Marches, for it is a prodigious long way, to ad|vance
to <HI>Mu&s;cow,</HI> and thence to the Fronciers;
his Infantry at the &s;ame time were drawn together
from all Parts, and were computed to make very
near 100000 Men, the Hor&s;e were reported to be
25000; but the&s;e were not all the Troops prepa|red
for that Expedition, for his Maje&s;ty had a
con&s;iderable Body of Men, which were come to
<HI>Novogorod,</HI> but were not at the Battle at <HI>Narva,</HI> be|ing
tho&s;e who the <HI>Czar</HI> went in Per&s;on to bring for|ward,
which was the happy Rea&s;on that he was not
in the Battle him&s;elf; which if he had, he would
have run a very great Ri&s;que of being taken Pri|&s;oner
by the <HI>Swedes.</HI></P>
<P>ABOUT the clo&s;e of the Month of <HI>Augu&s;t,</HI> his
<HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty re&s;olv'd upon the War with <HI>Sweden,</HI>
<PB N="100" REF="101">
and in <HI>September,</HI> his Troops inve&s;ted <HI>Narva,</HI> his
Declaration of War having been in the mean time
publi&s;hed to all the World to the Purpo&s;e following.</P>
<P>THAT altho' the <HI>Swede</HI> had a&s;&s;ur'd the <HI>Czar</HI>
that he would maintain Peace with him, and bind
it by a &s;trict Amity, and Corre&s;pondence; and for
that Rea&s;on had &s;ent a &s;olemn Emba&s;&s;y to renew
his Treaties, neverthele&s;s his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty com|plain'd
and averred, that the King of <HI>Sweden</HI> had un|derhand
made u&s;e of &s;everal Intrigues to cro&s;s his
De&s;igns, and among others had propos'd to the King
of <HI>Poland</HI> a League to act in Conjunction with
him again&s;t the <HI>Czar;</HI> and tho&s;e Intreagues were
the Cau&s;e in part of the difficulties which happen|ed
at <HI>Con&s;tantinople</HI> in the Conclu&s;ion of the
Peace between the <HI>Czar,</HI> and the Port, which
his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty cannot forbare to make
known to all the World, and particularly to all
Chri&s;tian Princes, in hopes they will acknowledge
that he has been oblig'd to make u&s;e of tho&s;e law|ful
Means, which he has in his Power for the
Pre&s;ervation of his Dominions; and that if he
has declar'd War again&s;t <HI>Swedeland,</HI> 'its only to
prevent her doing him any injury by &s;uch unju&s;t
Proceedings: The &s;econd Motive is, for that
the <HI>Czar</HI> and his Predece&s;&s;ors have always held a
&s;trict Alliance with the Kings of <HI>Denmark,</HI> by
Virtue of which, they were oblig'd to the mutual
A&s;&s;i&s;tance of each other, and reciprocally to re|venge
the Wrongs done to either; that the King
of <HI>Sweden</HI> had Landed in Per&s;on in <HI>Zeeland</HI> with a
&s;trong Army, in the ab&s;ence of the King of <HI>Den|mark,</HI>
and put his capital City, and his whole
Kingdom in danger; that he had not only con|&s;train'd
the said Prince to make a di&s;advantageous
Treaty with the Duke of <HI>Hol&s;tein,</HI> but had al&s;o
excluded the King of <HI>Poland,</HI> his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty's
<PB N="101" REF="102">
Friend and Confederate, that he might have an
Opportunity to oppre&s;s and utterly Ruin him,
that for the&s;e Rea&s;ons his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty found
him&s;elf oblig'd to revenge the Wrongs done his
Friends and Allies, and to break all the dange|rous
Practice again&s;t them.</P>
<P>AFTER this he &s;ent to his Re&s;ident in <HI>Sweden</HI>
to make known his Re&s;olutions to that Court,
and having his Levies ready, which are re|ported
to con&s;i&s;t of five and twenty Thou&s;and
Hor&s;e, and &s;eventy Thou&s;and Foot, together with a
Train of four Hundred and &s;ixty Cannon and Mor|tars;
he took Po&s;t for <HI>Ple&s;ko,</HI> to take a review
of his Forces; the command of which he had con|ferr'd upon <HI>Aframaon Go&s;owitz,</HI> as General, who has
under him <HI>Theodore Alexovitz Golovin,</HI> as General
of the Hor&s;e, with General <HI>Adan Wyde,</HI> and &s;everal
<HI>German</HI> Officers. Of the&s;e 'twas &s;aid that the <HI>Czar</HI>
intended to &s;end between twenty and thirty Thou|&s;and
Men to Re-inforce the King of <HI>Poland</HI>'s Ar|my,
and that he intended to divide the re&s;t in|to
two Bodies, one of which was to be&s;iege <HI>Narva,</HI>
and the other to Po&s;t them&s;elves at &s;ome di&s;tance
from thence, to hinder Relief from coming to the
Town.</P>
<P>THE City of <HI>Nerva</HI> or <HI>Narva,</HI> &s;tands upon the
hither Side of the <HI>Gulph</HI> of <HI>Finland,</HI> toward the Pro|vince
of <HI>Ingria,</HI> upon a River of the &s;ame Name,
which formerly &s;eparated <HI>Livonia</HI> from <HI>Mu&s;covy:</HI>
On the other Side of the River &s;tands the Fortre&s;s of
<HI>Ivanagrod,</HI> formerly built upon a &s;leep Rock that
appears in the River, like a Penin&s;ula; and which
was thought impregnable till the Year 1617, that
it was taken by <HI>Gu&s;tav$s Adolphus,</HI> King of <HI>Sweden;</HI>
at the Foot of this Rock lies a Town call'd <HI>Ru&s;&s;ian,</HI>
or <HI>Mu&s;covite Narva,</HI> the City in di&s;pute: This
<PB N="102" REF="103">
City is Inhabited by natural <HI>Mu&s;covites,</HI> but Sub|jects
to the Crown of <HI>Sweden;</HI> the River of <HI>Narva&punc;</HI>
which ri&s;es out of the Lake of <HI>Peipus,</HI> and dis|charges
it&s;elf there into the <HI>Gulph</HI> of <HI>Finland,</HI> is
very rapid, and there is a Precipiece in it about
half a League above the City, where the Waters fall
with an extraordinary violence and noi&s;e, and by
accident produces a wonderful effect, for the Sun
&s;hining all the Morning upon the falling Water,
cau&s;es the appearance of a Rainbow, as lovely
as that which is &s;een in the Clouds; by rea&s;on
of this Fall, the Merchants are forc'd to unload
in that Place all their Goods which are &s;ent from
<HI>Pleskow</HI> and <HI>Dorpat</HI> to <HI>Narva,</HI> to be there Shipped
off upon the <HI>Gulpb</HI> of <HI>Finland:</HI> The City of <HI>Nar|va</HI>
was built in 1213, by <HI>Waldemare</HI> II, King of
<HI>Denmark, John Ba&s;ilides</HI> Grand Duke of <HI>Mu&s;covy</HI>
took it in the Year 1558, from the <HI>Tuetonick</HI>
Knights; but the Citizens of <HI>Revel,</HI> who then in
vain implor'd the Succour of the grand Ma&s;ter
<HI>Bernard Keltier,</HI> and Chri&s;tian King of <HI>Denmark,</HI>
threw them&s;elves at length into the Arms of <HI>Eric</HI>
the IV King of <HI>Sweden,</HI> who receiv'd them into his
Protection upon certain Conditions, and coming to
their A&s;&s;i&s;tance, &s;ecured them from the de&s;tiny of o|ther
Cities, his Succe&s;&s;or John III, retook <HI>Narva</HI> from
the <HI>Mu&s;covites</HI> in 1581, &s;ince which time the <HI>Swedes</HI>
have continu'd in po&s;&s;e&s;&s;ion of it, notwith&s;tanding all the Attempts of the <HI>Mu&s;covites</HI> to regain it.</P>
<P>THUS the <HI>Swedes</HI> had at once three powerful
Enemies upon their hands; Namely, the <HI>Danes,</HI>
the <HI>Poles,</HI> and the <HI>Mu&s;covites;</HI> the King of <HI>Poland</HI>
would have &s;ent 8000 Men, 4000 Foot, and 4000
Hor&s;e to a&s;&s;i&s;t the King of <HI>Denmark,</HI> but the E|lector
of <HI>Brandenburgh</HI> would not let them pa&s;s
thro' his Country, being re&s;olv'd to ob&s;erve an
<PB N="103" REF="104">
exact Neutrallity between all Parties, and they
were afterwards beaten by the <HI>Lunenburhger,</HI> in
pa&s;&s;ing thro' the lower <HI>Saxony.</HI> The <HI>Czar</HI> on
his Side prepar'd to &s;end 30000 Men into <HI>Lithu|ania,</HI>
to the a&s;&s;i&s;tance of the King of <HI>Poland,</HI> which
however his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty could not yet do, things
for a time, running very much again&s;t him, as we
&s;hall hear.</P>
<P>IT is not our bu&s;ine&s;s in writing of the <HI>Czar</HI>
of <HI>Mu&s;covy,</HI> to examine what happen'd in every
part of this War, any farther than to bring things
to the pre&s;ent Ca&s;e in hand, and to introduce
&s;uch incidents as relate to the <HI>Czar</HI> him&s;elf.</P>
<P>THE King of <HI>Sweden</HI> young in his Throne, and
not yet above 18 Year old in Per&s;on, yet being
encouraged by the united Squadrons of <HI>Great Bri|tain</HI>
and <HI>Holland,</HI> which appear'd, as (a kind of)
Umpire in the <HI>Baltick;</HI> I &s;ay encourag'd by
them, he embark'd an Army, and from <HI>Schonen</HI>
joyning the Fleet of the Allies, with his own, comes
directly to the &s;ound, lands his Army in the
I&s;le of <HI>Zeeland,</HI> and lies there ready to, ct ei|ther
one way or other, as the Treaty of <HI>Traven|dal,</HI>
which was then carrying on by Mediators
&s;hould direct.</P>
<P>THE King of <HI>Denmark</HI> &s;urpriz'd, and over|power'd,
ha&s;tens up the Peace, and &s;o the King of
<HI>Sweden,</HI> reimbark'd his Troops, and went back to
<HI>Sweden,</HI> very little blood being &s;hed in that Part
of the War; this was the well known Treaty of
<HI>Travendal,</HI> &s;ign'd, and concluded the 18th of
<HI>Augu&s;t.</HI></P>
<P>WHILE the&s;e things were tran&s;acting, the King
of <HI>Poland</HI> made his Fruitle&s;s attempt upon <HI>Riga,</HI> of
which mention has been made already, I call it but
an attempt, for altho' he inve&s;ted the Place the 8th
<PB N="104" REF="105">
of <HI>Augu&s;t,</HI> he &s;pent two Months before it, without
any con&s;iderable Progre&s;s and then left his Army;
turning the Seige into a kind of Blockade, and &s;o
as if he had waited on purpo&s;e for the King of
<HI>Sweden</HI> to come and beat him, did nothing till the
next Spring.</P>
<P>IN <HI>September,</HI> as I have ob&s;erv'd, the Troops
of <HI>Mu&s;covy</HI> began to move; it was a long &s;tep
they had to take; but the <HI>Czar</HI> being at the
Head of them, they made long Marches, and the
2d of <HI>November</HI> they joyn'd the Troops before
<HI>Narva.</HI> Hither the Duke <HI>de Croy</HI> came, with a|bout
fifty Gentlemen, all Officers of Experience,
and who came from <HI>Hungary,</HI> where they had
&s;erv'd the Emperor again&s;t the <HI>Turks;</HI> as &s;oon as
he arriv'd, the <HI>Czar</HI> who had invited him to his
Service, gave him the command of the Siege; him|&s;elf
commanding the Army; the other Officers
which he brought with him, were appointed Com|mands
in different Places, according to their parti|cular
Experience in Service.</P>
<P>THESE Gentlemen joyn'd to the foreign Of|ficers,
which his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty had entertain'd
before, brought the <HI>Mu&s;covite</HI> Troops into the be&s;t
Method of pro&s;ecuting a Siege; caus'd them to En|trench
their Camp, as well with Circumvalations,
as Contravallations, and had the Army been al|low'd
a Campaign or two for the Practice of tho&s;e
new Methods, the <HI>Swedes</HI> would not have had &s;o
cheap a Bargain of them; but as the Men might
be &s;aid to be put out of their old way of Fight|ing,
and not well acquainted, or fully Exerci&s;ed
in the New, between both, they were more ea&s;ily
put into Confu&s;ion.</P>
<P><PB N="105" REF="106">
THIS will appear by the General Duke <HI>de
Croy's</HI> Letter to the King of <HI>Poland,</HI> in which he
applauds the readine&s;s of the <HI>Mu&s;covite</HI> Soldiers
in their new Exerci&s;es, how regularly they
began to Fire, how well they plyed their Artil|lery,
and how &s;oon they hoped to make good
Soldiers of them, which conforms with what I
have ob&s;erv'd, as above: The Letter is as follows.</P>
<P>&startq;LIEUTENANT General <HI>Hallard</HI> arriv'd
the 2d of this Month before <HI>Narva,</HI> where
he found the Governor of <HI>Novogrod</HI> with 8000
Men entrench'd in a &s;quare Camp, 2500 Paces
from the Town; the fir&s;t of the&s;e two, has
view'd the Place and the Fortifications, and
has ob&s;erv'd &s;everal Parts very imperfect, and
among the re&s;t, two Curtins which are in a ve|ry
bad Condition, which makes us pre&s;ume, that
this important Place cannot hold out long.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;THE 4th of this Month, the <HI>Czar</HI> caus'd a
Bridge of Boats to be laid over the River <HI>Nar|va,</HI>
and pa&s;t it him&s;elf at the Head of 22 Ba|talions,
with a half Pike in his hand, and
march'd &s;omewhat farther; his Men much re|&s;emble
ours, and are very well Arm'd and Di&s;|ciplin'd,
they have al&s;o 32 bra&s;s Field Pieces; 'tis
a Plea&s;ure to &s;ee the <HI>Mu&s;covites</HI> fire them, and
with what Diligence and Addre&s;s they ply
their Artillery; his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty cau&s;es his
Men to keep good Orders, and an exact Di&s;|cipline,
which is the Rea&s;on that the Products
of the Earth are carefully pre&s;erv'd; they are
hard at Work in rai&s;ing the Circumvallations;
the be&s;ieg'd play very thick with their great
Guns; neverthele&s;s we have had but one Sol|dier
kill'd, and two wounded; the heavy Ar|tillery
<PB N="106" REF="107">
will arrive in the Camp within few Days.
General <HI>Weyde</HI> is upon his March with a great
Body of an Army, and Mar&s;hal General <HI>Gollowin</HI>
who has above 50000 Men with him in <HI>Me&s;&s;ap|pa</HI>
is to follow him with the &s;ame Number; and
the Prince <HI>Loym</HI> with 11000, &s;o that in a little
time the Army will be about 200000 Men, with
a noble Train of Attillery; as for the Lines of
Communication his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty has drawn
them him&s;elf, after he had view'd the
Place.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;A <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> Officer who De&s;erted out of <HI>Nar|va,</HI>
&s;urrendred him&s;elf, &s;ome few Days ago to
his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty, who examin'd him, and we
under&s;tood that Colonel <HI>Horn</HI> Commands in
<HI>Narva,</HI> that the Garri&s;on con&s;i&s;ts of 900 Foot,
and 150 Hor&s;e, 400 Pea&s;ants, and 400 Burghers,
that Lieutenant Colonel <HI>Stahl</HI> commanded
the Artillery, and that it was in a good Condi|tion,
there are &s;ome Bra&s;s Pieces; but all the
rest are Iron.&endq;</P>
<P>IT is too well known to conceal it, that the
King of <HI>Sweden</HI> rais'd this Siege with the fatal o|verthrow
of the <HI>Mu&s;ocvite</HI> Army; but the Circum|stances
of that Action are &s;o full of the Flattery
of the Writers, in their Encomiums upon the King
of <HI>Sweden,</HI> that they totally forget the Decency
which the Merit of the Prince, he had at that
time the better of demanded; and who command|ed
it from them in &s;ome &s;mall time after; in the
mean time we &s;hall not fail to do the <HI>Swedes</HI> ju|&s;tice
on all occa&s;ions, as well as on this of the
Battle of <HI>Narva.</HI></P>
<P>HISTORY brings the King of <HI>Sweden</HI> from
<HI>Carel&s;coon</HI> to <HI>Peruau</HI> in <HI>Livona,</HI> with an Army of
<PB N="107" REF="108">
about 20000 <HI>Swedes,</HI> all choice Troops, about the
beginning of <HI>Augu&s;t.</HI></P>
<P>ON the 16th of <HI>Novem&punc;</HI> the <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> Army be|gan
their March towards <HI>Narva:</HI> The <HI>Czar,</HI> who
fore&s;aw that the King of <HI>Sweden,</HI> a daring and en|terpri&s;ing
young Prince, would play the de&s;perate
Game, &s;ent &s;ome &s;trong Detachments to &s;ecure
the Pa&s;&s;es at <HI>Sillajoggi,</HI> and on the &s;ide of <HI>Dorpat;</HI> not
doubting but that tho&s;e Troops, which were at lea&s;t
20000 Men, would give the <HI>Swedes</HI> &s;ome little &s;top
at Places &s;o easy to be defended, and at lea&s;t Cau&s;e
them to take a greater Compa&s;s about; in the
mean time his Maje&s;ty went him&s;elf for <HI>Novogo|rod,</HI>
to bring up a Body of 40000 Men, who were
by this time gotten thither, and to ha&s;ten their
March.</P>
<P>BUT the King of <HI>Sweden,</HI> by a feint of pa&s;|&s;ing
by tho&s;e Detachments, having gotten between
them and their main Army, and thereby cut off
their Retreat, cau&s;ed a &s;trong Body to Face a|bout
and attack them, which Surprize a&s;&s;i&s;ted to
put them into di&s;order, &s;o that they made but a
faint Re&s;i&s;tance, and were &s;oon Defeated. This
opened the way to the attack of the grand Army,
which the <HI>Czar</HI> being ab&s;ent, and tho&s;e Troops
defeated, were extreamly di&s;courag'd.</P>
<P>HOWEVER the Duke <HI>de Croy,</HI> an old Soldier,
and not at a lo&s;s what to do, had the Men he Com|manded
been equal to the Work, po&s;ted his
Troops to all the Advantage the Ground would
admit, and did all that the be&s;t General in the
World could have done to animate them to a vi|gorous
Defence; he po&s;ted the Infantry in the
Entrenchment, where they fir'd as in a cover'd
Way, and a &s;econd Line to &s;upport them, and
the Cavalry behind them to &s;upport the Foot,
<PB N="108" REF="109">
with proper Intervals for them to Advance; but
the <HI>Mu&s;covite</HI> Foot wanted the Pre$ence of their
Ma&s;ter to animate them, which had been better
than the 40000 Men he was gone to fetch; and
tho' they &s;tood their Ground bravely for &s;everal
Hours, and made a terrible fire upon the <HI>Swedes,</HI>
from behind their Entrenchment, by which a great
many of the brave&s;t of their Men were kill'd; yet
the <HI>Swedes</HI> animated by the Pre&s;ence of their
King, and General <HI>Rebinder</HI> at the Head of eight
Batallions, pouring fre&s;h upon that part of the
<HI>Mu&s;covite</HI> Line, which had been twice before at|tack'd,
there was no re&s;i&s;ting the de&s;parate Fury
of the <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> Foot, led on by a general of as
much Fame as any in their Army, who fought at
the Head of them, like a Lyon, and was kill'd
in the very Action, altho' after the Troops were
entred: In &s;hort, the Line was forc'd in that
Place, and the Foot enter'd, and the Pioneers
immediately going to Work with the Shovel and
Pick-ax, wide &s;paces were made in the Brea&s;t-work
for the Hor&s;e to follow, who pre&s;ently Charging
in upon the Rear of the <HI>Mu&s;covite</HI> Foot, which
were in the other part of the Line, put all into
Confu&s;ion, the &s;econd Line advancing were then
Charg'd by the Victorious <HI>Swedes,</HI> and driven back
upon the Cavalry, who by that Means were put
into Di&s;&s;order, and had no room to come up to
the Charge; and thus the Day was lo&s;t: The re&s;t of
the Infantry, being &s;traightn'd within the Compa&s;s
of their Camp, had no room to make an orderly
Retreat, but were oblig'd to thro' down their Arms,
and take Quarter. The Hor&s;e not able to re&s;i&s;t
the Torrent after their Infantry were thus Defeat|ed,
made off and Retreated in as good order as
they could to <HI>Novogrod,</HI> in the way whether they
<PB N="109" REF="110">
were met, and their Spirits a little encouraged by
the Troops which were Advancing to their A&s;&s;i|&s;tance, and by the
<HI>Czar</HI> their Soveraign.</P>
<P>IT was ob&s;erv'd, that the <HI>Czar</HI> &s;hew'd not the lea&s;t
Di&s;order, either in his Countenance, or in his Con|duct,
when he had the News of the Defeat of his Ar|my,
or any Re&s;entment at his flying Troops; but
immediately apylyed him&s;elf to gather the &s;cat|ter'd
Troops together, encourag'd the Men, &s;poke
kindly to the Officers, and prepar'd to put a &s;top
to the pur&s;uit of the Conquerers, if their Succe&s;s
&s;hould prompt them to follow his Men, and to
put all things in a po&s;ture of Defence, in Ca&s;e
the King of <HI>Sweden</HI> &s;hould undertake any new
Enterpri&s;e, or attempt to pu&s;h farther into the
Country.</P>
<P>BUT the <HI>Swedes</HI> had not their Victory &s;o
cheap neither, as to be in Condition for any far|ther
attempt at that time of the Year. They had
by their own Confe&s;&s;ion lo&s;t above 3000 Men,
be&s;ides the wounded, among which were a great
many brave Officers, as General <HI>Rublinghen, Re|binder,</HI>
and &s;everal others; add to this, the King
of <HI>Sweden</HI> had the Winter Sea&s;on before him,
which was already far Advanc'd; and as the
Snows and Fro&s;ts were not yet come in, the ways
were unpa&s;&s;able, and no Magazines erected for
providing the Army with Forage or Provi&s;i|ons;
so that he contented him&s;elf with having
relieved the Town, and beaten the Army, as he
might very well.</P>
<P>THE <HI>Czar</HI> advancing to <HI>Pe&s;kow</HI> within twelve
Leagues of <HI>Narva,</HI> made a &s;tand there, to give
his Men opportunity to return to their Colours,
which many did, who it was, thought had been lo&s;t,
and here his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Majesty form'd a new Army,
<PB N="110" REF="111">
in order to di&s;pute the Ground with the <HI>Swedes,</HI> if
they had offer'd to Advance.</P>
<P>BUT the King of <HI>Sweden,</HI> as I ob&s;erv'd, having
reliev'd <HI>Narva,</HI> and gain'd a compleat Victory,
put his Troops into Quarters of Refre&s;hment for
the Sea&s;on, and contented him&s;elf with boa&s;ting
of what great things he would do in the <HI>Czar</HI>'s
Dominions the next Year, and to give tho&s;e <HI>Ga|&s;conades</HI>
an Appearance of reality, he &s;ent
expre&s;s Orders to <HI>Sweden</HI> to &s;end over into <HI>Livonia,</HI>
with the fir&s;t of the Spring, that is, as &s;oon as the
Seas were open again, his whole remaining Army,
in the room of which they were order'd to make
new Levies for the common Guard of their Coun|try;
the&s;e Forces were &s;aid to con&s;i&s;t of about
12000 Foot, and 6000 Hor&s;e, and Dragoons, but
Heaven and his own Fate found the King of <HI>Swe|den</HI>
other Work than to enter <HI>Mu&s;covy,</HI> or to Pro|&s;ecute
his Revenge at that time.</P>
<P>IT cannot be denyed, that had, the King of
<HI>Sweden,</HI> when tho&s;e Forces did arrive pu&s;h'd the
Advantages, which his late Victory had put into
his Hand, and per&s;ued his Revenge &s;ingly again&s;t
<HI>Mu&s;covy,</HI> the <HI>Czar</HI>'s Troops, tho' Numerous, be|ing
nothing like to what we find them to be
&s;ince, or as we may &s;ay to what the King of <HI>Swe|den</HI>
has taught them to be &s;ince, he might with
a victorious Army of 40000 Men, have bid fair for
the Ruin of the <HI>Czar,</HI> and of all his great De&s;igns;
but ju&s;t Heaven, who knew what a furious inexo|rable
Enemy, the <HI>Swede</HI> at that time was, tyed
up his Hands, till the <HI>Czar</HI> learnt how to Conquer
his Conqueror, and to beat him into a better
Knowledge of him&s;elf; making him pay for a like
de&s;perate Attempt upon the <HI>Mu&s;covites,</HI> with the
lo&s;s of the Honour of all his former Victories,
<PB N="111" REF="112">
and of two &s;uch Armies as he never &s;aw him&s;elf
Ma&s;ter of afterwards, of all which in his order.</P>
<P>SUCCESS had now made the King of <HI>Sweden</HI>
famous, I will not &s;ay it had made him in&s;olent,
becau&s;e a Hi&s;torian &s;hould write in Temper, e|ven
of tho&s;e Actions, which were not perform'd
in Temper, and treat all Sides with an impartial
Re&s;pect.</P>
<P>THE King of <HI>Sweden</HI> had al&s;o another Call,
from the pur&s;uit of his Victory at <HI>Narva,</HI> and
this was the attempt of the <HI>Saxons</HI> upon the o|ther
&s;ide of <HI>Livonia,</HI> where the King of <HI>Poland</HI>
had, <HI>as I &s;aid,</HI> inve&s;ted <HI>Riga,</HI> taken the <HI>Dunamun|der
Schans,</HI> and had Quartered his Troops in &s;uch
a manner, as to hold the &s;aid City of <HI>Riga</HI> in a
manner block'd up.</P>
<P>THE <HI>Saxons</HI> were e&s;teem'd by the <HI>Swedes</HI> a more
Soldierly Enemy, than the <HI>Mu&s;covites,</HI> and at that
time, perhaps they were &s;o, but thus it is when Hea|ven
appoints to rai&s;e a young King to a pitch of
Glory beyond him&s;elf; the <HI>Saxons</HI> at <HI>Riga</HI> real|ly
behav'd wor&s;e a great deal than the <HI>Mu&s;co|vites</HI>
at <HI>Narva,</HI> and were &s;o &s;hamefully beaten in
every Action, and even without Action, that
there could nothing be &s;aid for them.</P>
<P>THE <HI>Mu&s;covite</HI> Army po&s;ted in their En|trenchments,
and encumber'd with the Lines, and
Circumvallations of a Camp, did their Duty till
being forc'd in one part, they were driven upon one
another and Defeated, meerly for want of Field
room, for their Cavalry to act in; for it cannot
be doubted, that had the <HI>Mu&s;covite</HI> Calvalry;
which were at lea&s;t 25000 Hor&s;e and Dragoons,
had room to act, and to have fallen in, and &s;ur|rounded
the <HI>Swedes,</HI> as by their Number they were
able to have done, the <HI>Swedes</HI> would have paid
<PB N="112" REF="113">
much dearer for their Victory, than they did, if
perhaps they had not been &s;oundly beaten.</P>
<P>BUT the <HI>Saxons</HI> play'd the <HI>Poltrons</HI> in &s;uch an
egregious manner, as made even their own King
a&s;ham'd of them; and as encourag'd the <HI>Swedes</HI>
to pu&s;h into the Heart of <HI>Poland,</HI> at that time
wretchedly divided into factions and Parties, pro|&s;ecuting
mortal Feuds against one another, with
&s;uch an implacable Violence, that they cho&s;e
to Sacrifice their Country to the common E|nemy,
and bring a foreign War into their own
Bowels, rather than not pur&s;ue their private
Feuds and Family Quarrels, to the De&s;truction
of one another, and at la&s;t to the Ruin of their
King and their Country; which they brought into
an entire Subjection to the tyrannical Conqueror,
the King of <HI>Sweden.</HI></P>
<P>I AM oblig'd to give an Account here of the
Progre&s;s of the War in <HI>Poland,</HI> becau&s;e the King
of <HI>Sweden;</HI> having by the impetuo&s;ity of his Vi|ctory
brought the King of <HI>Poland</HI> to the utmo&s;t
Di&s;tre&s;s, Rea&s;on and Policy of State, as well as
the natural Genero&s;ity of Friend&s;hip, brought his
<HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty into the War, and made <HI>Poland</HI>
the Field, or Seat of the affair, as well between
the <HI>Czar,</HI> of <HI>Mu&s;covy,</HI> and the King of <HI>Sweden,</HI>
as between the King of <HI>Poland,</HI> and the King of
<HI>Sweden,</HI> and the King of <HI>Sweden,</HI> not thinking fit
to &s;eek his Enemy, the <HI>Czar</HI> at his capital City of
<HI>Mu&s;cow,</HI> as he had given out he would; his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI>
Maje&s;ty was oblig'd to &s;eek him the King of
<HI>Sweden</HI> out, even where he was to be found; as
we &s;hall &s;ee he did effectually in the Pro&s;ecution
of this War. This Defeat of the <HI>Saxons</HI> was a|bout
the beginning of July 1701, by which means
the King of <HI>Sweden</HI> got po&s;&s;e&s;&s;ion of the Dutchy
<PB N="113" REF="114">
of <HI>Courland,</HI> where in the Ca&s;tle of <HI>Mittau,</HI> he
&s;eized the whole Magazine of Arms and Ammu|nition
belonging to, and laid up for the King of
<HI>Poland's</HI> Army, valued at 300000 Crowns, and
afterwards retook the Fort of <HI>Dunamunder,</HI> where
he found the Train of Artillery of the &s;ame Ar|my,
con&s;i&s;ting of 90 Pieces of Bra&s;s Cannon for
Battery, and 20 bra&s;s Mortars, which was a mo&s;t
agreeable Booty to a Prince ju&s;t entring upon a
War again&s;t two &s;uch Potent Nations, as the
<HI>Mu&s;covites</HI> and the <HI>Poles.</HI></P>
<P>BUT leaving the King of <HI>Sweden,</HI> guided by
his ill Fate to pur&s;ue and embarra&s;s him&s;elf in
the Affairs of <HI>Poland,</HI> where fir&s;t he will cloth
him&s;elf with Glory and load himself with Lawrels,
which mu&s;t be all taken from him in one Day, by
the more glorious Conqueror, the <HI>Czar;</HI> I &s;ay,
leaving him there to pur&s;ue his Fate, and omit|ting
the only offer that he will ever have of ruin|ing
his fir&s;t Enemy the <HI>Czar</HI> of <HI>Mu&s;covy,</HI> and
pu&s;hing his Victory in its proper time, which if
he had done, the <HI>Czar</HI> had perhaps never been
able to &s;tand before him: I mu&s;t now go back to
his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty's conduct after this capital
Blow given to his Forces before <HI>Narva.</HI></P>
<P>I HAVE mention'd how his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty
as if unconcern'd at the &s;urprizing News, ap|ply'd
him&s;elf to comfort and encourage his Offi|cers
and Soldiers, his Cavalry had not really
&s;uffer'd much, his Infantry indeed was ruin'd and
gone; but every Body knows foot Soldiers are
pretty cheap in <HI>Mu&s;covy,</HI> where the <HI>Czar</HI> being
ab&s;olute Monarch, commands as many of his Peo|ple
to the Wars as he plea&s;es.</P>
<P><PB N="114" REF="115">
HOWEVR, this was not his Maje&s;ty's ca&s;e now, for
in&s;tead of commanding out &s;uch and &s;uch Num|bers
of Men, for the Summer Service, and let|ting
them go Home again when the Campaign
was over, perhaps, calling another Hundred
Thou&s;and out the next Year, who never &s;aw the
Field or an Enemy before, His <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty
now took a new Cour&s;e; he caus'd the Drums
to beat for Voluntiers over all his va&s;t Em|pire,
telling the People their Advantages, how
they &s;hould be new Cloathed, that they &s;hould be
duly Paid as Gentlemen Soldiers; and that in their
due Order, and as they merited by their Behavi|our,
they &s;hould be, Prefer'd and Rewarded; &s;o
that every Foot Soldier was capable of being not
a Captain only, but a General, if he behaved
well in his Po&s;t.</P>
<P>THIS which was a new Thing in <HI>Mu&s;covy,</HI>
went a great way, and caus'd a va&s;t Number of
Men to come in and Li&s;t, who were immediately
encouraged with half a Ruble advance Money,
and Weekly Pay, be&s;ides &s;ufficient to &s;ub&s;i&s;t them,
and make them live Ea&s;y and Plea&s;ant; be&s;ides
this&punc; his Maje&s;ty caus'd all the Boyars or Nobility
to $end a certain Number of Men, in proportion
to the Number of Servants which they kept, and
to the Revenue of their E&s;tates.</P>
<P>BY this means, his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty had his Ar|my
prefently full, &s;o that before the next Cam|paign,
he had near 120000 New li&s;ted Men ready
rai&s;ed, whom he caus'd to be form'd into Regi|ments
after the manner of <HI>Europe;</HI> &s;ome of four
Baltalions, &s;ome of two Battalions, and &s;ome of
but one Battalion, as he found Cau&s;e.</P>
<P><PB N="115" REF="116">
AS for the <HI>Strelitzes,</HI> the <HI>Czar</HI> had now &s;uppre&s;t
the very Name, and as much as po&s;&s;ible de&s;ir'd to
ra&s;e out the very Memory of them from the
Earth; in their Room his Maje&s;ty form'd &s;eve|ral
new Reigments of &s;elect choice Men; mo&s;t
of them old Soldiers, and a great many of
them <HI>Germans,</HI> or Foreigners of other Nations,
tho' none of them were admitted but &s;uch as had
&s;erv'd Abroad in &s;ome of the Wars, either on the
<HI>Danube</HI> or the <HI>Rhine.</HI></P>
<P>AS the <HI>Czar</HI> had lei&s;ure thus to rai&s;e this Ar|my;
&s;o the King of <HI>Sweden</HI> being fully engag'd
in pur&s;uing the King of <HI>Poland,</HI> as a particular
Enemy, gave his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty full Lei&s;ure to
make all his new Army, what they never could be
&s;aid to be before; that is, not only Men, but Sol|diers,
for they had lei&s;ure to be fully acquainted
with their Arms, and to under&s;tand how to do
their Exerci&s;e after the <HI>German</HI> method by beat
of Drum: He po&s;ted them al&s;o in great Bodies
upon the Frontiers of <HI>Livonia,</HI> where, tho' the
<HI>Swedes</HI> behav'd with their wanted Bravery and
oftentimes were too hard for them; yet in their
turn they beat the <HI>Swedes</HI> too, and oftentimes
$ut whole Parties of them in Pieces; by which they
began to be enured to the War, acquainted them|&s;elves
with the New manner of Fighting; learn'd to
look a bold Enemy in the Face, and to find that
the <HI>Swedes</HI> were not invulnerable or invincible: In
a Word, they learn't by frequent fighting the <HI>Swedes,</HI>
not to be &s;o much afraid of them, as u&s;ual, and
thus if they did not always beat the <HI>Swedes;</HI> yet
they continually harra&s;s'd them, and wa&s;ted their
Numbers, which the <HI>Swedes</HI> not being ea&s;ily Re|$ruited
with Numbers as the <HI>Mu&s;covites</HI> were, and
the King of <HI>Sweden</HI> pu&s;hing his Re&s;olution of de|po&s;ing
<PB N="116" REF="117">
King <HI>Augu&s;tus</HI> with &s;uch vigour, that he
as it were neglected his own Subjects of <HI>Livonia:</HI>
The <HI>Czar</HI> improving in the mean time every op|portunity,
and keeping his Troops full, &s;end|ing
con&s;tant Supplies of fre&s;h Men to make up
the Lo&s;s of tho&s;e that were kill'd, or di&s;abled;
his Reigments in <HI>Livonia</HI> became in two or three
Year equal with the <HI>Swedes</HI> in goodne&s;s of the
$word$, and infinitely Superiour to them in Num|$$r,
till the <HI>Swedes</HI> came to be beaten oftentimes,
Hand to Hand with equal Numbers, were pu&s;h'd
from Po&s;t to Po&s;t, and at la&s;t pu&s;h'd out of the
whole Province, as we &s;hall &s;ee its in Cour&s;e.</P>
<P>AT the &s;ame time the Troubles of <HI>Lith$ania</HI>
ope$'d a Door for the two Enemies, the <HI>Mu&s;covites</HI>
and the <HI>Swedes</HI> to enter on that Side. The two great
Families of <HI>Saphiea</HI> and <HI>Ogin&s;ki,</HI> had brought
their Breach, which was at fir&s;t but a private
Quarrel, to be an open War: <HI>Ogin&s;ki</HI> was &s;up|ported
by the King of <HI>Poland,</HI> and <HI>Saphiea</HI> call'd
in the King of <HI>Sweden</HI> to his Succour, and he (the
King of <HI>Sweden</HI>) e&s;pous'd the <HI>Saph$iea's,</HI> and made
them Superiour to <HI>Ogin&s;ki</HI> and his Party; &s;o <HI>Ogin|&s;ki</HI>
finding the King of <HI>Poland</HI> not able to &s;up|port
him, having his handful of the <HI>Swedes,</HI> he
call'd in the <HI>Mu&s;covites</HI> to his aid; his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Ma|je&s;ty
taking him into his Protection, did not a&s;&s;i&s;t
him with a handful of Men, as it were on purpo&s;e
to prolong the War, but at two or three times
&s;ent him at lea&s;t 30000 Men; &s;o that tho' the
<HI>Swedes</HI> had many times the better of him too, yet
he always maintain'd him&s;elf in the Field, till
all went to wreck, and King <HI>Augu&s;tus</HI> him&s;elf
was Forc'd to abandon them all, and quit the
Crown, of which in its Place.</P>
<P><PB N="117" REF="118">
THESE Tran&s;actions kept the World in &s;u&s;|pence
three or four Years, during which time, the
<HI>Mu&s;covite</HI> Troops gain'd every Day new Expe|rience,
and new Reputation in the World, being
by the <HI>Czar's</HI> particular Direction all fill'd, not
only with <HI>German</HI> Officers, but having among
them abundance of <HI>German, Poli&s;h,</HI> and other fo|reign
Soldiers, mo&s;t of them Men of Service, and
who had been fully acquainted with the War be|fore
they were entertain'd and as his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Ma|je&s;ty
gave very good Encouragement to all
Strangers, who Li&s;ted in his Troops, he had a
great many De&s;erters, even from the <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI>
Troops them&s;elves.</P>
<P>BUT this was not all, for as he &s;oon after
this, Conquer'd whole Provinces from the King of
<HI>Sweden,</HI> and had occa&s;ion to act with his Armies in
&s;everal parts of the Empire, as in <HI>Pomeren</HI> in the
Dutchy of <HI>Mecklemburgh</HI> in <HI>Hol&s;tein,</HI> and in <HI>Den|mark;</HI>
&s;o he fail'd not of entertaining all the a|ble
Experience'd Soldiers he could get in all tho&s;e
Countries; by which means many of his Regi|ments,
and particularly his Guards were made up
of the choice&s;t Men all that part of the World could
affrod: As for the Provinces conquer'd from <HI>Swe|den,</HI>
the <HI>Czar</HI> has rais'd all the Men that it was
po&s;&s;ible to get in <HI>Livonia,</HI> and in <HI>Finland,</HI> of whom
he has in his Army at this time &s;everal whole
Regiments; particularly of <HI>Finlanders,</HI> who being
&s;ome of the be&s;t, the bolde&s;t, and mo&s;t hardy Men
of all the King of <HI>Sweden's</HI> Dominions, are now
the <HI>Czar's</HI> proper Subjects, and the la&s;t levey the
<HI>Czar's</HI> Generals made there, was of 3500 Men,
which I am told are form'd into one Regiment,
and call'd the Royal <HI>Finlanders;</HI> but 'tis added
that the <HI>Czar</HI> chu&s;es to employ that Regiment in the
<PB N="118" REF="119">
remoter part of his Country again&s;t the <HI>Turks,</HI>
lea&s;t when they come to act again&s;t their old
Ma&s;ter the King of <HI>Sweden,</HI> they &s;hould play
Booty, and go over to his Side.</P>
<P>I NEED give no farther Account, either why,
or how the <HI>Mu&s;covite</HI> Troops came to be what we
&s;ee they are; Namely, equal to other Nations in
the Field; but I may take the liberty to add, that
if the <HI>Mu&s;covite</HI> Troops come to be as good as the
<HI>Swedes,</HI> or other Neighbouring Nations; it mu&s;t
be allowed, that their Numbers are &s;o far Superior
to them, that there will be no room for the Fu|ture
for that Contempt, with which tho&s;e Nations
have formerly look'd on the <HI>Ru&s;&s;ian</HI> Empire.</P>
<P>IT is a &s;peculation worthy the be&s;t and greate&s;t
Polititians of <HI>Europe,</HI> how much the ma&s;culine
Genius of one Prince, may alter the Circum&s;tances
not of his own Subjects only, but of all the Nations
in the World that are any way influence'd by them;
for as they are of Weight in the Ballance of
the Nations, &s;o the Intere&s;t of the Neighbouring
Nations, are more or le&s;s concern'd to Support, or
Suppre&s;s them.</P>
<P>THE Empire of the <HI>Czar</HI> of <HI>Mu&s;covy,</HI> extend|ed
as it is from the North to the South, for the
length of 2500 Miles, that is to &s;ay, from the North
Sea, bounding the Coa&s;t of the <HI>R&s;&s;ian Laponia,</HI> in
the Latitude of 72 or from the extream Part of
<HI>Nova Zembla,</HI> in the Latitude of 81, to the Coa&s;ts
of <HI>Carakathay,</HI> and the De&s;arts of the <HI>Calumuck
Tarters,</HI> even to the <HI>Ca&s;pian</HI> Sea is by the Scituation
&s;o plac'd, as to be effectually cover'd from all man|ner
of Enemies, either on the Ea&s;t, the North, or
the South, and has nothing to regard, but the We&s;t|&s;tern
&s;ide of its Dominion.</P>
<P><PB N="119" REF="120">
I CAN liken the &s;ituation of the <HI>Czar</HI> of <HI>Mu&s;|covy's</HI>
Dominion to nothing &s;o well, as to a well
cho&s;en &s;trong Encampment, plac'd in a piece of
Ground every way inacce&s;&s;ible, but in the Front,
and the Front &s;o Fortify'd, as not to be ea&s;ily
attack'd, <HI>for Example,</HI> the North Ocean is on its
Right, the River <HI>Wolga,</HI> and the De&s;arts of <HI>Tar|tary</HI>
on its Left: The unpa&s;&s;able Wa&s;t from the
River <HI>Oby</HI> to <HI>China</HI> in its whole Reer, and no|thing
lying open, but its Front.</P>
<P>THIS Front is guarded on its <HI>Right Wing,</HI> by
the <HI>Bothnick Gulph,</HI> and the <HI>Gulph</HI> of <HI>Finland,</HI>
with inacce&s;&s;ible Shores, and a multitude of well
fortify'd Ports from <HI>Abbo</HI> round the latter <HI>Gulph,</HI>
by <HI>Wyburg, Cron&s;loot, Petersbourgh, Narva,</HI> and <HI>Re|vel,</HI>
to <HI>Riga,</HI> and the Shores of <HI>Courland,</HI> with the
Dutchy of <HI>Courland</HI> in Po&s;&s;e&s;&s;ion, as an Out-work,
or advanc'd Ba&s;tion in a Town, to keep off an E|nemy
from the Body of the Place.</P>
<P>ALL the Left Wing of this prodigious extend|ed
Line, is cover'd with the <HI>Ca&s;pian</HI> Sea, the De|&s;arts
of <HI>Circa&s;&s;ia,</HI> the <HI>Palus-Meotis,</HI> and the rapid
<HI>Bori&s;thenes,</HI> till we come to the <HI>Ru&s;&s;ian Ukrania</HI>
which lyes again like a &s;trong Out-work, guard|ed
with a Hundred Thou&s;and faithful <HI>Co&s;&s;acks,</HI>
the terror of the <HI>Tartars,</HI> and a &s;ufficient De|fence
again&s;t their Incur&s;ions, which they formerly
made that way into the Heart of <HI>Mu&s;covy.</HI></P>
<P>ALL the middle of this immen&s;e Front is
bordered by <HI>Poland,</HI> a Nation &s;o con&s;tantly em|broil'd
with it&s;elf&punc; as to be formidable to no Bo|dy;
and yet a Nation, that as it is not con&s;iderable
enough to be a terror to <HI>Mu&s;covy,</HI> or offer the <HI>Czar</HI>
any unea&s;ine&s;s on their own Account, &s;o they
are yet too con&s;iderable to be forc'd, to &s;uffer an
Inva&s;ion of <HI>Mu&s;covy,</HI> thro' their Country; &s;o that
<PB N="120" REF="121">
upon the whole, there &s;eems to be no Nation cap|able
of penetrating Into <HI>Mu&s;covy,</HI> but the <HI>Swedes;,</HI>
and how the Cafe &s;tands on that Side, will be &s;een
in the whole Cour&s;e of this Hi&s;tory.</P>
<P>ON the other Hand, the powerful <HI>Czar</HI> of
<HI>Mu&s;covy,</HI> if once his Army is prepar'd as I have
ob&s;erv'd, to come Hand to Hand$with any of the
Nations that lye thus on its Front, is able to Sally
out by all the&s;e ways, and will be much Superi|or
to them, on Account of the numberle&s;s Mul|titude
of his People, of whom he is able to rai&s;e
as many Thou&s;ands, as &s;ome of his Neighbours can
Hundreds, and that with le&s;s Expence than any
of them.</P>
<P>BUT I return to the Field of Afion, as the
<HI>Mu&s;covites</HI> were call'd into <HI>Litbuania</HI> to a&s;&s;i&s;t the
Sieur <HI>Ogin&s;ki</HI> again&s;t the <HI>Saphieas,</HI> and the <HI>Swedes;</HI>
&s;o by this time the King of <HI>Poland</HI> having lo&s;t
the Battle of <HI>Cracow,</HI> and the King of <HI>Sweden</HI> de|claring
his Re&s;olution to Dethrone him, and as it
appear'd, being Powerful enough to bring it to
pa&s;s, calls aloud to his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty to come
to his A&s;&s;i&s;tance al&s;o.</P>
<P>THE <HI>Czar</HI> too well under&s;tood his Bu&s;ine&s;s, not
to make his ju&s;t Advantage of the ob&s;tinate
warmth of his Enemy the King of <HI>Sweden,</HI> in pur|&s;uit
of the King of <HI>Poland;</HI> and therefore while
that Monarch, who was now with his whole Ar|my,
as is &s;aid, gotten the height of <HI>Cracow,</HI> and
where his Victory over the King of <HI>Poland,</HI> had fil|l'd
his Head with new Projects, for reduction of the
whole Country, and depo&s;ing the King; his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI>
Maje&s;t$, fir&s;t &s;ending 20000 to the aid of <HI>Ogin&s;ki</HI>
in <HI>Lithunia,</HI> thereby to keep the <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> Troops
on that Side employ'd; and after having caus'd
another Army to advance towards Great <HI>Po|land,</HI>
<PB N="121" REF="122">
to be ready to Succour King Augu&s;tus, taking
the advantage of the Ab&s;ence of the King of
<HI>Sweden,</HI> and his following his imaginary good
Portune, he caus' Fan Army of 60000 Foot, all
Regular, and Regimented Troops, form'd after the
new Model, as above, and Commanded by ex|perienc'd
Generals, as well as other Officers, mo&s;t
Foreigners, and 20000 Hor&s;e to enter <HI>Livonia,</HI> and
another Army of 30000 foot, and 10000 Hor&s;e
at the &s;ame time to enter <HI>Ingria,</HI> or <HI>Ingermandland,</HI>
a Province beyond <HI>Livonia</HI> Ea&s;tward, and joyning
to <HI>Finland;</HI> and the only way by which any
Troops from that Side of <HI>Sweden,</HI> call'd <HI>Finland,</HI>
could come by Land to the Succour of the <HI>Livo|nians.</HI></P>
<P>HERE his <HI>Gzari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty made him&s;elf full
Amends, and had his compleat Revenge of the
<HI>Swedes,</HI> for the Lo&s;s &s;u&s;tain'd at the Battle of
<HI>Narvaa;</HI> for Prince <HI>Czeremet,</HI> who Commanded
this Army, enter'd <HI>Livonia</HI> unre&s;i&s;ted, and having
Ravag'd all the ea&s;ter Part, call'd <HI>E&s;thonia,</HI> as
far as <HI>Dorpat,</HI> met with very little, if any op|pofition;
at length the <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> General <HI>Slipping|back,</HI>
having gotten together an Army of about
Ten Thou&s;and Men, all <HI>Swedes</HI> and old Soldiers,
and pre&s;uming upon the good Fortune of <HI>Narva,</HI>
and the u&s;ual contempt they had for the <HI>Mu&s;covite</HI>
Troops, oppos'd him&s;elf to the Prince; but he
paid for his Ignorance and Ra&s;hne&s;s, by the entire
Defeat of his whole Army, who were over-thrown,
and almo&s;t all cut in pieces by the <HI>Mu&s;covites.</HI></P>
<P>IT is true, the <HI>Swedes</HI> fought like Lyons, or like
Furies rather, and that in the Fight they pu&s;h'd
whole Brigades of the <HI>Mu&s;covite</HI> Infantry, put
them into Confu&s;ion, and in that Confu&s;ion, they
<PB N="122" REF="123">
flaughter'd many of them; and this is doing the
<HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> valour Ju&s;tice, for indeed they were over|come
by meer Numbers.</P>
<P>BUT ju&s;t the &s;ame they would have &s;aid of the
King of <HI>Sweden</HI> at the Battle of <HI>Narva,</HI> if he had
been repul&s;ed, that having an Army of 100000 Men
to deal with, his Men were overlay'd by the
innumerable Multitudes of their Enemies; that
they Fought like Lyons, but what could Men
do, who had an Army of $ix to one to deal with?
That Valour gave way at la&s;t to Number, <HI>and
the like,</HI> and had the <HI>Mu&s;covite</HI> Army had Field
room in that Action at <HI>Narva,</HI> and not been
Coup'd up in a Camp, where the foremo&s;t Troops
being put into di&s;order, the re&s;t were driven one
upon another, and made the In&s;truments of their
own Ruins; I &s;ay, had not this been the Ca&s;e,
'tis very like the <HI>Swedes</HI> had talk'd of the Action
at <HI>Narva,</HI> as they do now of that near <HI>Dorpat.</HI></P>
<P>BUT 'tis an an&s;werable return, which is made
to this; what an Un&s;oldierly ra&s;hne&s;s was it for
General <HI>Slippenback,</HI> to &s;uffer him&s;elf to be at|tack'd,
or pretend to Fight with 10000 Men, a|gain&s;t
60000? for &s;o many the <HI>Swedes</HI> &s;ay the
<HI>Mu&s;covites</HI> were; nay, and if it be true, that as
they &s;ay, General Slippenback was not above 6000
the pre&s;umption was the greater for Ra&s;hne&s;s,
and Temerity in Actons of War, are not to be
call'd Valour and Bravery, but Madne&s;s and Folly.</P>
<P>BUT to come to the Fact, it was from the Be|ginning
of <HI>May,</HI> 1702, that the Ru&s;&s;ians were
known to be drawing together; above 70000
Men, lay about <HI>Pl$&s;kow</HI> and the Frontiers of
the <HI>Czar's</HI> Dominions, and were encrea&s;ing
every Day: Now had the King of <HI>Sweden,</HI> thought
his Province of <HI>Livonia</HI> worth &s;ecuring, or had
<PB N="123" REF="124">
he not flattered him&s;elf, that the Ru&s;&s;ians would not
dare to appear in the Field, but that they would
be frighted with the Names of the <HI>Swedes;</HI> that the
Scripture Prophe&s;ie was to be fulfilled in <HI>Livo|nia,</HI>
in favour of his Men, <HI>That One &s;hould Cha&s;fe a
Thou&s;and, and Two put ten Thou&s;and to flight:</HI> I &s;ay,
had he not filled his Head with the mo&s;t de&s;pica|ble
Opinion of the <HI>Ru&s;&s;ians,</HI> he would never have
left &s;uch a Province as <HI>Livonia</HI> to be devour|ed,
and &s;uch gallant Troops as the <HI>Swedes</HI> really
were, to be cut in pieces in &s;mall Bodies for want
of Succour; while he was pur&s;uing his Revenge,
and talking upon him the giving a King too,
and pulling down a King from the Throne of his
Neighbour, the Kingdom of <HI>Poland.</HI></P>
<P>BUT thus it was, the <HI>Ru&s;&s;ian</HI> Army entred <HI>Li|vonia</HI>
Commanded by the Prince of <HI>Czeremetoff,</HI>
about the beginning of July. They were not
ignorant that the <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> General <HI>Slippenback,</HI>
lay encamp'd between <HI>Dorpat,</HI> and Revel, tho'
the Prince had not any Account of his Numbers,
and if he had, itcould not be depended upon, be|cau&s;e
he might be &s;uppos'd to receive Additions
every Day from <HI>Revel,</HI> and <HI>Riga,</HI> which were in
his Reer, and from the <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> General <HI>Myerfield</HI>
in <HI>Lithuania:</HI> For this Rea&s;on the Prince did not
undertake any Siege, re&s;olving to make War in
the open Field, and fir&s;t &s;eek out and fight his
Enemy, that he might not have the &s;ame Game
to Play, as had been fatally play'd at <HI>Narva.</HI></P>
<P>To this purpo&s;e the Prince march'd on, and
the 16th of <HI>July,</HI> having an Account that the
<HI>Swedes</HI> march'd towards him, he advanc'd di|rectly
forward: The <HI>Swedi&s;h,</HI> General hearing
what disparity of Numbers he had to engage with,
halted at a Village call'd <HI>Stagnitz</HI> on the River
<PB N="124" REF="125">
<HI>Emback,</HI> as if he had re&s;olv'd to expect the <HI>Ru&s;|&s;ians</HI>
There; and &s;o far was he from being &s;en&s;ible
of the odds there was between them, that he did
not &s;o much as offer to Entrench; but with an Ar|rogance
inimitable, kept his Situation, till the
<HI>Ru&s;&s;ians</HI> came in view, being in full March to attack
him, and in admirable Order of Battle: A little
&s;urpris'd with the Sight, he then, when it was too
late, put his Men in March, and repa&s;s'd the River
upon two Bridges, breaking the Bridges behind
him; but this only &s;erv'd to bring him to a Ne|ce&s;&s;ity
of Fighting afterwards, in a Situation not
more Advantagious than the fir&s;t; for the <HI>Ru&s;&s;ians</HI>
pa&s;&s;ing al&s;o the River at &s;ome di&s;tance; and be|ing
drawn up again as before, mov'd directly to|wards
them. Then it was the <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> General
boldly Fac'd about, and re&s;olv'd to Fight. The
oon&s;equence of which was, his being over-thrown,
and entirely defeated, and all his Infantry cut in
pieces, as I have &s;aid; tho' not till after an ob|stinate
and bloody Fight, which la&s;ted almo&s;t a
whole Day.</P>
<P>NOW that I may not be Partial in the Rela|tion
of this Action, I &s;hall give their own Ac|count,
which they &s;ent to all the Courts of <HI>Europe,</HI>
and which excepting the &s;mallne&s;s of their own
Number kill'd, we are content to refer to, which
is as follows,</P>
<P>UPON July 6, we &s;ay the <HI>Swedes</HI> receiv'd Intelli|gence,
that the <HI>mu&s;covites</HI> were enter'd into <HI>Livo|nia</HI>
with a numerous Army, and were advanc'd as
far as <HI>Crosfort;</HI> the next Day our avant Couriers
being repuls'd to our Guards, General <HI>Slippenback</HI>
detach'd 300 Hor&s;e to ob&s;erve the Enemy: This
Party upon the 18th in the Morning, met with a
Body of a 1000 <HI>Mu&s;covites,</HI> which they attack'd,
<PB N="125" REF="126">
and drove to the Body of their Army, but the
<HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> Cavalry being &s;urpris'd at the &s;ight of
&s;uch a numerous Ho&s;t, dur&s;t not make any long
&s;tay, but retreated in great Confu&s;ion; &s;o that
being pur&s;u'd by the Enemy, we lo&s;t Major <HI>Ro&s;e,</HI>
and &s;ome other Officers, who were &s;lain; the
Major General being inform'd of what had hap|pen'd,
rod him&s;elf to view the Enemy's Army,
and pre&s;ently perceiving they had a de&s;ign to &s;ur|round
his &s;mall Body; he judg'd it convenient by
the Advice of a Council of War, to cro&s;t the Ri|ver
of <HI>Emback,</HI> to prevent their De&s;ign; which was
done in view of the Enemy, and in very good
order over two Bridges that were broken, &s;o &s;oon
as our Men were over; but the River being then
very low, and the Enemy making u&s;e of &s;everal
Pontons to waft over their Artillery, 'twas im|po&s;&s;ible
to prevent their pa&s;&s;ing with the re&s;t of
their Army; &s;o that General <HI>Slippenback</HI> find|ing
that a great Number of the Enemy were al|ready
got on our Side, could not avoid coming
to a Battle; all the Advantage at the beginning
was on our Side; we beat the Enemy every
where, we pur&s;u'd them above a <HI>German</HI> Mile; we
took from them &s;ix pieces of Cannon, part of their
Baggage, and &s;ome Colours, and at length we
pre&s;s'd &s;o hard upon 'em, that they threw them|&s;elves
into the River; but the re&s;t of their
Army a&s;ham'd to fee their Fellows fly, and mad
to be beaten by &s;uch a &s;mall Number of Men, Fac'd
about of a &s;udden, and put the <HI>Finland</HI> Cavalry
into &s;uch di&s;order, that they fell foul upon the
Infantry, and betook them&s;elves to flight, with|out
any po&s;&s;ibility of being rally'd, &s;o that our
Artillery, as well as that which we had taken, fell
<PB N="126" REF="127">
into the Enemies Power, and our Infantry after
a $tout re&s;&s;i&s;tance was almo&s;t cut in pieces: This
Action began about &s;ix in the Morning, and la&s;ted
for ten Hours together; our General would fain
have rally'd them again, and po&s;ted us at <HI>Helmer,</HI>
but finding it impo&s;&s;ible to &s;top the Hor&s;e that
were fled and di&s;pers'd, and being no longer a|ble
to &s;tand his Ground with the remains of his
Infantry, he was con&s;train'd to retreat to
<HI>Perna$.</HI></P>
<P>UPON this Occa&s;ion, the <HI>Swedes</HI> loft 7 Captains,
30 Lieutenants, 11 En&s;igns, and 25 Subalterns;
37 Drums, and 1916 common Soldiers; we know
indeed that the Lo&s;s of the Mu&s;covites was much
greater, but it was hardly preceptible, by rea&s;on
of their Multitude: After this Expedition the
<HI>Mu&s;covites</HI> were about to have march'd back, but
they were hardly arriv'd at the <HI>Lake</HI> of <HI>Peipus,</HI>
when they receiv'd Orders to return, and put all
<HI>Livonia</HI> to Fire and Sword, which they have done
in a mo&s;t cruel manner, till within &s;ome Leagues
of <HI>Riga.</HI></P>
<P>THIS is their own Account in which the im|partial
Reader will certainly conclude, that had the
<HI>Mu&s;covites</HI> Number been &s;o great, and theirs
&s;o &s;mall, as they would repre&s;ent them, it could
&s;carce be po&s;&s;ible that they could defend them|&s;elves
ten Hours, and be Defeated at la&s;t too;
having no Shelter, no Retreat, no Entrenchments
or Defences at all, but their Arms.</P>
<P>BUT the Sum of the Ca&s;e was, and that appears
by the Accounts publi&s;h'd at that time, that the
<HI>Swedes</HI> were no le&s;t than ten Thou&s;and Men, o|thers
lay fourteen Thou&s;and, and the publick
Papers printed at that Time, as al&s;o by Letters
from <HI>Dantzick,</HI> and from <HI>Riga</HI> at the &s;ame time,
<PB N="127" REF="128">
both to <HI>London,</HI> and to <HI>Holland,</HI> give this Account
in few Words, <HI>viz.</HI> &startq;That Prince <HI>Czeremet</HI> the
<HI>Mu&s;covite</HI> General at the Head of a numerous
Army, had entirely defeated General <HI>Slippen|back,</HI>
with an Army of 10000 <HI>Swedes,</HI> not Far
from <HI>Dorpat,</HI> and that the <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> General with
a few Hor&s;e, who de&s;perately broke thro' the
<HI>Ru&s;&s;ian</HI> Army had e&s;caped; all the re&s;t of the
Army having been cut in pieces after a gallant
Re&s;i&s;tance, and a Fight, Which la&s;ted from eight
a-Clock in the Morning, to &s;even a-Clock at
Night.&endq;</P>
<P>THE la&s;t of the&s;e Accounts was certainly well
grounded, with this Exception only, that the
<HI>Swedes</HI> were not all cut in pieces, about 1200 be|ing
taken Pri&s;oners, with all their Baggage, Can|non,
Tents and Ammunition.</P>
<P>BUT the particular Rea&s;on why I publi&s;h here
their own Account of this Fight, is to repeat
what I have &s;o often mention'd, (<HI>viz.</HI>) of the dif|ference
between the <HI>Ru&s;&s;ian</HI> Soldiers now, and
what they were formerly; for now the <HI>Swedes</HI>
found, that after they had broke them &s;everal
times by the Fury of their Charge, and put them
into Confu&s;ion, yet that they rall$ed again by
the skill and dexterity of their Officers, and by
the aptne&s;s, and experience of their Soldiers, and
that they returned again to the Charge, after they
had been pu&s;h'd into Di&s;order; which was what
the <HI>Swedes</HI> did not expect to find among them,
and this was the ruin of the <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> Army.</P>
<P>AFTER this Action, the State of the War took a
new Turn; the <HI>Swedes</HI> were defeated upon all Oc|ca&s;ions,
and that not only an <HI>Livonia,</HI> but in <HI>Lithu|ani</HI>
al&s;o; <HI>Ogin&s;ki</HI> and his Friends, &s;upported by the
Troops the <HI>Gzar</HI> had &s;ent him, routed the <HI>Swedes</HI>
<PB N="128" REF="129">
twice in a Weeks time, killing 400, and taking 800
Pri&s;oners, in one Action, and killing 1000, and ta|king
700 in the &s;econd Action.</P>
<P>AFTER Prince <HI>Gzeremet</HI> had thus clear'd the Field
of his Enemy, he laid wa&s;t the whole Province., <HI>as a|bove;</HI>
the Rea&s;on was, that he found them univer&s;al|ly
aver&s;e to Submit, even when &s;ubdued; and that
upon an order from the King of <HI>Sweden</HI> to the
Country, to take Arms, they did &s;o, and fell up|on
his Men wherever they found them.</P>
<P>THIS was what his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje$ty does not
delight in, nor does he &s;uffer his Troops to Practice
it in the other Countries of his Conque&s;ts; but
he had been treated with &s;uch per&s;onal Indignity
by the King of <HI>Sweden</HI> on all Occa&s;ions, that he
found him&s;elf oblig'd to &s;hew his Re&s;entment;
and on the other Hand he was repre&s;ented by the
<HI>Swedes</HI> them&s;elves, as an Enemy &s;o contemptible,
that no Rules of Honour, or Ju&s;tice were to be ob&s;er|ved
with him; and it behov'd his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty
on both the&s;e Accounts, to let the Subjects of <HI>Swe|den</HI>
know, that he was in a Condition to make
him&s;elf be better us'd, and that they might have
Rea&s;on to fear him, in&s;tead of in&s;ulting him.</P>
<P>THERE was al&s;o another Rea&s;on for this Severi|ty,
<HI>viz.</HI> that the great Towns of <HI>Livonia</HI> under who&s;e
Protection, the <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> Forces &s;heltered, might
not be able to &s;ub&s;i&s;t them; and al&s;o that his Ene|mies
might not fill their Magazines in <HI>Courland,</HI>
and in Lithuania out of the fruitful Provinces of
<HI>Livonia,</HI> and <HI>Ea&s;tonia.</HI></P>
<P>AFTER this Execution, the Prince &s;at down be|fore
<HI>Dorpat</HI> with his whole Army, keeping at the
&s;ame time great Detachments of Hor&s;e to &s;cour
the Country to the Gates of <HI>Per$a$,</HI> and even to <HI>Ri|ga,</HI>
to prevent the <HI>Swedes</HI> gatheringany Number of
<PB N="129" REF="130">
Troops into a Body together, to attempt to Re|lieve
the Place.</P>
<P>WHILE the&s;e things went on thus pro&s;pe|rou&s;ly
in <HI>Livonia,</HI> the <HI>Ru&s;&s;ian</HI> Army in <HI>Ingria</HI> were
no le&s;s Succe&s;sful, the Fortre&s;s of <HI>Skan&s;terny</HI> after a
vigorous Attack was &s;urrender'd to the <HI>Mu&s;covites,</HI>
and the <HI>Mu&s;covite</HI> General&mdash;<HI>Slippenbach</HI> with a
&s;trong Body of an Army being &s;ent to the Edge of
<HI>Finland,</HI> landed not far from <HI>Wyburgh</HI> with 24000
Men, in 400 Tran&s;port Ve&s;&s;els, and in a plain
Field gave Battle to the <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> Forces under Gene|ral
<HI>Crooniort,</HI> and entirely defeated them, the
<HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> General, and a few of his Men making
their Retreat, and e&s;cap'd to <HI>Wyburg.</HI></P>
<P>THUS the whole Province of <HI>Ingermania</HI> or <HI>In|gria</HI>
fell into his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty's hand, and his
Troops made daily Excur&s;ions upon the Enemy
in <HI>Finland</HI> it&s;elf (<HI>viz.</HI>) fir&s;t Thus</P>
<P>THE particulars of this Action are thus diver|&s;ly
related, fir&s;t thus.</P>
<P>IN the mean time the <HI>Mu&s;covites</HI> get Ground in
the&s;e Parts having lately obtain'd very con&s;idera|ble
Advantages over a volant Camp of the <HI>Swedes</HI>
commanded by General <HI>Crooniort</HI> in tho&s;e Quarters,
the <HI>Mu&s;covites,</HI> with a Body of 25000 Men, being
conducted through by, and impracticable ways, fell
upon the <HI>Swedes</HI> when lea&s;t expected, and after a
bloody Fight, which la&s;ted from &s;ix in the Morn|ing
till two in the Afternoon, being much Supe|rior
in Number, put the <HI>Swedes</HI> to the Rout; how|ever
'tis &s;aid that the <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> General after a vi|gorous
Re&s;i&s;tance, made good his Retreat to <HI>Wy|burg:</HI>
There is &s;ince publi&s;h'd a more exact Rela|tion
of this Encounter between the <HI>Swedes</HI> and
<HI>Mu&s;covites,</HI> which gives the following Account,
<PB N="130" REF="131">
(<HI>viz.</HI>) that General <HI>Crooniort</HI> having Advice, that the
<HI>Mu&s;covites</HI> had fram'd a De&s;ign utterly to de&s;troy
his &s;mall Army, and for that end had embark'd
a great Number of Troops, in 8 Frigats, 400
&s;mall Tran&s;port Ve&s;&s;els, and two great Floating
Machines, whereon Batteries were plac'd, de&s;ign|ing
to Cannonade the Enemy with their Fleet,
while the re&s;t of their Army fell upon them by
Land; the Major General thereupon, &s;ent out
Parties to ob&s;erve the Motions of the <HI>Mu&s;covites;</HI>
one whereof return'd towards Morning, and brought
Advice that they had di&s;cover'd &s;ome of their
Troops within an hours March of the <HI>Swedes</HI>
Out-guards, who immediately prepar'd to receive
them; the <HI>Ru&s;&s;ians</HI> contrary to their Expectati|ons
finding the <HI>Swedes</HI> in a readine&s;s, drew back
in order to be joyn'd with more Troops, not far
behind; which they had no &s;ooner done, but they
return'd and Charg'd the <HI>Swedes</HI> with great vigour;
who, tho' but a handful as it were, defended
them&s;elves very well, till General <HI>Crooniort</HI> came
up to them with a Reinforcement of Hor&s;e and
Foot; but the Pa&s;s of <HI>Su&s;terback,</HI> where the <HI>Swedes</HI>
were po&s;ted, being too narrow for the Hor&s;e to
do any Service, the Foot were oblig'd to give way
to the Superiour Numbers of their Enemies, who
pre&s;s'd them clo&s;e at the Heels, and did not fail to
make the be&s;t of their Advantage; but the <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI>
Hor&s;e coming up again, put a &s;top to their Progre&s;s;
the <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> General began then to di&s;cover from the
great clouds of Du&s;t that aro&s;e in &s;everal Places,
that the re&s;t of the <HI>Mu&s;covite's</HI> Army was coming
up with their Cannon, and not doubting but they
were infinitely &s;tronger then him&s;elf: His Army
not exceeding 4000 Men, the General thought it ad|vi&s;eable
to order the Foot to draw off with the Can|non
<PB N="131" REF="132">
and Carriages to <HI>Wyburg,</HI> on which the Enemy
&s;eem'd to have an Eye; and the rather becau&s;e
the General di&s;cover'd part of their Troops
marching along the Sea &s;ide, to get behind him; the
Foot retir'd in excellent order, while the General
taking the Advantage of the Ground with the
Cavalry alone, kept the Enemy in play (with
a Bravery not to be paralell'd) four Hours toge|ther,
when the <HI>Mu&s;covites</HI> retir'd, but threaten'd to
return in a &s;hort time: By a Li&s;t of the Pri&s;oners
taken and carryed away by the <HI>Mu&s;covites</HI> upon
this incur&s;ion, there are three Colonels, two Majors,
eighteen Captains, Twenty-five Lieutenants, three
Cornets, &s;eventeen En&s;igns; a Thousand Soldiers,
and a great Number of other Per&s;ons of both
Sexes.</P>
<P>HERE his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty contriv'd the Scheme,
and actually laid the Foundation of a new For|tre&s;s
at the Entrance of the <HI>Nye</HI> or <HI>Neva,</HI> the In|let,
which opens the Communication between the
Lake <HI>Ladoga,</HI> and the <HI>Baltick;</HI> which Fortre&s;s he
called <HI>Croon&s;lot</HI> and farther up his Maje&s;ty has
begun to build a Town, which he has call'd after
his own Name <HI>Petersburgh,</HI> or according to &s;ome
St. <HI>Petersburgh.</HI></P>
<P>THIS was at fir&s;t but a &s;mall Place, but &s;ince is
become a Royal City, and at pre&s;ent contains,
be&s;ides publick Edifices, Churches, and a Magni|ficient
Pallace, not yet quite fini&s;h'd above Thirty
Thou&s;and Hou&s;es.</P>
<P>HIS <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty having now, as has been
alledg'd Di&s;peopled the populous Provinces of <HI>Li|vonia</HI>
and <HI>Ingria,</HI> made the poor People &s;ome a|mends
by a Proclamation, or Placart, inviting
all the Families, not of tho&s;e Countries, but of
<PB N="132" REF="133">
all other Countries to come and Settle in his Do|minions,
and was to the purpo&s;e following, (<HI>viz.</HI>)</P>
<P>TO Invite all Sorts of Artificers, Workmen,
and People u&s;ing Manufactures, and other Per|&s;ons
profe&s;&s;ing Trades and Sciences, to come and
Settle in his Dominions; promi&s;ing them, that &s;o
&s;oon as they arriv'd upon the Frontiers, they &s;hall
be conducted where they plea&s;e to Settle; that they
&s;hall have the free Exerci&s;e of their Religion,
and the convenience of Churches; that they &s;hall
have the Liberty to employ them&s;elves in what|&s;oever
they &s;hall think mo&s;t for their Advantage,
without being Subject to any Duties, Offices or
Impo&s;ts: That as for tho&s;e who &s;hall find them|&s;elves
capable to undertake any Trade, and &s;hall
not have where withal to follow it, his Maje&s;ty
promi&s;es to &s;upply them with Money out of
his Trea&s;ury, without any Intere&s;t; and La&s;tly,
as are at any time unwilling to &s;tay in his Domi|nions,
&s;hall have Licen&s;es to depart, and at their
fir&s;t Reque&s;t &s;hall be conducted at the <HI>Czar's</HI> ex|pences
to the Frontiers, or to any Sea-Port.</P>
<P>HIS Maje&s;ties Armies rang'd now freely over
both the&s;e Provinces, only with this Exception,
that the great Towns in <HI>Livonia, &amp;c.</HI> were &s;till in
the Hands of the <HI>Swedes;</HI> but having &s;ecur'd all
behind him, by the taking of the Places above|mention'd,
as al&s;o of <HI>Notteburg</HI> and of <HI>Nyen&s;chans.</HI>
His Maje&s;ty now re&s;olv'd to begin with the other
in the next Place, and &s;o fini&s;h the Reduction of
<HI>Livonia.</HI></P>
<P>IN <HI>December,</HI> 1702, the City of <HI>Narva</HI> had like
to have been &s;urpriz'd; but tho' the <HI>Ru&s;&s;ians</HI> mi&s;s'd
their aim as to the Place, yet they did a great
deal $word$ mi&s;chief to the Suburbs, and defeated a
<PB N="133" REF="134">
&s;trong Party of <HI>Swedes,</HI> which defended them:
The Story is told thus,</P>
<P>UPON the la&s;t Day of the la&s;t Year, accord|ing
to our Account, the <HI>Mu&s;covites</HI> made an In|cur&s;ion
in the Night time, by the Favour of the
Ice, and after they had &s;urpriz'd the advanc'd
Guards, advanc'd under the very Cannon of the
City, and committed great Di&s;orders in the Neigh|bouring
Villages, which they laid in A&s;hes,
making a great Slaughter of the Inhabitants, as al|&s;o
of &s;ome Soldiers that were Quarter'd among
them; they have al&s;o reduc'd into heaps of Rub|bi&s;h
&s;everal Hou&s;es in the Suburbs; two Sawing
Mills, &s;everal Country Habitations, notwith&s;tand|ing
that the great Guns from the City and
the Ca&s;tle of <HI>Ivanagrod,</HI> continually fir'd upon
them: That they might get more ea&s;ily into
Peoples Hou&s;es, they run about the Streets knock|ing
at the Doors, and crying out in the Language
of the Country, <HI>u&s;a, u&s;a, vendein tules,</HI> fly, fly, the
<HI>Ru&s;&s;ians</HI> are a coming; then upon the People open|ing
their Doors to know what-was the matter, be|lieving
them to be their Friends, the <HI>Mu&s;covites$</HI>
ru&s;h'd into their Hou&s;es and put all to the Sword,
not &s;paring either Age or Sex, that could not e|&s;cape
to the City, the Cavalry of the Garri&s;on
&s;ally'd out upon them, but were beaten back to
their very Counter&s;carp; this bloody Execution
continu'd &s;ix Hours.</P>
<P>THUS the <HI>Swedes</HI> went to wreck every where,
and the victorious <HI>Ru&s;&s;ians</HI> carried all before them;
the <HI>Czar</HI> him&s;elf pleas'd with Succe&s;s, and re&s;olv'd
to pu&s;h his good Fortune, came down in Per&s;on to
the Army, which he had ordered to be&s;iege the
City of <HI>Dorpat;</HI> the Place made a good Defence,
<PB N="134" REF="135">
but they found that the Ca&s;e was altered, the <HI>Mu&s;|covite</HI>
Engineers proceeded as regularly in their
Approaches as any other of the Nations of <HI>Europe,</HI>
and attacked, and a&s;&s;ualted as boldly, and as
punctually as po&s;&s;ible: The Outworks were carried
by degrees, being well defended, and well attack'd;
In a Word, after about 27 Days open Trenches,
the Garri&s;on finding they could not hold out, and
that no relief was to be expected, beat a Parly,
and had very honourable Conditions; they &s;ur|render'd
the 26th of <HI>July,</HI> and were conducted
to <HI>Riga:</HI> Hi$ <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty appear'd on Hor&s;e|back
with his Sword in his hand, at the Head of
his Guard du Corps when the Garri&s;on march'd out,
and the Governour &s;aluting his Maje&s;ty, he was
pleas'd to return it with great Civility, and
at the Governours reque&s;t afterwards granted him
leave to go to <HI>Narva,</HI> tho' the City was then
Block'd up by his Forces under General <HI>Schein.</HI></P>
<P>THE Affairs of <HI>Poland</HI> were now come to a
&s;trange <HI>Cri&s;is,</HI> and &s;uch as particularly oblig'd his
<HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty to concern him&s;elf more than or|dinarily
with them; for the King of <HI>Sweden</HI> had
&s;o far pu&s;h'd his Conque&s;t as to bring the <HI>Poles</HI> to
an Election of a new King, and carried on his
particular Re&s;entments again&s;t King Augu&s;tus, to
that extremity of Rage, as nothing could abate
it; no Treaties, no Propo&s;als, no Mediation of
foreign Powers could interpo&s;e, &s;o as to bring
him to any Terms.</P>
<P>NOW was the time for a generous Prince to engage
heartily for his Friend; I call <HI>Augu&s;tus</HI>
&s;uch, becau&s;e has <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty openly profe&s;&s;es
in his Letter to the States or Republick of <HI>Poland,</HI>
that he had always entertain'd a per&s;onal Friend|&s;hip,
<PB N="135" REF="136">
for the King of <HI>Sweden,</HI> and now <HI>I &s;ay</HI> was the
time to &s;how it.</P>
<P>AS for the King of <HI>Poland</HI> him&s;elf, to give due
honour to his Merit, he never gave out; he fought
his Ground by Inches, he &s;truggl'd with an In|vincible
Spirit again&s;t all the Difficulties that &s;ur|rounded
him: He had a terrible Prince in the
Bowels of his Country to deal with, a factious
divided and un&s;teady People to govern, who
were neither rea&s;onable in their Demands of him,
or &s;atisfy'd when they were granted; who were
never with him till they were brib'd to it with
Money, nor faithful to him when they had it; who
when they oppos'd him, ruin'd their Country,
and when they joyn'd, ruin'd him; who had Trea|chery
enough to do him Mi&s;chief, and not Cou|rage
enough to do him Good; out of Action, al|ways
In&s;olent, in Action always Cowardly; who
when they &s;hould run, would always be for fight|ing,
and when they &s;hould fight would always
run away: Never Man of Honour ri&s;qu'd his Life,
&s;pent the Blood of a faithful Nation (his <HI>Saxons</HI>)
and &s;uch a ma&s;s of Trea&s;ure as he brought among
them, for a &s;uch a fal&s;e perver&s;e unperforming
Generation: Take the State of King <HI>Augu&s;tus</HI>'s
Ca&s;e, and the Character of his <HI>Pali&s;h</HI> Friends in
the Words of a known Writer of that Day, <HI>Thus.</HI></P>
<P>HOWEVER nothing di&s;courag'd the King, and
the King of <HI>Sweden</HI> &s;etting up a new King, not
only whetted his Courage, but animated tho&s;e
few <HI>Poles,</HI> that Hood by him, and encreas'd
their Number, &s;o that after the Election King <HI>Au|gu&s;tus</HI>
grew &s;tronger than he was before, nor would
the King of <HI>Sweden</HI> have ever been able lo have
reduc'd him, had not the unlucky Defeat of a
new raised Body of <HI>Saxons</HI> open'd a Door to the
<PB N="136" REF="137">
<HI>Swedes</HI> to enter <HI>Saxony;</HI> This brought the King
<HI>entirely</HI> down, and forc'd him to &s;igh the <HI>Chart$
Blanc</HI> to the King of <HI>Sweden,</HI> and yeild to what|ever
he demanded of him: Some particulars of
which were &s;o hard, and &s;o grating to a Man of
Spirit, as King Augu&s;tus is known to be, that the
King of <HI>Sweden</HI> lo&s;t more honour in Impo&s;ing
them upon him, than the King of <HI>Poland</HI> did in
&s;ubmitting to them; the former putting them up|on
him, as matter of Triumph over his Misfor|tunes,
and the other &s;ubmitting to them purely to
prevent the intire De&s;olation of his Country, and
the ruin of his People; &s;uch were the delivering
up General <HI>Patkul,</HI> the writing a Letter to <HI>Stani&s;|la$s</HI>
giving him the Title of King, and the
re&s;toring the Trophies of his Valour, the Stan|dards
and Colours taken at the great Battle of
<HI>Cali&s;ch,</HI> where he had defeated the whole united
Army of the <HI>Swedes</HI> and <HI>Poles,</HI> and gain'd a com|pleat
Victory over them, killing above 12000 on
the &s;pot, and taking all their Cannon and Baggage,
with a great many Colours and Standards, all
which the King of <HI>Sweden</HI> obliged him to re|&s;tore.</P>
<P>BUT leaving the King of <HI>Sweden</HI> to make War
as never Prince before him did, Namely to gain
Victories abroad, and loo&s;e his Country at Home;
to Conquer for other People, and be Conquered
for his own; invade <HI>Saxony,</HI> which he knew he
mu&s;t quit and loo&s;e <HI>Livonia Ea&s;t-honia, Ingria,</HI> and
part of <HI>Finland,</HI> which he never &s;hall recover; if
this be per&s;uit of glory, be that fame peculiar
to him&s;elf, for he &s;eem'd to be the only Prince in
the World that ever &s;ought his Glory, at the Ex|pence
of the Lo&s;s of his Dominions, and to cut
in p$ices the worthle&s;s <HI>Poles,</HI> &s;at &s;till and let his
<PB N="137" REF="138">
own Subjects be cut in peices, and his Dominions
ravag'd and made a de&s;olation; his Subjects flying,
or being carried away, to People the Dominions of
the Conquerer.</P>
<P>BUT thus it was with the King of <HI>Sweden,</HI> for
at the &s;ame time that he was thus pu&s;hing the
King of <HI>Poland,</HI> and &s;pending the Strength and
Arms of <HI>Sweden,</HI> to &s;upport a new Boy-King
in <HI>Poland;</HI> he abandon'd his faithful Subjects in
<HI>Livonia,</HI> and quietly let his <HI>Czarish</HI> Maje&s;ty go on
with an unterrupted Cour&s;e of Conque&s;t, not &s;end|ing
the lea&s;t Relief to his be&s;ieged Cities, or to his
faithful Garri&s;ons, till they all fell into his Enemies
Hands; for the <HI>Czar</HI> left him not a Foot of Land
on the South Shores of the <HI>Baltick,</HI> and took from
him Countries and Provinces, equal in Wealth
and Commerce, to his whole Kingdom of <HI>Swed|land.</HI></P>
<P>IT was now that mindful of the Di&s;tre&s;s
that the King of <HI>Poland</HI> was in, and that the
Republick was like to be brought to, his
<HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty, at the &s;ame time that with an
uninterrupted Cour&s;e of Victory he rais'd his
Glory in the Conque&s;t of the <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> Dominions,
Concern'd him&s;elf in a more particular manner
for the Intere&s;t of King <HI>Augu&s;tus;</HI> and be&s;ides
the numerous Armies, which upon &s;everal Occa&s;ions,
he &s;ent to his Relief, and tho' his Troops were
&s;eldom well Treated in <HI>Poland,</HI> which made them
le&s;s Serviceable than they would otherwi&s;e have
been, yet he continu'd to Succour them by all po&s;|&s;ible
Methods.</P>
<P>To this End his Maje&s;ty wrote that famous Let|ter
to the Republick; the Mea&s;ures of which had
they thought fit to have per&s;ued, they had never
<PB N="138" REF="139">
fallen a Prey as they did to the cruel Enemy, who
Triumph'd over them.</P>
<P>THIS Letter becau&s;e the Contents of it were
dictated immediately from his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty's
own Mouth, and becau&s;e it &s;hows how perfectly
he was acquainted with the true Intere&s;t of <HI>Poland,</HI>
and with the Methods how their Liberty and Glo|ry
was to be retriev'd, I &s;hall give at large as it
was rendred in <HI>Engli&s;h</HI> at the time it was &s;ent, <HI>as
follows.</HI></P>
<DIV2 TYPE="letter">
<HEAD>The Letter of the Czar of Mu&s;covy, to the Repub|lick
of Poland; Printed in Latin and French, by
Order of his Mini&s;ters, and Communicated to mo&s;t
of the Potentates in Chri&s;tendom, is as followeth,</HEAD>
<P>&startq;PETER ALEXEWITZ, by the Grace of
GOD mo&s;t Serene, and mo&s;t Powerful great
Lord, Czar and great Duke of the whole Great,
Le&s;&s;er, and <HI>White Ru&s;&s;ia,</HI> Soveraign of <HI>Mu&s;co|vy,
&amp;c.</HI>&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;TO the mo&s;t Illu&s;trious, mo&s;t Eminent and
mo&s;t Reverend Lords, <HI>Michael Stephen Radzi|owski,</HI>
Archbi&s;hop of <HI>Geu&s;ne,</HI> Cardinal and Pri|mate
of <HI>Poland;</HI> and to the mo&s;t Illu&s;trious ge|nerous
and magnificient Lords, the Senators of
the Kingdom, and other Orders of the mo&s;t Se|rene
Republick of <HI>Poland,</HI> and great Dutchy
Lithuania, Salutation and Pro&s;perity.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;MOST Illu&s;trious, mo&s;t Eminent, and mo&s;t
Reverend Lord Archbi&s;hop and Cardinal, and
Reverend Primate of the Kingdom of <HI>Poland,</HI>
and Great Dutchy of <HI>Lithuania,</HI> mo&s;t Illu&s;tious
generous and magnificient Lords, the Senators,
and other Ordrs of mo&s;t Serene Republick of
<PB N="139" REF="140">
<HI>Poland</HI> and great Dutchy of <HI>Lithuania</HI> our
Friends, and mo&s;t dear Neighbours, notwith|&s;tanding
we have been inform'd a long time
&s;ince, and the like Reports were &s;pread through
mo&s;t part of <HI>Europe,</HI> that &s;ome of your Republick
led by the Motives of a certain inveterate Ha|tred,
and full of wicked Intention, made u&s;e
of all po&s;&s;ible Means to drive from his Throne
his &s;acred poli&s;h Maje&s;ty, our Brother, and
mo&s;t dear Neighbour, who is in mo&s;t &s;trict Al|liance
with us, that they may afterwards more
Effectually carry on the ill De&s;igns they have
contriv'd, and more &s;$afely obtain their Aim;
yet we had &s;o good an Opinion of your Equity
and Ju&s;tice, that not only we were unwilling to
give Credit to tho&s;e Reports which came from all
Parts; but al&s;o forbore to con&s;ider the &s;ame, with
the &s;erious Attention that they de&s;erved from
our Thoughts, that if that Fury and abominable
Pa&s;&s;ion had crept among&s;t &s;ome of the Orders of
your Republick, yet the number of &s;uch who think
on what they owe to God, and their Country,
and to Honour and Virtue, would much exceed the
Number of tho&s;e, who not duly weighing the
fatal Con&s;equences of tho&s;e De&s;igns, have &s;uf|fered
them&s;elves to be blinded by a depraved
Pa&s;&s;ion and their private Intere&s;ts; we thought
al&s;o that tho&s;e great Agitations being Supported
by no Chri&s;tian Powers, would be ea&s;ily ap|peas'd
among&s;t your &s;elves; but we have after|terwards
ob&s;erv'd, and are convinc'd by un|que&s;tionable
Proofs, that that Evil was more and
more increa&s;ing and taking deeper Roots, we
thought it was our Duty more than any
body el&s;e to intervene, and expre&s;s publickly
how much we were concern'd upon hearing of &s;o
<PB N="140" REF="141">
pernicious a De&s;ign, which does no ways become
a Chri&s;tian Nation: In fine after having matu|rely
con&s;ider'd that Point, we have re&s;olv'd to
do by our Interpo&s;ition what we believe every
hone&s;t Man is bound to do, e&s;pecially con&s;ider|ing
the great Office we exerci&s;e upon Earth, and
the general Obligation laid upon all Chri&s;tian
Princes, by God and human Society, to expel
Violence and re&s;train Inju&s;tice, and &s;uch wicked
Advices, as tend to the &s;ubver&s;ions of Laws,
and to other ties of human Society, and di&s;turb
the publick Peace of Chri&s;tendom; &s;o that Ju|&s;tice
may be every where admini&s;tred, and In|nocence
protected, that the common Cau&s;e of
Princes, and the Rights of Kings may be chiefly
pre&s;erved entire; that in&s;tead of that honou|rable
Liberty allowed by the divine and human
Laws, which are de&s;ervedly made the Joy of free
Nations: People may not be carried away to
the Exce&s;&s;es of &s;lighting Princes, and tramp|pling
under Foot crown'd Heads, who&s;e Ma|je&s;ty
is deriv'd immediately from God, that
the &s;ame may not be expo&s;ed to the Fury of
&s;uch as love Novelties. La&s;tly, that the fun|damental
Laws e&s;tabli&s;h'd by Nature its &s;elf
for the Pre&s;ervation of human Society be not
de&s;troyed, and that Men created in the Image
of God, may not degenerate into Brutes, and
live without any Law; be&s;ides all the&s;e Rea|&s;ons
we are particularly oblig'd to concern
our &s;elves in this Affair, by Virtue of the
Peace concluded in the Year 1686, with the
Kingdom of <HI>Poland;</HI> wherein 'tis &s;aid in ex|pre&s;s
terms, that the brotherly Love, and in|vincible
Peace be maintain'd between us and the
mo&s;t Serene King of <HI>Poland;</HI> that they
<PB N="141" REF="142">
mind the good Advantage of each other; that
as Brothers they may a&s;&s;i&s;t each other, and
that their Maje&s;ties are as others, bound to
&s;how each other all the Duties of Humanity,
Friend&s;hip, and Brotherly Affection, and e|very
thing el&s;e that may tend to their re|&s;pective
Advantage; and take all po&s;&s;ible Care
to avoid all things which may breed Enmity,
or occa&s;ion Violence, and more e&s;pecially &s;uch
as might create War, and occa&s;ion the effu&s;ion
of human Blood, and the ravage of their re|&s;pective
Countries, as it becomes Chri&s;tian
Princes; and &s;hall take care that no new Wars
and Divi&s;ions may break out upon any Ac|count
whatever; all the&s;e things having been in
a &s;olemn manner Sworn to upon the Book of the
Go&s;pel, the Succe&s;&s;ors in both Kingdoms are in|di&s;putably
bound thereto: Grounded upon the&s;e
Foundations we have contracted a per&s;onal
Friend&s;hip with the mo&s;t &s;erene King of <HI>Poland,</HI>
now reigning, and Concluded with him an Alli|ance
more &s;trict and particular than the former;
whereby above all other things we have pro|mis'd
each other, that as long as Providence
would pre&s;erve us our Kingdoms, which may
God render happy, we &s;hould always, and re|giou&s;ly
maintain a &s;incere Friendship, and per|form
to each other all the Duties of a good
Neighbourhood; that we &s;hould never infringe
the &s;ame, but rather &s;hould mutually defend
one another again&s;t all our Enemies what&s;o|ever;
moreover, we are oblig'd to concern our
&s;elves in this Affair, becau&s;e of the great Care
we are &s;trictly to provide for the Peace and
Soveraignty of our Territories &s;ituated on the
Frontiers of <HI>Poland;</HI> for while we &s;ee a &s;ire
<PB N="142" REF="143">
kindled in our Neighbourhood, and threatning
to put all in Flames, we ought to think our
&s;elves concerned in that eminent Danger, and
fear that tho&s;e Flames may &s;pread them&s;elves
into our Dominions, and deprive them of the
Conveniences a peaceful Neighbourhood does u&s;|ual
procure; In &s;hort, we know what &s;ort of
Mon&s;t$er &s;ome of you Nouri&s;h in your Bo&s;om
again&s;t us, making no &s;cruple to entertain &s;uch
pernicious De&s;igns, and being not a&s;hamed to
&s;ay publickly that after having put in executi|on
what they nave contriv'd again&s;t the &s;acred
Per&s;on of his Maje&s;ty, they wall join our Ene|my,
which is however directly contrary to
the perpetrated Peace afore&s;aid, which was ob|tain'd
with the effu&s;ion of much human Blood;
for among&s;t the &s;everal Conditions to &s;ettle the
&s;tability of the Peace between the two Nati|ons,
with the mo&s;t &s;erene King and Republick
of <HI>Poland;</HI> it is expre&s;ly $tipulated, that his
Maje&s;ty, and his Succe&s;&s;ors who &s;hall be
Elected after him; the great Dukes of <HI>Lithua|nia</HI>
and the whole Republick of the Crown of
<HI>Poland,</HI> and great Dutchy of <HI>Lithuania,</HI> the
Eccle&s;ia&s;tical and &s;ecular Orders of each Nati|on
promi&s;e to favour no ways our declared or
&s;ecret Enemies, neither by them&s;elves, nor by
others to have any Corre&s;pondence with them,
and never to &s;uffer them to commit the lea&s;t
Ho&s;tility: To the End then, that this fire which
lies concealed under the&s;e treacheous A&s;hes may
be extingui&s;hed in a due time, before it breaks
out into a Flame, and that abominable De&s;ign
abhorred of God and Man, perfidiou&s;ly to break
an Oath, and violate what has been &s;olemnly
Sworn to, may be &s;tifled in its beginning; we have
<PB N="143" REF="144">
concern'd our &s;elves in this Affair, being &s;atis|fied
that we have &s;ufficiently &s;hown to all the
World that it is our Duty and Right to interpo&s;e
our &s;elves therein, and have thought fit in the fir&s;t
Place to appeal our &s;elves to your mo&s;t &s;erene
Republick, and induce you by this friendly
Exhortation to weigh every thing in this ex|tremity,
and to admoni&s;h without interruption,
&s;uch who entertain tho&s;e pernicious De&s;igns,
(dete&s;ted by all good Men) to reflect upon them|&s;elves,
and consider what they undertake, and
that they not only expo&s;e their Honour and Re|putation,
but likewi&s;e the Security of their
Country to an evident Danger.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;THE Rea&s;ons upon which they fancy they may
ground the dethroning of a King elected ac|cording
to Law, a re-acknowledg'd by his great|e&s;t
Enemies to appear &s;o unju&s;t and frivilous to
unintere&s;ted Per&s;ons, that the Authors of
tho&s;e Councils cannot avoid the Name and Cha|racter
of Enemies and perfidious Men, which
have been be&s;towed upon them by their own
Brothers, nor hinder all Chri&s;tian Princes, and
e&s;pecially &s;uch, who are oblig'd by Treaties or
Rea&s;ons of State to Defend, and Protect the
&s;acred Maje&s;ty of Kings from oppo&s;ing with
all their might the Election of another Per&s;on,
to the prejudice of the publick Good of Chri|&s;tendom,
and puting a &s;top to tho&s;e impious De|&s;igns:
They cannot be ignorant that his &s;acred
Maje&s;ty as Elector of <HI>Saxony</HI> has &s;till Forces e|nough
to repell tho&s;e Ho&s;tilities, and main|tain
the good Cau&s;e and Right, he has once
acquired; and rather the more, becau&s;e the be&s;t
Part of the mo&s;t &s;erene Republick, in con&s;ide|ration
of their Duty, and their Oath, have de|clar'd
<PB N="144" REF="145">
their Readine&s;s to &s;pill their Blood for
their King, and Sacrifice their Lives and Re|putation
for his Defence, to the immortal Glory
of them, and their Po&s;terity; and what can be
the End of all this, but to make their own Coun|try
a Theatre of War, and open a large Field
for the Plunder and Deva&s;tation of their Neigh|bouring
Nations? As to the Authors of this De|&s;ign,
and &s;uch who favour them, they will re|ceive
the puni&s;hment they ju&s;tly de&s;erve; they
will bring a blot upon them&s;elves and their Po|&s;terity,
which &s;hall never be wip$d of, and &s;inking
at la&s;t under, the weight of Divine Ju&s;tice,
which never leaves tho&s;e attempts unpuni&s;hed,
they will deplore their own Misfortunes, but
too late.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;As to tho&s;e among you who have Cau&s;e to
complain, for we know very well, that the
whole mo&s;t Serene Republick is not hurried a|way
by that impiety, but is for the major Part
inclined for the King, we may &s;ay that 'tis cer|tain
that God him&s;elf, and the be&s;t and mo&s;t
prudent Princes cannot equally plea&s;e all the
World, and that the Chagrin and Di&s;atisfaction
of &s;ome proceed from particular Affections,
which u&s;ually &s;way the Words and the Writings,
and from Pa&s;&s;ion and private Intere&s;t of Parties;
but although they had ju&s;t Cau&s;e of Complaint,
which does not hitherto appear, they ought for
all that to con&s;ider, that tho&s;e political Di&s;tem|pers
do not occa&s;ion &s;o much Danger to the Re|publick,
as commonly do the means which, &s;ome
are endeavouring to make u&s;e of as a remedy in
the pre&s;ent Ca&s;e, and to neglect the Friendly and
Amicable ways pre&s;crib'd by the fundamental
Laws of <HI>Poland,</HI> even to the offended Party,
<PB N="145" REF="146">
and have immediately recour&s;e to Violence and
Extremities, is a Practice contrary to the di|vine
and human Laws.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;IF the Authors of the&s;e Novelties &s;hould by
the permi&s;&s;ion of God, for &s;ome &s;ecret Rea|&s;ons
of which there are &s;ome In&s;tances obtain
their Aim, what would they Gain thereby? ex|cept
to &s;uffer &s;omewhat &s;ooner or later the Pu|ni&s;hment
due to their Wickedne&s;s, and their
Po&s;terity &s;hall never wa&s;h off the Infamy they
have brought upon them&s;elves, and their Nati|on;
the A&s;&s;i&s;tance of a Foreign Prince encourages
them in this De&s;ign, but the Event will enable
them to make a true Judgement of their Acti|ons,
and time will &s;how their vanity in build|ing
&s;uch great things on a &s;andy Foundation,
and that they have rely'd on a broken Reed;
they have taken for the Defender of the Cau&s;e;
and have e&s;pous'd a Prince, who for recom|pen&s;ing
him&s;elf for the trouble he mu&s;t be at,
and reimbur&s;e him&s;elf of the Expences and
Charges, will &s;eize upon after having ruined
their whole Country; we think it needle&s;s to en|large
any further upon a Subject of &s;o dangerous
a Con&s;equence, and flatter our &s;elves that &s;uch
who de&s;ire the Pre&s;ervation of their Republick,
among&s;t whom there is a great Number of Sena|tors
and good Patriots will exert their utmo&s;t
Prudence to make their Brethren &s;en&s;ible of
their Mi&s;take, and bring back into the right
way &s;uch who have been &s;educ'd; as to the re&s;t,
we declare to the mo&s;t Serene Republick, that
we are re&s;olved to Interpo&s;e our good Offices,
and in Order that &s;uch who remembring what
they owe to God, their King and Country, have
promis'd to lay down their Lives for his Ma|je&s;ty,
<PB N="146" REF="147">
and likewi&s;e &s;uch who have the impu|dence
to oppo&s;e their Prince, and &s;tir Heaven
and Earth to obtain their Aim, may equally
know our Intentions towards them; we do
offer with a &s;incere Heart our good Offices
to pacify the Divi&s;ions and Quarrels which have
been excited between his Sacred <HI>Poli&s;h</HI> Ma|je&s;ty,
and &s;ome Members of the mo&s;t Serene
Republick, out of our Affection for our Bro|ther,
Friend and good Neighbour; and are ful|ly
per&s;waded that God's ble&s;&s;ing, and the A&s;&s;i|&s;tance
of our Friends, and Confederates con|cerned
therein, we &s;hall re&s;tore Peace, Union
and Pro&s;perity to the &s;atisfaction of both Parties,
and the common Advantage of the Kingdom of
<HI>Poland,</HI> and Great Dutchy of <HI>Lithuania;</HI> doubt|ing
not in the lea&s;t, but that this offer of our
good Offices proceeding from the &s;incerity of
our Heart will appear free from all Su&s;picions
to the re&s;pective Parties; for as his Sacred Ma|j$&s;ty
is fully a&s;&s;ured of our con&s;tant Friend&s;hip,
and Brotherly Affection, &s;o the mo&s;t Serene
Republick may firmly rely upon our plain and
&s;incere Intentions, whereby we are induced
to Protect their Liberty in Con&s;ideration of the
perpetual Peace herein alledged; therefore we
friendly invite by this Letter to a &s;peedy
and Categorical an&s;wer, that we may know
whether our Offers are accepted with the &s;ame
Di&s;po&s;itions for the Peace and Tranquility of
<HI>Poland</HI> and <HI>Luthania,</HI> as we do pro&s;e&s;s before
God we have at this time.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;HOWEVER we &s;hall continue the necc&s;&s;ary
Preparations, that in Ca&s;e the di&s;a&s;tected Party
per&s;i&s;t in their wicked De&s;igns, we may be able
to exert the power God has given us to Support
<PB N="147" REF="148">
and Maintain his Sacred Maje&s;ty on a Throne
he is lawfully po&s;&s;e&s;s'd of: As to tho&s;e who &s;hall
&s;ide with the King, or &s;hall in a due time re|turn
to their Duty, we &s;hall grant them our
&s;pecial Favour, and &s;how them as much Affecti|on,
as if they had done &s;omething for our &s;elves,
and promoted our own Advantage; promi&s;ing
to a&s;&s;i&s;t them with all our Power for pacifying
the&s;e troubles; but for &s;uch who oppo&s;e the mo&s;t
Serene King of <HI>Poland</HI> their Soveraign, and will
not de&s;i&s;t from their pernicious De&s;ign, we de|clare
them our Enemies, with all their Ad|herents,
and &s;hall puni&s;h them as &s;uch every
where, and &s;hall not forbear our Ho&s;tilities a|gain&s;t
them, till tho&s;e Di&s;turbers of the publick
Peace, and Enemies of their Country, as they
have been ju&s;tly called by their own Countrymen
in the Acts, and publick Decrees, made during
this Inte&s;tine War, have been &s;everely puni&s;h|ed,
made an example to others, and are pluck|ed
out like a Weed of the Kingdom of <HI>Poland,</HI>
and Great Dutchy of <HI>Lithuania,</HI> whereof the
Peace and Tranquility is as dear to us, as that
of our own Dominions; And in fine, till our
Neighbourhood is cleared of tho&s;e wicked Men,
and that this Letter may be of greater force,
and that not only the Serene Republick, but
al&s;o all the World may know that this is our
De&s;ign, and Re&s;olution; we &s;hall communicate
this Declaration to all the Princes who favour
our Cau&s;e, that the Ju&s;tice of what we are going
to undertake may appear every were; but for
our Neighbours, who have the &s;ame good Rea|&s;ons
as we, to look upon this Affair as concern|ing
them in a particular manner, we invite
them to join, and enter into Alliance with us&punc;
<PB N="148" REF="149">
and being re&s;olv'd to neglect nothing for the
Defence of the &s;acred Per&s;on of his Maje&s;ty,
we &s;hall take care of his Cau&s;e, Scepter and
Crown, as of our own: We wi&s;h with all our
Hearts the Graces and Ble&s;&s;ing of the Almighty
to &s;uch who &s;incerely de&s;ire the Advantage and
Pre&s;ervation of the mo&s;t Serene Republick, and
that they may &s;ucceed in the De&s;ign they &s;hall
go upon for the glory of God, the pre&s;ervation
of their King, and the Honour and Advantage
of their Country, and we wi&s;h them a good
Health. Done at <HI>Mu&s;cow,</HI> of your Eminency,
your Excellencies and great Genero&s;ities, the
good and affectionate Friend.&endq;</P>
<CLOSER><SIGNED>Peter.</SIGNED></CLOSER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2>
<P>IN Con&s;equence of this Letter, and at the Reque&s;t
of the King of <HI>Poland,</HI> his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty order|ed
a Body of 45000 Men, Choice Troops and very
well appointed to march to the Frontiers of <HI>Po|land,</HI>
on the Side of <HI>Sendomir,</HI> and there to re|ceive
Orders from the King of <HI>Poland;</HI> which they
did very opportunely for the Service of that
Prince, who was clo&s;ely pur&s;ued by the <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI>
General <HI>Rhen&s;child</HI> with an Army much Superi|or
to his own, and was oblig'd to pa&s;s the <HI>Vi&s;tule</HI>
at <HI>Petrowinnear &s;endomir,</HI> and break down the
Bri$ge behind him to prevent his being fallen
upon.</P>
<P>BUT now being Supported by a &s;trong Confe|derate
ready at his call, and the appren&s;ions of his
being join'd by the <HI>Ru&s;&s;ian</HI> Army, having &s;top'd Ge|neral
<HI>Rhen&s;child</HI> in his pur&s;uit, the King of <HI>Poland</HI>
had time given him to Summon his Friends about
him, and which was more the <HI>Palatinates</HI> on that
Side, which were before in the <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> Intere&s;t &s;ee|ing
<PB N="149" REF="150">
a powerful Army at hand to protect them, and
that they might march &s;ecurely, began now to draw
together, and flocking in to the Support of their
King; his <HI>Poli&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty had pre&s;ently a powerful
Army of his own, and the Swedi&s;h General was
glad to retreat in his turn to <HI>Cracow.</HI></P>
<P>THUS his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty gave a Turn to the
Affairs of <HI>Poland,</HI> and King <HI>Augu&s;tus</HI> from this
time appear'd every Day more formidable than
other: Here at <HI>sendomir</HI> he Summon'd a great
Council from all the Palatinates which continu'd
faithful to him, and they all under the Encourage|ment
of the Strength and Figure he appeared in,
took now a new Oath to him in Oppo&s;ition to
the Confederate Rebels, who by the Politicks and
Influence of the <HI>Swedes</HI> pretended to declare an
<HI>Interregnum,</HI> and choo&s;e a new King.</P>
<P>IN this A&s;&s;embly they declar'd their abhorence
of that perfidious Conventicle, which call'd them|&s;elves
a Diet met at <HI>War&s;aw,</HI> and took a new Oath,
obliging them&s;elves to oppo&s;e it with all their
Might: In the next Place they declared, That any
Prince who &s;hall take upon him the Title of King
of <HI>Poland</HI> or &s;hall &s;tand Candidate in the pretended
Election, &s;hall be deem'd the Enemy and Tyrant
of the Country; the Primate and the Bi&s;hop of
<HI>Pozen</HI> being look'd upon as the chief Authors Pro|moters
of the&s;e troubles, not minding and the
King's favours towards them, were declared Ene|mies
of their Country, Infamous and Rebels. And
Application is ordred to be made to the Pope, That
tho&s;e Prelates be proceeded again&s;t by Excommu|nication,
and other Cen&s;ures of the Church, as be|ing
the occa&s;ion of the Effu&s;ion of &s;o much Chri|&s;tian
Blood, and that in the mean time, their
Revenues &s;hall be &s;eiz'd and confi&s;ticated; the
<PB N="150" REF="151">
Mar&s;hal of the Crown, and others who have enter|ed
into the Confederacy at <HI>War&s;aw,</HI> are declar'd
Rebels, and condemn'd as &s;uch, unle&s;s within
four Weeks they quit the Party of the Rebels, and
return to the Obedience of their Soveraign,
which favour was granted them upon the King's
earne&s;t de&s;ire, that &s;uch who &s;hall return to their
Duty, &s;hall have their Pardon without any Re|&s;triction,
and &s;hall be paid off their Arrears, if
they are in Service; that the Governours and Com|manders
of the Fortre&s;&s;es of the Kingdom &s;hall
no longer re&s;pect the Orders of the Mar&s;hal of
the Crown; but &s;hall receive Directions from
the Mar&s;hal of the Royal Confederacy for King
<HI>Augu&s;tus.</HI> Eightly and La&s;tly, That the Alliances
made, or to be made with the Neighbouring
Princes to invade by way of Diver&s;ion the Ter|ritories
of <HI>Sweden,</HI> &s;hall $e con&s;idered, provided
there be not the lea&s;t di&s;membering the Do|minions
of the Republick: The&s;e Articles,
being &s;ub&s;crib'd and confirm'd by Oath, the
Royal Confederacy repair'd to Church, where
Te <HI>Deum</HI> was Sung, to return Thanks for the U|nanmity
of their Re&s;olutions; The King has on
the other hand &s;wore again to keep the <HI>Pacta Con|venta,</HI>
that he &s;hall not exact from the Republick
the Sums of Money he has borrowed; That his
<HI>Saxons</HI> Troops &s;hall be under the Command and
Direction of the General of the Army of the
Crown; That the Sub&s;idies that &s;hall be granted,
&s;hall $e applied to the Payment of the &s;aid Ar|my.
And La&s;tly, that any Conque&s;ts that &s;hall be
made on the Enemies of his Maje&s;ty, and the
Nation &s;hall be annexed to the Republick.</P>
<P><PB N="151" REF="152">
IN a few Days after this 12000 <HI>Ru&s;&s;ian</HI> Foot,
and 4000 <HI>Co&s;&s;acks</HI> join'd his Army, which was al|&s;o
reinforc'd in and about 10 Days by 3000 <HI>Sax|ons,</HI>
Strengthen'd by the&s;e A&s;&s;i&s;tances and the <HI>Pa|latinates,</HI>
as above, coming in with a great many
of their Troops, he found him&s;elf of a &s;udden
from 1500 Hor&s;e, which was all he had at his
coming to <HI>Sendomir,</HI> encrea&s;ed to 12000 Hor&s;e,
and 18000 Foot.</P>
<P>FINDING him&s;elf in this Po&s;ture, the King an
active vigilant Prince, having by good Intelli|gence
learnt that the Cardinal Primate, the great
Dome&s;tick Enemy of his Crown; the pretended
new King's Lady and Family, with abundance of
his mo&s;t Capital Enemies continu'd in the City
of <HI>War&s;aw,</HI> a Place of no great Strength, attend|ed
but with a very indifferent Number of Troops,
he re&s;olv'd to beat up their Quarters; in pur&s;u|ance
of this Re&s;olution he remov'd with all his
Calvalry, with the utmo&s;t Silence in the Night,
and without letting one Man in his whole Army
know any thing of his De&s;ign; he march'd direct|ly
for <HI>War&s;aw,</HI> he executed this Project with a
Celerity &s;carce Practicable, ordering his Infantry
to follow with all po&s;&s;ible &s;peed, and puting his
Cannon into Boats on the <HI>Vi&s;tula:</HI> In this
Po&s;ture before his Enemies had the lea&s;t Notice
of his being Decamp'd from <HI>Sendomir,</HI> he appear|ed
at the Gates of <HI>War&s;aw,</HI> in the Morning, before
it was quite break of Day, and inve&s;ted the Place:
The Confu&s;ion it occa&s;ion'd to tho&s;e within, may
a little be gue&s;s'd at, and the Succe&s;s of it is a
little de&s;crib'd in the following Account, which
tho' not &s;o very much relating to the Affairs of
<HI>Ru&s;&s;ia,</HI> yet as the <HI>Ru&s;&s;ian</HI> Troops were concern'd in
it, I could not omit the Relation.</P>
<P><PB N="152" REF="153">
THE unexpected approach of that Prince&punc; ob|lig'd
the Cardinal Primate&punc; the pretended new
Queen, with the <HI>Palatines</HI> of <HI>Siridia, Lenite</HI> and <HI>Pod|lochia,</HI>
and &s;everal other Grandees to quit <HI>War&s;aw,</HI>
with the utmo&s;t precipitation; and they had the
good Luck to e&s;cape: His <HI>Poli&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty having not
fully infe&s;ted the City till the next Day; but Ge|neral
Horn, who took upon him the Command of the Life Guards of the new King, with &s;ome
<HI>Swedes, Valachians</HI> and <HI>Co&s;&s;acks</HI> &s;eem'd re&s;olv'd to
defend the Place to the la&s;t Extremity: This ob|lig'd
King <HI>Augu&s;tus</HI> to rai&s;e &s;ome Batteries; but as
&s;oon as they were ready, General Horn quitted the
Town, and retired into the Ca&s;tle. The Forces of
King <HI>Augu&s;tus</HI> took po&s;&s;e&s;&s;ion thereof the 3d in the
Morning, but they were forbidden to Plunder,
the Magi&s;trates having promi&s;ed to pay 50000
Rix Dollars; the &s;ame Day General <HI>Brandt,</HI> who
had pa&s;s'd the <HI>Vi&s;tule</HI> with 6000 <HI>Co&s;&s;acks</HI> and
1000 <HI>Saxon</HI> Hor&s;e, made preparations to attack
the Ca&s;tle, and a Battery of 4 Pieces of Cannon
was erected the 4th in the Morning to Batter the
&s;ame: This oblig'd General <HI>Horn</HI> to &s;urrender
with all the Officers Soldiers, and other Adherents
of the <HI>Swedes,</HI> therein Pri&s;oners of War, the King
having refus'd to grant them any other Terms. The
State Pri&s;oners were the Bi&s;hop of <HI>Po&s;nania,</HI> who
proclaim'd the new King; the <HI>Sieurs Wa&s;lager,</HI> and
<HI>Palemberg</HI> Plenipotentiaries of the King of <HI>Sweden;</HI>
Lieutenant General <HI>Horn,</HI> the <HI>Ca&s;tillan Kimp&s;ki,</HI> I
tenant Colonel, 2 Majors, 10 Captains, 15 Lieu|tenants,
14 En&s;igns, 1 Adjutant, 72 Sergeants,
260 Soldiers, be&s;ides $25 <HI>Swedes</HI> taken &s;ome Days
before by General <HI>Bra$dt</HI> at <HI>Latowitz;</HI> where
he cut in pieces $20 <HI>Swedes&punc;</HI> the fir Equipage of
Prince <HI>Alexander,</HI> his Hor&s;es Mules, <HI>&amp;c.</HI> wee
<PB N="153" REF="154">
taken in the Ca&s;tle; the Sieur <HI>Wal&s;chlager</HI> being
born a Subject of the Republick, King <HI>Augu&s;tus</HI>
has not &s;howed the &s;ame regard towards him, as
towards the Sieur <HI>Palemberg,</HI> and has &s;ent him Pri&s;|oner
into <HI>Saxony</HI> with the Bi&s;hop of <HI>Po&s;nania,</HI> and
the two Sons of the <HI>Ca&s;tellan</HI> of <HI>Cracow:</HI> General
<HI>Horn</HI> obtain'd leave to go to the <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> Camp up|on
his Parole of Honour, to &s;urrender him&s;elf
Pri&s;oner in <HI>Saxony,</HI> within two Months time, un|le&s;s
his Liberty was obtain'd before.</P>
<P>IN a very few Days after this Action, the King
of <HI>Poland</HI> pa&s;s'd the <HI>Vi&s;tula</HI> again at <HI>War&s;aw,</HI> and
advancing towards <HI>Sile&s;a,</HI> encamp'd at a Place
call'd <HI>Whip&s;ogrod,</HI> where he receiv'd a Body of
16000 <HI>Saxons,</HI> all fine Troops, and their Cavalry
exceeding well Mounted, and to join whom it
was, that he March'd that way, for he immediate|ly
returned.</P>
<P>ALL this while the King of <HI>Sweden,</HI> who&s;e
Fate it often was to be wining a great way off, and
lo&s;eing nearer home, was advanc'd as far as the
farthe&s;t part of <HI>Poland,</HI> and was attacking <HI>Lem|berg,</HI>
which he took, and his Men exerci&s;ed &s;uch
there unheard of Cruelties upon the <HI>Jews,</HI> and o|ther
Inhabitants to Extort from them the Di&s;cove|ry
of their Trea&s;ure, that made all the Chri&s;tian
World a&s;toni&s;h'd, and made the Name of a <HI>Swede</HI>
odious to the whole <HI>Poli&s;h</HI> Nation.</P>
<P>WHILE the&s;e things were doing his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Ma|je&s;ty
went on in a rapid Cour&s;e of interrupted
Victory in <HI>Livonia,</HI> and having taken the whole
Province of <HI>Ingria,</HI> as above, taken <HI>Nyen&s;chans,</HI>
and <HI>Dorpat</HI> by Compo&s;ition, raz'd <HI>Schan&s;terney,</HI>
built <HI>Petersburgh, Croon&s;lot,</HI> and all the Forts on
the Entry of that Royal Port, His Maje&s;ty now
re&s;olv'd on the attack of <HI>Narva,</HI> and the Fort on
<PB N="154" REF="155">
the other Side of the River call'd <HI>Ivanagrod:</HI> He
had held the Place block'd up for &s;ome time, but
now he re&s;olv'd to pu&s;h the Siege with the utmo&s;t
Vigour.</P>
<P>AND here the Governour found the difference be|tween
the <HI>Mu&s;covite</HI> attacks now, and in the former
Siege: The Trenches were open'd the 27th of <HI>Au|gu&s;t,</HI>
and the Place batter'd with 40 Pieces of hea|vy
Cannon, and 12 Mortars. The Batteries were
&s;o well &s;erv'd, and the Defences of the Be&s;ieg'd
&s;o effectually beaten down, that after 13 Days
open Trenches, the <HI>Ru&s;&s;ians</HI> gave a general A&s;&s;ault,
and manag'd it &s;o well, mounting the Breach
with &s;uch Bravery, that tho' the Garri&s;on which
con&s;i&s;ted of 1600 Men, be&s;ides Burghers, defend|ed
them&s;elves with the utmo&s;t Bravery, the <HI>Ru&s;|&s;ians</HI>
entered the Place, Sword in hand, and put
the Garri&s;on, and arm'd Burghers to the Sword;
the <HI>Swedes</HI> not calling for Quarter, but defending
them&s;elves, as it may be &s;aid to the la&s;t Man.</P>
<P>I NEED &s;ay no more to convince the Reader
how the <HI>Ru&s;&s;ians</HI> were now improv'd in the Affairs
of War, than to &s;how how they behav'd on e|very
occa&s;ion, and particular in the attacking
of this Town, which is now Storm'd in 13 Days,
open Trenches, whereas General <HI>Horn</HI> formerly
Defended it &s;ix Weeks again&s;t 100000 Men, till
the King of <HI>Sweden</HI> came and reliev'd it.</P>
<P>THUS the <HI>Czar's</HI> Di&s;grace, as it was call'd be|fore
<HI>Narva</HI> was compleatly wip'd out: People
began to enquire by what Magick his Maje&s;ty had
infus'd Courage and Co$duct into the <HI>Ru&s;&s;ians,</HI>
who before were the Contempt of all the Soldiery
of <HI>Europe.</HI></P>
<P>THE Ca&s;tle of <HI>Ivanag$od,</HI> oppo&s;ite to <HI>Narva,</HI>
held out for &s;ome Days, but &s;eeing the <HI>Ru&s;&s;ians</HI>
<PB N="155" REF="156">
go &s;eriou&s;ly to Work with them, and fearing to
&s;hare the &s;ame Fate with the City, the Gover|nour
beat a Parly, after &s;u&s;taining a prodigious
Battery for &s;ix Days: In &s;hort he Surrendered the
Fortre&s;s upon honourable Conditions.</P>
<P>As to the City of <HI>Narva,</HI> being taken by
Storm, it was given up to Plunder as a reward of
the Labours of the Soldiery, only that they were
forbid to kill any of the Inhabitants, except &s;uch
as were arm'd, and made Re&s;i&s;tance: In the Heat
of this Execution the <HI>Czar</HI> gave &s;uch Orders, and
took care to have them &s;o well executed, that the
Ware-Hou&s;es of the <HI>Engli&s;h</HI> and <HI>Dutch</HI> Merchants,
and al&s;o their Dwelling-Hou&s;es and Families
were not touch'd; no, tho' upon the A&s;&s;urances gi|ven
them of Safety, they &s;uffer'd their Hou&s;es to
be a Retreat for many of the Citizens, and for an
immen&s;e Trea&s;ure, which they brought to them
for Pre&s;erving it from the Soldiers.</P>
<P>HAVING thus made an Entrance upon the Sea-Coa&s;t,
his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty divided his Army into
three Bodies, and &s;ent one Part to block up <HI>Revel,</HI>
and the other <HI>Riga,</HI> ordering the other Part to co|ver
their Camp, and Guard the Pa&s;&s;es into the
Country, being re&s;olved to reduce tho&s;e two im|portant
Places, before any Relief could come to
them.</P>
<P>HOWEVER for &s;ome time his Maje&s;ty de&s;erred
his Re&s;olution to Be&s;iege them in Form being cal|led
off to yeild a yet more powerful A&s;&s;i&s;tance to
his di&s;tre&s;'d Allie the King of <HI>Poland;</HI> in order
to which, he order'd an Army of 60000 Men to
draw together in <HI>Lithuania,</HI> with which his
<HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty re&s;olv'd to Advance in Per&s;on,
and give the King of <HI>Sweden</HI> Battle; as the only
way to make a &s;hort End of the De&s;ola|tions
<PB N="156" REF="157">
of <HI>Poland,</HI> and drive his Enemies out of the
County.</P>
<P>BUT as he was now for the fir&s;t time entering
<HI>Poland,</HI> at the Head of an Army to make War as
I may call it in his own Name, tho' for the Inte|re&s;t
of the King of <HI>Augu&s;tus;</HI> he publi&s;hed a Mani|fe&s;to
to the <HI>Poli&s;h</HI> Nation, and to the <HI>Lithuanians,</HI>
&s;ignifying to them his Rea&s;ons for entering their
Country with an Army, a Piece which will for
ever record the Ju&s;tice of the attempt, and con|vince
Po&s;terity al&s;o of the Nece&s;&s;ity of it at that
time: The <HI>Manefe&s;to</HI> therefore, is worth their peru|&s;&s;ing,
who think it worth while to acquaint them|&s;elves
with the Hi&s;tory of tho&s;e Times; the whole
at large is as follows, (<HI>viz.</HI>)</P>
<P>&startq;WE by the Grace of God, the mo&s;t Illu&s;tri|ous,
and mo&s;t Potent <HI>Czar,</HI> and great Duke,
<HI>Peter Alexewitz,</HI> ab&s;olute Soveraign of the Great|er,
Le&s;&s;er, and <HI>White Ru&s;&s;ia,</HI> and Hereditary
Succe&s;&s;or, Lord of &s;everal Principalities and
Countries, in the Ea&s;t, and We&s;t, Northern Parts
of the World.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;SIGNIFY hereby to the Illu&s;trious and Magni|ficent
Senators. Dignitaries, both Spiritual and
Temporal, and the re&s;t of the great Officers,
and Nobility of the mo&s;t Serene Republick of
<HI>Poland,</HI> and the great Dutchy of <HI>Lithuania,</HI> that
we pur&s;uant to the perpetual Peace, concluded
formerly between both Nations, and the &s;ub&s;e|quent
Alliances made with his Maje&s;ty <HI>Augu&s;tus</HI>
II, and the whole Republick of <HI>Poland,</HI> for a
mutual Pro&s;ecution of the War again&s;t our com|mon
Enemy, have employ'd our utmo&s;t endea|vours
to oblige that Enemy, who has invaded
the Republick of <HI>Poland</HI> to retire out of it; and
<PB N="157" REF="158">
to prevent the Effects of &s;uch impious Factions,
as either for Intere&s;t, or fear of the Enemies
Power and Threats, have endeavoured the&s;e
two Years pa&s;t to Dethrone their lawful King;
we have formerly declared our Abhorrence of
&s;uch perfidious Proceedings, in a Letter &s;ent to the
whole Republick, wherein we acquainted them
at the &s;ame time that we were bound by the
&s;tronge&s;t Ties of Brotherly Love and Alliances;
and by our own Inclinations to defend the com|mon
Rights of Princes to prevent &s;uch a horri|ble
De&s;ign, which de&s;erves the &s;evere&s;t Expre&s;|&s;ions
of God's Vengeance and Wrath; and that
we &s;hould be oblig'd to look upon &s;uch Rebels
to their King and the Republick, as our Ene|mies,
and pur&s;ue them with Fire and Sword;
the&s;e our Exhortations and Warnings had &s;uch
good Effect at fir&s;t, that the Fire which had be|gun
to &s;pread it&s;elf, &s;eem'd extingui&s;h'd, but
as appears &s;oon after, it was only hid under de|ceitful
A&s;hes till the <HI>Swedes</HI> did blow it up a|gain
into a &s;udden Flame, and the <HI>Waywod</HI> of
<HI>Po&s;en, Le&s;cin&s;ky</HI> was unlawfully elected by a
&s;mall Number of incon&s;iderable Per&s;ons to be
King, contrary to the Sentiments of many of
the Confederates that appear'd at the Electi|on,
and in oppo&s;ition to the Liberties, and
Rights, not only of <HI>Poland,</HI> but the whole uni|ver&s;e;
and this dete&s;table Act was not only
prote&s;ted again&s;t by the Archbi&s;hop and Cardi|nal
Primate <HI>Radziow&s;ki,</HI> and other Senators of
the fir&s;t Rank, though they had at that time
quarrel with their lawful Prince; but the Mar|&s;hal
of the Confederated Nobility could never
be per&s;waded to give his con&s;ent to this illegal
Choice; but the <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> notwith&s;tanding, per&s;i&s;t|ing
<PB N="158" REF="159">
ing ob&s;tinately in his De&s;ign, and exerci|&s;ing
an ab&s;olute Power on the Republick, has
compelled &s;ome of the Nobility to conclude a
Treaty with the <HI>Swedes;</HI> Envoys, in the Name
of the elected, who very &s;ubmi&s;&s;ively hearken
to the Dictates of the <HI>Swedes:</HI> Part of the afore|&s;aid
Confederates were indeed taken Pri&s;oners
by their lawful King, and the re&s;t were di&s;|pers'd;
but not only the di&s;tance of our main
Army, and the Animo&s;ities between the Forces
of the Republick, but al&s;o the &s;mall Number
of <HI>Saxons,</HI> &s;oon after oblig'd the foremention'd
King <HI>Augu&s;us</HI> to march to <HI>Saxony,</HI> with part of
his <HI>Saxon</HI> Troops, in order to prevent the in|tended
Inva&s;ion of the <HI>Swedes</HI> in that Electorate;
He de&s;ign'd to return &s;oon to <HI>Poland,</HI> but his
return has hitherto been ob&s;tructed by the
<HI>Swedes,</HI> who have &s;hut up all the Pa&s;&s;ages, this
emboldened the Enemy to publi&s;h in the Name
of the Cardinal Primate, Circular Letters con|firming
the foremention'd unlawful Election,
and having call'd together the petty Dyetts the
26 of <HI>June,</HI> a general one was Summon'd to meet
the 11th of the next en&s;uing Month; we cannot
believe that the&s;e Univer&s;alia were i&s;&s;ued
by the Cardinal Primate, who being not only
the Head of the Clergy, but al&s;o the fir&s;t Mem|ber
of the Republick, was chiefly concern'd to
endeavour a Reconciliation between the Sub|jects
of <HI>Poland,</HI> and their lawful Prince; &s;o
that we have Rea&s;on to think that this unlaw|ful
A&s;&s;embly of the Deputies of <HI>Poland,</HI> was
purely contriv'd by the &s;ubtile Enemy, as may
partly appear by the fal&s;e Rumours &s;pread by
him, (<HI>viz.</HI>) that the King of <HI>Pru&s;&s;ia</HI> di&s;ponding
<PB N="159" REF="160">
of a Reconciliation between King <HI>Augu&s;tus,</HI> and
the <HI>Swedes,</HI> had embrac'd the Party of the King
of <HI>Sweden,</HI> and the elected Per&s;on; the fal&s;hood
of this imputation is manife&s;t by the Letter
&s;ent to the King of <HI>Pru&s;&s;ia</HI> by the Cardinal upon
this Account, and although the King of Pru&s;&s;ia be|ing
a neutural Prince in this War, has not been
adver&s;e to the Party of the <HI>Swedes;</HI> yet we are
a&s;&s;ur'd that he will not Recognize the elected
Per&s;on, in regard it would injure all crown'd
Heads, who in this World have none above them,
be&s;ides the Omnipotent Judge, who according
to his holy Will and Plea&s;ure depo&s;es Kings,
and places others in their room; &s;o that we
cannot imagine this dete&s;table Practice, which
is &s;o abhorr'd in the &s;ight of God can be
approved by Men; even, if not only a &s;mall
Number, but al&s;o all the Subjects &s;hould with|out
&s;ufficient Cau&s;e pre&s;ume to dethrone their
Prince in compliance with his Enemies de&s;ires;
for which Rea&s;on we are confident, that the
faid <HI>Univer&s;alia</HI> were publi&s;h'd by the Enemy,
who therein make mention of the de&s;olations
of the Country of <HI>Poland,</HI> and the depredations
committed upon the holy Churches and Lands;
but the Per&s;ons guilty thereof was not Named,
yet it was propos'd therein, to call a general
Diet to prevent &s;uch Grievances for the future,
and that the be&s;t expedient for that End would
be to confirm the illegal Choice of the <HI>Waywod</HI> of
<HI>Po&s;en,</HI> and to depend upon the Promi&s;es of the
King of <HI>Sweden,</HI> as though he were come into
<HI>Poland</HI> to pre&s;erve the violated Laws of the Re|publick;
we do verily believe that only &s;uch
as are blinded by Bribes, will give any Credit to
this cunning, dangerous and pernicious Deceit,
<PB N="160" REF="161">
the plundering the Towns and Ca&s;tles in <HI>Poland</HI>
and <HI>Lithuania</HI> of their Wealth, Ornaments, Am|munition
and Artillery; the Churches and Mo|na&s;tries
of the Relicts of Saints, their Orna|ments
and their very Bells; and the Oppre&s;&s;i|ons
of the Waywod&s;hips and other Lands by in|tollerable
Taxes exacted there, &s;how what a
Friend to <HI>Poland</HI> the <HI>Swede</HI> is, notwith&s;tanding
all his pretences that he is to come into <HI>Poland,</HI>
not to &s;eek his own Intere&s;t, but to Protect the
Republick, and by the a&s;&s;uming the Soveraign|ty
of <HI>Courland,</HI> and giving his General <HI>Lewen|haupt</HI>
the Title of Vice Governour of that
Country, it may be apprehended he will do
the like by &s;ome forfeited Towns in <HI>Pru&s;&s;ia:</HI>
The&s;e things con&s;ider'd again, we do declare
that we will defend our Brother and Allie King
<HI>Augu&s;tus</HI> to the utmo&s;t of our Power, by vertue
of our &s;olemn Alliances with that Prince, and
the Republick, and are for that End re&s;olv'd up|on
the Petition deliver'd to us in the Name of
the Republick to advance in Per&s;on with an
Army into <HI>Poland,</HI> without any regard to our
own Intere&s;t; and therefore we notify to all the
States of the Republick to forbear coming to
any Congre&s;s, or coming them&s;elves to &s;uch as
are A&s;&s;embled at <HI>War&s;aw,</HI> in favour of the
Elected, on pain of being puni&s;h'd in their Per|&s;ons
and Po&s;&s;e&s;&s;ions, with Fire and Sword; and
to prevent any Plea of Ignorance, we require
all Sons of their Native Country, after they
&s;hall have detected the Artifices of the Enemy,
to lay a&s;ide their private Animo&s;ities, and to joyn
unanimou&s;ly for their common good; and in or|der
thereunto to endeavour the expul&s;ion of the
enemy who has di&s;turb'd your Peace; we Pro|mi&s;e,
<PB N="161" REF="162">
on our Parole, that we will a&s;i&s;t you herein
as a faithful Allie, having no Preten&s;ions up|on
you. And we te&s;tify, before God, that we
are advanc'd with our Forces into the Lands of
the Republick, meerly upon pre&s;&s;ing Invitations
and Intreaties, and for the &s;ake of your Intere&s;t
only. And that we demand for the Sub&s;i&s;tance
of our Army, &s;uch Quantities of Bread as had
&s;tipulated in our Alliance with the Republick,
and that we will enjoin our Forces, on Pain of
Death, to commit no Di&s;orders in your Coun|try.
We heartily wi&s;h that you will be unani|mous,
and open your Eyes to your Welfare,
as the only Means to recover your Liberty.
We remain a Faithful Allie, and Affectionate
Friend.&endq;</P>
<P>THE King of <HI>Sweden,</HI> at this Time, was in no
Condition to meet &s;uch a Power, his Troops being
di&s;per&s;ed, and the King of <HI>Poland</HI> was him&s;elf in
<HI>Saxony,</HI> di&s;po&s;ing Things as his Circum&s;tances
would permit, to prevent the King of <HI>Sweden</HI>'s
falling into that Country. But his Army having
been defeated at the Battle of <HI>Frauen&s;tadt,</HI> it was
not po&s;&s;ible for him to rai&s;e another time enough
for the Work.</P>
<P>HOWEVER, the King hearing that his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI>
Maje&s;ty was arrived in <HI>Lithuania,</HI> went Incogni|to
from <HI>Saxony,</HI> and by his exceeding &s;wift Riding,
having prevented any De&s;ign to intercept him,
arriv'd at <HI>Tycockzin,</HI> where the <HI>Ru&s;&s;ian</HI> Army lay,
and there it was, that his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty let him,
&s;ee what an Army he had brought to &s;erve him.
The Sea&s;on of the Year not pre&s;enting any Op|portunity
of immediate Action, and &s;ome new
Di&s;orders having happen'd at <HI>Mo&s;cow,</HI> the <HI>Czar</HI>
<PB N="162" REF="163">
took a Re&s;olution to go away Po&s;t thither, which
he did, leaving Prince <HI>Alexander Menzickoff</HI> to
Command the <HI>Ru&s;&s;ian</HI> Army, with po&s;itive Di|rections
to obey the Orders of King <HI>Augu&s;tus</HI>
in all Things, as effectually as if it had been
his own.</P>
<P>HIS <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty, by his &s;udden coming
to <HI>Mo&s;cow,</HI> &s;urpriz'd his Enemies, as he had done
more than once before, and having made &s;ome
Examples of Ju&s;tice, and put to Death the prin|cipal
Authors of the Trea&s;on, he &s;oon return'd to
the Frontiers.</P>
<P>BUT I &s;hould have taken Notice that his
<HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty, before he came into <HI>Lithuania</HI>
with this Army, had been pre&s;ent at the taking
the Town of <HI>Mittau,</HI> the Capital of <HI>Courland.</HI>
The <HI>Swedes</HI> pretended that his Troops had receiv'd
a Defeat at their fir&s;t Enterance into <HI>Courland,</HI> a
Body of 7000 <HI>Swedes</HI> under General <HI>Lewenhaupt</HI> ha|ving
attack'd them with great Vigour, and yet,
even in this Action, the <HI>Ru&s;&s;ians</HI> behav'd &s;o well,
that in the Accounts which the <HI>Swedes</HI> them&s;elves
publi&s;h'd of the Action, they have this Expre&s;|&s;ion;
the <HI>Mu&s;covite</HI> Foot were cut down in Rank
and File, as they &s;tood, for tho' they faw the
Hor&s;e broken, yet not a Man of them would
&s;tir from their Po&s;t, tho' &s;urrounded by the
Enemy.</P>
<P>BUT this Victory, as the <HI>Swedes</HI> would call it,
was far from an Overthrow, and far from reliev|ing
their Cau&s;e; for about three Days after the
Battle, the <HI>Czar</HI> advanc'd with his whole Army,
and &s;urpriz'd, as I ob&s;erved above, and took
<HI>Mittau,</HI> with 900 <HI>Swedes</HI> in it Pri&s;oners of War,
with a great Magazine of Military Stores and Pro|vi&s;ion
laid up there by the <HI>Swedes,</HI> which, as was
<PB N="163" REF="164">
well ob&s;erv'd by the Writers of tho&s;e Times,
was but a very indifferent Token of their having
been beaten in a Set Battle, and 7000 of them
killed upon the Spot.</P>
<P>Nor was this all, but immediately after this Bat|tle,
I might have &s;aid this Victory, for &s;uch, in|deed
it was to the <HI>Ru&s;&s;ians.</HI> General <HI>Lewenhaupt</HI>
retired out of the Country, and the <HI>Mu&s;covite</HI>
General, Prince <HI>Czeremettoff,</HI> cau&s;ed the City of
<HI>Riga</HI> to be be&s;ieged in Form, which for want of
Relief, was al&s;o taken about 2 Months after, the
Garri&s;on having been reduced to the la&s;t Extre|mity.</P>
<P>IT is hard to come at the Journals of the&s;e
Sieges, no particular Account of them having
been pnbli&s;h'd in the World, but this may Sum
up that Part; that while the King of <HI>Sweden</HI> went on pu&s;hing King <HI>Augu&s;tus</HI> with an implaca|ble
Rage out of his Kingdom, his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty
over-run all the <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> Dominions, on the South
Side of the Gulph of <HI>Finland,</HI> and even the
Dutchy <HI>Courland</HI> it &s;elf; this would have been
called a Diver&s;ion in King <HI>Augu&s;tus</HI>'s Favour, in
any Place in the World, but here; perhaps to any
Prince in the World, but to the King of <HI>Sweden</HI> it
would have been &s;o: For, who could have
&s;uppos'd, that any Prince like this, would have
pu&s;h'd on a remote Conque&s;t, in which his own
proper Dominions were &s;o little concerned, and
for the meer Satisfaction, or if you will, for the
Glory of pulling down a King, who he had already
&s;ufficiently reduced; and at the &s;ame Time, &s;uf|fer
his own Hereditary Dominions to be torn from
him, his mi&s;erable Subjects ruined and ravaged
without Succour; his &s;trong and mo&s;t Important
Towns taken from him, without relieving them;
<PB N="164" REF="165">
and his Brave Troops be beaten for want of Rein|forcement.</P>
<P>HE that can do thus, may indeed &s;ay that no
Expedition of his Enemies, by way of Diver&s;ion,
can be a Relief to tho&s;e he pu&s;hes with Revenge.
'Tis evident here, that the King of <HI>Sweden</HI> could
not be &s;aid to fight for Peace, but for Revenge and
Glory. For, it is evident, he might have glo|ried
in making Peace, both with <HI>Poland,</HI> and the
<HI>Czar</HI> of <HI>Mu&s;covy</HI> al&s;o, upon very Honourable Con|ditions.
But nothing would &s;erve him but redu|cing
and dethroning the One; after which, he
grew &s;o opinionate, that he fancy'd he could do
the like by the <HI>Czar</HI> of <HI>Mu&s;covy;</HI> Nay, and his
Mini&s;ters gave it openly out, that he had re&s;ol|ved
to do it: And had Heaven &s;uffer'd him to
have carry'd on his Victory that Length, 'tis not
doubted but he would have depo&s;ed all the Kings
of the Earth, if it had been in his Power.</P>
<P>BUT we mu&s;t not anticipate our Relation of
Things, we &s;hall in the Cour&s;e of this Hi&s;tory,
bring his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty and the King of <HI>Sweden</HI>
nearer together in the War, than we have done
yet, in order to this, we &s;hall begin with what
his Troops did in <HI>Poland,</HI> before the <HI>Czar</HI> came to
act in Per&s;on.</P>
<P>THE <HI>Czar,</HI> as I have &s;aid, had left the War in
<HI>Livonia</HI> to the Prince <HI>Czeremetoff,</HI> who managed
it with &s;uch Succe&s;s, that he beat the <HI>Swedes</HI> upon
all Occa&s;ions, and at la&s;t compleated the Conque&s;t
of <HI>Livonia,</HI> by taking the Towns of <HI>Riga, Pernau,
R$vel,</HI> and <HI>Neyen,</HI> with all the other Towns and
Forts of any Strength; Po&s;ted a &s;trong Body of
Troops in <HI>Courland,</HI> to Cover <HI>Livonia</HI> from the Re|turn
of the <HI>Swedes,</HI> and then followed his Ma&s;ter,
the <HI>Czar&punc;</HI> into <HI>Lithuania.</HI></P>
<P><PB N="165" REF="166">
HIS <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty's Troops in <HI>Livonia</HI> had
block'd up <HI>Riga,</HI> the <HI>Dunamund</HI> Schans was almo&s;t
ruined by a Di&s;a&s;ter of Fire, which taking hold
of the Powder in the Magazein, blew it all up
with a terrible Noi&s;e, 300 of the <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> Garri&s;on
peri&s;hing in the Bla&s;t. This Accident caus'd the
<HI>Ru&s;&s;ian</HI> General <HI>Baver,</HI> who Commanded at <HI>Mit|tau,</HI>
to advance towards <HI>Riga</HI> with 3000 Men, to
&s;ee if he could make any Advantage of that Acci|dent,
but the Fate of that Place was not yet come.</P>
<P>WE are to under&s;tand now, that a great Coun|cil
of State had been a&s;&s;embled by King <HI>Augu&s;tus</HI>
at <HI>Grodno,</HI> in <HI>Lithuania&punc;</HI> where the King met &s;them,
and where they declar'd King <HI>Stani&s;taus</HI> a Traytor
and U&s;urper, and agreed to a&s;&s;i&s;t King <HI>Augu&s;tus</HI>
with the whole Army of the Crown, which was
to be made up to 36000 Men, and to furni&s;h Mo|ney
for their Payment.</P>
<P>THIS nettled <HI>Stani&s;taus,</HI> and he flies to the
King of <HI>Sweden</HI> for Help, who drawing his Forces
together, pretended to march to attack King <HI>Au|gu&s;tus</HI>
and his Army, at <HI>Tycockzin:</HI> But when he
found that the <HI>Ru&s;&s;ian</HI> Forces had join'd with him,
he thought better of it, and marched back, not
thinking it fit to venture his Army. The Parti|culars
of this fruitle&s;s Attempt, was thus related
from the very Place, by a Per&s;on who was an Eye
Witne&s;s of it all.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2>
<HEAD>GRODNO, <DATE>Decemb. 31, 1705.</DATE></HEAD>
<P>&startq;THE King of <HI>Sweden</HI> having decamp'd from
<HI>Bloni$,</HI> pa&s;&s;ed the <HI>Vi&s;tula</HI> with all his Forces the
28th In&s;tant, on the Bridge of Boats; and from
thence continued his March with all Expedition
to attack the <HI>Mu&s;covites</HI> at <HI>Grodno</HI> and <HI>Tycockzin,</HI>
the latter had &s;ecured the Bridges on the River
<PB N="166" REF="167">
<HI>Bug.</HI> But the <HI>Swedes</HI> being favour'd by the great
Fro&s;t, they pa&s;s'd that River with all their Ar|tilery
over the Ice. The <HI>Mu&s;covites</HI> upon Ad|vice
of his Approach, left 3000 Men in that
Place, under the Command of Lieutenant
General <HI>Ronne,</HI> with Orders to defend it to the
la&s;t Extremity, and march'd with the re&s;t of
their Forces, quartered in tho&s;e Parts, to join
the King of <HI>Poland</HI> at <HI>Grodno.</HI> That Prince
receiv'd Advice the 30&s;t, that the <HI>Swedes</HI> having
not thought fit to attack <HI>Tycockzin,</HI> were in a full
March towards <HI>Grodno,</HI> and were already ad|vanc'd
within 10 Leagues of his Camp; whereon
he held the 22d. a Council of War, with all the
<HI>Poli&s;h, Saxon,</HI> and <HI>Mu&s;covite</HI> Generals; wherein
it was re&s;olv'd, that the Army &s;hould continue
near <HI>Grodno,</HI> and expect the <HI>Swedes</HI> in Order of
Battle; and that to render the Approaches to
their Camp the more difficult, a con&s;iderable
Body of Troops were po&s;ted in a Wood, to &s;ecure a
De&s;ile through which the <HI>Swedes</HI> would be oblig'd
to pa&s;s: They &s;ettled likewi&s;e in that Council
the Rank of the General Officers; the Right of
the Army was given to Velt Mare&s;chal <HI>Ogliby;</HI>
and the Left to General <HI>Allard;</HI> and the Body
of the Battle was commanded by the <HI>Mu&s;covite</HI>
Prince <HI>Menzickoff;</HI> all under the Orders and
Direction of the King of <HI>Poland.</HI> This was the
Po&s;ture of Affairs in <HI>Lithuania</HI> the 23d pa&s;t,
when the la&s;t Letters came away. But a Gen|tleman
of the King of <HI>Polands,</HI> who is ju&s;t now
arriv'd from thence, and who left the Court of
that Prince the 31ft, reports, that the King of
<HI>Sweden</HI> being advanc'd in Sight of the <HI>Mu&s;|covite</HI>
Army, and finding the &s;ame advantagi|cu&s;ly
po&s;ted; he did not think fit to attack the
<PB N="167" REF="168">
King of <HI>Poland:</HI> And continu'd his March to|wards
<HI>Wilna;</HI> his <HI>Poli&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty held thereupon
another Council of War, and according to the
Re&s;olutions taken therein. He march'd imme|diately
after, with a Detatchment of 3000 Hor&s;e
directly towards <HI>War&s;aw,</HI> and was arriv'd at
<HI>Fokzen,</HI> in his way thither, when this Gentle|man
was di&s;patched away; he adds, that Prince
<HI>Menzickoff</HI> is &s;ent for <HI>Mo&s;cow,</HI> by expre&s;s Or|ders
of his Ma&s;ter, and has left the Command
of the <HI>Mu&s;covite</HI> Army to Velt Mar&s;hal <HI>Ogliby;</HI>
the King of <HI>Poland</HI> endeavoured to fall upon
the Rear of the <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> Army, and a 1000 Dra|goons
commanded by Major General <HI>Henke</HI> fell
upon their Baggage, and took 40 Waggons;
the Sieur <HI>Smigiel&s;ki</HI> with his <HI>Poles,</HI> had al&s;o a
Skirmi&s;h with them, and took 3 Lieutenants,
with 50 Soldiers, be&s;ides the Secretary of <HI>Stani&s;|laus.</HI>&endq;</P>
<P>I have mention'd that his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty ha|ving
an Occa&s;ion to make a Tour to <HI>Mo&s;cow,</HI> left
his Troops in <HI>Lithuania</HI> with po&s;itive Orders to
obey the King of <HI>Poland,</HI> and the above Relation
will &s;how a little how they behaved: But this
is not all, for I mu&s;t new add that the King of
<HI>Poland</HI> led them the Path to Glory; taking a
&s;trong Body of them with him, to the great Bat|tle
of <HI>Kali&s;h</HI> in <HI>Po&s;nania,</HI> which follow'd &s;oon after
the la&s;t recited Action.</P>
<P>IT mu&s;t be ob&s;erv'd here that the King of
<HI>Sweden,</HI> finding he could not weary out, or di&s;|courage
his Indefatigable Enemy the King of
<HI>Poland;</HI> but if he was beaten in one Place he re|vived
in another, and that the Confederated <HI>Pa|latinates</HI>
in the South of <HI>Poland,</HI> who form'd the
A&s;&s;embly of <HI>Sendomir,</HI> continu'd to Supply him
<PB N="168" REF="169">
with Money, and Troops, and particularly the
famous <HI>Smegiel&s;ki,</HI> and above all the <HI>Czar</HI> of <HI>Mu&s;|covy</HI>
in Per&s;on, who&s;e Army having entered <HI>Li|thuania,</HI>
had appear'd too &s;trong to be attack'd, as
above, and had another Army ready to a&s;&s;i&s;t his
<HI>Poli&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty, lying on the Frontiers of <HI>Sendo|mir,</HI>
12000 of which had actually joyn'd him, and
that be&s;ides this, he receiv'd daily great Succours
out of <HI>Saxony:</HI> I &s;ay, the King of <HI>Sweden</HI> finding
this, re&s;olv'd upon the only effectual way he had
left to reduce the King of <HI>Poland;</HI> and this was
to enter the Electorate of <HI>Saxony</HI> with his whole
Army: The King of <HI>Poland</HI> had been aware of
this &s;ome time, and had both written to the
States of <HI>Saxony</HI> to put them&s;elves into a po&s;ture
of Defence, and had gone thither him&s;elf to &s;ee
it effectually done, but the <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> General <HI>Rhen&s;|child</HI>
having routed the <HI>Saxon</HI> Army at <HI>Fruaen&s;tat,</HI>
and the Country, by that means being quite
naked of Defence, the <HI>Swedes</HI> enter'd at once,
without re&s;i&s;tance.</P>
<P>THIS immediately brought the King of <HI>Po|land</HI>
to Terms; his <HI>Poli&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty like a true Fa|ther
of his Country, could not &s;top his Ears to the
Cries of his People, as the King of <HI>Sweden</HI> had
done to tho&s;e of his mi&s;erable Subjects in <HI>Livo|nia,
Ingria</HI> and <HI>Finland;</HI> if I may &s;uppo&s;e he
heard tho&s;e Cries, for &s;ome People &s;ugge&s;ted that
Court <HI>Piper,</HI> General <HI>Steenboch,</HI> and tho&s;e Men
who managed Affairs for the Prince, conceal'd
from him the Mi&s;eries of his People: If it be
true, that they did &s;o, no doubt but the Ruin of
his Country, and the Blood of its Inhabitants lye
at their Door, &s;eeing by a ju&s;t and honourable
Peace it might have been all prevented.</P>
<P><PB N="169" REF="170">
BUT to return to the Hi&s;tory of Fact, the King
of <HI>Sweden</HI> having enter'd the <HI>Electorate</HI> of <HI>Saxony</HI>
contrary to the Repre&s;entations made by the Mi|ni&s;ters,
of the Queen of <HI>Great Britain,</HI> the States Ge|neral
of the united Provinces, and &s;everal other
Potentates, who all pre&s;s'd him not to make &s;uch
a Breach upon the Peace of the Empire, and
would no doubt in time have join'd to have dri|ven
him out again, the King of <HI>Poland</HI> was at the
Entreaty of his States of <HI>Saxony,</HI> brought to
name Plenipotentiaries for a Treaty, and this
Treaty was actually carrying on; but while the&s;e
Agents were hammering at a Peace, the Armies
in <HI>Poland</HI> having made no Ce&s;&s;ation of Arms, act|ed
on every Side as u&s;ual, and the <HI>Swedes,</HI> that
the King of <HI>Poland</HI> might not have an opportuni|ty
to follow them into <HI>Saxony,</HI> had po&s;t'd Major,
General <HI>Mardevelt</HI> with an Army of about 25000
Men, <HI>Lithuanians, Poles</HI> and <HI>Swedes,</HI> at <HI>Kali&s;h,</HI> in
the Le&s;&s;er <HI>Poland,</HI> as it were directly in the way
to <HI>Saxony.</HI></P>
<P>HIS <HI>Poli&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty re&s;olving to re&s;cue his own
Dominions whatever it co&s;t him, found it ab&s;o|lutely
nece&s;&s;ary to fight this Army in the fir&s;t
Place, and having now the Support of a power|ful
Army from his faithful Alie the <HI>Czar</HI> of
<HI>Mu&s;covy,</HI> he re&s;olv'd upon the attempt, and there|upon,
call'd a great Council of War, at which
were pre&s;ent the <HI>Ru&s;&s;ian</HI> General Prince <HI>Menzic|koff,</HI>
and &s;everal of the <HI>Poli&s;h</HI> Nobility that were
in his <HI>Poli&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty's Intere&s;t, who all agreed to
what the King of <HI>Poland</HI> had re&s;olv'd (<HI>viz.</HI>) to
Fight; what followed upon this, will be be&s;t un|der&s;tood
by the following Account, written up|on
the Spot where the Action was perform'd.</P>
<P><PB N="170" REF="171">
&startq;IT having been re&s;olved in a Council of War,
held by his Maje&s;ty at <HI>Peterkan,</HI> that the Army
Should continue their March in que&s;t of the
Enemy; the two Mare&s;chals of the Crown,
and General <HI>Brod</HI> were detach'd the 22d In|&s;tant,
with 8000 Men; and the 23d his Maje|&s;ty
and Prince <HI>Alexander Menzickoff</HI> followed
with the main Body. The 26th, the two Bodies
join'd near <HI>Szat,</HI> two Leagues from <HI>Kali&s;h,</HI>
with a Re&s;olution to expect us; thereupon his
Maje&s;ty went to take a narrow View of them,
and cau&s;ed immediately the <HI>Calmuck Tartars,</HI>
and <HI>Co&s;&s;acks,</HI> to advance under the Cannon of
<HI>Kali&s;h,</HI> to that &s;everal Skirmi&s;hes happen'd be|tween
them and the Enemy. The 28th, the
whole Army advanced within a &s;mall League
of that of the Enemy commanded by General
<HI>Mardevelt;</HI> but having &s;everal Defiles, and a
Bridge to pa&s;s before he could get at them,
his Maje&s;ty employ'd the remaining part of
that Day, in making the nece&s;&s;ary Di&s;po&s;itions
for attacking them the next, with the utmo&s;t Vi|gour.
The 29th, his Maje&s;ty march'd directly
towards the Enemy in Order of Battle, and
finding their Army drawn up likewi&s;e, behind
an Eminence, about Three in the Afternoon
gave the Signal for the Attack, by three Can|non
Shot; the Enemy an&s;wer'd by two Shots,
and came down into the Plain with their whole
Army, having intermix'd their Squadrons with
their Batallions; their Right Wing being com|pos'd
of Poli&s;h Troops, was commanded by the
Sieur <HI>Potocki,</HI> Palatine of <HI>Kiow;</HI> their Left con|&s;i&s;ting
of <HI>Lethuanians,</HI> had Prince <HI>Sapieha</HI> at
their Head; their Center was commanded by
the Swedi&s;h General <HI>Mardevelt;</HI> and the
<PB N="171" REF="172">
whole Army was cover'd with two deep Mo|ra&s;&s;es,
the Town of <HI>Kali&s;h,</HI> and a good Baracade
of Waggons; in&s;omuch, that the De&s;ign of at|tacking
them, &s;eem'd to be attended with al|mo&s;t
in&s;uperable Difficulties; notwith&s;tanding
which, King <HI>Augu&s;tus</HI> per&s;i&s;ted in his Re&s;olution.
In order to put the &s;ame in execution, his Ma|je&s;ty
form'd the Center, and the two Wings of
his Army, and divided his <HI>Saxon</HI> and <HI>Mu&s;covite</HI>
Troops; be&s;ides which, there were two Bodies
of Re&s;erve of the <HI>Poli&s;h</HI> Forces, commanded by
the two Generals of the Crown; his Maje&s;ty
took the Command of the Left Wing upon him|&s;elf;
gave that of the Right to Prince <HI>Alexander
Menzickoff;</HI> and the Center to General <HI>Brand,</HI> or
<HI>Brod.</HI> The Ingagement began between three and
four a Clock, and his Maje&s;ty's Troops fought
with &s;o much Vigour, that the Enemy's Right
Wing was &s;oon overthrown, and driven within
the Baracade of Waggons they had near the Town
of <HI>Kali&s;h,</HI> but the re&s;t of their Army defended
them&s;elves with great ob&s;tinacy till fix at
Night; his Maje&s;ty, during the whole Action,
expos'd him&s;elf where the Fire was greate&s;t, and
charg'd the Enemy &s;everal Times in Per&s;o$,
with his Hor&s;e Guards, and &s;everal other Squa|drons;
but his Maje&s;ty having no Foot, his
Hor&s;e &s;uffer'd much by the continual Fire of
the Enemy's Infantry, and particularly of the
<HI>French</HI> Troops, and others, who, in the Action
at <HI>Frawen&s;tadt,</HI> flung down their Arms, and
went over to the <HI>Swedes.</HI> Neverthele&s;s, the
Enermy was pu&s;h'd with the utmo&s;t Vigour, and,
by the Ble&s;&s;ing of God, we obtain'd a compleat
and &s;ignal Victory over them. Their Forces,
before the Battle, con&s;i&s;ted of 10000 <HI>Swedes,</HI> and
<PB N="172" REF="173">
15000 <HI>Poles</HI> and <HI>Lithuanians;</HI> and ours of 7000
<HI>Poles,</HI> 5000 <HI>Saxons,</HI> 9000 <HI>Mu&s;covites,</HI> and &s;ome
Thou&s;ands of <HI>Tarters,</HI> or <HI>Calmuck Co&s;&s;acks;</HI> &s;o
that the two Armies were, almo&s;t of equal
Strength; mo&s;t of the <HI>Sweeds</HI> were kill'd in
the Field of Battle; twenty <HI>Poli&s;h</HI> Companies
of their Party, came over to us during the
Action; and the next Morning, &s;ome Thou&s;and
<HI>Poles,</HI> who were retired within the Barricades of
Waggons, were likewi&s;e oblig'd to yield them|&s;elves
Pri&s;oners of War; among the latter,
were the Sieur <HI>Patocki,</HI> Palatine of <HI>Kiow,</HI> his
Lady and all her Children; Sieur <HI>Tarlo,</HI> Ma&s;ter
Cook of the Crown; and &s;everal other Per&s;ons of
Note; who were all di&s;arm'd, and their Hor&s;es
taken, as were al&s;o 10000 Waggons that made
up their Barricade: The <HI>Sweeds</HI> had left their
Baggage at <HI>Kali&s;h,</HI> under a Guard of 300 Men,
and after the Action, 500 Hor&s;e e&s;caped thither,
but they were all afterwards obliged to &s;ur|render
at Di&s;cretion. However, his Maje&s;ty
was &s;o generous, as to re&s;tore the Baggage to
the Officers. All the Enemy's Artillery and
Ammunition was taken. The <HI>Saxon</HI> Cavalry
took 19 Standards and Colours from the <HI>Swedes,</HI>
44 from the <HI>Poles,</HI> and 4 Pair of Kettle Drums;
the re&s;t were taken by the <HI>Poles</HI> in our Army,
and the <HI>Mu&s;covites.</HI> This Victory is &s;o com|pleat,
that 'tis believ'd, not above 2000 of the
Enemy e&s;cap'd. All the Troops, as well <HI>Poles,</HI>
and <HI>Saxons,</HI> as <HI>Mu&s;covites,</HI> behaved them&s;elves
in this Action, with great Courage and Intripi|dity;
and all their re&s;pective Generals &s;igna|liz'd
them&s;elves in Emulation of each other.
Our Lo&s;s is very incon&s;iderable, for we had
only one Officer of Note kill'd, <HI>viz.</HI> Colonel
<PB N="173" REF="174">
<HI>Guer&s;dorf;</HI> this Victory is the more remarka|ble,
becau&s;e his <HI>Poli&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty's Troops had
undergone great Fatiegues, by their continual
Marches and Countermarches, during the
Campaign; whereas the Enemy's had been a
long time in Quarters of Refre&s;hment.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;HERE follows a Li&s;t of the Pri&s;oners taken
from the <HI>Swedes,</HI> both in the Field of Battle,
and in the Town of <HI>Kali&s;h,</HI> be&s;ides the <HI>Poles</HI>
that were taken the next Day, in the foremen|tion'd
Brigade of Waggons, <HI>viz.</HI> General <HI>Mar|dervelt,</HI>
who commanded in Chief; 4 Colo|nels,
<HI>viz. Mar&s;chal, Muller, Horn</HI> of the Foot,
<HI>Horn</HI> of the Hor&s;e, 5 Lieutenant Colonels, <HI>viz.
Guilden&s;tern, Raad, Horn, I&s;&s;endorff,</HI> and <HI>Mu|mand;</HI>
4 Majors, to wit, <HI>Bornfold, Openba&s;ch,
Schelling,</HI> and <HI>Rur&s;t;</HI> 27 Captains of Foot, and
4 of Hor&s;e, 39 Lieutenants, 21 En&s;igns, 4
Adjutants, 294 Subaltern Officers, 1600 Sol|diers,
making in all 2007 Pri&s;oners taken in
the Battle, tho&s;e taken in the Town of <HI>Kali&s;h,</HI>
are, 1 Major, 1 Captain of Hor&s;e, 16 Captains of
Foot, 19 Lieutenants, 15 Cornets, 6 En&s;igns,
4 Mini&s;ters, 18 Subaltern Officers, and 800
Soldiers, in all 894 Pri&s;oners; which with
tho&s;e taken in the Battle, amount to 2901.
We had 806 <HI>Germans</HI> and <HI>Saxons</HI> kill'd, and 800
wounded.&endq;</P>
<P>THE great Share his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty's
Troops had in this Victory, was acknowledg'd by
King <HI>Augu&s;tus</HI> him&s;elf, till he found it nece&s;&s;ary
for Rea&s;ons of State to Cancel all the Obligations
which he ow'd to his Supporters, and Con&s;equent|ly
to le&s;&s;en the Merit of the Support, which they
had given him; but as he own'd to have in his
<PB N="174" REF="175">
Army 9000 <HI>Mu&s;covite</HI> Soldiers, I mean Regular
Troops under Prince <HI>Menzickoff;</HI> &s;o 'tis known&punc;
he had ol&s;o as many <HI>Co&s;&s;acks</HI> and <HI>Circa&s;&s;ians</HI> of his
<HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty's Subjects, who in their way did
him very good Service on that occa&s;ion.</P>
<P>BUT now we come to the Tran&s;actions of King
<HI>Augu&s;tus</HI>'s Life, which are the meane&s;t part of his
Hi&s;tory, Namely, that of abandoning the Crown
of <HI>Poland,</HI> quitting his Alliance with the <HI>Czar</HI> of <HI>Mu&s;+covy,</HI>
who had never for&s;aken him in his greate&s;t
Di&s;tre&s;s, and yielding to the lowe&s;t Steps, which
his in&s;ulting Enemies could put upon him.</P>
<P>IT mu&s;t be confe&s;t that the Plenipotentiaries
on either Side, had &s;ign'd the Treaty at <HI>Alt Ran|&s;tadt,</HI>
nay, the Peace was concluded and &s;ign'd
four Days before the Battle of <HI>Kali&s;h</HI> was fought;
otherwi&s;e, perhaps King <HI>Augu&s;tus</HI> would have
ventur'd with his victorious Army to have march'd
directly again&s;t the <HI>Swedes,</HI> who tho' they were
indeed in po&s;&s;e&s;&s;ion of the open Country of the
<HI>Electorate,</HI> yet had no fortify'd Place in their Hands,
nor above 15 or 16000 Men in their Army, where|as
the King of <HI>Poland</HI> could in le&s;s than 12 Days
have had 60000 Men in his Army, be&s;ides what
Troops he had in <HI>Saxony.</HI></P>
<P>BUT it was too late, and King <HI>Augu&s;tus</HI> made
it a point of Honour to &s;tand to the Agreement
his Plenipotentiaries had made, however di&s;hon|ourable
it might be; &s;o he laid down his Arms at
once, and gave up the Kingdom of <HI>Poland,</HI> and all
his Friend, and Intere&s;t there to the Mercy of a Mer|cenary,
who the <HI>Poles</HI> di&s;pis'd mo&s;t heartily, tho'
many of them were oblig'd to call him King, and
this was the Condition of things when his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI>
Maje&s;ty return'd to his Army in <HI>Lithuania.</HI></P>
<P><PB N="175" REF="176">
BUT this no way di&s;courag'd the <HI>Czar,</HI> he re|&s;olv'd
to Support the Party that had &s;tood for the
Liberty of their Country again&s;t the <HI>Swedes,</HI> and
to this purpo&s;e he publi&s;h'd a Declaration, or
Memorial to the <HI>Poli&s;h</HI> Nobility, and having re|ceiv'd
a formal Notification of the Treaty con|cluded
by King <HI>Augu&s;tus</HI> with the King of <HI>Swe|den,</HI>
he wrote Letters to the General of the
Crown, the Primate of the Kingdom, and other
Grandees, who were in the Party of King <HI>Au|gu&s;tus,</HI>
to repre&s;ent to them, That he concluded an
&startq;Alliance with the Republick, and not in parti|cular
with <HI>Augu&s;tus,</HI> and that he was re&s;olved
to perform all the Articles thereof, of a&s;&s;i&s;t
the Republick with all his Forces again&s;t the
<HI>Swedes,</HI> who being not &s;atisfy'd with having oblig'd
King <HI>Augu&s;tus</HI> to adicate his Crown, would im|po&s;e
a King of their own Election upon them.
His <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty promi&s;es therein to repair
&s;hortly to <HI>Lemberg</HI> to concert Mea&s;ures with
the Republick, and in the mean time to &s;end &s;uch
an Army as will be &s;ufficient to enable the <HI>Poles</HI>
to vindicate their indpendency; the Primate
having held a great Council with the Officers of
the Crown, has appointed a great Council to
meet at <HI>Lembergh</HI> the 17th of the next Month,
and has declared the Throne vacant, bidding
all the <HI>Poles</HI> to acknowledge the <HI>Palatine</HI> of <HI>Po|zen,</HI>
under the Name of <HI>Stani&s;laus,</HI> the Primate
al&s;o has written to the Emperor, the Queen of
<HI>England,</HI> the Kings of <HI>Denmark,</HI> and <HI>Pru&s;&s;ia,</HI> the
States General, the Pope and other Potentates,
to acquaint them with the vacancy of the Throne.
The General of the Crown, has al&s;o publi&s;hed
univer&s;alia, forbidding the Forces of the Re|publick
to receive any Orders from King <HI>Au|gu&s;tus,</HI>
<PB N="176" REF="177">
or King <HI>Stani&s;laus,</HI> and promi&s;ing a re|ward
of 5000 Rixdollars to &s;uch who &s;hall de|liver
up alive the Sieur <HI>Smigiel&s;ki,</HI> or 2000 to
&s;uch who &s;hall deliver him dead; that Gentle|man
has lately embrac'd the Party of King
<HI>Stani&s;laus,</HI> and &s;et at Liberty the Weywood of
<HI>Kali&s;h,</HI> which has &s;o provoked Prince <HI>Menzic|koff,</HI>
that he has caus'd him to be hang'd in Ef|figie.&endq;</P>
<P>IN pur&s;uit of the&s;e Re&s;olutions, his Maje&s;ty
came in Per&s;on to <HI>Zolkiew</HI> in <HI>Poland,</HI> the 11th of
<HI>January,</HI> 1707. And being inform'd by his Mi|ni&s;ters
&startq;of what had pa&s;s'd during his Ab&s;ence;
he order'd them to write to all the Generals of
the Army, and of the Crown, and to the Sena|tors
to invite them to repair to him, he al&s;o or|der'd
univer&s;aly in his own Name to be print|ed
for confirming tho&s;e already publi&s;h'd by
his Mini&s;ters; the 9th he went to Church attended
by Prince <HI>Menzickoff,</HI> and other Officers and
Generals, and afterwards Din'd in Publick;
the 10th and 11th were &s;pent in Conferences a|bout
the di&s;po&s;ing of the Army, and in &s;ending
private Di&s;patches to divers foreign Courts.&endq;</P>
<P>PURSUANT to this Summons of the <HI>Czar</HI> of
<HI>Mu&s;covy,</HI> the 7th of <HI>February</HI> the great A&s;&s;embly
of Senators, Generals and great Officers, that
is to &s;ay, the <HI>Poli&s;h</HI> Nobility met together at
<HI>Lemberg,</HI> there to con&s;ult with his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje|&s;ty
what was to be done in the pre&s;ent Con|juncture:
This Grand Council, for &s;uch they were
call'd, open'd their fir&s;t Se&s;&s;ion, by going in
formal Proce&s;&s;ion to Church to implore the Ble&s;|&s;ing
of Heaven on their Proceedings, then they
repair'd to the Hall of Council, where &s;everal
Pathetic Speeches were made to explain to one
<PB N="177" REF="178">
Author the Rea&s;on of their A&s;&s;embly, and re|pre&s;ent
the pre&s;ent State of their Country, all
of them concurring to declare the Throne vacant.</P>
<P>&startq;AFTER the&s;e things they renew'd the Confe|deracy
of <HI>Sendomir,</HI> as the mo&s;t effectual Means,
to put them&s;elves in a Condition to a&s;&s;ert their
Liberties; they &s;eem'd very unanimous in their
Resolutions; but had not yet taken any Mea|&s;ures
for a new Election. And King <HI>Augu&s;tus</HI>
having not notify'd unto them his Renuncia|tion
of the Crown; the A&s;&s;embly &s;eem'd to act
rather, as if their King was Pri&s;oner among&s;t
his Enemies, or ab&s;ent, than if the Throne
were Vacant. Prince <HI>Dolhorucki,</HI> Chief Mini|&s;ter
of State to the <HI>Czar,</HI> had then his fir&s;t
publick Audience of the Council, to which
he was conducted by one of the Chief Officers
of the Crown, with 7 Coaches, and a Detach|ment
of the Cavalry of the General of the
Crown; he was placed in the Congre&s;s, be|tween
the two chief Mini&s;ters of the Repub|lick;
and delivered a Letter to the A&s;&s;embly
from the <HI>Czar,</HI> and then made a Speech in the
<HI>Poli&s;h</HI> Language, importing, That notwith|&s;tanding
the Republick &s;eem'd reduced to the
la&s;t Extremities, by the Retreat of King <HI>Au|gu&s;tus,</HI>
yet, they were &s;till in a Condition, to
retrieve their Affairs and Glory, if they would
concur in the Mea&s;ures that &s;hould be propo&s;ed
unto them on the Part of the <HI>Czar,</HI> a faithful
Ally of <HI>Poland;</HI> whom no private Advantage
what&s;oever, that may be propo&s;ed unto him,
&s;hall be able to &s;eparate from the Intere&s;t of
the Republick; Concluding with a pathetical
Exhortation, to take vigorous Mea&s;ures again&s;t
their Common Enemy; and a&s;&s;uring them that
<PB N="178" REF="179">
the <HI>Czar</HI> would re&s;tore to the Republick, the
Places in the <HI>Ukraine,</HI> that formerly belonged
to <HI>Poland,</HI> and furni&s;h the Sums he had <HI>belonged
fed</HI> for paying of the Army of the Crown.&endq;
The Primate of the Kingdom An&s;wered, in the
Name of the Republick; &startq;And having return'd
Thanks to the <HI>Czar</HI> for his Affection and Friend|&s;hip,
he a&s;&s;ured his Mini&s;ter that the Council
would not &s;eparate 'till they had taken &s;uch Re|&s;olutions,
as the Glory of their Nation, and
the di&s;tre&s;&s;ed Conditon of their Country re|quired
from them. Then Prince <HI>Dolhorucki</HI> was
conducted back to his Hou&s;e with the &s;ame Cere|mony:
The 19th his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty with his el|de&s;t
Son Prince <HI>Alexander,</HI> Prince <HI>Menzickoff,</HI> and
&s;ome other Per&s;ons of Note arrived there from
<HI>Zolkiew;</HI> he was Complimented upon his arrival
by the Primate, and other Grandees, and nob|ly
entertain'd by the General of the Crown;
the 20th that Prince a&s;&s;i&s;ted at the Ceremony
of the Con&s;ecration of the Bi&s;hop of <HI>Cujavia</HI>
perform'd in the Cathedral, and pre&s;ented that
Prelate with a Crucifix, valued, at 15000 Rix-dollars;
the 21&s;t, there was a long Conference
between the Mini&s;ters of that Prince, and the
Council of <HI>Poland;</HI> but the Re&s;olutions taken
therein were kept very private: His Maje&s;ty
with the Prince and Mini&s;ters, &s;et out the next
day to return to <HI>Zolkiew,</HI> and Prince <HI>Dolhoureki,</HI>
continued there as his Plenipotentiary, the
Count <HI>de Denhoff,</HI> Governour of <HI>Crawcow</HI> or|dered
the Fortification of that place to be aug|mented
with all po&s;&s;ible &s;peed, and has in con|cert
with the <HI>Czar,</HI> order'd the Neighbouring
Di&s;tricts to furni&s;h without delay a quantity of
<PB N="179" REF="180">
Forage, and Corn it being re&s;olved to make a
great Magazine in that City.&endq;</P>
<P>The following Letter was al&s;o written by the
<HI>Czar</HI> to the great General, and dated from <HI>Zolkiew</HI>
the 7th of <HI>February.</HI></P>
<P>THE King of <HI>Sweden,</HI> having by Force and
Management, compa&s;s'd his De&s;ign again&s;t King
<HI>Augu&s;tus,</HI> &s;eeks with no lefs Cunning to gain his
Ends of us and the Republick, and to render Fruitle&s;s
our good Di&s;po&s;itions to maintain the common Intere&s;t.
In this View, his Mini&s;ters in all foreign Courts in&s;i|nuate,
that he is treating of a Peace &s;eparately with
us. We do not deny, that (when) formerly, at <HI>Seoli|za,</HI>
&s;everal Mini&s;ters of foreign Potentates, &s;ounded
our Inclination to Peace; we intimated, that out of
Chri&s;tian Duty, and to &s;pare the Effu&s;ion of Blood,
we &s;hould always be ready to hearken to all Propo&s;tions
of Peace which the King of <HI>Sweden</HI> &s;hould offer,
but on Condition, that &s;uch Peace &s;hould be negotiated
openly, and with the Con&s;ent and Participation of
the Republick, and concluded by Commi&s;&s;ioners
appointed by all the Nations concern'd. We never did,
or &s;hall entertain any Thoughts of treating of Peace
&s;ecretly, by the Intervention of any foreign Courts;
prefering to all Intere&s;t and Advantage, the Reputa|tion,
Honour, and Inviolable good Faith of a Mo|narch,
in the &s;trict Ob&s;ervation of all his Alliances.
We therefore, a&s;&s;ure your Lord&s;hip, that we have not
yet enter'd into any Manner of Negotiation of Peace
with <HI>Sweden,</HI> nor, for the future, will enter into any,
otherwi&s;e than we have already declared, with the
Participation and Con&s;ent of the E&s;tates of the Re|publick;
being ab&s;olutely determin'd to keep inviolably
<PB N="180" REF="181">
the Alliance and Guarantee we are ingaged in with
the Republick.</P>
<P>IN Pur&s;uit of the <HI>Czar's</HI> Re&s;olutions to a&s;&s;i&s;t
the <HI>Poles,</HI> we find that his Maje&s;ty's Troops were
very numerous in <HI>Poland.</HI></P>
<P>THE Body of <HI>Mu&s;covits</HI> in <HI>Pru&s;&s;ia</HI> con&s;i&s;ted of
18000 Men, and were augmented con&s;iderably;
the City of <HI>Dantzick</HI> were not a little alarm'd at
it, e&s;pecially &s;ince they receiv'd a threatning Let|ter
from the <HI>Czar</HI> on Account of their acknow|ledging
<HI>Stani&s;laus.</HI> The Body of <HI>Mu&s;covites</HI> about
<HI>Thorn</HI> were &s;o &s;trong, that they oblig'd Prince
<HI>Lubomir&s;ky</HI> to retire with his Troops into great
<HI>Poland.</HI> The <HI>Mu&s;covites</HI> al&s;o form'd another Bo|dy
near <HI>Cali&s;h,</HI> making near 30000 Men; and a
Fourth about <HI>Gue&s;na.</HI> During the&s;e things the
<HI>Czar</HI> &s;eeing the <HI>Poles</HI> un&s;teady in their Re&s;olutions,
and di&s;puting Trifles with their be&s;t Friends, went
him&s;elf in Per&s;on to the great Council of Senators,
which were adjourn'd from <HI>Lemberg,</HI> and met at
<HI>Lublin;</HI> where is <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty arrived the 20th
of <HI>May,</HI> 1707, with a Guard of 3000 Dragoons.
The Senators had all agreed as above, that up|on
the King of <HI>Poland</HI>'s having abdicated the
Crown, they were in a State of <HI>Interregnum,</HI> and
that the Throne was vacant; but could never be
brought to fill up the Vacancy, and elect a new
King, which his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty ju&s;tly thought
was the only way to engage them heartily, &s;o
that they might be depended on.</P>
<P>BUT they put it always off, alledging that
King <HI>Augu&s;tus</HI> had not &s;ignified his Re&s;olution of
abandoning the Crown to them in Particular, and
therefore they ought to &s;end a Deputation to
<PB N="181" REF="182">
him, to have his la&s;t An&s;wer from his own
Mouth.</P>
<P>THIS the <HI>Czar</HI> took for gro&s;s Triffling with
him, and &s;uch indeed it was; for they had their
Articles of Peace between the King of <HI>Sweden</HI> and
the King of <HI>Poland,</HI> publi&s;h'd by the &s;aid two
King's re&s;pectively, and the Letter which the
King of <HI>Sweden</HI> oblig'd the King of <HI>Poland</HI> to
write to King <HI>Stani&s;laus,</HI> owning him for King of
<HI>Poland,</HI> all the&s;e were before them, and yet they
made Excu&s;es to put off a new Election of a
King.</P>
<P>THEY were indeed, all of them willing to have
his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty to advance with his Army,
and propo&s;ed to concert Mea&s;ures to act again&s;t
the King of <HI>Sweden</HI> with joint Forces, and Endea|vour
to bring the King of <HI>Sweden</HI> to a deci&s;ive
Battle; which his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty was willing
enough to do, as &s;oon as a new King &s;hould be
nam'd, but did not think any other Step le&s;s
than that, could &s;ufficiently a&s;&s;ure him of
the Fidelity and Steadine&s;s of the <HI>Poles,</HI> who in
Ca&s;e of a Battle, he knew well enough might
have an Opportunity to make their Peace at his
Maje&s;ty's Expence; and indeed, tho&s;e Uncer|tainties
produced &s;uch a general Di&s;ta&s;te, and
gave &s;uch a plain Ground of Mi&s;tru&s;t, that they,
the <HI>Poles,</HI> only &s;ought a Delay, and to &s;ee what
Mea&s;ures the King of <HI>Sweden</HI> would take, or whe|ther
he re&s;olved to bring his Army again into
<HI>Poland,</HI> or not, that they might have Time to
take up with the Stronge&s;t; that his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Ma|je&s;ty,
from this Time, begun to &s;ee plainly, he
had nothing but his own Power to depend upon;
and that the <HI>Poles</HI> were not to be tru&s;ted; and
this brought in the End, all the Con&s;ultations,
<PB N="182" REF="183">
Confederacies and Pretences of Defending the
Liberties of <HI>Poland</HI> to nothing, and ended as &s;uch
generally do, in their falling all into the Hands
of their Enemies; and being oblig'd to &s;ubmit to
King <HI>Stani&s;laus,</HI> as we &s;hall pre&s;ently &s;hew.</P>
<P>BUT his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty who knew them too
well, to be drawn into any Snare by them;
acted an open, plain, and fair Part with them;
and let them know, that &s;ince they would not do
their Duty, and were not mov'd either by their
pre&s;ent or future Intere&s;t, he would take Care
to depend upon him&s;elf only, and take &s;uch
Mea&s;ures as he &s;hould think fit. But whereas
their famous Champion <HI>Smegielski,</HI> who had done
&s;o many gallant Exploits again&s;t the <HI>Swedes</HI> in the
Cau&s;e of King <HI>Augu&s;tus,</HI> had now made his Peace,
and was gone over to <HI>Stani&s;laus,</HI> and had commit|ted
&s;ome Ho&s;tilities again&s;t the <HI>Ru&s;&s;ians:</HI> The <HI>Ru&s;|&s;ian</HI>
General caus'd him to be hang'd in Effigie,
as a Traytor to his Country, and put a Reward
upon his Head, to any who &s;hould bring him in alive or dead.</P>
<P>AT the &s;ame Time, his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty &s;eeing
him&s;elf thus u&s;ed, by King <HI>Augu&s;tus,</HI> even ju&s;t
after his Troops had obtain'd a great Victory for
him, the &s;aid King <HI>Augu&s;tus;</HI> and that notwith|&s;tanding
all this, he had not only abandon'd his
Confederacy or Alliances with his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje|&s;ty,
but had joyn'd his Enemy the King of <HI>Swe|den,</HI>
and obliged him&s;elf to act Con$rary to the
Intere&s;t he had e&s;pou&s;ed; and al&s;o that King <HI>Au|gu&s;tus</HI>
had &s;ent Letters and Memorials to <HI>England,</HI>
to <HI>Holland,</HI> and other Places, to excu&s;e and palli|ate
the Treachery of his Friend&s;hip. I &s;ay, &s;ee|ing
him&s;elf thus u&s;ed by King <HI>Augu&s;tus;</HI> his <HI>Czar|i&s;h</HI>
Maje&s;ty thought it needful to write to the
<PB N="183" REF="184">
&s;ame Powers to expo&s;e the Ingratitude of King
<HI>Augu&s;tus,</HI> and to let them &s;ee, what in the Cour&s;e
of the late War, his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty had done for
him; the Copy of this Letter to the Queen
of <HI>Great Britain,</HI> being as follows, that to the
States General, being <HI>mutatis mutandis,</HI> much the
&s;ame.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2>
<HEAD>Mo&s;t honoured and beloved SISTER.</HEAD>
<P>ALTHOUGH 'tis not unknown to your Royal
Maje&s;ty yet we have judged it nece&s;&s;ary as Af|fairs
now &s;tand in a Friendly and Brotherly manner,
to acquaint you by this Letter, and as briefly as po&s;&s;i|ble
with the Services we have done King <HI>Augu&s;tus,</HI>
from his fir&s;t Election to the Kingdom of <HI>Poland,</HI>
having by our powerful Endeavours for the common
Benefit of that Crown, hindered the Prince of <HI>Con|ti,</HI>
who had been cho&s;en before by part of the Repub|lick
from taking po&s;e&s;&s;ion of it, and even &s;ent a nu|merous
Army again&s;t the Prince of <HI>Conti</HI>'s Party, for
the u&s;e and Service of tho&s;e Senators, that &s;ided with
King <HI>Augu&s;tus,</HI> before any League had been conclud|ded
with him, or his Enterance into <HI>Poland;</HI> the
Army was immediately upon his arrival put under his
command, that he might be able to puni&s;h his Enemies,
be&s;ides which we threatned the contrary Party with
Fire and Sword; upon Apprehen&s;ion hereof, many
were forced to acknowledge him, and &s;o by our Assi|&s;tance
he was firmly Settled upon the Throne; after|wards
by his particular Intreaties, and a Me&s;&s;age by
General <HI>Carlowitz</HI> in the Year 1700, we concluded
with him an Alliance again&s;t the King of <HI>Sweden,</HI>
in which there was no Sub&s;idies of Money promi&s;ed
him, moreover many Affronts and Injuries having
<PB N="184" REF="185">
been done us at the beginning of the War by the Crown
of <HI>Sweden,</HI> we were prevail'd with by the earne&s;t
Sollicitations of his Mini&s;ter General <HI>Langa</HI> in an
unproper Sea&s;on, it being the latter End of Autumn
for his Relief, and to make the Enemy turn their
Arms again&s;t us, to begin to attack <HI>Narva,</HI> and then
his Forces, contrary to his Promi&s;e, leaving ours in
Action, went into Quarters in <HI>Poland,</HI> and <HI>Cour|land,</HI>
on which occa&s;ion our Forces &s;uffer'd no &s;mall
Lo&s;s, notwith&s;tanding which, a League being renewed
with him at <HI>Bir&s;a,</HI> in 1701, not a &s;mall Sum of Mo|ney
was Lent him, be&s;ides which, we a&s;&s;i&s;ted him with
20000 Foot, neverthele&s;s this &s;ignified nothing, nor
were our Arms made u&s;e of according to the Treaty,
but by the Intrigues of the <HI>French</HI> Amba&s;&s;ador <HI>du
Heiron,</HI> to whom contrary to our Agreement and
Per&s;onal Prote&s;tations confirm'd by us, full power
was at that time given to Treat about a &s;eparate
Peace, tho&s;e our Forces without nece&s;&s;ity were greatly
fatigued and the Enemy permitted to pa&s;s the <HI>Dwina,</HI>
di&s;mi&s;s'd without being &s;upplied with Provi&s;ions, du|ring
their March, for which the &s;aid King received
Money from us, which cau&s;ed great Numbers of
them to peri&s;h, and others to De&s;ert: Notwith|standing
all this, upon his repeated A&s;&s;urance, and
Me&s;&s;ages, we renewed a League with him in the Year
1703, and promi&s;ed 300000 Rubles for the u&s;e of
his Forces, and 12000 Foot to be maintain'd at our
own Charges, which we faithfully perform'd; and al|though
the Sub&s;ides, and Auxilliaries were not then
&s;pecified in that Treaty, nor whether the &s;ame &s;hould
be given Yearly, yet we &s;ent him every Year no le&s;s
then the abovementioned Sum, not reckoning other im|men&s;e
Charges, we were at, for the pre&s;erving the
Republick in his Intere&s;t; but in&s;tead of imploying the
Forces again&s;t the Enemy, he made them March to
<PB N="185" REF="186">
and fro in <HI>Poland,</HI> whereby they were very much fa|tigued;
and afterwards parting from them without
any occa&s;ion, be permitted them to be driven into <HI>Sax|ony,</HI>
together with the <HI>Saxons,</HI> whereby without any
nece&s;&s;ity half of them were unaccountably lo&s;t, and
the re&s;t were forced to die with Hunger; and altho'
free Winter Quarters were promis'd them in the
Treaty, yet on the contrary, 'twas forbidden to sup|ply
them with Bread in their Quarters: Upon which
our Mini&s;ter extraordinary, <HI>Van Patkul,</HI> then re|&s;iding
at his Court, and chief General of tho&s;e Forces,
in order to pre&s;erve them from utter and certain
Ruin, agreed with the Emperor's Mini&s;ters to put
them into his imperial Maje&s;ty's Service, for which
by the Sugge&s;tions of the &s;aid King's wicked and trea|cherous
<HI>Saxon</HI> Mini&s;ters, he was put under Arre&s;t
contrary to the Law of Nations, and without our
con&s;ent, was ca&s;t like a Traytor into a loath&s;ome Pri|son,
altho' we were oblig'd for the Intere&s;t of the
&s;aid King <HI>Augu&s;tus,</HI> as well as before the Affront of|fered
to our Mini&s;ter, as after the going of the &s;aid
King out of <HI>Poland,</HI> in order to pre&s;erve him upon
his Throne, and defend the Republick of <HI>Poland</HI> a|gainst
the <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> Forces, to leave all our Armies
to Act for his Intere&s;t; and at the de&s;ire of the Re|publick
by their extraordinary Emba&s;&s;y to March
with all our Forces into <HI>Poland,</HI> where they were ob|lig'd
to be maintain'd to this Day to our great Charge
in own Pay; yet notwith&s;tanding all this, his Generals
at his going out of <HI>Saxony,</HI> with our and their Troops,
&s;uffered them&s;elves, not without &s;u&s;picion of Treache|ry,
to be beaten without any Re&s;i&s;tance; and our
Forces were &s;o De&s;erted, that only 1600 of them re|mained,
and the&s;e with much a-do &s;aved them&s;elves,
and return'd into <HI>Saxony,</HI> although King <HI>Augu&s;tus</HI>
upon our repeated In&s;tances and Sollicitations, pro|mis'd
<PB N="186" REF="187">
both before and after his infamous Peace, by
his Me&s;&s;ages and Prote&s;tations made to us by General
<HI>Goltz,</HI> either to deliver up to us, or &s;ecretly to &s;et
at Liberty our &s;aid Mini&s;ter, General <HI>Van Patkul;</HI>
yet nothing was performed, notwith&s;tanding which,
without regarding the intolerable Fal&s;hoods of the &s;aid
King <HI>Augu&s;tus,</HI> his Non-performances of the Treaty
made with us, his impri&s;oning our Mini&s;ter, and vio|lating
the Laws of the Nations, and tending to &s;e|parate
Peace, as well by the Sieur <HI>Octima,</HI> as by
Count <HI>Koningmark,</HI> and afterwards in Writing by
their Secretary <HI>Nemitz</HI> and <HI>Figg&s;tone</HI> from the
beginning of the War, and after their enterance into
<HI>Saxony,</HI> of which Tran&s;actions we had Notice given
us by &s;everal of our faithful Friends, and notwith|standing
we had tho&s;e Treaties in our Hands, yet we
did not leave to a&s;&s;i&s;t him, both with our Forces and
Money; and in the la&s;t Compaign, though the Sea&s;ou
of the Year was &s;o far advanced, it being the latter
End of Autum, yet being de&s;ir'd to draw the Ene|my
back, and harra&s;s his Army, we &s;ent our Caval|ry
under the command of our General Prince <HI>Men|zikoff</HI>
to join him, and his <HI>Saxon</HI> and <HI>Poli&s;h</HI> Forces,
who Marching towards <HI>Cali&s;h,</HI> met with the <HI>Swe|di&s;h</HI>
General <HI>Mardefelt,</HI> and the <HI>Poles</HI> of the con|trary
Party under the command of the <HI>Waywode</HI> of
<HI>Kiow,</HI> and by the A&s;&s;i&s;tance of the mo&s;t High, entirely
defeated them, and took their chief General and ma|ny
other inferior Officers, and Soldiers, Pri&s;oners of
war, whereby all great <HI>Poland</HI> was brought under his
Obedience; after this, being fully &s;upplyed with all
Nece&s;&s;aries, we de&s;$gn'd, by the Help of the mo&s;t High,
to act still in his Defence, which was begun with the
Action at <HI>Wyburg</HI> in <HI>Finland,</HI> and did expect many
good Con&s;equences from that Defeat, and rely'd on
a strict Ob&s;ervance of the Treaty, pur&s;uant to the <HI>A&s;&s;ur</HI>
<PB N="187" REF="188">
ances we had receiv'd from him in two Letters,
written &s;ince the Battle, the fir&s;t dated the 31&s;t. of
<HI>October,</HI> and the &s;econd the 20th of <HI>November;</HI>
but &s;aw at fir&s;t, that he begun to take away from our
&s;aid General, Prince <HI>Menzikoff,</HI> the General Officers,
and other Pri&s;oners we had taken, giving his Royal
Word, and many A&s;&s;urances, that he either would
exchange them for our Generals and other Officers,
detain'd in <HI>Sweden;</HI> for the Performance whereof,
General <HI>Mardefelt,</HI> with the Re&s;t of the Officers,
gave al&s;o their Parole, and confirm'd the &s;ame to our
General; or, if it were not po&s;&s;ible to effect this Ex|change,
that he would re&s;tore the &s;aid Pri&s;oners into
our Hands; but contrary to all his Promi&s;es, he let
them go without any Exchange. After this, we under|&s;tood
to our great A&s;toni&s;hment, that he had already
concluded a di&s;honourable Peace with the King of <HI>Swe|den,</HI>
and <HI>Le&s;cheinsky;</HI> yielded up all his Rights to
the <HI>Crown</HI> of <HI>Poland,</HI> and &s;urrendering all to the
Plea&s;ures of his Enemies, without giving us any previ|ous
Notice, that we might have provided for our own
Security, in Return of the innumerable Favours done
him by us; but what &s;hows his Ingratitude to the
highe&s;t Degree, is, that the Peace was confirm' by him
many Days before the Battle. After which, by his
Letters, he gave his earne&s;t A&s;&s;urances of his firm
Adherence to the Treaty; the Incon&s;tancy of his Pro|mi&s;es,
Non-performance of the League, and Forgetful|ne&s;s
of our many Favours and A&s;&s;istance, we leave
to the righteous Judgement and Vengeance of Almigh|ty
God, and upon who&s;e powerful A&s;&s;i&s;tance in our ju&s;t
Cau&s;e, we firmly rely; prote&s;ting again&s;t the &s;aid
King <HI>Augu&s;tus</HI> and his Subjects; and Leave al&s;o to
all the World to Judge impartially of our faithful
Performance of the League to the very la&s;t. More|over,
we are extreamly &s;urpriz'd, at three Articles in
<PB N="188" REF="189">
the afore&s;aid League, viz. the 11th, 12th, and
20th, in the fir&s;t of which, be, the &s;aid, late
King Augu&s;tus, promi&s;ed to deliver up our publick
Mini&s;ter and Plenipotentiary re&s;iding at his Court,
into the Hands of our Enemies, in an unheard of
Manner, and to his utter Ruin, upon Pretence of his
being a <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> De&s;erter. Secondly, in the 12th
Article be maliciou&s;ly obliges him&s;elf to deliver up to
the Enemy, as Prisoners of War, the Remains of 12
Regiments, <HI>viz.</HI> 1600 Auxiliary Troops, who for his
Pre&s;ervation have often expos'd their Lives; and were
there &s;ent by him as Auxiliaries into the Empire;
which is not only contrary to divine and human Laws,
but even to the Cu&s;toms and Laws of Barbarians:
<HI>Thirdly,</HI> In the 20th Article, he &s;tipulates for him|&s;elf,
in Ca&s;e of Peace between us and the Enemy, full
Satisfaction. And afterwards, he the &s;aid <HI>Augu&s;tus,</HI>
in that Treaty, obliges him&s;elf, to procure your Roy|al
Maje&s;ty Guarantee, therefore we in a brotherly and
friendly Manner, de&s;ire your Royal Maje&s;ty, that
through your innate and wonted Goodne&s;s, you would
be plea&s;ed not to con&s;ent thereunto, nor countenance
his di&s;honourable Actions. It would have been nece&s;|&s;ary
we &s;hould, before this Time, have exhibited this
our Prote&s;tation, both to your Royal Maje&s;ty, and
other Potentates in writing, which we ab&s;olutely would
have performed by our Mini&s;ters, had we not been de|luded&punc;
as we have made it appear, by the the fre&s;h A&s;&s;u|rance
he &s;ent us by Major General <HI>Goltz,</HI> who among
many other fal&s;e A&s;&s;urances of Friend&s;hip engaged for
the Performance of the League, and &s;olemnly a&s;&s;ured
us, that our Mini&s;ter &s;hould never be deliver'd up,
and that in Ca&s;e, it &s;hould come to the la&s;t Extreme|ly,
King <HI>Augu&s;tus,</HI> &s;hould either &s;et him privately
at Liberty, or detain him in <HI>Koning&s;tein</HI> 'till the De|parture
of the <HI>Swedes;</HI> and afterwards, deliver him
<PB N="189" REF="190">
into our Hands. But we have &s;ince, with Wonder,
and bitter Grief under&s;tood, that that Prince fore|going
his Honour, has deliver'd up our innocent pub|lick
Mini&s;ter, contrary to the Law of Nations, and
even Cu&s;toms of <HI>Barbarians,</HI> and without the Fear of
God, into the Hands of his Enemies. For which
Rea&s;on, we have the rather thought fit to acquaint
your Maje&s;ty with all the Premi&s;es; and in a friendly
and brotherly Manner, to defire, that you would be
plea&s;ed, by your good Offices, to procure the Liberty
of our &s;aid Mini&s;ter, <HI>Van Patkul,</HI> or at lea&s;t, that
he may be u&s;ed by the King of <HI>Sweden,</HI> as our Mini|&s;ter,
and not as his Subject, which we are confident,
his <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty will grant, at your Royal Ma|je&s;ty's
De&s;ire, whereby he will gain, with all the
World, the Name of a magnanimous Monarch, in|stead
of giving an Example of &s;o wicked and barbarous
an Action. But, if on the Contrary, <HI>Van Patkul</HI>
be hardly dealt with, and not u&s;ed as our Mini&s;ter,
we &s;hall be forced to &s;eek Opportunities to return the
like U&s;age. Tru&s;ting that in our ju&s;t Cau&s;e, we &s;hall
receive all A&s;i&s;tance from the Mo&s;t High. We hope
likewi&s;e, by your Maje&s;ty's good Offices, and others,
our Subjects detain'd at <HI>Stockholm,</HI> and now under
Arre&s;t, <HI>viz.</HI> the &s;ame Number and of the &s;ame
Rank, as tho&s;e that were permitted to go upon their
Parole from our General, Prince <HI>Menzikoff,</HI>
namely, his General <HI>Mardefeldt,</HI> and other Officers,
and Soldiers, by Order of King <HI>Augu&s;tus;</HI> and on
the Parole of the re&s;t of the <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> Officers. The
&s;aid <HI>Augu&s;tus,</HI> having thus, Evidently before all the
World, violated his Vows, and the Laws of Nations,
by his unheard of di&s;honourable Proceedings, contra|ry
to the Dictates of Con&s;cience; as appears by tho&s;e
Treaties, we &s;hall be oblig'd to do our &s;elves the
Ju&s;tice, and &s;eek for entire Satisfaction from him, as
<PB N="190" REF="191">
Elector of <HI>Saxony,</HI> and a Member of the <HI>Roman</HI>
Empire, which our fair Proceedings and Stedfa&s;tne&s;s
to the League entitiled us too. The rather, becau&s;e
by the 20th Article, contrary to his own Con&s;cieoe,
be propo&s;es to &s;eek for full Satisfaction from us; the
remaining Part of our Auxiliary Troops now upon the
<HI>Rhine,</HI> we put under your Royal Majesty's Protection;
and de&s;ire that they may either enter your Maje&s;ty's
Service, or that of your Allies; or at lea&s;t we en|treat
your good Offices, that they may have Leave to
return Home with Safety; hoping that you will fa|vour
us with your Concurrence and A&s;&s;i&s;tance in the&s;e
our ju&s;t De&s;ires; We the Imperial Czari&s;h Maje&s;ty.
Pray God to Grant, your Royal Maje&s;ty many Years
Health, and a happy Reign, over your Maje&s;ty's Do|minions.</P>
<CLOSER><DATELINE>Given at <HI>Zolkew,</HI> <DATE>April 27,</DATE> and in the 25th,
Year of our Reign,</DATELINE>
<HI>Your Maje&s;ty's Affectionate</HI>
Loving Brother,
<SIGNED>PETER</SIGNED></CLOSER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2>
<PB N="191" REF="192">
<P>THIS Letter is too &s;ignificant, and the Sub&s;i&s;t|tance
of it of too much Weight, to be pa&s;s'd over,
it being an Abridgement of the Conduct of his
<HI>Czarish</HI> Maje&s;ty, in Aid of the King of <HI>Poland,</HI>
and of his treacherous Return, and al&s;o a kind
of Summary of the State of Things between
them at that Time.</P>
<P>THERE are two Ca&s;es mention'd in this Le|tter,
which have not yet been &s;poken to; the one
is, That of the 1600 <HI>Ru&s;&s;ians,</HI> who had been put
into the Service of the Confederates in the Em|pire,
and were acting upon the <HI>Rhine,</HI> as Part of
King <HI>Augu&s;tus</HI>'s Quota to the grand Alliance a|gainst
<HI>France;</HI> and the other, is that of General
<HI>Patkull,</HI> who the <HI>Czar</HI> here declares to be his Mini|&s;ter
and Amba&s;&s;tador to King <HI>Augu&s;tus;</HI> certain it
is, that King <HI>Augu&s;tus</HI> yielded both the&s;e Points to
the King of <HI>Sweden,</HI> that is to &s;ay, as far as lay
in his Power; he gave up the <HI>Ru&s;&s;ian</HI> Troops up|on
the <HI>Rhine</HI> to the King of <HI>Sweden;</HI> but the
Emperor, who had more Humanity and Honour,
than to be a Party to &s;o di&s;honourable an Action,
&s;tood out &s;o long, 'till the &s;aid Regiments had
Opportunity to retire from thence, and to di&s;|band,
and by &s;mall Parties to pa&s;s through the
Imperial Countries into <HI>Poland,</HI> and &s;o to their
own Country. But as for General <HI>Patkull,</HI> he de|liver'd
him up to the King of <HI>Sweden,</HI> who, deaf
to all Interce&s;&s;ion, and not regarding him as a
Publick Mini&s;ter, but as a Traytor, cau&s;ed him
without Mercy, to be put to Death, by breaking
him a-live, and that with &s;ome extraordinary Marks
of Cruelty, &s;uch as particularly cau&s;ing his own
Nephew, an Officer then in the King of <HI>Sweden</HI>'s
Service, to be the Per&s;on to &s;ee the Execution
<PB N="192" REF="193">
perform'd, to the A&s;toni&s;hment and Horror of all
that heard it.</P>
<P>BUT to return to his <HI>Czarish</HI> Maje&s;ty, he now
found that nothing was to be done with the <HI>Poles,</HI>
and that he mu&s;t re&s;olve to &s;tand upon his own
Feet, again&s;t the King of <HI>Sweden,</HI> who having
encrea&s;ed his Army, in <HI>Saxony</HI> to 50000 Men, by
rai&s;ing Men almo&s;t over the whole Empire, was
in Motion towards <HI>Poland.</HI> I &s;ay, finding this, his
Maje&s;ty leaving 40000 Hor&s;e in <HI>Poland,</HI> to Coun|tenance
the <HI>Poles</HI> if they would be &s;teady, and
di&s;charge them&s;elves as was their Duty: Went
him&s;elf into <HI>Lithuania,</HI> to draw his Forces toge|ther
there, in order to be in a Condition to Face
the King of <HI>Sweden,</HI> or, withdraw the re&s;t of his
Troops, as he &s;hould find Occa&s;ion.</P>
<P>THE King of <HI>Sweden</HI> left <HI>Saxony,</HI> the Begin|ing
of <HI>September,</HI> to the great Joy of the Poor
People there, who had been terribly impoveri&s;h'd
by their long Stay in the Country. They ad|vanced
by long Marches through <HI>Sile&s;ia,</HI> and came
the 10th of October, to Ca&s;imir in <HI>Poland,</HI> where
the barbarous Execution of Count <HI>Patkull,</HI> above|mention'd,
was perform'd, being the fir&s;t Town
they halted at, on their entering <HI>Poland.</HI></P>
<P>His <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty being, as I have &s;aid, gone
into <HI>Lithuania,</HI> had his head Quarters at <HI>Wilda;</HI>
before the withdrawing his Army, he ordered the
Lands of the <HI>$alatines,</HI> in the Interc&s;t of the U|&s;urper
<HI>Stani&s;laus</HI> to be laid Wa&s;te, which his Ene|mies
repre&s;ented as a mighty Injury; altho' he
therein only follow'd the Example of the <HI>Swedes,</HI>
who had &s;o often done the like in an extraordina|ry
manner, to the Lands and E&s;tates of the No|bility
who adheard to the Intere&s;t of their Coun|try.</P>
<P><PB N="193" REF="194">
THIS was the Ca&s;e wherein the King of <HI>Swe|den</HI>'s
Party pretended the <HI>Czar</HI> had rifled the Seats
of the Nobility in <HI>Poland,</HI> and carry'd away the
Pictures, Statues, Orange Trees, &amp;c. into <HI>Mu&s;covy,</HI>
as al&s;o &s;everal Extraordinary Libraries with
many valuable Manuf&s;cripts, and other Curio&s;ities,
or Rarities in Nature and of Art, part of which,
if it were &s;o, was relative only to the Hou&s;es of
his Enemies, which by the Laws of War he had
Right to, they being now in Arms again&s;t him.</P>
<P>THE Diet or A&s;&s;embly at <HI>Lublin,</HI> continued
&s;ome time longer, and &s;eem'd to adhere to their
former Re&s;olutions, and to &s;upport their Liber|ties,
again&s;t King <HI>Stani&s;laus</HI> and the <HI>Swedes,</HI> but
as the <HI>Czar</HI> had no Confidence in them, &s;o indeed,
he had no Rea&s;on, as the Event &s;hew'd after|wards;
for the King of <HI>Sweden</HI> advancing, they
all &s;eparated and di&s;appear'd, leaving his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI>
Maje&s;ty to &s;tand by him&s;elf, as it may be &s;aid,
in the War with the King of <HI>Sweden,</HI> which how
well he was able to do, and how Ill they de|&s;erv'd
it of him, will &s;oon appear in the Con&s;e|quence
of the Story.</P>
<P>NOT that they ever fell in heartily with the
King of <HI>Sweden,</HI> or with <HI>Stani&s;laus,</HI> which made
the Revolution which follow'd, the more ea&s;ie to
the King of <HI>Poland.</HI> But the King of <HI>Sweden</HI>
coming with &s;o formidable a Power, back into
<HI>Poland,</HI> and bending the fir&s;t of his March towards
<HI>Thorn,</HI> and the Towns on the lower <HI>Vi&s;tula;</HI> it
was no more Que&s;tion'd for &s;ome Time, but that
his <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty, Would in the fir&s;t Place, clear
the Country of all King <HI>Sani&s;laus</HI>'s Enemies, and
u&s;e them with the uttmo&s;t Severity.</P>
<P>BUT the King of <HI>Sweden,</HI> who&s;e dark Hour&s;
were ju&s;t now begining, and who, as &s;ome have
<PB N="194" REF="195">
ob&s;erv'd, &s;carce ever took one right Step, after
his coming from <HI>Saxony,</HI> but delay'd his Proceed|ings
either one Way or other, for near three
Months, hovering on that Side of <HI>Poland</HI> next the
Borders of <HI>Sile&s;ia,</HI> 'till he had brought the Empe|ror
to Execute fully a Treaty which had been
made between them, in the behalf of the Pro|te&s;tants
of <HI>Sile&s;ia.</HI></P>
<P>AND indeed, he was oblig'd to &s;tay thus long
about <HI>Po&s;en,</HI> and <HI>Cali&s;h,</HI> and tho&s;e Parts, to lay
up Magazins, and Stores of Provi&s;ions for his
Army; for the <HI>Ru&s;&s;ians</HI> had ruined the Country
with a De&s;igns to render it difficult to him to &s;ub|&s;i&s;t,
and it had the de&s;ired Effect; for after he be|gun
to extend him&s;elf, there was no Forrage to be
found, &s;ufficient to &s;upply his Army on any con|&s;iderable
Occa&s;ion, and this made the King of
<HI>Sweden</HI> lye &s;till, till the Month of <HI>February</HI> at
lea&s;t.</P>
<P>DURING all this Time, things hung in &s;u&s;pen&s;e
between the King of <HI>Sweden,</HI> and the <HI>Czar</HI> of
<HI>Mu&s;covy;</HI> &s;everal Powers, and Princes, &s;ought to
mediate a Peace between his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty and
the King of <HI>Sweden;</HI> Nor was the <HI>Czar</HI> aver&s;e to
a Peace, upon equitable and ju&s;t Conditions; but
the King of <HI>Sweden</HI> breathed nothing but War
and declar'd or the World was &s;o unju&s;t as to
publi&s;h it in his Name, that nothing &s;hould &s;ati&s;|fy
him now, but dethroning the <HI>Czar</HI> of <HI>Mu&s;covy,</HI>
as he had dethron'd the King of <HI>Poland;</HI> So that
the <HI>Czar</HI> might be truly &s;aid to fight for his
Crown, as he had fought before for his Friend
the King of <HI>Poland,</HI> and for the Peace of the
Republick.</P>
<P>IN Pe$&s;uance of this wicked Principle of Re|venge,
he turn'd his Arms froom <HI>Poland,</HI> not yet
<PB N="195" REF="196">
&s;ubdued, and left his new pretended King,
to &s;trugle with a half reduced Nobility, and a di|vided
Nation, and profe&s;s'd to make War again&s;t
neither &s;mall nor great, but again&s;t his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI>
Maje&s;ty in Per&s;on.</P>
<P>THIS chymerical Piece of Per&s;onality in War,
drew is <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty, otherwi&s;e a mo&s;t gallant
and experienc'd Prince, into &s;o many wild and
de&s;perate Undertakings, as have never been heard
of before; and into &s;uch Mi&s;takes, to &s;ay no
wor&s;e of them, as never any General of an Army
run into, and which at la&s;t ended in his utter Ruin,
and overthrow, as will pre&s;ently appear.</P>
<P>His <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty, di&s;pi&s;ing the Threatening
or <HI>Ga&s;conade</HI> of Depo&s;ing him; but not at all Di&s;|pi&s;ing,
either the Per&s;on or Armies of the King
of <HI>Sweden,</HI> had no more to do than to draw off his
Armies from <HI>Poland,</HI> keep his new Conque&s;ts well
guarded, and provided, and bring all his Forces
into &s;uch po&s;ts, as that he might &s;oone&s;t draw to|gether
his Power, when he &s;aw where the Cloud
would break; wait to &s;ee which Way this new In|vader
would go about this great Work of entering
the <HI>Ru&s;&s;ian</HI> Empire, in order to bring to pa&s;s the
Revolution he had projected.</P>
<P>IT was with &s;ome Rea&s;on that his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Ma|je&s;ty
thought the fir&s;t Step that the King of <HI>Swe|den</HI>
would take, would be to march into <HI>Livonia,</HI>
and there endeavour to recover what he had lo&s;t;
retrieve the ruin'd Condition of that flouri&s;hing
Country, and like a true Father thereof, re&s;tore
Peace to his People. But far from this, he found
that on a &s;uddain, his Enemy turn'd his Face to
the <HI>South,</HI> or rather to the <HI>South Ea&s;t,</HI> and bent his
Marches really towards his Maje&s;ty's Dominions.</P>
<P><PB N="196" REF="197">
THEN it was, that the <HI>Czar,</HI> who early pene|trated
into the De&s;ign; fore&s;aw, that &s;ome Trea|chery
mu&s;t be form'd among the <HI>Co&s;&s;acks</HI> of the
<HI>Ukrain,</HI> and that the King of <HI>Sweden</HI> had held
&s;ome private Corre&s;pondences with the Traytor
<HI>Maz$ppa,</HI> General of that fal&s;e and fickle People:
And this was the more probable, becau&s;e it was
the only View that the King of <HI>Sweden</HI> could
have on that Side: The <HI>Tartars</HI> of <HI>Cira&s;&s;ia,</HI> and all
that Side of the Country, were too remote for
any &s;uch Attempt, nor would it be po&s;&s;ible for the
King of <HI>Sweden</HI> to penetrate into <HI>Mu&s;covy</HI> any
o$ her Way, the Frontiers lying de&s;olate for
&s;o long a Way before he could come to the inha|bited
fruitful Part of <HI>Mu&s;covy,</HI> that it would be
impo&s;&s;ible for an Army to &s;ub&s;i&s;t, to find For|riage
for their Hor&s;es, and Food for their Men,
and that the carrying it with them for &s;o long a
March, would be as Impracticable, as the other
would be Impo&s;&s;ible.</P>
<P>BUT the <HI>Ukrain,</HI> a fruitful and populous Coun|try
could it be brought into a Revolt, as the
<HI>Swedes</HI> had flatter'd them&s;elves, or as &s;ome had
brought them to believe it would, might indeed,
have given him an Inlet into the Heart of the
Country, and have furni&s;h'd them with Carriages
and H$re&s;es for carrying their Provi&s;ions, if the
<HI>Czar</HI> &s;hould lay wa&s;te the Enterance into his
Dominions, as they might conclude would be
done.</P>
<P>WITH this View, the King of <HI>Sweden</HI> began
the de&s;perate undertaking, and marching thro'
the whole Kingdom of <HI>Poland,</HI> pa&s;t the <HI>Bori&s;the|nes,</HI>
and advanc'd directly towards the <HI>Ukra|nia</HI>
by long and Fateaguing Marches, having
42000 Men compleat in his Army, which a fine
<PB N="197" REF="198">
Train of Artillery, and &s;uch an infinite Store
of Ammunition and other millitary Things, as
al&s;o of Provisions and Baggage as took up 11000
Waggons to carry after them, be&s;ides Mules and
Baggage Hor&s;es innumerable, and be&s;ides an Army
of 16000 Men, under the Command o$ Genral
<HI>Lewenhaupt</HI> who his <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty left to come af|ter
him, with another Train of Artillery, and 7000
Waggons of Amunition and Warlike Stores more.</P>
<P>NOW his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty knew his Bu&s;ine&s;s;
the Field was mark'd out for him, and he knew
where to expect his Enemy. Now he &s;aw where
this gathering Cloud would break, and where the
Storm would fall; and he had no more to do but
to follow and provide for his Defence.</P>
<P>HE did not however, abandon all Hopes from
the confederate States of <HI>Poland,</HI> or their A&s;&s;em|bly
at <HI>War&s;aw,</HI> tho' he cea&s;ed to depend upon their
A&s;&s;i&s;tance; but as he knew the Di&s;po&s;ition of the
<HI>Poles</HI> perfectly well, he knew that tho' they
would not go on in the Path that he propo&s;ed,
that is to &s;ay, to bring Things to a Point, and
&s;et up another King; which, after they had de|clar'd,
and publi&s;h'd an <HI>Interregnum,</HI> one would
have thought they &s;hould not have &s;tuck at; yet,
that they had gone too far, to go back again to
King <HI>Stani&s;laus,</HI> and that at lea&s;t they would create
him a great deal of Trouble, and employ a great
many of his Troops, to prevent him joyning with
the King of <HI>Sweden,</HI> and this happen'd exactly as
the <HI>Czar</HI> fore&s;aw it would.</P>
<P>UPON this Foot, I &s;ay, he did not break with
them, and leave them abruptly, and entirely to
them&s;elves, which had been to have them all
torn in Pieces by the King of <HI>Sweden,</HI> or to have
forc'd them to go in at once to King <HI>Stani&s;laus,</HI>
and to joyn him again&s;t his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty's
<PB N="198" REF="199">
Armies. But to prevent either of the&s;e Extreams,
the <HI>Czar,</HI> tho' he retir'd with the Gro&s;s of his
Army, to his own Frontiers; and as I have &s;aid,
prepar'd to defend him&s;elf, yet he left a Body of
Troops with them, to encourage, and a&s;&s;i&s;t them,
and manag'd them &s;o well, that they could ne|ver
be brought to joyn King <HI>Stani&s;laus,</HI> or fall in|to
his Mea&s;ures, and Intere&s;t, to the la&s;t, no not
when the King of <HI>Sweden</HI> had 60000 Men in the
Bowels of their Country.</P>
<P>BUT to return to the King of <HI>Sweden,</HI> it has
been ob&s;erv'd by &s;ome Writers, and &s;uch too, as
have made the be&s;t Judgement of tho&s;e Things,
that the King of <HI>Sweden</HI> never took one pro&s;pe|rous
Step, nor did any Thing thrive that he un|dertook,
after the cruel Execution of Count <HI>Pat|kull,</HI>
nor after his unju&s;t and per&s;onal War again&s;t
the <HI>Czar</HI> of <HI>Mu&s;covy</HI>'s Crown: I mean his declar'd
Re&s;olution, to depo&s;e and dethrone his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI>
Maje&s;ty; a Thing the World laugh'd at, and
which was in it&s;elf, con&s;idering the numerous
Armies the <HI>Czar</HI> had then on Foot, really ridicu|lous.
But this is by the Way.</P>
<P>THE King of <HI>Sweden</HI> having layn &s;till, in the
<HI>le&s;&s;er Poland,</HI> as above, near 3 Months, and ha|ving
con&s;ulted with his Generals, and re&s;olv'd
what Cour&s;e to &s;teer, what Forces to take with
him, and what Armies the Generals &s;hould Com|mand
in his Ab&s;ence, &s;et forward the 8th of <HI>March</HI>
on his re&s;olv'd Expedition into <HI>Mu&s;covy.</HI></P>
<P>THE Troops he took with him, were about
forty two Thou&s;and Men, all well di&s;ciplin'd cho|&s;en
Men, and he left General <HI>Rhen&s;child</HI> Field
M$r$&s;cha, and Governor of <HI>Livonia</HI> as above,
with 15000 Men more, and a &s;econd Train of
Artillery, with 6000 Waggons Loaden with
<PB N="199" REF="200">
Amunition, and Military Stores, and Provi&s;ions,
to follow him.</P>
<P>THIS was indeed, a formidable Force, and
might have been more &s;uitable to the Under|taking,
had he been actually in the Field of
Action, that is to &s;ay, had he been in the inha|bited
populous Part of <HI>Mu&s;covy,</HI> and had not a va&s;t
unpeopled wa&s;ted Country to march through,
and which the <HI>Czar</HI> had on purpo&s;e &s;trip'd of all
po&s;&s;ibility of &s;ub&s;i&s;ting him, and that he mu&s;t
carry every Mouthful of Provi&s;ions with him,
as well Forrage for his Hor&s;e, as Bread for his
Men.</P>
<P>HOWEVER, about <HI>March,</HI> the King of <HI>Sweden,</HI>
a Prince re&s;olute and unalterable in his Underta|kings,
when once his Councils were concluded,
began his March, as I have &s;aid, for <HI>Mu&s;covy,</HI> and
pa&s;&s;ing the <HI>Vi&s;tula,</HI> fir&s;t advanced to wards <HI>Lithua|nia:</HI>
HIS <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty had left a Body of 3000
Hor&s;e, and 22000 Foot, to guard the Pa&s;&s;ages of
the <HI>Vi&s;tulla,</HI> again&s;t any Parties of the <HI>Swedes;</HI> but
with Orders to Retreat in Ca&s;e the whole <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI>
Army &s;hould advance.</P>
<P>His <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty, was at this Time, gone
to <HI>Mu&s;cow,</HI> to &s;ettle the Minds of his People, and
to rai&s;e Money for carrying on the War; as al&s;o,
to appoint more Troops to advance towards the
Frontiers, He likewi&s;e, &s;ettled his Affairs of
Civil Government, and appointed a Body of an
Army to continue about <HI>Mo&s;cow,</HI> to keep all quiet
at the Capital.</P>
<P>HE had left the Army above, under the Com|mand
of the Princes <HI>Czermet</HI> and <HI>Repuin,</HI> both
bold daring Officers, and accu&s;tom'd to the Ser|vice,
tho' natural <HI>Ru&s;&s;ians,</HI> and who had often
look'd the <HI>Swedes</HI> in the Face. But, as above, it
<PB N="200" REF="201">
was the <HI>Czar</HI>'s expre&s;s Order to them, to harra&s;s
the <HI>Swedes</HI> with continual Parties, and Excur|sions,
but never to come to a general Battle with
them if it was po&s;&s;ible to avoid it.</P>
<P>THIS they ob&s;erv'd exactly, &s;o that when the
<HI>Swedes</HI> pa&s;s'd the <HI>Vi&s;tula</HI> the&s;e retreated before
them; in the mean Time, the pretended King,
<HI>Stani&s;laus,</HI> with a &s;trong Body of Troops, as well
<HI>Poles</HI> as <HI>Swedes</HI> advanc'd toward <HI>Sandomir,</HI> to try
if po&s;&s;ibly he could, either by fair Means, or foul,
bring over the confederate Nobility to joyn
with him; and he had the more Pro&s;pect of it at
that Time, becau&s;e he carry'd with him the In|&s;trument
of King <HI>Augu&s;tus</HI>'s relinqui&s;hing them,
and in which, was &s;omthing particularly reflect|ing
upon their Conduct; and which, <HI>if they re&s;ent|ed,</HI>
it might be very propable they would take
Part with the new King. But it was not to be
done, the <HI>Poles</HI> true to them&s;elves, <HI>that is to &s;ay,</HI>
ever factions, and &s;teady to nothing but their
Un&s;treadine&s;s; tho' they had declin'd the <HI>Czar</HI>'s
Propo&s;al for a new Election, tho' they had no
new King, and their old One had di&s;own'd them,
as a People not worth any Prince's while to Go|vern;
yet they would not hear of <HI>Stani&s;laus,</HI> but
a&s;&s;embling again at <HI>Opatow,</HI> they bound them|&s;elves
by a new Oath, to oppo&s;e King <HI>Stani&s;laus,</HI>
and the <HI>Swedes</HI> al&s;o, to the la&s;t Drop. So that
King <HI>Stani&s;laus</HI> not being willing to u&s;e Force with
them, lea&s;t he &s;hould drive them again into the
Arms of the <HI>Czar</HI> of <HI>Mu&s;covy;</HI> and indeed, not be|ing
&s;trong enough, to attack them, came away and
left them, and jovn'd the King of <HI>Sweden</HI> at <HI>Min&s;k,</HI>
in <HI>Lithuania.</HI> That which encouraged the Con&s;e|derate
Nobility the more, was, that be&s;ides 22000
<HI>Ru&s;&s;ians,</HI> which the <HI>Czar</HI> had ordered to march to
<PB N="201" REF="202">
<HI>Opatow,</HI> to defend them; they had by a particu|lar
Negotiation, brought over the <HI>Co&s;&s;acks</HI> of the
<HI>Ukraine,</HI> to favour their Intere&s;t; and General
<HI>Mazeppa,</HI> the famous Chief of the <HI>Co&s;&s;acks</HI> ad|vanced
to joyn them with 30000 Hor&s;e, and pro|mi&s;ed
them, on Occa&s;ion, 20000 more.</P>
<P>THIS encourag'd them &s;till the more, and made
the other of the Nobility come in to them; &s;o
that they began to ri&s;e on every Side, again&s;t
<HI>Stani&s;laus;</HI> his Friends had their Hou&s;es in|&s;ulted,
and their Lands Wa&s;ted, and were every
where fain to fly to the <HI>Swedes</HI> for Succour; even
the Palatine of <HI>Kiow,</HI> was obliged to follow the
Cour&s;e of King <HI>Stani&s;laus,</HI> and with all his Depen|dents,
making about 6000 Men, came to the
<HI>Swedes</HI> Camp at <HI>Min&s;k.</HI></P>
<P>THE <HI>Swedes</HI> continu'd in <HI>Lithuania,</HI> from <HI>March</HI>
to the Middle of <HI>June,</HI> not yet re&s;olving, it &s;eems,
which Rout yet to take; And the King of <HI>Swe|den</HI>
not finding <HI>Poland</HI> in a Po&s;ture fit to be
left to their own Defence; In all this Time, they
could never come to any con&s;iderable Action with
the <HI>Czar</HI>'s Troops; The principal Skirmi&s;h we
had with them, was near <HI>Mohilow,</HI> on the <HI>Bori&s;|thenes,</HI>
where they &s;urpriz'd a Body of about
8000 of our Men, mo&s;t of them Dragoons; who,
after a very Gallant Defence, in which the <HI>Swedes</HI>
lo&s;t abundance of Men, were oblig'd to retire
with the Lo&s;s of about 3000 Men kill'd, and
taken Pri&s;oners.</P>
<P>THIS Days Action might have let the <HI>Swedes</HI>
have &s;een, that the <HI>Mu&s;covite</HI> Troops were now
quite another &s;ort of People than they u&s;ed to be,
and fought with as much Order and regularity as
other People; that they rallied as expertly after
any Di&s;order; and retreated as orderly after a
<PB N="202" REF="203">
Defeat. In a Word, That they would &s;oon be
equal to other Nations on all Occa&s;ions; but the
<HI>Swedes</HI> were too blind in their own Prai&s;es, to
fore&s;ee the Fate that was before them; &s;o that this
little Victory, did but animate them to their own
Ruin, and prepare them &s;till to do more ra&s;h
Things than ever they had done before.</P>
<P>THE <HI>Swedes,</HI> as if irre&s;olute &s;till what Cour&s;e
to take, &s;tay'd at <HI>Mohilow</HI> 'till the 20th of <HI>July.</HI>
They were now at a Cri&s;is of thier Affairs, if
they had a Mind to march for <HI>Mo&s;cow,</HI> as they pre+tended;
the Way was before them from <HI>Mohilow</HI>
North Ea&s;t to <HI>Smolen&s;kow,</HI> and &s;o keeping the <HI>Bo|ri&s;thenes</HI>
or <HI>Neiper</HI> on their Left, they had a plain
Country, of about 360 Miles from <HI>Smolen&s;kow</HI>
to <HI>Mo&s;cow;</HI> it is true, the <HI>Czar</HI> had laid wa&s;te
the Frontiers, and lay full in his Way with three
Armies, which altogether made about 140000 Men,
and the&s;e he was re&s;olv'd they &s;hould fight at
three Times, one after another, and all within
two or three Days of one another, before they
could go on.</P>
<P>BUT here it was plain the King of <HI>Sweden</HI> car|ry'd
on a &s;ecret Intelligence with that ruin'd Tray|tor
<HI>Mazeppa,</HI> having found Means by Bribe|ry,
and other Methods, to corrupt him, who had
indeed, the <HI>Ukranian Co&s;&s;aks</HI> much at his Call, be|ing
their hereditary General.</P>
<P>THIS Treaty was carry'd on, as we afterwards
under&s;tood, by &s;ome of King <HI>Stani&s;laus</HI>'s his Party,
and particularly by the Palatine of <HI>Kiow,</HI> or,
<HI>Kiovia,</HI> the King of <HI>Sweden</HI>'s fa&s;t Friend; And
in a &startq;Word, was fully concluded, tho' in an ill
Hour, as well for him&s;elf, as the King of <HI>Sweden,</HI>
while their Armies lay at <HI>Mohilow.</HI></P>
<P><PB N="203" REF="204">
As &s;oon as the King of <HI>Sweden</HI> had a full Satis|faction
that this Treaty was concluded, he de|camp'd
from <HI>Mohilow,</HI> and to the Surprize, not of
the <HI>Ru&s;&s;ians</HI> only, but of all the World, left the
direct Road for <HI>Mo&s;cow,</HI> and turn'd away South,
keeping the River on his Right, and march'd Di|rectly
to <HI>Czernikiow</HI> on the River <HI>De&s;na&punc;</HI> on the
Frontiers of the <HI>Co&s;&s;acks</HI> Country, and where he
had more immediate Corre&s;pondence with the Re|bel
<HI>Mazeppa,</HI> as we &s;hall &s;ee pre&s;ently.</P>
<P>HAD his <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty continued at <HI>Mohilow,</HI>
but 10 Days longer, he had been joyn by his
famous General <HI>Lewenhaupt</HI> with 15000 Men, all
gallant Troops indeed, and with a new Train of
heavy Cannon, and a va&s;t Quantity of military
Stores, who was in full March to joyne him. But
the King of <HI>Sweden,</HI> as I have ob&s;erv'd, was un|der
the great <HI>Climacterick</HI> of his Fame, and all
Things went again&s;t him, &s;o he marched away,
and General <HI>Lewenhaupt</HI> followed.</P>
<P>IT has been ob&s;erv'd, by tho&s;e who tell this
Story in Favour of the King of <HI>Sweden,</HI> that Ge|neral
<HI>Lewenhaupt,</HI> having 15000 Men with him,
all old Soldiers, and experienc'd well di&s;$iplin'd
Regiments, he might be very well &s;uppo&s;ed not
to want a Convoy; and the mean Opinion the
<HI>Swedes</HI> had of the <HI>Mu&s;covites,</HI> added to their Con|fidence
in that Affair; the King of <HI>Sweden</HI> having
on that Occa&s;ion, &s;aid, as 'tis Reported, that an
Army of 15000 <HI>Swedes</HI> was never beaten by the
<HI>Mu&s;covites,</HI> in a pitch'd Battle before, at lea&s;t in
the Memory of Man.</P>
<P>GENERAL <HI>Lewenhaupt</HI> had a long March,
for he came from the Provinces of <HI>Courland,</HI> and
<HI>Livania,</HI> where he had drawn this Army together,
with great Care, and been four or five Months in
<PB N="204" REF="205">
his Preparations; he made ea&s;y Marches through
<HI>Lithuania,</HI> where he was joyn'd by &s;ome old Re|giments
of <HI>Swedes</HI> out of the <HI>Great Poland,</HI> and
he was now come within three Leagues of <HI>Mohilow:</HI>
His <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty having Notice, of
his March, re&s;olv'd to try the Mettle of his Troops,
upon this Body of Men, and to Cut them off
from joyning the <HI>Swedes</HI> if po&s;&s;ible; and, indeed,
it was a Juncture that required &s;ome <HI>Coup d' Eclat;</HI>
for that the King of <HI>Sweden</HI> was already po&s;&s;e&s;s'd
of <HI>Czernikiow,</HI> on the <HI>De&s;ua,</HI> where he had been
joyn'd by the Traytor <HI>Mazxeppa,</HI> with 10000 <HI>Co&s;|&s;aks,</HI>
and had the plentiful Country of the
<HI>Ukrain</HI> open to him; &s;o had General Lewenhaupt
Joyn'd him, with the&s;e 15000 Men, his Army
would &s;oon have been 100000 Men; that is to &s;ay,
44000 of his own Army, 15000 of General <HI>Lew|enhaupt,</HI>
all <HI>Swedes,</HI> 8000 of the Palatine of <HI>Kiow,</HI>
who lay ready to joyn him, and 36000 <HI>Co&s;&s;aks</HI>
who <HI>Mazeppa</HI> had promi&s;ed to bring in.</P>
<P>IN this Ca&s;e therefore, I &s;ay, the <HI>Czar</HI> re&s;olv'd
to begin and try his Fortune with General <HI>Lew|enhaupt:</HI>
For this Action he drew out a Select
Body of Men out of all his Army, being about
8000 Hor&s;e, and 23000 Foot, which was the
mo&s;t, and gave the Command of them to that
fortunate General Prince <HI>Menzikoff.</HI> But the
<HI>Czar</HI> knowing the Importance of the Action, went
him&s;elf in Per&s;on to &s;ee it executed, tho' not ta|king
any Command upon him&s;elf, but &s;erv'd un|der
his General as a Voluntier.</P>
<P>THE Fight la&s;ted two Days, and almo&s;t a
Night, the Prince having marched with &s;ome
Speed in the Morning, to come up with the Ene|my,
having &s;hown him&s;elf in Order of Battle,
ab$ut Eleven a-Clock, he gave his Men &s;ome Time
<PB N="205" REF="206">
to Re&s;t, and Refre&s;h them&s;elves; &s;o that he did
not begin the Fight, 'till near Three in the After|noon;
when advancing in excellent Order, he came
again in View of their Line, which was drawn
up to great Advantage, being &s;urrounded with a
Mora&s;s on one Flank; and by their Carriages and
a Rivulet running clo&s;e by them on the other
Flank: Had he entrench'd his Front, which it
was ea&s;y for him to have done, and which he had
Lei&s;ure enough for, it would not have been
practicable for our Men to have attack'd him:
But the <HI>Swedes</HI> &s;corn'd to Entrench again&s;t an
Army of <HI>Mu&s;covites.</HI> And this arrogant Tem|per
of theirs, was more than this once their
De&s;truction. For now they gave us a fair
Front to fall on, and we failed not to take the
Offer.</P>
<P>&startq;THE On&s;et was given by the <HI>Ru&s;&s;ian</HI> Dra|goons,
Prince <HI>Menzikoff</HI> commanded Colonel
<HI>Campbell,</HI> a <HI>Scotch</HI> Man who had the Van|guard,
to cau&s;e his Regiment of Dragoons to
Di&s;mount and attack two Battalions, which
the <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> General Count <HI>Lewenhaupt</HI> had
cau&s;ed to advance about a Mile before the
Front of his Line, and po&s;ted behind a little
Mora&s;s, to di&s;pute our Pa&s;&s;age: Tho&s;e two
Battallions made &s;o quick a Fire upon our Men,
that they had hardly any time to Form them|&s;elves
into Order of Battle; Colonel <HI>Campbell</HI>
ob&s;erving how active the Enemy were, caus'd
the five Squadrons who had Di&s;mounted to ad|vance,
to give Opportunity to the re&s;t of his
Troops to put them&s;elves into a Po&s;ture to fol|low
them; and tho&s;e Di&s;mounted Dragoons ha|ving
&s;tood the Enemies Fire for &s;ome time, his
<HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty cau&s;ed them to be &s;upported by
<PB N="206" REF="207">
four Battalions of his Guards, and two of <HI>Inger|manland:</HI>
Our Men pouring in their Shot, up|on
the two fore-mention'd Battalions, killed
above half of them that guarded the Pa&s;&s;age,
and &s;o facilitated our drawing up in Battalia
before the Enemies front.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;GENERAL <HI>Lewenhaupt,</HI> perceiving his Van|guard
was Beaten, re&s;olved to prevent us; and
cau&s;ed his Army to march up and meet us in
Battalia, then his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty ob&s;erving
that the Enemies Line extended wider than
ours, ordered his Highne&s;s Prince <HI>Menzikoff,</HI>
to cau&s;e four Regiments of Dragoons to alight,
and they were immediately placed in our Left
Wing, with two Regiments of Hor&s;e to cover
their Flank, under the Command of General
<HI>Pflug;</HI> and our Right was commanded by the
Princes of <HI>Gallcizin</HI> and <HI>Darm&s;tadt,</HI> who&s;e Flank
was cover'd by two Regiments of Dragoons of
his Highne&s;s Prince <HI>Menzikoff</HI>'s Guards; all
the&s;e Di&s;po&s;itions being made, about Eleven a
Clock the Signal for attacking the Enemy was
given by a general Di&s;charge of all our Artillery:
About 12 a Clock the Enemy began to advance
towards us with great Fiercene&s;s and Re&s;olution;
and the Fight being hot and ob&s;tinate on both
Sides, for above an Hour and half, the Vict|ory
hung in Su&s;pence.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;DURING the terrible Fire, which was made
every where, his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty appear'd in the
Places of mo&s;t Danger, to annimate by his Va|lour,
and Pre&s;ence, all the Officers and Soldiers;
and ob&s;erving that the Left &s;uffer'd much, he
cau&s;ed it to be reinforced by the Regiment of
Guards of Prince <HI>Menzikoff.</HI>&endq;</P>
<P><PB N="207" REF="208">
&startq;THE Enemy ob&s;erving, how well we acquit|ted
our &s;elves under the Eye of our Augu&s;t Ma|&s;ter,
begun to give Ground, yet drew off in
Order of Battle.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;THEN we redoubl'd our Efforts, to improve
that Advantage: The Enemy being driven
back to their Waggons and Baggage, the Action
was for &s;ome time forborn on both Sides; about
three a Clock our Cannon coming up, began to
play again.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;THINGS &s;tanding thus, His <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty
being inform'd, that General <HI>Bour</HI> was within
half a League of him with 4000 Men, thought
fit to wait a little for his Arrival.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;ABOUT four a Clock General <HI>Bour</HI> came up
with his Body, and was oblig'd to endure the
Fire of the Enemies Artillery, before he
could joyn our Right, where he was to po&s;t
him&s;elf.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;FROM this Junction, his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty be|gan
to entertain Hopes that all would end well;
and order'd that neither Right nor Left, &s;hould
renew the Fight one without the other; but
the Left Wing, having &s;tood a good while
without attacking, the Impatience of all our
Officers and Soldiers &s;uperceeded that Order,
our Right Wing renew'd the Attack likewi&s;e
with the utmo&s;t Vigour.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;THE Enemy &s;eeing them&s;elves repuls'd,
caus'd two Battallions and ten Squadrons of
their Re&s;erve to advance, and Charge our Right
in Flank; but they were &s;o well received, and
afterwards &s;o clo&s;ly pur&s;u'd, that, of the two
Battallions, not above 50 Men e&s;caped. Upon
this Advantage, our left, and our Center, pu&s;h'd
forward among the Enemies Waggons, break|ing
<PB N="202" REF="209">
all their Left Wing. On their Right <HI>Lew|enhaupt</HI>
rallying his Troops, faced our Men who
were among their Waggons, and cau&s;ed &s;uch a
Fire to be made on our Battallions and Squa|drons,
as oblig'd them to retire; but our Cen|ter,
and Left Wing advanced at the &s;ame Time
again&s;t the Enemy, who were oblig'd to Face
to the Right about, to make Head again&s;t us; then
the Charge, was renewed with greater Fury than
before, both by the Hor&s;e and Foot, and their
Fire which the Enemy an&s;wer'd duly, did not
cea&s;e 'till it was dark Night, when we could no
longer di&s;tinugi&s;h our own Men, from our
Enemis.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;IN the Night, his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty con&s;ider|ing
the Difficulty of di&s;lodging the Enemy
from behind the Waggons, forbid the Officers,
on pain of being Ca&s;hier'd, and the Soldiers of
being hang'd, to quit their Ranks, to rifle the
killed; &s;o the Army kept all Night under Arms
watching the Enemy, In the mean Time the
Trophies of the Day, were pre&s;ented to his
Maje&s;ty, con&s;i&s;ting of 47 Colours, and 10
Standards; and 16 Cannon, which he had
gain'd, were added to our Train of Artillery.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;THUS we pa&s;s'd the Night, which was very
Cold, and towards the Morning, we &s;aw the
Enemy kindle Fires, about their Waggons. His
<HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty order'd that Fires al&s;o &s;hould be
made in the Front of our Line, and that
we &s;hould hold our &s;elves in a Readine&s;s again&s;t
Break of Day; which being come, we march'd
towards the Enemies Waggons, expecting to meet no le&s;s Re&s;i&s;tance than before; but we
found that <HI>Lewenhaupt,</HI> had made u&s;e of that
Stratagem to cover his Flight, abandoning to
<PB N="203" REF="210">
our Di&s;cretion, all the Wounded, and 7000
Waggons de&s;ign'd to Supply the Want under
which the King his Ma&s;ter Labours.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;GENERAL <HI>Pflug</HI> was immediately order'd
with a 1000 Granadiers on Hor&s;e-back, and
2000 Dragoons, to pur&s;ue and harra&s;s the fly|ing
Enemy; he had not March'd above half
a League, when he found the Remains of the
Enemy in a Wood, and falling upon them,
he made a Slaughter among them for the
Space of a League and a half, to <HI>Propoi|&s;ick'</HI>
where the re&s;t of the Run-aways, to the
Number of 3000, retir'd into the Church-Yard.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;OUR General advancing to Force them,
they made a Signal that they were de&s;irous
to Capitulate; and then he &s;ent a Lieutenant
Colonel, with &s;ix Granadiers, to receive their
Offers of Capitulation; but many of the <HI>Swe|di&s;h</HI>
Soldiers being Drunk with Brandy, would
not agree to their Officers Propo&s;itions, and
many of them Firing, kill'd two of our Gra|nadiers,
the Lieutenant Colonel &s;eeing their
Headine&s;s, retir'd. And General <HI>Pflug</HI> re&s;olv'd
not to &s;pare them; our Granadiers and Dra|goons
enter'd the Church Yard Sword in
Hand, kill'd all that re&s;i&s;ted. During this Exe|cution,
part of them fled towards the River
<HI>Soza;</HI> General <HI>Miku&s;ch</HI> pur&s;u'd that Party two
Hours, and &s;aw Count <HI>Leuwenhaupt</HI> Swimming
through that River among his Men; whereup|on
he &s;wam it with his Detachment, and com|ing
to the other Side, mo&s;t of the <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> Offi|cers
begg'd Mercy and he gave them Quarter,
but caus'd the Soldiers to be put to the Sword:
He rejoyn'd General <HI>Pflug,</HI> with all the Officers
<PB N="202" REF="211">
<GAP DESC="DUPLICATE" EXTENT="1 page">
<PB N="203" REF="212">
<GAP DESC="DUPLICATE" EXTENT="1 page">
<PB N="204" REF="213">
and Booty; and tho&s;e Pri&s;oners reported, that
General <HI>Leuwenhaupt</HI> was Dead of two Shots
through his Body.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;THE next Day, his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty caus'd
Thanks to be &s;olemnly return'd to the Almigh|ty
for this &s;ignal Victory, which co&s;t the Ene|my
20 Regiments, amounting to 16000 Men,
among them, Major General <HI>Sculemburgh,</HI> who
was kill'd on the Field of Battle, with all the
Officers that were not taken Pri&s;oners.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;WE have 2673 Pri&s;oners, 103 Officers, 47
Colours, 10 Standards, 16 Cannon, 7000 Wag|gons,
and all the Arms and Baggage; the
Victory being compleat.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;ON our Side, we lo$t 70 Officers kill'd or
dangerou&s;ly wounded, 1277 Soldiers kill'd,
2734 wounded, among them his Highne&s;s the
Prince of <HI>Darm&s;tadt,</HI> General <HI>Baur,</HI> Colonel
<HI>Weiden,</HI> and two <HI>Mu&s;covite</HI> Colonels.&endq;</P>
<P>UPON this Di&s;&s;a&s;ter, the <HI>Swedes</HI> were at a full
Stop, they could neither go forward, or back|ward,
they had lo&s;t all their Ammunition, and all
their Magazine, among which were 20000 &s;mall
Arms, wherewith they propos'd to Arm, and
Di&s;cipline the <HI>Co&s;acks</HI> which &s;hould Rebel; they
lo&s;t 500 Ton of Musket Bullets, 6000 Barrels of
Powder, and about 600000 Rixdolars in Money;
their Communication with <HI>Poland</HI> was entirely
cut off, and the Palatine of <HI>Kiow,</HI> the King of
<HI>Sweden</HI>'s faithful Allie, was utterly di&s;abled
by another Defeat given him, by the Crown
Army of <HI>Poland;</HI> &s;o that King <HI>Stani&s;laus,</HI>
and General <HI>Cra&s;&s;au,</HI> who with another Army of
18000 were advanc'd almo&s;t to <HI>Lemberg,</HI> could
get no intelligence of the King of <HI>Sweden,</HI> or
<PB N="205" REF="214">
of his Army, nor by any Means break thorough
to &s;et him Free.</P>
<P>IT is true, the Province of <HI>Ukrania,</HI> a rich,
fertil, and plentiful Country, &s;upply'd the King
of <HI>Sweden</HI> effectually with Provi&s;ions in Great
Plenty; and his <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty &s;eeing what
Condition he was reduced to, mark'd out a Camp,
in a very advantagious Situation, on the River
<HI>De&s;na</HI> between <HI>Czeruikhow</HI> and <HI>Meko&s;zi;</HI> where he
caus'd &s;trong Entrenchments to be made, and
mounted his Cannon re&s;olving not to be attack'd
by Surprize. Here he re&s;olv'd to &s;tay till he had
recruited his Magazines of Millitary Provi&s;ions
as well as his Army with Troops; but during his
whole Stay here, his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty &s;o &s;cour'd
the Country with continual Parties, that no Me&s;|&s;enger
he could ever &s;end arriv'd, nor could he
receive any Intelligence from the re&s;t of <HI>Poland,</HI>
or they from him.</P>
<P>DURING this long Encampment, his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI>
Maje&s;ty's General, by ince&s;&s;ant Parties, cut off
abundance of his Men, and continually harra&s;s'd
them with his Troops, and gave them two or three
very con&s;iderable Defeats.</P>
<P>IN the mean Time, the <HI>Swedes</HI> on the other
Hand, found Means to get &s;ome Supplies of Amu|nition
out of <HI>Podolia,</HI> and from <HI>Lemberg</HI> they got
&s;ome &s;mall Arms, tho' all was with great Difficulty
brought to them, the Confederates being &s;tronge&s;t
on that Side, and it being a mo&s;t tedious Way to
bring things all by Land Carriage to <HI>Kiovia</HI> in
the <HI>Ukrainal&s;o;</HI> and on the Side of <HI>Vol$inia,</HI> they
Li&s;ted a great many Men, with which they fill'd
up all the Regiments of General <HI>Leuwenbaupt</HI>'s
Army, which we had defeated, and made them
as &s;trong as when we fir&s;t attack'd him; on|ly,
<PB N="206" REF="215">
with this Exception, namely, that they were
not &s;o good Soldiers by a great Deal.</P>
<P>THUS the two Armies pa&s;s'd the Winter, and
the fir&s;t part of the Spring. But the Sea&s;on ad|vancing,
and the King of <HI>Sweden</HI> &s;till fancying
him&s;elf &s;trong enough to put his De&s;igns in Ex|ecution,
and hoping for great Matters from the
<HI>Co&s;&s;acks,</HI> he prepar'd for his Enterprize.</P>
<P>IT &s;hould have been ob&s;ery'd here, that the
Rebel <HI>Mazeppa,</HI> finding the <HI>Czar</HI> Pre&s;s'd hard up|on
the <HI>Co&s;&s;acks,</HI> and terrify'd them from follow|ing
him; &s;o that he could not bring that Number
with him to his new Confederate the King of
<HI>Swden,</HI> as he had Promis'd, endeavour'd by Par|ties
and Inroads on the side of <HI>Mu&s;covy,</HI> to in|tercept
all the Provi&s;ions that &s;hould be convey'd
that Way to the <HI>Czar</HI>'s Army, and ravag'd the
Country far and near, by the King of <HI>Sweden</HI>'s
Order; to puni&s;h them for which Treachery, Prince <HI>Manzickoff</HI> advanc'd with Treachery,
Prince <HI>Menzickoff</HI> advanc'd with 24000 Foot,
And 6000 Hor&s;e, to the Ea&s;t Side of the <HI>Ukrain,</HI>
and having caus'd the greater Part of the <HI>Co&s;|&s;acks</HI>
on that Side to return to their Duty, he
a$van$'d to <HI>B$ury$ Mazeppa</HI>'s chief Town and
which he had &s;or$i&s;y'd, as well as the Place and
Time would permit; <HI>Mazeppa</HI> &s;ore&s;ecing the De|&s;ign,
Pu$ 6000 <HI>Co&s;&s;aeks,</HI> bold, hardv re$olute Fel|l$$s
into the Place; which be&s;$les, was very
well &s;ur$i&s;n'd with every T$ing nece&s;&s;ary for it's
D$fence; the Prince, however, $ame &s;a$ly up
$word$ Town, and formall$ attack$d it, tho the
S$$$$ in a marner look $$$n.</P>
<P>He had $word$ Time to l$$&s;e in the Formalities
pece&s;$$ f$r a lo$g $$ge, but having r$i&s;ed
three Battcries in two Days Time, with the Help
or a $$$lti$$$ of Han$s, he fired &s;o furiou&s;ly on
<PB N="207" REF="216">
the Place, that in one Night and Day, he had
made a tolerable Breach, which tho' it was not
what they call practicable, in the Common Dia|lect
of the Enginiers, yet he caus'd it to be
&s;torm'd: The Garri&s;on defended them&s;elves with
a great deal of Ob&s;tinacy, and kill'd the <HI>Mu&s;|covites</HI>
by Heaps in their Ditches. But the Ru&s;&s;i|ans
led on again, and annimated by the Pre&s;ence
of their Generals, fell on with &s;uch Fury, and
withal, in &s;uch Numbers, that they enter'd the
Town Sword in Hand, cut all the Traytor <HI>Co&s;&s;acks,</HI>
being 6000, as above, in Pieces; not giving Quar|ter
to one of them; which was a Piece of requi&s;ite
Ju&s;tice, not only upon them for their Trea&s;on
and Rebellion, but in Terror to the re&s;t, who
had &s;hew'd Inclination enough to Rebel; as for
the Town it was plunder'd by the Soldiers.</P>
<P>NOR did their Execution fail of its di&s;ign'd End,
for it effectually aw'd the re&s;t of the <HI>Co&s;&s;acks,</HI> from revolting to the King of <HI>Sweden,</HI> as was the de&s;ign
of the whole Nation of them, be&s;ides which, it
le&s;&s;en'd the King of <HI>Swedens</HI> Army 6000 Men, for
tho&s;e 6000 were Part of the 10000 who had join'd
the <HI>Swedes</HI> with their General.</P>
<P>AFTER the taking of this Town, which was
Sight of the whole <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> Army, the River
<HI>De&s;ua</HI> only parting them; over which, however,
the <HI>Swedes</HI> had no Bridge. I &s;ay, after this, the
<HI>Ru&s;&s;ian</HI> General &s;uppre&s;&s;'d entirely the Di&s;&s;afecti|on
of the <HI>Co&s;&s;acks,</HI> and having proclaim'd <HI>Mazep|pa</HI>
a Traytor, and cau&s;ed him to be bang'd in
Effigic, made the whole Body of <HI>Co&s;&s;acks</HI> meet,
and choo&s;e another Chief or General, which was
done with the loud Acclamations of the People;
&s;o the <HI>Czar</HI> was in &s;ome Degree even with the
King of <HI>Sweden,</HI> for if he depo&s;ed one King, the
<PB N="208" REF="217">
<HI>Czar</HI> of <HI>Mu&s;covy</HI> now depo&s;ed another, for tho
<HI>Mazeppa</HI> was not a King in Title, he was equal
to a King in Power, and every way Equal if not
Superior to King <HI>Augu&s;tus</HI> in the divided Circum|&s;tances,
in which his Power &s;tood, even at the
be&s;t of it.</P>
<P>AND now the King of <HI>Sweden</HI> having re&s;olv'd
to move forward, decamp'd, in an evil Hour for
him, in the begining of <HI>June,</HI> and pa&s;&s;ing the <HI>De&s;|na</HI>
at <HI>Czeruibow</HI> advanced towards <HI>Pultowa.</HI> The
Country all the Way in this March being low and
level, is full of Rivers-which fall into the <HI>Neiper,</HI>
and lying ju&s;t cro&s;s the Way which the <HI>Swedes</HI> were
to March, they had &s;ometimes three or four of
tho&s;e Rivers to pa&s;s in a Day; the Rea&s;on of this
is plain, for that the Cour&s;e of the <HI>Bori&s;thenes</HI>
being here from <HI>North</HI> to <HI>South,</HI> and the great
River receiving into it all the &s;maller Rivers of
the Country of both Sides, the Cour&s;e of tho&s;e
Rivers naturally mu&s;t be from <HI>Ea&s;t</HI> to <HI>We&s;t,</HI> on
the Side where the <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> Army march'd.</P>
<P>THIS retarded the March of the <HI>Swedes</HI> very
much, who were oblig'd to mate Bridges over
mo&s;t of tho&s;e Rivers, and who drew a great
Train of Carriages with them for their Baggage,
and Ammunition, be&s;ides their Artillery.</P>
<P>SOME of the&s;e Rivers indeed, the Weather
being dry, and the Sea&s;on &s;o far advanc'd, were
low, and might be foarded by the Cavalry and
Carriages, but others again could not.</P>
<P>HOWEVER, the King of <HI>Sweden</HI> who&s;e Autho|rity
pre&s;s'd on his Men, forc'd to March over all
the Rivers, and whatever Difficulties offer'd to
&s;tand in his Way, pu&s;h'd on till he came to <HI>Pul|towa;</HI>
a Town which the <HI>Czar</HI> had forti$y'd in a
better manner than formerly; and as it was a
<PB N="209" REF="218">
Frontier again&s;t the <HI>Budriack Tarter,</HI> who u&s;ed to
make their Incur&s;ions that way into <HI>Mu&s;covy.</HI></P>
<P>His <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty finding the <HI>Swedes</HI> in
Motion, broke up with all his Army from <HI>Smo|len&s;ko,</HI>
where he had encamped in order to di&s;pute
the Ground Inch by Inch with them, if they had
offer'd to move towards <HI>Mo&s;cow,</HI> and mov'd after
them; he had never &s;tirr'd from that Situation
with the Gro&s;s of his Army while the King of
<HI>Sweden</HI> lay on the Bank of the <HI>De&s;na,</HI> lea&s;t find|ing
his Army remov'd, they &s;hould counter
March and &s;lip by him on the Way to <HI>Mo&s;cow;</HI>
but now finding the <HI>Swedes,</HI> running farther
into the Net, he pur&s;u'd with his whole Army,
which was about 70000 Men, be&s;ides about 42000
which were po&s;ted at di&s;tant Places, as at <HI>Mohi|low,</HI>
and at the River <HI>Bug,</HI> to prevent Succours
pa&s;&s;ing to the <HI>Swedes.</HI></P>
<P>WITH this Army his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty follow'd
the <HI>Swedes</HI> &s;o clo&s;e, that he was always at Hand
to take any Advantage that might offer.</P>
<P>THE King of <HI>Sweden,</HI> who was now near the
End of his good Fortune, and found him&s;elf
embarra&s;s'd with the Difficulties of the Country,
encamp'd under the Walls of a Town, tho' not
considerable in it &s;elf, yet better fortified, and
better furni&s;h'd than he expected, wanting many
Things nece&s;&s;ary for a Seige of Importance; and
which was wor&s;e, the <HI>Czar,</HI> who he had always
flatter'd him&s;elf, would never venture a Battle, was,
as I have &s;aid at his Back with an Army of 70000
Men, and not only &s;eem'd re&s;olv'd to venture a
Battle with him, but po&s;ted him&s;elf in &s;uch a man|ner,
as that it was apparent he would Be&s;iege him
and his Camp, and perhaps attack his Intrench|ments.</P>
<P><PB N="210" REF="219">
HAD not the King of <HI>Sweden</HI>'s Courage exceed|ed
his Di&s;cretion at that Time, and his ill Fate
hurry'd him on to his own De&s;truction, he would
certainly have carry'd on his Attacks in the u&s;ual
Form, and choo&s;ing a &s;trong Situation, have en|camped
with the Gro&s;s of his Army to cover the
Siege; expecting that if the <HI>Czar</HI> would rai&s;e the
Seige, he &s;hould fight him with all the Di&s;advan|tages
u&s;ual on &s;uch Occa&s;ions; as namely, that of
attacking a Powerful Army entrenche'd up to the
Teeth, and po&s;ted with all po&s;&s;ible Art and Ad|vantage.</P>
<P>BUT on the other Hand, had their Re&s;olution
to Fight been attended with the u&s;ual Prudence of
a good General, &s;uch as the King of <HI>Sweden</HI> cer|tainly
was, and &s;uch, as if he had not been &s;o
him&s;elf, all his other leading Men were e&s;teem'd
to be; particularly, Field Mari&s;chal <HI>Rhen&s;child,</HI>
the Generals <HI>Lewenhaupt, Slippenback, Stakelberg,
Stenbook</HI> and others; and it was very &s;trange they
&s;hould not re$rain him, by Rea&s;oning again&s;t the
Mea&s;ures taken; but to do him Ju&s;tice, it is re|ported
that his <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty was not &s;o much
for fighting as his Generals were, and that it was
$word$ in a Council of War, before the King gave
his Opinion: The ca&s;e was dubious, and every
Man $word$ to &s;peak fir&s;t again&s;t Fighting, lea&s;t
be &s;hould be &s;uppo&s;ed to want Courage, and lea&s;t
the King, who&s;e Temper was 7s;o well known,
&s;hould re&s;ert it; thus it was that all Men voted
for $span$ even almo&s;t every one of them
were again&s;t it in their Judgements.</P>
<P>THIS was too much the Effect of the exceed|ing
Fire in the Temper of their Monarch, who was
&s;o much $word$ by his Officers, that they it
$word$ voted as they thought would be mo&s;t agree|able
<PB N="211" REF="220">
to their Prince's Humour, than Safe and pru|dent
for his Intere&s;t and Honour.</P>
<P>THE Neighbourhood and Strength of the <HI>Mu&s;covite</HI>
Army made it difficult, and &s;carce practicable
to carry on the Siege of the Place, the Garri&s;on
being numerous al&s;o, and well furni&s;h'd, and the
<HI>Swedes</HI> began to &s;ee a Nece&s;&s;ity of removing the
Enemy, or of rai&s;ing the Siege, and upon this
Occa&s;ion, the great Council of War was called,
where it was, unfortunately for them, re&s;olv'd
to Fight.</P>
<P>BEING now come to mention the Battle it &s;elf,
I refer the Reader to a full Account of it given
by the Enemy them&s;elves, becau&s;e what they ac|knowledge
comes with ah Authority not to be
deny'd; whereas, &s;peaking of a Thing of &s;uch
Con&s;equence on the Side of that Monarch, who&s;e
Story we write, we may be the more &s;u&s;pected
of Flattery and partiality; take it then from
their own Accounts as follows,</P>
<P>&startq;Our Army, <HI>&s;ay</HI> they, con&s;i&s;ted of about 36000
Men if we had been all together, of whom our
Cavalry made the better Half; our Infantry in
the Battle, were not above 15000; neither had
we any Artillery with us; the De&s;ign being to
force an Enterance, and then break in with our
Hor&s;e; of the&s;e Forces we left our whole Body
of Re&s;erve as before noted, in the Camp; which,
with other Troops left there, were about 8000
Men; &s;o that in the Battle we had not above
28000 Men.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;THE King led on his Cavalry, and with him
General <HI>Lewenhaupt, Steenboch,</HI> and <HI>Spar; Rhen&s;|child,
Horn and Stakelberg</HI> commanded the Foot;
as &s;oon as we came out of the Defiles, and &s;aw
the Countenance of the Enemy, it was ea&s;ie to
<PB N="212" REF="221">
&s;ee we had a terrible Task on our Hands; but
there was no looking back, the King with his
u&s;ual intrepidity advanc'd to the Charge, and
with his Hor&s;e fell upon a great Body of <HI>Mu&s;co|vite</HI>
Hor&s;e, who were advanc'd from The re&s;t,
and in a Moment drove them into the Line of
Hor&s;e, which &s;tood behind them, upon which
the re&s;t of the <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> Hor&s;e advancing the
whole Line acted at once, and pu&s;h'd the Ene|my
&s;everal times into Confu&s;ion; but by the
Vigilance of their Officers, and the help of new
Troops, they re&s;tored their Line and fought with
the utmo&s;t ob&s;tinacy: During this part of the
Action, the Enemy with a great Body of Hor&s;e,
and &s;ome Foot had wheel'd at &s;ome di&s;tance,
and appear'd on our Flank in order to &s;ur|round
our Cavalry, &s;ome Troops charg'd them,
but being over power'd were repul&s;ed, and
this made us &s;lacken the Charge in Front for
fear of being cut of from our Infantry.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;THAT in the mean time our Infantry ad|vancing,
and the Hor&s;e making a Halt till they
came up, form'd them&s;elves in order of Battle,
the Hor&s;e on the Wings, and the Foot in Cen|ter,
and advanc'd again directly to the Enemy,
Charging them with great Fury and good Suc|ce&s;s;
but the Cannon from the entrench'd
Camp advancing, and the Troops opening in
&s;everal Places for their playing upon us; it
was impo&s;&s;ible our Foot could keep their or|der,
or the Men &s;tand in the Face of &s;eventy
Peices of Cannon, loaden with Cartouches of
&s;mall Shot; &s;o that our Generals &s;aw it ab&s;olute|ly
nece&s;&s;ary to draw of the Foot, the Hor&s;e all
this while continu'd engaged, and drove the
Cavalry of the Enemy every where before them,
<PB N="213" REF="222">
but the Enemies Foot advancing to &s;upport
their Cavalry with their Fire, our Hor&s;e al&s;o
&s;ounded a Retreat, and drew off in very good
order out of the Field of Battle, recover|ing
the Defiles were our Foot was po&s;ted. The
Enemy made a no pur&s;uit at that time, the E|nemy
made &s;hew of advancing indeed on our
Left, and &s;ome Skirmi&s;hes happen'd, but they
were beaten off with Lo&s;s; however, having
thus left the Field of Battle to the Enemy, &s;e|veral
Di&s;a&s;ters follow'd; as fir&s;t, being cut of
from our Camp, our Body of Re&s;erve, our Ar|tillery,
heavy Baggage, Carriages, <HI>&amp;c.</HI> fell all
into the Enemies Hands, and the Troops left
there were oblig'd to yeild them&s;elves Pri&s;o|ners
of War; in this Condition there was nothing
left to con&s;ider of, but Retreating with all po&s;|&s;ible
Speed before the Enemy &s;hould be in a
po&s;ture to attack us, and the way for this was,
if po&s;&s;ible to reach the <HI>Bari&s;thenes,</HI> and get
means to pa&s;s over the Troops, and reach to
<HI>Kiou.</HI>&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;GENERAL <HI>Lewenhaupt</HI> had the Conduct of the
Retreat, and he march'd with &s;uch Expedition,
that all the Troops came to the Bank of the
River the next Day, about One at Night, tho'
extreamly fatigu'd and harra&s;s'd, e&s;pecially
the poor Infantry, of whom many died by the
way, either of their Wounds, or by the extremity
of the March; in&s;omuch, that as appear'd after|wards,
there were not 4000 of them left, above
3000 of them cho&s;e rather to fall into the Enemies
Hands, then &s;uffer &s;o &s;evere a March, and &s;o drop'd
off &s;ome and &s;ome by the way, expecting every
Hour to be knock'd on the Head by the Ene|my,
many of them wandered about the Coun|try,
<PB N="214" REF="223">
and got into <HI>Poland</HI> afterwards, and Li&s;ted
in the Troops of King <HI>Stani&s;lans,</HI> &s;o e&s;caping to
the <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> Army at better Lei&s;ure.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;BUT we were in no better Condition now then
before, for the River was a full &s;top to us; Boats
there was none, we had no Materials for a
Bridge, or time to ma ke it, we knew the Ene|my
was at our Heels; we had neither Strength
left to Defend our&s;elves, nor Ammunition to
Supply a Battle if we were di&s;po&s;ed to it; nei|ther
had we Provi&s;ions to keep our Men from
peri&s;hing: In this &s;trait the main Concern of
our Generals was for the &s;afety of the King, to
have him fall into the Hands of the Enemy
was wor&s;e than Death to think of, there was
but one way, which was to venture to Swim the
great and rapid River that we lay on the Bank
of, and then to make the be&s;t of his way into the
<HI>Turks</HI> Dominions, his Maje&s;ty made light of the
hazard; but it was ea&s;ie to &s;ee that it was with
extream reluctance that he parted with his be|loved
Troops, who he knew mu&s;t immediately
fall into the Hands of the Enemy; but there
was no deliberating in the Choice; his Maje&s;ty
could not by &s;taying &s;ave his Men, and falling
into the Enemies Hands with them, would but
increa&s;e their Misfortune, &s;o it was re&s;olv'd;
and the next morning the King, attended by
about $word$ of the be&s;t Hor&s;e pa&s;s'd the River in a
little Boat, mo&s;t of the re&s;t Swam the River, be|ing
$word$ by &s;ome <HI>Co&s;&s;ack</HI> Gentlemen, who it
&s;eems in that Country make light of it;
they all $word$ &s;afe on the other Side. His Ma|j$&s;ty
$word$ private Orders to the re&s;t of his
Men $word$ if $word$ could make any e&s;cape, they
&s;hould f$llow towards the <HI>Turks</HI> Dominions,
<PB N="215" REF="224">
where they would &s;oon hear of him, if he got
&s;afe thither. That &s;ame Evening the <HI>Mu&s;covite</HI>
Prince <HI>Menzickoff</HI> at the Head of about 10000
Hor&s;e, appear'd in &s;ight of our Camp, and Ge|neral
<HI>Rein&s;child,</HI> who was then Pri&s;oner among
them, having &s;ignify'd to them, as they &s;aid,
that it was probable in the Condition we was
in, we would Capitulate; the Prince &s;ent a Trum|pet
with a <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> Captain, and a <HI>Mu&s;covite</HI> Co|lonel
with a Letter to our General, to offer us,
if we would Surrender, good U&s;age and hono|rable
Conditions; this was the more welcome
to us, becau&s;e it was wholly unexpected: The
matter needed no Debate, our Circum|&s;tances
admitted of nothing el&s;e, and if
he had not &s;ent to us; we mu&s;t have &s;ent to
him, and have yeilded; wherefore our General
after holding a &s;hort Council of War,
return'd a re&s;pectful An&s;wer to the Prince,
&s;ignifying, that if he might have Soldier like
u&s;age, and be treated honourably, he would en|ter
into a Treaty, but that if not, they would
die with their Swords in their Hands, and &s;ell
their Lives as dear as they could; in the mean
time many of our Men enrag'd at the Thoughts
of the Slavery of <HI>Mu&s;covy,</HI> threw them&s;elves
madly into the River, &s;ome &s;trip'd and Swam,
but they found it wor&s;e, for many of them pe|ri&s;h'd
with Hunger, and with wandering naked
over the Country, and &s;ome not able to reach
over, for the River is there very Broad, were car|ried
down the Current and drown'd; to be &s;hort
with this di&s;mal Story; we obtain'd very hono|rable
Conditions, and Surrendered to the <HI>Mu&s;|covites;</HI>
tho' we cannot &s;ay tho&s;e Conditions
have been &s;o honourably p$r&s;$rm'd as they
<PB N="216" REF="225">
ought to have been. The Articles of our Sur|render
were as follows.&endq;</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2>
<HEAD>THE under-written AGREEMENT &s;hall be
concluded in the Name of his Czari&s;h Maje&s;ty,
the Emperor of Ru&s;&s;ia, on the one Hand, and of
the King of Sweden on the other Part; by the
&s;ub&s;cribing Generals.</HEAD>
<P>I. ALL the <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> Troops, without Exception,
who were commanded by Count <HI>Lewenhaupt,</HI>
as well Generals and Officers, as Soldiers; &s;hall with
their Servants yield them&s;elves Pri&s;oners of War to
his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty.</P>
<P>II. All private Soldiers, Troopers, Dragoons, and
Mu&s;quetiers, &s;hall lay down their Arms, and remain
Pri&s;oners of War, 'till their Exchange or Ran&s;om;
but they &s;hall keep their Mounting, and all that they
have, except their Arms and Ammunition; and all
their Hor&s;es, exept tho&s;e belonging to the Officers,
&s;hall be delivered to his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty.</P>
<P>III. All General Officers, and other Officers, &s;hall
keep their Baggage and Equipages, and their Per&s;ons
&s;hall be relea&s;ed without Ran&s;om, or Exchange, as
&s;oon as Peace &s;hall be made between his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI>
Maje&s;ty, and the King of <HI>Sweden,</HI> and in the mean
Time they &s;hall be honourably us'd, and be permit|ted
to go for a while to their own Country, on their
Parole.</P>
<P>IV. The <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> Artillery, all the Ammunition,
Colours, Standards, and In&s;truments of Mu&s;ick, &s;hall
be deliver'd to his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty, as likewi&s;e the
Military Che&s;t, or Camp Trea&s;ure.</P>
<P><PB N="217" REF="226">
V. The <HI>Zaperogian,</HI> and other Rebels, now a|mong&s;t
the Troops of <HI>Sweden,</HI> &s;hall be immediately
deliver'd to his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty.</P>
<P>VI. For the Security and Confirmation of the&s;e
Agreements, the afore-mentioned Articles, &s;hall be
&s;ign'd by the Generals Commanding the Army of his
<HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty, and that of the King of <HI>Sweden;</HI>
and a Duplicate &s;hall be made of this Capitula|tion.</P>
<CLOSER><DATELINE>Done In the Camp
<HI>Perewoloczea,</HI>
<DATE><HI>June</HI> the 30th.
O. S. 1709.</DATE></DATELINE>
<SIGNED>Sign'd
ALEXANDER, Prince of <HI>Menzicoff.</HI>
Count of <HI>Lewenhaupt.</HI></SIGNED></CLOSER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2>
<HEAD>ADDITION.</HEAD>
<P>All the Officers and Generals, &s;hall not only retain
their Baggage, but likewi&s;e their Servants, and the
Commi&s;&s;ioners, Auditors, Secretaries, Chaplains, and
Surgeons, &s;hall likewi&s;e be permitted to keep their Bag|gage
and Servants as the Officers.</P>
<P>UPON the&s;e Articles they being &s;ent and ex|chang'd,
the next Day being the fir&s;t of <HI>July,</HI>
we laid down our Arms, and &s;o ended our <HI>Mu&s;|covite</HI>
Expedition: The Number and Particulars
of this Surrender, as they were taken an Account
of at the Surrendery; a Duplicate of which was
given to the <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> General, and which was
<PB N="218" REF="227">
afterwards made publick by the <HI>Czar.</HI> Was as
follows,
<HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> Generals Pri&s;oners.</P>
<P>Count <HI>Lewenhaupt,</HI> General of Foot, and Go|vernor
of Riga; M. <HI>Creutz</HI> and <HI>Cra&s;s,</HI> Major Ge|nerals;
the Counts <HI>Douglas</HI> and <HI>Bonde.</HI> Adjutants
of the Field; Mare&s;chal General <HI>Rein&s;child.</HI></P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2>
<HEAD>Regiments of Hor&s;e.</HEAD>
<P>Life Guards, <HI>Carelia,</HI> Standard of the <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI>
Nobility, Standard of the Nobility of <HI>Livonia,
Abo&s;ck</HI> and <HI>Bernebourgh, Smaland, Nieland,</HI> and
<HI>North Scania. South Scania, Cru&s;e,</HI> and <HI>O&s;ter
Gotten.</HI></P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2>
<HEAD>Regiments of Dragoons.</HEAD>
<P>Guards, <HI>Wenner&s;tadt,</HI> Prince of <HI>Wirtemberg,
Slippenbach, Schrotenfels, Meyerfeld, Helms,
Tauben, Ducker, Alfendiel, Guilden&s;tern;</HI> in
the&s;e Regiments were &s;even Colonels, nam'd in the
Li&s;t, ten Lieutenant Colonels, and &s;ixteen Majors
nam'd, 182 Captains, 217 Captain Liuetenants, 215
Cornets, 10 Quarterma&s;ters of Regiments, 17 Adju|tants,
522 inferior Officers, and 8637 Corporals and
private Soldiers: Be&s;ides 26 Chaplains, 4 Commi&s;&s;a|ri$s,
18 Clarks, 20 Surgeons, and 44 Surgeons Ser|vants,
13 Kettle Drums, 67 Trumpeters and Haut|loy$,
$7 Drummers, 528 Provo&s;ts, and nece&s;&s;ary
Attendants on the Troops.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2>
<HEAD>Of the King's Foot Guards.</HEAD>
<P>Colonel, <HI>$aro$</HI> $word$ Major, Count <HI>Oxen&s;t$rn,</HI>
8 Captains, 19 Lieutenants, 21 $word$, 1 Adju|tant,
<PB N="219" REF="228">
121 inferior Officers, and 1196 Corporals and
private Soldiers; be&s;ides a Commi&s;&s;ary, a Provo&s;t of
the Regiment, 6 Chaplains, 7 Clarks of Regiments,
6 Hautboys, 53 Drumers and Fifes, 13 common
Provo&s;ts, in all 1465.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2>
<HEAD>Regiments of Foot, or Remains of them.</HEAD>
<P>Upland, Dulkler, We&s;tmandland, We&s;tergotz,
Sundermondland, Werk <HI>and</HI> Warmanland, Ofter
Gotten, Jencoping, We&s;ter Gotten, Cronenburgh,
<HI>and</HI> Colmar, in the&s;e Regiments were 2 Colonels
nam'd, 4 Lieutenant Colonels nam;d, 3 Majors nam'd,
60 Captains, 2 Voluntier Captains, 68 Captain Lieu|tenants,
8 Quarter Ma&s;ters, 6 Adjutants, 71 En&s;igns,
296 inferior Officers, and 3056 Corporals and pri|vate
Soldiers; be&s;ides 5 Commi&s;&s;aries, 6 Chaplains,
4 Voluntiers, and 15 Surgeons and their Men; in all
3606.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2>
<HEAD>Officers of Artillery, and Men employ'd in
the Train.</HEAD>
<P>Colonel <HI>Bierone,</HI> &s;ince dead of his Wounds, Lieute|nant
Colonel Appleman, 1 Po&s;t, 1 Major, 4 Captains,
1 Captain Lieutenant, 6 Sub-Lieutenants, 6 En&s;igns,
1 Adjutant, with Gunners, Montro&s;&s;es, Miners,
Fireworkers, Bombardiers, and Artificers; to the
Number in all, 535; the Total 1627 Per&s;ons, be|&s;ides,
the following of the King's Hou&s;hold, <HI>Charles
Guntzau,</HI> Chamberlain; <HI>Sickigell,</HI> Apothecary of
the Hou&s;hold and Army; <HI>Sokimbers,</HI> Quarter Ma|&s;ters; <HI>A&s;il, Bier,</HI> and <HI>Brampt,</HI> Commi&s;&s;iaries; 5
Purveyors, and other Servants, Colonels, Standars,
142; Bra&s;s Cannon, four five Pounders, one of five
Pound and a half Ball, 12 of three pound Ball;
<PB N="220" REF="229">
<HI>Ru&s;&s;ian</HI> Pieces of 3 Pound Ball, taken by the <HI>Swedes</HI>
at <HI>We&s;prick,</HI> 2 Hanwitzers of 16 Chambers, 4 Mor|tars
of &s;ix, and four of three Pound Ball.</P>
<P>OUR Lo&s;s being thus of our whole Army, it is
needle&s;s to enquire how many fell in each particu|lar
Action; but, this is certain, that what the
<HI>Mu&s;covites</HI> have publi&s;h'd of 10000 Men &s;lain in
the Battle, cannot be true; we reckon about 6000
kill'd in the Action, 2000 Pri&s;oners, at that time
al&s;o, 7000 in the Camp before <HI>Pultowa,</HI> about
2000 who &s;wam over the River, with, and after
the King, 3000 who wandred away and e&s;cap'd
into the Country, and 16000 now with General
<HI>Leuwenhaupt;</HI> thus far the <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> Account.</P>
<P>I COME then to the Account, which was given
from the <HI>Mu&s;covite</HI> Army, which is more proper|ly
my Part, and which varies in nothing, but the
Manner of Things: Which, however, is very
&s;ignificant to know, and is as follows.</P>
<P>&startq;AFTER the <HI>Mu&s;covites</HI> had pa&s;s'd the River
<HI>Work&s;$a</HI> with their whole Army on the 20th of
<HI>June, O. S.</HI> they encamp'd within a League of
the <HI>Swedes</HI> till the 24th, that Day they advanc'd
within a Quarter of a League of them, and en|camping,
pre&s;ently caus'd an Entrenchment
to be thrown up before the Camp to prevent
all Surprize; their Cavalr$ was po&s;ted in the
Woods, cover'd by the Re$oubts, furni&s;h'd with
Men; and tho' the <HI>Czar</HI> gave out Orders for
preparing to attack the Enemy, they prevent|ed
him according to their u&s;ual Cu&s;tom; for on
the 27th early in the Morning, while it was
yet dark, the <HI>Swedes</HI> came nut of the Defiles,
where they had lain all Night on their Arms,
and attack'd the <HI>Mu&s;covite</HI> Cavalry both
<PB N="221" REF="230">
with their Hor&s;e and Foot &s;o vigorou&s;ly, that
notwith&s;tanding they were repul&s;ed &s;everal
times, and beaten off with Lo&s;s from the Redoubts
which they a&s;&s;aulted, the <HI>Mu&s;covite</HI> Cavalry,
who cou'd not be a&s;&s;i&s;ted in time by the Infan|try,
were oblig'd to retire towards their En|trenchments;
but &s;oon return'd to the Charge,
entirely defeating the <HI>Swedes</HI> Right Wing, and
took Pri&s;oner General <HI>Slippenback,</HI> who com|manded
it; while this was doing the <HI>Czar</HI> de|tach'd
Prince <HI>Menzickoff,</HI> General in chief of
the Army, and Lieutenant General <HI>Rentzell,</HI> as
well to cut of the Troops, who were advancing
to the A&s;&s;i&s;tance of the Enemy, as to attack
tho&s;e left in the Trenches under the <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> Ge|neral
<HI>Ro&s;en;</HI> the Prince marching accordingly,
met in his way the Enemy's Body of Re&s;erve
of 3000 Men, who&s;e Right Wing was Flank'd
by a Wood; after &s;ome Re&s;&s;i&s;tance he broke
them, put &s;ome to the Sword, gave Quarters to
the re&s;t, and return'd to the main Army; leaving
Lieutenant General <HI>Rentzell</HI> to proceed on
to <HI>Pultowa,</HI> at who&s;e approach the <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> Ge|neral
<HI>Ro&s;en</HI> retir'd with his Regiments into the
Works they had made; however, the <HI>Mu&s;covite</HI>
General attack'd him, and forc'd him after &s;ome
Re&s;&s;i&s;tance to Surrender with all his Men at
Di&s;cretion: On the other hand, the <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> Army
having in retiring joyned their Foot; all
the <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> Army drew up in order of Battle a|gain&s;t
the <HI>Mu&s;covite</HI> Front, at the di&s;tance of a|bout
a Quarter of a League; the <HI>Czar</HI> at the
&s;ame time caus'd two Lines to move out of the
Entrenchments, leaving the Third to guard the
Camp, and drew up his Army in &s;uch a manner,
that his Infantry made the main Body, and
<PB N="222" REF="231">
the Cavalry the two Wings, of which the
Right was commanded by Lieutenant <HI>Bauer</HI>
in the room of Lieutenant General <HI>Rence,</HI> who
was wounded in the fir&s;t Engagement: The
Left was commanded by Prince <HI>Menzickoff,</HI> his
Pre&s;ence being mo&s;t nece&s;&s;ary, and his main
Body was commanded by the <HI>Czar</HI> in Per&s;on:
The Field Mar&s;hal <HI>Czeremettoff;</HI> the Generals
of the Foot, Prince <HI>Rep$in</HI> and M. <HI>Hallard,</HI>
as al&s;o Lieutenant General <HI>Belling</HI> attend|ing
at his Po&s;t; Lieutenant General <HI>Brous</HI> had
the Direction of the Artillery; the <HI>Mu&s;covite</HI>
Army being in this po&s;ture, no &s;ooner began
to move towards the <HI>Swedes,</HI> then contrary to
expectation, the&s;e had the boldne&s;s after the re|pul&s;e
they had receiv'd, to advance to meet
them: About nine in the Morning the Fight
began, and the fire grew thick on both Sides,
which the <HI>Mu&s;covites</HI> continu'd with &s;uch Brave|ry
that they defeated and broke the <HI>Swedes</HI> Army,
after a Battle of half an Hour; a thing very
&s;trange, and put both their Hor&s;e and Foot to
the Rout, the latter not daring to Halt, or
make farther oppo&s;ition, and were driven like
a Herd of Cattle, with Sword, Bayonet and
Pike quite to the Woods. Major-General <HI>Sta|kelberg</HI>
was the fir&s;t Pri&s;oner taken, then Gene|ral
<HI>Hamilton,</HI> Field Mar&s;hal <HI>Rhen&s;child,</HI> the
Prince of <HI>Wirtenberg,</HI> Cou&s;in to the King of
<HI>Sweden;</HI> many Colonels and Subaltern Officers,
and &s;ome thou&s;ands of Foot and Hor&s;e, a great
Number of which yielded them&s;elves volunta|rily
with their Hor&s;es, and Arms. The <HI>Mu&s;co|vites</HI>
Cavalry pur&s;ued the <HI>Swedes</HI> full &s;peed a|bove
half a League, that the Plains and Woods
for three Leagues round the <HI>Pultowa,</HI> were &s;trew|ed
<PB N="223" REF="232">
with the Enemies Bodies; the Number of
their kill'd being 8 or 10000; thus by the help of
the Almighty they gain'd &s;o compleat a Victo|ry
over the <HI>Swedes,</HI> that it is hardly to be paral|lel'd,
and that with little Lo&s;s by the Victori|ous
Arms of the <HI>Czar,</HI> and under his own Con|duct,
in which he mo&s;t eminently fignaliz'd
his Valour and Experience in the War, expo&s;ing
him&s;elf to all Dangers, and had his Hat &s;hot
thro'; Prince <HI>Menzickoff</HI> had three Hor&s;es
wounded under him; 'tis worthy to be remark|ed,
that 'twas only a Line of Foot, of 10000
Men, who defeated the Enemy, the other Line
not being engaged. Here follows a Li&s;t of the
Pri&s;oners, and of what was taken from the
<HI>Swedes,</HI> as far as they could inform them&s;elves
in the fir&s;t two Days.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;COUNT <HI>Piper,</HI> fir&s;t Mini&s;ter to the King, his
Privy Coun&s;ellor, and great Mar&s;hal; Count
<HI>Rein&s;child</HI> Field Mar&s;hal and Privy Coun&s;ellor;
the Majors General, <HI>Slippenback, Stackleberg,
Ro&s;en</HI> and <HI>Hamilton;</HI> the Colonels, Prince <HI>Wir|temberg,</HI>
Prince <HI>Applegreen,</HI> Count <HI>Horn,</HI> and
Prince <HI>Rhen&s;child,</HI> 6 Lieutenant Colonels, 4
Majors, 2 Captains of Hor&s;e, 20 of Foot, 1
Lieutenant of Hor&s;e, 2 of the King's Life|Guards,
1 of the King's Quarter-Ma&s;ters of Re|giments,
53 Lieutenants of Foot, 3 Adjutants,
1 Trumpeter, 4 Surgeons, 3 Clerks of Regi|ments,
21 under Officers of Foot and Hor&s;e,
2528 Hor&s;e and Foot Soldiers, 12 Hautboys, 4
Surgeons Mates, 24 Drums: Of the Chancery
were Pri&s;oners, the Secretary <HI>Cederkielm,</HI> the Se|cretary
<HI>Dickbon,</HI> 2 Writers in the Chancery;
the King's Chaplain, and Mr. <HI>Morbergh;</HI> Pri&s;oners;
<PB N="224" REF="233">
in all 2978, taken from the <HI>Swedes,</HI> the
following Trophies, 34 Standards of Hor&s;e, 29
of Dragoons, 69 Colours, of which 6 are of the
Regiments of Guards; in all 134 Standards and
Colours. In this Battle only 4 Cannon were ta|ken,
becau&s;e the <HI>Swedes</HI> brought no more into
the Action, 1 pair of Kettle Drums of Silver,
belonging to the Guards, 3 Pair of Copper. In
the intrim, Prince <HI>Menzickoff,</HI> who march'd
the 28th in pur&s;uit of the <HI>Swedes,</HI> could not
overtake them till the 30th, notwith&s;tanding
all the Expedition he made; for they retir'd
precipitately, leaving behind them the greate&s;t
part of their Baggage, that Day his Highne&s;s
di&s;cover'd them po&s;ted very Advantageou&s;ly
near the &s;mall Town of <HI>Perecolocza,</HI> at the
Foot of the Mountain on the Bank of the <HI>Bo|ri&s;thenes,</HI>
and was inform'd by the Quarter-Ma&s;ters
of a Regiment, and &s;ome Machians,
who were taken Pri&s;oners; that the King of
<HI>Sweden</HI> had pa&s;s'd the <HI>Bori&s;thenes,</HI> by &s;wim|ming
with Major General <HI>Spar</HI> and <HI>Lagereroon,</HI>
and 300 of the be&s;t mounted Troopers about 3
Hou$&s; before, and had left on this Side the re|mains
of his Army, under the command of Ge|neral
<HI>Lewenhaupt:</HI> Some &s;aid the King was
wounded the Day before the Battle in the Head,
others in the Ankle; and indeed, &s;o various
were the Stories concerning him, that we
cannot here repeat them; he retired as
they &s;ay to <HI>Ockzakow,</HI> a Town at the Mouth of
the Bay, in the Country of the <HI>Budzaick Tar|tars;</HI>
but we heard afterwards that he was gone
to <HI>$ender,</HI> on the River <HI>Nie&s;ter,</HI> and that
he was Royally us'd by the <HI>Turks;</HI> where we
mu&s;t leave him, and return to Prince <HI>Menzic|koff;</HI>
<PB N="225" REF="234">
who without lo&s;s of time, caus'd his Body
of Men, which did not exceed 9000 to advance
again&s;t the <HI>Swedes,</HI> and &s;ome Pri&s;oners having ad|ded,
that they believed they might be di&s;pos'd to
&s;urrender them&s;elves on terms of Capitulation:
His Highne&s;s &s;ummon'd them to yield, intimating
to them, that they were depriv'd of all Means of
e&s;caping by a Retreat, and that if they rejected
his offer, they were not to hope for Quarter,
but be all put to the Sword.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;HEREUPON the <HI>Swedes</HI> &s;ent to his Highne&s;s
Major General <HI>Cruitz,</HI> Colonel <HI>Duckers,</HI> Lieute|nant
Colonel <HI>Tran&s;etter,</HI> and Adjutant General
<HI>Douglas</HI> to Capitulate, and an Agreement was
pre&s;ently made, &s;ign'd afterwards by Prince
<HI>Menzickoff,</HI> and General <HI>Lewenhaupt;</HI> pur&s;uant
to which, the <HI>Swedes</HI> who contrary to all expecta|tion,
were yet 16286 Men &s;trong, well arm'd
and mo&s;tly Hor&s;e, yielded them&s;elves Pri&s;oners
of War, and laid down their Arms, &s;urrender|ing
that Day to Lieutenant General <HI>Bauer,</HI>
with the Camp Che&s;t or Trea&s;ure, the Military
Chancery; all the Colours, Standards, Kettle-Drums,
and Drums; the <HI>Czar</HI> came up in Per|&s;on
and joyn'd Prince <HI>Menzickoff,</HI> ju&s;t at the
time when the <HI>Swedes</HI> laid down their Arms.&endq;</P>
<P>IMMEDIATELY after the Action, and before
the taking of General <HI>Leuwenhaupt,</HI> and the Sur|render
of the Army Pri&s;oners; the <HI>Czar,</HI> him&s;elf,
&s;ent an Account of the Fight in general, to &s;eve|ral
Courts, Princes, and Per&s;ons, by Expre&s;s; the
Letters being written by his Maje&s;ty's own Hand,
as particularly, to the Court of <HI>Eerlin,</HI> to <HI>Vienna,</HI>
to the <HI>Hague,</HI> and King <HI>Augu&s;tus;</HI> the <HI>Czar</HI>'s Let|ter
to his Mini&s;ter, M. <HI>Goltz,</HI> at the Court of <HI>Ber|lin,</HI>
was as follows.</P>
<LETTER>
<PB N="226" REF="235">
<OPENER>To the General, Velt Mari&s;chal, Lieutenant.
MONSIEUR,</OPENER>
<P>I Acquaint you, by the&s;e Pre&s;ents, with the great
Victory I have (unexpectedly) obtain'd, by the
Ble&s;&s;ing God, and the un&s;peakable Bravery of my
Troops, with very little Lo&s;s on my Side; in the fol|lowing
Manner: The Enemy early this Morning, at|tack'd
with all their Forces, both Hor&s;e and Foot;
our Cavalry, which behav'd them&s;elves &s;o well, that the
<HI>Swedes</HI> were repul&s;ed with great Lo&s;s; they drew up
again in Order of Battle before our Army, where|upon,
we cau&s;ed our Infantry to march out of our
Intrenchments, and drew up our Forces in order of
Battle; and po&s;ted our Hor&s;e, on the Wings of the
Foot, which being perceiv'd by the Enemy, they did
the like, and having attack'd us, they were &s;o well
receiv'd by our Troops, that they were oblig'd to
quit the Field; and our Troops took many Standards,
Colours, and Cannon; and among the Pri&s;oners,
there are the General Velt Mare&s;chal <HI>Ren&s;child,</HI> be|&s;ides
four other Generals, <HI>viz. Slippenbach, Sta|kellbrugh,
Hamilton,</HI> and <HI>Ro&s;en;</HI> the fir&s;t Mini&s;ter
of State, Count <HI>Piper,</HI> the two Secretaries of
State, <HI>Hermelin</HI> and <HI>Cederkielm;</HI> and &s;ome thou|&s;ands
of Soldiers and Officers, of which we will cau&s;e
the Particulars to be &s;ent to you very &s;peedily, becau&s;e
the Shortne&s;s of the Time does not permit to do it at
pre&s;ent. To &s;ay all in a Word, the Enemy's whole
Army has bad the Fate of <HI>Phaeton;</HI> we do not yet
know what is become of the Per&s;on of the King of
<HI>Sweden,</HI> whether he be Living, or with our Fathers.
We have commanded our Lieutenants General, <HI>Galic|zin</HI>
and <HI>Baurs,</HI> to pur&s;ue the flying Enemy with our
<PB N="227" REF="236">
Cavalry. We wi&s;h you, with this our Victory, all
Pro&s;perity.</P>
<CLOSER><SIGNED>Sign'd
PETER.</SIGNED></CLOSER>
</LETTER>
<P>THUS ended all the va&s;t De&s;igns of the King
of <HI>Sweden,</HI> of whom we &s;hall &s;ay no more here,
than that he e&s;caped, as hath been &s;aid, into the
Dominions of the Grand Seignior, and was well
receiv'd by the Order of the Port at the City of
<HI>Bender,</HI> a Frontier of the <HI>Turks,</HI> on the Side of
<HI>Tartary,</HI> and on the Banks of the <HI>Nei&s;ter,</HI> and
where he meditated his Revenge, in a Manner &s;o
unbecoming a Chri&s;tian Prince, as to animate
the <HI>Manometans</HI> and Common Enemies of <HI>Chri&s;ti|ans,</HI>
to make a War again&s;t the <HI>Czar;</HI> and was
again the Occa&s;ion of much Blood, and much
Co&s;t to the <HI>Chri&s;tian</HI> World, as &s;hall appear in its
Place.</P>
<P>HIS <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty had now no more Work
upon his Hands of this Kind, the Grand Enemy
being thus gone, and that Army entirely defeat|ed,
which had been &s;o long the Terror of <HI>Poland;</HI>
what remain'd, was the Work of meer Negotiation
and Alliance. The pretended King <HI>Stani&s;laus,</HI>
and his Party, having now lo&s;t their main Sup|porter,
fell into their fir&s;t Nothing, whence they
came, and King <HI>Augu&s;tus</HI> dethron'd in an Arbitra|ry
and violent Manner, as has been &s;aid; was in|vited
to re-a&s;&s;ume the Kingdom, even by many of
tho&s;e, who had been In&s;truments in turning him out.</P>
<P><PB N="228" REF="237">
THAT Part of the Affairs of <HI>Poland,</HI> relate &s;o
much to the Affairs of <HI>Mu&s;covy,</HI> and the <HI>Czar</HI> had
&s;o much Glory in re&s;toring that ruin'd Prince
King <HI>Augu&s;tus,</HI> notwith&s;tanding he had relinqui&s;h'd
his Friend&s;hip, and broken his Treaties with him,
that it cannot be omitted.</P>
<P>AS Moderation, and doing Good for Evil, is
one of the Be&s;t of <HI>Chri&s;tian</HI> Virtues, &s;o forgetting
Injuries, and relieving oppre&s;s'd Princes, is one
of the brighte&s;t Parts in the Glory of the Conque|ror;
the <HI>Czar</HI> made it one of his fir&s;t Di&s;patches,
to give King <HI>Augu&s;tus</HI> a Part in the Joy of his
Victory, and thereby let his <HI>Poli&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty &s;ee,
that he had Kindne&s;s enough left, to forget what
was pa&s;t, and place it all to the Account of the
Violence he was under; and we were told a Me&s;|&s;age
was &s;oon after &s;ent to invite him to rea&s;|&s;ume
the Throne, with A&s;&s;urances of Support,
from the &s;ame conquering Hand, which had driven
his only Enemy, <HI>that is to &s;ay,</HI> his only formi|dable
Enemy out of <HI>Chri&s;tendom,</HI> and who was
now in a State of Exile, among the <HI>Barbarians,</HI>
without an Army, without his victorious Gene|rals,
without his Chief Mini&s;ter Count <HI>Piper,</HI>
without Friends, and without Money; and con|&s;equently,
that there was no Room to fear his
Return into <HI>Poland,</HI> or meddling any more with
the Affairs of that Country.</P>
<P>WHETHER this were &s;o or not, <HI>this is certain,</HI>
that King <HI>Augu&s;tus</HI> no &s;ooner received this &s;urprizing
and unexpected News, but he began to ca&s;t
about his Return and meditate his going back in|to
<HI>Poland,</HI> to recover the Crown, which was torn
from his Head by Violence and War: Nor was it
long before he receiv'd &s;uch Invitations from the
<HI>Poles</HI> them&s;elves, as without any Room to con&s;ider
<PB N="229" REF="238">
farther, determin'd him in the Affirmative, as
we &s;hall &s;ee pre&s;ently.</P>
<P>IF the Overthrow of the King of <HI>Sweden</HI> was
a Surprize of Joy to the abdicated King <HI>Augu&s;tus,</HI>
it was no le&s;s an A&s;toni&s;hment to King <HI>Stani&s;laus;</HI>
indeed it was a Clap of Thunder to him, a Bla$t
from Heaven, that at one Gu&s;t, overthrew him
and all his Intere&s;t and Friends.</P>
<P>HE was at <HI>Lemberg</HI> when he met with the
News, and had with him General <HI>Cra&s;&s;au,</HI> with a
Body of 16000 <HI>Swedes,</HI> very good Troops, and
had about 12000 <HI>Poles,</HI> who were mo&s;t of them
Gentlemen, and were very well mounted: So
that he had near 30000 Men, be&s;ides the Palatine
of <HI>Kiou,</HI> who was hearty in his Intere&s;t, and had
about 8000 Men more, with him, at his capital
City of <HI>Kiou,</HI> or <HI>Kiovia.</HI></P>
<P>HAD the King of <HI>Sweden,</HI> after the Lo&s;s of
the Battle at <HI>Pultowa,</HI> in&s;tead of Flying into the
<HI>Turks</HI> Dominions he &s;carce knew whether, kept
to the North, and gone to <HI>Kiou,</HI> and had directed
all that could e&s;cape to have done the like, he
had play'd a Game, that might &s;till have renew'd
the War, for his Cavalry which &s;urrender'd to
the <HI>Ru&s;&s;ians,</HI> would immediately have &s;eparated,
and in &s;mall Bodies have e&s;cap'd, and perhaps
five or &s;ix Thou&s;and of them, have got together
there; and having &s;uch a Body of Men at Hand,
as King <HI>Stani&s;laus,</HI> and the Palatine <HI>Kiou</HI> had, as
above, he would have been 50000 &s;trong again
immediately; but, <HI>Lui Jupiter vult perdere hos
dementat,</HI> his <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty was not to take one
right Step, or do any thing but what was to pre|cipitate
him&s;elf, and all his Friends into farther
Ruin.</P>
<P><PB N="230" REF="239">
AS &s;oon as King <HI>Stani&s;laus,</HI> his People, receiv'd
the News, they &s;tood like Men Thunder-&s;truck,
looking at one another; the <HI>Poles</HI> that were with
him, and adheard to his Intere&s;t, began to con|&s;ult
their own Safety, and fled like <HI>I&s;raelites</HI> eve|ry
Man to his Tent; &s;o that of 12000 Hor&s;e, he
had in a Weeks time, &s;carce 2000 left, General
<HI>Cra&s;&s;an;</HI> with his <HI>Swedes,</HI> fore&s;eeing the Storm that
began immediately to gather behind him, I mean
from <HI>Saxony,</HI> and of which I &s;hall &s;peak at large
pre&s;ently, began to con&s;ider in what Part of the
World he was, namely in the remote&s;t Part of
<HI>Poland,</HI> that he had no Time to lo&s;e, and that if
he did not immediately &s;ecure the Pa&s;&s;ages into
<HI>Pru&s;&s;ia</HI> and <HI>Pomerania,</HI> his Retreat might be cut
off, or he might be obliged to cut his Way
through with the Sword.</P>
<P>UPON this Con&s;ideration, he immediately put
him&s;elf in a Po&s;ture to Retreat, and by long
Marches, made towards great <HI>Poland;</HI> nay, he
made &s;uch Expedition, that it look'd as if he had
been pur&s;u'd by the <HI>Mu&s;covite</HI> Army; but the
Truth of the Ca&s;e was, that he feared more his
Enemies that were before him, than tho&s;e that
were behind him; King <HI>Stani&s;laus</HI> went with him,
and glad he was to have &s;uch a Convoy; for he,
that a little before, had a great Body of Troops at
his Command, was glad now to take Shelter in a
<HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> Camp, and to quit <HI>Poland,</HI> as fa&s;t as he
could, lea&s;t he &s;hould fall into the Hands of his
Rival.</P>
<P>AND this brings me to the Sum of the Affair
on that Side; the Victory of his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty
at <HI>Pultowa,</HI> had more Influence upon that remo|ter
Part of the World, by a great deal, than up|on
that Part where it was tran&s;acted; the <HI>Czar</HI>
<PB N="231" REF="240">
had nothing to do, but to &s;tand &s;till and &s;ee with
Plea&s;ure, the Con&s;equences of his Victory over
the whole Kingdom of <HI>Poland,</HI> over the whole
Electorate of <HI>Saxony,</HI> and indeed over all <HI>Eu|rope.</HI></P>
<P>I HAVE mention'd before how the Confede|rated
Nobility, call'd the a&s;&s;embly at <HI>Lublin,</HI> had
rejected the, Invitations of King <HI>Stani&s;laus,</HI> and
how they met afterwards at <HI>Sendomir,</HI> and how even
after the King of <HI>Sweden's</HI> return into <HI>Poland,</HI> they
yet kept together, and took an Oath to &s;tand by
one another; tho' at the &s;ame time they would
not come into the Mea&s;ures, which the <HI>Czar</HI> would
have brought them to, <HI>viz,</HI> to Choo&s;e a third King
of <HI>Poland.</HI></P>
<P>NOTHING is more certain than that this Con|federacy
were the Life of King <HI>Augu&s;tus</HI> Cau&s;e at
la&s;t, for they all a long kept a Corre&s;pondence
with him, and waited only an Opportunity to re|&s;tore
him to the Crown; nor were they without
very rational pro&s;pects of bringing it about, even
from the fir&s;t time, that they &s;aw the King of
<HI>Sweden</HI> pur&s;ue &s;uch wild Chimerick Projects as
dethroning the <HI>Czar,</HI> marching into <HI>Mu&s;covy,</HI> and
afterwards into <HI>Urkania;</HI> but e&s;pecially after
they found that the <HI>Czar,</HI> at the Head, but of a
Part of his Army had defeated General <HI>Lewen|haupt,</HI>
and &s;uch an Army of Soldiers as he had
with him, who were thought to be invincible, and
that all the Ammunition, and Millitary Provi&s;ions,
which were carrying to the King of <HI>Sweden,</HI> were,
fallen into the Hands of the <HI>Ru&s;&s;ians;</HI> the&s;e things
not only put the Confederated Nobility in Heart;
but they actually pur&s;ued the De&s;ign of bringing
back King <HI>Augu&s;tus,</HI> let his Engagements &s;ubmit|ted
<PB N="232" REF="241">
to, when under Violence, and Oppo&s;ition of
the King of <HI>Sweden</HI> be what they would.</P>
<P>&startq;ON the other Hand it was ea&s;ie to &s;ee for &s;ome
time before the Battle of <HI>Pultowa,</HI> that King
<HI>Augu&s;tus,</HI> had form'd new De&s;igns, and was ta|king
Mea&s;ures for another Attempt upon <HI>Po|land,</HI>
he found that notwith&s;tanding the King of
<HI>Sweden's</HI> advance into <HI>Poland,</HI> he made no great
influence on the <HI>Poles;</HI> that the Nobility had an
univer&s;al hatred to King <HI>Stani&s;laus;</HI> he found
al&s;o, that altho' the <HI>Czar</HI> pu&s;h'd at a new Electi|on,
yet he could not, bring the <HI>Poles</HI> to con&s;ent to
it; but that they manife&s;ted an exceeding Af|fection
to his Per&s;on, and a great de&s;ire to &s;ee him
once again at the Head of his Armies in <HI>Poland;</HI>
the <HI>Czar</HI> al&s;o found he &s;hould never bring the
<HI>Poles</HI> to fall into a Conjunction with him, but
that the Intere&s;t of King <HI>Augu&s;tus</HI> reviv'd, and
that he could not with all his Art, no not by
threatening to abandon them to the <HI>Swedes,</HI> bring
them to publi&s;h an <HI>Interegnum,</HI> much le&s;s to
hear of a new Election; but that they owned
to him, that they knew as King <HI>Augu&s;tus</HI> was
driven by violence to give up the Crown, &s;o
he would not be backward to take the fir&s;t op|portunity
to re-a&s;&s;ume it. The&s;e Con&s;iderati|ons
brought the <HI>Czar</HI> and King <HI>Augu&s;tus</HI> al&s;o to
a &s;ecret Corre&s;pondence, and even before the
Battle of <HI>Le&s;no,</HI> where Count <HI>Lewenhaupt</HI> was
beaten; King <HI>Augu&s;tus,</HI> who all the World ex|pected
would have retrench'd his Expences, and
le&s;&s;en'd his Troops to recover his Lo&s;ies, on a &s;ud|den
li&s;ted Men throughout all his Dominions,
and among all the Princes of his Hou&s;e, till he
had &s;uch an Army as all well knew the Revenues
of his own Country could not maintain, tho'
<PB N="233" REF="242">
it had been in the time of his greate&s;t Pro&s;peri|ty;
for he had rais'd above 30000 Men, where|of
at leaft 16000 were Hor&s;e; a Force which
it was apparent, was with &s;ome extraordinary
Enterpri&s;e in View: Certain it was, he could
not fore&s;ee the Defeat of the King of <HI>Sweden,</HI>
neither could he expect with all the Forces,
which it was in his power to rai&s;e, to be able to
fight the <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> Forces; &s;o that if he had not
had &s;ome &s;ecret A&s;&s;urances, he could never have
been &s;o weak to have ventured a &s;econd. At|tempt,
after the fir&s;t had been &s;o fatal to him;
It is true, when by the frequent going, and re|turning
of Courriers to and from the <HI>Czar</HI> of
<HI>Mu&s;covy,</HI> and King <HI>Augu&s;tus,</HI> and from publick
Conferences held with the Mini&s;ter of the <HI>Czar</HI>
at <HI>Dre&s;den,</HI> &s;ome umbrage was taken, that he
was forming new De&s;igns in Concert with the
<HI>Czar</HI> again&s;t the <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> Intere&s;t, he endeavour'd
to take off tho&s;e Apprehen&s;ions by publickly
declaring there was no De&s;igns of that kind on
Foot; ordering his Mini&s;ter at the Court of <HI>Ber|lin</HI>
to &s;ignifie to his <HI>Pru&s;ian</HI> Maje&s;ty, that the
Rea&s;on of tho&s;e Conferences, and Di&s;patches,
were only to $ettle &s;ome mutual Preten&s;ions
between him, and the <HI>Czar;</HI> particularly, as to
<HI>Patkull's</HI> Papers, and Writings belonging to his
<HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty, which were in the Hands of
a <HI>Mu&s;covite</HI> Commi&s;&s;ary, who died at <HI>Dre&s;den;</HI>
The&s;e were the An&s;wers given upon tho&s;e Occa|&s;ions;
but we found not long afterwards that
this fir&s;t was only to amuze the Courts of <HI>Eu|rope,</HI>
till his De&s;igns were ripe for Execution;
for no &s;ooner was Count <HI>Lewenhaupt</HI> defeated
at <HI>Le&s;no,</HI> as has been &s;aid, and the <HI>Swedi&s;h.</HI>
Communication with <HI>Poland</HI> cut off, the <HI>Czar</HI>
<PB N="234" REF="243">
&s;ending Word to King <HI>Augu&s;tus,</HI> that he had the
King of <HI>Sweden</HI> at an Advantage, and that he
would an&s;wer for giving a good Account of him.
I &s;ay, no &s;ooner were the&s;e Appearances of Suc|ce&s;s
in his View, but King <HI>Augun&s;tus</HI> began to
discover him&s;elf; the great and open Concour&s;e
of the <HI>Poli&s;h</HI> Nobility to his Court, the fre|quent
Expre&s;&s;es &s;ent to <HI>Cracow,</HI> where the No|bility
in his Intere&s;t were A&s;&s;embled; the vi&s;i|ble
Concert of Mea&s;ures with the Crown Ge|neral,
and the <HI>Poli&s;h</HI> Army, and &s;everal other
Circum&s;tances made it no longer doubted but
that he had re&s;olv'd to return into <HI>Poland;</HI> but
as &s;oon as he had receiv'd by Expre&s;s from the
<HI>Czar,</HI> on Account of the Battle of <HI>Pultowa,</HI> and
of the entire defeat of the <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> Army, as
you have heard, with the Flight of his <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI>
Maje&s;ty to the <HI>Turki&s;h</HI> Dominions; he then
threw off the Mask, and made his De&s;igns no
longer a Secret.&endq;</P>
<P>BUT this went farther immediately, for now
the <HI>Poli&s;h</HI> Nobility throng'd to <HI>Dre&s;den,</HI> to make
their Court to the King, and to tender their Ser|vice
to him, and a little after this came a &s;olemn
Deputation from the Crown Army, and from the
Confederate Nobility at <HI>Sendomir,</HI> to invite him
to return to his People, and to take upon him a|gain
the Governvent; promi&s;ing all the Obedi|ence
and Fidelity of Loyal Subjects, and to &s;et
him upon the Throne again, and maintain him
thereon again&s;t all his Enemies what&s;oever.</P>
<P>UPON all the&s;e Encouragements he could do no
le&s;s than con&s;ent, &s;o he receiv'd the <HI>Poli&s;h</HI> Deputati|on,
acquainted them with his Re&s;olution to return
into <HI>Poland,</HI> and at the &s;ame time &s;ent an Amba&s;&s;ador
$the <HI>Czar</HI> of <HI>Mu&s;covy,</HI> to Congratulate him upon
<PB N="235" REF="244">
the News of his Victory, and to acquaint him
with his new Mea&s;ures, de&s;iring his Concur|rence,
and A&s;&s;i&s;tance, which was only matter of
Form, all that Part having been concerted, and
concluded between them long before his Prepa|rations.</P>
<P>IT is time now to look back to his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Ma|je&s;ty's
Proceedings after the great Battle at <HI>Pul|towa;</HI>
the fir&s;t thing was to &s;end a &s;trong Body
of Troops over the <HI>Bori&s;thenes,</HI> to pu&s;h the flying
Enemy; this Party pick'd up &s;ome &s;traglers, but
the chief Service was to hurry the King of <HI>Swed|land</HI>
forward, who hearing of tho&s;e Troops in
his Rear, would be &s;ure not to return towards
<HI>Poland,</HI> which was the only thing that the <HI>Czar</HI>
was unwilling &s;hould happen.</P>
<P>SOME of the &s;tragling <HI>Swedes,</HI> who e&s;caped
from the Battle, fell into the Hands of a <HI>Mu&s;co|vite</HI>
Officer, who was po&s;ted on the Frontier of
<HI>Polodia,</HI> who attack'd them, and after a &s;hort,
but bloody Engagement, the <HI>Swedes,</HI> of whom
about 120 were kill'd, &s;urrendered, and were
made Pri&s;oners, being about 250 Men; but as
for about 800 <HI>Co&s;&s;acks,</HI> the <HI>Ru&s;&s;ian</HI> General looking
on them as Rebels, and Traytors, would give
them no Quarter, but they were all cut in Pieces.</P>
<P>THE <HI>Palatine</HI> of <HI>Kiou</HI> was the only Man that
&s;tood firm for King <HI>Stani&s;laus,</HI> even after he had
receiv'd News of the Lo&s;s at <HI>Pultowa,</HI> and after
the Retreat of the &s;aid King <HI>Stani&s;laus,</HI> and of
General <HI>Cra&s;&s;au,</HI> as above; but as his Forces were
&s;mall, he was fallen upon by a Deteachment from
the <HI>Ru&s;&s;ian</HI> Army and entirely defeated, and fled
afterward to the King of <HI>Sweden</HI> at <HI>Bender.</HI></P>
<P>THIS was that <HI>Palatine</HI> of <HI>Kiou,</HI> who brought
the <HI>Cham</HI> of the <HI>Tartars</HI> and the King of <HI>Sweden</HI>
<PB N="236" REF="245">
together, and &s;o wrought with the <HI>Cham,</HI> and
thro' his means with that <HI>Turki&s;h</HI> Emperor, that
he brought the <HI>Czar</HI> into the fatal War with the
<HI>Turks,</HI> in which he had that Misfortune to pur|cha&s;e
Peace with the Lo&s;s of that important For|tre&s;e
of <HI>A&s;oph,</HI> and there-with of all that pro|&s;pect
the <HI>Czar</HI> had of Commerce, and Conque$t on
the Side of the <HI>Black-Sea,</HI> of which &s;o much has
been &s;aid in the beginning of this Hi&s;tory, and of
which we &s;hall have more to &s;ay very quickly.</P>
<P>IT might take up &s;ome time here to look into
<HI>Mu&s;covy,</HI> and take &s;ome Notice of the rejoycings
there, upon the News of this Victory and the
Triumph of the <HI>Czar</HI> at his return to <HI>Mu&s;cow,</HI> his
Capital City; but I &s;hall Couch it all in this
&s;hort Abridgement at pre&s;ent, (<HI>viz.</HI>) that it was
&s;uch as it is impo&s;&s;ible to de&s;cribe.</P>
<P>THE <HI>Mu&s;covites</HI> were not a little in pain at fir&s;t,
on the approach of &s;uch a Prince, and &s;uch an
Army, as Fame had repre&s;ented the King of <HI>Swe|den</HI>
and his Army to be; and at the Apprehen&s;i|ons
of that very Prince approaching them, who
had &s;o terribly defeated them at the Battle of
<HI>Narva;</HI> and to have an Account that this Prince
was beaten, and that in &s;uch a manner, as &s;carce
ever Army was beaten before, <HI>viz.</HI> &s;o that none
at all of &s;o great a Power &s;hould e&s;cape, except
&s;uch a trifling Number as is mentioned to have
gone away with that King; this mu&s;t be &s;urpri|&s;ing
(to be &s;ure) to them, &s;ince it was &s;o to all the
World.</P>
<P>BUT the Triumph of their Prince exceeded all
the re&s;t, and indeed his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty had as
much Rea&s;on to Triumph as ever any <HI>Roman</HI>
Con&s;ul, or <HI>Roman</HI> Emperor had for the greate&s;t
Victory they ever won; for the <HI>Romans</HI> exceeded
<PB N="237" REF="246">
in Military Knowledge, and the Experience of
Wars of all the Nations of the World; but here was
a Prince, and even a Nation, who were, as it
might be &s;aid, but as of Ye&s;terday in War, yet
victorious over the brave&s;t and mo&s;t experienc'd
Soldiers then thought to be in the World: In a
Word, it was a Victory that the World thought
impo&s;&s;ible; the Scholars beating their Ma&s;ters
the <HI>Ru&s;&s;ians</HI> beating the <HI>Swedes,</HI> was like the <HI>Gauls</HI>
beating the <HI>Romans;</HI> which was the Wonder of
the World.</P>
<P>AS the Glory of the Victory was great, &s;o,
the <HI>Czar</HI> being willing his Subjects &s;hould &s;ee
what their Monarch had fought &s;o boldly for, and
to &s;how familliarly to them the Affair of War, he
let them &s;ee the Trophies which he brought, and
what had been purcha&s;ed at the Expence of their
Blood. This glorious Triumph was made the
21&s;t of <HI>December,</HI> 1701, and is here &s;et down at large, from the mo&s;t Authentick Account.</P>
<P>On the 11th, his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty attended by
Admiral <HI>Aparxin,</HI> and &s;everal of the Nobility,
arriv'd at a Country Seat, call'd <HI>Kolem&s;ki,</HI> which
is about five <HI>Engli&s;h</HI> Miles di&s;tant from <HI>Mo&s;cow,</HI>
Prince <HI>Menzikoff</HI> went thither on the 14th, and
on the 16th, the whole Court took up their Lodg|ings
in one of the Suburbs which is &s;eparated
from the Town by the River <HI>Mo&s;cow;</HI> his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI>
Maje&s;ty had appointed to receive the Compli|ments
of all the Foreign Mini&s;ters on the 17th,
but a great Fire happening to break out in the
Neighbourhood, the <HI>Briti&s;h</HI> Envoy was oblig'd
to defer his Vi&s;it $till the Day following; at
which Time the <HI>Czar</HI> receiv'd him with great
Di&s;tinction, at Prince <HI>Menzikoff</HI>'s Appartment,
<PB N="238" REF="247">
and was pleas'd to confer with him &s;everal Hours.
Mon&s;ieur <HI>$uel,</HI> Envoy from the King of <HI>Denmark</HI>
to that Court, together with Mon&s;ieur <HI>Grand,</HI> his
Predece&s;&s;or, had Audience of his Maje&s;ty, in a
private manner. But it being inconvenient the
Court &s;hould &s;tay in a Place where there were &s;o
litle Accommodation, his Maje&s;ty gave Orders that
the Publick Entry &s;hould be made on the 21&s;t,
altho' the Preparations which were making for
that Solemnity were not compleated, and the
Triumphal Arches, of which they had erected
&s;even, were not perfectly fini&s;h'd; the nece&s;&s;a|ry
Instructions being accordingly given, the Pro|ce&s;&s;ion
was perform'd on the 21&s;t, in the following Manner.</P>
<P>The <HI>Seminiowski</HI> Regiment led the Way, who were
followed by the Cannon, Colours, and Officers that
were taken in the Battle again&s;t General <HI>Lewen|haupt;</HI>
the&s;e were clo&s;ed by a Company of <HI>Preobra|fenski</HI>
Guards, the <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> Remains, of the Battles
of <HI>Pultowa,</HI> and <HI>Perewolo&s;ch</HI> marched in the next
Place, the Non-commi&s;&s;ion'd Officers of this Body led
the Way, next to them the En&s;igns and &s;econd Lieute|nants,
in the third Place came the Lieutenants, and
next to them the Captain Lieutenants, after whom
the Captains of both Foot and Hor&s;e; the&s;e were
followed by the Officers and other Attendants of the
Train of Artillery, who preceeded the Ordinance;
after which were carry'd the Kettle-Drums, and Co|lours;
then march'd the Majors, Lieutenant Colonels,
Colonels, and General, Adjutans and were &s;ucceeded
by the King of <HI>Sweden</HI>'s Hou&s;hold, and Equipage, to|gether
with the Litter and Bed that he u&s;ed in the Day
of Battle; after which came the chief Officers, each
marching &s;ingle, in this Order; Mon&s;ieur Po&s;&s;e Colonel
<PB N="239" REF="248">
General of the Guards, Major General <HI>Hamilton,</HI>
Major General <HI>Stakelbergh,</HI> Major General Ro&s;e,
Major General <HI>Cra&s;s,</HI> Major General Caxcits,
Major General <HI>Schelippenback,</HI> General <HI>Lewen|haupt,</HI>
Field Mare&s;chal <HI>Rhein&s;child;</HI> the whole, be|ing
clo&s;ed by Count <HI>Piper,</HI> the King of Sweden's fir&s;t
Mini&s;ter of State, then his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty on a &s;tately
Hor&s;e, which had been pre&s;ented to him by King Au|gu&s;tus, with his Sword drawn, which was formerly a pre|&s;ent
from King Augu&s;tus to the King of <HI>Sweden:</HI> He
followed the Pri&s;oners, at the Head of the <HI>Preobra&s;en&s;|ki</HI>
Guards, having Prince <HI>Menzikoff</HI> on his Right,
and Prince <HI>Dolgoruki</HI> on his Left; in this Order
they made their Proce&s;&s;ion through the City, and his Maje&s;ty was received at the fir&s;t Triumphal-Arch, by
the Magi&s;trates, at the &s;econd, by Prince <HI>Gavari</HI>
Governour of the Town; at the third, by the Nobi|lity;
at the fourth, by the principal Merchants;
at the fifth, by the Clergy; at the &s;ixth, by the
Empre&s;&s;es Dowager, and the Princes of the Blood;
and at the la&s;t, by the Burghers: The foreign Mini|&s;ters
had &s;eparate Hou&s;es allotted them for their Cere|mony,
and his Maje&s;ty made a &s;hort &s;tand at the re|&s;pective
Places where they &s;tood: The Cannon was
fired &s;everal times round the Town during the Solem|nity,
and all po&s;&s;ible Demon&s;trations of Joy, were ex|pre&s;s'd
on that Occa&s;ion: About Eight or nine Thou|&s;and
Soldiers that were taken Pri&s;oners, were brought
into the Town on the Day preceeding; but the Officers
belonging to the King of <HI>Sweden</HI>'s Foot Guards, ha|ving
not arriv'd from <HI>Kiow,</HI> &s;oon enough to appear in the <HI>Czar</HI>'s Triumphant Entry, they were publickly
conducted into that City, on the 27th, with the &s;ame
Solemnity, as the other Pri&s;oners, had before march|ed,
on the fir&s;t In&s;tant.</P>
<P><PB N="240" REF="249">
HIS <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty treated all the chief Per|&s;ons
of Quality, and the foreign Mini&s;ters at a
publick Dinner; in the Evening &s;umptuous Fire
Wor$s, on which were &s;everal In&s;criptions, and
Repre&s;entations, was prepar'd and went off with
great Exactne&s;s: The chief Machines were, a
<HI>Pha$iton</HI> &s;truck with a Thunder-Bolt; and another
Figure, in allu&s;ion to a late Medal Struck in <HI>Swe|den,</HI>
two Pillars were fir&s;t lighted, which &s;up|ported
imperial Crowns, and were adorn'd with
great Variety of blue, green and pale Flames;
when they had burnt &s;ome Time, a Lion mov'd
forward, on who&s;e Approach, the fir&s;t Pillar
broke &s;hort at the Pede&s;$al, but as he advanc'd
near the &s;econd, a Spread Eagle repre&s;enting his
Maje&s;ty's Arms, launch'd a Rocket, which blew
the Lions Head and Neck off, and the Pillar re|mained
firm to the la&s;t.</P>
<P>HIS <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty, however, made but a &s;hort
Stay at <HI>Mo&s;cow,</HI> he knew as well how to im|prove,
as how to gain a Victory, having there|fore
driven his two capital Enemies, the King of
<HI>Sweden,</HI> and the Palatine of <HI>Kiow</HI> into the <HI>Turki&s;h</HI>
Dominions, &s;ecur'd the Frontiers as well of <HI>Poland,</HI>
as of <HI>Mo&s;covy,</HI> from their returning, by po&s;ting
a &s;trong Body of Hor&s;e, on the Frontiers of the
former, about <HI>Lemberg</HI> and <HI>Kiovia;</HI> and another
on that Side of the <HI>Unkrain,</HI> on the Bank of the
<HI>Bori&s;thenes,</HI> with Orders to them both, to Scour
the Countries &s;o effectually, that no Foreign
Troops might enter. <HI>I &s;ay,</HI> His <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty
having thus &s;ecur'd the King of <HI>Sweden,</HI> from re|turning
into <HI>Poland</HI> or <HI>Mu&s;covy;</HI> he order'd his
Troops to File off to the <HI>North,</HI> and by ea&s;y
<PB N="241" REF="250">
Marches to come to <HI>Smolen&s;ko,</HI> under the Leading
of Prince <HI>Czeremetoff,</HI> and General <HI>Baur,</HI></P>
<P>FROM thence, one Body of them marched in|to
<HI>Lithuania,</HI> and about 28000 of them, were di|rected
to wait the Orders of King, <HI>Augu&s;tus,</HI> who
was now, in Concert with the <HI>Czar</HI> returning in
to <HI>Poland</HI> as above; as &s;oon as they heard his <HI>$soli&s;h</HI>
Maje&s;ty had pa&s;s'd the <HI>Oder,</HI> they were to ad|vance
to the Banks of the <HI>Vi&s;tula,</HI> on the other
Side of <HI>War&s;aw,</HI> to be ready to go wherever the
King of <HI>Poland</HI> &s;hould lead them.</P>
<P>HIS <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty had now a clear Country
before him, and having before reduc'd all the
Inland Part of the Province of <HI>Livonia,</HI> taken
<HI>Narva,</HI> reduc'd <HI>Ingermanland,</HI> razed <HI>Scan&s;terny</HI> on
the <HI>Neva,</HI> built the Fortre&s;s of <HI>Croon&s;lot,</HI> and be|gan
to build the Royal City of <HI>Petersburg;</HI> he
re&s;olv'd now, to attack the Coa&s;t Towns of <HI>Livo|nia,</HI>
which were very Strong, and had in them
numerous Garri&s;ons of <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> Soldiers, who were
&s;ure to make a long and vigorous Defence; at
the &s;ame time, his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty re&s;olv'd, to
extend his Conque&s;t on the North of <HI>Ingermanland,</HI>
into <HI>Finland,</HI> and the Hereditary Dominions of <HI>Sweden.</HI></P>
<P>IN Con&s;equence of the&s;e Re&s;olutions, his <HI>Cza|ri&s;h</HI>
Maje&s;ty ordered a Body of an Army to march
from the Side of <HI>Ple&s;kow</HI> and <HI>Novogrod</HI> into <HI>Fin|land,</HI>
and attack the &s;trong City of <HI>Wybourgh,</HI> the
be&s;t Port in all that Part of the Country, while
another Army at the &s;ame time march'd thro'
<HI>Lithuania</HI> into <HI>Livonia,</HI> and be&s;ieg'd the &s;trong
City of <HI>Riga.</HI></P>
<P>THIS la&s;t was an Undertaking of great Impor|tance,
for the City of <HI>Riga</HI> was a terrible Place,
&s;trong by &s;ituation, and that &s;ituation improv'd
<PB N="242" REF="251">
with the otmo&s;t Art; it had a numerous Artille|ry,
a &s;trong Fort, or rather Fortre&s;s command|ing
the Entrance to it by Sea, call'd the <HI>Duna|muder
&s;cans,</HI> being indeed a Royal Citadel, exquir|&s;itely
Fortified, and almo&s;t inacce&s;&s;ible; it was
reported that there was in the City and the <HI>Shcans</HI>
a Garri&s;on of 10000 Men, including the Burghers,
who did Duty as Soldiers, commanded by General
<HI>Stromfield,</HI> an experienced Officer, and a Man
from whom the World expected all that became
a Man of Honour, and of the utmo&s;t Bravery.</P>
<P>BUT all this was far from Discouraging the
<HI>Czar</HI> from the attempt; he knew the importance
of the Enterpri&s;e, and that now was the critical
Juncture, in which it was to be Undertaken,
with a pro&s;pect of Succe&s;s; the Affairs of <HI>Swe|den</HI>
being in &s;uch Confu&s;ion, that he was very
&s;ure to meet with no Interruption from without,
his Maje&s;ty therefore re&s;olv'd on the Seige.</P>
<P>THIS Siege was begun by Field Mar&s;hal <HI>Cere|mettoff,</HI>
but was after &s;ome time &s;top'd, and af|terwards
carried on only by a Bombardment and
Blockade, in order to &s;ave the effu&s;ion of Blood;
it was certain that there was time enough before
them to reduce the Garri&s;on to Extremity, no
Relief being likely to come to the Place by Sea,
and none po&s;&s;ible to be brought by Land; at the
beginning of this Blockade a mo&s;t lamentable Dif|&s;a&s;ter
befel the Be&s;ieg'd, in which the Be&s;iegers
had no hand at all; for the 22d of <HI>January</HI> the
Labratory where the Engineers made their Fire|works,
and fill'd their Bombs, which was built in
the Rear of the Ba&s;tions, adjoyning to one of the
Magazines belonging to the Garri&s;on took fire by
accident, and the fire reaching one of the shells
it bur&s;t, and in an in&s;tant the whole Hou&s;e, with
<PB N="243" REF="252">
the Magazine, adjoyning, blew up into the Air
with a Bla&s;t that &s;hoke the whole City, and made
even the Earth as far as the <HI>Ru&s;&s;ian</HI> Camp trem|ble:
There was, 800 Barrels of Gunpowder in the
Magazine, be&s;ides what was in the Labratory;
and be&s;ides the Shells which were fill'd; the Con|&s;ternation
in the City was inexpre&s;&s;ible, not a
a Hou&s;e but &s;uffer'd, and the whole Place look'd
like a City in Ruins; of the Garri&s;on the Bar|racks
being near the Place, 600 Men were entire|ly
lo&s;t, including the Guard of the Ba&s;tion; the
Ba&s;tion it &s;elf was entirely ruined, and the great
Ho&s;pital, in which was 1200 &s;ick or wounded Sol|diers,
be&s;ides the Officers of the Hou&s;e attending
them was blown up, and not a Soul of them all
left a live; &s;o that in the whole, near 2000 Peo|ple
were de&s;troyed, be&s;ides &s;uch as were wounded
an other Parts of the Town.</P>
<P>THE Governor under the greate&s;t &s;urpri&s;e of
Mind, as well as influenced by the Bla&s;t being on
the Parade of the Place, giving orders for a Sa|lly
fell down as one dead; and when by proper
Applications he recovered him&s;elf, he could not
hear, no not the Noi&s;e of a Drum; he had no Notion
for a great while, but that a Mine had been Sprung
by the Enemy under the Ba&s;tion, and that they
would immediately Storm the Breach.</P>
<P>THE force of the Powder had not only blown up
the Ba&s;tion, but it had made a Breach in the Bo|dy
of the Place nine or ten Yards wide, &s;o that e|ven
the Hor&s;e might have come in; the re&s;t
of the Officers, while things were in this Extre|mity,
being under no &s;uch great Concern, and
Con&s;equently le&s;s &s;urpris'd, than the Governour,
re&s;olv'd &s;ooner what was to be done, and beat|ing
to Arms, rais'd the whole Garri&s;on to defend
<PB N="244" REF="253">
the Place if they &s;hould be attack'd; then they
caus'd all the Hor&s;e Dung and Litter, which could
be had to be brought to the Place, and made up
the Breach in the Ba&s;tion as well as time could
permit, &s;etting three Rows of Palli&s;&s;adoes before
the Breach, and making a large Coupre or Re|trenchment
behind it; &s;o that tho' the <HI>Ru&s;&s;ians,</HI> had
they been aware of the Blow, might have made an
Advantage of it; yet &s;uch was the Diligence of
The Garri&s;on, that they made it up, as above, the
&s;ame Night that the Di&s;&s;a&s;ter happen'd; nor could
<HI>Mu&s;covite</HI> Generals make any advantage of it.</P>
<P>THE Blockade of this Place held till the latter
End of <HI>July,</HI> 1710, when General <HI>Stromfield,</HI> the
Governor was oblig'd to Capitulate, the Garri&s;on
being reduc'd by Hunger, and hard Service, and
by the fire of the Bombs, together with the Di&s;|&s;a&s;ter
above-mention'd, to le&s;&s; than 2000 &s;ound
Men; the <HI>Ru&s;&s;ian</HI> Velt Mar&s;hal gave them honour|able
Conditions, as well for the Garri&s;on, as to the
Burghers and Inhabitants, Courts of Ju&s;tice, and
Nobility, to whom all their Priviledges, Judica|tories,
and civil Rights were continu'd and pre|&s;erved;
as to the Garri&s;on, they were allowed all
Soldierly Honours, and to be conducted to <HI>Revel,</HI>
upon Condition neverthele&s;s, that they &s;hould Em|bark
there, and return to <HI>Stockholm.</HI></P>
<P>GENERAL <HI>Baur,</HI> who as I have noted before,
&s;erv'd under the Velt Mar&s;hal <HI>Czeremet</HI> at this
Seige was immediately after the &s;urrender of <HI>Ri|ga,</HI>
Detach'd with a good Body of Troops, to at|tack
<HI>Peruan,</HI> which he reduc'd in about 6 Weeks,
being taken the 19th of <HI>September.</HI></P>
<P>DURING the Blockade of <HI>Riga,</HI> General, or
Admiral <HI>Apraxin,</HI> who for the time commanded
the Land Army, be&s;ieged <HI>Wybourgh</HI> in <HI>Finland,</HI> as
<PB N="245" REF="254">
above. The Governor had Conditions granted
him al&s;o upon the Capitulation; but the Admiral
thought fit after the Surrender to detain the Gar|ri&s;on,
by way of Repri&s;al, till &s;atisfaction was
obtain'd for &s;everal Breaches of the Rules of War,
which the King of <HI>Sweden</HI> in the time of his Pro&s;|perity
had practis'd upon his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty's
Subjects: As <HI>fir&s;t,</HI> detaining a Ship &s;ent by his
<HI>Gzari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty's order into <HI>Sweden</HI> with a Flag
of Truce, to propo&s;e &s;ome Regulations of Pa&s;&s;es
and Rules for vi&s;iting the Ships of Neutral Nations,
which Ship contrary to the Law of Nations was
never re&s;tor'd. (2.) Detaining the <HI>Ru&s;&s;ian</HI> Re&s;ident
at <HI>Stockholm,</HI> at the breaking out of the War, tho'
the <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> Resident at <HI>Mu&s;cow</HI> was &s;uffer'd to go
Home, without any manner of Re&s;traint. (3.)
Becau&s;e the Subjects of <HI>Saxony,</HI> who went into
<HI>Sweden,</HI> and liv'd there in the time of Peace, on
the meer Affairs of Commerce, and behaving
quietly and peaceably, had notwith&s;tanding their
Effects &s;eiz'd and confi&s;cated.</P>
<P>GENERAL <HI>Apraxin</HI> found in <HI>Wybourg,</HI> part of
the Magazine for the whole Province of <HI>Finland,</HI>
The particulars are as follows,</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2>
<HEAD>An Inventory of the Artillery, Arms, and Ammu|nition
found in Wybourg.</HEAD>
<P>&startq;EIGHT Mortars, Four-Bombs, from 40 to 80
Pound weight; 2 Hauwitezers of 16 Poun|ders,
3 Bra&s;s Cannon of 9 Pound Ball, and 95
of Iron, from 3 Pound to 24 Pound Ball, 8644
Granadoes, from 5 Pound to 30, 17540 Bullets,
from 3 to 40 Pound, 1816 Cartridges, for from
3 to 24 Pounders, 638 Quintals of Powder, 16 of
Brim&s;tone and Salt Petre, 3 of Match, and 2
<PB N="246" REF="255">
of Copper, 1660 new Mu&s;quets, and 1950 u&s;ed,
1700 new Carbines, 189 damaged, <HI>&amp;c.</HI> There
were likewi&s;e found in the Town 58 Colours,
and one Standard.&endq;</P>
<P>THE City and Port of <HI>Revel,</HI> the I&s;le of <HI>O&s;el,</HI>
the Town of <HI>Arensburg,</HI> and <HI>Kexholm</HI> in <HI>Finland,</HI>
were all taken this Campaign; a Year almo&s;t, as
glorious to the <HI>Czar</HI> as the la&s;t: In the&s;e Places
the <HI>Mu&s;covites</HI> found great Quantities of Cannon,
and Ammunition, as al&s;o &s;mall Arms, and Hand
Granadoes in abundance.</P>
<P>THE whole Province of <HI>Livonia</HI> was now re|duced,
except the <HI>Dunamunder &s;chans,</HI> which Hea|ven
gave into his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty's hands &s;oon af|ter,
his own way, that is, by another Bla&s;t of
Powder. The <HI>Czar</HI> of <HI>Mu&s;covy,</HI> having by this time
compleated the Conque&s;t of <HI>Livonia,</HI> and con&s;e|quently
Triumph'd over the <HI>Swedes</HI> in tho&s;e Parts
of the World; his Maje&s;ty, to gain the Affection
of the People promis'd them, not only the con|tinuation
of their Priviledges, but likewi&s;e to
di&s;charge them from &s;everal heavy Burthens they
complain'd of under the Regency of the <HI>Swedes.</HI>
He al&s;o publi&s;h'd a Proclamation to encourage
Trade, and Navigation, and permitted the Ex|portation
of all the Goods of the Country, ex|cept
Timber fit for building of Ships, which he
had occa&s;ion for him&s;elf, being re&s;olv'd to have
in a &s;hort time a con&s;iderable Navy in the <HI>Baltick.</HI>
Foreign Shirps which were come into the Harbours
of <HI>Livonia</HI> &s;ince the Conque&s;t thereof, have been
receiv'd with all po&s;&s;ible Civility; and in &s;hort,
the <HI>Mu&s;covites</HI> neglected nothing to render their
Government acceptable to Foreigners as well as
to the Natives.</P>
<P><PB N="247" REF="256">
WE mu&s;t now look a little back to the King
of <HI>Poland,</HI> and to the Powers with whom the <HI>Czar</HI>
of <HI>Mu&s;covy</HI> had nece&s;&s;arily to do in this War;
I have taken notice that his <HI>Poli&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty having
been invited by the Confederated Nobility, and
encourag'd by his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty, and e&s;pecially
upon the Victory at <HI>Pultowa,</HI> to re-a&s;&s;ume the
Crown of <HI>Poland,</HI> had declar'd his Re&s;olution to
do &s;o, and was march'd for <HI>War&s;aw,</HI> with 800
Hor&s;e, having pa&s;s'd the Order the 24th of <HI>Augu&s;st,</HI> 1709.</P>
<P>IT remains to take notice that his <HI>Poli&s;h</HI> Ma|je&s;ty,
at his Entrance into <HI>Poland</HI> publi&s;h'd a full
<HI>Circular Letter</HI> of the Rea&s;ons, both of his having
Abdicated, and of his Return, which has &s;o much
in it of his former Concert of Mea&s;ures with his
<HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty, and &s;o much ju&s;t Acknowledge|ment
of his Obligation to the <HI>Czar,</HI> that when
we &s;hall find him forgetting tho&s;e Obligations a
&s;econd time, we &s;hall have occa&s;ion to look back
upon this <HI>Circular Letter,</HI> as a great Satisfaction, in
order to make a Judgement of the Ju&s;tice of his
Proceedings. The <HI>Circular Letter,</HI> is as follows;</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2>
<HEAD>We Augu&s;tus II, by the Grace of God, King of
Poland, Great Duke of Lithuania, &amp;c.</HEAD>
<P>TO All, and every One, this may concern, and in
particular, to the mo&s;t Venerable, the Venerable
in Je&s;us Chri&s;t; the mo&s;t Illu&s;trious, Magnificent, and
Generous Senators, and Officers of the Nobility, and
to all the Inhabitants of the Kingdom of <HI>Poland,</HI>
and the great Dutchy of <HI>Lithuania,</HI> of what &s;oever
Condition they be: We make known what follows, you
may have ea&s;ily under&s;tood from our Proceedings, tho'
<PB N="248" REF="257">
we did not declare it; that altho' through a hard but
unavoidable Nece&s;&s;ity, we were obliged to ab&s;ent our
&s;elves from you with the Body, yet you always re|main'd in our Hearts: However, &s;eeing that God
who has been mov'd with Compa&s;&s;ion on one Part,
for our Sufferings and Misfortunes; and provok'd on
the other, by the exce&s;&s;ive Pride of our Enemies; be|gins
to promi&s;e more favourable Days to the King|dom
of <HI>Poland;</HI> and &s;eeing on the other Hand, that
in maintaining the Confederation of <HI>Sendomir,</HI> in all
its Parts, you have u&s;ed your utmo&s;t Endeavours, for
pre&s;erving the Republick in the &s;ame Condition in
which we left it, according to the Example of true
and faithful <HI>Polanders;</HI> who have on all Occa&s;ions,
expre&s;s'd their Loyalty to their Kings. And
1a&s;tly, Seeing that after an Heroical Patience, and &s;o
long a Tryal, you are continually exhorting us, to re|turn
and Re&s;ume the Government of the Kingdom of
<HI>Poland.</HI> We on our Parts being no le&s;s de&s;irous than
you, or any Member of the Republick, to expre&s;s our
Paternal Affection and Fidelity, being &s;o indi&s;penci|bly
obliged thereunto, by the <HI>Pacta Conventa;</HI> that
according to the expre&s;s Terms thereof, it ii not left
in our Power, altho' we &s;hould have a Mind to it,
to renounce a Crown which was &s;o lawfully put upon our
Head: In&s;omuch, that what&s;oever has been done con|trary
thereunto, is to be look'd upon as null and void,
as you have declar'd, in the Diets of <HI>Leopold</HI> and
<HI>Lublin:</HI> Therefore we are return'd into <HI>Poland,</HI> to
a&s;&s;ert and defend the Honour of the Crown; and we
declare, by the&s;e Pre&s;ents, that as we have therein no
other Aim, than chiefly to maintain the holy ortho|dox
Faith, defend the ancient Rights and Privileges
of the Nation, and pre&s;erve the Bounds of the King|dom;
of all which, we are ready to give full A&s;&s;u|rances,
in the next A&s;&s;embly or Council, by confirm|ing
<PB N="249" REF="258">
the <HI>Pacta Conventa,</HI> as to the Points afore&s;aid,
according to the de&s;ire of the States: Therefore, We
earne&s;tly invite all &s;uch, as are faithful to us, and
adhere to our Maje&s;ty, either Burghers or Military
Men, to a&s;&s;i&s;t us; and in this, we think to give them
Proofs of our paternal Gratitude; at the &s;ame time
we offer our Clemency, and paternal Affection, to all
tho&s;e, who before we left the Kingdom, or &s;ince, have
quitted our Party upon any Pretence what&s;oever; re|pre&s;enting
unto them, that unle&s;s they are willing,
through a de&s;perate Attempt, to expo&s;e the Publick
to a general Subver&s;ion, they have no Rea&s;on to de|cline
this Act of Indemnity; being willing to forget
their Offences, and promi&s;ing to receive them into our
Favour and Protection. Furthermore, We a&s;&s;ure the
States of the Republick, that in the Pa&s;&s;age and
Quartering of our Troops, we will keep them under
an exact Di&s;cipline, and will have all po&s;&s;ible Regard
to the E&s;tates of the Clergy and others, as long as the
War will continue; and after the Conclu&s;ion thereof,
which we pray God to ha&s;ten, we promi&s;e, upon our
Royal Word, to &s;end them, without delay, out of the
Kingdom; being willing, wholly to conform our&s;elves
therein, to the Intentions of the Republick. We
Command all Officers, Civil and Military, and others,
to cau&s;e the&s;e Pre&s;ents to be read and publi&s;hed, in
all Places.</P>
<CLOSER><DATELINE>Given, <DATE>Augu&s;t 1,
1709.</DATE></DATELINE>
<SIGNED>Sign'd,
AUGUSTUS, Rex.</SIGNED></CLOSER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2>
<PB N="250" REF="259">
<P>THIS <HI>Circular letter</HI> was publi&s;h'd by King <HI>Au|gu&s;tus,</HI>
at the Head of his Army as &s;oon as he
enter'd <HI>Poland,</HI> and it was annex'd to a long <HI>Mani|fe&s;to,</HI>
and to a like <HI>Circular Letter</HI> to the Nobility
and Clergy of <HI>Lithuania</HI> inviting them to come
and joyn him at <HI>War&s;aw,</HI> offering to receive them,
and promi&s;ing his Amni&s;ty, or Pardon, even to
tho&s;e who had joyn'd King <HI>Stani&s;laus,</HI> and acted
again&s;t him.</P>
<P>THE <HI>Poles</HI> embraced this latter part, with al|mo&s;t
an universal Con&s;ent, and the King of <HI>Poland</HI>
was received with all the Care&s;&s;es, and all the
Tokens of Zeal and Affection imaginable; as to
the particulars, &s;uch as the va&s;t Concour&s;e of the
Nobility to him at <HI>War&s;aw,</HI> and the Harangues,
Speeches, Compliments, and Promi&s;es, <HI>&amp;c.</HI> made
to him, by tho&s;e that attended his Court at <HI>War|&s;aw,</HI>
they relate more particularly to the Hi&s;tory
of King <HI>Augu&s;tus,</HI> and I therefore refer the Rea|der
to other Writers of them; only ob&s;erving that
in the Cour&s;e even of his Hi&s;tory, we may per|haps
&s;ee of how little importance, Vows and Pro|te&s;tations
of Sincerity, Loyalty, and Fidelity
are in this Age, in tho&s;e Parts of the World.</P>
<P>BUT leaving the&s;e things, it follows of Cour&s;e
now to carry our Hi&s;tory farther from his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI>
Maje&s;ty's &s;hare of acting than before, and go as
far as <HI>Denmark</HI> to find another Allie in this War,
in who&s;e Territories, we &s;hall quickly find his
Maje&s;ty obliged to act, as well in Per&s;on as by his
Armies and Navies, and to make a yet more
con&s;iderable Figure in the War, than ever he did be|fore.</P>
<P>IT has been mention'd in the beginning of this
Work, how far the King of <HI>Denmark</HI> was an Allie
with the King of <HI>Poland,</HI> and with his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Ma|je&s;ty,
<PB N="251" REF="260">
in the beginning of the War with <HI>Sweden;</HI> how
the <HI>Engli&s;h</HI> and <HI>Dutch</HI> a&s;&s;i&s;ting the <HI>Swedes</HI> by Sea,
and the Troops of the Hou&s;e of <HI>Lunenburg</HI> a&s;&s;i&s;ting
the Duke of <HI>Hol&s;tein</HI> by Land, the King of <HI>Den|mark</HI>
was forced to make a Di&s;advantageous Peace
with both <HI>Sweden</HI> and <HI>Hol&s;tein,</HI> and have the Mor|tification
to &s;ee his Conque&s;t in <HI>Hol&s;tein</HI> &s;natch'd
out of his Hands, to rai&s;e his Siege of <HI>Toningen,</HI>
and to &s;ee the King of <HI>Sweden</HI> under the Protecti|on
of the <HI>Briti&s;h</HI> and <HI>Dutch</HI> Squadrons Land ju&s;t
at his Palace Gate, and Bombard his capital City
of <HI>Copenhagen.</HI></P>
<P>BUT now the Tables were turn'd, the King
of <HI>Sweden</HI> was, as it were, out of the World, and
the <HI>Czar</HI> the King of <HI>Denmark</HI>'s Allie, and fa&s;t
Friend, was Victorious, and very Formidable; now
his Maje&s;ty of <HI>Denmark</HI> thought it was a Juncture
happily offer'd by Heaven, for him to pu&s;h the
<HI>Swedes</HI> in his Turn, and to retrieve the Di&s;honour
which he had &s;uffer'd, and that he had as ju&s;t Rea|&s;on,
to Break with the King of <HI>Sweden,</HI> as the
King of <HI>Poland</HI> had, who&s;e Ca&s;e was many Ways
the &s;ame.</P>
<P>WITH the&s;e Thoughts, and concerting Mat|ters
with his <HI>Czar&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty for a&s;&s;i&s;tance, as
well by Sea as by Land, he re&s;olv'd to break
with <HI>Sweden</HI> immediately, and according to the
King of <HI>Poland</HI>'s Method, his <HI>Dani&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty
publi&s;h'd al&s;o a Manife&s;to, of the Rea&s;ons for
his Re&s;olution; this, as being not to our pre&s;ent
Purpo&s;e, I omit, and only mention it to Intro|duce
the Story of his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty's Part in
this War, which follow'd after.</P>
<P>THE King of <HI>Denmark</HI> having declar'd &startq;War,
and brought a con&s;iderable Army together, re|&s;olv'd
to pa&s;s over with them to <HI>S$honen,</HI> a Pro|vince
<PB N="252" REF="261">
of <HI>Sweden,</HI> once belonging to <HI>Denmark,</HI>
but Conquer'd formerly by the King of <HI>Sweden,</HI>
and conceded to <HI>Sweden,</HI> by the Treaty of Ro&s;|child.</P>
<P>TO bring this Abridgment of the Hi&s;tory of
this War into a narrow Compa&s;s, it is to be ob|&s;erv'd,
that the <HI>Swedes</HI> being at fir&s;t &s;urpriz'd, to be
thus attack'd, were at fir&s;t under great Apprehen|&s;ions,
but General, Count <HI>Steinhock,</HI> one of the
<HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> Officers at the Battle of <HI>Pultowa,</HI> and who
made his E&s;cape out of that Battle, being ap|pointed
to Command the <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> Army, gave
Battle to the <HI>Danes,</HI> under the Walls of <HI>Hel&s;ing|burgh</HI>
in <HI>Schonen,</HI> and entirely defeated their
whole Army, taking all their Cannon, Baggage,
and Ammunition, and forcing the Remainder of
their Army, to embark as well as the could, on
board &s;ome <HI>Dutch</HI> Ships in the <HI>Sound,</HI> and get
over into <HI>Jutland,</HI> and to <HI>Ele&s;nore,</HI> to &s;ave their
Lives; the <HI>Swedes</HI> kill'd in this Battle, about
3000 Men, and took near 4000 Pri&s;oners.</P>
<P>THIS Victory deliver'd <HI>Sweden</HI> effectually,
for a time; but the King of <HI>Denmark,</HI> who burn'd
with an impatient De&s;ire of Revenge, not
being equal to his Enemies, enter'd into a
Treaty with his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty, to be &s;upply'd
with 8000 Men, who were to be Convey'd to
<HI>Copenhagen</HI> by Sea.</P>
<P>IT now comes in the Event of Things, to take
Notice that the <HI>Czar</HI> of <HI>Mu&s;covy,</HI> having, as has
been fail, built a Royal City on the <HI>Neva,</HI> and a
Fortre&s;s defending the Port, by which it was effectulaly
&s;ecur'd, &s;o as to be able to receive and
protect any Number of the bige&s;t Ships. His
Maje&s;ty who&s;e Genius for the Sea Service, has
been &s;ufficiently mentioned, re&s;olv'd to build
<PB N="253" REF="262">
him&s;elf a Royal Navy; and to that Purpo&s;e,
having now made him&s;elf Ma&s;ter of <HI>Narva,</HI> and
<HI>Riga, Wyborg,</HI> and <HI>Revel,</HI> and other Places on that
Coa&s;t, he thereby got great Supplies of Seamen,
be&s;ides what he hir'd at other places.</P>
<P>IN a Word, &s;uch Expedition his Maje&s;ty made
in building Ships of his own, and employing al&s;o
&s;everal Per&s;ons to buy Ships of great Burthen,
in <HI>England</HI> and <HI>Holland,</HI> which he fitted up as Ships
of War; that by this Means his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty
began to haVe a Fleet at Sea, as well as the <HI>Swedes</HI>
and <HI>Danes,</HI> tho' not at fir&s;t of &s;o great Ships; tho'
now he has built &s;o many noble, large, beautiful
Men of War, that he di&s;pi&s;es tho&s;e bought Ships,
which being built generally for Merchants Bu&s;i|ne&s;s,
and not for the War, were not &s;o u&s;eful as
tho&s;e which he built.</P>
<P>FOR the effectual Furni&s;hing the&s;e Ships with
experienced Seamen, for managing them, his
<HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty was not di&s;maid with the Impo&s;|&s;ibility;
he got Men for Money, in almo&s;t all Parts
of <HI>Europe:</HI> And thus his Men of War appear'd in
the <HI>Baltick</HI> in this <HI>Dani&s;h</HI> War, of which we &s;hall
&s;ay more in its Place, &s;ooner than could have
been imagin'd: From the&s;e Beginnings, his <HI>Czar|i&s;h</HI>
Maje&s;ty has rai&s;ed him&s;elf to that formidable
Po&s;ture in his Marine Affairs, which we &s;ee him in at Pre&s;ent.</P>
<P>BY the Conver&s;ing with, and by Direction of the
foreign Seamen, which his Maje&s;ty has entertain'd
in his Pay, his own Subjects are gradually bred up
to thte Sea, and are found to be as expert in guid|ing
the Ships, and as bold and daring in Fight,
as can be de&s;ir'd of them; and even the Men, fol|lowing
in that, the Genius of their Sovereign, appear
pleas'd and delighted with the Service,
<PB N="254" REF="263">
and with Maritime Affairs; &s;o that now his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI>
Maje&s;ty has many Thou&s;and able Seamen of his
own Subjects, and will in a few Years have as
many Thou&s;and more as he plea&s;es.</P>
<P>TO furni&s;h him&s;elf with Ships he had nothing
to do but to furni&s;h him&s;elf with Builders, and
Carpenterps, having all the Materials for building
with in him&s;elf, and able to furni&s;h all the Nati|ons
of the World, be&s;ides: Naval Stores of all
kinds are the natural Produce of his Country,
and our Ea&s;t Country Merchants know very well,
that even the Royal Navies of great <HI>Britain, Hol|land,
Frarce</HI> and <HI>Sweden</HI> are furni&s;h'd with Hemp,
Flax, Timber Pla$k Pitch and Tar, from his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI>
Maje&s;ty's Dominions, and as for his Iron, which is
the only thing wanting, he has enough in his own
Country, if they plea&s;e but to dig for it, and of
Copper al&s;o.</P>
<P>HIS <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty's known Diligence in
the&s;e things is &s;uch, and his Application has been
follow'd with &s;o much Succc&s;s, that the Li&s;t of
his Fleet, as I have &s;een it in the latter End of the
Year 1720, was thus,
<LIST>
<ITEM>36 Ships of the Line, from 50 to 104
Guns each.</ITEM>
<ITEM>28 Frrgates, from 12 to 40 Guns each.</ITEM>
<ITEM>20 Brigantines and Sloops, from 4 to 10
Guns each.</ITEM>
<ITEM>360 Gallies for Tran&s;porting Soldiers.</ITEM>
<ITEM>120 Tran&s;port-Ships, and Ships employ'd in
fetching Timber, and Naval Materials from
<HI>Riga</HI> to <HI>Petersburg.</HI></ITEM>
</LIST></P>
<Q>Be&s;ides hir'd Ships.</Q>
<P>IF this Li&s;t he a true One, I refer the Reader
to any, or all the Hi&s;tories in the World, to find
<PB N="255" REF="264">
out one Example of any Prince in the World,
who from having not one Ship, or one Sea-Port in
tho&s;e Seas, did in &s;o &s;hort time furni&s;h out &s;uch a
Navy, and bring a Nation, who before knew little
or nothing of the Sea, and had neither Genius for
it, or Notion of it, to be Ma&s;ters of the Bu&s;ine&s;s, ex|pert
and able Seamen, and equal, if not Superi|or
to all his Neighbours of the <HI>Baltick.</HI></P>
<P>IT was but three Years between his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Ma|je&s;ty
having not one Ship, and a &s;trong Navy,
not one Port in tho&s;e Seas, and be Ma&s;ter of &s;ix
of the &s;tronge&s;t Port Towns in the North, (<HI>viz.</HI>)
<HI>Riga, Pernau, Revel, Narva, Petersburg</HI> and <HI>Wy|bourg.</HI></P>
<P>THE King of <HI>Denmark,</HI> as I have noted had
declared again&s;t <HI>Sweden,</HI> and had Landed an Ar|my
in <HI>Sc$honen,</HI> but was driven out again by plain
Force, and his Army entirely routed, and cut in
Peices at the great Battle of <HI>Hel&s;ingburg:</HI> This
throws him into the Arms of his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty,
who was now become the general Refuge of op|pre&s;s'd
Monarrhs, his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty embracing
all occa&s;ions to Support the Enemies of <HI>Sweden,</HI>
went in Per&s;on to his A&s;&s;i&s;tance, where a &s;econd
De&s;cent upon <HI>Schonen,</HI> was re&s;olved, and his Ma|je&s;ty
carried &s;uch a Fleet, and &s;uch an Army to
a&s;&s;i&s;t in that Work, that had been more than &s;uf|ficient
to have reduc'd the whole Kingdom of
<HI>Sweden,</HI> rather than a Province, which attempt,
how it was laid a&s;ide, and why, and what the
Con&s;equences of it were, we may &s;ee farther that
the relating the Story, of which in its turn.</P>
<P>BUT we mu&s;t now turn our Eyes to the Ea&s;t
and the South, from whence new Enemies were
rais'd up by the indefatigable bu&s;tle of the King
of <HI>Sweden,</HI> and the <HI>Palatine</HI> of <HI>Kio$u,</HI> of whom I took
<PB N="256" REF="265">
Notice, that being defeated he fled to <HI>Bender,</HI>
after the King of <HI>Sweden.</HI></P>
<P>THE King of <HI>Sweden</HI> was now come to <HI>Bender,</HI>
where the <HI>Ba&s;&s;a</HI> receiv'd him Civily, but would
not go any Length in protecting and &s;uccouring
him, without Orders, and therefore &s;ent a <HI>Chioux</HI>
Expre&s;s to <HI>Con&s;tantinople,</HI> for farther Instructions,
in the Affair of the King of <HI>Sweden;</HI> the An&s;wer
to which, was, an expre&s;s Order to &s;hew the King
of <HI>Sweden</HI> all po&s;&s;ible Re&s;pect, to a&s;&s;ure him of
the Protection of the <HI>Grand Senior,</HI> and to a&s;&s;ign
him a Place to re&s;ide in, near the Town; and to
defray his Expence, and the Expence of all his
Retinue, out of the Publick Trea&s;ure; &s;ending
at the &s;ame time, a Me&s;&s;enger to the King of
<HI>Sweden,</HI> to condole the Nece&s;&s;ity of his Flight,
and to a&s;&s;ure him of a powerful Protection from
the Grand <HI>Signior;</HI> with his A&s;&s;i&s;tance, as far as he
was able to re&s;tore his Affairs: This was brought
at the fir&s;t Enterance of the King of <HI>Sweden</HI> into
the <HI>Turk</HI>'s Dominions, but the King of <HI>Sweden</HI>
found Means afterwards, to put the whole <HI>Turk|i&s;h</HI>
Government into a Ferment, by the Means
of the <HI>Cham</HI> of <HI>Tartary,</HI> and the Platine of
<HI>Kiow</HI> above-nam'd.</P>
<P>IT &s;eems, the Palatine was an Intimate of
the <HI>Tartar</HI> Prince, and receiv'd &s;ignal Favours
from him, upon the fir&s;t News of his Misfor|tunes,
and &s;ome time after, the Palatine took
a Journey to the Camp of the <HI>Cham,</HI> to return his
Acknowledgement, but principally to &s;et$ on
Foot the Conferences, which afterwards produc'd
&s;uch remarkable Events.</P>
<P>AT this Interview, the Palatine firmly in|gaged
the <HI>Tartar</HI> Prince, in the King of <HI>Sweden's</HI>
Intere&s;t; and from that Time forward, they
<PB N="257" REF="266">
meditated together, the proper Mea&s;ures for bring|ing
in the Port to the &s;ame Sentiments, and to
break, if po&s;&s;ible, the Peace between the <HI>Grand
Seignior</HI> and the <HI>Czar,</HI> and bring a War upon the
<HI>Mu&s;covites.</HI></P>
<P>THEY had Room to In&s;inuate the exorbitant
growing Greatne&s;s of the <HI>Czar,</HI> upon this Defeat
of the King of <HI>Sweden,</HI> the Danger which hung
over the Head of the whole <HI>Ottoman</HI> Empire
from the encrea&s;e of Naval Power in the <HI>Black
Sea;</HI> the <HI>Czar</HI> building a Royal Navy at <HI>Veronitz,</HI>
his Fortifying of <HI>Azoph,</HI> and threatening, even
the imperial City of <HI>Con&s;tantinople</HI> it &s;elf.</P>
<P>THIS with &s;ome other, and more powerful
Motives, inflam'd the <HI>Cham</HI> of <HI>Tartary,</HI> who fail'd
not to have them repre&s;ented with Advantage to
the Grand <HI>Vizier,</HI> Embarking the Ba&s;&s;a of <HI>Bender</HI>
al&s;o in their Intere&s;t.</P>
<P>THIS I&s;&s;ued in the Palatine of <HI>Kiow</HI>'s going to
<HI>Con&s;tantinople;</HI> &s;ome told us he was &s;ent for by
the <HI>Grand Vizier;</HI> others, That he was &s;ent as an
Envoy from the King of <HI>Sweden;</HI> others, That
he was &s;ent by the <HI>Cham,</HI> or <HI>Han</HI> of <HI>Tartary.</HI> Be
that as it will, `tis certain that they manag'd
their Affairs &s;o artfully, that a grand <HI>Divan</HI> was
call'd at <HI>Con&s;tantinpole;</HI> the <HI>Grand Seignior,</HI> the
<HI>Grand Vizier,</HI> the <HI>Muffty,</HI> and the <HI>Captain Ba&s;&s;a,</HI>
or Admiral, were all brought into it being per&s;wad|ed
that a&s;&s;i&s;ting the <HI>Swede,</HI> and declaring again&s;t
the <HI>Mu&s;covite,</HI> was ab&s;olutely nece&s;&s;ary, and this
was the only Cri&s;is, when it might be effectual|ly
brought to pa&s;s, and when the <HI>Czar</HI> would
nece&s;&s;arily be reduc'd, and all the Danger ap|prehended
from him, be avoided, and return'd
upon him&s;elf.</P>
<P><PB N="258" REF="267">
IT was about the middle of <HI>November,</HI> 1710,
when the <HI>Turks</HI> came to a Re&s;olution, in their
great <HI>Givan</HI> at <HI>Con&s;tantinople,</HI> that it was nece&s;&s;ary
to Break with the <HI>Czar;</HI> immediately the Hor&s;e-Tail,
was &s;et up at the Gate of the <HI>Vizier</HI>'s Pal|lace,
and the Ru&s;&s;ian Amba&s;&s;ador was clapt into
Pri&s;on in the &s;even Towers, according to the Cu|&s;tom
of the <HI>Turks</HI> in &s;uch Ca&s;es.</P>
<P>THE <HI>Cham</HI> of <HI>Tartary</HI> was, it &s;eems, at this
<HI>Divan,</HI> and appearing to concur with the Propo|&s;al
of a War, making a long Speech to the Coun|cil
to move them to it, by &s;etting forth the great
Growth of the <HI>Czar's</HI> Empire, the Improvement
of his Soldiery, and the Naval Preparations
which he was making, to attack the Imperial Ci|ty
of <HI>Con&s;tantinople,</HI> and to Force a Pa&s;&s;age and
Communication with the <HI>Levant,</HI> and with the
Emperor, and the <HI>Venetians,</HI> the ancient Enemies
of the <HI>Turki&s;h</HI> Empire.</P>
<P>THIS Di&s;cour&s;e, together with his &s;etting forth
the great Opportunity put into their Hands, upon
this Junction of the King of <HI>Sweden,</HI> to reduce the
Power of the <HI>Czar,</HI> and even, if needful to de|throne
him, annimated the <HI>Turks</HI> to that Degree
$$at the War was re&s;olv'd on with the greate&s;t
Allacrity imaginable, and the Preparations began
Immediately; for the <HI>Cham</HI> was &s;ent Back to be|gin
Ho&s;tilitics and order'd to make Excur&s;ions;
the Palatine of <HI>Kiou</HI> had a great Sum of Money
given him, for the King of <HI>Sweden;</HI> and that
Prince was encourag'd to entertain a Body of
Troops, to be able to enter <HI>Poland,</HI> under the
Protecton of the Grand Army of the <HI>Turks,</HI>
when they &s;hould advance to the Frontiers;
and Mun&s;ieur de <HI>Kiou</HI> had 10000 Dollars given
<PB N="259" REF="268">
him for his own Share, and to &s;upport him&s;elf and
Friends.</P>
<P>HIS <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty was not much alarm'd at
this, his Affairs being at that Time in &s;o good a
po&s;ture, that he was able to appear Equal in the
Field to any of his Enemies, or to all of them if
they were put together. However, his Maje&s;ty
was not backward to make the needful Prepara|tions;
and when it appear'd that nothing was to
be done by Negotiation, he prepar'd to repel
Force by Force, and in the mean Time, cau&s;ed
his Troops to march for the Frontiers, to prevent
the Ravages and Incur&s;ions of the <HI>Tartars.</HI></P>
<P>WHILE the&s;e Things were doing, and that
both Sides prepar'd for War, we mu&s;t bring our
own Country of <HI>England</HI> into a little <HI>Demellez,</HI>
or Broil, with his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty, in which there
is, however, this to be &s;aid, that her Maje&s;ty
Queen, <HI>Anne</HI> being &s;en&s;ible, that the Injury was
done on the Side of <HI>England,</HI> and that the <HI>Czar</HI>
had Ju&s;tice on his Side, nothing was omitted that
could rea&s;onably be done, to give his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Ma|je&s;ty
Satisfaction; the Ca&s;e was about an Affront
put on the <HI>Czar</HI>'s Amba&s;&s;adour, by &s;ome Trade&s;men
here, who very ra&s;hly, and without con&s;idering
as they ought to have done, the publick Character
he carryed, Arre&s;ted Mon&s;ieur <HI>Matteuoff,</HI> the <HI>Ru&s;&s;ian</HI>
Amba&s;&s;ador, and in&s;ulted him very rudely, al&s;o
detaining him in Cu&s;tody for &s;ome Time.</P>
<P>THIS we mu&s;t not over-look; the Story is thus,
Mon&s;ieur <HI>Andrew Matteuoff,</HI> was Emba&s;&s;ador
Re&s;ident to her Maje&s;ty the Queen of <HI>Great Britain,</HI>
from the <HI>Czar</HI> of <HI>Mu&s;covy:</HI> Upon &s;ome Occa&s;ion
or other, he was Arre&s;ted, as above, by &s;ome private
Per&s;ons; who finding his Excellency had had
Audience of Leave of the Queen, and was going
<PB N="260" REF="269">
away; and imagining, or pretending to imagine,
he would leave the Kingdom, as it were in Cog|nito,
without paying a few Debts which he ow'd;
imploy'd &s;ome Bayliffs to Arre&s;t him; the Am|ba&s;&s;ador
ju&s;tly &s;urpris'd at this Treatment, in
Relation to the Laws of Nations; and perhaps
not &s;o readily &s;ubmitting to the &s;top, was very
roughly handled by tho&s;e &s;ort <HI>Canibals:</HI> Upon
which, he made Application for Redre&s;s to her
Maje&s;ty, and her Council, who immediately
took Care to confine tho&s;e Fellows, who had
thus, in Contempt of Authority, put this Affront
upon him. There were various Stories which
flew about, in Reference to the Particulars of
Reparation in&s;i&s;ted on, by his Excellency, which
I &s;hall not trouble my &s;elf to repeat. But in
&s;hort, his Excellency, at la&s;t, &s;eem'd to be a lit|tle
&s;atisfy'd; and her Maje&s;ty, even after his De|parture,
order'd her Attorney-General, a little
before the Beginning of that <HI>Micaelmas</HI> Term, to
pro&s;ecute tho&s;e who had been guilty in that Par|ticular,
in the <HI>Queen's-Bench</HI> Court. That this
was all that could be done, was certain; but
how little the <HI>Ru&s;&s;ian</HI> Amba&s;&s;ador was &s;atisfy'd
with it, will appear by the following Letters,
which pa&s;s'd between Mr. <HI>Henry Boyle,</HI> now Lord
<HI>Charleton,</HI> then Secretary of State, and the &s;aid
Mon&s;ieur <HI>Mattueoff,</HI> who was retir'd to <HI>Holland;</HI>
and by which the whole of the fir&s;t Part of that
tedious Story may be fully under&s;tood; the fir&s;t
Letter was from, the Amba&s;&s;adour to the Secreta|ry,
as follows.</P>
<LETTER>
<PB N="261" REF="270">
<OPENER>London, <DATE>July 22, 1708.</DATE> O. S.
<SALUTE>SIR,</SALUTE></OPENER>
<P>&startq;HAVING ob&s;erv'd (ever &s;ince I had the ho|nour
of being Amba&s;&s;ador extraordinary
of his (<HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty the Emperor of <HI>Great
Ru&s;&s;ia,</HI> at the Court of <HI>Great Britain</HI>) the &s;incere
and particular Affection which her Maje&s;ty as
&s;howed to my Ma&s;ter, and her earne&s;t De&s;ire of
Maintaining a good Corre&s;pondence between
the two Crowns of <HI>Great Ru&s;&s;ia,</HI> and <HI>Great Bri|tain;</HI>
al&s;o the Queen's Zeal for Ju&s;tice, &s;o well
known throughout the Univer&s;e: And, La&s;tly, the
&s;ingular Favour and Benevolence her Ma|je&s;ty
has been pleas'd to Confer on me, I have
all the Rea&s;on in the World to hope that &s;he will
vouch&s;afe to give me a Satisfaction proportio|nable
to the unparalell'd Affront which was put
upon me Ye&s;terday in the Evening, in the
Street call'd, <HI>Charles-Street.</HI>&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;THE matter of Fact &s;peaks of it &s;elf, and I
&s;hall only &s;ay in &s;hort, that the Bailiff of that
City had the Ra&s;hne&s;s to Arre&s;t me in my Coach,
and to carry me a Pri&s;oner to the <HI>Black Raven,</HI>
a &s;candalous Hou&s;e, without notifying to me the
Rea&s;on, and to abu&s;e me, by thru&s;ting him&s;elf
into my Coach, and &s;eizing on my Per&s;on, af|ter
taking away my Sword, Hat and Cane, as
it were from a Malefactor; not only contrary
to the Law of Nations, but even the Right of
all private Per&s;ons, the immunity of Amba&s;&s;a|dors,
and their &s;acred Priviledges are &s;ufficient|ly
<PB N="262" REF="271">
known; and as for the Pretence of Debts
alledg'd, it is impudently done; for I have
appointed this very Day for the time of Pay|ment,
and I am &s;o far from going away with|out
Di&s;charging them, that I have not as yet
receiv'd any Letter of Recredence, nor Pa&s;&s;port,
nor other things Nece&s;&s;ary for my Departure;
&s;o that this &s;hare has been laid for me, purely
with a De&s;ign to in&s;ult the Honour of his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI>
Maje&s;ty, in the Per&s;on of his Repre&s;entative;
therefore I &s;olemnly Prote&s;t again&s;t this Vio|lence
offer'd to the Law of Nations, and Demand
that all tho&s;e who are guilty of it be hereby pu|ni&s;hed.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;THE Queen, who is &s;o zealous of the Re&s;pect
to the Amba&s;&s;adors of Crown'd Heads, and has
&s;o gloriou&s;ly vindicated the Honour of the
Earl of <HI>Manche&s;ter</HI> her Amba&s;&s;ador at <HI>Venice,</HI>
and caus'd a rigorous Puni&s;hment to be inflicted
on the Officers of the Cu&s;tom-Hou&s;e; &s;ome of
whom were &s;et in the Pillory, and others con|demned
to Impri&s;onment, only for in&s;ulting the
Gentlemen of his Retinue, cannot but mo&s;t ju&s;t|ly
Revenge the Affront lately put upon me by
a Corporal Puni&s;hment.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;COUNT <HI>Zobor,</HI> who was delivered up to the Di&s;|cretion
of the King of <HI>Sweden,</HI> for picking a Quar|rel
with his Envoy; likewi&s;e affords an In&s;tance
of the &s;atisfaction I require, as being de&s;irous of
nothing with greater Earne&s;tne&s;s, than to avoid
all the ill Con&s;equences of this Affair: For in
Ca&s;e the Criminals are conniv'd at under any
Colour what&s;oever, I &s;hall be oblig'd to take o|ther
Mea&s;ures, and retire without Recreden|tials,
leaving the whole matter to the Manage|ment
of his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty my Ma&s;ter, as the
<PB N="263" REF="272">
Protector of his injur'd Honour, and his abus'd
Mini&s;ter,&endq;</P>
<CLOSER>Sir, I am, &amp;c.
To Mon&s;. <HI>Boyle,</HI> Mini&s;ter
and Secretary of State
to Her Maje&s;ty of <HI>Great
Britain.</HI>
<SIGNED>Sign'd
A. De MATUEOFF.</SIGNED>
Mon&s;. <HI>Mattueoff,</HI> receiving no An&s;wer to this Letter
&s;o &s;oon as he expected, be followed it with ano|ther
in four Days time, as follows, (<HI>viz.</HI>)</CLOSER>
</LETTER>
<LETTER>
<OPENER>London, <DATE>July 26, 1708.</DATE> O. S.
<SALUTE>SIR,</SALUTE></OPENER>
<P>&startq;FOR as much as I have not Receiv'd any Te&s;timony
of Concern or Regret, neither on
the Part of the Queen's Maje&s;ty, nor from any
of her Mini&s;ters &s;ince <HI>Thursday</HI> la&s;t, the 22d In|&s;tant,
when I &s;ent to you in writing any Com|plaints
about the wicked Attempts made upon
my Character; and in Regard that no Re&s;entment
has been in any wife &s;hewed upon the occa&s;ion
of that Indignity, in which the Honour of his
<HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty my Ma&s;ter has &s;uffered, after an
unheard of manner, you cannot take it ill that:
I intreat you to get a Pa&s;s-port for me as &s;oon
as po&s;&s;ible, and without Delay, to the End that
I may forth with go out of this Kingdom,&endq;</P>
<CLOSER>I am, Sir, <HI>&amp;c.</HI>
<SIGNED>Sign'd,
A. De MATUEOFF.</SIGNED></CLOSER>
</LETTER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="letter">
<PB N="264" REF="273">
<HEAD>A Copy of the An&s;wer to the Former from
White-hall, the <DATE>27th of July, 1708.</DATE></HEAD>
<OPENER><SALUTE>SIR,</SALUTE></OPENER>
<P>ACCORDINGLY, as I had the Honour to tell your
Excellency the fir&s;t time I was with you, after
the great Affront that was put upon you, I have us'd
my utmo&s;t Endeavours with all the Zeal I Profe&s;s
for your Excellency's Per&s;on, and Character, to find
out the mo&s;t effectual Means for cau&s;ing a due Repara|tion
to be made you; as &s;oon as I arriv'd at <HI>Wind|&s;or,</HI>
I inform'd the Queen of the Outrage committed
again&s;t your Excellency, and her Maje&s;ty order'd me to
a&s;&s;ure you, that she is extreamly Concern'd upon account
of that enormous Procedure, and highly di&s;pleas'd with
Her Subjects who were the Authors of it; and for as
much as the Queen has all the Re&s;pect imaginable for
his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty, who&s;e Friend&s;hip and good Cor|re&s;pondence
have been at all Times, and ever will be
mo&s;t Dear and Precious to Her; and in Regard that
&s;he has a very peculiar E&s;teem for your Excellency's
Per&s;on and Merit, &s;he will omit nothing that lyes in Her
Power, to give an ample Satisfaction for the extraordi|nary
affront which has been put upon your Excellency;
and to &s;hew her own Re&s;entments on <HI>Sunday</HI> la&s;t, an extraordinary A&s;&s;embly of her Maje&s;ty's Privy-Coun|cil
was call'd at <HI>Wind&s;or,</HI> and &s;even of the Princi|pal
Accomplices in that de&s;perate Attempt were ta|ken
up, and committed to Pri&s;on; and the Council
is to meet again about that Affair, as &s;oon as po&s;&s;ible,
which will be on <HI>Thur&s;day</HI> next, to Treat in the &s;ame
manner the re&s;t who &s;hall be found guilty of that in|&s;olent
Pre&s;umption: And further, the Queen has or|dered
her Attorney General to draw up an Indictment
<PB N="265" REF="274">
again&s;t all tho&s;e Per&s;ons, to the End that they may
be Puni&s;hed after the mo&s;t &s;evere and rigorous Manner,
that can be according to the Law of this Realm; and I
am very &s;orry that your Excellency expre&s;&s;es &s;o much
earne&s;tne&s;s to Depart, &s;ince one would be glad that you
would &s;tay to &s;ee with what &s;trictne&s;s Endeavours would
be us'd to give you Satisfaction.</P>
<P>AS for my Part, I am extreamly troubled the Oc|ca&s;ion is
&s;o Bad, and the Subject &s;o Di&s;agreeable, up|on
which I profe&s;s my &s;elf Devoted to your Service,
but as I always took great Delight, when I was other|wi&s;e
employ'd; &s;o your Excellency will permit me even
on this unfortunate Account to declare how much I
am Concern'd for your Intere&s;t, and with what Af|fection
and E&s;teem,</P>
<CLOSER>I am your, <HI>&amp;c.</HI>
<SIGNED>Sign'd,
H. BOYLE.</SIGNED>
To his Excellency M. <HI>DE MAT|TUEOFF,</HI>
Amba&s;&s;ador Ex|traordinary
of his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty.</CLOSER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2>
<P>THE Amba&s;&s;ador was &s;o far from being &s;atis|fied
with the Letter above, that he immediately
demanded his Pa&s;s-port for him&s;elf, and Family,
in a &s;hort Letter as follows,</P>
<LETTER>
<OPENER>London, <DATE>July, 27, 1708.</DATE> O. S.
<SALUTE>SIR,</SALUTE></OPENER>
<P>&startq;PURSUANT to your Word, which I obtain'd
this Day, I waited from Noon, till about
Half an Hour after Three a-Clock for the
Re&s;olution in Writing about the &s;olemn Com|plaints
<PB N="266" REF="275">
I to you the 22d wrote In&s;tant; but
for as much as the Bu&s;ine&s;s very much Re&s;embles
&s;o many former Promi&s;es, which prov'd Inef|fectual
in other Affairs, I &s;hall leave it to your
Di&s;cretion, and only intreat you to &s;end me a
Pa&s;s-port for my &s;elf and Family: Sir, I expect
at lea&s;t this Favour from your kind Di&s;po&s;i|tion,&endq;</P>
<CLOSER>Who am, <HI>&amp;c.</HI>
To Mon&s;ieur <HI>Boyle,</HI>
Mini&s;ter and Se|cretary
of State to
her Maje&s;ty the
Queen of <HI>Great
Britain.</HI>
<SIGNED>Sign'd
A. DE MATUEOFF.</SIGNED></CLOSER>
</LETTER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2>
<HEAD>Mr. Secretary Boyle, tho' very unwilling the Am|ba&s;&s;ador
&s;hould have gone away without having fir&s;t
receiv'd full Satisfaction for the Ill-u&s;age he had
met with, &s;ent him the following Letter, with the
Pa&s;s-port enclos'd.</HEAD>
<P>&startq;I HAVE &s;ent to your Excellency this Morn|ing
the <HI>Pa&s;s-port</HI> you de&s;ir'd, and as for the
Orders concerning your Moveables, having
writ about them &s;ome time ago, I have &s;ince got
further Information in the Trea&s;ury, where
they a&s;&s;ure me that the Orders are i&s;&s;ued
out; and that the Officers of the Cu&s;tom-Hou&s;e are to
wait on your Excellency this Morning, to cau&s;e
the Equipages to be Tran&s;ported without any
Mole&s;tation, and I hope they have already done
it to your Excellency's Satisfaction.&endq;</P>
<P><PB N="267" REF="276">
&startq;I ALSO give my &s;elf the Honour to notifie to
your Excellency, That an extraordinary&punc; Meet|ing
of the Lords of the Queen's Privy Coun|cil
is to be held this Day at Noon, to enquire
farther into the Circumstances of that di&s;mal
Affair; they have made a &s;trict Search after
tho&s;e who were in any Wi&s;e Concern'd therein,
and have caus'd Ten others to be apprehended;
&s;o that there are at pre&s;ent Seventeen Per&s;ons
confin'd in Pri&s;on, for being concern'd in that
enormous Action again&s;t your Excellency, and
further Orders have been given again to the At|torney
General to Pro&s;ecute them with the ut|mo&s;t
Rigour, and to omit nothing that may
Contribute toward the making to your Excellen|cy
the mo&s;t &s;ignal Reparation that can be accord|ing
to our Laws.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;I have already had the Honour to a&s;&s;ure your
Excellency of the Queen's Sentiments touching
this Outrage: But I am to Repeat again, that
Her Maje&s;ty will not forbear by all po&s;&s;ible
Means, to &s;hew the extraordinary Indignation
She has conceiv'd, again&s;t tho&s;e who have put &s;o
notorious an Affront upon the Amba&s;&s;ador of
Her good Friend, and Allie, his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty
your Ma&s;ter.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;I cannot conclude without returning Thanks
to your Excellency for your la&s;t Letter of Ye|&s;terday,
a&s;&s;uring you that my Duty, as well as
Inclination engages me to u&s;e my utmo&s;t Efforts,
in order to procure the mo&s;t ample Satisfaction
for your Excellency; and that nothing affords
me greater Delight, than being per&s;waded
<PB N="268" REF="277">
that you'l do me the Ju&s;tice to believe, that I
am with a great Deal of Re&s;pect, and Af|fection,</P>
<CLOSER><SALUTE>SIR,</SALUTE>
To his Excellency, Mon&s;ieur
<HI>De MATEUOFF,</HI> Am|ba&s;&s;ador
Extraordinary
of his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty.
<SIGNED>Sign'd
H. BOYLE.</SIGNED></CLOSER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2>
<P>AFTER the&s;e Letters were written on both
Sides, the <HI>Mu&s;covite</HI> Amba&s;&s;ador retir'd to <HI>Hol|land;</HI>
but a new Memorial was &s;oon after pre|&s;ented,
on his Part, at the <HI>Briti&s;h</HI> Court, with
a Letter &s;ent by his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty him&s;elf, a
Copy of which is here &s;ubjoin'd.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="letter">
<HEAD>A Tran&s;lation of a Letter, written in Latin, by
His Sacred Czari&s;h Maje&s;ty, to the Mo&s;t Serene
Queen of Great Britain.</HEAD>
<Q>(After both Titles, at large)</Q>
<P>WE, cannot forbear notifying to your Maje&s;ty, with
how great Trouble of Mind and horror, by the
humble Remon&s;trances of <HI>Andrew de Matteuoff,</HI> our
Amba&s;&s;ador at your Court, Charg'd with &s;everal im|portant
Commi&s;&s;ions; me have receiv'd an unexpected
Peice of News, <HI>viz.</HI> That the &s;aid Amba&s;&s;ador,
after having obtain'd an Audience of Leave of your
Maje&s;ty, at <HI>London,</HI> the Place of your Re&s;idence;
out of premeditated Malice, and of &s;et Purpo&s;e, (as
<PB N="269" REF="278">
it appears) was &s;et upon in the open Street, by &s;everal
Bailiffs, who receiv'd their Commi&s;&s;ion from a certain
Vi&s;count or Sheriff, and acted like Robbers again&s;t
the Publick Laws of Nations, with an unheard of,
and unparallell'd Barbarity: For by Di&s;per&s;ing his
Servants, violently breaking his Coach, taking away
his Sword, Cane and Hat, and tearing his Cloaths;
put, upon him &s;uch a notorious Affront as no civil|liz'd
Per&s;on would pre&s;ume to offer to a foreign Mini|&s;ter
of his Character; nor even to a Commoner, unle&s;s
he would run the Ri&s;que of being Mo&s;t &s;everely pu|ni&s;h'd:
And what mo&s;t of all inhances the Heinou&s;|ne&s;s
of the Fact, while our &s;aid Amba&s;&s;ador, crying
out for Help, again&s;t the Outrage and Robbery, had
got together &s;ome Per&s;ons, who intended to re&s;cue
him out of the Hands of the Pillagers; and when
they, for that Purpo&s;e, bad &s;topp'd the Coach, and
being de&s;irous to know the Cau&s;e, brought him into
the next Victualling Hou&s;e, the audacious Mi&s;creants,
produc'd a Warrant to detain the &s;aid Amba&s;&s;ador,
for the Sum of 50 l. Sterling, due from him, to cer|tain
Merchants: And when the People, who ran
together, began to &s;eparate again, upon the Di&s;covery
of the Matter; they forthwith hurry'd him into a
Hackney Coach, taken by Force, and delivered him
up to be confin'd in a certain Infamous Hou&s;e, call'd
the <HI>Black Raven</HI> and altho', our &s;aid Amba&s;&s;a|dor,
had notify'd this unheard of, and flagitious Out|rage,
to the Secretary of State, neverthele&s;s, he could
not be found; and Secretary <HI>Walpole,</HI> only came
to the Hou&s;e, not to &s;et him at Liberty, (as mo&s;t
evidently appears) but to be an Eye Witne&s;s of this
U&s;age; the like of which, was never &s;een under the
Sun; neither did he offer any A&s;&s;i&s;tance to our Am|ba&s;&s;adour,
as a Per&s;on &s;kill'd in the publick Law of
Nations, which Protects the Character of an Ainba&s;&s;a|dor
<PB N="270" REF="279">
from all manner of In&s;ults, but went away: So
that our &s;aid Amba&s;&s;ador being de&s;titute of all Help,
and for&s;aken, was forced to Redeem him&s;elf, from
the Hou&s;e of Bondage; and after a long Space of
Time, to procure his Liberty.</P>
<P>Fora&s;much, then, as our Maje&s;ty is apparently
a&s;&s;aulted, by thi$ wicked Attempt and Indignity, put
upon the Per&s;on of our Amba&s;&s;adour, &s;uch as was
never practi&s;ed nor even heard of in the whole World;
much le&s;s among civiliz'd People; not only profain|ing,
but quite &s;ubverting the Law of Nations.
Therefore hoping that your Royal Maje&s;ty will have
due Regard, to the grievous Affront offer'd to us, in
the Per&s;on of our Amba&s;&s;ador, together with the In|fringement
of the Law of Nations, occa&s;ion'd primal|ly
by the Sheriff, as the Author of the whole Mi&s;|chief,
inasmuch, as the &s;aid Sheriff countenanc'd &s;o
a$ndacious an attempt, and look'd upon the detaining
$ur Amba&s;&s;adour, as a Tri$le. And, &s;econdly, by the
Bailiff who pre&s;um'd to abu&s;e our &s;aid Amba&s;&s;ador
in the open Street, after the above-mention'd Manner.
And la&s;tly, by the Merchants, who occa&s;ion'd his
Confinement, (as is evident from their malevolent
$&s;tigation, in order to overthrow the ancient Friend|&s;hip
e&s;tabli&s;h'd with us and our Empire) wherefore,
we being per&s;$aded, that your Maje&s;ty will e&s;teem
$word$ Per&s;ons no otherwi&s;e, than as the mo&s;t pro$li|ga$e
of Pillagers and Violater of the Law of Nations,
prop$rtio$aile to their Guilt, we intreat your Maje|&s;ty
to Con&s;ent, for an Example to others, a diligent
Search may be made after the re&s;t of the Accompli|ces
of the Crime, and that a capital Puni&s;hment ac|cording
to the rigour of the Law, be in$$icted on them
all, or at lea&s;t &s;uch a one, as is adequate to the Na|ture
of the Affront, which every Particular Per&s;on
put upon the Amba&s;&s;ador.</P>
<P><PB N="271" REF="280">
The &s;ame Amba&s;&s;ador, by Vertue of the In|&s;tructions
given him, on this Subject, will more
largely explain our Reque&s;t to your Maje&s;ty, which
has been already declar'd, by our Mini&s;ters, to your
Maje&s;ty's Re&s;ident in our Court; on tho&s;e Con&s;ide|rations
we have Rea&s;on to hope, from your Maje&s;ty's
ju&s;tice, &s;uch a Satisfaction for this Intolerable Out|rage;
and the rather in regard that your Maje&s;ty's
Honour, and Reputation of all your Subjects of
Great Britain, will by this Means become famous
throughout the whole World; and we &s;hall be certain|ly
a&s;&s;ur'd of the Continuance of your Royal Friend|&s;hip,
and all Effects of a contrary Opinion, will be
entirely remov'd: And lea&s;t, upon Failure of a Satis|faction
worthy of, and equivolant to our injur'd
Honour, we be compell'd to obtain it by way of Repri|&s;al;
which, indeed, would be very irk&s;ome to us, upon
Account of that particular E&s;teem, we have for your
Maje&s;ty's Friend&s;hip. Finally, We wi&s;h your Maje&s;ty
Health, and a pro&s;perous Reign.</P>
<CLOSER>Given at our Camp, near the Village of <HI>Sowo|lewo,</HI>
the 17th Day of <HI>September, O. S.</HI> in
the Year of our Lord, 1708, and the 27th
of our Reign, by your affectionate Brother.
Sign'd by his Sacred <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty,
<SIGNED>PETER.</SIGNED>
Under-neath,
Count <HI>Golo&s;kin,</HI> Peter Scapiraff,
Secretary of the Privy. Council.</CLOSER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="letter">
<PB N="272" REF="281">
<HEAD>To the Amba&s;&s;adors Letter, Mr. Secretary
Boyle return'd the following An&s;wer.</HEAD>
<OPENER><SALUTE>SIR,</SALUTE></OPENER>
<P>&startq;I Did not think Fit to return a Speedy An|wer,
to the two Letters of the 27th of
<HI>November,</HI> and 4th of <HI>December</HI> la&s;t, <HI>N. S.</HI> with
which your Excellency was pleas'd to Honour
me; becau&s;e I could not inform you, what Sa|tisfacton
our Laws would afford, again&s;t tho&s;e
who put that grievous Affront upon your Excel|lency's
Per&s;on: But fora&s;much, as-I am appre|hen&s;ive
that too long a Silence, may be taken for
want of due Re&s;pect for your Excellency; or,
that I have net been &s;ufficiently &s;olicitous to put
in Execution, every thing that is incumbent
upon the Queen's Maje&s;ty, in order to procure
the promis'd Reparation: I could no longer for|bear
making An&s;wer to your Excellency, to
a&s;&s;ure you, that the Re&s;entment you expre&s;s of
the outragious Affront, particularly in your
Letter, of the 27th of <HI>November</HI> ult. Cannot
be greater, than the Indignation which her Maje&s;ty
has conceiv'd upon that Account; and I
doubt not, but Mr. <HI>de Ayrolle,</HI> according to the
Inructions he receiv'd, has already notify'd to
your Excellency, that the indi&s;pen&s;able Forms
of the Laws of this Kingdom, cannot admit of a
final Determination of that Affair, till the
next Se&s;&s;ions of our Court of Judicature, which
is &s;o well known, and &s;o firmly regulated here,
that in order to puni&s;h any Malefactor, for the
mo&s;t enormous Crimes, even Trea&s;on again&s;t
<PB N="273" REF="282">
her Maje&s;ty's Sacred Per&s;on, he mu&s;t be brought
to his Tryal, according to u&s;ual Forms e&s;tabli&s;h'd
in this Country: I am per&s;waded that
your Excellency's Saga&s;ity and Equitablene&s;s,
will di&s;tingui&s;h between the In&s;olence and Bru|ti&s;hne&s;s
of &s;ome particular &s;en&s;le&s;s Men, and the
Marks of a very particular E&s;teem and Re&s;pect,
which you have receiv'd upon all Occa&s;ions,
as well from the Queen, as from Per&s;ons em|ploy'd
in the highe&s;t Offices of the Govern|ment:
And that your Excellency will be &s;o
Ju&s;t, as to believe, that they would not have
failed to give you the mo&s;t ample Satisfaction,
long ago, if the Means of doing it were as rea|dy
at Hand, and Practicable, as the Queen's
inclination is forward to &s;atisfy his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Ma|je&s;ty thereupon: Therefore I hope your Excel|lency,
will repre&s;ent the State of this Affair,
to his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty, after the mo&s;t favoura|ble
Manner, a&s;&s;uring him, that nothing has been
neglected by, and that nothing for the Future,
&s;hall be omitted, which tends to procure all the
Reparation the utmo&s;t rigour of the funda|mental
Laws of this Kingdom can afford. And
farther, if this be not found &s;ufficient, and any
thing can be &s;ugge&s;ted, that is in the Queen's
Power, whereby the may expre&s;s her high Di&s;|plea&s;ure
again&s;t tho&s;e who committed &s;o notorious
an in&s;ult, which may contribute to the
maintaining of Amity and good Corre&s;pondence
between her and his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty, &s;he will
not fail on her Part, to be always ready to do
it; upon that Account, I lately propo&s;ed, by
the Queen's &s;pecial Order to the Parliament of
<HI>Great Britain,</HI> that a Bill might be brought in,
<PB N="274" REF="283">
for e&s;tabli&s;hing, and &s;ecuring the Privileges of
Amba&s;&s;adors and other foreign Mini&s;ters, as well
to prevent the like Outrages for the future, as to
notify, at the &s;ame Time, to the whole World,
how far her Maje&s;ty, and the whole <HI>Briti&s;h</HI> Na|tion
dete&s;t the Violence that was offer'd to your
Excellency's Per&s;on and Character, but for as
much, as her Maje&s;ty, is de&s;irous of nothing
more, than to be in a Capacity of giving
Satisfaction in that Affair and &s;he is ab&s;o|lutely
di&s;po&s;ed to do all that lies in her
Power for that Purpo&s;e, we are per&s;waded,
that his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty will not forbear ha|ving
&s;o ju&s;t a Regard to the Queen's Friend&s;hip,
and the ancient Alliancies, between the
two Crowns, that he will not in&s;i&s;t upon her
attempting Impo&s;&s;ibilities; and that he will
not undertake any thing, which may in any
wife be prejudicial to the good Corre&s;pondence
that has been hitherto maintain'd between
both their Maje&s;ty's, and which, as I hope
will continue for ever. I have the Satisfaction
to inform your Excellency, that the Queen
had no &s;ooner Notice, that two young <HI>Mu&s;|covite</HI>
princes, the Relations of his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Ma|je&s;ty,
were arrived in this Kingdom, but &s;he
forthwith gave Orders for their Reception
and Entertainment, with that particular Di|&s;tinction,
and Re&s;pect, which is due to their
high Birth. As for what Concerns my
&s;elf have, in executing the Queen's Orders
on this Emergency, I &s;hall di&s;charge my
Duty with a great deal of Delight: And I
can a&s;&s;ure your Excellency, at that time, that
no Per&s;on in the World can be more for|ward
<PB N="275" REF="284">
in expre&s;&s;ing to you upon, all Oppor|tunities
which &s;hall offer them&s;elves, with
how great E&s;teem and Re&s;pect,&endq;</P>
<CLOSER>I am,
<SALUTE>SIR,</SALUTE>
Your Excellency's, &amp;c.
<SIGNED>H. BOYLE.</SIGNED></CLOSER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="letter">
<HEAD>To this Letter the Amba&s;&s;ador of Mu&s;covy
made An&s;wer to this Effect.</HEAD>
<OPENER><SALUTE>SIR,</SALUTE></OPENER>
<P>I HAD the honour to receive your Letter, dated
from White-hall, the 11th In&s;tant, O. S. and I
find therein many Declartions and Promi&s;es for the
future, as to what relates to the Reparation to the un|paralell'd
A&s;&s;ault made upon me by the Rabble, which
Promi&s;es are directed to his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty my Ma|&s;ter,
on the part of the Queen of <HI>Great Britain;</HI> but
for the re&s;t, all that I can ob&s;erve mo&s;t con&s;iderable,
is the Propo&s;al you have tendered to the Parliament of
<HI>Great Britain,</HI> by the Queen's In&s;tructions, in order
to get a Law enacted for the Security, and Mainte|nance
of the Sacred Privileges of Amba&s;&s;adors, and
other foreign Mini&s;ters, re&s;iding in her Maje&s;ty's Courts;
indeed this is a very proper Means to di&s;&s;ipate the Fears
which they were &s;eized with, &s;ince the In&s;ult that was
made, on a Mini&s;ter of the fir&s;t Rank, however, give me
<PB N="276" REF="285">
leave to tell you farther, that nothing carries le&s;s Ap|pearance
of the Satisfaction which his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje|&s;ty
requires, &s;ince the definitive Re&s;olution is &s;till want|ing
and is referr'd to the particular Laws of the
Country, &s;o that the Bu&s;ine&s;s is protracted by putting
it off from Time to Time, and from one Delay to a|nother:
If it were in the Queen's Power to con&s;ult the
Parliament about enacting of a new Law, touching the
immunity of foreign Mini&s;ters, and to prevent the Out|rages
which might be hereafter offer'd to them, could
not due Mea&s;ures have been taken at the &s;ame time,
for the Reparation of the pa&s;s'd Affront, which ac|cording
to your Letter is dete&s;ted by the, Queen, and
the whole <HI>Briti&s;h Nation:</HI> Certainly, it is a very ea|&s;y
Matter to do it, in Ca&s;e her Maje&s;ty has the lea&s;t
Inclination to bold an amicable Corre&s;pendence with
his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty, as his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty is di&s;|po&s;ed
to do with her, and to maintain the Law of
Nations in its Vigour, as the whole Univer&s;e does;
which ought to be the rather to be expected from the
Queen, &s;ince &s;he has formerly Contributed very much
to the Pre&s;ervation of the &s;ame, by firmly demand|ing
of the Republick of <HI>Venice,</HI> for an affront
offer'd to the Earl of Manche&s;ter her Amba&s;&s;ador,
altho' the In&s;ult was only made upon his Barks
and dome&s;tick Servants; &s;o that the S$nate, not|with&s;tanding
the mo&s;t ancient Laws of the Re|publick,
was prevailed upon to follow the Law of
Nations, by &s;atisfying the Amba&s;&s;ador, after the
manner he de&s;ir'd and demanded. Sir, You de&s;ire
by the &s;ame Letter, that I &s;hould acquaint his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI>
Maje&s;ty with the delay of your Courts of Judicature,
which binders this Affair; from being brought to an
I&s;&s;ue, altho' it might have been very conveniently ad|ju&s;ted
in the Space of &s;ix Months, &s;ince which Time
the Accident happen'd. But fora&s;much as your Let|ter
<PB N="277" REF="286">
contains nothing definitive, with Re&s;pect to the Sa|ti&s;faction.
I am extreamly concern'd, that it is not in
my Power to comply with your De&s;ires in that Particu|lar,
and I am &s;o much the more uncapable of doing it,
in regard that I have receiv'd his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty's
po&s;itive Re&s;olution upon the Bu&s;ine&s;; as al&s;o, later
Orders, earne&s;tly to pre&s;s for the Qneen's An&s;wer
to my Ma&s;ter's Letter, and a Categorical Determi|nation,
whether the Law of Nation, with Re&s;pect
to foreign Powers, will be ob&s;erv'd or not? There|fore,
pur&s;uant to the &s;aid Orders, which I have
newly receiv'd, I would entreat you, Sir$ to honour
me with an An&s;wer to the above-mention'd Articles,
after you have &s;hewn the Contents to the Queen; to
the End that this Affair may be no longer de&s;err'd,
for the Delay occa&s;ion'd by your Laws, cannot give
any manner of &s;atisfaction to his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty,
As to the Honours that have been lately done, by the
Queen's &s;pecial Command, to the two yomng Noble
Men, who are taken for <HI>Mu&s;covite Princes,</HI> related
to his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty, and are now at <HI>London;</HI>
I can a&s;&s;ure you, that his Maje&s;ty reckons none but the
Imperial Hereditary Prince within the Virge of his
augu&s;t Hou&s;e: They are two young Lords of illu&s;tru|ous
Birth, who have the Honour of being a Kin to
him, and are Travelling, <HI>incognito,</HI> to &s;ee the
World. But his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty does not de&s;ire that
they &s;hould be defray'd by any Power, they have
where withal to bear their own Charges, and if with|out
their Ma&s;ter's Orders, they think fit to accept of
Lodgings, or any thing el&s;e of that Nature, they are
to be accountable for t be &s;ame. It only remains, that
I return Thanks for the Kindne&s;s and Good Will you
profe&s;s to have for me, of the future Continuance of
which you are al&s;o pleas'd to a&s;&s;ure me; offering
you, my reciprocal Readine&s;s, to expre&s;s to you,
<PB N="278" REF="287">
the particular E&s;teem, and unlimited Affection, where|with,</P>
<CLOSER>I am,
<SALUTE>SIR,</SALUTE> &amp;c.
<SIGNED>De MATUEOFF.</SIGNED></CLOSER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2>
<P>IN the <HI>February</HI> next, after this, the Per&s;ons
were brought to Tryal on an Information in the
Queen's Name again&s;t Tho. Morton, I&s;aac Spilt$mb,
<HI>Andrew Slan, Ed. $oung,</HI> and Ten more, for Meet|ing$
Con&s;ulting and Con&s;piring to Arre&s;t the &s;aid
Ru&s;&s;ian Mini&s;ter, for which they were all, except
$o$ug found Guilty; the &s;pecial Matter of the
Privilege of Amba&s;&s;adors being refferr'd by the
Jury to the Opinion of the Judges.</P>
<P>BESIDES this pro&s;ecution, a Bill was brought
into the next Parliament for pre&s;erving the Pri|vilege
of Amba&s;&s;adors, and other publick Mini|&s;ters,
which was done to prevent the like for
the future; but this would not be taken as Satis|faction
to the <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Mini&s;ter, for what had pa&s;s'd
before; bat to give him as much Satisfaction as
the Ca&s;e would bear, and to give as much weight
to the &s;aid Pro&s;ecution and Act of Parliament as
po&s;&s;ible.</P>
<P><HI>Mon&s;ie$r</HI> D' Ayrole's, the Queen's Secretary at
the Hague, wrote to Mon&s;ieur <HI>Mattueoff,</HI> as fol|lows.</P>
<P>The Amba&s;&s;ador was then at <HI>Am&s;terdam.</HI></P>
<LETTER>
<PB N="279" REF="288">
<OPENER><SALUTE>MY LORD,</SALUTE></OPENER>
<P>&startq;YESTERDAY in the Evening came in 5 Po&s;ts
from <HI>England,</HI> whereupon being inform'd
that your Excellency will not be here till the
end of the Week, I would not fail to give you
an Account without delay, according to my
Promi&s;e; and for due Execution of my Orders
of what has happen'd la&s;t in <HI>England,</HI> concern|ing
your Affairs; I therefore acquaint your Ex|cellency,
that on the 14th and 15th of the la&s;t
Month, the Per&s;ons engag'd in Arre&s;ting your
Excellency appeared before the Lord Chief Ju|&s;tice
in the Court, which we call the <HI>Queen's|Bench;</HI>
her Maje&s;ty's two Secretaries of State,
the Lord <HI>Sunderland</HI> and Mr. <HI>Boyle</HI> being pre|&s;ent
there, with a great Number of other Per|&s;ons
of Note, who were no le&s;s de&s;irous of
&s;eeing the Criminals brought to condign Pu|ni&s;hment,
then they were concern'd at the In|&s;ult
offer'd to your Excellency. The Indict|ment
was laid again&s;t <HI>Thomas Morten,</HI> and
other Creditors of your Excellency; as
al&s;o again&s;t one <HI>Ben&s;on,</HI> an Attorney em|ployed
in taking out the executory Orders
for Arre&s;ting your Excellency, and the two
Bailiffs who actually Arre&s;ted you; the Par|ties
being heard, after a long and con&s;idera|ble
Plea, made by the Queen's Attorney Gene|neral,
Sollicitor General, and other Per&s;ons
learn'd in the Law, acting for her Maje&s;ty, the
Jury con&s;i&s;ting of Gentlemen of Di&s;tinction,
and plentiful E&s;tates in the Country; more
e&s;pecially Cho&s;en on that Occa&s;ion, declared
the Per&s;ons mention'd in the Indictment, ex|cept
<PB N="280" REF="289">
one <HI>$oung,</HI> again&s;t whom no Evidence ap|pear'd,
to be convicted of having Comploted and
Con&s;pired together to Arre&s;t your Excellencies
Per&s;on,
notwithstanding they knew the &s;ame to
be inve&s;ted with the Character of an Amba&s;&s;ador;
as al&s;o having by that Means occa&s;ion'd a
Mi&s;-under&s;tanding betwixt the Queen and his
<HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty, and of having a&s;&s;aulted, ar|re&s;ted,
impri&s;oned, and abus'd the &s;aid Per&s;on of
your Excellency; the Jury having thus given in
your Verdict, and the Ca&s;e being &s;o Extraordi|nary,
of very great importance, altogether New,
and without Pre&s;ident in our Courts of <HI>England,</HI>
the Lord Chief Ju&s;tice could not take upon him
to determine it, but referr'd the Point relating
to the Privileges of Amba&s;&s;adors, that is to &s;ay,
how far the Laws of the Realm may reach for
the Puni&s;hing of tho&s;e who violate them to a
Scrutiny, which is to be made the next Term
before him, a&s;&s;i&s;ted hy the other Judges of
the Kingdom: This is the pre&s;ent State of
the Bu&s;ine&s;s, it is not ab&s;olutely decided,
but the indicted Per&s;ons are found guilty of the
Fact, and Puni&s;hment will be &s;olemnly
debated before all the Judges of the King|dom,
the Ca&s;e having never before been
known in our Law, therefore if you plea&s;e
tis Requi&s;ite that your Excellency have a
little more Patience to &s;ee the final deter|mination
of this Proce&s;s, and content your &s;elf
in waiting with your wonted Prudence, and Mo|deration
for the i&s;&s;ue of the Queen's efforts in
pro&s;ecuting the Criminals, &s;ince her Maje&s;ty has
omitted nothing on her Part for that purpo&s;e, for
if our Formalities of Inju&s;tice appear'd long and
tedious; 'tis what cannot in any wi&s;e be reme|died;
<PB N="281" REF="290">
it being part of our Con&s;titution, to which
every individual Per&s;on in the Kingdom is ob|lig'd
to &s;ubmit; I have already had the honour
to Treat with your Excellency &s;o often upon
this Subject, that I hope you are &s;en&s;ible there|of,
and of the Queen's mo&s;t &s;incere Intentions to
do every thing that lies in her Maje&s;ty's power
for repairing the injury done to your Per&s;on,
and Character, I doubt not but the whole will
terminate in the common Satisfaction, I am with
profound re&s;pect,&endq;</P>
<CLOSER><SALUTE>My Lord,</SALUTE>
<HI>Your Excellencies,</HI> &amp;c.
<HI>Sign'd,</HI>
<SIGNED>J. D' AYROLLE.</SIGNED></CLOSER>
</LETTER>
<P>TO this the Amba&s;&s;ador made a &s;hort Reply,
intimating, that the other Letter was not &s;atis|factory;
on which Mr. Secretary <HI>Boyle,</HI> being
willing, if po&s;&s;ible, to give him full Satisfaction,
wrote as Follows.</P>
<LETTER>
<PB N="282" REF="291">
<OPENER><SALUTE>SIR,</SALUTE></OPENER>
<P>&startq;FOR as much as Mr. <HI>D' Ayrole,</HI> has had Or|ders
from time to time, to notifie to your
Excellency, what has happen'd with Re&s;pect to
the Trial of tho&s;e Per&s;ons, who put the Out|ragious
Affront upon your Excellency; I look'd
upon it as needle&s;s to trouble your Excellency
with any Letters about that Affair; but &s;ince
I perceive by the Honour of your la&s;t, that you
pre&s;s for an An&s;wer to his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty's Let|ter,
with a great deal of earne&s;tne&s;s, I can no long|er
exempt my &s;elf from acquainting-your Excel|lency,
that the Queen on her Side is very de&s;irous
of being in a capacity to An&s;wer the &s;aid Let|ter,
after &s;uch a manner as is Requi&s;ite; but
for as much as the Tryal cannot be brought to
a Conclu&s;ion, by Rea&s;on of the indi&s;penable
Formalities of our Laws; it is evident that an
An&s;wer mu&s;t needs be imperfect before a final
Determination of this Ca&s;e; this is the only
Rea&s;on, for which it has been judged expedi|ent
to defer the An&s;wer, and I doubt not but
your Excellency will do &s;o much Ju&s;tice to the
Queen, as to make convenient Excu&s;es there|upon,
to the End that his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty may be
certified, that this &s;top put to the Bu&s;ine&s;s, does
not proceed from any affected procra&s;tination,
but from an in&s;uperable Nece&s;&s;ity, and I ought
to a&s;&s;ure your Excellency, that when the &s;aid
Cau&s;e comes to be determined, her Maje&s;ty will
not $$ail to An&s;wer his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty's Letters,
in &s;uch Terms as that he will clearly perceive
the Queen is Solicitous of nothing more, then
to give the mo&s;t ample Satisfaction which can
<PB N="283" REF="292">
be made for the &s;aid Indignity; I likewi&s;e do
my&s;elf the Honour to inform your Excellency,
that the Bill for maintaining the Privileges of
Amba&s;&s;adors is ready to pa&s;s into the Hou&s;e of
Lords; &s;o that in a &s;hort time the Queen will
give the Royal A&s;&s;ent thereto, and thus your
Excellency will &s;ee how much the <HI>Briti&s;h</HI> Nation
is concern'd at what has &s;o unfortunately befal|len
you, &s;ince it is therein expre&s;s'd at large, that
the &s;aid Outrage was the only Motive which in|duc'd
them to make &s;uch an Act; and further, I
cannot forbear acquainting your Excellency, that
for as much as the 2 <HI>Mu&s;covite</HI> Princes have lately
&s;ignified that this Bu&s;ine&s;s obliges them to pa&s;s
over into <HI>Holland;</HI> the Queen who has conferred
extraordinary Favours upon them, by Rea&s;on
of the Honour they had in being nearly related
to the <HI>Augu&s;t</HI> Hou&s;e of his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty, has
given them to under&s;tand, that they are at full
Liberty to &s;et out on their Voyage, when, and
in what manner they &s;hall Judge mo&s;t expedi|ent;
and that her Maje&s;ty will endeavour to
make their Departure as agreeable, as &s;he has
hitherto made their Re&s;idence in the&s;e Parts
ea&s;y, and delightful: I have often a&s;&s;ur'd your
Excellency of my particular Inclination to your
Service, that it were needle&s;s to add any thing
more, but a Repetition of the E&s;teem and Re|&s;pect
with which I have the Honour to be.&endq;</P>
<CLOSER>Your Excellencies, <HI>&amp;c.</HI>
<SIGNED>Sign'd
H. BOYLE</SIGNED></CLOSER>
</LETTER>
<P><PB N="284" REF="293">
BUT all this would not pacify the <HI>Ru&s;&s;ian</HI> Mini|&s;ter,
as may appear by the following Reply of
Mon&s;ieur <HI>Matteuoff.</HI></P>
<LETTER>
<OPENER><SALUTE>SIR,</SALUTE></OPENER>
<P>I Have defer'd 'till now, the returning an An&s;wer
to the Letter with which you honoured me, dated
29th of <HI>March, O. S.</HI> becau&s;e, my Lord, Duke of
<HI>Marlborough,</HI> and the Secretary of the Queen of
<HI>Great Britain,</HI> Mr. <HI>d' Ayroll,</HI> had &s;everal Times a&s;|&s;ur'd
me, they were ready to bring to pa&s;s the ju&s;t
Reparation, that his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty, my Ma&s;ter,
requires of the unheard of In&s;ult made upon me, and
the Satisfaction due to my Honour, and the great
Damages I have &s;u&s;tain'd; waited for the I&s;&s;ue
thereof, with &s;o much the greater Complacency, in
regard, that by your Letter, you confirm'd to me
the &s;ame A&s;&s;urance, of the &s;incere Intention, and
particular Care taken for that Purpo&s;e. But, for
as much, as the Letters from <HI>England,</HI> of the 17th.
In&s;tant, <HI>O. S.</HI> do not expre&s;s, that from the 11th,
which was the Beginning of the <HI>Term,</HI> to the &s;aid
13th Day any Progre&s;s has been made in the
Courts of Judicature, in order to obtain the Sen|tence
which ought to be pronounced again&s;t tho&s;e
Wret$bes, who a&s;&s;aulted me; nor even that the Af|fair
has been debated; it appears to me, that the
application of the Court, does not concur &s;o much
as the &s;incere friend&s;hip betwixt his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty
and the Queen of <HI>Great Britain</HI> requires, in order
to put an End to tho&s;e Delays, and Means of demur|ing
which have cau&s;ed the Bu&s;ine&s;s to be protracted,
for the Space of almo&s;t a whole Year: And there|fore,
<PB N="285" REF="294">
not &s;eeing at this very In&s;tant, any apparent
Effects of the fair Promi&s;es which have$been made
to me, and finding my &s;elf oblig'd to obey the Orders
I receiv'd from his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty; again, once
more to demand, whether it be the Queens Plea&s;ure, to
give Satisfaction proportionable to the Outragiou&s;ne&s;s
of the Affront, &s;uch as his Maje&s;ty, my Ma&s;ter, re|quires,
and to an&s;wer his Letter; I would al&s;o in|treat
you to &s;end me an an&s;wer in Writing, which I
impatiently expect, to the End that I may &s;end it to
the Court, conformable to my Orders. As to the no|tifying
the Act newly made, upon the Occa&s;ion of the
late A&s;&s;ault, upon my Per&s;on, for maintaining the
Privileges of Amba&s;&s;adors, of which Act Mr. <HI>d Ay|roll</HI>
afterwards deliver'd a Copy to me, by your Or|der,
I do my &s;elf the Honour to tell you, that it con|tributes
not, in any wi&s;e, to the Satisfaction now in
Debate; becau&s;e, the &s;acred Characters of Amba&s;&s;a|dors
have been in all Ages, accounted inviolable among
the <HI>Chri&s;tan</HI> Powers, before that Declaration; which
being but a particular Law, can only &s;erve to ju&s;tify
the Honour of the Nation, and prevent for the Fu|ture,
all Inconveniencies which may happen to foreign
Mini&s;ters in <HI>Great Britain,</HI> as well as to tho&s;e of
your Crown, in other Courts: 'Tis very much again&s;t
my will, that my Name is Celebrated in &s;uch a Man|ner
in your Con&s;titution, and that the Example is
tran&s;mitted to P$&s;terity; whereas, there being no|thing
Blame worthy in my Conduct, during my Re|i|dence
in <HI>London;</HI> I had Rea&s;on to hope, I &s;hould not
be thus expo&s;ed to the deadly Affront, put upon the
Character of an Amba&s;&s;ador, with which I am
inve&s;ted. For the re&s;t, being per&s;waded of your par|ticular
Friend&s;hip, and that you are de&s;irous to give
me farther Marks thereof, upon this Occa&s;ion, I
would have you to believe, that I am, as I formerly
<PB N="286" REF="295">
bad the Honour to be, with a mo&s;t profound E&s;teem,
and Affection,</P>
<CLOSER><SALUTE>SIR,</SALUTE> <HI>&amp;c.</HI>
<SIGNED>Sign'd,
De MATUEOFF.</SIGNED></CLOSER>
</LETTER>
<P>AFTER this Mr. <HI>Mat$ueoff</HI> &s;ent over a Letter
from the <HI>Czar</HI> him&s;elf, to her <HI>Britanick</HI> Maje&s;ty,
wherein he expre&s;s'd in very Warm, but re&s;pect|ful
Terms, his Re&s;entment of the Treatment of
his Amba&s;&s;ador, and that he expected &s;uch Repa|ration,
as was &s;uitable to the Indignity he had
received.</P>
<P>ALL the&s;e Writings to, and again, having
brought this Affair to no Conclu&s;ion, it was re|&s;olved
on both Sides, at la&s;t, that the Queen
&s;hould &s;end a &s;olemn Emba&s;&s;y to the <HI>Czar</HI> to his
Court at <HI>Mo&s;cow,</HI> to make an Acknowledgment
for the Affront, and to de&s;ire his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty
to be pacify'd, and to take this, for a Te&s;timony
of her Maje&s;ty's great De&s;ire to give him ample
Satisfaction upon that Occa&s;ion, and indeed, it
was a great Te&s;timony of it.</P>
<P>ACCORDINGLY, Mr. <HI>Whitworth</HI> was &s;ent by
her Maje&s;ty to <HI>Mo&s;cow,</HI> what he did, and how
this Matter was ended, in a manner very honou|rably
to his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty, may be &s;een at large,
by the following Account of his Reception at
<HI>Mo&s;cow,</HI> &amp;c.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2>
<PB N="287" REF="296">
<HEAD>A RELATION of what pa&s;t at Mo&s;cow,
on the 16th of February, N. S. 1710. the Day
his Maje&s;ty, Peter, Emperor of Great Ru&s;&s;ia,
admitted to publick Audience, his Excellency Mr.
Charles Whitworth, formerly Envoy Extraordi|nary
of her Maje&s;ty, Anne Queen of Great Bri|tain;
and &s;ince, ve&s;ted with the Character of her
Amba&s;&s;ador Extraordinary, Commi&s;&s;ioner and Ple|nepotentionary,
expre&s;ly and purpo&s;ely to make &s;o|lemn
Excu&s;es in her Name, for the in&s;ult done at
London, the fir&s;t of Augu&s;t, N. S. 1708. to his
Excellency, Mr. Andrew Artemonides de Ma|tueoff,
Mini&s;ter of State, Governor of the Dutchy
of Jaro&s;law, and at that Time, Amba&s;&s;ador Ex|traordinary
of his Czari&s;h Maje&s;ty, at the Court
of her Britannick Maje&s;ty. To which are added,
the Articles &s;tipulated in the Conference between
the Mini&s;ter of the Czar, and the &s;ame Amba&s;&s;a|dor
of the Queen.</HEAD>
<P>THE 8th of <HI>February,</HI> being appoint|ed
for the Solemnity, Mon&s;ieur <HI>Ba&s;ilis
de Salticof,</HI> Chief Carver to his <HI>Czar|i&s;h</HI>
Maje&s;ty, accompany'd by Mon|&s;ieur
<HI>Athana&s;ius de Dmitreemomonof,</HI>
Cup-Bearer, who officiated as Ma&s;ter of the Cere|monies,
went from the Court in one of his <HI>Czar|i&s;h</HI>
Maje&s;ty's Coaches, to the Hou&s;e of her <HI>Brita|nick</HI>
Maje&s;ty's Amba&s;&s;ador, being follow'd by
twenty other Coaches, of the Grandees, and
Principal Lords of the Court, &s;ome, only to
make up a Train for Show; and others, for
<PB N="288" REF="297">
the Amba&s;&s;ador's Secretary and Gentlemen, who
were all richly Cloath'd, an&s;werable to the
Coaches in which they Rode.</P>
<P>BEING come to the Amba&s;&s;adors Hou&s;e, the
Carver, and Cup-Bearer, went up to his Appart|ment,
where they declared to his Excellency, the
Bu&s;ine&s;s they were come about, and after &s;ome
Moments Conver&s;ation, they went into the
Coach with the Amba&s;&s;ador, who took the Place
of Honour; the Chief Carver &s;at by his Side,
and the Cup Bearer again&s;t him; the Secretary,
and Centlemen of the Emba&s;&s;y, went in the
Coaches appointed for them, each according to
his Rank, and the Train being encrea&s;ed by the
Amba&s;&s;ador's Coaches, proceeded to the Court.</P>
<P>ARIVING there, the two Regiments of Guards
<HI>Preobrazenski</HI> and <HI>Semiona&s;ski,</HI> who were drawn
up within the Court, made the Salutes of Honour
to the Amba&s;&s;ador according to Cu&s;tom, and re|main'd
&s;tanding in Parade During the whole
Audience; making a very fine Shew, the Rich|ne&s;s
of their Cloaths, and the neatne&s;s of their
Arms and Accoutrements &s;etting off the comely
Men, of which tho&s;e Regiments are compos'd;
the Officers at their Head made the mo&s;t Splendid
Appearance that can be imagin'd; and the whole
Extent of the Court, as large as 'tis, could hard|ly
afford them Room enough.</P>
<P>Mon&s;ieur <HI>de Narichkin,</HI> Gentleman of the Bed-Chamber,
to his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty, received the
Amba&s;&s;ador at the Foot of the Stair-Ca&s;e, where
his Excellency came out of the Coach, and com|plimented
him; Prince <HI>George de Scherhaty,</HI> Coun|&s;ellor
of State perform'd the &s;ame Honours to him
at the Top of the Stair-Ca&s;e; and Mon&s;ieur <HI>de
Mu&s;&s;inpuchkin,</HI> Privy-Coun&s;ellor, complimented
<PB N="289" REF="298">
him in the Anti-Chamber, and the Amba&s;&s;ador
was conducted according to the Cerimonial, to the
Hall of Audience, where his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty was
&s;tanding, uncover'd, under a Canopy, leaning
again&s;t a Table, having an arm'd Chair behind
him, the Grandees, and Mini&s;ters of the Court,
with the Generals of his Armies &s;tanding on each
Hand of him.</P>
<P>AS &s;oon as the Amba&s;&s;ador came in Sight of
him, he made his fir&s;t Obei&s;ance, in the Middle
of the Hall, his &s;econd, and the third when he
had a&s;cended the E&s;trade on which his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI>
Maje&s;ty &s;tood; where &s;tanding, and with his Hat
off, his Excellency made a Speech in <HI>Engli&s;h,</HI> of
which the Secretary read aloud, a Tran&s;lation in
the <HI>German</HI> Tongue, &s;ign'd with the Amba&s;&s;ador's
Hand, to the End, the foreign Mini&s;ters, who
had been formally Invited to a&s;&s;i&s;t at this Solem|nity,
might under&s;tand the Contents of it; and
then one of his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty's Secretaries read
it out in the <HI>Ru&s;&s;ian</HI> Language, for the Information
of the Lords and Gentlemen of the Empire; the
Speech was as follows,</P>
<LETTER>
<OPENER>Mo&s;t High, and mo&s;t Powerful Emperor.</OPENER>
<P>&startq;'TIS not without a very &s;en&s;ible Grief,
that I am oblig'd to mention to your
Maje&s;ty, the Affront which was offer'd to your
Amba&s;&s;ador, in <HI>Great Britain;</HI> and I &s;hould be
much more concern'd at it, were I not furni&s;h'd
with expre&s;s Orders, and full Power, to de|clare,
with how great Diligence, her Maje|&s;ty,
the Queen of <HI>Great Britain,</HI> my mo&s;t gracious
Mi&s;tre&s;s, has endeavour'd to give &s;ufficient
Satisfaction for it, proportion'd, as well to her
<PB N="290" REF="299">
Equity, as to her Greatne&s;s of Soul; and &s;uch,
as may &s;erve, as an evident Mark of her con|&s;tant
Friend&s;hip, which &s;he has always had for
your Imperial Maje&s;ty, and which her Ma|je&s;ty,
is de&s;irous inviolably to continue to
you.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;THE fir&s;t Advice of that unfortunate Acci|dent,
was no &s;ooner brought to Court, but the
Guilty were made &s;en&s;ible of her Royal Indig|nation;
they were immediately arre&s;ted; they
were examin'd before the Queen, in her Coun|cil;
they were impri&s;on'd, and pro&s;ecuted with
the utmo&s;t Severity of our Laws: And tho'
the&s;e were found not to be exten&s;ive enough,
yet, they were declared infamous, by the Con|&s;ent
of the whole Nation, a&s;&s;embled in Parlia|ment,
who declar'd to the whole World, by a
publick Act, how much they abhor'd the Indig|nity
of the Fact, and took nece&s;&s;ary Precau|tions
to prevent the like In&s;olencies for the
Future. Neither did they &s;top there, for tho&s;e
Criminals, were afterwards declared unworthy
any Favour or Protection, and excluded from
the General Pardon, which her Maje&s;ty, the
Queen, cau&s;ed to be publi&s;h'd, for all her
Subjects; even, for tho&s;e, who had in a mo&s;t
inormous manner, attempted again&s;t her &s;acred
Person; and tho' other Criminals do actually
Enjoy that Benefit, tho&s;e are &s;till under her
Maje&s;ty's high Di&s;plea&s;ure.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;AND to the End, that her Royal Equity
and Amity may reach farther, and become the
more &s;hining in the World, her Maje&s;ty, has
graciou&s;ly been pleas'd to honour me with
the Charracter of her Amba&s;&s;ador Extraordina|ry,
Commi&s;&s;ary, and Plenipotentiary, and to
<PB N="291" REF="300">
give me the Power, to repre&s;ent her Royal Per|&s;on,
as if her &s;elf were here pre&s;ent, in the fir&s;t
Place to te&s;tify the Sorrow, and the ju&s;t and
high Abhorrence &s;he has for that ra&s;h Deed per|petrated
again&s;t a Publick Mini&s;ter, e&s;pecially,
again&s;t &s;uch a one as her Maje&s;ty the Queen, has
a mo&s;t particular E&s;teem for; and afterwards,
to beg Excu&s;e for the Defect, and In&s;ufficiency
of our ancient Con&s;titution, in the Ca&s;e of &s;o
extraordinary a Violation of the Law of Nati|ons;
for which, the Criminals &s;hould with
Ju&s;tice have been puni&s;hed with the utmo&s;t Ri|gour,
according to your Imperial Maje&s;ty's De|&s;ire:
And in the la&s;t place, to a&s;&s;ure your Ma|je&s;ty,
in the mo&s;t &s;incere manner, how much
her Maje&s;ty, the Queen, is inclin'd to maintain
the ancient Friend&s;hip, and good Core&s;pondence,
which for &s;o long a Time, have been between
the two Crowns: Of which your Imperial Ma|je&s;ty,
may plea&s;e to take further Notice, in this
her Letter, which is a Te&s;timony of the great
Affection, and high E&s;teem, her Maje&s;ty the
Queen, has for your Imperial Maje&s;ty.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;WHEREFORE, I mo&s;t in&s;tantly de&s;ire, in the
Name of her Maje&s;ty, the Queen, that your
Imperial Maje&s;ty, may vouch&s;afe to accept the
afore&s;aid Excu&s;e, with the u&s;ual fraternal Af|fection,
and not to impute either to her Maje|&s;ty,
the Queen, or the <HI>Briti&s;h</HI> Nation, and Action
of which, &s;ome di&s;orderly Per&s;ons are the Au|thors:
But that entirely putting the &s;ame in
Oblivion, your Imperial Maje&s;ty may again
generou&s;ly continue you high Affection to the
Queen, my Mi&s;tre&s;s, and her Subjects.&endq;</P>
<P><PB N="292" REF="301">
&startq;FOR my own part, I &s;hall e&s;teem my &s;elf
mo&s;t happy, if I may any way contribute to
&s;o great a Work, &s;o advantagious to both the
Crowns, and &s;o nece&s;&s;ary to the Pre&s;ent State
of <HI>Europe.</HI>&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;SEVERAL great Benefits and Marks of Fa|vour,
which I have already receiv'd, during the
Di&s;charge of my former Employment, of which,
I &s;hall ever retain a thankful Remembrance,
makes me hope for the &s;ame favourable Recep|tion,
during the Remainder of my Stay here,
in the Exerci&s;e of my new Commi&s;&s;ion, as
often as I &s;hall have the Honour to make any
new Propo&s;al to your Imperial Maje&s;ty's
Court, by Order of my mo&s;t gracious Queen.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;IN the Conclu&s;ion, I beg Leave to recommend
the <HI>Briti&s;h</HI> Subjects, who live in this Country,
to your Imperial Maje&s;ty's high Protection,
with Re&s;pect to the Free Trade, which their
Ance&s;tors began fir&s;t, by the way of <HI>Archangel,</HI>
with great Expence, and Lo&s;s of abundance of
Men.&endq;</P>
<CLOSER><SIGNED>Sign'd,
CHARLES WHITWORTH.</SIGNED></CLOSER>
</LETTER>
<P>AFTER the Speech was made, and two Tran|&s;lations
of it Read, his Excellency the Amba&s;&s;a|dor,
deliver'd to his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty, her Ma|je&s;ty's,
the Queen of <HI>Great Britain</HI>'s Letter, to
the Effect following.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2>
<PB N="293" REF="302">
<HEAD>(After the u&s;ual Titles on both Sides.)</HEAD>
<P>WE have already written to your Imperial Maje&s;ty,
to declare to you, the Grief we conceiv'd, for
the unhappy Affront which was offer'd to your Am|ba&s;&s;adour
before he left our Court: We have &s;ince re|ceiv'd
the Letter which your Imperial Maje&s;ty wrote
to us, and we can a&s;&s;ure your Imperial Maje&s;ty, that
we were touch'd with true Sorrow, when we &s;aw how
highly you re&s;ented the Violence which had been offer'd
to your Imperial Maje&s;ty's own Per&s;on, in the Cha|racter
of your Amba&s;&s;ador, and we were the more
griev'd on this Occa&s;ion, when we reflected on the in&s;uf|ficiency
of our Laws, to give as ample a Satisfaction as
we de&s;ire to make, as well for the ju&s;t Sen&s;e, We our
Self had, of the Indignity which had been offer'd, as
to Convince your Imperial Maje&s;ty, how much we were
Inclin'd to make a &s;uitable Reparation, for the Inju|ry
done &s;o good a Friend and Ally; but we mu&s;t con|fe&s;s,
that at the &s;ame Time, we had a &s;ingular Plea&s;ure,
in ob&s;erving your Imperial Maje&s;ty's de&s;ire, to pre|vent
the Mi&s;under&s;tanding that might ari&s;e there|from;
and the great E&s;teem you &s;hew'd for our
Friend&s;hip; as well as the Care you Expre&s;s'd, to pre|&s;erve
and cultivate it by Reciprocal marks of Friend|&s;hip
and Affection.</P>
<P>Wherefore, we promi&s;e our &s;elf, from your Good|ne&s;s,
that upon the Repre&s;entations, which, from
Time to Time have been made to you, in our Name,
by our Envoy Extraordinary, at your Imperial Court,
your Imperial Maje&s;ty will be plea&s;ed, to examine in|to
the Nature of this Affair; where your Imperial
Maje&s;ty, will not &s;ee the lea&s;t Inclination, to favour
the Criminals, nor to &s;creen them from Justice.
But that there are in&s;uperable Difficulties, with Re|&s;pect
<PB N="294" REF="303">
to the ancient and fundamental Laws of the
Government of our People; which we fear, do not
permit &s;o &s;evere and rigorous a Sentence to be given,
as your Imperial Maje&s;ty, at fir&s;t, &s;eem'd to expect&punc;
in this Ca&s;e; and we per&s;wade our &s;elf, that your
Imperial Maje&s;ty, who are a Prince Equally famous
for Clemency, aud exact Ju&s;tice, will not require us,
who are the Gaurdian and Protectre&s;s of the Laws,
to inflict a Puni&s;hment upon our Subjects, which the
Laws do not impower us to do.</P>
<P>Neverthele&s;s, we have not been wanting, at the
&s;ame Time, to u&s;e all the Means, which we judg'd
mo&s;t effectual, to per&s;wade your Maje&s;ty, and the
whole World, of the Sincerity of our Intentions, and
of our Endeavours in this Affair; and to the End
the guilty might be Puni&s;h'd, &s;o far, as the Laws and
Con&s;titutions of our Kingdoms, which were then in
Force, would permit; we gave expre&s;s, and re|peated
Orders to our Officers of Ju&s;tice, and to
our Mini&s;ters, to pro&s;ecute them with the uttermo&s;t
&s;everity.</P>
<P>That Pro&s;ecution has been long continu'd with ve|ry
great Diligence, and nothing has been omitted, to
bring it to as &s;peedy a Conclu&s;ion as po&s;&s;ible: But
after all&punc; the Matter is &s;uch, that we find our &s;elf
oblig'd, to inform your Imperial Maje&s;ty, that as
well, becau&s;e of the different Pleadings, in Favour
of the Criminals, the &s;low, but indi&s;per&s;able Manner
of proceeding in a Law Suit of &s;o great Importance;
as of the Ca&s;e it &s;elf, which is of an extraordinary
Nature, again&s;t which, no &s;ufficient Provi&s;ion is
made; in the ancient Statutes of the&s;e Kingdoms: It
has not been in the Power of our Council Learned in
the Law yet to obtain a Sentence, nor a final Deci&s;&s;ion
in this Affair.</P>
<P><PB N="295" REF="304">
Wherefore, con&s;idering all the&s;e Inconveniencies,
and fore&s;eeing the Delays which might probably hap|pen,
in the ordinary Cour&s;e of Law, and de&s;iring,
at the &s;ame Time, to give you &s;ignal Marks of our
Sorrow; as al&s;o to &s;hew you the Indignation of all
our Subjects on this Occa&s;ion, we have pa&s;s'd an Act
of Parliament made in the mo&s;t &s;olemn manner, by
the Council, and A&s;&s;embly of our Kingdom of <HI>Great
Britain,</HI> wherein is made a Declaration as Authen|tick
as po&s;&s;ible, of the ju&s;t Horror which our Sub|jects
in general have again&s;t this violent In&s;ult, and
all the Acts and Proceedings which relate to the Ar|re&s;t
of the Per&s;on of your imperial Maje&s;ty's Amba&s;|&s;adour,
are annul'd, and raz'd out of the Regi&s;ters of
our Courts of Ju&s;tice; and tho&s;e who had a Share
therein,
are branded as infamous Criminals, and ob|noctious
to the Laws, which were then in Force; and
if any Per&s;on hereafter, dur&s;t commit the like Offence,
or any ways violate the Privileges of Amba&s;&s;adors
and other foreign Mini&s;ters, they will be lyable to
the mo&s;t &s;evere Penalties and Puni&s;hments, which the
arbitrary Power of the Judges, &s;hall think fit to inflict
upon them, and to which no bounds are given, in this
new Act; &s;o that all In&s;ults of this Nature, will be
prevented for the Future, and the Security, which
all Prince's Mini&s;ters ought to enjoy, will be firmly
e&s;tabli&s;h'd and pre&s;erv'd by this famous Law; And
this will remain as a Monument to all Po&s;terity; as
a Defference, which has been &s;hewn to your Imperial
Maje&s;ty: And all the Mini&s;ters, which &s;hall come for
the Future, will be indebted for this extraordinary
Act for their Protection, to the particular Con&s;idera|tion
which we, and our People have had for your Im|perial
Maje&s;ty's Honour: Therefore, your Imperial
Maje&s;ty cannot but &s;ee, that we have u&s;ed our utmo&s;t
Endeavours in pro&s;ecuting the Criminals, and in
<PB N="296" REF="305">
causing them to be puni&s;hed, tho' not with the Suc|ce&s;s
we could have wi&s;hed; and &s;ince we have pro|cur'd
an Act to be made by the Repre&s;entative of all
our Subjects of <HI>Great Britain,</HI> as well for Repara|tion
of what has been done, as to prevent the like
In&s;olence &s;or the Future, we in&s;tantly pray your Impe|rial
Maje&s;ty, to accept of all that we have done on
our Side, as the mo&s;t we could do here, for your Sa|tisfaction;
whereby your Imperial Maje&s;ty will give us
the &s;tronge&s;t Proof that can be of your Affection
towards us, and you may be a&s;&s;ured that we &s;hall
not fail on our Side to do all that lies in our Power,
on all Occa&s;ions, to &s;hew you our Gratitude, by our
firm Friend&s;hip and E&s;teem.</P>
<P>And to the End, that nothing may be omitted,
which is in our Power, to do farther, by way of
&s;uitable Reparation, we thought fit to make Choice of
&s;ome worthy and able Per&s;on to declare to your Im|perial
Maje&s;ty, in the mo&s;t publick and &s;olemn Man|ner
the Indignation we conceiv'd at the Affront
offer'd, and our Concern that it is not in our Power
to cau&s;e the Criminals to be puni&s;h'd according to
their De&s;erts: And as our tru&s;ty and well beloved,
Mr. <HI>Charles Whitworth,</HI> has merited our Royal
Approbation, by his Ability and Experience in all
the Affairs which have been entru&s;ted with him, as
al&s;o, by his good Conduct at your Imperial Maje|sty's
Court, for &s;everal Tears pa&s;t; we have therefore
given him a &s;pecial Power and Commi&s;&s;ion, to repre|&s;ent
our Per&s;on, as our Amba&s;&s;adour Extraordinary
for this End, and de&s;ire you to give entire Credit to
all that he &s;hall &s;ay to you in our Royal Name,
as if we were Pre&s;ent, to do it in Per&s;on. We
will only add, as a Mark of our E&s;teem, for your
Amba&s;&s;adour him&s;elf, who &s;uffer'd this In&s;ult, that
as we were &s;en&s;ible of his Per&s;onal Virtues, and
<PB N="297" REF="306">
great Qualities, during his Re&s;idence at our Court;
&s;o we were more particularly concern'd, that &s;uch
an Injury &s;hould be offer'd to a Gentleman of &s;o
great Merit and Con&s;ideration; being, be&s;ides, the
Amba&s;&s;adour of &s;o great a Prince, and &s;o good an
Allie. And &s;o praying, that the Di&s;pencer of all
good Things, will vouch&s;afe to Power forth his
heavenly Benedictions, upon the Per&s;on and King|doms
of your Imperial Maje&s;ty, we recommend you
to his holy Protection.</P>
<CLOSER>Your Imperial Maje&s;ty's,
Mo&s;t Affectionate Si&s;ter,
<DATELINE>Given at our Palace,
at <HI>Wind&s;or,</HI> the
&mdash;Day of <DATE>Au|gu&s;t,
1709.</DATE></DATELINE>
<SIGNED>ANNE R.</SIGNED></CLOSER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2>
<P>HIS <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty, having receiv'd this Let|ter
from the Hands of the Amba&s;&s;ador, deliver'd
it to the Count <HI>de Galoffkin,</HI> great Chamberlain
of his Empire, and was pleas'd to make the fol|lowing
An&s;wer in his own Tongue.</P>
<P>&startq;IT was but requi&s;ite, that her Maje&s;ty, the
Queen, &s;hould have given us Satisfaction,
by puni&s;hing the Criminals, conformably to our
Demands, in the mo&s;t rigorous Manner, as is
the Cu&s;tom in &s;uch Ca&s;es through out the Uni|ver&s;e:
But &s;eeing her Maje&s;ty has ordered you
<PB N="298" REF="307">
to make Excu&s;es, in the Quality of her Am|ba&s;&s;ador
Extraordinary conferr'd upon you, ex|pre&s;ly
for this Purpo&s;e, and to remon&s;trate that
her Maje&s;ty could not inflict &s;uch a Puni&s;h|ment
upon them, becau&s;e of the Defect in that
Particular, of the former e&s;tabli&s;h'd Con&s;titu|tions
of her Kingdom, and that with the una|nimous
Con&s;ent of the Parliament, her Maje|&s;ty
has cau&s;ed a New Act to be pa&s;&s;ed, to &s;erve
as a Law therein for the Future, we accept
all this, for a Proof of the Affection, her Ma|je&s;ty
has for us, and for &s;ufficient Satisfaction;
and we will give Orders to our Mini&s;ters, to
&s;ettle entirely this Affair with you in a Con|ference.&endq;</P>
<P>HIS <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty having conluded his An|&s;wer,
his Excellency, the Amba&s;&s;ador, retired
backwards out of the Hall, making three Obei|&s;ances,
in the &s;ame Manner as when he came in,
and was conducted back to his Hou&s;e, with the
&s;ame Ceremony, and with the &s;ame Train, ac|company'd
by the Carver and the Cup-Bearer,
the Fir&s;t of which, treated him three Days &s;uc|ce&s;&s;ively,
by expre&s;s Orders of his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje|&s;ty,
with the greate&s;t Plenty, Delicacy, and Mag|nificence,
the Officers of his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty's
Hou&s;hold &s;erving at the Table.</P>
<P>ON the 9th. <HI>O. S.</HI> The Amba&s;&s;ador came to
the Hou&s;e of his Excellency, the Count <HI>de Goloff|kin,</HI>
Great Chamberlain of the Empire, and
there had a Conference with him, and other Mi|nisters
of his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty, in which this trou|ble&s;ome
Affair was terminated, to the mutual Sa|tisfaction
of the two Powers, the Differences
which had been occa&s;ion'd by &s;o ill an Accident,
<PB N="299" REF="308">
were Compos'd, and the ancient Friend&s;hip, and
good Corre&s;pondence between the two Crowns
renew'd, on the Condition, that the following
Articles, which were &s;tipulated, &s;hould be per|form'd;
the Amba&s;&s;ador of her <HI>Britanick Maje&s;ty,</HI>
Engaging to procure the Execution of the la&s;t
but one.</P>
<P>THAT his Czari&s;h Maje&s;ty Emperor of <HI>Great
Ru&s;&s;ia,</HI> will &s;end Orders to Mon&s;ieur <HI>de Ma|tueoff</HI>
his Amba&s;&s;ador, and Plenipotentiary, at the
<HI>Hague;</HI> to notify, provi&s;ionally, by a Letter to her
Maje&s;ty, the Queen of <HI>Great Britain,</HI> that Mr.
<HI>Charles Whitworth,</HI> being ve&s;ted with the Cha|racter,
of her Amba&s;&s;ador Extraordinary, and Pleni|potentiary,
expre&s;ly, and purpo&s;ely to make Excu&s;es,
on occa&s;ion of the Affront, in Que&s;tion has perform'd
that Commi&s;&s;ion; and that his Maje&s;ty, having re|gard
to the In&s;tances of her Maje&s;ty, the Queen,
has been plea&s;ed to accept the &s;aid Excu&s;es, made in
her Name, for Satisfaction of the outrage done at
<HI>London,</HI> to the Amba&s;&s;ador of his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje|&s;ty;
with an Intention, thereby to &s;hew, the high
Value he puts upon the Friend&s;hip of her <HI>Britanick</HI>
Maje&s;ty, and on the Continuance of that Friend&s;hip,
and in Hope of the like Return on her Part, in
Occa&s;ions wherein his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty may be con|cern'd:
And that in Con&s;equence hereof, his <HI>Czar|i&s;h</HI>
Maje&s;ty is willing to forgive the criminal Pro|ceedings
of the Authors and Accomplicies of the &s;aid
Affront; and de&s;ires her Maje&s;ty, the Queen, to be
plea&s;ed to order them to be di&s;charg'd from the Pro|ce&s;s
i&s;&s;ued again&s;t them, and from the Sentence pro|nounced,
and the Penalties to which they were con|demned
for to the &s;aid In&s;ult.</P>
<P><PB N="300" REF="309">
His <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty having a ju&s;t regard, to the
faithful and &s;ignal Services which his &s;aid Amba&s;|&s;ador,
who was in&s;ulted, has perform'd; and in
a gracious Remembrance of the laudable Zeal of his
decea&s;ed Father, his Excellency, Mon&s;ieur <HI>Artemon
Sergiewicz de Matueoff,</HI> fir&s;t Mini&s;ter and Boyar
in the Reign of his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty's Father, and
Grand-father of glorious Memory, who in exhorting
Rebels to their Obedience, Crowned his faithful and
important Services with his Blood, &s;hed by Mutiniers:
He cannot but (in token of his good Will towards
him) after his own Satisfaction, regard the particu|lar
Satisfaction of his Mini&s;ter, namely, the Repa|ration
of his Honour, and that of his Family by the
Expedient of a Letter from her Maje&s;ty, the Queen,
and the Reimbur&s;ement of all the Co&s;ts and Dama|ges
which he has been obliged to be at, and to &s;uf|fer
on Account of the &s;aid Affront.</P>
<P>His <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty, will give Orders to his
&s;aid Amba&s;&s;ador, to demand his Letter of Re-cre|dence,
which he refu&s;ed to accept when he left <HI>Lon|don,</HI>
as well as the u&s;ual Pre&s;ent, and the Yatch
which her Maje&s;ty cau&s;ed to be offer'd to him; and
this, becau&s;e of the afore&s;aid Affront.</P>
<P>All that is above &s;pecify'd, being Executed, his
<HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty will acquaint her Maje&s;ty, the
Queen, that he is content with the afore&s;aid Satis|faction,
by a Letter, which &s;hall be deliver'd to the
Ambassador, Mr. <HI>Whitworth.</HI></P>
<P>THUS ended this Affair, in which, &s;ome Peo|ple
thought the Queen &s;toop'd to low to the
<HI>Czar;</HI> as if the <HI>Czar</HI> had not been a Prince of
&s;uch Fame and Power, as merited &s;o much Con&s;i|deration;
but the Queen and her Council knew
better what Figure the <HI>Czar</HI> made in the World,
<PB N="301" REF="310">
and of what U&s;e the Commerce of <HI>Great Britain</HI>
to the <HI>Ru&s;&s;ian</HI> Dominions was of; and be&s;ides this,
her Maje&s;ty very well knew, al&s;o, that Ju&s;tice
requir'd it, as &s;he would expect her Mini&s;ters
abroad &s;hould be well u&s;ed, by the Princes and
Powers, her Neighbours; and as &s;he expected o|ther
Princes and Nations &s;hould act by her, if
her Mini&s;ters receiv'd any Affront from the Rables
and Clamours of the People.</P>
<P>WE are now to return to the Affair of the
<HI>Turks,</HI> the <HI>Czar</HI> was really, very loath to fall out
with the <HI>Turks.</HI> But, as he found his Enemy,
the King of <HI>Sweden,</HI> and the Palatine of <HI>Kiow,</HI>
had the A&s;cendant there, and would kindle a
Flame whether he would or no, he made the ne|ce&s;&s;ary
Preparations for his own Defence.</P>
<P>HOWEVER, heat the &s;ame time wrote Letters,
and &s;ent Amba&s;&s;adors to the Grand Seignior, if
po&s;&s;ible, to prevent a Rupture, and publi&s;h'd
&s;everal Declarations, offering to refer any Differ|ences
that might happen between the Grand
Seignior and him&s;elf, to the Arbitration of other
Princes; and the <HI>Turks</HI> at the &s;ame Time, &s;end|ing
an Aga, as a Mini&s;ter to <HI>Vienna,</HI> to prevent the
Emperor taking Umbrage at his Breach with the
<HI>Czar,</HI> His <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty tran&s;mitted one of his
Declarations to <HI>Vienna,</HI> that it might be commu|nicated
to the &s;aid <HI>Turki&s;h</HI> Mini&s;ter, upon his Ar|rival
there; this Declaration &s;hewing a Readi|ne&s;s
in the <HI>Czar,</HI> to pre&s;erve the Publick Peace;
is of very great Con&s;equence in this Ca&s;e, to
clear the Character of the <HI>Czar,</HI> from the Scan|dal
of Breach of Treaty, which was pretended
to be charg'd upon him, the <HI>Turks</HI> being manife&s;t|ly
the Aggre&s;&s;ors.</P>
<P><PB N="302" REF="311">
WHEREAS, we have receiv'd certain Informa|tion,
from divers Places, that the <HI>Ottoman</HI> Port
endeavours to ju&s;tify the Violation of Peace, by a War;
already declared again&s;t us, and actually begun, by
the Irruption of the <HI>Tartars</HI> into our Territories:
And for that Purpo&s;e, charge us with &s;everal ground|less
Matters, by which, they pretend they were forc'd
to come to a Rup$ure; and among&s;t others, as if we
were not inclin'd to continue in Peace with them, but
had actually re&s;olved to begin a War: As al&s;o, that
contrary to the Peace concluded with the <HI>Otto|man's</HI>
we had erected&s; &s;everal new Fortifications, on
our Frontiers; &s;uffer'd our Troops to Enter the
<HI>Turki&s;h</HI> Dominions; and that we would not give
them Leave to Convoy the King of <HI>Sweden</HI> in
Safety, back to his own Territories. We have
thought it nece&s;&s;ary to declare here openly, that
we never had the leaft Intention, to break in any
Manner what&s;oever, the Peace concluded between us
and the <HI>Ottoman</HI> Port, and to enter into a War
with the <HI>Turks;</HI> but the &s;ame has been hitherto,
religiou&s;ly, and inviolably ob&s;erved by us; the For|tifications
erected by us, are likewi&s;e, in no Re&s;pect,
again&s;t the Treaty, but upon our own Territories;
which partly belong'd to us of Old, and partly was
yielded to us by the Treaty, and the Limits marked
out by the Commi&s;&s;aries on both Sides, which have
been fixed many Years ago: And it is therefore to be
wonder'd, that the <HI>Port</HI> would take Occa&s;ion to com|plain
thereof, at this Juncture; our Troops never
enter'd on the <HI>Turki&s;h</HI> Dominions, but remain'd only
upon the Frontiers; and altho', they did &s;ome Time
ago&punc; according to the Laws of War, pur&s;ue their Enemy
into the <HI>Turki&s;h</HI> Territories, and &s;eized them there|in;
which, however, was done in &s;uch Places, where
<PB N="303" REF="312">
there were, no Inhabitants; yet all this as well as
other Matters, were fully &s;etled and adju&s;ted, in the
Confirmation of Peace, renew'd la&s;t Year; whereby
the <HI>Port</HI> did likewi&s;e &s;tipulate with our Amba&s;&s;a|dor,
that they &s;hould Convoy the King of <HI>Sweden,</HI>
with 500 <HI>Turks,</HI> thro' <HI>Poland,</HI> and that we &s;hould
Guard him by our Officers from the Frontiers; to
which, we not only con&s;ented, but al&s;o, promi&s;ed to
procure the like Con&s;ent, from the King and Repub|lick
of <HI>Poland:</HI> But this being not accepted by the
<HI>Port,</HI> on the Account of &s;everal Pretences, we did
at la&s;t, in two of our Letters to the Sultan, and
by our Amba&s;&s;ador, and Privy-Councellor <HI>Tol&s;hoy,</HI>
at <HI>Con&s;tantinople,</HI> declare that we would &s;uffer
the King of <HI>Sweden</HI> to pa&s;s through <HI>Poland</HI> free,
and unmole&s;ted, into his own Dominions; and to
that End, permit him a Guard of 5000 <HI>Turks,</HI>
to &s;end him &s;afe thro' <HI>Poland;</HI> whereby our peace|able
Temper &s;ufficiently appears, and that on our
Part, we have contributed all, what might pre|vent
all manner of Di&s;turbance, and maintain
a good Corre&s;pondence, and Neighbourly Friend|&s;hip
with the <HI>Ottoman</HI> Port, and that all the
World may be &s;en&s;ible thereof, we confirm here,
with our former Declaration an Offer, before a
tedious War be commenc'd, to accommodate Matters
with the <HI>Port,</HI> and to live in a neighbourly Amity
with her, as formerly: And notwith&s;tanding, in
order to provide for our Precaution and Security;
(after we have been informed from all Parts, of a
Rupture, and that the War is actually declared
again&s;t us at <HI>Con&s;tantinople,</HI> and our Amba&s;&s;a|dor
carried Pri&s;oner to the <HI>Seven Towers</HI>), we
have cau&s;ed our Troops to march to the <HI>Turki&s;h</HI>
Frontiers: They &s;hall, however, not undertake any
Ho&s;tilities, provided the <HI>Turks</HI> live on their Part,
<PB N="304" REF="313">
peaceably; put a Stop to all Preparations of War,
and &s;et our Amba&s;&s;ador with all his Retinue, at
Liberty; and we will, as &s;oon as we are &s;ufficient|ly
a&s;&s;ured of the&s;e Things, by the <HI>Ottoman</HI> Port;
Order our Forces to with draw from the Frontiers,
and facilitate as much as in us lies, a friendly Ac|commodation:
So we willingly accept, and herewith
de&s;ire the Mediation of his Imperial Maje&s;ty, her
Maje&s;ty the Queen of <HI>Great Britain,</HI> and their High
Mightine&s;&s;es the States General. But in Ca&s;e the
<HI>Port,</HI> without any Occa&s;ion given her by us, &s;hould
per&s;i&s;t in her Re&s;olution to break the Peace with us,
and begin the War again&s;t us; we declare before God,
and all the World, that we are excu&s;able, and not
guilty of all the Blood that may be &s;pilt on this Oc|ca&s;ion;
and we have an entire Confidence in God,
that he will a&s;&s;i&s;t our ju&s;t Cau&s;e, and pro&s;per our
Arms with Victory, again&s;t an Enemy who breaks
Treaties; and who but a Year ago, by &s;o many Oaths
and Promi&s;es, confirm'd, and renew'd the Peace with
us.</P>
<CLOSER><DATELINE>Mo&s;cow, <DATE>Feb. 28.
1711.</DATE></DATELINE>
<SIGNED>PETER.</SIGNED></CLOSER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2>
<P>AFTER this, the War being actually begun by
the <HI>Turks,</HI> his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty publi&s;hed another
Declaration, which was &s;ent to all the Mini&s;ters
of Chri&s;tian Powers at <HI>Con&s;tantinople,</HI> in order
to have them in&s;i&s;t as Occa&s;ion offer'd, with the
<HI>Turki&s;h</HI> Mini&s;ters, upon the Terms offer'd, there|in,
as follows.</P>
<P><PB N="305" REF="314">
&startq;TIMES have produced Revolutions, Peace
and War have alternately &s;ucceeded
in the World; and Mankind in every Age,
has been to&s;s'd with &s;trange Vici&s;&s;itudes: But
the pre&s;ent Profidiou&s;ne&s;s of the <HI>Ottomans,</HI>
is &s;uch, as Antiquity can &s;car&s;e Paralel, and
the modern Ages de&s;ervedly abhor.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;NO doubt, but the Common Report of this,
has reached mo&s;t Peoples Ears; Be it therefore,
manife&s;tly Known to all, how <HI>Achmet,</HI> the
now Reigning Sultan of the <HI>Turks,</HI> has impi|ou&s;ly,
frivolou&s;ly, and without the lea&s;t, ju&s;t
Occa&s;ion, violated, and broken the 30 Years
Peace, concluded between his &s;acred <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Ma|je&s;ty,
and his Predece&s;&s;or, Sultan <HI>Mu&s;tapha,</HI>
tho' renew'd by him&s;elf, this very la&s;t Year,
1710, and ratify'd by a &s;olemn Oath, in the
Pre&s;ence of the mo&s;t high God of Heaven;
which he afterwards confirm'd, as well in his
Letters which he writ to his &s;aid <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje|&s;ty,
as in the Deed of publick Renovation;
and yet, in the Month of <HI>November,</HI> the very
&s;ame Year, e're the Sun had compleated its
annual Cour&s;e, he declared War publickly, at
<HI>Con&s;tantinople;</HI> and contrary to the Law of
Nations, ca&s;t his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty's Amba&s;&s;ador,
and Privy-Councellor, Mon&s;ieur <HI>Tol&s;$oy,</HI> and
his whole Family, into the Pri&s;on called the
<HI>Edicul,</HI> after having fir&s;t affronted him in a
mo&s;t ignominious Manner, and &s;eized upon
his Goods.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;IT is true, he has not herein degenerated
from his Fore-fathers; for being born an
Enemy to the Name of CHRIST, he never Ar|ticles
with an Intention to ob&s;erve the &s;acred
<PB N="306" REF="315">
Laws of Peace; but as a Man void of all
Honour, does it only, that he may after|wards,
with greater Security, attack, and ut|terly
overwhelm tho&s;e that rely upon the
religious Sanctions of publick Treaties.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;The Hi&s;torians of former Ages, and e&s;peci|ally
that mo&s;t excellent Patriarch of <HI>Jeru&s;alem,</HI>
St. <HI>Nectaris</HI> te&s;tifies, that the <HI>Ottomans,</HI> from
their very Beginnings, made it their chief
Study, to watch Quarrels and Di&s;agreements,
that at any Time happen'd between any <HI>Chri|&s;tian</HI>
Princes, and States; and that as often as
they found Occa&s;ion, they never &s;tuck at any
Stipulations of Peace, or &s;olemn Oaths; and
that thus, the Offspring of Thieves and Rob|bers,
did in a few Years, &s;ubdue to their own
Dominions, &s;o many ancient and renowned
<HI>Chri&s;tian</HI> Kingdoms and Provinces, together
with a great many holy and venerable Places;
and at la&s;t became the mo&s;t powerful, and
formidable People.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;THE poor oppre&s;s'd <HI>Grecians, Valachians,
Bulgarians,</HI> and <HI>Servians,</HI> groan &s;till under
Yoke, and their Mi&s;ery &s;hews by woful
Experience, how little a Value do tho&s;e Bar|barians
&s;et upon publick Treaties. Nor has
the Kingdom of <HI>Hungary</HI> experienced le&s;s to
its great Detriment.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;THE <HI>Ru&s;&s;ian</HI> Monarchy, &s;till bears in Mind,
the De&s;truction with which it was threaten'd,
in the Year, 1677, when in the Reign of the
<HI>Czar, Theodore Alexowits,</HI> Emperor of all
<HI>Russia,</HI> of pious and glorious Memory; the per|fidious
<HI>Turk,</HI> being in Hopes that the le&s;&s;er
<HI>Russia,</HI> &s;hould become a Prey to his Ambition,
thro' the Treachery of <HI>Poro&s;zen,</HI> General of the
<PB N="307" REF="316">
<HI>Co&s;&s;acks,</HI> beyond the <HI>B$ri&s;thenes,</HI> broke the Peace,
and with a va&s;t and dreadful Army, invaded
the <HI>Ukrain,</HI> and tho' he had been already inform'd
that the &s;aid Traytor, had &s;ubmitted to
his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty's Mercy, and the <HI>Higirin,</HI>
the Place of his chief Re&s;idence, was actually
Garri&s;on'd, by his &s;aid Maje&s;ty's Forces: Yet
finding that the noble Firmne&s;s of the <HI>Ru&s;&s;ian</HI>
Troops, did hinder him from penetrating far|ther
into the <HI>Ukrain,</HI> he bent all the Fury,
which he de&s;ign'd to make the whole Province
feel, again&s;t the City, which he in Vain be|&s;ieg'd,
tho' but &s;lightly fortify'd, in&s;omuch,
that the <HI>Ru&s;&s;ians</HI> them&s;elves, would have aban|doned
and demoli&s;h'd it, but that the Exegency
of the War requir'd their keeping it for that
Time: So, that after a prodigious Lo&s;s of Men,
he was forc'd to retire to his own Teritories,
loaded with Shame and Ignominy, and to beg
Peace of his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty, which was con|cluded
in 1681.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;THE memorable Slaughter, made of the&s;e
Peace Breakers at <HI>Vienna</HI> in <HI>Au&s;tria,</HI> in 1683,
and the wonderful Progre&s;s of the <HI>Chri&s;tian</HI>
Arms afterwards, are &s;till fre&s;h in every Bo|dy's
Memory; nor is it needful to mention,
the In&s;olence, with which they then broke in,
to be&s;iege that Metropolis.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;IT is recorded in the Archieves of <HI>Chri&s;tan</HI>
Princes, the having &s;eriou&s;ly fore-&s;een the cun|ning
De&s;igns, which the <HI>Barbarians</HI> form'd, of
&s;wallowing up their &s;everal Dominions, one by
one; they enter'd into a holy and mutual
League: To wit, his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty, the Em|peror
of the <HI>Romans,</HI> the <HI>Roman</HI> Empire,
his <HI>Poli&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty, the Republick of <HI>Poland,</HI>
<PB N="308" REF="317">
and <HI>Venice,</HI> and the Pope of <HI>Rome;</HI> and their
<HI>Czarean</HI> Maje&s;ties, <HI>John Alexowitz,</HI> of pious
Memory, and <HI>Peter Alexowitz,</HI> who now happily
Reigns, being likewi&s;e invited, for the common
Safety of <HI>Chri&s;tianity;</HI> and induced both by the
continual Irruptions of the <HI>Turks</HI> and <HI>Tartars</HI>
into their Territories, and their Ho&s;tilities
and Incur&s;ions into the Dominions of other
<HI>Chri&s;tian</HI> Princes; join'd fir&s;t in a perpetual
Peace, and a perpetual League, offen&s;ive and
defen&s;ive, with his Royal Maje&s;ty the King of
<HI>Poland,</HI> in 1696; and the Following Year 1697,
in a triennial Alliance, with his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje|&s;ty,
the Emperor of the <HI>Romans,</HI> and the Re|publick
of <HI>Venice,</HI> mutually Engaging them|&s;elves,
to deliver the Kingdoms of <HI>Hungary,
Sclavonia, Dalmatia,</HI> and the <HI>Morea;</HI> together
with the Cities of <HI>Tanna,</HI> (commonly called <HI>A|zoph</HI>)
and <HI>Ca&s;ifurmen,</HI> from the Tyranny of the
Infidels: Nor could this De&s;ign well fail of the
wi&s;h'd Succe&s;s, if by continuing the War, a few
Years longer, as his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty would have
had it. The Enemy, who was already reduc'd
to great Straits; had been brought &s;o low, as
not to have it in their Power, but at the Peril
of their unavoidable Downfal, ever to annoy
the <HI>Chri&s;tian</HI> World any where again.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;BUT to our great Sorrow, the&s;e irreconcilea|ble
<HI>Barbarians,</HI> did at the Congre&s;s of <HI>Carlowitz,</HI>
partly by Per&s;wa&s;ions, and partly by Artifice,
induce the High Confederates to enter into a
Treaty with them; made Room for Intrigues,
&s;ow'd the Darnel of Di&s;cord, and withdrew
all the above-mention'd Potentates from his
<HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty's Alliance, and at la&s;t conclud|ed
a 25 Years Peace, exclu&s;ive of him; no
<PB N="309" REF="318">
other Remedy being left, Mon&s;ieur <HI>Worniori,</HI>
his &s;aid Maje&s;ty's Amba&s;&s;ador, but to adju&s;t a
Truce for two Years, on the 3d of <HI>July,</HI> 1700;
which was &s;oon followed, by 30 Years Peace,
concluded at <HI>Con&s;tantinople,</HI> between his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI>
Maje&s;ty, and the late Sultan <HI>Mu&s;tapha,</HI> by his
&s;aid Maje&s;ty's Envoys, Mon&s;ieurs <HI>Ucran&s;tow,</HI>
and <HI>Heredajow:</HI> But enough of Things done
&s;o long ago, let us come to Matters near
Hand, which require a more diligent Exami|nation.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;HIS <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty did &s;o religiou&s;ly ob|&s;erve
the Articles of this Treaty; and tho' be|fore
it was ratify'd, the Sultan of the <HI>Budziack
Tartars,</HI> did offer to &s;ubject him&s;elf, and his
People, to his mo&s;t powerful Scepter; the
Propo&s;al was rejected, becau&s;e nothing &s;hould
be done, that might have the lea&s;t Appearance
of Contravention; nor did the <HI>Turki&s;h</HI> Subject,
<HI>Kubjick Murza</HI> &s;ucceed better afterwards, when
he came to <HI>Azoph,</HI> with a con&s;iderable Body
of <HI>Cubak Tartars,</HI> to offer al&s;o Homage.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;AND his &s;aid Maje&s;ty being al&s;o&punc; re&s;olv'd, to
ob&s;erve the Peace, &s;till with more Exactne&s;s,
after it was ratify'd by his Amba&s;&s;ador Extra|ordinary,
and Plenipotentiary, Prince <HI>Deme|trius
Galickzin;</HI> he enjoyn'd all his Governors in
the Frontier Towns, the General of the <HI>Zaporavi|an
Tartars,</HI> who was one of his Subjects, and all
other Commanders of his Troops, as well Na|tives
as Foreigners, under mo&s;t &s;evere Penalties,
that they &s;hould not pre&s;ume to di&s;turb the
Peace, and good neighbourly Friend&s;hip, by
any Incur&s;ions, into the Teritories, either of
the <HI>Turks,</HI> or <HI>Tartars.&endq;</HI></P>
<P><PB N="310" REF="319">
&startq;AND his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty carry'd the punctu|al
Ob&s;ervation of the Articles of this Treaty,
to that Height; that whereas, &s;ome of the
<HI>Zaporavion Tartars,</HI> did in the Tear 1701, Rob
&s;ome <HI>Grecians,</HI> who were coming to the <HI>Ukrain</HI>
with Merchandize, and that the Sultan of the
<HI>Turks</HI> demanded the Damage to be made good; his
<HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty knowing, it was to no Purpo&s;e, to
expect any Reparation from the Robers, order'd
that the &s;aid <HI>Grecians</HI> &s;hould be indemnify'd out
of his own Trea&s;ury, and that 100000 Dollars
of an Ounce Weight, &s;hould be paid to them.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;ON the other Hand, notwith&s;tanding this,
Peace was confirm'd by both the Sultans own
Letters, and his &s;olemn Oath, the <HI>Turks</HI> and
<HI>Tartars</HI> did continually, and by all manner of
Ways, injure his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty's Subjects, kil|ling
line &s;ome, carrying others into Captivity; and
taking away their Hor&s;es, and other Cattle; as
the following In&s;tanoes, faithfully extracted out
of the Regi&s;ters, do clearly mark out, as well
the Crime, as the Time when it was Committed.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;IN the Neighbourhood of <HI>Azoph,</HI> upon the
Sea Coa&s;t, near the Towns of the <HI>Co&s;&s;acks,&endq;</HI>
