<P><PB N="311" REF="320">
&startq;HIS <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty's Amba&s;&s;ador at <HI>Con&s;tan|tinople,</HI>
made his Complaint of the&s;e Outrages;
but to no purpo&s;e: For neither were the Da|mages
made good, nor any Stop put to tho&s;e
Depredations; tho' on his Maje&s;ty's Side,
the <HI>Turks</HI> receiv'd Satisfaction, even to their mo&s;t
frivolous pretentions.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;WHO would have doubted, but that after the
above-mention'd In&s;tances of his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje|&s;ty's
true Friend&s;hip, in rejecting &s;o many Ho|mages
offer'd him, he &s;hould at lea&s;t have met
with a &s;uitable Return on the like Occa&s;ion;
but it was quite otherwi&s;e.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;THE <HI>Turks</HI> in the Year 1708, did not only
give Shelter and A&s;&s;i&s;tance to the fugitive Re|bel
<HI>Co&s;&s;acks, Neara&s;&s;aw,</HI> and his Adherents;
but permitted the <HI>Tartars</HI> to join with them,
and make Inroads into his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty Ter|ritories.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;NOR did they act with more Candor, in the
Year 1709, in <HI>Reference,</HI> to the Remains of
the <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> Forces, after the glorious and me|morable
Battle of <HI>Pultoua:</HI> For the King him|&s;elf,
with as many of the Officers, and Soldiers
of his routed Army, as did e&s;cape the Conque|ror's
Sword, and his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty's Be|trayor
the ba&s;e <HI>Mazeppa,</HI> with his Adherents,
retiring into the <HI>Turki&s;h</HI> Dominions, where pro|tected
there: And tho' by the Law of Nations,
and War, his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty's Troops might
have pur&s;ued them, yet they receiv'd Orders
by no Means to approach <HI>Oczacow,</HI> where
the Enemy and the afore&s;aid Rebels were, but
on the Contrary, to come back again to their
own Territories. And whereas his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Ma|je&s;ty
did fir&s;t by his Amba&s;&s;ador, and after|wards,
<PB N="312" REF="321">
by three different Letters, which he
writ to the Sultan, demanded that he would
not protect his Enemy; but that without far|ther
Delay, he would make him depart his
Dominions, and deliver up the Rebels: Neither
was he comply'd with, nor any An&s;wer return'd
to his Letters in a great while: But rather
Leave granted to the Enemy, and the Rebels
to invade his Maje&s;ty's Dominions; which they
did in conjunction with the <HI>Valachians</HI> and <HI>Tar|tars,</HI>
&s;urprizing in the Night-time, the Town
of <HI>Jaharhick,</HI> and carrying away the Com|mander,
with whatever belong'd to him.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;AFTERWARDS, in the Year 1710, they car|ry'd
off all the Inhabitants of <HI>Jargowitz</HI> and
<HI>Nemback,</HI> with all their Sub&s;tance; kill'd a
Captain and &s;everal Soldiers, of <HI>Uman Co&s;&s;acks;</HI>
carry'd away another, with 150 private Centi|nals;
they plundered a great Company of Car|riers,
that were coming with Salt from <HI>Mo|lo$naw,</HI>
carrying away mo&s;t of the Men, and
all the Hor&s;es; they al&s;o robb'd the Waggons
de&s;ign'd for carrying the Baggage of the Army,
at a Place call'd <HI>Cammen Laton,</HI> carrying off
mo&s;t of the Waggons, and all the Bea&s;ts of
Carriage, and plunder'd the Town of <HI>Comen&s;ea,</HI>
in the Di&s;trict of <HI>Czigirin.</HI>&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;NO Redre&s;s was ever made for any of the&s;e
Damages, nor any &s;atisfactory An&s;wer given,
to the many Complaints made of &s;uch ho&s;tile
Inva&s;ions, but the Matter &s;till put off, with
frivolous Excu&s;es.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;THE <HI>Ottomans</HI> at la&s;t, being re&s;olv'd to carry
their wicked De&s;igns, under the Ma&s;que of
Peace, their chief Mini&s;ter, the Vi&s;ier <HI>Ali Ba&s;ha,</HI>
propo&s;ed to his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty's Amba&s;&s;ador,
<PB N="313" REF="322">
that if his Maje&s;ty would con&s;ent, to confirm
the thirty Years Peace concluded between him
and the pre&s;ent Sultan's Brother, and give his
po&s;itive Word, that he was firmly re&s;olv'd, to
ob&s;erve it; he promi&s;ed, that the Sultan then
would not only ratify it, but that al&s;o, the
King of <HI>Sweden</HI>'s departure out of his Domini|ons
&s;hould be agreed upon.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;HEREUPON, his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty was plea&s;ed
to &s;end full Powers to his Amba&s;&s;ador for that
Purpo&s;e, and writ to the Sultan him&s;elf about
it; upon which the Sultan of the <HI>Turks,</HI> did &s;o|lemnly
confirm the Peace with his Maje&s;ty,
in <HI>December</HI> 1709, and bound him&s;elf by Oath,
calling the great God of Heaven, to witne&s;s,
(as &s;hall appear by the Copy hereto annexed)
that he would Religiou&s;ly ob&s;erve the Laws of
it, and the Ratifications were afterwards mutu|ally
exchang'd.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;AS to what concerns the King of <HI>Sweden,</HI> it
was agreed with the chief Mini&s;ter <HI>Ali Ba&s;ha,</HI>
1. 500 <HI>Turks</HI> &s;hould be permitted to accompa|ny
him thro' <HI>Poland</HI> into his own Country; and
that for his greater Security, from being in&s;ult|ed
by any of his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty's Troops, one
of his Maje&s;ty's Officers, and &s;ome of the <HI>Ru&s;|&s;ian</HI>
Garri&s;ons would receive him upon the Fron|tiers,
and conduct him &s;afe thither, but that in
Reference to the Rebel <HI>Co&s;&s;acks,</HI> they &s;hould be
all expell'd the <HI>Turki&s;h</HI> Dominions.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;HIS <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty gave Con&s;ent to this
Agreement, and order'd Letters to be writ
thereupon to his Amba&s;&s;ador; But the <HI>Turk,</HI>
far from putting the Articles thereof in Execu|tion,
did neither di&s;mi&s;s the King of <HI>Sweden,</HI>
nor expel the Rebels; But rather gave way to
<PB N="314" REF="323">
&s;everal ill De&s;igns, which were carrying on
again&s;t his <HI>Cari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;UPON Notice of the&s;e Artifices, his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI>
Maje&s;ty re&s;olv'd to write a Letter to the Sul|tan,
(the Copy of which is hereunto annex'd,
and mark'd with an A); wherein he was plea&s;ed
to declare to him, that he con&s;ented that the
Number of the <HI>Turks</HI> de&s;ign'd to accompany
the King of <HI>Sweden,</HI> &s;hould be augmented to
3000; &s;ending Orders at the &s;ame Time, to
his Amba&s;&s;ador, that they &s;hould be made up
5000.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;BUT it was to no Purpo&s;e to expect any
An&s;wer to this point: On the contrary, the
Report began ro encrea&s;e, that the <HI>Turks</HI> began
to incline their Thoughts to War.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;WHEREUPON his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty order'd a
&s;econd Letter to be written to the Sultan, on
the 18th&mdash;29th of <HI>October</HI> 1710, (as appears
by the Copy hereunto annex'd, and mark'd B)
and di&s;patch'd an Envoy Extraordinary on pur|pose
with it. But in &s;tead of an An&s;wer, Word
was brought to him, that-his Envoy, contrary
to the Law of Nations, was &s;eiz'd and put
into a Dungeon, where he Lies to this very
Day.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;Couriers at length began to arrive from all
Parts, with Advice, that the Sultan at the In|&s;tigation
of the Han of <HI>Tartary,</HI> had actuallay
declar'd War at <HI>Con&s;tantinople</HI> again&s;t his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI>
Maje&s;ty, without any Con&s;cience, and only
with a bear Pretence, that his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty
had given &s;ome Motives thereunto, as forced
him to break the Peace; which is but a ridicu|lous
&s;aying; for tho&s;e very Motives pretended,
were all decided by the la&s;t Peace. They
<PB N="315" REF="324">
further brought Word that his Maje&s;ty's Amba&s;|&s;ador,
after &s;everal ba&s;e Affronts put upon
him, was impri&s;on'd; the warlike Preparations
were making throughout the whole <HI>Turki&s;h</HI>
Empire; the Troops were drawing together
about <HI>Bender,</HI> and the Expedition was notify'd
to all the <HI>Yurki&s;h</HI> Generals (commonly call'd
<HI>Ba&s;has</HI>) with Orders to rai&s;e Soldiers.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;THESE Proceedings were more than enough,
to expo&s;e the perfidiou&s;ne&s;s of the Sultan; how|ever,
his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty, to convince the whole
World, that the Breach of the Peace, and the
Effu&s;ion of Humain Blood, which of Nece&s;&s;ity
mu&s;t follow, ought not to be laid to his Charge,
but to the Sultans; did after all, tho' to little
Purpo&s;e, order another Letter to be writ to him
in his Name, dated at <HI>Petersburg,</HI> the 6th, 17th,
of <HI>January</HI> la&s;t, of the &s;ame Tenure with the
Copy (here unto al&s;o annex'd, and mark'd with
C. (<HI>viz.</HI>) that if the &s;aid Sultan did not acquaint
him put of Hand with his po&s;itive Re&s;olutions,
of renewing, and &s;trictly ob&s;erving the Treaty
of Peace; he would look upon it as a real Breach
of it; nor would he &s;uffer him&s;elf to be amus'd,
or circumvented by any Craft; but would
(with God's a&s;&s;i&s;tance) begin Warlike Prepara|tions
with all Expedition, in order to oppo&s;e him
early both by Sea and Land.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;NOW let the hone&s;t and impartial Part of
the World examine the &s;everal Heads of the
<HI>Turki&s;h</HI> Declaration of War, &s;o fal&s;ely and &s;o
awkardly patch'd together, and publi&s;h'd
every where, as al&s;o, the Crimes they charge
us with.&endq;</P>
<P><PB N="316" REF="325">
&startq;THE <HI>Ottomans</HI> give out, that they began this
War purely to a&s;&s;i&s;t the Rebel <HI>Lezein&s;ky,</HI> whom
they look upon to be the right King of <HI>Poland,</HI>
and to deliver the Republick from his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI>
Maje&s;ty's Troops, and that they do this at the
Reque&s;t of the &s;aid Republick, pre&s;cribed there|to
(<HI>viz.</HI>) the depriv'd Palatine of <HI>Kiow Polocky,</HI>
and <HI>Poniatow&s;ky,</HI> but who in every Fact, are Be|trayers
of their native Country; and likewi&s;e,
becau&s;e his &s;aid <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty had refu&s;ed at
the <HI>Turks</HI> Reque&s;t, to withdraw his Troops out
of the Kingdom, and to relinqui&s;h his Royal
Confederate <HI>Augu&s;tus</HI> the Second, King of <HI>Poland.</HI>&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;WHO is the Man will &s;ay, that this was a
Thing fit to be done; or that &s;uch a Demand
was ju&s;t; whereas the whole Republick of <HI>Po|land,</HI>
and the grand Dutchy of <HI>Lithuania,</HI> do own
his Royal Maje&s;ty <HI>Augu&s;tus</HI> the Second, for their
lawful King, and the &s;aid King and Kingdom,
continue in Alliance with his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty,
by Vertue of which, the &s;aid Troops are obli|ged
to continue in <HI>Poland,</HI> as Auxiliaries; and
that the King and Senate, are under a Nece&s;&s;i|ty
of keeping them there: For it is as clear as
the Sun at Noon, that their Common Enemy,
the King of <HI>Sweden,</HI> and the <HI>Poli&s;h</HI> Rebels are
protected by the Sultan, for no other End but
that through their Means, a bloody War might
be again kindled in the <HI>Ru&s;&s;ian</HI> and <HI>Poli&s;h</HI> Domi|nions:
Be&s;ides if his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty had with|drawn
his &s;aid Troops, the Con&s;equence would
be; that the <HI>Turks</HI> introducing the King of
<HI>Sweden</HI> into <HI>Poland</HI> on one Side, and <HI>Lezein&s;ky</HI>
entring on the other, after they had ravaged
the whole Kingdom at their Plea&s;ure, would
<PB N="317" REF="326">
unite their Forces, and fall upon his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI>
Maje&s;ty, and &s;o create wor&s;e Di&s;orders than
the former: This is the Rea&s;on why his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI>
Maje&s;ty refu&s;ed to comply with the <HI>Turki&s;h</HI>
Arrogance, or by relinquishing his Confedera|cy,
to expo&s;e <HI>Poland</HI> as a Pray to the <HI>Barba|rians.</HI>&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;WHY was not the King of <HI>Sweden</HI> all this
while di&s;mi&s;s'd out of <HI>Turkey,</HI> by &s;ome of the
ways propo&s;ed by his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty, either by
Sea or Land, or even with a &s;elect Guard, or
by &s;ome other better Way; laying a&s;ide all
tno&s;e far fetch'd, and Frivilous Pretences, which
are made use of; and then his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty
would immediately have withdrawn all his
Troops out of <HI>Poland,</HI> and out of the fortify'd
Towns of the Republick, which for their Com|mon
Security he is at Pre&s;ent oblig'd to Gar|ri&s;on,
until the Danger be over.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;THE <HI>Turks</HI> complain be&s;ides in their Declara|tion
of War, that his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty had built
&s;ome Forts, within the Boundaries of the <HI>Otto|man</HI>
Dominions; but this Pretence is manife&s;tly
fal&s;e: For his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty cau&s;ed no Forts
to be Built any where, but in tho&s;e Places that
were incorporated with his Empire, and expre&s;|ly
adjudg'd to belong to it, as well by the
Treaty of Peace, as by the Agreement ad|ju&s;ted
on a&s;&s;ertaining the Boundaries on the
Side of <HI>Tana,</HI> vulgarly call'd <HI>Azoph,</HI> between
Mon&s;ieur <HI>Tol&s;toy</HI> Governor of the &s;aid City;
and <HI>Ha&s;an</HI> Ba&s;ha, in 1704: And in the <HI>Ukrain,</HI>
between Mon&s;ieur <HI>Ukrain&s;tow,</HI> and <HI>Ka&s;i Me$e|met</HI>
Ba&s;ha, in the Year 1705.&endq;</P>
<P><PB N="318" REF="327">
&startq;AND as for what the <HI>Turks</HI> object, in the
&s;ame Declaration about his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty's
Troops breaking into their Territories, in pur|&s;uit
of the fugative <HI>Swedes,</HI> where they killed
&s;ome and en&s;lav'd others; the <HI>Mu&s;covites</HI> did
this according to the Manner and Cu&s;tom of
War; with which the <HI>Turks</HI> did not find Fault,
when the Thing was afterwards rightly ex|plain'd
to them; be&s;ides, that this Affair, was
entirely adjudg'd, and for ever to be hu&s;h'd by
the la&s;t renewing of the Peace.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;BUT as far as we dive into the true De&s;ign
of the <HI>Turks,</HI> it appears to be, fir&s;t, To force
by previous Aggre&s;&s;ions, his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty's
Troops, who by Virtue of the Alliance with
his Royal Maje&s;ty King <HI>Augu&s;tus,</HI> and the Re|publick
of <HI>Poland</HI> as is already mention'd, re|main
the Kingdom as Auxiliaries, to return out
of it. Next, to introduce the King of <HI>Sweden</HI>
thither; afterwards, to rai&s;e a Sedition; then
drive the afore&s;aid Lawful King again from
his Throne; and la&s;t of all to obtrude with
Fire and Sword, the Rebel <HI>Stani&s;laus Lezein&s;ky,</HI>
whom the King of <HI>Sweden</HI> did by Violence &s;et
up, and &s;o, not only Subject the Kingdom to
the barbarous Yoke of the <HI>Ottomans,</HI> by a
Free Tribute of three Millions of Gold Ducats
Yearly, to be paid by the Republick, but also,
the &s;everal Provinces being for ever di&s;mem|bred
from it, &s;hould together with the &s;trong
Fortre&s;s of <HI>Caminick,</HI> be yielded up to the In|fidels,
according to the Promi&s;es made by the
King of <HI>Sweden,</HI> and the late Palatine of <HI>Kiow
Po&s;toki,</HI> and <HI>Poniatow&s;$$</HI> in <HI>Lezeni&s;ky's</HI> Name;
be&s;ides, what by the Artifice of their Confede|rates,
what by means of the <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> Forces, and
<PB N="319" REF="328">
tho&s;e of <HI>Lezein&s;ky,</HI> now lurking in <HI>Pomerania,</HI>
they would rai&s;e a Storm in the <HI>Roman</HI> Empire,
and kindle a War there; which done, to carry
on the War again&s;t his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty, in
conjunction with their Confederates, and by
the perfidious Means of the <HI>Mazeppian</HI> Rebels,
and <HI>Blavian</HI> Co&s;&s;acks, to foment Sedition within
his Maje&s;ty's Empire; and thus to put in Ex|ecution
tho&s;e mo&s;t pernicious and abominable
De&s;igns which they have premeditated as
well again&s;t his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty, and the
King of <HI>Poland,</HI> as again&s;t the whole <HI>Chri&s;tian</HI>
World.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;THAT therefore, the Ju&s;tice of his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI>
Maje&s;ty's Cau&s;e, may clearly appear to all
the hone&s;t Part of the World, that he never
&s;ince this fir&s;t Minute of the Truce of <HI>Carlo|witz,</HI>
and the Conclu&s;ion of the 30 Years Peace,
which the Sultan of the <HI>Turks</HI> has now ba&s;ely
broke to this very Hour, gave him any Occati|on
for &s;uch a Breach, but did holily and reli|giou&s;ly
ob&s;erve the &s;ame, notwith&s;tanding
the great and many Attempts made to the Con|trary,
on the Part of the <HI>Turks,</HI> what by ho|&s;tile
Irruptions in his Dominions; and what by
protecting his rebel Subjects, and giving Shelter
to his Enemy, he has the Contrary been graci|ou&s;ly
Pleas'd to command this mo&s;t wicked
Breach of the <HI>Turks</HI> to be expo&s;ed to all Mens
View.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;LET every Body now con&s;ider the Inclinati|on
which his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty has &s;hew'd all along
for Peace: Then di&s;cu&s;s the ju&s;t and Moderate
Steps he made in the whole Series of this Af|fair,
and judge whether there was the lea&s;t Oc|cation
given on his Maje&s;ty's Side, for break|ing
<PB N="320" REF="329">
of the Peace, and whether after the previ|ous
Marks which he gave of his good Intentions,
he could ab&s;tain from declaring War in his
Turn, again&s;t the profidious and perpetual
Enemy of <HI>Chri&s;tanity:</HI> And finally, let him
conclude, that this particular War was forced
upon his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty contrary to the Faith
of Treaties, and the Sacred Tye of publick
Oaths; who thereupon with God Almighty's
A&s;&s;i&s;tance, has re&s;olv'd in his own Defence, to
order his Army, to March to his Frontiers
again&s;t his perfidious Enemy, the Sultan of the
<HI>Turks,</HI> and all his Confederates and Abettors:
And to follow it him&s;elf in Per&s;on, very &s;oon,
and committing upon his bended Knee, the
Ju&s;tice of his Cau&s;e, to the &s;ame great God's
Judgment, thus betakes him&s;elf to Arms.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;AT the &s;ame time the <HI>Czar</HI> wrote a Letter to
the Grand Seignior him&s;elf, to remove the Ob|jection
about the conveying the King of <HI>Sweden</HI>
into his own Territories, offering to give him free
Pa&s;&s;age through the <HI>Mu&s;covite</HI> and <HI>Poli&s;h</HI> Domini|ons,
with a &s;ufficient Guard for the Safety of his
Per&s;on, or to allow the <HI>Turks</HI> to convoy him
with a certain Number of Troops. The Letter
is as follows.&endq;</P>
<P>WE wrote twice to your Highne&s;s, namely, <HI>fir&s;t</HI>
the 28th of <HI>July,</HI> and <HI>&s;econdly,</HI> the 29th of
<HI>October,</HI> of the la&s;t Year, that according to inter|cepted
Letters, and by the long Abode of the King of
<HI>Sweden</HI> in your Territories, it was to be fear'd
that that Prince and his Adherents, with the <HI>Co&s;|&s;acks,</HI>
<PB N="321" REF="330">
Rebels to us, and to the King of <HI>Poland,</HI> our
Ally; would by Means of the tryaterous Palatine of
<HI>Kiow,</HI> and others, who finding Refuge in your Ter|ritories,
endeavours to engage your Highne&s;s in a
War; for which Rea&s;on we de&s;ir'd that your Highne&s;s
would Cau&s;e his <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty forthwith to depart
your Territories, and return into his own; offering
him a free Pa&s;&s;age through our Armies, under a
a Guard of 4000 <HI>Tartars,</HI> and 5000 <HI>Turks,</HI> in ca&s;e
your Highne&s;s &s;hould think it proper, for his greater
Security: This is what our Amba&s;&s;ador was charged
to propo&s;e to you; and his <HI>Poli&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty having
likewi&s;e con&s;ented to it, we were bound to an&s;wer for
the &s;aid free Pa&s;&s;age.</P>
<P>Moreover, We declared, that in ca&s;e your High|ne&s;s
would grant a more numerous Guard to the King
of <HI>Sweden,</HI> and conduct him into <HI>Poland</HI> by force of
Arms, This would be look'd upon by us, and by his
<HI>Poli&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty, that your Highne&s;s had a mind to
break the Peace of <HI>Carlowitz</HI> and that we &s;hould be
oblig'd to oppo&s;e the &s;ame to the utmo&s;t of our Power,
by Virtue of the Alliance, whereby we are mutually
bound to a&s;&s;i&s;t each other.</P>
<P>We are not the violators of that Peace, but would
religiou&s;ly ob&s;erve it on our Part, to prevent the Effu|&s;ion
of Human Blood; God will &s;urely revenge it
upon the Fomentor of the War, and Violator of the
mo&s;t Solemn Treaties: and &s;hould the King of <HI>Swe|den</HI>
offer to return into his Dominions by any other
Way than has been propo&s;ed to him under Colour of
greater Security, we &s;hall look upon that Proceeding
as an open Violation of the Peace.</P>
<P>We have not yet received any An&s;wer from your
Highne&s;s, to our former Letters, nor from our Am|ba&s;&s;dor,
to let us know whether he deliver'd them
to your Highne&s;s, and whether he had any An&s;wer
<PB N="322" REF="331">
or not: But on the Contrary, we have received cer|tain
Advice, from &s;everal Places, that our Amba&s;|&s;ador
has been arre&s;ted, that the War again&s;t us has
been re&s;olv'd upon at <HI>Con&s;tantinople,</HI> and Orders
are given for forming an Army at <HI>Bender;</HI> and that
the <HI>Tartars</HI> who are ready to conduct the King of
<HI>Sweden,</HI> are order'd to enter <HI>Poland</HI> by Force of
Arms; wherefore we thought fit to write this Letter
to your Highne&s;s, to exhort you once more to an&s;wer
our former Letters, and to let us know whether you
intend to ob&s;erve the Treaty prolong'd with us la&s;t
Year, for 30 Years, confirm'd with &s;everal Oaths,
made before the Judge of all our Actions, or to vio|late
if, without the lea&s;t Occa&s;ion on our Part
given.</P>
<P>We al&s;o declare, that in ca&s;e we receive no An&s;wer
touching your Intention to pre&s;erve the Peace, and
that your Highne&s;s continues your Military Prepa|rations,
to conduct the King of <HI>Sweden</HI> through <HI>Po|land,</HI>
with a powerful Army, we &s;hall look, upon this
as an open Violation of the Truce; and calling God
to our A&s;&s;i&s;tance, &s;hall provide for our own Safety,
and endeavour to repul&s;e our Enemies with the Ar|my
we have &s;ent upon the Frontier.</P>
<P>In the mean while, if the Rupture of the Peace
be attended with the Effu&s;ion of Human Blood, we
declare, before God and Man, that it will not be
our Fault, but that we &s;hall be forc'd to it. We like|wise
take God to Witne&s;s that it was never our In|tention
to break the Truce, but to ob&s;erve it religi|ou&s;ly
as we promi&s;ed, wherefore, without Tru&s;ting
in any vain Immagination, but only in the &s;upreme
Judge, we hope, he will defend us again&s;t all Di|&s;turberso$
the Peace and Violators of Cat$s.</P>
<P><PB N="323" REF="332">
We expect therefore, an An&s;wer to the&s;e Pre|&s;ents
and in ca&s;e none comes, we &s;hall look. up|on
it, as a Breach of the Peace: But if we
&s;ee by your Highne&s;&s;es An&s;wer, that your Inten|tion
is to let us alone, and inviolably to main|tain
the Peace with us, (the King of <HI>Sweden</HI> be|ing
&s;ent back, without its being in any wi&s;e in|fringed)
all our Umbrage will Cea&s;e.</P>
<P>And as our Army is advancing towards the
Frontiers, without committing any Act of Ho&s;ti|lity,
the Rupture cannot be attributed to us;
the le&s;s becau&s;e, if the Satisfaction that is re|quir'd
be given us, our Troops &s;hall forthwith with|draw
from your Neighbourhood, and we will in|violably
maintain the Truce, with your Highne&s;s;
We wi&s;h your Highne&s;s perfect Health.</P>
<CLOSER><DATELINE>Given at <HI>Petersburgh,</HI>
the <DATE>16th of <HI>Janu|ary,</HI>
1711.</DATE></DATELINE>
<SIGNED>Sign'd
PETER.</SIGNED></CLOSER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2>
<P>ALL these Things put together, will convince
any indifferent Per&s;on, that the <HI>Czar</HI> was no
ways acce&s;&s;ary to this War; but that on the Con|trary,
his Maje&s;ty u&s;ed all ju&s;t Means con&s;i&s;tent
with his Honour, to keep the Peace, &s;o newly
entred into, and &s;o &s;olemnly &s;worn between him|&s;elf
and the <HI>Turks.</HI> But it could not be, the
<HI>Turks</HI> prepair'd for War, with all imaginable
Diligence; the King of <HI>Sweden</HI> began to grow
formidable again at <HI>Bender,</HI> having gotten near
20000 Men together, very good Troops, mo&s;t of
them <HI>Swedes</HI> and <HI>Poles,</HI> and now the Grand Army
<PB N="324" REF="333">
of the <HI>Turks</HI> which had encamped at <HI>Adrinople</HI>
&s;ome Time, began to advance.</P>
<P>THE <HI>Czar</HI> had a good Army of excellent
Troops, and he had order'd the Hor&s;e for &s;ome
Time to rendezvous about <HI>Lemberg,</HI> where his
<HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty came &s;oon after in Per&s;on, and
advanc'd with them to the Frontiers; they con|&s;i&s;ted
in about 40000 Hor&s;e, and a great Body of
the Hor&s;e remain'd about <HI>Ja&s;&s;y,</HI> to &s;ecure the
Communication.</P>
<P>WITH this Army, when joyn'd by the Infant|ry,
the <HI>Czar</HI> advanced; and having an intimate
Corre&s;pondence with the Ho&s;podar of <HI>Moldavia,</HI>
he made Conditions with him, to furni&s;h his,
Army with Bread, and other Provi&s;ions, and
to give him Pa&s;&s;age and Re-pa&s;&s;age thro' the
Country.</P>
<P>SOME have &s;aid the Ho&s;podar kept a &s;ecret
Corre&s;pondence with the Grand Vizier, all the
while; and did this on purpo&s;e to betray the
<HI>Czar,</HI> but this was grounded on a Mi&s;take; the
Ho&s;podar perform'd his Agreement as long as he
was able to do it without ruining him&s;elf, and
all his Affairs; but drew off, when he &s;aw the
<HI>$urki&s;h</HI> Army was &s;o much &s;uperior to the <HI>Czar,</HI>
that he apprehended a Blow, and that he &s;hould
fall into the Hands of the <HI>Turks;</HI> then indeed,
it was to be expected he would act with more
Caution.</P>
<P>ON the other Hand, 'tis &s;aid, the Ho&s;poder
did perform his Part effectually, as to furni&s;hing
what Provi&s;ions the <HI>Czar</HI> requir'd, and that no|thing
was deficient, but that the Ho&s;podar never
condition'd to furni&s;h Troops, or to draw his
Sword in the Quarrel.</P>
<P><PB N="325" REF="334">
BUT to let that pa&s;s, his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty &s;et
out from <HI>Jaro&s;law,</HI> the 10th of <HI>June,</HI> 1710,
where Matters were concerted between the King
of <HI>Poland</HI> and him&s;elf, for mutual A&s;&s;i&s;tance
in this War, after which the King of <HI>Poland</HI>
went away into <HI>Saxony,</HI> to &s;ettle his Affairs
in <HI>Germany;</HI> and the <HI>Czar</HI> went from thence
to <HI>Lemberg,</HI> as above, then the Army; that is to
&s;ay, the Cavalry, were order'd to advance to the
<HI>Dnei&s;ter;</HI> His Maje&s;ty joyn'd them near <HI>Kami|nieck</HI>
and march'd, keeping the River on his
Right, till he came to <HI>Ra&s;kow,</HI> on the <HI>Dnei&s;ter,</HI>
where he was joyn'd by the four Regiments of
his Guards, or Hou&s;hold Troops; the re&s;t of the
Infantry coming up in a few Days more, by the
Way of <HI>Bracklaw</HI> and <HI>Czarka&s;&s;y;</HI> &s;ome pa&s;&s;ing
by <HI>Kiovia,</HI> and &s;ome by <HI>Pultowa,</HI> a Place made
famous by the late Overthrow of the King of
<HI>Sweden.</HI></P>
<P>WHEN the whole Army was brought toge|her,
they reckon'd them to be 35000 Foot, and
40000 Hor&s;e, all choice Troops, e&s;pecially
the Infantry; 3000 <HI>Turks</HI> po&s;ted overagain&s;t <HI>Ra&s;kow,</HI>
in order to di&s;pute their Pa&s;&s;age Over the <HI>Neither,</HI>
abandon'd their po&s;t upon the coming up of 2000
<HI>Mu&s;covite</HI> Grenadiers, who had pa&s;s'd in the
Night in &s;ome &s;mall Boats, at about a League di|&s;tance,
and out of their Sight.</P>
<P>AS &s;oon as the <HI>Turks</HI> were fled, two Bridges
being laid upon the River, and a &s;mall En|trenchment
at the End of each Bridge, to &s;e|cure
the Pa&s;&s;age, the whole Army pa&s;&s;ed over
with their Artillery and Baggage.</P>
<P>FROM the <HI>Nei&s;ter,</HI> the Army advanced to
the <HI>Pruth,</HI> and the <HI>Czar</HI> went in Per&s;on with
5000 Dragoons to <HI>Ja&s;&s;y,</HI> the Capital of <HI>Moldavia;</HI>
<PB N="326" REF="335">
to Conver&s;e with the Ho&s;podar, and to &s;ecure
&s;ufficient Magaziens of <HI>Provi&s;ions</HI> which that Coun|try
and <HI>Wallachia,</HI> being very fruitful, were very
well able to Furni&s;h: Here the <HI>Czar</HI> &s;taying too
long, gave the <HI>Turks,</HI> who where then as far off
as the <HI>Danube,</HI> Time to come up, for the Vizier
hearing that the <HI>Czar</HI> was pa&s;t the Nei&s;ter, made
long Marches, fearing the <HI>Ru&s;&s;ians</HI> &s;hould reach
to the Banks of the <HI>Danube</HI> before him, and con|&s;equently
&s;hould prevent or di&s;pute his Pa&s;&s;age,
and perhaps have given him a Blow, if he had
attempted it.</P>
<P>The Vizier was decamp'd from <HI>Adrianople</HI> ac|cording
to the be&s;t Advices, when the <HI>Czar</HI> came
to the Banks of the <HI>Nei&s;ter;</HI> but had &s;ent a great
Body of his Infantry that they might pa&s;s the
Straights of the Mountain <HI>Hemus,</HI> which runs
in a Chain, from the Shore of the <HI>Venetian</HI> Gulph,
thro' <HI>Macedonia</HI> and <HI>Thrace,</HI> to the <HI>Euxine</HI> Sea;
but as &s;oon as the Vizier had an Account, that
the <HI>Czar</HI> had advanc'd, he put him&s;elf in full
March with the Hor&s;e, and came to the <HI>Danube,</HI>
the 24th of <HI>June.</HI></P>
<P>HAD not his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty been delay'd at
<HI>Ja&s;&s;y</HI> too long, but had pa&s;s'd the <HI>Pruth</HI> at that
City, and march'd on directly to the <HI>Danube,</HI> he
had certainly carry'd the Point, and the Vizier
had been kept at Bay, at the pa&s;&s;ing that River;
for he would not have ventur'd to have pa&s;s'd
the <HI>Danube,</HI> which is a prodigious great River at
<HI>Sili&s;iria, a little above which he went over,</HI> and the
Stream fierce and Rapid: I <HI>&s;ay,</HI> he would not
have ventur'd to pa&s;s that River, in the Teeth
of the <HI>Ru&s;&s;ian</HI> Army; or if he had, he would
have run a great Ri&s;que of being defeated.</P>
<P><PB N="327" REF="336">
IT was without doubt, either a Mi&s;take, or a
Misfortune, that his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty's Army
&s;hould Halt upon the <HI>Pruth,</HI> and let the <HI>Turks</HI>
pa&s;s the <HI>Danube;</HI> and his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty &s;aw it,
when it was too late; for had the Banks of the
<HI>Danube</HI> been &s;ecured, the King of <HI>Sweden</HI> mu&s;t
have &s;hifted his Quarters, and have quitted
<HI>Bender,</HI> with as much Precipitation, almo&s;t, as
he did <HI>Pultowa,</HI> and perhaps would have found
it more difficult to have made his E&s;cape.</P>
<P>NOR would the Forces of the <HI>Tartars</HI> have
been &s;o trouble&s;ome, if the Grand Army of the
<HI>Turks</HI> had been kept off; for tho' they call'd
the <HI>Tartars</HI> 50000 yet the <HI>Ru&s;&s;ians</HI> would have
fac'd about, and have made them &s;hift off, as
fa&s;t as they came: But when the <HI>Turks</HI> lay at
the <HI>Danube</HI> before, and the <HI>Ru&s;&s;ians</HI> had their
Hands full of them in their Front, it was ea&s;y
for a Body of <HI>Tartars</HI> to do Mi&s;chief in the
Rear.</P>
<P>'TIS to no Purpo&s;e to enlarge upon what
might have been done, it is our Part to give
the Hi&s;tory of what was really done; and the
<HI>Czar</HI> having lo&s;t 12 Days Time at <HI>Ja&s;&s;y,</HI> the
Banks of the <HI>Pruth,</HI> the Grand Army of the
<HI>Turks</HI> Pa&s;s'd the <HI>Danube</HI> undi&s;turb'd, and advanc'd.
a-pace.</P>
<P>WHILE the <HI>Turks</HI> and the <HI>Ru&s;&s;ians</HI> were then
facing one another, the <HI>Tartars</HI> by their Inroads
Harra&s;s'd the <HI>Ru&s;&s;ian</HI> Army, took many Hor&s;es,
and killed a great many People, and at la&s;t,
effectually cut off their Provi&s;&s;ions, &s;unk or
burnt all the Boats they had on the <HI>Purth,</HI> and
in a Word, being very numerous, they did the
<HI>Ru&s;&s;ians</HI> a World of Mi&s;chief.</P>
<P><PB N="328" REF="337">
THIS brought them to a Battle, for the <HI>Turks</HI>
advancing to the <HI>Pruth,</HI> and the <HI>Ru&s;&s;ians</HI> &s;eeing
them&s;elves almo&s;t reduced to an Extremity, re|&s;olv'd
to wait their coming and Fight, them;
the My&s;tery of this Engagement, and of the
&s;udden Peace which was the Con&s;euence of it
is not fully known in the World, and perhaps
never may.</P>
<P>THE Sum of the Story, is this; the <HI>Turks</HI> ad|vancing,
and appearing very numerous, the <HI>Czar</HI>
cau&s;ed his Men to entrench, believing the Ene|my
would attack them; as, indeed, they did
the next Day; the Entrenchment which they
attack'd, was Guarded by 12 Battallions of <HI>Mu&s;|covite</HI>
Infantry, and about 3000 Granediers;
who all together ply'd their Time &s;o well, and
lay'd &s;o many of the Enemy dead upon the
Spot; that the <HI>Janizaries</HI> after a furious Attack,
which la$ted four Hours, the Ba&s;ha's bringing
on fre&s;h Men, as the others were beaten off,
were finally repul&s;ed with great Slaughter; a
Body of Dragoons, who were po&s;ted to Support
the Defendants, falling out al&s;o upon them in
their Retreat.</P>
<P>THAT Night the Intrenchments were en|larg'd,
and 10000 Foot, &s;upported by Dragoons,
were po&s;ted to defend them; the Enemy came
on again to the A&s;&s;ault, with 20000 <HI>Janizaries,</HI>
&s;upported by a great Body of Hor&s;e; the <HI>Ru&s;&s;ian</HI>
Army &s;tood in Order of Battle in two Lines, in
their Camp, which was al&s;o entrench'd; the Fight
was ob&s;tinate, and very bloody; the Fury of the
<HI>Turks</HI> not being to be re&s;i&s;ted, without great Lo&s;s
on the <HI>Ru&s;&s;ian's</HI> Part al&s;o; However, the <HI>Turks</HI>
were again Beaten off; and in the&s;e two Days, it
was &s;aid, that the <HI>Turks</HI> lo&s;t 12000 of their be&s;t
Men.</P>
<P><PB N="329" REF="338">
HOWEVER, as the <HI>Turks</HI> &s;till prepar'd to re|new
their Efforts, as if re&s;olv'd to carry the
Entrenchments, whatever it Co&s;t; and his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI>
Maje&s;ty finding the <HI>Tartars</HI> which harraz'd him,
continually in the Rear, had 10000 Foot &s;ent
them from the Viziers Army, and that he &s;hould
be in Danger of being quite Surrounded by two
va&s;t Armies of near 100000 Men each; and which
was wor&s;e, that his Convoys were cut off by the
<HI>Tartars;</HI> he re&s;olv'd to Retreat; which, however,
was done in &s;uch Order, and with &s;uch daring
Boldne&s;s of Courage, in Sight of the Enemy,
that when the <HI>Turki&s;h</HI> Cavalry, pretended to pur|&s;ue
them, the Foot fairly faced about, threw
down their <HI>Chevauz de Frieze,</HI> and pour'd in
their Volleys upon the <HI>Turks,</HI> and then Re|treated.</P>
<P>HOWEVER, this retreating fareagu'd the Army
to the la&s;t Degree, and the <HI>Tartars</HI> &s;urprizing
a great many of the <HI>Czar's</HI> Hor&s;es, added to the
Misfortune, &s;everal Regiments of Hor&s;e be|ing
entirely di&s;mounted: So the <HI>Czar</HI> finding a
convenient Situation to Encamp and Entrench,
halted again.</P>
<P>HERE the Vizier came up with the whole
<HI>Turki&s;h</HI> Army, but dur&s;t not attack the <HI>Ru&s;&s;ian</HI>
Camp, the Front being defended by a Mora&s;s;
the Right Wing, by a winding Branch of the Ri|ver
<HI>Pruth;</HI> and the Left, by a Hill, which the
<HI>Mu&s;covite</HI> Infantry, had entrenched: The Vizier
&s;eeing this, brings up his Cannon, and Can|nonaded
them in their Camp, with 50 Pieces of
heavy Artillery; and their Camp lying expo&s;ed
to this Battery, there was no hindring it; at the
&s;ame Time, they &s;eem'd entirely to be &s;hut in,
by the winding of the River <HI>Pruth,</HI> and the E|nemy;
<PB N="330" REF="339">
&s;o that in &s;hort, the Generals began to
look one upon another, as Men de&s;perate, and
at a Lo&s;s what to do.</P>
<P>THE Colonels, and inferiour Officers, were
for drawing out the Array, and giving the <HI>Turks</HI>
Battle, and the Common Soldiers cry'd out to
be led again&s;t the Enemy, that they might dye
with their Swords in their Hands, and &s;ell their
Lives as dear as they could, rather than be torn
in Pieces with the Cannon, and peri&s;h in the
Camp for Want of Provi&s;ions: But his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI>
Maje&s;ty, who alone was not di&s;maid at the Cir|cum&s;tances
he was in, quikly re&s;olv'd what to
do, and order'd a Trumpet with three Officers,
to the Vizier, writing a Letter to the Vizier
him&s;elf.</P>
<P>THE Effect of this Me&s;&s;age, <HI>what ever the Pro|po&s;al
was,</HI> an&s;wer'd &s;o well what his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Ma|je&s;ty
de&s;ir'd, that it produc'd a Treaty; and tho'
it mu&s;t be confe&s;s'd, that the Circum&s;tances of
the <HI>Ru&s;&s;ian</HI> Army then were &s;uch that a De|feat
was inevitable, except by a de&s;perate Brave|ry
they could have broke thro' the whole <HI>Turki&s;h</HI>
Army, which being &s;o de&s;titute of Hor&s;es, was
next to impo&s;&s;ible; yet, as they were all re|&s;olv'd
to dye with their Emperor, and to &s;ell
their Lives like Men of Honour; the Vizier, who
knew it, mu&s;t have cau&s;ed a mo&s;t bloody Action,
and perhaps might have been ruinous to him al&s;o,
thought fit to con&s;ider what Propo&s;als were made
and whether the Demands he might make, might
not only &s;ave the pre&s;ent Effu&s;ion of Blood, but
a future Expence both of Blood and Trea&s;ure
to the whole <HI>Ottoman</HI> Empire.</P>
<P><PB N="331" REF="340">
UPON this Foot, he Demanded the City of
<HI>A&s;oph,</HI> which was indeed, a Purcha&s;e, which a
whole Campaign, and a good Array could not
have procur'd them; (<HI>&s;ome &s;ay,</HI> his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Ma|je&s;ty
offer'd the City of <HI>A&s;oph</HI>) he demanded
al&s;o 1200000 Dollars in Money; the fir&s;t, he
called, the Agreement of Peace; and the &s;econd,
he called, the Ran&s;om of the Army; who, he
&s;uppo&s;ed, to be all as good as his Pri&s;oners, and
con&s;equently Slaves, ready to be &s;old at Market;
which indeed, as Things &s;tood, was almo&s;t the
Ca&s;e.</P>
<P>THE bringing &s;uch a Treaty to Conclu&s;ion,
in &s;uch an Exigency, was a Ma&s;ter-Piece of
the <HI>Czar</HI>'s own conducting; for on the other
Hand, the King of <HI>Sweden</HI> did his utmo&s;t to pre|vent
it, nay, even he reproach'd the Vizier in
the Head of has Army, complaining that he
&s;hould give up the Grand Seignior Enemy, when
he was in his Hand, and that in one Day the
<HI>Czar</HI> mu&s;t be his Pri&s;oner, and all his Army;
and even threatening to repre&s;ent it to the
Grand Seignior, as to be &s;ure he afterwards did.</P>
<P><HI>I &s;ay,</HI> it was a Ma&s;ter Piece indeed, for the
Vizier, by what Means is yet unknown, and per|haps
will ever be &s;o, continued firm, and repre|&s;ented
the Advantages of Peace on the Terms
propo&s;ed, particularly the re&s;toring of <HI>A&s;oph,</HI> a
Place, the Lo&s;s of which, had been a hear
Breaking to the <HI>Turki&s;h</HI> Court: <HI>I &s;ay,</HI> he repre|&s;ented
this &s;o effectually to the Port, that the
Sultan confirmed the Treaty, and ratify'd it
with great Satisfaction, notwith&s;tanding all the
Repre&s;entations of &s;ome of his Courtiers, who
were again&s;t it.</P>
<P><PB N="332" REF="341">
AS for the King of <HI>Sweden,</HI> and the Han of
<HI>Tartary,</HI> they fail'd not, to give a quite diff|erent
Account of the Thing, repre&s;enting the
Vizier as Confederate with the <HI>Czar,</HI> to betray
his Ma&s;ter, the Grand Seignior's Intere&s;t; and
that he had taken a great Sum of Money to let
the <HI>Czar</HI> e&s;cape out of his Hands, when he might
with Ea&s;e have carry'd him away in Triumph,
and have deliver'd him up, at the Gate of the
Seven Towers in <HI>Con&s;tantinople.</HI></P>
<P>THIS they aggravated to that Degree after|wards,
and told their Tale &s;o &s;peciou&s;ly, that the
Grand Seignior was quite turn'd about in his
Judgment of the Thing, and re&s;ented it to the
Ruin of the <HI>Grand Vizier,</HI> who was &s;trangled
&s;oon after, by Order of his Ma&s;ter, for making
the Treaty, which he him&s;elf had approv'd.</P>
<P>BY this Treaty, (the Peace being made) the
<HI>Czar</HI> of <HI>Mu&s;covy,</HI> and his whole Army, march'd
&s;afe and quietly, to the Bank of the <HI>Dnei&s;ter,</HI>
and &s;o by ea&s;y Marches, into the <HI>Ukraine,</HI> with
all their Cannon and Baggage; and thus ended
this &s;hort War, wherein tho' the <HI>Czar</HI> indeed
lo&s;t the Honour of the Field, yet he gain'd this
great Point; namely, that the <HI>Turks</HI> abandon'd
the Intere&s;t of the King of <HI>Sweden;</HI> which was
all i. deed, that the War was made for; and
which if they would have done before, the <HI>Czar</HI>
would never have took the Field at all: The
Lo&s;s the <HI>Czar</HI> &s;u&s;tain'd in this Battle, was not
much le&s;s than 10000 Men, and a prodigious
Number of Hor&s;es, &s;ome &s;aid 30000, but no
Artillery, or Trophies.</P>
<P>HIS <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty having thus gotten over the main Article, the War with the <HI>Turks;</HI> little
of Moment pa&s;s'd for &s;ome time, the King of
<PB N="333" REF="342">
<HI>Poland</HI> was wholly taken up in &s;ettling him&s;elf in
his newly re&s;tored Kingdom; and the <HI>Czar</HI>
giving his Troops a whole <HI>Winters</HI> Re&s;t, had lei|&s;ure
to recrute and refre&s;h them, and in particular
to fill them up with Forreigners, <HI>Germans, Scots,
Livonians, Poles,</HI> nay, even with the <HI>Swedes,</HI> them|&s;elves,
for whole Companies of the <HI>Swedes,</HI> who
&s;urrendered at <HI>Pultowa,</HI> and were taken in Bat|tle
there, and other Places, finding no other
End of their Misfortunes, Li&s;ted in the <HI>Czar's</HI>
Service, and were generally employ'd on the
Side of <HI>Cyrka&s;&s;ia,</HI> and <HI>Ukrania,</HI> and &s;uch remote
Parts of his Dominions.</P>
<P>THE Articles of Peace, thus agreed upon,
by the <HI>Turks,</HI> and the <HI>Czar</HI> of <HI>Mu&s;covy,</HI> however
they may be thought hard, and worded di&s;ho|nourably
for his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty, the Ju&s;tice due
to an impartial Hi&s;tory, requires they &s;hould be
recorded, as follows.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2>
<PB N="334" REF="343">
<HEAD>The grand Rea&s;on of this authentick
WRITING is, That by the Grace of God, the
victorious Mu&s;&s;elman's Army, having by &s;ur|rounding
and &s;hutting up the Czar of Mu&s;covy,
with his whole Army, in the Neighbourhood
of the River of Pruth, brought him into
Sraights; he him&s;elf de&s;ir'd Peace, and on the
In&s;tance of the &s;aid Czar, the Treaty and Ar|ticles
were &s;ettled and concluded, in the fol|lowing
Manner.</HEAD>
<P>I. THAT be &s;hall re&s;tore the Fortre&s;s of <HI>Azoph,</HI>
in the Condition wherein he formerly took it,
with its Territories and Di&s;tricts.</P>
<P><HI>II.</HI> That <HI>Taiganrog, Kamenki,</HI> and the new
Fort on the further Side of the River <HI>Kaman,</HI> &s;hall
be totally demoli&s;h'd, the Cannon and Ammunition
of War in the Fortre&s;s <HI>Kamenki</HI> (or <HI>Kaminick</HI>)
to be left therein, to the Illu&s;trious Port, and no new
Fort to be ever built in the &s;ame Place.</P>
<P><HI>III.</HI> That the <HI>Czar</HI> &s;hall not concern him&s;elf with
the <HI>Polacks,</HI> nor with the <HI>Co&s;&s;acks,</HI> their Depen|dants,
named, <HI>Baraba&s;ci</HI> and <HI>Porcali;</HI> nor with
the Dependants of the mo&s;t &s;ucce&s;sful <HI>Han Daubet
Gherai;</HI> but &s;hall leave them in their former Con|dition,
and withdraw all his Forces out of tho&s;e
Cou$tries.</P>
<P><HI>IV.</HI> That M$rcha$ts may come $y Land into the
w$ll guarded Dominio$s, with their Merchandize;
but no Per&s;on &s;hall be admitted to re&s;ide at the
Illu&s;trious <HI>Port,</HI> in the Quality of Amba&s;&s;ador.</P>
<P><HI>V.</HI> That all <HI>Mu&s;&s;elmen,</HI> who formerly, or in this
War have been taken, and are Slaves in the Hana$
of the <HI>Mu&s;covi$es,</HI> &s;hall be Re&s;tored to Liberty.</P>
<P><PB N="335" REF="344">
<HI>VI.</HI> That the King of <HI>Sweden,</HI> having taken
Sanctuary under the Wings of the powerful Protection
of the illu&s;trious Port, &s;hall have free and &s;afe Pa&s;|&s;age
without being in any manner hindred or &s;topp'd
by the <HI>Mu&s;covites;</HI> and in ca&s;e they can come to a
good Under&s;tanding together, and have a Mind to
make Peace, it may in Con&s;equence be treated between
them.</P>
<P><HI>VII.</HI> And for the future, no Damage or Injury
&s;hall be done by the Port to the <HI>Mu&s;covites;</HI> in like
Manner, the&s;e la&s;t &s;hall do no Wrong to the former,
or their Subjects or Dependants</P>
<P>&startq;WHEREFORE, the immence Goodne&s;s of my
mo&s;t powerful and gracious Emperor, and
Lord, is be&s;ought, to be pleas'd, to ratify the
foregoing Articles, and to overlook the pa&s;t ill
Behaviour of the <HI>Czar.</HI>&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;THUS, and in the foremention'd Manner, by
Vertue of the full Power to me given, is this pre|&s;ent
Treaty made and deliver'd; we &s;hall there|fore
confer about the Ho&s;tages given by the &s;aid
<HI>Czar,</HI> for Performance of the Articles contain'd
in the &s;aid In&s;trument; likewi&s;e, the Treaty
of Peace nam'd <HI>Temeruki</HI> &s;hall be mutually Ex|changed;
after which his Army &s;hall march off
free, and the direct way to their own Country,
without any Hindrance, either by the Victorious
Army, or by the <HI>Tartars,</HI> and others; the fore|going
Articles, &s;hall of Cour&s;e be executed, and
the Capitulation mutually Exchang'd; after
which we will immediately give Liberty to the
Two Ho&s;tages that are in the victorious Army,
namely, the Chiefe&s;t among the Nobility of
the Nation of the <HI>Me&s;&s;iah,</HI> his Privy Chancel|lor,
Baron <HI>Peter Schaphirof,</HI> and the Grand&s;on
of <HI>Czeremext Michael Boriz</HI> (Who&s;e Ends be
<PB N="336" REF="345">
Happy) after every Point &s;hall have been per|form'd;
in Te&s;timony of what is agreed, this
pre&s;ent Writing, Sign'd in the afore&s;aid Camp,
the 6th of the Month <HI>Gemaiel Ac$ir,</HI> of the
<HI>Heg$ira,&endq;</HI> 1123, (or, the 21&s;t of <HI>July,</HI> 1711.)</P>
<P>WE &s;hall now bring our Hi&s;tory into a more
compact Method of Relation; for as hitherto,
the &s;everal ally'd Powers of <HI>Mu&s;covy, Denmark,</HI>
and <HI>Poland,</HI> have acted &s;ingle, and in &s;eperate
Parts of the World, So that we have been ob|lig'd
to trace their Proceedings from one Part
of the World to another, and give the Story
a-part; we &s;hall now find them joyn all three
together in pu&s;hing the <HI>Swedes</HI> as their Common
Enemy, in order to thru&s;t them quite out of
<HI>Germany,</HI> and di&s;po&s;&s;e&s;s them of all their Domini|ons,
on this Side of the <HI>Baltick Sea.</HI></P>
<P>IT has been already noted, how King <HI>Augu&s;tus,</HI>
after the Defeat of the <HI>Swedes</HI> at the great Battle
of <HI>Pultowa,</HI> had rea&s;&s;um'd the Crown of <HI>Poland;</HI>
'tis no part of my Bu&s;ine&s;s to relate his Proceed|ings
there; or the Manner in which he went on
to E&s;tabli&s;h him&s;elf on that Throne, other than
as the <HI>Czar</HI> of <HI>Mu&s;covy,</HI> who&s;e Story we are up|on,
was Concern'd in it, that part belongs more
particularly to the Hi&s;tory of King <HI>Augu&s;tus,</HI> and
his Affairs in <HI>Poland.</HI></P>
<P>BUT now we &s;hall find the <HI>Czar,</HI> King <HI>Au|gu&s;tus,</HI>
and the King of <HI>Denmark,</HI> all in a Body
acting together in concert, and all in one Place,
<HI>viz.</HI> in <HI>Pomerania,</HI> in order to pu&s;h the <HI>Swedes</HI>
out of that Country; which, in &s;hort, was the
Center of all their Force, and by which Country
all their Reinforcements from <HI>Sweden</HI> arriv'd;
And here General <HI>Cra$$an,</HI> with a Body of Troops,
<PB N="337" REF="346">
had hover'd over the Frontiers for &s;ome time,
threatening <HI>Saxony</HI> with another Inva&s;ion, and
perhaps had made good their Menaces they gave
out, had not the Power and Princes of the Grand
Alliance's form'd, what they call'd, a neutral
Army to prevent it.</P>
<P>THIS the <HI>Swedes</HI> re&s;ented in the highe&s;t Man|ner
po&s;&s;ible, and fail'd not to te&s;tify their Re|&s;entment,
in Seizing the Ships belonging to the
&s;aid Confederates in the <HI>Baltick,</HI> and refu&s;ing to
allow them the Liberty of Trade to the Towns
of <HI>Livonia,</HI> taken from them by the <HI>Czar,</HI> as par|ticularly
<HI>Riga, Pernau, Revel,</HI> and <HI>Narva,</HI> as al&s;o
<HI>Wyburgh,</HI> and even to <HI>Dantzick.</HI></P>
<P>THINGS &s;tanding thus, the Allies above-nam'd,
re&s;olv'd to reduce the Provinces of <HI>Pomerania,</HI>
and the <HI>I&s;le of Rugen,</HI> as the only Footing the
<HI>Swedes</HI> had on this Side the <HI>Baltick,</HI> except the
City and Port of <HI>Wi&s;mar,</HI> which they afterward
found Means to reduce al&s;o.</P>
<P>THE King of <HI>Poland</HI> began this Part of the
War, as the Per&s;on who was more nearly con|cern'd,
and having publi&s;h'd a large Manife&s;to
of his Rea&s;ons for it; the <HI>Czar</HI> came in rather as
an Auxiliary than otherwi&s;e tho' his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje|&s;ty's
Quarrel at the <HI>Swedes,</HI> was equally concern'd
with any of them; this Manife&s;to &s;tating the Ca&s;e
of the whole War, I amoblig'd to mention, becau&s;e
the <HI>Czar</HI> is nearly concern'd in the Con&s;equences,
tho' not in the Rea&s;on of that part of the
Quarrel.</P>
<P><PB N="338" REF="347">
HOW great a Regard the mo&s;t Serene King of
<HI>Poland</HI> has ever had &s;ince the Beginning of this
War, to the Friend&s;hip of the mo&s;t Serene <HI>Allies</HI> in
the War again&s;t <HI>France;</HI> and what he has done up|on
that Con&s;ideration, mu&s;t be &s;ufficiently known to
all the World; how al&s;o, and often po&s;tponing his own
Advantage; he has neglected no Occa&s;ion to expre&s;s
his Inclination and Readine&s;s to promote their In|tre&s;t,
of which, certainly, his Maje&s;ty gave an unde|niable
In&s;tance, in the Year 1709, when the <HI>Swed|i&s;h</HI>
Troops under General Cra&s;&s;au retir'd from <HI>Po|land</HI>
into <HI>Pomerania;</HI> it was doubtle&s;s his <HI>Poli&s;h</HI>
Maje&s;ty's Intere&s;t, to fall upon his Enemies at that
Time, and give them no time to re-e&s;tabli&s;h their
Forces, in order to di&s;turb again the Kingdom of
<HI>Poland,</HI> or invade the Hereditary Dominions of his
&s;acred Maje&s;ty, or at lea&s;t to keep them in continual
Apprehen&s;ions of an Irruption: The&s;e were &s;uffici|ent
Rea&s;ons to induce his Maje&s;ty to the Enterprize,
and he had Forces enough to execute it; For, be&s;ides
the Army of <HI>Poland</HI> and <HI>Lithuania,</HI> the Auxiliary
Troops of <HI>Mu&s;covy,</HI> under General <HI>Goltz,</HI> were at
Ha$d&punc; his Maje&s;ty might very well have followed the
Example given him by the King of <HI>Sweden</HI> him&s;elf,
in the Year 1706, and have pur&s;u'd and attack'd
the <HI>Swedes</HI> in <HI>Pomerania;</HI> but notwith&s;tanding
this appear'd highly nece&s;&s;ary for his own Security,
he for$ore it of his own accord, at the de&s;ire of
the High Allies, making War again&s;t <HI>France,</HI> he &s;o
wi&s;ely, and prudently directed that Affair, that upon
Condition of a certain and &s;ufficient Guaranty, which
was to be given by the &s;aid <HI>Allies;</HI> for the Security
of the co$federated Princes in the <HI>North,</HI> they alter'd
their Re&s;olution to pur&s;ue the Troops under General
<HI>Cra&s;&s;au,</HI> in the Province afore&s;aid. The <HI>Czar</HI> of
<HI>Mu&s;covy,</HI> and the Republick of <HI>Poland,</HI> caus'd im|mediately
<PB N="339" REF="348">
after, their Mini&s;ter at Ratisbon and the
<HI>Hague,</HI> to &s;ignify, as they did likewi&s;e them&s;elves,
by Letters, their good Intentions, for the Confede|rates
again&s;t <HI>France;</HI> adding, however, a Clau&s;e, or
Condition, that not only the <HI>Saxon</HI> Territories, but
al&s;o the Kingdom of <HI>Poland,</HI> and the <HI>Dani&s;h</HI> Pro|vinces,
afterwards mention'd in the publick Acts of
the <HI>Nutrality,</HI> &s;hould be ab&s;olutely &s;ecur'd again&s;t all
Inva&s;ion on the part of the <HI>Swedes,</HI> by the Guarant|y
of the High <HI>Allies,</HI> again&s;t <HI>France;</HI> for it would
have been highly unju&s;t in any, to have procured a free
and &s;afe Flight and Retreat for the Enemies above|&s;aid,
and to have refus'd, at the &s;ame time to pre|vent
the Danger that might be apprehended from
them.</P>
<P>This being approv'd, Treaties were &s;et on Foot,
and concerted for that Neutrallity at the <HI>Hague</HI>
and <HI>Ratisbon</HI> in the u&s;ual manner, and the mo&s;t Se|rene
<HI>Allies,</HI> look'd upon that Affair, at that time,
almo&s;t as the Safety and Pre&s;ervation of the Empire,
and as if the Fate of the whole Common Cau&s;e de|pended
thereupon; the <HI>Confederates</HI> in the <HI>North,</HI>
having the &s;ame Notions, accepted the Neutrality,
and by means thereof, bound them&s;elves in &s;ome man|ner
with the <HI>Allies</HI> again&s;t <HI>France;</HI> and it was re|&s;olved,
that if any &s;hould act contrary to this Agree|ment,
that the other, &s;hould unite their Forces again&s;t
the Infringer of the &s;aid Neutrality. The mo&s;t Se|rene
King of <HI>Poland</HI> ob&s;erved religiou&s;ly what had
been concerted and agreed to, by the <HI>Allies</HI> on both
&s;ides; expecting and confiding, that the King of <HI>Swe|den</HI>
would agree, and conform him&s;elf to that Con|vention,
according to the obligatory Declaration of
the Royal <HI>Senate</HI> of <HI>Stockholm,</HI> delivered in a
&s;olemn manner in Writing at the <HI>Hague;</HI> but con|trary
to the Opinion and Expectation of all, the King
<PB N="340" REF="349">
<HI>Sweden</HI> was of a different Opinion, and manife&s;ted
the &s;ame by Word and Deed, as it is &s;ufficiently
known to the World; be endeavour'd at fir&s;t, amu&s;se
the mo&s;t Serene <HI>Allies</HI> in &s;everal ways, and &s;et
on Foot a Treaty with them for putting into their Ser|vice
8000 Men, to be detach'd from the Troops un|der
general <HI>Cra&s;&s;au</HI> in <HI>Pomerania;,</HI> but when Great
Britain, and the <HI>States,</HI> had con$ented to every
Thing that had been de&s;ired of them, and the Treaty
was look'd upon as concluded, $e forbid the Senate
of <HI>Stockholm</HI> to part with any Forces for the Ser|vice
of the <HI>Allies.</HI></P>
<P><HI>I.</HI> Not contented therewith, he augmented his
Army in <HI>Pomerania,</HI> above one half of the
Number the &s;ame was at fir&s;t, by new Levies.</P>
<P><HI>II.</HI> He cau&s;ed a con&s;iderable Number of Men, to
be brought over, at &s;everal Times, from <HI>Swe|den,</HI>
into <HI>Pomerania,</HI> &s;ometimes 500 Men, and
at other times 800.</P>
<P><HI>III.</HI> He cau&s;ed &s;everal <HI>Dani&s;h</HI> Ships belonging to
the Provinces included in the Neutrality, to be
cha&s;ed by his Men of War, and u&s;ed in a $word$
manner, breaking thereby the Neutrallity afore|&s;aid.</P>
<P><HI>IV.</HI> After having concluded an Alliance with the
<HI>Ottoman</HI> Port, the Hereditary Enemy of the
<HI>Chri&s;tian</HI> Name, which cannot be excu&s;ed; he
did not &s;cruple do declare a$ the <HI>Hague,</HI> and
at the Diet of <HI>Ratisbon,</HI> by a &s;olemn Writing
dated from <HI>Bender,</HI> the 30th of <HI>November,</HI>
1710; that he rejected the Neutrallity afore&s;aid,
and would not be oblig'd to the &s;ame; and the
Baron <HI>de Stralenheim,</HI> his Envoy at the Impa|rial
Court, had already prote&s;ted again&s;t it, the
11th of Augu&s;t the &s;aid Year; $e u&s;ed there|in
<PB N="341" REF="350">
a har&s;h Stile, attended with Mennaces, hard|ly
to be endur'd, as that the Convention for the
&s;aid Neutrality was partial (tho' it was for his
Advantage, if he would con&s;ider the Thing
Right:) that $e re&s;erv'd to him&s;elf an unlimit|ed
Liberty, to employ his Forces again&s;t whom&s;oever,
and in &s;uch Times, and Places, as $e
&s;hould think fit, according to the Laws and
Cu&s;toms of War; if any one offer'd to hinder
him from pur&s;uing his declared Enemy with his
Arms, he could not but con&s;ider him as an Ag|gre&s;&s;er,
and declare him for &s;uch: Which a|mounts
in Effect, not only to a Declaration of War
again&s;t the Confederated Princes in the <HI>North</HI>
in general, and again&s;t the mo&s;t Serene King of
<HI>Poland,</HI> in particular, and a Signification that
he will attack him in the <HI>Poli&s;h</HI> Dominions, and
in his Electorate, or, where&s;oever he &s;hould
think fit; but may be look'd upon al&s;o, as a De|claration
of War again&s;t the <HI>Allies,</HI> now in War
again&s;t <HI>France;</HI> and an intimation that he will
carry on the &s;ame on all Sides, by the help of
his Confederates the <HI>Turks</HI> and <HI>Tartars:</HI> This
the King of <HI>Sweden</HI> has expre&s;s'd in plain
Terms, in his Manife&s;to dated from <HI>Bender,</HI>
28th of <HI>January,</HI> of this pre&s;ent Year 1711.
which the Palatine of <HI>Kiow</HI> di&s;per&s;ed in <HI>Po|land,</HI>
attended with an Army of <HI>Barbarians</HI>
and <HI>Infidels,</HI> and which was directly intended
again&s;t the King of <HI>Poland,</HI> wherein he declar'd
be has made an Alliance with the <HI>Turks</HI> and
<HI>Tartars,</HI> for that Purpo&s;e; But the&s;e Threats
will not binder the mo&s;t Serene <HI>Allies;</HI> again&s;t
<HI>France,</HI> from adbearing to the Mea&s;ures con|certed,
for maintaining the Neutrality, afore|&s;aid.</P>
<P><PB N="342" REF="351">
<HI>V.</HI> To what has been already &s;aid, it mu&s;t, be ad|ded,
that the Rebel <HI>Smigielski,</HI> was lately &s;ent
from the <HI>Swedi&s;h Pomerania</HI> with a Manife&s;to
of Count <HI>Lezinski</HI> (who not only continues in
the Country, but is maintain'd therein) and with
&s;ome Troops has made an Irruption into the
Country to exhort the <HI>Poles</HI> to Rebellion, and
has actually committed Ho&s;tilities again&s;t the
Troops of the King of <HI>Poland,</HI> and when they
were Pur&s;uing him, he retired again into the
<HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> Province afore&s;aid, where he is en|tertain'd,
and &s;upply'd with Nece&s;&s;aries, by
which Action, this Neutrality has been again
infringed by the <HI>Swedes:</HI> Therefore the mo&s;t
Serene King of <HI>Poland,</HI> is not only grounded in
Justice, But be&s;ides, lies under a pre&s;&s;ing Nece&s;&s;ity,
to make u&s;e of all lawful Means, for eradica|ting
this Evil, and preventing tho&s;e Dangers in
their very Source.</P>
<P>There is no Rea&s;on to believe, that when the mo&s;t
Serene <HI>Allies</HI> again&s;t <HI>France,</HI> induced the mo&s;t Serene
King of <HI>Poland,</HI> and his Allies, to accept, out of
Regard to them, a Neutrality &s;o advantagious to the
King of <HI>Sweden,</HI> tho' he had rejected it with Scorn,
ever pretend that this Compliance and Readine&s;s of
his <HI>Poli&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty, &s;hould turn to the Ruin of the
Kingdom of <HI>Poland,</HI> and other Provinces belonging to
him; tho' this has, in a great Mea&s;ure, already hap|pen'd;
&s;eeing that out of Fear of an Inva&s;ion on the
Part of the &s;aid <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> Forces in <HI>Pomerania</HI>
Many Subjects of his Majesty have abandon'd their
Country, whereby the Credit of the Merchants among&s;t
Forreigners, and trade in general, has receiv'd great
Prejudice: be&s;ides this Damage; the Expences for
rai&s;ing new Forces, and equiping them, their
<PB N="343" REF="352">
Marches, and Maintenance, with the rai&s;ing of the
Militia throughout the whole Electorate of <HI>Saxony,</HI>
have not only put the mo&s;t Serene King of <HI>Poland</HI> to
great Charges, and involv'd him in great Difficulties,
but have al&s;o le&s;&s;en'd very much his Revenues, and
occa&s;ion'd many other Lo&s;&s;es.</P>
<P>Furthermore, it would be altogether unrea&s;onable,
that the King of <HI>Sweden,</HI> who has already receiv'd
this Benefit of the Convention of the Neutrality tho'
irreverently rejected by him, in that no Body has pur&s;u'd
the Forces of <HI>Cra&s;&s;au</HI> into <HI>Pomerania,</HI> &s;hould conti|nue
to enjoy the &s;aid Neutrality, to the Prejudice of
the King of <HI>Poland,</HI> and his Allies, in the <HI>North;</HI>
for no Body can be in&s;ensible that the <HI>Turki&s;h</HI> War
is founded on the Augmentation of the <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> Army
in <HI>Pomerania,</HI> and the future Inva&s;ion by the &s;ame,
of <HI>Poland</HI> or <HI>Saxony.</HI></P>
<P>The State of Affairs being &s;uch, and the World
being per&s;waded that the King of <HI>Sweden</HI> has &s;o ex|plain'd
his Mind by Words and Deeds, that nothing
further is to be expected from him; and that on the
other Hand, it appears, after other violent Means of
that King, which were &s;carce ever heard of before, from
a <HI>Chri&s;tian</HI> Prince; That the Security of the mo&s;t
Serene King of <HI>Poland,</HI> and his Dominions depends
on the Di&s;per&s;ion of the <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> Army in <HI>Pomera|nia;</HI>
it follows that the mo&s;t Serene <HI>Allies</HI> again&s;t
<HI>France,</HI> are oblig'd to a&s;&s;i&s;t him with their Forces,
according to the Tenor of the Convention, and as the
Pre&s;ervation and Tranquility of the Holy <HI>Roman</HI>
Empire, and the happy Succe&s;s of the Common Cau&s;e
depend, in a great Mea&s;ure on this Point; the mo&s;t
Serene King of <HI>Poland</HI> expected that the mo&s;t Serene
<HI>Allies</HI> again&s;t <HI>France,</HI> would have &s;ent their Forces,
de&s;ign'd for maintaining the &s;aid Neutrality, to be
employ'd under his Command, as being the Party of|offended,
<PB N="344" REF="353">
and in Danger; but as they have not $word$
able hitherto, to execute their good Intentions, as the
Delays of the March of their Troops they had pro|$$i&s;ed,
and other Difficulties &s;ufficiently &s;hew; the mo&s;t
Serene King afore&s;aid, thinks him&s;elf Nece&s;&s;itated to
take without delay, &s;uch Mea&s;ures as are nece&s;&s;ary
for his Affairs, and for preventing the Inconvenien|cies,
and Damages afore-mention'd, and their Con&s;e|quences;
on the other Hand, the faithful States of
the Kingdom of <HI>Poland,</HI> will be no longer uncer|tain,
as wi&s;hing to &s;ee the Tranquility of their Coun|try
&s;ettled upon a firm Bottom.</P>
<P>But the Rea&s;ons alledg'd here, for the Pre&s;erva|tion
of <HI>Poland</HI> and <HI>Saxony,</HI> are not the only Motives
that induce his <HI>Poli&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty to make u&s;e of the
lawful Means afore&s;aid; but the Tranquility of the
holy <HI>Roman</HI> Empire, whereof the Pre&s;ervation is
chiefly committed to his Care, at this pre&s;ent time as
<HI>Vicar</HI> thereof, be&s;ides the Dignity of Director of the
Circle of <HI>Upper Saxony,</HI> does chiefly require this
from him; e&s;pecially, &s;eeing it is known that the King
of <HI>Sweden</HI> has lately made an Alliance with the King
of <HI>France,</HI> the Tenor of which, could not be kept
a Secret, but that the <HI>Allies</HI> had notice of it: Be|&s;ides,
it is likewi&s;e known, that the <HI>Swedes</HI> in <HI>Pome|rania</HI>
wait only that the Elector of <HI>Bavaria</HI> may ex|ecute
his Projects on the <HI>Upper Rhine,</HI> again&s;t the
Holy <HI>Roman</HI> Empire, there being no doubt but they
would lay hold of that Opportunity to invade <HI>Saxony,</HI>
and the Provinces of <HI>Germany,</HI> rather than tho&s;e of
<HI>Poland:</HI> From whence it appears, how nece&s;&s;ary it
is to u&s;e proper Means in Time, that thro' the Di&s;per|&s;ion
of the <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> Army in <HI>Pomerania,</HI> that Tran|quility
of the Holy <HI>Roman</HI> Empire, may be &s;ettled,
and pre&s;erv$d, that the dangerous Machinations,
afore &s;aid, may be prevented, and that the Fire hid
<PB N="345" REF="354">
under tho&s;e treacherous A&s;hes, may be Extingui&s;h'd
therefore no Body can blame the De&s;ign of the mo&s;t
Serene King of <HI>Poland,</HI> to provide for his Security,
and di&s;charge his Office with the Forces God has
given him, and the A&s;&s;i&s;tance of his Allies; Its further
more declared, on the Part of the mo&s;t Serene King
of <HI>Poland,</HI> that he has no other Intention and De|&s;ign,
but to procure the Security of the Holy <HI>Roman</HI>
Empire, and his own; and that he is induced to it
that the mo&s;t Serene <HI>Allies</HI> again&s;t <HI>France,</HI> will &s;ee
that the mo&s;t Serene <HI>Allies</HI> in the <HI>North,</HI> have made
&s;uch Di&s;po&s;itions, and taken &s;uch Mea&s;ures, that they
will more readily concur therein, and perform what
they are oblig'd to, by their Agreement; and this
happy <HI>Band of UNION</HI> among them&s;elves, which is
hitherto continued may remain in-di&s;oluble to their
Common Advantage.</P>
<P>THO' the King of <HI>Poland</HI> began this Part of
the War, in declaring the Intentions of the Allies,
yet the King of <HI>Denmark</HI> fir&s;t enter'd the Country,
that Prince perhaps glad to leave his own Domi|nions,
and his Capital City where the Plague
rag'd, at that Time, mo&s;t violently, enter'd the
<HI>Swedi&s;h Pomerania</HI> with his Army, the 8th of
<HI>Augu&s;t,</HI> 1711. And without any Re&s;i&s;tance, that
was con&s;iderable, advanced to the Neigbourhood
of <HI>Stral&s;ound.</HI></P>
<P>BUT this was too great an undertaking for the
King of <HI>Denmark's</HI> Army who were not full 20000
Men, without the King of Poland; however
in <HI>September,</HI> the <HI>Saxons</HI> arriv'd, to the Number
of 12000 Men, and the two Armys being thus
joyn'd, they inve&s;ted <HI>Stral&s;und:</HI> But <HI>Stral&s;und</HI>
&s;trong by Situation, and well fortify'd, was too
knotty a Piece of Work, even for both the Kings
<PB N="346" REF="355">
united; for they found, that there was no In|ve&s;ting
it effectually, unle&s;s the <HI>I&s;le of Rugen,</HI>
which lies over-again&s;t it, &s;hould be fir&s;t reduc'd;
to prevent this, the <HI>Swedes</HI> had in that I&s;land, and
in the City, an Army of old Soldiers, Stronger
in Foot, than both the King's Armies put toge|ther,
tho' not equal to them in Hor&s;e; they like|wi&s;e
found, that the <HI>Swedes</HI> Daily relieved the
Town, by Sea, as they thought convenient;
having a Squadron of Men of War, and Frigats,
always in the Harbour; the&s;e Difficulties oblig'd
them at la&s;t to rai&s;e the Siege, without &s;o much
as carrying on any effectual Attack, or, &s;o much
as offering to Storm any of the Out-works. But
it mu&s;t be enquir'd a little how they &s;pent their
Time.</P>
<P>IT was the End of <HI>October</HI> before the <HI>Saxon</HI>
Artillery arriv'd in the Camp, as for the <HI>Danes,</HI>
they brought no heavy Cannon along with
them, but had &s;ome afterwards, when it was
too late.</P>
<P>HOWEVER, for a great while they amu&s;ed the
World with their Re&s;olutions to attack the <HI>I&s;le of
Rugen,</HI> and the <HI>Danes</HI> who under&s;tand Sea Affairs
better than the <HI>Saxons,</HI> contriv'd to make great
Rafts of Timber, on which to tran&s;port their
Hor&s;e; but the Arrival of &s;ome <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> Fregats
who lay at a Di&s;tance, and batter'd tho&s;e Rafts,
and threw Bombs upon them, &s;hew'd the King
of <HI>Poland</HI> that the tran&s;porting their Cavalry
in that manner, would be impracticable.</P>
<P>IN the mean time, 12 <HI>Swedes</HI> Men of War
arriv'd on the Back of the I&s;land, and Landed
&s;ome Troops, and &s;ent 3 Ships about to <HI>Stral&s;und,</HI>
laden with Ammunition for the Garri&s;on, and
two more large Ships laden with Corn, which
<PB N="347" REF="356">
were <HI>Dani&s;h</HI> Ships, that were bringing of Corn to
the <HI>Danish</HI> Army, which was in great want of it,
but they fell into the Hands of the <HI>Swedes,</HI> and
the be&s;ieged had the Satisfaction of eating the
Bread which was furni&s;h'd for the Be&s;iegers.</P>
<P>THE <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> Captain gave out, that a large
Embarkation of Troops and other Nece&s;&s;aries,
was pr&aacute;eparing at <HI>Carel&s;croon,</HI> and would &s;ail in a
few Days; this News di&s;courag'd the Be&s;iegers, and
in a Word, Provi&s;ions al&s;o growing very &s;carce,
in an exhau&s;ted Country, and the Sea&s;on ad|vancing,
the Troops &s;eparated, and gave over
the Enterprize for that Year. But I &s;hould have
mention'd, that before this, a &s;trong Detatch|ment
of 15000 <HI>Mu&s;covites,</HI> in 1$ Regiments, all
Infantry, arrived in the Camp; and a &s;trong Squa|dron
of <HI>Dani&s;h</HI> Men of War, came to the Back
of the <HI>I&s;land of Rugen,</HI> pretending to &s;upport the
Allies in attacking of the Town but it was too late.</P>
<P>HIS <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty was all this while Carry|ing
on his Intere&s;ts of one kind or another, on the
Frontiers of <HI>Tartary,</HI> by Negotiations with the
<HI>Turks,</HI> on the Subject of Peace, of which, in its
Place.</P>
<P>HE arriv'd the 24th of <HI>October</HI> at <HI>Torgau</HI> on the
<HI>Elb,</HI> where the Marriage of his elde&s;t and only
Son was &s;olemniz'd with the Prince&s;s of <HI>Wolfem|buttel;</HI>
an happy Match, of an unhappy Son!</P>
<P>THIS Marriage had been concerted for &s;ome
Time, but was not con&s;ummated till the latter
End of the Year; the View that the <HI>Czar</HI> had in
this Match, was very well lay'd, for as his <HI>Cza|ri&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty always aim'd at the getting a Footing,
by &s;ome Means or other, in the Empire of <HI>Germany,</HI>
he did not que&s;tion but by this Alliance, &s;ome
Pretentions might in Time ari&s;e, to give him
<PB N="348" REF="357">
Room to intermedle on that Side, as afterwards
he try'd again in the Dutchy of <HI>Mecklemberg,</HI> but
both without Succe&s;s, as &s;hall appear in its
Place.</P>
<P>BUT ro return to the Siege of <HI>Strael&s;und,</HI> the
<HI>Mu&s;covite</HI> Infantry having joyn'd the Confede|rate
Army, and the <HI>Dani&s;h</HI> and <HI>Saxon</HI> Artillery
being all arriv'd, and a <HI>Dani&s;h</HI> Squadron of Men
of War &s;uperiour to the <HI>Swedish,</HI> the World ex|pected
they would go on with Succe&s;s; but we
&s;hall &s;ee this Part re&s;erv'd for a further Exerci&s;e of
their Patience.</P>
<P>THE <HI>Danes</HI> indeed, out did them&s;elves on this
Occa&s;ion, at Sea; for their Fleet con&s;i&s;ted, if
we may believe the Li&s;t they publi&s;h'd, of 36
Men of War of the Line of Battle, from 50
Guns the lea&s;t, to 110 Guns the highe&s;t, and
eight Fregats; but we &s;hall never &s;ee them fit
out &s;uch a Fleet again, neither were the&s;e all at
Sea together; nor were tho&s;e that were out fully
mann'd for an Engagement: However, the <HI>Swedes</HI>
had no Fleet able to look the&s;e in the Face,
&s;o that their Affairs, had they managed them
rightly, were in a fair way, and the <HI>Swedes</HI> mu&s;t
have yielded up the Town. Their Troops
were as follows.</P>
<LIST>
<ITEM><HI>Danes</HI>&mdash;57 Squadrons of Hor&s;e, making 5000
22 Battallions&mdash;13200</ITEM>
<ITEM>4 large Bat. Militia 3600
<LIST>
<ITEM>Foot 16800</ITEM>
</LIST></ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>Saxons</HI>&mdash;46 Squadrons&mdash;Hor&s;e 4600</ITEM>
<ITEM>15 Battalions&mdash;Foot 7500</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>Mu&s;covites</HI> 12 Regiments of Infantry making
30 Battallions&mdash;Foot 15000</ITEM>
<ITEM>48900</ITEM>
<ITEM><PB N="349" REF="358">
Some Accounts &s;ay the <HI>Mu&s;covite</HI>
Troops Con&s;i&s;ted of&mdash;Foot $word$ 10000</ITEM>
<ITEM>and Dragoons 5000</ITEM>
</LIST>
<P>THIS was a great Army, had they been well
apply'd, and well &s;upply'd, but the Sea&s;on of the
Year was too far gone; they had u&s;ed the Coun|try
ill at their fir&s;t coming, e&s;pecially the <HI>Danes,</HI>
&s;o that if the poor People who would have &s;upp|ly'd
them, had neither Corn nor Forrage left
them to bring to the Camp; in a Word, the
Country was Exhau&s;ted, and the <HI>Swedes</HI> at the
Beginning &s;cour'd the Seas &s;o, that nothing could
come that Way; for the <HI>Danes</HI> Fleet came too
late, and when 'twas to no Purpo&s;e to open
Trenches, the whether being Cold, and begining
to freez; this made their Soldiers dye and defert
for meer Want, and the Severity of the Weather
and &s;ervice; &s;o that the <HI>Danes</HI> Foot were reduc'd
to a Handful, the Cavalry was ruin'd and the
Hor&s;e &s;tarv'd; and in a Word, the <HI>Danes</HI> did not
march off above 9000 effective Men, <HI>as we were
told,</HI> out of 21800 they brought with them as
above.</P>
<P>AS for the <HI>Ru&s;&s;ian</HI> Troops they came late, but
they brought &s;ome Stores with them, which a&s;&s;i&s;t|ed
them, and yet they &s;uffer'd very much too,
and were extremly fateigu'd with long Mar|ches.</P>
<P>BUT to return to the Siege, as the Difficul|ties
and Hard&s;hips the Troops indured were
great, &s;o their Councils were divided; the able&s;t
Generals were of Opinion, to rai&s;e the Siege, hold
the Place block'd up during the <HI>Winter,</HI> and At|tack
it early in the Spring with 60000 Men;
others were for carrying it on, whatever it co&s;t;
<PB N="350" REF="359">
and to that Purpo&s;e to &s;end for more Troops,
and both the Kings were really loath to break
up the Siege, e&s;pecially, while the <HI>Danish</HI> Fleet
was &s;o &s;trong, and the <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> Fleet dur&s;t not
appear.</P>
<P>BUT a new Piece of Advice alter'd their
Mea&s;ures, the King of <HI>Denmark,</HI> had Advice that
the <HI>Swedes</HI> prepar$d a great Fleet of Tran&s;ports
at <HI>Carel&s;croon,</HI> with a Convoy of 28 Capital
Men of War, and that they Shipp'd 18000 Men,
on Board this Fleet, under the Command of Count
<HI>Stienboch,</HI> a Name terrible to the <HI>Danes;</HI> this
brought the King immediately to con&s;ider, how
naked he had left his Capital City, the Army
and Fleet being all here; and that if the <HI>Swedes</HI>
&s;hould go directly to <HI>Copenbagen,</HI> they would ruin
him at once, while he was pu&s;hing a foreign
Project.</P>
<P>WITH this Apprehen&s;ion, which was very
ju&s;t in it &s;elf; the <HI>Dani&s;h</HI> Fleet was &s;ent back to
the Coa&s;t of <HI>Denmark,</HI> except &s;ome Fregates
left to Crui&s;e before the <HI>I&s;le of Rugen,</HI> and the
Strait at <HI>Strael&s;und,</HI> to prevent Succours being
brought to the Garri&s;on.</P>
<P>BUT the <HI>Swedes,</HI> who &s;hew'd them&s;elves, on
this Occa&s;ion, appear'd in the Beginning of
<HI>December</HI> upon the Back of <HI>Rugen,</HI> where the
Tran&s;ports immediately Landed about 8000
Men with a great Quantity of Ammunition, a
Train of Artillery, and Store of Provi&s;ions for
the Be&s;ieged, and immediately &s;tood back again
for the Coa&s;t of <HI>Sweden,</HI> to fetch more Troops,
which, however they did not bring at that
Time.</P>
<P><PB N="351" REF="360">
IN this Po&s;ture, Things &s;tood till the End of
<HI>December,</HI> when the two Kings finding they
&s;hould but ruin their Armies, and perhaps fail
in their Enterprize at la&s;t, re&s;olv'd to break up
the Siege; and accordingly the Troops de|camp'd
the 17th of <HI>January;</HI> and we &s;hall find
this difficult Work re&s;erv'd for the power|ful
A&s;&s;i&s;tance, and Councils of the <HI>Czar</HI> in
Per&s;on.</P>
<P>ABOUT the Beginning of <HI>November</HI> this Year,
the Hereditary Prince of <HI>Mou&s;covy,</HI> with his new
Bride, the Prince&s;s of <HI>Wolfembuttle,</HI> &s;et out from
her Father the Dukes Court, on their return
to <HI>Petersburgh;</HI> the <HI>Czar</HI> at the &s;ame time came to
meet them at <HI>Koningsberg</HI> in the <HI>Royal Pru&s;&s;ia,</HI> the
19th, where he was magnificently treated by the
Duke of <HI>Hol&s;tien Sonderburgh</HI> Governor of <HI>Pur&s;&s;ia,</HI>
who went to receive him at <HI>Fredericksburg,</HI> on
the Frontiers of that Dutchy; they all return'd
to <HI>Petersburgh</HI> in <HI>December,</HI> where the Prince&s;s
(<HI>afterwards unhappy!</HI>) was treated by the <HI>Czar</HI>
him&s;elf, with great Affection aud Tenderne&s;s:
But we &s;hall &s;ay more of this Affair hereafter,
perhaps in a Treati&s;e by it &s;elf.</P>
<P>WHILE the&s;e things were in agitation, the
<HI>Turks</HI> began to di&s;cover &s;ome unea&s;ine&s;s at the
<HI>Ru&s;&s;ians</HI> not having perform'd the Articles of the
late Peace, particularly that, about the Surren|der
of <HI>A&s;opb,</HI> and the withdrawing the <HI>Ru&s;&s;ian</HI>
Troops out of <HI>Poland;</HI> the <HI>Czar</HI> had, indeed, de|&s;ired
to have the King of <HI>Sweden's</HI> Pa&s;&s;age &s;ettled
fir&s;t, for his Return to his own Dominions; but
the <HI>Turks</HI> were po&s;itive, and in&s;i&s;ted that the
manner of his Return was not any Part of the
Condition, upon which the evacuating of <HI>A&s;opb</HI>
was &s;tipulated.</P>
<P><PB N="352" REF="361">
AFTER many Debates on either Side, the
<HI>Czar</HI> not having the lea&s;t Apprehen&s;ions of the
manner of his Return, one Way or other, re|&s;olv'd
to perform his Part of the Treaty; and
accordingly order'd all the additional Works at
<HI>A&s;oph</HI> to be demoli&s;h'd, and the royal Fort over|again&s;t
it with the magnificent Bridge, the mo&s;t
beautiful Building in that Part of the World, to
be all blown up in the Air, and the Town to be
put in the &s;ame Po&s;ture at was before, and then
gave it up to three Ba&s;&s;a's, who were &s;ent with
&s;ome Troops from <HI>Con&s;tantinople</HI> to receive it; at
the &s;ame time, his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty declared to
the Court of the Grand Seignior, that he would
oppo&s;e the <HI>Turks</HI> by Force, if they offer'd to
&s;end back the King of <HI>Sweden,</HI> either through his
Dominions, or through the King of <HI>Poland's</HI>
Country with an Army, or with more than
5000 Hor&s;e, the Number propo&s;ed; and thus
ended that knotty Bu&s;ine&s;s, the only Action
of his Life, which the <HI>Czar</HI> had brought to
Account of Lo&s;s, where he led his Armies in
Per&s;on having never been per&s;onally defeated
before.</P>
<P>I mu&s;t now look back again to <HI>Pomerania,</HI>
to lay a Foundation of &s;ome great Actions, which
will bring his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty into the Field on
this Side of the World, where he was, perhaps,
lea&s;t expected: The Siege of <HI>Strael&s;und</HI> was rai&s;ed,
as has been ob&s;erv'd, and the two Kings of <HI>Den|mark</HI>
and <HI>Poland</HI> gone Home, and their Troops
put into <HI>Winter</HI> Quarters. In this Interval, the
<HI>Swedes</HI> brought over more Troops; and together
with tho&s;e already there, form$d a con&s;iderable
Army and that, &s;uch a one, as they threaten'd
to invade their Enemies with, on every Side,
<PB N="353" REF="362">
and particularly, they were greatly alarm'd
with the Apprehen&s;ions of them in <HI>Saxony.</HI></P>
<P>THIS made his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty, at the pre&s;|&s;ing
In&s;tances of the King of <HI>Denmark</HI> and
<HI>Poland,</HI> prepared for an early Campaign, and
his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty re&s;olv'd to be there al&s;o
in Per&s;on; accordingly 25000 <HI>Ru&s;&s;ians,</HI> of the
choice&s;t of his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty's Army, began
their March &s;o early, that they were upon
the Frontiers of <HI>Pomerania</HI> by the End of <HI>April;</HI>
the <HI>Danes</HI> were longer, becau&s;e their Naval Pre|parations
&s;eem'd to take them up, almo&s;t entir|ely;
being re&s;olved to &s;upport the next Years Enter|prize,
with &s;uch a Fleet, as that the <HI>Swedes</HI> &s;hould
not dare to &s;how them&s;elves at Sea to interrupt
them; but we &s;hall &s;oon &s;ee the Effect.</P>
<P>THE <HI>Swedes</HI> in the Mean time had Ship'd off
&s;o many Troops, and &s;uch a Prodigious Quanti|ty
of Arms and Amunition, that they began to
threaten to take the Field with an Army; and
yet to leave the Cities of <HI>Stetin</HI> and <HI>Strael&s;und</HI>
with &s;ufficient Garri&s;ons to defend them&s;elves in
Ca&s;e of an Attack; they had al&s;o put a &s;ufficient
Number of Troops into <HI>Wi&s;mar,</HI> which the <HI>Danes</HI>
had in vain block'd up, the Year before: The
King of <HI>Pru&s;&s;ia</HI> was plea&s;ed &s;o far to favour this
War again&s;t <HI>Sweden,</HI> that he gave Pa&s;&s;age to
Prince <HI>Menzikoff,</HI> who commanded the <HI>Ru&s;&s;ian</HI>
Army, and to his Troops in their March for <HI>Po|merania,</HI>
and the &s;aid Prince <HI>Menzikoff,</HI> pa&s;s'd by
<HI>Koningsburgh,</HI> the 15th of <HI>April,</HI> 1712.</P>
<P><HI>Europe</HI> had now been allarm'd for &s;everal Months
with the News that the King of <HI>Sweden</HI> at <HI>Bender,</HI>
by his own Intere&s;t, and by the Solicitation of the
Cham of <HI>Tartray,</HI> had prevailed with the Grand
Seignior to break again with the <HI>Czar</HI> of <HI>Mu&s;covy,</HI>
<PB N="354" REF="363">
and to renew the War; and &s;o much there was
of truth in it, that the <HI>Turks</HI> made &s;everal ex|travagant
Demands, and that with &s;ome Mena|ces
added to them, which were, (however, in&s;i&s;ted
on) yet very unju&s;t, but as his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty
had in the fir&s;t Place, perform'd the la&s;t Treaty
in every Part of it; and more-over, that Ways
and Means were found oat to bring over the
Cham of <HI>Tartary,</HI> from the Intere&s;t of the King
of <HI>Sweden:</HI> A new Treaty was &s;et on Foot, at
<HI>Cor&s;tantinople,</HI> which was at length fini&s;h'd, and
&s;ign'd, the principal Articles are as follows.</P>
<P>I. THAT the <HI>Czar</HI> &s;hall be oblig'd within 30
Days to withdraw all his Forces out of <HI>Po|land,</HI>
which &s;hall not return thither upon any
Pretence what&s;oever, unle&s;s it &s;hould happen that the
King of <HI>Sweden</HI> being return'd into his Dominions,
&s;hould joyn with the <HI>Poles</HI> and attack <HI>Mu&s;covy</HI>
on that Side, in which Ca&s;e his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty
&s;hall be at Liberty to march again into <HI>Poland</HI> with
his <HI>Troops.</HI></P>
<P>II. That the <HI>Port</HI> &s;hall be allow'd to procure the
Return of the King of <HI>Sweden</HI> into his Dominions,
by &s;uch Ways as the Grand Seignior &s;hall think fit,
without allowing the <HI>Mu&s;covites</HI> to fix the Time of
his Departure, or his Way; but in ca&s;e that
Prince marches through the Territories of <HI>Mu&s;|covy,</HI>
the <HI>Turki&s;h</HI> Troops that &s;hall attend him,
&s;hall commit no manner of Ho&s;tilities or Ravages.</P>
<P>III. That the <HI>Czar</HI> &s;hall remain in Po&s;&s;e&s;&s;ion of
<HI>Kiou</HI> and <HI>Ukrania,</HI> with their ancient <HI>Limits,</HI> but
shall renounce all his Pretentions to the Country of
<PB N="355" REF="364">
the Co&s;&s;acks on this &s;ide of the <HI>Borifthenes,</HI> that
are not in the Dependance of <HI>Kiof,</HI> and on a certain
I&s;land in that River, and that good Orders &s;hall be
given on both &s;ides, to prevent the Excur&s;ions of the
<HI>Co&s;&s;acks</HI> and <HI>Tartars.</HI></P>
<P>IV. That for the Future, no Fortre&s;s &s;hall be
erected between the two Frontier Places of A&s;oph
and <HI>Ciraski</HI> by either of the Parties, and that the
Forts erected by the <HI>Mu&s;covites</HI> in the Teritories of
A&s;oph &s;hall be demoli&s;h'd in four Months, but that
the Grand Signior &s;hall be at Liberty to rebuild
the Fort of <HI>Cinoli,</HI> over-again&s;t A&s;oph.</P>
<P>V. That whereas by the Articles of the Treaty
concluded at <HI>Moldavia,</HI> it was &s;tipulated that <HI>A&s;oph</HI>
&s;hould be re&s;tor'd in the &s;ame Condition that it was in
when the <HI>Mu&s;covites</HI> took it, and that it appears
that there were then in that Place 60 Pieces of Bra&s;s
Cannon, which have not been found therein when it
was re&s;tor'd; his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty &s;hall be obliged to
re&s;tore the &s;aid Artillery, or pay the Value thereof,
and the <HI>Turks</HI> &s;hall deliver to the <HI>Mu&s;covites</HI> the
Iron Cannon that they have left in that Place.</P>
<P>VI. That none of the Parties &s;hall be allow'd
to erect any Forts at <HI>Comenski</HI> and <HI>Savar,</HI> which
by Virtue of the Treaty of <HI>Moldavia</HI> have been de|moli&s;h'd.</P>
<P>VII. That the Peace &s;hall be continu'd 25 Years,
to reckon from the &s;igning of the Treaty, but may
be prolonged before that time is elap&s;ed; and la&s;tly,
that after the Ratification of the pre&s;ent Treaty,
the <HI>Czar</HI> &s;hall be allow'd to &s;end an Amba&s;&s;ador to
Con&s;tantinople to receive the &s;ame, <HI>&amp;c.</HI></P>
<P>BY the beginning of <HI>May,</HI> the <HI>Ru&s;&s;ian</HI> Troops
arriv'd in <HI>Pomerania,</HI> commanded by Prince <HI>Men|zikoff,</HI>
and encamped at <HI>Schweds,</HI> having there
<PB N="356" REF="365">
a Bridge over the <HI>Oder,</HI> being the &s;ame Place
where <HI>Gu&s;tav$s Adolphus,</HI> the Great King of <HI>Swe|den</HI>
encamp'd, when he reduced that Country;
but notwith&s;tanding all this, the <HI>Danes</HI> did not
appear, and in a Word, the <HI>Czar</HI> was fain to re|mit
them 90000 Crowns before they could &s;tir
out of their Quarters: With this Relief, the King
of <HI>Denmark</HI> came to his Army at <HI>Itzhoe</HI> the 10th
of <HI>July,</HI> and when all the World expected him
to march Into <HI>Pomerania</HI> to joyn the <HI>Ru&s;&s;ian</HI> and
<HI>Saxon</HI> Armies, his <HI>Dani&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty turn'd his
Arms another Way, and pa&s;&s;ing the <HI>El$,</HI> enter'd
the Dutchy of <HI>Bremen,</HI> then-under the Govern|ment
of Count <HI>Welling</HI> for the King of <HI>Sweden;</HI>
and not to enter into that Part of the Story too
far, he reduced it entirely, and with it the Coun|try
of <HI>Verden,</HI> and afterwards Morgag'd them to
the King of <HI>Great Britain;</HI> which will give
Occa&s;ion of farther Hi&s;tory to relate the Affair
which attended that Mortgage.</P>
<P>THIS Attempt was a Diver&s;ion, however, to
the Arms of <HI>Sweden;</HI> as was al&s;o the Attack of
<HI>Wi&s;mar,</HI> which the King of <HI>Denmark</HI> and the
<HI>Hanover</HI> Troops, for the King of <HI>Great Bri|tain,</HI>
as Elector of <HI>Hanover,</HI> had declared
again&s;t <HI>Sweden</HI> al&s;o, held block'd up a great
while.</P>
<P>BUT to return to the Affair of <HI>Pomerania,</HI> his
<HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty arrived in that Country the
26th of <HI>July,</HI> and it was time to enter upon
Action.</P>
<P>I cannot omit, in this Place, (tho' it be a
Tran&s;ition at once, from the <HI>Baltick</HI> Shore, to
the <HI>Black Sea</HI>) to mention that the good Under|&s;tanding
at this time &s;ettled between the <HI>Turks</HI>
and the <HI>Czar</HI> of <HI>Ma&s;covy,</HI> was &s;o firm and pro|mi&s;ing,
<PB N="357" REF="366">
notwith&s;tanding all the Mannagement
of the King of <HI>Sweden,</HI> and his Friends, that no|thing
could be better e&s;tabli&s;h'd; and the World
wat &s;urpriz'd to hear that the <HI>Mu&s;covite</HI> Re&s;ident
at <HI>Con&s;tantinople,</HI> had made a formal Rejoycing,
or Fe&s;tival in that City, on the Birth-Day of
his Ma&s;ter, the <HI>Czar;</HI> this being what was not
u&s;ually allow'd by the <HI>Turks</HI> to any Princes Am|ba&s;&s;adors,
was done the more publickly now,
that the Princes of <HI>Europe</HI> might &s;ee that the great
Boa&s;t that the <HI>Swedes</HI> had made of the powerful
Intere&s;t that the King of <HI>Sweden</HI> had at <HI>Con&s;tan|tinople,</HI>
was really nothing in Sub&s;tance, and
that the <HI>Turks</HI> &s;hew'd all po&s;ible Honours to
the <HI>Ru&s;&s;ian</HI> Amba&s;&s;ador: The Particulars of this
Rejoycing are very remarkable, as follows.</P>
<P>&startq;The 10th of this Month being the Fe&s;tival of
St. <HI>Peter</HI> and St. <HI>Paul,</HI> the fir&s;t being the Name
of the <HI>Czar,</HI> the Baron de <HI>Schapfir of,</HI> Vice-Chancellor
of his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty, his Privy-Councellor,
and his Amba&s;&s;ador Extraordina|ry
and Plenipotentiary at the Port, gave a great
Entertainment upon that Account, and al&s;o for
celebrating the Anniver&s;ary of the famous Bat|tle
of <HI>Pultowa,</HI> tho' he had already ob&s;erv'd
the &s;ame two Days before with Illuminations in
his Hou&s;e. All the Amba&s;&s;adors re&s;iding here
were invited to the &s;ame, as were al&s;o the
Re&s;ident of the Emperor, the Vicar of the
Pope, the Secretaries of Amba&s;&s;adors, and
the chief Merchants of all Nations, &s;o that
there was an Appearance of above 100 Per|&s;ons,
for whom there were &s;even Tables,
and they were treated with an extraordinary
Magnificence. During the Entertainment
<PB N="358" REF="367">
there was a fine Con&s;ort of Vocal and In&s;tru|mental
Mu&s;ick, and after the &s;ame, the Com|pany
was entertained with a Comedy in the
<HI>Mu&s;covite</HI> and <HI>Italian</HI> Tongues. The Secretary
Interpreter of the Amba&s;&s;y, pronounced after|wards
the Panegyrick of his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty
in <HI>Latin,</HI> and another Gentleman recited &s;ome
Epigrams on the &s;ubject of the Fea&s;t, to the
Satisfaction of the Company, <HI>&amp;c.</HI> The Col|lonels
of the Jannizaries of the Guard, had
cau&s;ed the Doors of the Hou&s;e of the Amba&s;&s;a|dors
of that Prince to be adorn'd with Fe&s;toons
of Palm, Lawrel, <HI>&amp;c.</HI> which Civility the
Vice Chancellor afore-&s;aid, acknowledg'd with
a Pre&s;ent. The Windows of the Hon&s;e were
illuminated at Night with Emblems of the He|roick
Actions of the <HI>Czar;</HI> and there was a
Fire-work repre&s;enting the Arms of that
Prince, his Name in Cyphers, and the Town of
<HI>Pultowa</HI> with proper De&s;criptions. On the
&s;ide of that Fire there were two Decorations,
each repre&s;enting two Hearts united, and upon
one there were this In&s;cription, <HI>Long live the
Emperor</HI> Perer I. <HI>and the Empre&s;s</HI> Catherina;
and on the other, <HI>Long live the Prince Imperial</HI>
Alexis, <HI>and the Prince&s;&s; Imperial</HI> Charlote. The&s;e
two Decorations continued illuminated all
Night, and the two Nights following, and the
Fea&s;t concluded with a B$ll, which la&s;ted till the
next Morning, and during the &s;ame there was
a magnificent Collation, <HI>&amp;c.</HI> This Fire-work
and the Illuminations were expre&s;ly noted in
the Con&s;ent given by the Port to that Enter|tainment,
which has been &s;eldom allow'd to any
Foreigm Mini&s;ters, and e&s;pecially in <HI>Con&s;tanti|nople,</HI>
which &s;heweth the Value the <HI>Turks</HI> put
<PB N="359" REF="368">
$upon the Friendship of his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty, and
their E&s;teem for his Mini&s;ters.&endq;</P>
<P>BUT to return to <HI>Pomerania,</HI> where the <HI>Czar</HI>
and King <HI>Augu&s;tus,</HI> now commanded in Per&s;on,
as above, the King of <HI>Denmark</HI> being employ'd
in the Reduction of <HI>Bremen,</HI> as before; yet the
<HI>Dani&s;h</HI> Fleet put to Sea in aid of the <HI>Pomeranian</HI>
War, and the <HI>Swedes</HI> having been at Sea, to bring
over Troops of Reinforcement to the <HI>I&s;le of Ru|gen,</HI>
the <HI>Danes</HI> attack'd them in their Return,
and had a &s;harp Fight, but the <HI>Swedes</HI> having
done their Bu&s;ine&s;s, made a rnnning Fight over
to their own Coa&s;t, and the <HI>Danes</HI> could do no
more but fall in among the Tran&s;ports, of which
they de&s;troy'd near 20: However, the <HI>Danes,</HI> to
keep their Reputation a-float; which, as to their
War with the <HI>Swedes</HI> &s;hrunk very low, the <HI>Swedes</HI>
always beating them, cry'd this up for a great
Victory: But this has not been his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje|&s;ty's
Method to boa&s;t of Victory, when he had
won nothing from his Enemy; the Truth is, if
any had the Victory, it was the <HI>Swedes,</HI> for they
did their Bu&s;ine&s;s, <HI>viz.</HI> landed their Troops;
and their Bu&s;ine&s;s then, was not to Fight, but
to go back to fetch more, which they al&s;o did,
notwith&s;tanding all the <HI>Danes</HI> could do.</P>
<P>HAD the <HI>Danes</HI> met them at Sea, with their
Army on Board, and fought them then, had they
either &s;unk or taken any of the Men of War, or
hinder'd their going to land the Troops, and
made them go back again with them to their
own Coa&s;t, there had been a Victory indeed;
but as it was, the boa&s;ting of a Victory, becau&s;e
the Swedes declin'd a clo&s;e Engagement, and
<PB N="360" REF="369">
the taking a few empty Tran&s;ports was rather
a Ga&s;conade than any thing el&s;e.</P>
<P>THE Troops which the <HI>Swedes</HI> landed amount|ed
to 2000 Hor&s;e, and 7000 Foot, Which added
to the Forces they had before, made the At|tempt
upon that I&s;land appear impracticable,
and &s;o the <HI>Czar</HI> and the King of <HI>Poland</HI> lay'd
the Thought of it a&s;ide, for that Year al&s;o,
while the <HI>I&s;le</HI> of <HI>Rugen</HI> is not reduc'd.</P>
<P>HIS <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty therefore, finding no|thing
con&s;iderable could be done more, and his
Affairs calling his Maje&s;ty to <HI>Petersburgh,</HI> he left
the Army the 7th of <HI>October,</HI> under the Com|mand
of Prince <HI>Galiczin;</HI> but with Direction
to obey in all things, the Orders of King <HI>Au|gu&s;tus.</HI></P>
<P>THE Army was then &s;o po&s;ted, as to hold
both <HI>Stral&s;ond</HI> and <HI>Wi&s;mar</HI> block'd up all the
<HI>Winter;</HI> which contributed greatly to the further
Di$tre&s;&s;ing the Enemy, who, notwith&s;tanding
their Reinforcement, could do nothing con&s;idera|ble,
till they had yet another Embarkation of
Troops from <HI>Sweden,</HI> as we &s;hall &s;ee pre|&s;ently.</P>
<P>BUT now we mu&s;t come in its Turn to do
Ju&s;tice to our Enemies, and to &s;hew what Mea|&s;ures
they took, in the Pro&s;ecution of this War:
The <HI>Czar</HI> who was the Life of the War, being
gone, and the Armies being left, as I have &s;aid,
to the Order of King <HI>Augu&s;tus,</HI> the <HI>Swedes,</HI> who
were now grown &s;trong by the arriving of the
Succours above named, tran&s;ported their Troops
over from the <HI>I&s;le of Rugen</HI> to <HI>Stral&s;ond,</HI> and
Count <HI>Steenbock</HI> who commanded them, form'd
an Army of 18000 Men in the Plain, under the
Cannon of <HI>Stral&s;ond,</HI> and began to threaten to
<PB N="361" REF="370">
act offen&s;ively; nor were the <HI>Ru&s;&s;ian</HI> and <HI>Saxon</HI>
Army in the be&s;t Condition to receive them, ha|ving
been much dimini&s;h'd and fateigu'd by the
Service, and much want of Provi&s;ions be&s;ides.
If Count <HI>Steinbock</HI> had re&s;olv'd to attack them,
&s;o near Hand, he could have drawn eight or nine
thou&s;and Men more out of the Garri&s;ons of
<HI>Stral&s;ond, Grip&s;wald,</HI> and other Places, which he
could not do when he &s;hould march farther from
their own Territories.</P>
<P>THINGS &s;tanding thus, King <HI>Augu&s;tus</HI> and the
<HI>Ru&s;&s;ian</HI> General Count <HI>Galiczen,</HI> order'd their Po&s;ts
to be intrenched, and the &s;everal Pa&s;&s;es by
which the <HI>Swedes</HI> might march out, to be forti|fy'd
with very good Lines and Redoubts, and
po&s;ted their Troops in them to oppo&s;e their
Enemies.</P>
<P>As the <HI>Swedes</HI> are allow'd to be a daring and
Enterprizing People, &s;o their Generals are uni|ver&s;ally
Men that under&s;tand their Bu&s;ine&s;s, and
want no military Experience: Count <HI>Steinbock</HI>
being now once more at the Head of an Army,
and <HI>Pomerania</HI> being no Place to &s;ub&s;i&s;t them in
at this Time, When it was &s;o exhau&s;ted by other
Troops, that it &s;tarv'd its own Inhabitants, he
re&s;olv'd to pu&s;h out, and try the Fortune of the
Field; accordingly he began his March the 3d
of <HI>November,</HI> and having forc'd the Pa&s;s of <HI>Dam|garten,</HI>
which the frighted <HI>Saxons</HI> quited, and let
him pa&s;s by, much too cheap; he entered the
County of <HI>Mecklemburgh</HI> with his whole Ar|my,
the 6th, and marched directly towards <HI>Wi&s;mar.</HI></P>
<P>IMMEDIATELY upon this News, away run the
<HI>Danes,</HI> who had roo&s;ted all the <HI>Summer</HI> at <HI>Ro&s;tock,</HI>
and other <HI>Dani&s;h</HI> Regiments likewi&s;e; who car|ry'd
<PB N="362" REF="371">
on the Blockade of <HI>Wi&s;mar</HI> marched off with
the greate&s;t Precipitation, nor to hazard their
Rear, which the Garri&s;on pre&s;s'd upon, but were
di&s;appointed.</P>
<P>THE Dominions of <HI>Denmark</HI> upon the Conti|nent
were allarm'd at this March, and the King
of <HI>Denmark,</HI> who&s;e Troops lay about <HI>Hamburgh,</HI>
from which City they had, drawn about 260000
Rix Dollars, began to gather togther, and to ad|vance
for fear of being cut off from joyning
their <HI>Allies</HI> the <HI>Ru&s;&s;ians,</HI> without whom, they
were not able, as will appear pre&s;ently, to look
their Enemies in the Face.</P>
<P>THE King of <HI>Denmark</HI> ha&s;ten'd likewi&s;e to
his Army, he left <HI>Gottorp</HI> the 19th, and having
joyn'd General <HI>Schoult</HI> and all his Troops, ad|vanc'd
to meet the <HI>Swedes,</HI> who were as forward
as his Maje&s;ty to come to Action: This Excur|&s;ion
of the <HI>Swedes,</HI> as it relates to the War, in
which his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty was &s;o much concern'd,
cannot be omitted here, or the Acton which fol|low'd
it, becau&s;e it would render the Hi&s;tory of
his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty uncompleat, the <HI>Czar</HI> having
acted in it pre&s;ently afterwards in Per&s;on,
with all his Army; the Story of the Excur&s;ion
of the <HI>Swedes</HI> is ab&s;olutely Nece&s;&s;ary, that it
may appear how ill the <HI>Danes</HI> and <HI>Saxons</HI> did their
Part; for certainly, if they had done their Duty
at the Pa&s;s of <HI>Damgarten,</HI> which they pretended
to Guard, and which, as will appear by the Ac|count
following, a few Troops well di&s;po&s;ed,
might have defended, the <HI>Swedes</HI> could never have
broke through, and then all the Lo&s;s and Di&s;|grace,
and all the Mi&s;eries that the King of <HI>Den|mark</HI>'s
Dominions &s;uffer'd af$erwards had been
Prevented; whereas it was manife&s;t, by what
<PB N="363" REF="372">
follow'd, and if the <HI>Czar</HI> had not afterwards
come to his A&s;&s;i&s;tance, his <HI>Da$i&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty
had been utterly ruin'd at that Time.</P>
<P>The Account of this Action, as publi&s;h'd by
the <HI>Swedes,</HI> is as follows, <HI>viz.</HI></P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2>
<HEAD>From the Head Quarters of Count Steinbock at
Ribitz, <DATE>November 5. 1712.</DATE></HEAD>
<P>&startq;ALL the Troops that were in the <HI>I&s;land
of Rugen,</HI> having been brought over to
<HI>Strael&s;und</HI> the 30th pa&s;t, in the Evening, with
their Baggage, Count <HI>Steinboch,</HI> Commander
in Chief of the <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> Army, took his Leave
the next Day of the Garri&s;on and Burghers of
<HI>Strael&s;und,</HI> who were drawn up in Arms, to
whom he made a pathetick Speech, wherein he
exorted them to continue Faithful to their So|vereign
and Country, and be Vigilant in their
&s;everal Stations for the Pre&s;ervation of that
Place. The &s;ame Night he gave Orders to the
Generals of the Army, and the next Day the
Troops began to move, it being given out, that
they were to attack the Lines of the Enemy
before <HI>Strael&s;und.</HI> The general Di&s;po&s;ition of
their March was as follows; Lieutenant Gene|ral
<HI>Ducker,</HI> who commanded the Van-Guard,
con&s;i&s;ting of the Cavalry of the Dutchy of
<HI>Bremen,</HI> and the Dragoons of <HI>Marderfeldt</HI> and
<HI>Stromfeldt,</HI> with nine Pieces of Cannon, was
to march with all Speed towards <HI>Damgarten,</HI> to
take Po&s;t there, and lay Bridges over that Ri|ver,
before the Enemy could draw their Troops
<PB N="364" REF="373">
together, and hinder the <HI>Swedes</HI> from pa&s;&s;ing
the &s;ame; and as the Succe&s;s of the whole
Enterprize depended in a great Mea&s;ure on
the Secrecy and Expedition of the March of
this Body; Care had been taken for three Days
together, that none &s;hould go out of <HI>Strael|&s;und</HI>
or the Camp, to inform the Enemy there|with.
General <HI>Ducker</HI> with his Detatch|ments,
continu'd all that Night at <HI>Ribbartz,</HI>
from whence the Adjutant General <HI>Leppenon</HI>
was detatch'd with 200 Men toward <HI>Frautz|bergh</HI>
to ob&s;erve the Motions of the Enemy
behind their Lines, and give timely Notice
thereof. Lieutenant General <HI>Taube</HI> with the
Cavalry of the Province of <HI>We&s;tergothland,</HI> a
<HI>Pomeranian</HI> Regiment of Hor&s;e, and one of
Foot of Colonel <HI>Ekeblad</HI> encamped that Night
at <HI>Karnin,</HI> having under him Major General
<HI>A&s;henberg.</HI> This was the Body of Battle, and
the Rear commanded by Count <HI>Steinboch</HI> him|&s;elf,
and under him by Major General <HI>Patkul,</HI>
con&s;i&s;ted of the re&s;t of the Hor&s;e, Foot and
Artillery. The&s;e were followed by 1500
Boors, carrying Deal Boards and other Matte|rials
to lay Bridges. The Roads being very
bad by Rea&s;on of Rainy Weather, the Rear of
the Army could not march from Noon till the
Evening, above one League, and encamped at
Pyts. King <HI>Stani&s;la$s</HI> came after the Rear
with his Retinue, The 2d, Lieutenant Gene|ral
<HI>Ducker</HI> advanced to <HI>Damgarten,</HI> where he
took Po&s;t, and marched immediately through a
Defile to a &s;mall Fort, or Redoubt, the Enemy
had erected on the other Side near <HI>Ribnitz,</HI>
which he took Sword in Hand, whereby the
Enemy had many Men kill'd and Wounded.
<PB N="365" REF="374">
Lieutenant General <HI>Taube</HI> continu'd at <HI>Kar|nin</HI>
till Count <HI>Steinboch</HI> came up with the
Rear, and then they march'd together to <HI>Lan|gen-Han&s;agen.</HI>
The following Day, being the
3d In&s;tant, they march'd by Break of Day to
<HI>Damgarten,</HI> where all the Troops joyn'd about
Noon, the General taking his Quarters at <HI>Blom|mon&s;dorf</HI>
on the River <HI>Ribnits,</HI> within a Quar|ter
of a League of that Place. That River
has on both &s;ides a long and deep Mora&s;s, which
e&s;pecially on the &s;ide of <HI>Mecklemburgh</HI> was &s;aid
to be unpa&s;&s;able even for Cattle tho' in the hot|te&s;t
Summer; but however, Count <HI>Steinboch</HI> re|&s;olved
to try whether his Troops could go over it
or no. In order thereunto, he commanded Boards
and Planks to be joyn'd together, to &s;erve
in&s;tead of Bridges over &s;uch Places as &s;hould
appear too deep to be pa&s;s'd otherwi&s;e, and
po&s;ted 400 Foot with 8 Field Pieces, on the
Banks of the River to cover the Men who
were &s;ent before to take a View of the Mora&s;s,
and to &s;ee which way it might be more con|veniently
pa&s;s'd over. The Enemy who ob|&s;erv'd
the&s;e Motions, po&s;ted about 1000 Hor&s;e,
on the other &s;ide of the Mora&s;s, but were ob|lig'd
to quit that Po&s;t by the extraordinary Fire,
that was made from the Field Pieces afbre&s;aid,
and retire into the Wood. The <HI>Swedes</HI> po&s;ted
at <HI>Damgarten</HI> fir'd al&s;o upon them, and they
had above 90 Men kill'd and wounded. The
General order'd the Pontons to be brought
down the River, with other Materials for Brid|ges
over the &s;aid Mora&s;s, and at <HI>Damgarten,</HI>
which were fini&s;h'd that Night. The Generals
being call'd together, Count <HI>Steinboch</HI> gave
them the following Directions for the next
<PB N="366" REF="375">
Day. Lieutenant General <HI>Ducker</HI> was order'd
to pa&s;s over the Bridge laid at <HI>Damgarten,</HI>
with &s;ix Pieces of Cannon and the Vanguard
of the Army, con&s;i&s;ting of the Regiments of
Dragoons of <HI>Marderfeldt</HI> and <HI>Stromfeldt,</HI>
the Cavalry of <HI>We&s;tergothland</HI> and <HI>Bremen,</HI>
and the Regiments of Foot of <HI>Ekebladt,
Schultz,</HI> and <HI>Elf$org;</HI> while Count <HI>Steinboch</HI>
him&s;elf and Lieutenant General <HI>Taube</HI> with the
re&s;t of the Foot and eight Field Pieces &s;hould
pa&s;s the River and Mora&s;s by <HI>Blommendorf.</HI>
The re&s;t of the Cavalry was order'd, if po&s;|&s;ible,
to march after them; but in ca&s;e they
found it too long and difficult, they were order'd
to pa&s;s over the Bridge of <HI>Damgarten,</HI> under
the Command of the Majors General <HI>A&s;henberg;</HI>
and <HI>Mere&s;chal.</HI> The 400 Foot po&s;ted on the
Bank of the River afore&s;aid, under the Com|mand
of Lieutenant Colonel <HI>Slippenback</HI> and
Major <HI>Lewenhaupt,</HI> were order'd to march fir&s;t
of all over the Mora&s;s, and take Po&s;t on the
other &s;ide. The&s;e were to be follow'd by the
Detatchment who carry'd the Planks and
Bridges de&s;igned to be laid over the deep or un|pa&s;&s;able
Places of the &s;aid Mora&s;s. Major Ge|neral
<HI>Patkul</HI> was to march next with the Regi|ments
of <HI>Sudermania, Dalecarlia,</HI> and <HI>We&s;ter|gotbland.</HI>
The&s;e were to be follow'd by the
Prince <HI>de la Gardic,</HI> who brought up the Rear
with the Regiments of <HI>O&s;tergothland, We&s;tman|land,
Helfinge$,</HI> and the two Regiments of the
Provinces of <HI>Narike</HI> and <HI>Wermerland.</HI> Lieu|tenant
General <HI>Cron&s;tedt</HI> was order'd to follow
the Infantry with the Artillery, but if he did
not find it practicable, he was commanded to
march after the Cavalry by <HI>Damgarten.</HI> Col|lonel
<PB N="367" REF="376">
<HI>Rozen</HI> with 600 Hor&s;e and 500 Foot was
order'd to guard the Avenues to <HI>Damgarten,</HI>
that the Enemy might not attack the Baggage
which was &s;ent thither. Adjutant General <HI>Lop|penon</HI>
with his 200 Hor&s;e came the &s;ame Night
from <HI>Frautsbergh,</HI> and reported that the Enemy
were quiet in their Lines, and he had met only
with a Party of <HI>Hu&s;&s;ars</HI> of whom he had kill'd
$ix. According to the Di&s;po&s;itions afore&s;aid,
the March begun the following Day, the Sol|diers
carrying along with them Pla$ks and all
the Doors they could get from the Hou&s;es, and
be&s;ides every other Man carry'd a Fa&s;cine to fill
&s;uch Holes as they &s;hould meet in their way,
whereby not only the Infantry but even the
Artillery pa&s;s'd in good Order over the Mora&s;s,
Which as it has been &s;aid before, was thought
impa&s;&s;able even for the Cattle in the <HI>Summer</HI>
Time. The General &s;eeing there was no Ene|my
to oppo&s;e him on the other &s;ide of the Mo|ra&s;s,
order'd the Cavalry to pa&s;s over the
Bridge at <HI>Damgarten,</HI> and the whole Army be|ing
on the other &s;ide in the Country of <HI>Mack|lenburgh,</HI>
was drawn up in Order of Battle,
and made a general Salvo of their 8 Field
Pieces and &s;mall Arms for this happy Succe&s;s
in their Pa&s;&s;age, without the Lo&s;s of one Man,
and which has rendred u&s;ele&s;s the &s;trong Lines
on which the Enemy have been employ'd about
a Year. The Prince of <HI>Wey&s;&s;enfeldt,</HI> who com|manded
3000 Men on that &s;ide, retired to|wards
<HI>Ro&s;tock,</HI> but not thinking him&s;elf Safe
in that Place retired farther, and Colonel <HI>Ba&s;|&s;e$$itz</HI>
was &s;ent to take Po&s;&s;e&s;&s;ion thereof.&endq;</P>
<P><PB N="368" REF="377">
UPON the News of this Succe&s;&s; of the <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI>
General, the <HI>Czar</HI> who was then at <HI>Dre&s;den,</HI> took
Po&s;t immediately to put him&s;elf at the Head of
his Army in <HI>Pomeren,</HI> where he arrived the 25th,
having before order'd a &s;trong Reinforcement of
Troops to joyn them.</P>
<P>KING <HI>Augu&s;tus</HI> was there with his Army alrea|dy,
&s;o that Count <HI>Steinboch</HI> had no le&s;s than 3 Mo|narchs
at the Head of three Armies to encounter
with, and was &s;o &s;urrounded by them, that they
made no Que&s;tion to give a very good Account
of him; and for this Rea&s;on it was, that the <HI>Czar</HI>
re&s;ented very much a Ce&s;&s;ation of Arms for 15
Days, which was agreed between Count <HI>Stein|boch</HI>
and the <HI>Allies,</HI> and &s;poke with &s;ome Tokens
of Di&s;plea&s;ure again&s;t Prince <HI>Menzikoff</HI> on that
Account; but when his Maje&s;ty came to the
Army, that General convinc'd him, that King
<HI>Augu&s;tus</HI> had agreed to it without his Participati|on,
that he had oppo&s;ed it, and that he would have
had the <HI>Saxons</HI> to have joyn'd in following the
<HI>Swedes,</HI> till they &s;hould be forced to Fight all the
three Armies together.</P>
<P>IT is true, the <HI>Saxons</HI> were not ready, nor the
King of <HI>Denmark,</HI> &s;o that King <HI>Augu&s;tus</HI> acted
upon a ju&s;t Nece&s;&s;ity; and when he lay'd the
Rea&s;ons before the <HI>Czar,</HI> and convinc'd him that
he had no private Treaty in Hand, either with
the King of <HI>Sweden,</HI> or with <HI>Stani&s;laus,</HI> who was
then in the <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> Army, his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty
was better &s;atisfied, and the two Armies ad|vanc'd
to <HI>Gu&s;traw,</HI> where his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty
had his Quarters; the <HI>Danes</HI> who likewi&s;e had
not agreed to the Ce&s;&s;ation, but who alone had
the Benefit of it, having gain'd the Time to bring
their Army together, had they made a right U&s;e
<PB N="369" REF="378">
of the Advantage, were now advanced to <HI>Gad&s;|hu&s;ch;</HI>
&s;o that Count <HI>Steinboch</HI> was, as it were,
block'd up in the narrow Di&s;trict of <HI>Wi&s;mar,</HI>
having his Infantry quartered in the very City,
and his Cavalry canton'd in the Villages round;
where had the three Armies joyn'd, they mu&s;t
have fallen all into the Hands of the Allies,
without Fighting, at lea&s;t all the Hor&s;es, the
Country not affording Forrage Sufficient to &s;ub|&s;i&s;t
them.</P>
<P>BUT Count <HI>Steinboch</HI> knew the Enemy he had
to deal with, and gathering his Troops together
in one Days time, the Truce being to end the
very next Day, he put him&s;elf in full March to|wards
<HI>Gadsbusk,</HI> even before the <HI>Danes</HI> had No|tice
of his being &s;tirr'd from <HI>Wi&s;mar;</HI> as the
<HI>Saxons</HI> and <HI>Ru&s;&s;ian</HI> Armies were near, the King of
<HI>Poland</HI> detached 4000 <HI>Saxon</HI> Hor&s;e to reinforce
the King of <HI>Denmark</HI> as &s;oon as ever he heard
that Count <HI>Steinboch</HI> went that Way, and the <HI>Danes</HI>
ha&s;ten'd them in their way by many Me&s;&s;engers
on the Heels of one another, and at la&s;t by a
Signal of three Pieces of Cannon, which inti|mating
the Extremity, cau&s;ed the <HI>Saxon</HI> Cavalry
to make &s;uch Ha&s;te, that when they arriv'd, be|ing
immediately to go on Action, their Hor&s;e
were &s;o fateigu'd, that they were neither able to
fight, or to run away, and were ea&s;ily defeated,
helping rather, to di&s;courage, than reinforce
the <HI>Dani&s;h</HI> Army, who they came to &s;erve.</P>
<P>IT was the 20th of <HI>December</HI> when the two
Armies came to engage; a full Account of the
Battle can never be drawn from the Perticulars
which were made Publick at that time, each &s;ide
&s;etting forth their own Ca&s;e with the Boa&s;ts and
Rhodomontadoes, u&s;ual with tho&s;e Nations: But
<PB N="370" REF="379">
in few Words, 'tis evident the King of <HI>Denmark</HI>
was &s;oundly Beaten; his Army being driven out
of the Field; his Maje&s;ty, very little to his Ho|nour,
retiring even before the Battle was entire|ly
lo&s;t; the <HI>Swedes</HI> took all their Cannon and
Baggage, &s;everal Colours and Standards, and near
4000 Pri&s;oners, and the &s;catter'd Remains of their
Army retir'd to <HI>Olde&s;loe,</HI> and afterwards Count
<HI>Steinboch</HI> enter'd into <HI>Hol&s;tein,</HI> and had not the
<HI>Czar</HI> of <HI>Mu&s;covy</HI> reliev'd the King of <HI>Denmark</HI>
by joyning his Forces with the <HI>Danes</HI> and <HI>Saxons,</HI>
and per&s;uing the <HI>Swedes,</HI> the King of <HI>Denmark</HI>
had, in all human Probability, been Ruin'd.</P>
<P>THUS his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty has been fir&s;t, or la&s;t,
the Deliverer of all his <HI>Allies,</HI> and the only
Prince that has appear'd able to reduce the
haughty Courage of the <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> Nation; as &s;oon
as his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty had an Account of the
Battle, he joyn'd the King of <HI>Polands</HI> Army, and
all together march'd after Count <HI>Steinboch,</HI> who
had already pa&s;&s;ed the <HI>Trave,</HI> and was advanc'd
into <HI>Hol&s;tein;</HI> the Remains of the <HI>Dani&s;h</HI> Hor&s;e
which had e&s;caped the Battle of <HI>Gadsbu&s;ch,</HI>
joyn'd them in their March, being 2700 Men,
and the whole Army was now, by the Con&s;ent
of the two Kings, put under the Command of his
<HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty, as Generali&s;&s;imo.</P>
<P>IN the mean time, the <HI>Swedes</HI> went on, they
pa&s;&s;ed the <HI>Trave</HI> near <HI>Lubeck,</HI> and Advancing
towards the <HI>Elb,</HI> came to <HI>Hamburgh;</HI> here they
&s;ent out Parties to demand heavy Contribu|tions
of all the Country, and particularly, of the
City of <HI>Hamburgh</HI> it &s;elf; and having enter'd the
King of <HI>Denmark</HI>'s Territories, they burn'd <HI>Alte|na,</HI>
a rich trading Town, within two Miles of
<HI>H$mburgh:</HI> This they pretended was done in
<PB N="371" REF="380">
Repri&s;al for Towns the <HI>Ru&s;&s;ian</HI> Army and other
Confederates had de&s;troy'd in <HI>Pomerania.</HI></P>
<P>THIS barbarous Action, Count <HI>Steinboch</HI> lay'd
to the Charge of General <HI>Welling,</HI> late Governor
of <HI>Bremen;</HI> and in Ju&s;tification, publi&s;h'd the fol|lowing
Letters about it, one whereof pretends
to reproach his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty's Troops, in their
Treatment of their Ma&s;ters Enemies, perhaps
he intends <HI>Livonia</HI> tho' he names it not; the o|ther,
lays the &s;ame Violent Method to the
Charge of the <HI>Danes,</HI> and their U&s;age of the In|habitants
<HI>O&s;&s;enden</HI> in the Dutchy of <HI>Bremen;</HI>
which perhaps was the Occa&s;ion of this Works
being order'd by Count <HI>Welling,</HI> as above. The
Letters with the proper Introductions to them,
are as follows.</P>
<P>&startq;THE <HI>Swedes</HI> having continued for &s;ome Days
about <HI>Ode&s;loe</HI> and <HI>Segebergh,</HI> made a Motion to|wards
<HI>Pinenberg,</HI> and Colonel <HI>Ba&s;&s;ewitz</HI> with
200 Hor&s;e came to <HI>Altena,</HI> and requir'd the In|habitants
to pay a great Sum for Contributions.
On <HI>Sunday</HI> in the Afternoon Count <HI>Steinboch</HI>
came to <HI>Hamburgh</HI> with &s;everal Generals and
having had a long Conference with Count <HI>Wel|ling,</HI>
went to joyn his Troops po&s;ted before
<HI>Altena,</HI> which had been reinforced by several
Detatchments. 'Tis &s;aid the <HI>Swedes</HI> demanded
of that Place 200000 Rixdollars, whereupon,
they offer'd 50000, declaring, that it was im|po&s;&s;ible
for them to pay a greater Sum, upon
which the Agreement was broke, and the fol|lowing
Night &s;everal Detatchments march'd
into <HI>Altena,</HI> and &s;et it on Fire, whereby 'tis
computed that about 3000 Hou&s;es were reduc'd
to A&s;hes, together with the <HI>Popi&s;h</HI> Church; but
<PB N="372" REF="381">
tho&s;e of the <HI>Lutheran</HI> and Reform'd were pre|&s;erv'd,
with about 70 or 80 Hou&s;es. The
<HI>Swedes</HI> burn'd al&s;o &s;everal large Magazines along
the <HI>Elbe,</HI> whereby there are a World of People
ruin'd. The <HI>Dutch</HI> Factors who fore&s;aw that
Misfortune, withdrew mo&s;t of their Effects
from that Place, and removed them to <HI>Ham|burgh.</HI>
The Generals <HI>Fleming</HI> and <HI>Scholten,</HI>
who were there, &s;ent a Trumpeter to Count
<HI>Steinboch,</HI> to complain of this Proceeding, who,
as we heard, an&s;wer'd, that he would acquaint
the World by a Manife&s;to, with the Rea&s;ons
that have oblig'd him to carry Things to the&s;e
Extremities; and in the mean time, they
Hand about here a Copy of a Letter written
by that General to Mon&s;ieur <HI>Wibe,</HI> on of the
Privy-Coun&s;ellors to the King of <HI>Denmark,</HI>
which is as follows,&endq;</P>
<LETTER>
<OPENER><SALUTE>SIR,</SALUTE></OPENER>
<P>IT is with great Regret that I have found my &s;elf
con&s;train'd to de&s;troy the Town of <HI>Altena;</HI>
Rea&s;ons of War, and an inde&s;pen&s;able Nece&s;&s;i|ty,
have prevailed over my own Inclination, which is
not to imitate the Enemies confederated again&s;t the
King my Ma&s;ter: I can at lea&s;t a&s;&s;ure your Excellen|cy,
that the Deva&s;tation of &s;everal of his Maje&s;ty's
Provinces, and the Inhumanities committed therein,
will not move me but in the la&s;t Extremities, to re|taliate
the &s;ame on the Subjects of his <HI>Dani&s;h</HI> Ma|je&s;ty;
and 'tis with this &s;incere Intention that I
have thought fit, Sir, to recommend to you a Pre|caution
<PB N="373" REF="382">
ab&s;olutely nece&s;&s;ary to be u&s;ed with the Forces
of his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty, which is to hinder that they
do not leave behind them in <HI>Pomerania,</HI> upon their
marching out of that Country; burning Tokens and
frightful A&s;hes, to mark the Stay they have made
there, as they have done el&s;ewhere; of which the poor
Inhabitants will never lo&s;e the dreadful Remem|brances.</P>
<P>It will be ea&s;y for the King, your Ma&s;ter, for the
good of his own Subjects, to agree about this with his
<HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty, or el&s;e it will not be in my Power
to forbear u&s;ing, tho' again&s;t my Will, Repri&s;als in
the Dominions of his <HI>Dani&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty, and to de&s;troy
therein as many Towns and Villages as the <HI>Ru&s;&s;ians</HI>
&s;hall have laid in A&s;hes in <HI>Pomerania</HI> at their De|parture.
<HI>I am,</HI></P>
<CLOSER>Sir, <HI>&amp;c.</HI></CLOSER>
</LETTER>
<P>&startq;This is the Account Count <HI>Steinboch</HI> has
given him&s;elf of this Affair, and a Letter
written from his Camp, dated the 8th In|&s;tant,
from <HI>Pinenberg,</HI> gives &s;ome Explanation
of tho&s;e Rea&s;ons of War mention'd by that
General. That Letter is as follows,</P>
<P>COunt <HI>Stienboch</HI> having, receiv'd certain Intelli|gence
in his Camp at <HI>Segeberg,</HI> that they were ma|king
great Magazines at <HI>Altena</HI> to bake Bread and
to brew Drink for the <HI>Mu&s;covites</HI> and <HI>Saxons,</HI> which
were expected there, his excellency thought fit to al|ter
his March, and move that Way with his Army,
to de&s;troy, as the Rea&s;ons of War requir'd, tho&s;e pre|judicial
Stores of Provi&s;ions, which by more particu|lar
<PB N="374" REF="383">
Accounts, me knew the whole Town was $word$
with; but Time, (with Re&s;pect to the Approach of
the &s;aid Troops, and the want of Carriages) not
permitting to carry off the &s;aid Provi&s;ions, nor to
de&s;troy them otherwi&s;e than by &s;etting them on Fire,
his Excellency was oblig'd to give Order for the do|ing
it, thereby coming even with the <HI>Danes</HI> in &s;ome
Mea&s;ure, for the di&s;mal and cruel Burning exerci&s;ed
on the good and ancient Town of <HI>Staden.</HI> His Excel|lency
commanded however, that the Inhabitants &s;hould
be allow'd &s;ome Time to &s;ave their Effects, and a|bove
all, the Churches should be re&s;pected and &s;p$r'd,
tho' that ju&s;t Moderation was not ob&s;erv'd by the
<HI>Danes</HI> in the Burning and De&s;truction of <HI>Staden.</HI></P>
<P>AFTER this Count <HI>Steinboch</HI> publi&s;h'd a brief&punc;
but bold Manife&s;to on the &s;ame Occa&s;ion: As
follows,</P>
<P>COunt <HI>Magnus Steinboch,</HI> Coun&s;ellor of State
and War, and Commander in Chief of the Ar|my
of his Maje&s;ty the King of <HI>Sweden,</HI> notifies and
makes it known, that the Enemies of his Maje&s;ty ha|ving
pre&s;um'd to de&s;troy by Fire the Town of <HI>Staden,</HI>
and the Dutchy of <HI>Bremen,</HI> belonging to the King
of <HI>Sweden,</HI> his Maje&s;ty has commanded him to u&s;e
Repri&s;als, and burn down the Town of <HI>Altena;</HI> de|claring
further, that if the Enemies make any new
Execution by Fire in the Dominions of the King his
Ma&s;ter, he will make u&s;e of all the Severities of
War in the Dutchy of <HI>Hol&s;tein,</HI> and other Coun|tries
belonging to his <HI>Dani&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty, by Right of
Repri&s;als, as he has done at <HI>Altena.</HI></P>
<P><PB N="375" REF="384">
BUT the Ravages of the <HI>Swedes</HI> grew near
an End; the <HI>Czar</HI> mov'd a pace with his Ar|my,
joyn'd by the <HI>Saxons,</HI> towards the <HI>Swedes;</HI>
the <HI>Danes</HI> joyn'd his Army in their March, with
what Troops they had, and all together amount|ed
to 36000 Men, which was too many for the
<HI>Swedes</HI> to pretend to grapple with; his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI>
Maje&s;ty arrived at <HI>Hamburgh,</HI> the 14th of <HI>Janua|ry,</HI>
attended by Prince <HI>Menzikoff,</HI> and &s;everal
Generals, as well of his own Troops, as of the
<HI>Dane</HI>'s and <HI>Saxon</HI>'s Army, which Coming on by
&s;low Marches, the Weather, and the Ways being
extreamly bad, the Soldiers &s;uffer'd very much
in their March.</P>
<P>WHILE his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty continued in the
Neighbourhood of <HI>Hamburgh,</HI> he cau&s;ed a Day of
Fa&s;ting and Publick Prayers to be proclaim'd in
the united Army, to ask of Heaven Succe&s;s up|on,
their Undertaking, and to add Alms Deeds
to their Devotion, his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty cau&s;ed
1000 Rubles in Gold to be di&s;tributed to the poor
Sufferers at <HI>Altena,</HI> and cau&s;ed Propo&s;als, and
Encouragement to be offer'd them, if any of them
thought fit to go Abroad, and would &s;ettle in
any part of his Dominions.</P>
<P>WHILE this was doing, Count <HI>Fleming,</HI> the
<HI>Saxon</HI> General, and General <HI>Scholten</HI> the <HI>Dani&s;h</HI>
V$lt Mari&s;chal, wrot an expo&s;tulatory Letter to
Count <HI>Welling,</HI> upon the Subject of the Burning
of <HI>Altena,</HI> and the Rea&s;ons alledg'd, which Let|ters
are as Follows.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="letter">
<PB N="376" REF="385">
<HEAD>A LETTER from Count Welling,
Governor General of the Dutchies of Bremen
and Werden, to Count Flemming, and Mon|&s;ieur
Scholten.</HEAD>
<OPENER>Me&s;&s;ieurs.</OPENER>
<P>SINCE you have done me the Honour to com|municate
to me the letter you have written to
Count <HI>Steinboch,</HI> concerning the Burning of
<HI>Altena,</HI> tho' without mentioning the Magazines that
were therein; &s;o I &s;uppo&s;e you de&s;ign'd thereby to
engage me to explain my &s;elf upon this Matter.</P>
<P>I don't know, Me&s;&s;ieurs, whether the Sight of the
De&s;truction of <HI>Staden</HI> has been more dreadful to you,
than that of the Burning of <HI>Altena;</HI> but it is cer|tain,
that the former might have been avoided, where|as
the latter was ab&s;olutely nece&s;&s;ary. The Rea&s;ons
that obliged Count <HI>Steinboch,</HI> tho' entirely again&s;t his
Will, to come to &s;uch Extremities, have already been
made Publick. If the red hot Bullets you threw into
<HI>Stral$und</HI> and <HI>Wi&s;inar,</HI> had had their Effect, and
burnt tho&s;e Towns as well as our Magazines therein,
the Rea&s;on of War would have ju&s;tify$d you, as well as
it now does Count <HI>Steinboch.</HI></P>
<P>But the many Flames that have been kindled, and
the dreadful Deva&s;tations of &s;everal of the King my
Ma&s;ter's Dominions, cannot find the &s;ame Ju&s;tifica|tion,
being committed without any manner of Nece&s;&s;i|ty,
by tho&s;e of your Allies, that you even call <HI>Chri|&s;tians.</HI></P>
<P>The <HI>Dani&s;h Zealand,</HI> and <HI>Saxony,</HI> will always be
an Evidence, that the <HI>Swedes</HI> never had recour&s;e to
Flambeaux, unle&s;s they were forced to the &s;ame, by
Rea&s;ons of War; but that our Nation, always u&s;ed
<PB N="377" REF="386">
to revenge them&s;elves upon their Enemies, by way of
Arms, and of&punc; Humanity, never with Burning, and
exerci&s;ing of Cruelties.</P>
<P>The dreadful Ruins &s;everal of his <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> Maje|&s;ty's
Provinces and Towns belonging thereunto, have
&s;uffer'd, and the Chains of Slavery under which a|bove
a hundred Thou&s;and of the King of <HI>Sweden</HI>'s
Subjects, of both Sexes, who have been &s;old to the In|fidels,
groan at this very Time, will, for the good of
your Ma&s;ter's Countries, prevail upon you, to concur
with Count <HI>Steinboch</HI> in making a more humain
War.</P>
<P>I have deliver'd to Colonel <HI>Meyer</HI> the Precau|tion
Count <HI>Steinboch</HI> has recommended to Mon|&s;ieur
<HI>Wibe,</HI> to be taken in this Matter; and I do
not at all doubt, but you will contribute thereto.
Count <HI>Steinboch</HI> has a&s;&s;ur'd me, that for his Part,
he will proceed not to any Extremity again&s;t the
Dutchy of <HI>Hol&s;tein,</HI> unle&s;s he be nece&s;&s;itated to it.</P>
<P>Your own Wi&s;dom, and the Rea&s;on of War, will
ju&s;tify his Conduct in &s;uch a Ca&s;e.</P>
<CLOSER>Hamburgh, Jan.
I am, <HI>&amp;c.</HI>
<SIGNED>WELLING.</SIGNED></CLOSER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="letter">
<HEAD>A LETTER from the Generals
Flamming and Scholten, to General Welling.</HEAD>
<OPENER><SALUTE>SIR,</SALUTE></OPENER>
<P>BY the Letter which you have done us the Ho|nour
to write to us, we have &s;een the Rea&s;ons
which you alledge for the Burning of <HI>Altena.</HI></P>
<P><PB N="378" REF="387">
We being Parties, will not take upon us to be Judges,
There are enough to decide it. Mean while, you will
allow us to tell you, there is no Compari&s;on between
what has been done at <HI>Altena,</HI> and what happen'd at
<HI>Staden. Staden</HI> is a fortify'd Town, which re&s;i&s;ted
the Arms of his <HI>Dani&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty, and again&s;t which,
it was allowable to u&s;e all the Means that are ordi|narily
taken to reduce a Town: But <HI>Altena</HI> is an
open defencele&s;s Place; and we believe, Sir, that a
Parallel can never be made, between a Bombardment
and the &s;etting a Town on Fire with Torches. 'Tis
as if the inevitable Slaughter in a Battle or an A&s;&s;ault,
&s;hould be compared with a Ma&s;&s;acre of People who
do not defend them&s;elves, nor are in a State of De|fence.</P>
<P>The other Rea&s;ons for the Burning of <HI>Altena,</HI>
that have been made Publick, amount to this, that
Magazines were providing, and Bread baking there;
but 'tis certain, there was no Magazines in <HI>Altena,</HI>
or if there were, they were &s;o incon&s;iderable, that
there could be no Pretence on that Account, for
burning above 2000 Hou&s;es, and reducing &s;everal
Thou&s;ands of People to Beggary; and this, without
gaining any Advantage by it. According to this
Allegation that there were Magazines, was not
th$ught of in the An&s;wer which Count <HI>Steinboch</HI>
made to the Deputies of <HI>Altena;</HI> nothing was then
urg'd, but the Affair of <HI>Staden,</HI> to which we think
we have given a &s;ufficient Reply.</P>
<P>As to the Burning Bullets fired into <HI>Stral&s;und</HI>
and <HI>Wi&s;mar,</HI> we refer to what we have &s;aid about
the Bombarding of <HI>Staden.</HI> This is lawful, but
voluntary Burnings are abhorred.</P>
<P>As to the Conduct of our Allies, we &s;uppo&s;e you
will allow a Di&s;tinction between cutrages committed
without Order, and tho&s;e committed by expre&s;s
<PB N="379" REF="388">
Order. Count <HI>Steinboch</HI> him&s;elf made that Di|&s;tinction
very ju&s;tly &s;ome Months ago, when &s;peaking
of &s;ome Di&s;orders done by the <HI>Mu&s;covite</HI> Soldiers,
<HI>he ask'd,</HI> whether they had been order'd to commit
them; and being a&s;&s;ured, that not only &s;uch Orders
had never been given, but that the Authors of tho&s;e
Exce&s;&s;es had been puni&s;h'd; <HI>he &s;aid,</HI> he was glad to
hear it, adding, that he could not treat tho&s;e who
&s;hould commit &s;uch Outrages by Order, and who &s;hould
fall into his Hands, as Pri&s;oners of War, but as In|cendaries.
What you can alledge farther of the Con|duct
of our <HI>Allies,</HI> may be ea&s;ily ju&s;tify'd by the Right
of Reprizals. Remember only, Sir, what was
practi&s;ed on our Side, after the Battle of <HI>Ne$rva.</HI>
Before that Time, had any &s;uch Cruelties been
acted?</P>
<P>Tho&s;e who were Authors of the Fir&s;t, are an&s;wer|able
for all that have been committed &s;ince. You
know, Sir, that there is no other Foundation of the
Law of Nations than Agreement and Example.
After the Precedent yo$ have newly &s;et us, it will
be lawful for our Ma&s;ters to retaliate others upon
you, of what kind &s;oever, and this by the Law of
Nations.</P>
<P>In our Opinion the <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> Moderation in <HI>Zealand</HI>
ought not to be alledged on this Occa&s;ion, for the
King your Ma&s;ter not having landed there as an
Enemy, but as a Guarantee of Peace, could not exerci&s;e
Acts of Ho&s;tility there.</P>
<P>As for <HI>Saxony,</HI> your Intere&s;t had a greater Share
in your Humanity, than Humanity it &s;elf. With the
23 Millions which you drew from <HI>Saxony,</HI> it might
have been re&s;tored to its former State, had it been
all laid in A&s;hes. And how otherwi&s;e could you
have cloathed, recruited and remounted your Army.</P>
<P><PB N="380" REF="389">
Be this as it will, tho&s;e two Examples prove
however, that Burnings and Acts of Inhuma|nity,
are more authoriz'd by the Mini&s;ters and Ge|nerals
of the King of <HI>Sweden,</HI> than by that Prince
him&s;elf.</P>
<P>We have reply'd to the Example which you al|ledged
of the Ruin of &s;everal of your Provinces;
but we cannot apprehend what you mean by advi&s;ing
us to concur with Count <HI>Steinboch</HI> in carrying on the
War humanly, after the Example of Inhumanity and
Cruelty, which he has newly given us: A Cruelty,
that has co&s;t the Lives of &s;o many poor Innocents, of
Women in Childbed and in Labour, of Sick who were
not in a Condition to get out of Bed. How many
Children and Aged &s;natch'd from the Violence of
the Flames, were unable to endure the Extremi|ty
of the Cold, and peri&s;hed mi&s;erably in the
Snow?</P>
<P>How many unhappy Wretches of both Sexes and
all Ages, expo&s;ed to the Rigour of the Sea&s;on,
peri&s;h daily of Cold and Hunger? Are the&s;e the
In&s;tances of Humanity which Count <HI>Steinboch</HI> would
have us Imitate? Can we make such a Propo&s;ition
to our Ma&s;ters?</P>
<P>We have &s;een the Letter which Count <HI>Steinboch</HI>
wrote to Mon&s;ieur <HI>Wibe,</HI> we will &s;u&s;pend our Judg|ment
on it; bnt know that Threats work nothing
upon the Per&s;ons who are ju&s;t, and of generous Minds,
&s;uch as are in the Court of the King of <HI>Denmark.</HI>
We conclude, by &s;aying, that you can never ju&s;tify
the Burning of <HI>Altena;</HI> but it will Ju&s;tify all that
we may attempt for taking true Vengeance, if our
Augu&s;t Ma&s;ters, agreeably to their u&s;ual Humanity and
$word$, do not think fit to defer the imitating
&s;o cruel an Example, unle&s;s they are forced to it by
new Cruelties of the like Nature: We are a&s;&s;ured in
<PB N="381" REF="390">
the mean while, that the Almighty mill not let pa&s;ts
without Puni&s;hment, the unheard of Cruelties that
have been practi&s;ed at <HI>Alten.</HI></P>
<CLOSER><DATELINE>Hamburgh,
<DATE>Jan. 13, 1713.</DATE></DATELINE>
We are, <HI>&amp;c.</HI>
<SIGNED><LIST>
<ITEM>FLEMMING.</ITEM>
<ITEM>SCHOLTEN.</ITEM>
</LIST></SIGNED></CLOSER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2>
<P>AFTER all that has been &s;aid, of the Civility
of the <HI>Turks</HI> to the <HI>Czar,</HI> and to his Mini&s;ters,
&s;uch was the uncertainty of Things, on that Side
the World, that in the mid&s;t of the Proceedings of
the <HI>Czar,</HI> in &s;o remote a Part of the World, his
<HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty was again allarm'd with the Ru|mour
that his Amba&s;&s;ador at <HI>Cou&s;tantinople</HI> was a|gain
impri&s;oned in the <HI>Seven Towers,</HI> and that the
<HI>Turks</HI> had declared War again again&s;t him; and
he was earne&s;tly pre&s;s'd by his Generals to leave
this Petty Retail War, (<HI>as they called it</HI>) and ad|vance
to the Frontiers of <HI>Tartary,</HI> to prepare to
oppo&s;e the <HI>Turks.</HI></P>
<P>HOWEVER as his Maje&s;ty had better Intelli|gence
than his Enemies in the <HI>Ottoman Port,</HI> he
was always appriz'd of things as they really were
reported to be, and knew very well how far they
were True, and how far not. The <HI>Turks</HI> were
for awhile much influenc'd by the Han of <HI>Tartary,</HI>
and the Creatures of the King of <HI>Sweden;</HI> 'twas a
little hard that the King of <HI>Sweden</HI> &s;hould be able
to bribe the <HI>Turks</HI> with their own Money, and
di&s;tribute the &s;ame Sums, which the <HI>Port</HI> gave
him for his Support, to the great Officers of the
&s;ame <HI>Port,</HI> to engage them to break Faith with
the <HI>Czar</HI> of <HI>Mu&s;covy,</HI> after he had perform'd all
that was required by their la&s;t Treaty; had re|&s;tor'd
<PB N="382" REF="391">
<HI>A&s;oph,</HI> had di&s;mantled <HI>Ka&s;&s;irkameen,</HI> and
the other Places, and fully withdrawn his Troops
out of <HI>Poland.</HI></P>
<P>BUT the <HI>Czar</HI> was too many for them here too,
for his Mini&s;ters at the <HI>Port</HI> having Power given
them to enter upon a new Treaty, and the
<HI>Czar</HI> cau&s;ing about 70000 Men to advance to the
Frontiers of <HI>Moldavia,</HI> to let the <HI>Turks</HI> &s;ee he
was not unprovided; the <HI>Ru&s;&s;ian</HI> Mini&s;ters found
it much ea&s;ier to reconcile Matters with the <HI>Port,</HI>
than was imagin'd, and the old League was not
only renew'd for 30 Years, but other Terms were
gain'd, which made as much for his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje|&s;ty's
Intere&s;t as could be de&s;ir'd.</P>
<P>ALL this while his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty was at the
Head of the Confederate Army in <HI>Hol&s;tein,</HI> pu&s;h|ing
the <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> Army under Count <HI>Steinboch;</HI> his
Maje&s;ty had, indeed, determin'd to leave the
Army, and return to his own Dominions, and
the rather, becau&s;e of the Mi&s;chief which he knew
was breeding at <HI>Con&s;tantinople,</HI> by the Intreagues
of the King of <HI>Sweden;</HI> but knowing the Mi&s;un|under&s;tandings
in the Confederate Army
would be &s;uch, about the Command, that there
would be no Agreement; and it being hard, that
the Army, two Thirds of which were at the &s;ame
Time his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty's own Forces, &s;hould be
Commanded by any but his own Generals; up|on
this Con&s;ideration, he re&s;olv'd to manage
the other Part by Negotiation, and to Command
the Army in <HI>Hol&s;tein</HI> him&s;elf.</P>
<P>THE Confederates were, as things then &s;tood,
much too &s;trong for Count <HI>Steinboch;</HI> their Force
was above 36000 Men, the <HI>Swedes</HI> nor above
14000 at be&s;t, but led by an old Fox that knew
his Advantages, and how to lay hold of them, to
<PB N="383" REF="392">
a Tittle; that knew how to fight when he had a
feir Field, and how to avoid it, when he was out
Number'd and not in Condition.</P>
<P>THIS, Count <HI>Steinboch</HI> &s;eeing the Confederates
advance, and that they were too powerful for
him, march'd from <HI>Altena,</HI> North into <HI>Upper Hol|&s;tein,</HI>
and advancing along the <HI>Eyder&s;torm,</HI> kept the
Confederates at Bay a great while, about <HI>Fred|rick&s;tand,</HI>
near which Place they pa&s;s'd the &s;aid
River <HI>Eyder,</HI> and advanc'd to <HI>Oerfield,</HI> and to
<HI>Hu&s;um:</HI> Here they laid the Country under Con|tribution,
and rai&s;ed a very great Sum in Mo|ney,
and Provi&s;ions: Here Count <HI>Steinboch</HI> po&s;t|ed
him&s;elf to &s;o much Advantage among the Ri|vers
and Dikes, that it was not ea&s;y to attack
him.</P>
<P>BUT his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty re&s;olv'd to make
&s;hort Work with him, and in a Word, to attack
him, where-ever he could find him, co&s;t what it
would; for as I noted above, the <HI>Czar</HI> at this
Time, was pre&s;s'd by his own Affairs, not know|ing
whether his Affairs with the <HI>Turks</HI> would
End in Peace or War; Orders were therefore gi|ven
to make Di&s;po&s;itions for the Attack, while
the <HI>Swedes</HI> on the other Hand, fortify'd their
Camp, and made an Appearance of Re&s;i&s;tance,
threatening to give the <HI>Ru&s;&s;ians</HI> a very warm Re|ception.
But Count <HI>Steinboch,</HI> after repul&s;ing our
Men at the Attack of one of his Po&s;ts, where the
<HI>Ru&s;&s;ians</HI> and <HI>Danes</HI> had &s;ome Lo&s;s, thought fit
not to &s;tand the Shock of a general Attack by
the whole Army; and accordingly, quitted the
advantagious Camp, and retired to another, and
thus retiring from one Po&s;t to another, and the
Confederates &s;till following him Clo&s;e, and pu&s;h|ing
<PB N="384" REF="393">
him from Place to Place, he begun to be
brought to Extremity.</P>
<P>THE be&s;t Account of the&s;e &s;everal Motions
leave them very uncertain, and are &s;carce worth
our collecting; the &s;hort of the Matter is, that
the Confederates attack'd the <HI>Swedes</HI> at <HI>Holling|&s;tede,</HI>
but were repul&s;ed with the Lo&s;s of 300
Men; and the next Night the <HI>Swedes</HI> retired, and
po&s;ted their whole Army in a very &s;trong Situa|tion,
between <HI>Fredrick&s;tadt,</HI> and the Fortre&s;s of
<HI>Toningen.</HI> This la&s;t was a very &s;trong Place, be|longing
to the Duke of <HI>Hol&s;tein,</HI> and Garri&s;on'd
by his Troops, who being in <HI>Sweden,</HI> a Youth,
and under Age, the Admini&s;tration of his E&s;tates,
was left to the Care of his Uncle, the Prince
and Bi&s;hop of <HI>E$tin.</HI></P>
<P>THE Governor of this Fortre&s;s made Show of
keeping an exact Neutrality; and once, when
Count <HI>Steinboch</HI> &s;ent a Letter to him, &s;ent it un|open'd,
refu&s;ing to receive any Letter or Me&s;&s;a|ges
on either Side; and while Matters &s;tood thus,
Count <HI>Steinboch</HI> &s;tood but in very ill Terms,
being &s;treighten'd for Room, and al&s;o for Provi|&s;ions,
and almo&s;t &s;urrounded by the Confedorate
Armies, who were &s;o much &s;uperior.</P>
<P>IN this Po&s;ture the Confederates pre&s;s'd him
very hard; and tho' he avoided Fighting, and
retir'd from one Po&s;t to another, yet it was
apparent he mu&s;t at la&s;t Fight to his inevi|table
De&s;truction, or &s;u$$ender to his Ene|m$es.</P>
<P>HE defended him&s;elf, however, in this Man|ner
a long time, <HI>viz.</HI> from the Beginning of
<HI>January,</HI> till the 14th of <HI>February,</HI> 1712$ 13. In
vain pr$$ing the Governor of <HI>Tonnighen</HI> to give
him a Retreat into the Fortre&s;s, and being
<PB N="385" REF="394">
pu&s;h'd to Extremity by the Confederates, he
came with the whole <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> Army and encamp|ed
at <HI>Gardenghen,</HI> a Village, within half a League
of <HI>Toningen.</HI></P>
<P>THE Confederates follow'd him Clo&s;e, and
here the Governor of <HI>Toningmen,</HI> whether by
Order of the Prince Admini&s;trator of <HI>Hol&s;tein,</HI> or
by Stratagem of Count <HI>Steinboch,</HI> is very little
known to this Day: But the Governor, <HI>I &s;ay,</HI>
let the <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> General, and with him, his whole
Army, into the Place, to the great Relief and
Encouragement of the <HI>Swedes,</HI> who were, indeed,
brought to the Point of being ruin'd.</P>
<P>THIS was a Blow to the Confederates who had
been extreamly fateigu'd with the Service they
had been upon, having kept in the Field all the
<HI>Winter:</HI> The Matter was now come to a Point,
there was now no way left now to force them,
and nothing but a very clo&s;e Blockade, could
Effect their Reduction, and this the Army a|greed
on.</P>
<P>THE <HI>Czar</HI> finding now that the Thing would
be drawn out in Length, left the Army and went
to <HI>Hamburgh;</HI> and from thence, to <HI>Hanover.</HI> His
<HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty left the Army the 15th of <HI>Fe|bruary,</HI>
having fir&s;t had a long Conference with
the Kings of <HI>Denmark,</HI> where the Command of
the Army was &s;ettled, and the Rank of the
Troops, and every thing needful to carry on the
De&s;ign; for having Count <HI>Steinboch</HI> and the
<HI>Swedes</HI> in &s;o clo&s;e a Place, it was certain, they
ought not to let them go off, co&s;t what it would.</P>
<P>THE <HI>Czar</HI> having now left the Army, had &s;e|veral
private Affairs in Hand, as particularly, at
<HI>Wolfembotle,</HI> where he made &s;ome Stay, in order to
reconcile things between the Prince&s;s of <HI>Ru&s;&s;ia,</HI>
<PB N="386" REF="395">
his Daughter-in-Law, and her Husband, the
<HI>Czarowitz,</HI> or Hereditary Prince, who, it &s;eems
had had &s;ome Difference with the Prince&s;s, his
Spou&s;e, of which we &s;hall hear farther.</P>
<P>FROM <HI>Wolfenbuttel,</HI> the <HI>Czar</HI> went to <HI>Magde|burg,</HI>
and thence to <HI>Schoonho&s;en</HI> near <HI>Berlin,</HI> where
he had an Interview with the King of <HI>Pru&s;&s;ia,</HI>
and where his <HI>Pru&s;&s;ian</HI> Maje&s;ty entertain'd him
with the utmo&s;t Magnificence. This was the
10th of <HI>March,</HI> the next Day, the two illu&s;trious
Monarchs dined together; and the <HI>Czar</HI> having
abu$dance of Rea&s;on to be very well &s;atisfy'd
with his Reception, parted the &s;ame Afternoon
for <HI>Dantzick</HI> in his way to <HI>Livonia.</HI></P>
<P>WHAT was made Publick at this Time of his
<HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty's Journey, &s;eems to have Truth
in it, being writen from <HI>Dantzick,</HI> after the <HI>Czar</HI>'s
Arrival there as follows, <HI>viz</HI></P>
<P>THE Court of <HI>Wolfenbuttel</HI> is highly &s;atisfy'd
with the <HI>Czar</HI> of <HI>Mu&s;covy,</HI> and the Prince&s;s, Wife
to the Hereditary Prince, &s;et out the 16th of
<HI>March</HI> under the Di&s;charge of the Cannon for
<HI>Petersburg</HI> by the way of <HI>Berlin</HI> and <HI>Dantzick.</HI>
The <HI>Czar</HI> pre&s;ented her with a great Sum of Mo|ney
for the Charges of her Journey; and at the
&s;ame time a&s;&s;ur'd her, that &s;he &s;hould be u&s;ed
with &s;o much Re&s;pect in <HI>Mu&s;covy,</HI> that he did not
que&s;tion but &s;he would ea&s;ily forget <HI>Germany.</HI>
That Prince made con&s;iderable Pre&s;ents to the
Mother of that Prince&s;s, and among&s;t other
Things, pre&s;ented her with his Picture &s;et with
Diamonds, of a con&s;iderable Value. The Court
of <HI>Mu&s;covy</HI> is to continue at <HI>Petersburg</HI> for &s;ome
Time, and &s;ome Grandees of the Retinue of the
<HI>Czar,</HI> report, that that Prince intends to make
that Place the Seat of his Empire, and 20000
<PB N="387" REF="396">
Per&s;ons are remov'd thither from <HI>Mo&s;cow.</HI> His
<HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty de&s;igns to have at Sea this <HI>Sum|mer</HI>
a Squadron of his own Ships, and be&s;ides tho&s;e
that have been built in his own Harbours, he has
bought &s;everal Frigats at <HI>Dunkirk,</HI> and in <HI>Holland,</HI>
which are to be man'd and fitted out at <HI>Copen|hagen,</HI>
to act in Conjunction with the <HI>Dani&s;h</HI>
Fleet under the Command of Vice Admiral
<HI>Cruitz.</HI> Thus far this Account.</P>
<P>WHILE the&s;e things were doing, the <HI>Czar</HI>'s
Troops kept their Footing in <HI>Pomerania,</HI> and a
great Part of the Town of <HI>Wolga&s;t</HI> refusing to
pay their Contributions, was burnt by the
<HI>Ru&s;&s;ian</HI> General's Order. But the Attack of
<HI>Stral&s;und</HI> or <HI>Stetin,</HI> was not thought proper to be
undertaken 'till the <HI>Swedes</HI> in <HI>Hol&s;tein</HI> were en|tirely
reduc'd, which were yet a Work of Diffi|culty.</P>
<P>THIS Year his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty's Queen, or
rather Empre&s;s, tho' they call'd her in <HI>Mu&s;covy</HI>
by neither of tho&s;e Stiles, but that of <HI>Czarina,</HI>
was deliver'd of a Daughter, or Prince&s;s; this
happen'd very much to his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty's Sa|tisfaction,
ju&s;t after his Arrival at <HI>Petersburg.</HI>
This Prince&s;s was baptized a few Days after, ac|cording
to the Rites of the <HI>Greek</HI> Church, and
named, <HI>Maria Petra Witza.</HI></P>
<P>ALL this while the Preparations again&s;t the
<HI>Turks</HI> went on as before, the <HI>Ru&s;&s;ian</HI> Court not yet
knowing what the un&s;ettled Di&s;po&s;itions of the
<HI>Ottoman</HI> Court might i&s;&s;ue in; and his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI>
Maje&s;ty, that his Enemies might not flatter
them&s;elves with Hopes of taking him at the &s;ame
Advantage they did before, <HI>viz.</HI> to be &s;urround|ed
with their <HI>Tartars,</HI> to cut off his Provi&s;ions, or
to be betray'd by the <HI>Moldavians,</HI> who had under|taken
<PB N="388" REF="397">
to &s;upply the Army, <HI>I &s;ay,</HI> of take from his
Enemies all Expectations of that kind; his Maje|&s;ty
cau&s;ed three large Forts to be erected upon the
Banks of the <HI>Dnie&s;ter,</HI> and two Bridges of Com|munication
to be laid over the River; and here
he laid up, and re&s;olv'd to lay up Stores of Corn,
and Forrage, with Meal, and an infinite Quanti|ty
of other Provi&s;ions, &s;ufficient for his whole
Army; re&s;olving al&s;o, if he advanc'd into <HI>Mol|davia,</HI>
to build two &s;trong Forts; one at an impor|tant
Pa&s;s, in the Way to the <HI>Pruth;</HI> and another,
on the Bank of the <HI>Pruth;</HI> to &s;ecure his Convoys
and Provi&s;ions from the <HI>Tartars:</HI> In this Po&s;ture
the <HI>Turks</HI> found Things when they held their
great <HI>Divan,</HI> or Council, to conclude, whether
they &s;hould break with the <HI>Ru&s;&s;ians,</HI> or, no:
Their &s;eeing the <HI>Czar,</HI> in &s;uch a formidable Po|&s;ture,
contributed not a little to cool their
Warmth for a War, and to adhere to the wi&s;er
Councils of Peace, as we &s;hall hear pre&s;ently.</P>
<P>BUT to come back to <HI>Hol&s;tein,</HI> where the War
was now near a Clo&s;e, the <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> Army being at
length forc'd by the Confederates to quit their
Intrenchments and Fa&s;tne&s;&s;es they had made, and
retire into <HI>Tonningben,</HI> where they were reduced
to Extremity for want of Provi&s;ions, and the
<HI>Danes</HI> and <HI>Ru&s;&s;ians</HI> re&s;olving to attack them in
Form, and force them out of that Fortre&s;s Sword
in Hand, General Count <HI>Steinbock</HI> was forced to
Capitulate; &s;everal Treaties and Offers had been
made on one Side and other, which came to no|thing:
But on the 16th of <HI>May,</HI> the whole Mat|ter
was agreed on, and an End put to that War.
The Terms of this Capitulation, as it was call'd,
was as follows, <HI>viz.</HI></P>
<LIST>
<PB N="389" REF="398">
<ITEM><HI>I.</HI> THAT the whole <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> Army under Count
<HI>Steinboch,</HI> in the Territory of <HI>Eyder&s;tadt,</HI>
and in <HI>Tonningen,</HI> &s;hall &s;urrender with their
Commanders in Chief, Generals, Officers, Volun|teers,
and private Soldiers, to the King of <HI>Den|mark:</HI>
That all the General and chief Officers, to|gether
with the Volunteers, &s;hall keep all their Arms,
Baggage, Writings, Field Che&s;t; and every thing
thereto belonging, without being plunder'd. The
Subaltern Officers and Soldiers &s;hall keep only their
Swords and Cloaths; the Cannon, Fire Arms, as
al&s;o the Hor&s;es of the Troopers, Dragoons and Ar|tillery,
and what more belongs to the Military Ser|vice,
none of which &s;hall be &s;poil'd or made away
with, &s;hall be left behind, and after the March out
of <HI>Tonningen</HI> be given up at <HI>Heyer&s;worth,</HI> with
all the Colours, Standards, and Drums. The March
from <HI>Tonningen</HI> &s;hall be within three Days after
the &s;igning of the Capitulation, and &s;hall be com|pleated
in eight: The Rout for marching, and the
Quarters, &s;hall be &s;ettled by the <HI>Dani&s;h</HI> Commi&s;&s;a|ries
of War.</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>II.</HI> The Tran&s;porting the <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> Troops, when
they &s;hall be exchang'd or ran&s;om'd, &s;hall be to no
other Parts than to <HI>Sweden,</HI> at their own Charge:
They them&s;elves &s;hall pro$ide the Ve&s;&s;els for that
Purpo&s;e, the King of <HI>Denmark</HI> &s;hall furni&s;h Pa&s;|ports
to tho&s;e Ve&s;&s;els; and they may make U&s;e of
<HI>Dani&s;h</HI> and <HI>Hol&s;tein</HI> Ve&s;&s;els if they can be had
voluntarily for Hire.</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>III.</HI> The Swedi&s;h National Troops &s;hall no the &s;epa|rated
from the <HI>Germans,</HI> but be tran&s;ported to
<HI>Sweden</HI> together.</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>IV.</HI> The Tran&s;portation &s;hall be immediately after the
exchanging or ran&s;oming.</ITEM>
<ITEM><PB N="390" REF="399">
<HI>V.</HI> The <HI>Swedes</HI> &s;hall on their re&s;ting Day in their
March have free Lodging, but buy their Provi&s;ions
them&s;elves.</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>VI.</HI> The <HI>Danes</HI> or their <HI>Allies,</HI> who have been made
Pri&s;oners, and have &s;ince taken Service among the
<HI>Swedes,</HI> as al&s;o the De&s;erters, &s;hall be &s;topt; but
if the voluntarily return to their former Regiments,
they &s;hall be pardon'd.</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>VII.</HI> Of the <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> Troops, none &s;hall be forc'd into
and detain'd in Service, except Di&s;erters.</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>VIII.</HI> The Baggage of the Generals, chief Officers
and Volunteers, mention'd in the fir&s;t Article, &s;hall
be tran&s;ported to <HI>Sweden,</HI> or el&s;ewhere, un&s;earch'd
and free.</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>IX.</HI> The March out shall be by Brigades, which shall
be conducted by Commi&s;&s;aries, and be furni&s;h'd with
Provi&s;ions, the <HI>Swedes</HI> paying for it.</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>X.</HI> The Troops &s;hall march three Days, and re&s;t the
forth; and Waggons &s;hall be provided for tho&s;e who
&s;hall fall &s;ick on the Way.</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>XI.</HI> The Sick now in Tonningen, &s;hall be removed in|to
the <HI>Eyder&s;tad,</HI> till they are recover'd, at their
own Expence.</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>XII.</HI> The Mounting and Cloaths, which lie at <HI>Lubeck</HI>
and <HI>Hamburgh</HI> for the <HI>Swedes,</HI> and are paid for,
&s;hall be carry'd free to <HI>Sweden</HI> with Pa&s;ports.</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>XIII.</HI> All <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> Officers who are Pri&s;oners in <HI>Den|mark,
Hol&s;tein, Hamburgh,</HI> or el&s;ewhere, &s;hall
after the Cartel is &s;atisfy'd, be permitted to repair
to their re&s;pective Regiments.</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>XIV.</HI> The <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> Officers, who on Account of Sick|ne&s;s
or Wounds have been left at <HI>Lubeck, Ham|burgh,</HI>
or <HI>Wi&s;mar,</HI> &s;hall be tran&s;ported free with
Pa&s;&s;ports where ever they plea&s;e.</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>XV.</HI> So &s;hall their Baggage, and other Things.</ITEM>
<ITEM><PB N="391" REF="400">
<HI>XVI.</HI> For the Convoy of the <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> Troops to <HI>Swe|den,</HI>
two or three Frigots &s;hall be granted; the Tran|&s;portation
&s;hall be to <HI>Carel&s;croon, Carel&s;haven,
Cimber&s;haven,</HI> or <HI>Y&s;tedt;</HI> and if in the Pa&s;&s;age
any Ships be by &s;tre&s;s of Weather driven to the <HI>Da|ni&s;h</HI>
Coa&s;t, they &s;hall not be &s;eized again and detaind.</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>XVII.</HI> On the Part of the <HI>Danes</HI> a Phy&s;ician and
Surgeon &s;hall go into <HI>Tonningen</HI>&punc; to take Infor|mation
of the Sick; as al&s;o &s;ome Commi&s;&s;aries, to
take a Li&s;t of the Hor&s;es and other Things.</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>XVIII.</HI> The <HI>Swedes</HI> oblige them&s;elves to &s;et at
Liberty, pur&s;uant to the Cartel, the Pri&s;oners
taken frem the <HI>Northern Allies,</HI> and kept in
the <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> Provinces in <HI>Germany;</HI> and Count
<HI>Steinboch</HI> promi&s;es to u&s;e his be&s;t Endeavours that
the Pri&s;oners kept in <HI>Sweden</HI> may be di&s;charg'd
likewi&s;e.</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>XIX.</HI> The King of <HI>Denmark</HI> promi&s;es, that he will
not Bombard <HI>Tonningen</HI> this Year, and the Tren|ches
and Batteries which the <HI>Danes</HI> have made be|fore
the Place, &s;hall be levelled by the <HI>Swedes</HI> on
their marching out.</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>XX.</HI> The <HI>Swedes</HI> &s;hall be allow'd to de&s;ire the Guarn|ty
of other Potentates of the pre&s;ent Capitulation
Granted them; but their March out &s;hall not on
that account be delay'd.</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>XXI.</HI> The King of <HI>Denmark</HI> engages to perform all
that is above &s;tipulated, and to procure the Concur|ence
of the Commanders of the Armies of the <HI>Allies.</HI></ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>XXII.</HI> Two Copies of this Agreement &s;hall be made, to
be exchang'd again&s;t each other. Done and con|cluded
at <HI>Olden&s;worth,</HI> the 16th of <HI>May,</HI> 1713.</ITEM>
</LIST>
<CLOSER><SIGNED>Sign'd,
<LIST>
<ITEM>G. Roynbolt Patkull,</ITEM>
<ITEM>Carl. Mellin,</ITEM>
<ITEM>G. C. Stramfeldt.</ITEM>
<ITEM>Schwaudlodh</ITEM>
</LIST></SIGNED></CLOSER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2>
<PB N="392" REF="401">
<P>THIS Affair being thus concluded Prince <HI>Men|zikoff,</HI>
and the other <HI>Ru&s;&s;ian</HI> Generals prepared to
bring away the Army, and put them into Quar|ters
of Refre&s;hment, after &s;o &s;evere a Campaign,
which had la&s;ted now from the beginning of <HI>De|cember,</HI>
to the middle of <HI>May.</HI></P>
<P>ON the 4th of <HI>June,</HI> the <HI>Mu&s;covite</HI> Forces
march'd from their Camp with their Quota of the
<HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> Pri&s;oners Colours and Cannon: This Pro|portion,
or Quota was thus &s;tated, and agreed a|mong
the Generals of all Sides; the whole was
divided into five equal Parts, of which the <HI>Ru&s;&s;ians</HI>
had two Fifths, the <HI>Danes</HI> two, and the <HI>Saxons</HI> one,
and upon this Divi&s;ion, Prince <HI>Menzikoff</HI> &s;ent to
his Camp 47 <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> Colours, 27 Standards, 3
pair of Kettle Drums, and 6 Pieces of Cannon;
with the&s;e the Troops decamp'd, and march'd to|wards
the <HI>Trave;</HI> but the Prince <HI>Menzikoff</HI> then
went to <HI>Hamburgh,</HI> where he re&s;olv'd to humble
the City for &s;ome In&s;olences they had &s;uffer'd to
be put up on the <HI>Ru&s;&s;ians,</HI> and their Affairs; where|upon
he demanded 500000 Rixdollars of them,
and to give the more vigour to his demand, he
mark'd out a Camp for 15000 Men in their Ter|ritories,
he order'd the Troops to approach, as if
he intended really to attack them.</P>
<P>THE ju&s;t Pretentions the Prince had to be of|fended
at the Conduct of the <HI>Hamburghers</HI> were
&s;ent them in a Letter, and are to the Purpo&s;e
following.</P>
<LIST>
<ITEM>I. &startq;THAT &s;ome Years &s;ince they have print|ed
in this City fal&s;e Reports reflect|ing
on the Honour of his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty, and
that upon Complaint thereof, the Magi&s;trates
<PB N="393" REF="402">
have refu&s;ed to deliver up the Authors of the
&s;ame.&endq;</ITEM>
<ITEM>II. THAT the Sieur <HI>Vosbein,</HI> Director of Com|merce
&startq;for <HI>Mu&s;covy,</HI> was arre&s;ted and kept
Pri&s;oner, till he was relea&s;ed by giving Bail,
whereby he &s;u&s;tain'd a Damage, amounting
to above 100000 Florins, tho' he was known
to be under the Protection of the <HI>Czar.</HI>&endq;</ITEM>
<ITEM>III. &startq;THAT in the Year 1700, 20000 Fire Arms
belonging to that Prince, were betrayed by
the <HI>Hamburghers</HI> to the <HI>Swedes.</HI>&endq;</ITEM>
<ITEM>IV. &startq;THAT an Officer of the <HI>Czar</HI> coming
through <HI>Hamburgh,</HI> was &s;uffer'd to be plunder'd
at one of the Gates by the Officers of the
Cu&s;tom Hou&s;e, in &s;ight of the Guards.&endq;</ITEM>
<ITEM>V. &startq;THAT the Baron <HI>de Lewenwodle,</HI> Adjutant
General of the <HI>Mu&s;covite</HI> Army was lately af|fronted
in a mo&s;t &s;candalous manner at the
Gate of <HI>Altena,</HI> which the &s;aid Prince <HI>Menzi|koff</HI>
declares, that his Ma&s;ter expects a &s;uita|ble
Satisfaction.&endq;</ITEM>
</LIST>
<P>HIS <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty, who never Sleeps upon
the Enterprizes he has in View was at this time,
at <HI>Petersburgh,</HI> as is ob&s;erv'd above, and had the
&s;atisfaction in one Day to receive an Account
from <HI>Con&s;tantinople,</HI> the hopes his Mini&s;ters there
had of renewing the Peace with the <HI>Turks,</HI>
and from <HI>Hamburgh,</HI> of the Surrender of Count
<HI>Steinboch,</HI> and the whole <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> Army at <HI>Ton|ningen.</HI></P>
<P>THO' this did not ha&s;ten his Preparations for
his other De&s;igns, which he was re&s;olved to
have pu&s;h'd, tho' his Enemies had not made
Peace in <HI>Turky,</HI> or had not been reduc'd in <HI>Hol|&s;tein,</HI>
yet it added this to it, that he was now at
<PB N="394" REF="403">
Lei&s;ure to appear at the Head of his Army, and
on Board his Fleet for an Expedition again&s;t the
<HI>Swedes</HI> in <HI>Finland.</HI></P>
<P>THIS was the Enterprize, and it was not an
Undertaking of &s;mall Con&s;equence for could
he but reduce this Province, the <HI>Swedes</HI> would be
entirely driven not only out of the Gulph of <HI>Nar|va,</HI>
and the great Gulph of <HI>Finland,</HI> but even
out of the_Gulph of <HI>Bothnia;</HI> for if <HI>Finland</HI> was
once taken, the Ea&s;tern <HI>Bothina</HI> would fall of Cour&s;e.</P>
<P>IT was for this Rea&s;on, that his Maje&s;ty pre|par'd
&s;o con&s;iderable a Force for this Conque&s;t.
The <HI>Czar</HI> &s;ail'd the 19th from <HI>Petersburgh,</HI> with
with a Fleet of 20 Men of War 100 Gallies, and
200 Tran&s;port Ships, having on Board 18000 Foot,
with a Train of Artillery, as well of heavy Can|non
and Mortars, as of Field peices with a great
Magazine of all &s;orts of Stores of War directing,
his Cour&s;e &s;trait for <HI>Abo</HI> in <HI>Finland;</HI> the Cavalry,
con&s;i&s;ting of 9000 Hor&s;e, and Dragoons were or|der'd
to march by Land to meet the Army at
their coming on Shoar: The Hereditary Prince of
<HI>Ru&s;&s;ia</HI> al&s;o attended his Father the <HI>Czar</HI> in this
Expedition.</P>
<P>HIS <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty went on this attempt, as
to a certain Conque&s;t, for the Affairs of the <HI>Swedes</HI>
were at this time at &s;o low an Ebb, and the Nation
of <HI>Swedland</HI> under &s;uch di&s;couragements, that they
were in no Condition to repul&s;e him, or defend
them&s;elves; he therefore carried with him a Mani|fe&s;to
to be publi&s;hed at his Landing, to a&s;&s;ure the
Inhabitants, prevent their flying from their Ha|bitations,
and promi&s;ing them all po&s;&s;ible good
U&s;age, and that the Army &s;hould not Plunder,
but ob&s;erve good Di&s;cipline, and pay punctally
<PB N="395" REF="404">
for all the Provi&s;ions they took of them over and
above the ordinary Contributions, <HI>&amp;c.</HI></P>
<P>IT is not to be wondered at, if this Expedition
put the whole Kingdom of <HI>Swedeland</HI> into a ter|rible
Con&s;ternation, for &s;eeing the great Prepa|ration
making for a De&s;cent, and &s;o great an Army
embark'd, the Senate and Governors of <HI>Swedeland</HI>
made no Que&s;tion, but that it was de&s;igned again&s;t
the Capital of the Kingdom, and Con&s;equently
was a blow at the Root in order to &s;ubvert the
whole Government, and make an entire Conque&s;t
of <HI>Sweden</HI> it &s;elf, which as things then &s;tood, had
been no difficult thing for his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty to
have done: This alarm however, they had really
no Cau&s;e, for yet the Fright, had this good Effect,
that the Governor of <HI>Sweden</HI> drawing all the
&s;trength of the Kingdom together for the Defence
of the Coa&s;t about <HI>Stockholm,</HI> and the Coa&s;t of we&s;t
<HI>Gothia,</HI> between <HI>Stockholm</HI> and <HI>Um,</HI> and between
<HI>Stockholm</HI> and <HI>Carel&s;croon;</HI> &s;o they left the Province,
and Coa&s;t of <HI>Finland,</HI> whether the true de&s;ign of
the <HI>Czar</HI> was pointed quite unguarded, and in a
manner neglected, not that they forgot the need|ful
Care of it, but that being anxious to pre&s;erve
the Heart, or Main of the Kingdom of <HI>Sweden,</HI> they
had not Troops to &s;pare for the &s;uccour of the re|moter
Provinces, where the Danger indeed only
lay.</P>
<P>THIS gave his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty an ea&s;ie Con|que&s;t
of <HI>Finland,</HI> where he Landed his Army
without any con&s;iderable oppo&s;ition: He Landed
at <HI>He&s;ingsford,</HI> a &s;mall Port Town, which the <HI>Swe|di&s;h</HI>
Garri&s;on not being in Condition to defend,
&s;et on fire, and retired towards <HI>Abbo,</HI> where the
<HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> General <HI>Arenfield,</HI> who had the com|mand
of the Troops left for the Defence of that
<PB N="396" REF="405">
Province, drew all his Forces together to make
Head again&s;t the <HI>Ru&s;&s;ians,</HI> and had advanc'd to
<HI>Borgo,</HI> a &s;trong Pa&s;s, which he pretended to de|fend;
but we &s;hall afterwards &s;ee how well they
maintain'd them&s;elves there.</P>
<P>IN the mean time we mu&s;t ca&s;t back our Eyes
to Prince <HI>Menzikoff,</HI> and the <HI>Ru&s;&s;ian</HI> Army in their
Victorious return from the Country of <HI>Hol&s;tein,</HI>
their demand upon the City of <HI>Hamburgh</HI> has been
mention'd; the Conclu&s;ion of which was, that
the <HI>Hamburghers</HI> Paid the Prince 200000 Rixdol|lars,
and &s;o the <HI>Ru&s;&s;ian</HI> Army quitted their Di|&s;trict;
the like Preten&s;ions the Prince made upon
the Citizens of <HI>Lubeck,</HI> and got 100000 Marks
of them, and then without any &s;top they ad|vanc'd
towards <HI>Pomerania;</HI> it was propos'd to at|tack
<HI>Wi&s;mar,</HI> and the <HI>Danes</HI> provided a great
Train of Artillery for that Purpo&s;e; but the Ge|nerals
differing afterwards upon particular Diffi|culties
in the Enterprize it was laid a&s;ide, and the
<HI>Ru&s;&s;ian</HI> Army march'd and joyn'd the re&s;t of their
Troops in <HI>Pomerania,</HI> where being together, they
made up an Army of 36000 Men, with which
Prince <HI>Menzikoff</HI> re&s;olv'd to attack the City of
<HI>Stetin,</HI> the Capital of the Royal <HI>Pomerania.</HI></P>
<P>THIS is a City of great &s;trength, and the Works
were in very good Condition, and con&s;idering
the gallant Defence this City made when be&s;ieged
by the King of <HI>Pru&s;&s;ia's</HI> Father, then Elector of
<HI>Brandenburgh,</HI> again&s;t whom it defended it &s;elf to
the la&s;t Extremity; I &s;ay, con&s;idering this, it was
e&s;teem'd a de&s;perate Undertaking of the <HI>Ru&s;&s;ian</HI>
General, and the World expected it would be the
ruin of their Army, and the di&s;grace of the Gene|ral;
but this did not Di&s;courage Prince <HI>Menzikoff,</HI>
who about eight Days after he had Inve&s;ted the
<PB N="397" REF="406">
Place, rais'd a Battery again&s;t the <HI>Oder</HI> Fort, a
&s;trong Work, which guarded the Bridge, and af|ter
having Batter'd it two Nights, caus'd it to be
&s;torm'd, which his Men did with &s;uch Fury,
that the <HI>Swedes,</HI> which defended it, being not able
to maintain their Ground, the <HI>Ru&s;&s;ians</HI> entered
Sword in Hand, the Defendants being all cut in
pieces, except a very few, who had Quarter grant|ed
them: This gave the Courage of the Citizens
a &s;hock, and it was ea&s;ie to &s;ee they had not the
Gallantry and Re&s;olution of their Ance&s;tors.</P>
<P>WHILE this was doing, the <HI>Saxons</HI> who lay at
<HI>Damin</HI> and at <HI>Grip&s;wald,</HI> found means with the
help of &s;ome <HI>Dani&s;h</HI> Fregates, and &s;ome other
Ve&s;&s;els to Land upon the I&s;le of <HI>Rugen,</HI> the <HI>Swe|di&s;h</HI>
General <HI>Ducker,</HI> who commanded in the
I&s;land, having but very few Troops retired to a
&s;trong Pa&s;s in the way to <HI>Stral&s;und,</HI> and made a
&s;tand there, but kept his Retreat open to <HI>Stral&s;und,</HI>
if need were, and the <HI>Saxons</HI> receiving &s;ome Re|inforcements
from <HI>Gry&s;waldt</HI> advanced towards
him, on which being in no Condition to maintain
the Po&s;t, he retir'd to <HI>Stral&s;und,</HI> and left the
<HI>Saxons</HI> Ma&s;ters of the whole I&s;land; and now the
King of <HI>Denmark</HI> repented heartily that he had
not caus'd his Army to advance into <HI>Pomeren,</HI> for
now had been the Time to have attack'd the City
of <HI>Strael&s;und,</HI> in which there was not a &s;ufficient
Garri&s;on, or Provi&s;ions to have held out a Siege,
nor any Relief at Hand, the Affairs of <HI>Sweden,</HI>
being as I have &s;aid in great Confu&s;ion; the King's
Si&s;ter, &s;ince Queen of <HI>Sweden,</HI> being about that
time about taking upon her the Regency of the
Kingdom in the Ab&s;ence of the King.</P>
<P><PB N="398" REF="407">
THE <HI>Saxons</HI> were &s;en&s;ible of the Advantage they
had, but they wanted every thing needful for &s;uch
a Seige as that of <HI>Strael&s;und;</HI> however they &s;at
down before the Place, inve&s;ted it, and &s;urpriz'd
400 Hor&s;es, and 50 di&s;mounted Troopers, in the
Enclo&s;ures near the City, and di&s;patch'd Expre&s;&s;es
to <HI>Denmark</HI> for Cannon and Ammunition, which
came not in time, as you &s;hall hear, which occa|&s;ion'd
the Seige to be deferr'd till new Laurels
were prepar'd by the&s;e things for his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Ma|je&s;ty.</P>
<P>THERE happen'd at this very time a Di&s;covery
of the villainous De&s;ign again&s;t the Life of the
King of <HI>Poland,</HI> which made a very great Noi&s;e,
and oblig'd Count <HI>Flemning</HI> to go away imme|diately,
and the <HI>Saxon</HI> Troops were order'd to
draw off from the intended attack of <HI>Strael&s;und,</HI>
and follow with all &s;peed the King of <HI>Poland,</HI> ex|pecting
a General Revolt, e&s;pecially on the Side
of <HI>Lithuania;</HI> but his <HI>Poli&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty manag'd his
Affairs with &s;uch Dexterity that nothing of that
kind happen'd.</P>
<P>THE attack of <HI>Stetin</HI> was al&s;o deferr'd for the
pre&s;ent, but the City was clo&s;ely block'd up, and
the Blockade &s;o well concerted, that the Navigati|on
of the <HI>Oder</HI> was cut off from the <HI>Stetiners,</HI>
which was indeed the only Means to reduce
them.</P>
<P>THE Enemies of the <HI>Ru&s;&s;ian</HI> Glory had now the
Mortification al&s;o to &s;ee the renew'd Peace between
his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty and the <HI>Turks</HI> confirm'd, by in|telligence
from all Parts, and particularly from
the King of <HI>Sweden's</HI> exil'd Court near <HI>Adrianople,</HI>
and the Articles were publi&s;h'd by them&s;elves,
which being allow'd to be right and in Sub&s;tance,
are as follows.</P>
<LIST>
<PB N="399" REF="408">
<ITEM><HI>I.</HI> The <HI>Mu&s;covite</HI> Troops &s;hall march out of all
the Territories of <HI>Poland</HI> within two Months,
and &s;hall not return thither upon any Pretence
what&s;oever.</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>II.</HI> The Port &s;hall be allow'd to procure a Pa&s;&s;age
to the King of <HI>Sweden</HI> thro' <HI>Poland</HI> or <HI>Mu&s;co|vy</HI>
to his own Dominions, under a Guard,
at the Charge of the Grand Senior, and the &s;aid
Guard &s;hall return without any Hindrance or
Oppo&s;ition.</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>III.</HI> The <HI>Co&s;&s;acks</HI> &s;hall be re&s;tor'd to their ancient
Privileges, and <HI>Kiow</HI> with all the Country on the
other &s;ide of the <HI>Dnieper</HI> or <HI>Bori&s;tthenes,</HI> &s;hall
belong to the <HI>Czar,</HI> and the Country on the other
&s;ide of that River to the <HI>Port.</HI></ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>IV. A&s;oph</HI> &s;hall remain to the <HI>Turks,</HI> who are al|low'd
to repair the Fortifications thereof, but <HI>Ta|ganorock</HI>
&s;hall be demoli&s;h'd.</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>V.</HI> The 60 Pieces of Cannon which the <HI>Mu&s;covites</HI>
have carried away from thence, &s;hall be re&s;tor'd,
or an Equivalent given for it, after which they
&s;hall be at Liberty to take away the Iron Guns which
they have left in <HI>A&s;oph.</HI></ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>VI.</HI> According to the Peace concluded near the River
<HI>Pruth,</HI> the <HI>Turks</HI> &s;hall be at Liberty to rebuild
&s;ome Places in the neighbourhood of <HI>Caminieck,</HI>
that have been demoli&s;h'd.</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>VII.</HI> The River <HI>Zamara</HI> &s;hall be the Limits of <HI>Tur|key,</HI>
and that of <HI>Exceez</HI> &s;hall be the Frontier of
<HI>Mu&s;covy,</HI> and both Parties are allow'd to build
each a Fortre&s;s on their re&s;pective Frontiers;
but <HI>A&s;oph,</HI> and the Limits on that Side, &s;hall re|main
in the &s;ame Condition.</ITEM>
<ITEM><PB N="400" REF="409">
<HI>VIII.</HI> All acts of Ho&s;tility &s;hall cea&s;e on both Sides,
the <HI>Co&s;&s;acks,</HI> and other Countries belonging to
the <HI>Czar</HI> are included in this Peace.</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>IX.</HI> The <HI>Calmucks</HI> &s;hall remain to the <HI>Czar,</HI> and the
<HI>Crim Tartars</HI> to the <HI>Port,</HI> and tho&s;e two Na|tions
&s;hall be hindered from committing any Ho|&s;tilities.</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>X.</HI> The Pretentions of the <HI>Tartars</HI> of a yearly Tri|bute
&s;hall be referr'd to another Time.</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>XI.</HI> This Peace &s;hall continue for 25 Years, and may
be prolong'd for a longer Time.</ITEM>
</LIST>
<P>THE publi&s;hing of the&s;e Articles, &s;topp'd the
Mouths of tho&s;e People who in&s;ulted the <HI>Czar,</HI>
with having &s;ubmitted for fear of a War with
the <HI>Turks,</HI> to be Tributary to the <HI>Tartars,</HI> as for|merly
the <HI>Czars</HI> had been, but as his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI>
Maje&s;ty had always rejected the Articles with
Scorn, &s;o it was now apparent that the <HI>Turks</HI> had
dropp'd it.</P>
<P>THE <HI>Ru&s;&s;ian</HI> Army lay all this while before <HI>Ste|tin,</HI>
&s;ometimes re&s;olving to be&s;iege it in Form, and
then, at other times to blockade it; but now Prince
<HI>Menzikoff</HI> being returned from <HI>Berlin,</HI> where a
Treaty for Seque&s;tring the Town into the Hands of
the King of <HI>Pru&s;&s;ia</HI> had been &s;et on Foot, but came
to nothing. <HI>I &s;$y,</HI> the Prince being Return'd,
re&s;olv'd upon a Bombardment, which he knew
would either bring the City to &s;urrender, or the
King of <HI>Pru&s;&s;ia</HI> to yield to the Seque&s;tration upon
the Terms propos'd, which was to pay to the <HI>Czar</HI>
of <HI>Mu&s;covy</HI> 600000 Rix Dollars for the Charges
of the Siege.</P>
<P>ACCORDING to the&s;e Re&s;olutions, our Trenches
were open'd, and advanc'd to proper places; and
the Batteries rai&s;ed with the utmo&s;t Expedition,
<PB N="401" REF="410">
the Artillery con&s;i&s;ted of 58 Pieces of heavy
Cannon, and 32 Mortars: On the 20th of <HI>Sep|tmber,</HI>
all our Batteries of Cannon and Mor|tars
being in a Readine&s;s, it was re&s;olv'd to
Fire upon the Place the 28th in the Morn|ing.
All the Drums and Houtboys of the Ar|my
were order'd to meet in the Trenches about
9 of the Clock, where they play'd about an Hour,
to the great Surprize of the Be&s;ieged, who appear'd
on their Walls to &s;ee what the meaning of it
could be; but about Ten, we began to fire from
all our Batteries at once, and continu'd till the
Evening; which had &s;uch an Effect, that the
Inhabitants &s;eeing about 160 of their be&s;t Hou&s;es
burnt, and their Churches batter'd down, they
oblig'd General <HI>Meyrfelt</HI> to de&s;ire a Ce&s;&s;ation of
Arms. The Sieurs <HI>Ba&s;&s;ewitz</HI> and <HI>Brukenthal</HI> were
&s;ent into the Place, and told the Governor that the
Ho&s;tilities &s;hould be di&s;continu'd for &s;even Hours
only, and that he might take his Mea&s;ures there|upon.
Tho&s;e Gentlemen reported, that the
Burghers refu&s;ed to take up Arms, and the Regi|ment
of <HI>Pomerania</HI> expre&s;&s;ing an Inclination to
lay them down. General <HI>Meyrfelt</HI> offer'd to march
out with his Garri&s;on in 5 Days, provided they
would give him leave to &s;end an Expre&s;s to Count
<HI>Welling,</HI> to acquaint him there with; which was
granted him, upon Condition that a <HI>Mu&s;covite</HI>
Officer &s;hould go along with the Per&s;on he would
&s;end to the Count afore&s;aid, and that his Letter
to him &s;hould not be &s;eal'd. This being agreed
to, the <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> Officer and the <HI>Mu&s;covite</HI> &s;et out the
&s;ame Morning very early or <HI>Hamburgh,</HI> and we
hop'd in a few Days to be Ma&s;ters of this important
Fortre&s;s.</P>
<P><PB N="402" REF="411">
BUT while the Garri&s;on of <HI>Stetin</HI> were thus,
at the Extremity, another Medium was found
out, which made all Sides ea&s;y, and this was the
Treaty of Seque&s;tration, <HI>mention'd above.</HI> This
was ab&s;olutely, nece&s;&s;ary for Prince <HI>Menzkioff</HI> to
yield to; or, to break with the <HI>Danes,</HI> and the
King of <HI>Pru&s;&s;ia</HI> al&s;o; for the former, prote&s;ted
ab&s;olutely again&s;t <HI>Stetin</HI> being put into the Hands
of his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty &s;ingly, and in&s;i&s;ted that there
&s;hould be a Quota of <HI>Dani&s;h</HI> and <HI>Saxon</HI> Troops put
into Garri&s;on there, as well as <HI>Mu&s;covite,</HI> which
Prince <HI>Menzicoff</HI> rejected; tho&s;e Powers having
not contributed one Farthing towards the Siege.</P>
<P>IN a Word the King of <HI>Pru&s;&s;ia</HI> &s;ending a very
obliging An&s;wer to the la&s;t Offers of the Prince,
was in Return invited to the <HI>Ru&s;&s;ian</HI> Camp, where
his <HI>Pru&s;&s;ian</HI> Maje&s;ty arriv'd the 5th of <HI>October,</HI>
at ended with 3000 Dragoons and 9000 <HI>Pru&s;&s;ian</HI>
Foot, being on the other Side the <HI>Oder,</HI> where they
encamp'd. His <HI>Pru&s;&s;ian</HI> Maje&s;ty was very Magni|ficently
entertain'd by Prince <HI>Menzicoff,</HI> and a
Royal Tent &s;et up, in which his Maje&s;ty lodg'd;
the 6th at Night, having been &s;hewn all the Ap|proaches
of the <HI>Ru&s;&s;ian</HI> Army, their Batteries, and
the Preparations which the Ingineers had made for
&s;torming the Place, and that we were &s;ure of our
Game.</P>
<P>THE next Day the Seque&s;tration was &s;ettled
and agreed upon, and the Garri&s;on and Burghers of
<HI>Stetin,</HI> agreeing al&s;o that the King of <HI>Pru&s;&s;ia</HI> &s;hould
march into the City the 7th at the Head of 1600
Dragoons, his Infantry entering the Town by the
<HI>Oder</HI> Bridge the next Day.</P>
<P>BY this Treaty, the Po&s;&s;e&s;&s;ion of <HI>Stetin</HI> was to
remain a-like to the King of <HI>Pru&s;&s;ia,</HI> and the Duke
of <HI>Hol&s;tein</HI> till the Peace, and 1600 Men of the
<PB N="403" REF="412">
Troops of <HI>Hol&s;tein</HI> were allow'd to remain in Gar|ri&s;on
with 1600 <HI>Pui&s;&s;ians;</HI> and the King of <HI>Pru&s;&s;ia</HI>
paid Prince <HI>Menzikoff</HI> 500000 Rix Dollars, and &s;o
this trouble&s;ome Affair ended.</P>
<P>BUT I mu&s;t ob&s;erve here, that both the <HI>Saxons</HI>
and <HI>Danes</HI> took great offence at this Treaty; for
the Seque&s;tration of <HI>Stetin</HI> was not Communicated
to them, the <HI>Saxons</HI> alledg'd, &s;eeing the Cannon
furni&s;hed for the Siege belong'd to their King, his
<HI>Poli&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty ought to &s;hare the Money, and de|manded
one half of the 500000 Dollars; but Prince
<HI>Menzikoff</HI> gave them good Words, and kept all
the Money.</P>
<P>THE King of <HI>Denmark</HI> took the Allarm,
there being a Report &s;pread that another Treaty
was al&s;o on Foot for the Seque&s;tration of <HI>Wi&s;mar</HI>
and <HI>Stral&s;und,</HI> upon which the <HI>Dani&s;h</HI> Mini&s;ter
pre&s;ented a Memorial in his Ma&s;ter's Name, to
the Mini&s;ters of <HI>Pru&s;&s;ia</HI> and <HI>Mu&s;covy,</HI> intimating
that his Ma&s;ter had been very much &s;urprized to
hear&punc; that an Affair of &s;o much Importance as the
Seque&s;tration of <HI>Stetin</HI> had been concluded, and
that Place deliver'd to the Troops of the Duke of
<HI>Hol&s;tein,</HI> who&s;e Intere&s;t is in&s;eparable from that
of <HI>Sweden;</HI> That his Maje&s;ty hopes nothing &s;hall
be concluded without his Participation in relation
to <HI>Wi&s;mar,</HI> becau&s;e of his particular Concerns in
that Affair, and that the whole Matter, which has
been hitherto kept Secret from him, &s;hall be fairly
communicated to his Maje&s;ty, and in the mean
time the &s;aid Mini&s;ter has thought fit to prote&s;t
again&s;t whatever has been done in this Seque&s;tra|tion
without his Con&s;ent and Knowledge.</P>
<P>As to the Treaty for the Seque&s;tration of <HI>Wi&s;|mar</HI>
and <HI>Stral&s;und,</HI> it came to nothing; and all things
being now over, the <HI>Mu&s;covite</HI> Army, which was
<PB N="404" REF="413">
by this Time reduced by hard Service without
any con&s;iderable Action to 22000 Men from
36000; they began their March out of the Coun|try,
the 25th of <HI>September,</HI> according to the Capi|tulation
of which, that was one of the mo&s;t par|ticular
Conditions.</P>
<P>WHILE this was done, the Armies of his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI>
Maje&s;ty were Victorious in <HI>Finland;</HI> General <HI>Le|becker</HI>
had been recall'd from that Government,
and General <HI>Arenfield</HI> &s;ent in his Room, as is no|ted
above; but he had no better luck than the
other, for being encamped at a very advantagious
Po&s;t, with 7000 <HI>Swedes,</HI> regular and old Troops, and
18000 Men, new rai&s;ed, but well arm'd, and un|der
very good Officers, yet the <HI>Ru&s;&s;ians</HI> attack'd
them; the new rai&s;ed Troops being undi&s;ciplin'd,
yet made very great Re&s;i&s;tance at fir&s;t, but were
charg'd with &s;uch Fury, that they were at length
defeated; which occa&s;ion'd that the 7000 <HI>Swedes</HI>
were &s;urrounded, and after a very good Defence,
were almo&s;t all cut in Pieces, or taken Pri&s;oners,
with all their Artillery, and Baggage.</P>
<P>AFTER this Action, the <HI>Czar</HI>'s Troops enter'd
<HI>Abo</HI> without Re&s;i&s;tance, and his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty
re&s;olv'd to batter down the Defences of the other
two Forts, which lye adjoyning to the Sea, and
which interrupted his Progre&s;s; and thus he
became Ma&s;ter of the whole Province, with the
Lo&s;s of very few Men, and the Tranquility of
the Country w$s re&s;tor'd entirely: As the <HI>Czar</HI>
had gain'd this whole Province &s;o ea$ily, he was
re&s;olv'd it &s;hould not be &s;o ea&s;ily taken from him;
he therefore went to Work immediately, to forti|fy
the Towns of mo&s;t Importance, as <HI>Abo</HI> and
<HI>Hel&s;ingvos,</HI> and others, both which, he has &s;ince
made very &s;trong.</P>
<P><PB N="405" REF="414">
THIS Action with the <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> Troops under
General <HI>Ahrenfield,</HI> having been diver&s;ly reported,
and the <HI>Ru&s;&s;ians</HI> being charged with Partiallity, in
relating their own Affairs; I &s;hall therefore give
here a Copy of General <HI>Ahrenfields</HI> own Ac|count,
which tho' he makes the be&s;t of his Lo&s;s
to &s;ave his own Character; yet an impartial Rea|der
will ea&s;ily perceive, a Total defeat was given
him, and that he has lo&s;t not only his Army, but
the whole Province; &s;o that our Account will be
effectually ackowledg'd by the Enemy, which is the
be&s;t kind of Confirmation; his Letter is as follows:</P>
<P>THIS will inform, that we &s;u&s;tained Ye&s;terday a
fierce Attack from the Enemy, who, at la&s;t, oblig'd
us to give Ground. Our Intrenchments near <HI>Palka|na</HI>
were very &s;trong, and we reckon'd to be able to
de$end 'em a great while again&s;t con&s;iderable Forces:
But, contrary to our Expectation, the Enemy found
Means to land 7000 Men within a quarter of a
League behind us. I had made &s;everal Detachments, and
&s;ent our Parties to get Intelligence, by which I learnt,
that &s;everal of the Enemy's Boats were in &s;ight;
whereupon I made all the nece&s;&s;ary Di&s;po&s;itions to
hinder a De&s;cent; I al&s;o view'd the Place where the
Enemy de&s;ign'd to land, and caus'd &s;ame Hor&s;e to be
po&s;ted there. I had be&s;ides this, drawn two thirds of
the Infantry, that were within the Lines, in order
likewi&s;e to oppo&s;e the De&s;cent; but the Wind, which
had been contrary to the Enemy's de&s;ign all Night,
turn'd favourable to them at Break of Day; be&s;ides
which, there was a thick Fog, that we could not per|ceive
till they advanc'd upon us. Our Cavalry was
<PB N="406" REF="415">
at fir&s;t oblig'd to retire, becau&s;e the Infantry I had
drawn from our Line could not came up time enough
to &s;u&s;tain them; the Enemy before their approach,
having landed the be&s;t part of their Troops. Never|thele&s;s,
we advanc'd and charg'd them with a great deal
of Bravery, and by our &s;uperior Fire, pu&s;h'd them into
the Water; but they being &s;upported by &s;uch as hourly
landed on all &s;ides, we were obliged to give way in our
Turn. We had di&s;po&s;ed things in &s;uch a manner, that the
Hor&s;e was to attack the Enemy in Flank, and if they
had perform'd their Duty, 'tis probable we &s;hould have
had Succe&s;s: But tho' the Foot did all that could be
expected from the be&s;t Troops, yet we could never
prevail with the Cavalry to do the like, each
Plattoon giving way one after another. Things
being at this Pa&s;s, it was not difficult for the
Emnemy to attack our Lines; however, they lo&s;t abun|dance
of Men, till upon certain Con&s;iderations, I
order'd the Troops to abandon the Intrenchments.
The Lo&s;s we have &s;u&s;tain'd in tho&s;e Attacks is not
&s;mall. We were oblig'd to march through the mo&s;t con|venient
Places to favour our Retreat, and the Infantry
being obliged to take &s;everal Routs, it is not yet po&s;&s;ible
for me to know what Number of Men are mi&s;&s;ing. In
mean time, I have again po&s;ted my &s;elf in this Pa&s;&s;age,
in order to make all po&s;&s;ible Re&s;i&s;tance. The great
Number of Roads and Pa&s;&s;ages had oblig'd me to
divide my Troops in &s;uch manner, that I had only
with me 700 Hor&s;e and 1100 Foot to oppo&s;e the
landing. This Day the Enemy advanc'd near this
Place, and I am now in Expectation of their further
Undertakings, <HI>&amp;c.</HI></P>
<P>THE Truth of this Matter was thus, that Gene|ral
<HI>Ahrenfield</HI> was entirely defeated, his Hor&s;e
which indeed did not do their Duty were never
<PB N="407" REF="416">
heard of, till they were effectually &s;ecured at a|bout
60 Miles retreat North, and the General
with that &s;mall Remnant of his Infantry, which,
out of 25000 Men, did not amount to above 8000,
5133 being kill'd in the Action, and 512 taken
Pri&s;oners, quitted the whole Province, and made
long Marches, tho' none pur&s;ued them into <HI>Lap|land,</HI>
whence we heard of them no more; but
&s;uppo&s;e they got Boats to carry them over the
Gulph of <HI>Bothnia</HI> into <HI>Swedeland,</HI> where they were
at that time in Confu&s;ion enough.</P>
<P>THE Conque&s;t of this Province has been of great
advantage to his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty's Affairs, for he
was now &s;ufficiently &s;eparated from <HI>Sweden,</HI> and
under no Obligation to maintain a great Number
of Troops upon his Frontier, as before the keep|ing
of good Garri&s;ons in <HI>Abo</HI> and <HI>Hel&s;ingford,</HI>
Places which he has made very &s;trong, and
keeping a Number of Gallies always ready up|on
that Coa&s;t, is &s;ufficient to keep all quiet on
that Side.</P>
<P>FROM hence al&s;o his Maje&s;ty had drawn a va&s;t
Number of good Soldiers, the <HI>Finlanders</HI> being al|ways
e&s;teem'd the be&s;t Men in the <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> Ar|mies,
and e&s;pecially for Hor&s;e, it being a Coun|try
for breeding of Hor&s;es, the Men are naturally
good Hor&s;e-men, and yet I under&s;tand that his
Maje&s;ty has not Levy'd any Men there, but &s;uch
as voluntarily Li&s;ted into his Service.</P>
<P>THE <HI>Czar</HI> had now fini&s;h'd the Conque&s;t of
the <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> Territories, as far as they lay con|tiguous
to his own; nothing could more be at|tempted
again&s;t the <HI>Swedes,</HI> but by Naval Pre|parations
for a De&s;cent on the Kingdom of <HI>Swe|den</HI>
it &s;elf. His <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty had, as I have
mentioned already, very much improv'd his
<PB N="408" REF="417">
Marine Affairs, as well as his Millitary Affairs
by Land, but not to &s;uch Perfection, for his Land
Forces were brought to a Perfection not to be
que&s;tion'd; his Troops were able to grapple with
any of the Forces of his Neighbours Man for Man,
nay, he has often beaten the <HI>Swedes</HI> when they
have been &s;uperior in Number, and in the la&s;t
Action at the Siege of <HI>Stetin,</HI> where there were
no Troops but <HI>Ru&s;&s;ians,</HI> it appear'd how well they
did their Bu&s;ine&s;s; how regularly they carry'd
on their Approaches; how boldly they &s;torm'd;
how firmly they &s;u&s;tain'd the Sallies of the
<HI>Swedes;</HI> and how artfully they mannag'd the De|fence
of their Trenches. We &s;hall now &s;ee &s;ome
Proceedings in which their naval Force was al|ways
concern'd.</P>
<P>HIS <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty who knew the Di&s;po&s;ition
of the King of <HI>Sweden,</HI> as well as any Man;
knew there was no &s;itting &s;till while he was in
being; and the only way to reduce him to Rea|&s;on,
was, to pu&s;h his Kingdom of <HI>Sweden</HI> to the
utmo&s;t Extremity, while he was Ab&s;ent; if po&s;&s;i|ble,
to bring the Regency, newly e&s;tabli&s;h'd
there, in the Prince&s;s <HI>Ulrica Eleonora,</HI> and the
Senate, to the Nece&s;&s;ity of making a Peace,
before the King of <HI>Sweden</HI> return'd from <HI>Turkey.</HI></P>
<P>To this Purpo&s;e, the <HI>Czar</HI> cau&s;ed a Project
to be laid before the King of <HI>Denmark,</HI> for a &s;e|cond
and more effectual Invading of <HI>Schomen,</HI> an
Undertaking, which he knew very well, would
be very ageeable to the King of <HI>Denmark,</HI> who
having receiv'd a terrible Di&s;grace in his former
Attempt there, at the Battle of <HI>El&s;enburg,</HI> would
be very willing to retrieve that Blow, and al&s;o
pu&s;h the <HI>Swedes;</HI> he having likewi&s;e pu&s;h'd the
War on this &s;ide the <HI>Sound,</HI> to the utmo&s;t, and
<PB N="409" REF="418">
compleated the the Conque&s;t of <HI>Hol&s;tein, Bre|men,</HI>
and <HI>Verden;</HI> nothing remaining to the
<HI>Swedes</HI> on this &s;ide the whole <HI>Baltick</HI> Sea, but
<HI>Pomeren,</HI> and the City of <HI>Wi&s;mar;</HI> which were at
that time under a kind of Offer to be Seque|&s;trated
to the King of <HI>Pru&s;&s;ia,</HI> tho' afterwards
the King of <HI>Sweden</HI> forbid it.</P>
<P>HOWEVER the King of <HI>Denmark</HI> did not re|ceive
this Propo&s;al at fir&s;t, in &s;uch a manner
as the <HI>Czar</HI> of <HI>Mu&s;covy</HI> expected; and much
Time was &s;pent in debating upon the particu|lar
Branches of the Undertaking, and the Quo|tas,
and Expences nece&s;&s;ary to be furni&s;hed.
But at length his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty who knew this
was the only way by which the King of <HI>Sweden</HI>
could be effectualy humbled, conquered all his
<HI>Dani&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty's Objections, and offer'd &s;uch A&s;|&s;i&s;tance,
as well of Land Forces, as of Shiping,
that the King of <HI>Denmark</HI> &s;aw an evident Oppor|tunity
put into his Hands, for recovering that
Part of the old Kingdom of <HI>Denmark,</HI> which his
Ance&s;tors had lo&s;t to the <HI>Swedes,</HI> and which was
given up by the Treaty of <HI>Ro&s;child,</HI> viz. <HI>Scho|nen,
Bleaking,</HI> and <HI>Halland,</HI> Provinces extended
on the Coa&s;t of the <HI>Sound</HI> and the <HI>North Sea,</HI> from
<HI>Malmo</HI> to <HI>Gottenbro',</HI> and which lye in the very
Sight of his Pallace in <HI>Copenhagen.</HI></P>
<P>AS the King of <HI>Denmark</HI> began at la&s;t to li|&s;ten
to his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty's offer; &s;o Troops were
prepar'd, order'd to march into <HI>Pomeren,</HI> and <HI>Meck|lemburgh,</HI>
to be tran&s;ported from thence to <HI>Copen|hagen,</HI>
and in a Word, his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty made
&s;uch Preparations both by Land, and Sea, as con|vinc'd
the King of <HI>Denmark,</HI> that he &s;hould be put
into a Po&s;ture to humble <HI>Sweden</HI> effectually, and this
brought him to come heartily into the thing, tho'
<PB N="410" REF="419">
as it appear'd the Circum&s;tances of <HI>Denmark,</HI> were
not at that time equal to the Undertaking.</P>
<P>HOWEVER, as his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty &s;tuck at no|thing
in Rea&s;on to animate the King of <HI>Denmark,</HI>
to per&s;ecute the War with a&s;uitable vigour, 300000
Rixdollars were remitted to <HI>Copenhagen,</HI> and
200000 more afterwards to encourage the King of
<HI>Denmark</HI> to ha&s;ten out his Fleet to Sea, and in the
mean time the <HI>Czar</HI> fitted out his own Fleet, con|&s;i&s;ting
of 30 Men of War, mo&s;t of them being
brought and fitted up in <HI>England,</HI> and <HI>Holland,</HI> and
having embark'd 24000 Men on Board, they &s;ail'd
for the I&s;le of <HI>Aland,</HI> where his Maje&s;ty attack'd Ad|miral
<HI>Ehren&s;child,</HI> and took his Ship, and &s;ix Gal|lies,
killed 327 Men, and took about 936 Pri&s;o|ners,
and landed 16000 Men in that I&s;land$; which
put the whole Kingdom of <HI>Sweden</HI> into the mo&s;t
terrible Surprize, and Con&s;ternation imaginable,
the I&s;le of <HI>Aland,</HI> being as it were at the Mouth
of the River of <HI>Stockholm.</HI></P>
<P>BUT all this while the <HI>Danes</HI> did nothing, not|with&s;tanding
the A&s;&s;i&s;tance his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty had
&s;ent them, they pretended indeed to fit out their
Ships and joyn the <HI>Czar</HI>'s Fleet, but they were &s;o
long in doing it, that the <HI>Swedes</HI> was at Sea, and
rendezvous'd at the I&s;le of <HI>Bournholm</HI> before the
<HI>Danes</HI> were in Condition to act; &s;o that the expected
Conjunction was prevented, which indeed was the
Di&s;appointment of all farther Opperations for that
Summer.</P>
<P>THE <HI>Czar</HI> &s;eeing how little &s;uch Allies were
to be depended upon, put off his intended De&s;cent
upon <HI>Sweden,</HI> for the <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> Fleet was &s;o &s;trong,
being 20 Men of War, and &s;ome of their Men of
War &s;o large, for they had four or five three Deck
Ships from 84 to 106 Guns, and his Maje&s;ty's
<PB N="411" REF="420">
Fleet, tho' well appointed, yet con&s;i&s;ted chiefly
of Ships, bought in <HI>England,</HI> and <HI>Holland,</HI> mo&s;t
of them being from 44 to 60 Guns, three Ships or
four of his Maje&s;ty's own building might be there
of 70 and 80 Guns, But was not advi&s;eable to
come to a general Engagement with the <HI>Swedes,</HI>
without the Conjunction of the <HI>Danes.</HI></P>
<P>IT is to be remembered here, that his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI>
Maje&s;ty having for &s;ome Years, when he fir&s;t ap|plyed
his Thoughts to encrea&s;e his Naval &s;trength,
had his Eyes and all his Mea&s;ures employ'd up|on
building a Royal Navy for the Service of the
<HI>Black-Sea,</HI> &s;o he had now brought that Work to &s;uch
perfection, that he had a Fleet at <HI>Veronowitz,</HI> on
the <HI>Tanais,</HI> con&s;i&s;ting of 44 Ships, from 50 to 90
Guns, whereof 16 of them carried from 80 to 90
Guns; all which Preparations were intirely lo&s;t,
and rendered u&s;ele&s;s, by the &s;urrender of <HI>A&s;oph,</HI>
given back in Con&s;equence of the unhappy Cam|paign
in <HI>Moldavia</HI> a, s a above.</P>
<P>BUT the opening a Navigation into the <HI>Bal|tick,</HI>
by the taking the once impregnable Ca&s;tle of
<HI>Notteburgh;</HI> the making a Harbour and Port at
<HI>Croon&s;lot,</HI> and building the Imperial City of <HI>Pe|tersburgh,</HI>
which we find at the writing this Hi&s;to|ry
to be rais'd in about 22 Years from a vacant
piece of Ground, to a City of 50000 Hou&s;es be|&s;ides
publick Edifices, all the&s;e were at the time
of this taking of the I&s;land of <HI>Aland,</HI> but new
things, and therefore, tho' the Progre&s;s the <HI>Czar</HI>
had made, was for the time &s;urpri&s;ing to the World,
yet his Naval &s;trength was young, his Subjects
not yet enur'd to Sea-Service; and he was too wary
a Prince to put the Succe&s;s of all his great De|&s;igns
upon, the hazard of a general Engagement
<PB N="412" REF="421">
&s;o early, and as it were in the beginning of things;
and for this Rea&s;on he withdrew from the I&s;land
of <HI>Aland,</HI> upon the Di&s;appointment of the <HI>Danes,</HI>
and gave over his Enterprize for that Year.</P>
<P>SINCE this, we have found his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty
has improv'd his <HI>Marine</HI> &s;trength to &s;nch a degree,
and furni&s;h'd him&s;elf with &s;uch Capital Ships of
his own building, that now he is a Match for the
<HI>Swedes,</HI> and the <HI>Danes</HI> put together, and when|ever
tho&s;e Powers apprehend his coming to attack
them, thy are oblig'd to get the aid of a Squa|dron
of Men of War from <HI>Great-Britain</HI> to their
A&s;&s;$&s;tance, or rather as it may ju&s;tly be call'd for
their Protection.</P>
<P>BUT to return to the <HI>Danes;</HI> the King of
<HI>Denmark,</HI> began now to be&s;en&s;ible of his Mi&s;take,
and of his having lo&s;t the Opportunity for the
humbling his Enemy the <HI>Swede;</HI> and now to re|trieve
it we find, that the <HI>Czar</HI> pre&s;s'd him to en|gag
in a new Scheme for the &s;aid &s;econd Inva&s;ion
of <HI>Schonen,</HI> and offer'd him his A&s;&s;i&s;tance, as well
by Sea as Land; al&s;o &s;eeing how &s;ucce&s;sfully
the <HI>Czar</HI> went on, and how it might be probable
that at one time or other, the <HI>Czar,</HI> by his Supe|rior
&s;trength would break in upon the <HI>Swedes</HI>
without him, and then he might lo&s;e the Oppor|tunity,
and have no &s;hare at all of the Advan|tage:
This turned the Scale at the Court of
<HI>Denmark;</HI> and as the <HI>Czar</HI> pre&s;s'd him before, as I
have &s;aid to engage in &s;uch an Attempt, and
promis'd $o A&s;&s;$&s;t and Support him; &s;o now he, his
<HI>Dani&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty pre&s;s'd the <HI>Czar</HI> as much to come
into that Scheme, as if it had been contriv'd at
<HI>Copenhagen</HI> and not at <HI>Petersburgh.</HI></P>
<P><PB N="413" REF="422">
IN the mean time, the <HI>Czar,</HI> as I have &s;aid,
withdrew from <HI>Aland;</HI> and having order'd his
Gallies and light Fregates to carry the Land
Forces to <HI>Abo</HI> in <HI>Finland,</HI> he &s;ail'd with the Gro&s;s
of his Fleet, and the Ships, he had taken from the
<HI>Swedes</HI> to <HI>Petersburgh,</HI> where he made his publick
Entry, with almo&s;t as much Triumph as he did for+merly
at <HI>Mu&s;cow,</HI> after the Victory at <HI>Pultowa.</HI></P>
<P>AND his Maje&s;ty did this the rather, becau&s;e
it was the fir&s;t Snow of that kind, which had ever
been made in his new City; and becau&s;e it was a
heartening, and Encouragement to his Seamen, to
merit by their Bravery, and to other of his Sub|jects
to enter into the Sea-Service, which they might
&s;ee had &s;uch Honours, and Triumphs attending it.
The Sum of which is as follows: As to a particular
De&s;cription of his Triumphal-Arches, and other
Works for the Decoration of it, it is too long for
this Work: I &s;hall only &s;ay they were &s;uch as
&s;hewed, that the Contrivers of them very well
under&s;tood their Bu&s;ine&s;s, and if they had been in
<HI>France</HI> or <HI>Holland,</HI> they would not have been out
done by any: This Triumphal-Entry was
made at <HI>Petersburgh,</HI> the 20th of <HI>September,</HI> 1714,
in the following Order:</P>
<LIST>
<ITEM><HI>I.</HI> CAME up &s;ome <HI>Ru&s;&s;ian</HI> Ve&s;&s;els called <HI>Scam|pavia.</HI></ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>II.</HI> Three <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> Sh$erboats.</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>III.</HI> Six <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> Gallies.</ITEM>
<ITEM><PB N="414" REF="423">
<HI>IV.</HI> A <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> Frigate, (the&s;e taken in the Fight
with Admiral <HI>Ehren&s;child</HI>) all with the <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI>
Colours hanging down.</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>V.</HI> The <HI>Scampavia</HI> of the <HI>Czar,</HI> as Rear Admiral;
fix other <HI>Ru&s;&s;ian Scampavia,</HI> which Ve&s;&s;els being
come up over again&s;t the Triumphal Arch that was
erected on the Bridge near the Fotre&s;s, they &s;aluted
the &s;ame with all their Cannon, and were an&s;wered
with the like Di&s;charge from the Cannon of the
Fort and the Admiralty.</ITEM>
</LIST>
</DIV2>
<DIV2>
<HEAD>All the Men that were on Board land|ed
there, and the Proce&s;&s;ion began in the
following Order.</HEAD>
<LIST>
<ITEM><HI>I. A</HI> Company of <HI>Brebrezinski.</HI></ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>II.</HI> The Cannon on their Carriages which were
taken la&s;t <HI>Winter</HI> near <HI>Va&s;a</HI> by Lieutenant
General Prince <HI>Gali$zin</HI> in his Victory over the
<HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> Major General <HI>Arenfeldt.</HI></ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>III.</HI> Sixty three Colours or Standards taken in the
Action afore&s;aid, and the la&s;t Engagement.</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>IV.</HI> The <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> Subaltern Sea Officers, Soldiers
and Seamen.</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>V.</HI> Two Companies of <HI>Brebrezinski.</HI></ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>VI.</HI> The <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> Sea Officers, Pri&s;oners.</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>VII.</HI> The Flag of the Rear Admiral <HI>Ehren&s;|child.</HI></ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>VIII.</HI> The <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> Rear Adimiral <HI>Ehren&s;|child
Pri&s;oner.</HI></ITEM>
<ITEM><PB N="415" REF="424">
<HI>IX.</HI> The <HI>Mu&s;covite</HI> Rear Admiral, being the
<HI>Czar</HI> him&s;elf, with the re&s;t of the Regiment of
<HI>Brebenszki.</HI> As &s;oon as his Maje&s;ty came un|der
the Triumphal Arch, all the Senators,
Grandees and Foreign Mini&s;ters repaired there
to Congratulate his Maje&s;ty upon his Victory, and
the Governor of <HI>Mo&s;cow</HI> in the Name of the Em|pire
of <HI>Mu&s;covy,</HI> Complimented him on his Bra|very,
and thank'd him for his good Services,
and as an Acknowledgement thereof, declared
him Vice-Admiral. They proceeded then in the
Order afore&s;aid, and march'd into the Fort,
and there was another general Di&s;charge of the
Cannon, <HI>&amp;c.</HI> Then Prince <HI>Menzikoff</HI> took all
the Foreign Mini&s;ters into his Shallop, and car|ried
them to his Palace, hefore which there
was a magnificent Triumphal Arch erected on the
Water adorn'd with rich Hangings, and about
half an Hour after the <HI>Czar</HI> came thither,
being receiv'd at the &s;aid Arch by that Prince,
and then conducted in to the Palace, where a
mo&s;t magnificent Entertaiment was prepared,
which la&s;ted till Nine at Night. The <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI>
Rear-Admiral <HI>Ehren&s;child</HI> &s;at at Table be|tween
his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty and Prince <HI>Menzi|koff;</HI>
and during the Entertainment the <HI>Czar</HI>
took the Opportunity to compliment that Ad|miral
on his brave Defence in the Fight, a&s;&s;ur|ing
him &s;everal times of his particular E&s;teem
and Affection, and that he would take care to
make him as ea&s;y as the could under his Mis|fortune.
The other <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> Officers &s;at at ano|ther
Table, and were u&s;ed with all po&s;&s;ible Civi|lities,
and &s;o ended that great Solemnity.</ITEM>
</LIST>
<P><PB N="416" REF="425">
THERE was al&s;o a very Magnificent Fire-work
appointed to be performed or play'd off, at the
Gate of the Royal Palace. But the Engineers
repre&s;enting that they had not compleated the
De&s;ign, and could not be ready under three or
four Days, it was play'd off the <HI>Sunday</HI> after,
when his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty went publickly to the
great Church, to give Thanks for the Succe&s;s of
his Arms; and it was admirably perform'd,
without the lea&s;t Di&s;order or Mi&s;take.</P>
<P>IT is to be noted, That this was not a Triumph
for the bare taking of one Ship and &s;ome Gallies
from the <HI>Swedes</HI> at the I&s;le of <HI>Aland;</HI> but it was
upon a Conclu&s;ion of a long Series of Victories
obtain'd over the <HI>Swedes;</HI> and indeed, fini&s;hing
the Conque&s;t of all the Dominions which the
<HI>Swedes</HI> had po&s;&s;e&s;s'd on the <HI>South</HI> and <HI>Ea&s;t</HI> Sides
of the <HI>Baltick Seas,</HI> viz. the whole Province of
<HI>Livonia;</HI> of <HI>Ea&s;thonia,</HI> and of <HI>Carelia;</HI> and <HI>In|garmania;</HI>
the Town and Port of <HI>Narva;</HI> the
City of <HI>Stetin;</HI> the Ca&s;tle of <HI>Notteburg;</HI> the
City of <HI>Wyburgh;</HI> the I&s;le of <HI>Aland;</HI> and the
whole Country of <HI>Finland,</HI> a Province of it|&s;elf,
large enough, to be call'd a Kingdom,
and &s;eated upon the Sea Coa&s;t, for 300 Miles
in Length, where it is to be noted that the
&s;trong Ca&s;tle of <HI>Hel&s;ingvos,</HI> the la&s;t and only Place
which the <HI>Swedes</HI> held in that Province, was
taken at the relanding of the Army there; &s;o
that the whole Country was &s;ubdu'd, and the
<HI>Swedes</HI> put into a terrible Fright, even in the
Heart of <HI>Sweden.</HI> Nay, a Body of <HI>Mu&s;covites</HI> had
tran&s;p$$ted them&s;elves over the <HI>Bothnick</HI> Gulph,
and had landed on the Main of Old <HI>Sweden</HI>
it &s;elf, <HI>that is to &s;ay,</HI> in the Province of <HI>We&s;t Both|nia,</HI>
<PB N="417" REF="426">
where they had ravaged the Country,
burnt &s;everal con&s;iderable Towns and Villages,
where they had taken <HI>Uma</HI> the Capital of that Part
of the Country, and burnt it to the Ground;
after which, they extended Northwards to <HI>Torne,</HI>
and de&s;troy'd the Iron Works, which are very
Con&s;iderable that Way; and did incredible
Damage. Another Body of their Troops, ad|vanced
from <HI>Finland, North,</HI> into the Country of
<HI>Ea&s;t Bothnia,</HI> where the <HI>Swedi&s;h</HI> General <HI>Ahren|field</HI>
Commanded, and endeavour'd to fight him;
but he not daring to come to Action, retir'd North|ward,
into a remote and inacce&s;&s;ible, and indeed,
barren and uninhabited Country, where it was
not practicable to follow him, leaving the Coun|try
of <HI>Ea&s;t Bothnea</HI> open to the Spoil.</P>
<P>THESE things merrited a Triumph, as much
as the <HI>Roman</HI> Generals merited a Triumph for
the Conque&s;t of the mo&s;t powerful Nations they
&s;ubdued.</P>
<P>BUT to come to the Progre&s;s of the War
again, the <HI>Winter</HI> was no more pa&s;t in Idle|ne&s;s
than the <HI>Summer;</HI> and the <HI>Czar</HI> an active
and re&s;tle&s;s Genius, in all his great Underta|kings,
kept his Enemies the <HI>Swedes</HI> in Continu|al
Allarms, with the Rumour of an Attempt pro|jected
to pa&s;s the <HI>Bothnick</HI> Gulph in the Time
of Fro&s;t, with his whole Army over the Ice;
tho&s;e who know the Country, and tho&s;e Seas,
know very well, that as the <HI>Bothnick</HI> Sea is not
deep, and con&s;equently not agitated much
by Storms, and al&s;o, that there is very lit|tle
Tide, or Current there, it is the &s;oone&s;t
Frozen of any part of the <HI>Baltick Sea;</HI> and
then, as its Scituation is more Northerly than
<PB N="418" REF="427">
any other part of the <HI>Baltick,</HI> lying extended
to the 64th Degree of <HI>North</HI> Latitude; and
it thereby infinitely colder than the re&s;t, &s;o
it is no &s;trange thing to find that Sea like
one &s;olid Rock of Ice, for four or five Months
together, and the Country People travel|ling
over it them&s;elves, pa&s;&s;ing and re-pa&s;|&s;ing
as &s;ecurely as on dry Land, from the
one <HI>Bothnea</HI> to the other: Hence it was no
improbable thing, that the <HI>Czar</HI> might, if his
Views had been that Way, have marched with
his whole Army over that Sea, not excluding his
Baggage, Cannon, and Waggons.</P>
<P>BUT tho' his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty thought fit to
allarm the <HI>Swedes</HI> with the daily Apprehen|&s;ions
of &s;uch an Attempt; yet, this was really
none of his pre&s;ent View: However, it had
this Effect, it continually harra&s;s'd the <HI>Swedish</HI>
Army, in Marching, and counter Marching,
as their own Fears directed them; nay, it went
farther, for as the <HI>Swedes</HI> had tran&s;ported two
&s;everal Bodies of their regular Troops to the
I&s;le of <HI>R$gen</HI> and <HI>Pomerania,</HI> and a thind to
<HI>Wi&s;ma$;</HI> So that General <HI>Ducker</HI> who command|ed
there, threatned to take the Field, and ad|vance
into <HI>Hol&s;tein,</HI> and <HI>Jutland,</HI> as Count
<HI>Steinboch</HI> had done, having this Advantage in
&s;uch an Enterprize, <HI>viz.</HI> that he had no Army
of <HI>Ru&s;&s;ians</HI> and <HI>Saxons</HI> to follow him in the
Rear. The Allarm given to the <HI>Swedes</HI> in their
own Country, by his <HI>$zari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty hovering
over their Coa&s;t, as above, had obliged them to
&s;end for 7000 Men back again from <HI>Pomeren,</HI>
to reinforce their Army at Home, and to de|fend
the Capital of their Kingdom.</P>
<P><PB N="419" REF="428">
THUS the <HI>Danes,</HI> were deliver'd at once by
the powerful Fleet of the <HI>Czar,</HI> from an Ene|my,
which they dreaded in <HI>Hol&s;tein;</HI> and from
a War that would have perhaps been too heavy
for them, as well for the power of their Ene|mies,
as the Expence of it; for the <HI>Swedes</HI> would
at lea&s;t have ruin'd all the <HI>Dani&s;h</HI> Dominions on
the <HI>Terra firm,</HI> by the Contributions they would
have drawn from thence, and the Ravages of
the open Country, from whence the capital City
is furni&s;h'd with daily Provi&s;ions.</P>
<P>THIS very View gave the King of <HI>Denmark</HI>
an an additional Vigour in his new De&s;ign of
invading <HI>$word$,</HI> nothing could more effectually
deliver him from the ju&s;t Apprehensions of a
Vi&s;it from <HI>Pomerania,</HI> as a De&s;cent upon <HI>Schonen,</HI>
carrying the War home into the Heart of <HI>Sweden,</HI>
and finding the <HI>Swedes</HI> Employment to defend
their own Towns, in&s;tead of giving them Lei&s;ure
to meditate the Inva&s;ion of tho&s;e Abroad.</P>
<P>THIS Winter the King of <HI>Sweden</HI> came from
<HI>Turkey,</HI> and arriv'd Incognito at the City of <HI>Stral&s;und</HI>
in <HI>Pomerania,</HI> and the World had great Expectations,
that his coming there would give a new Turn to
the Affairs of <HI>Europe;</HI> but that Prince, who&s;e po&s;itive
Temper, aver&s;e to the Advice of his be&s;t Friends,
pu&s;h'd him upon the mo&s;t de&s;perate, and incon|&s;i&s;tent
Actions, quickly made all his Neighbours
ea&s;ie, as to their Appren&s;ions of his Power, for
embroiling him&s;elf with the King of <HI>Pru&s;&s;ia,</HI> and the
Elector of <HI>Hanover,</HI> &s;ince King of <HI>England;</HI> he fi|nish$d
his own Ruin by ab&s;olutely refu&s;ing the mo&s;t
honourable Propo&s;al for Peace that could be made
to him, and engaging him&s;elf in a new War to his
Ruin, for he was finally be&s;iged both by Sea and
<PB N="420" REF="429">
Land, in his City of <HI>Stral&s;und,</HI> and at la&s;t forc'd
to make his E&s;cape in a &s;mall Ve&s;&s;el by Sea,
which landed him in <HI>Sweden,</HI> leaving behind him all
his Dominions, and all his hopes in the Empire
of <HI>Germany,</HI> in which he never &s;et his Foot af|terwards.</P>
<P>AND here nece&s;&s;ity, and the &s;welling of the&s;e
Pages beyond Expectation too far, obliges us to
break of the Hi&s;tory. From this Period a new
Scene of War was drawn out, in which the <HI>Czar</HI>
of <HI>Mu&s;covy</HI> had not only a great Share, but
which ended infinitely to his Glory, and the
Security of his Allies. The <HI>Swedes</HI> were pu&s;h'd
at their own Doors; their Country invad|ed;
the rich Copper Works, and Iron Works,
on which the Commerce of their Nation de|pended,
were ruined; and to fini&s;h all, their
invulnerable Monarch, <HI>as they thought him to be,</HI>
was Slain; their Trea&s;ure exhau&s;ted, and they
were at la&s;t obliged to yield to their Misfor|tunes,
and make a Peace inexpre&s;&s;ibly di&s;ad|vantagious
to them&s;elves, and in Proportion
glorious to his <HI>Czari&s;h</HI> Maje&s;ty; all which Acti|ons
remain to be Recorded, and are &s;ufficient
to make another Hi&s;tory.</P>
<P>MAY &s;ome other Pen be honoured with the
Narration, that the Glories of our Augu&s;t Em|peror
of <HI>Ru&s;&s;ia,</HI> may be handed to Po&s;terity, in
a manner &s;uitable to his Fame; and to the
Merit of the greate&s;t Prince in all the Ea&s;tern
Part of the World. <HI>Amen.</HI></P>
